<TEXT>
<BODY><DIV1 N="Rawlinson C 285" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="[1: 104]"><HEAD>Prose Treatises of Ms. Rawl. C 285</HEAD>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Be whate takynes &thorn;ou sal knaw if &thorn;ou luf &thorn;in ennemy,
and what ensampyl &thorn;ou sal tak of Crist forto luf hym</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"><P>And if &thorn;ou be nogth styrd agaynes &thorn;e persone be angre or felle cheer
outward ne be na pryue haat in &thorn;i hert for to despyse hym or deme hym
or forto sette hym at nogth, &amp; &thorn;e mare schame &amp; vilany he dos to &thorn;e in
word or in dide, &thorn;e mare pete or compassion&macr; &thorn;ou has of hym as &thorn;ou wald
of a man &thorn;at war out of his mynd, and &thorn;ou thynkis &thorn;ou can nogth fynd in
&thorn;i hert forto hate hym, for luf es swa gud<MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="folio"> in it-self, bot pray for hym and helpe hym and desire his amendyng, nogth anly with &thorn;i mygth als ypocrytes can doe, bot &thorn;i affeccyon of luf in &thorn;i hert: &thorn;an has &thorn;ou parfyte charyte to &thorn;i eeuenristen.  &THORN;is charyte had saynt Sthephane parfytely when he prayde for &thorn;aim &thorn;at stanyd hym to dede.  &THORN;is charyte consayld Crist til all &thorn;at wald be hys parfite folowers, when he sayd &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Diligite inimicos vestros, benefacite hijs qui oderunt
vos, orate pro persequentibus &amp; calumpniantibus vos:</FOREIGN> &laquo;Lufis your enemys &amp; dose gud to &thorn;aim &thorn;at hat &yogh;ou, prayes for &thorn;aim &thorn;at pursues &amp; sclaundres &yogh;ow&raquo;.  And &thorn;arfor, if &thorn;ou wil folow Crist, be lik til hym in craft: Lere for to luf &thorn;i enemys


<PB N="1: 105">

and synfull men&mdash;ffor all &thorn;es er &thorn;i euencrysten.  Loke and by-thynke &thorn;e how
Crist lufd Iudas whilke was bath his bodely enemy and a synfull kaytif; how
gudly Crist was to hym, how benygne, how curtayse &amp; how lagthly to hym &thorn;at
he knew dampnabile, and neeuer-&thorn;e-lesse he chesed hym to his appostel and sent
hym to preche with other apostilis; he gaf hym power to wyrke myracles, he
schewyd to hym &thorn;e same gud chere in worde and in dede, als with his precious
body, &amp; prechede hym als he dede to &thorn;e tothir apostls; he weryd hym nogth
opynly ne myssayd ne dispised hym ne spak neeuer ille of hym&mdash;and &yogh;it &thorn;of he
had done all &thorn;is, he had sayd bot south!  And ouer-mare, when Iudas toke
hym, he kyssid hym &amp; callid hym his frend.  All &thorn;is charite schewid Crist to
Iudas, wilke he knew for dampnable, In no manere of fenyng ne flateryng, bot in
southfastnes of gud luf &amp; clene charyte.  For &thorn;of it war south &thorn;at Iudas was
vnworthy to haf any gift of god or any syngne of luf, for his wykednes,
neeuer-&thorn;e-lesse it was worthi and skyllfull &thorn;at our lord suld schew als he es.  He es
luf and gudnes, and for-&thorn;i it fallis to hym to schew luf and gudnes til all his
creaturs, als he did to Iudas.  Folow efter sum-whate if &thorn;ou may!  for &thorn;of &thorn;ou
be stoken in a house with &thorn;i body, neeuer&thorn;eles in &thorn;i hert, whare &thorn;e sted of luf
es, &thorn;ou sal mow haf part of swilk a luf to &thorn;i euencristen as I spek of.
Wha-sowenes &thorn;an hym-self to be a parfite folower of Ihesu Cristis techyng &amp; his lifyng as sum men wenes &thorn;at &thorn;ai be, in als mykel as he preches &amp; techys &amp; es pouer of werldly gud as Crist was; &amp; can nogth folow Crist in his luf &amp; charyte for to lufe his euene-cristen, ylke a man, gud and ille, frendes and faees with-outene
fenyng, flateryng, disp[is]ynge in hert, angrines &amp; malencolius reprouynge: southly,
he bigilis hym-self; &thorn;e nerrer &thorn;at he wenys for to be, &thorn;e ferrer he is.  For Cryst
sayd to &thorn;aim &thorn;at wald be his folowers &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hoc est preceptum meum vt diligatis inuicem, sicut dilexi vos:</FOREIGN> &laquo;&THORN;is es my bedynge &thorn;at &yogh;e luf to-gedir as I luf &yogh;ow;
ffor if &yogh;e luf as I lufde &thorn;an er &yogh;e my discipiles&raquo;.  He &thorn;at es meke suthfastly or wald be meke, can luf his euen-cristene, &amp; nan bot he.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>What thyng helpes mast a mans knawyng and gettis
hym &thorn;at hym wantes, &amp; mast distroys syne in hym</HEAD>

<P>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou may do &thorn;e better and &thorn;e mare redely, if &thorn;ou be bisy for
to sette &thorn;i hert mast opon a thyng: and &thorn;at thyng es nogth ellis bot a gastly
desire to god: ffor to pleise hym, for to luf hym, for to knaw hym, for to se
hym, and forto haf hym by grace here in a litell felyng, and in &thorn;e blisse of
heeuene with a full beyng.  &THORN;is desire if &thorn;ou kepe it, sall wele telle &thorn;e whilke
es syn and wilke nogth, whilk es gud and whilke es better gude; and if &thorn;ou
 wile fest &thorn;i<MILESTONE N="59" UNIT="folio"> thogth &thorn;ar-to, it sal ken &thorn;e all &thorn;at &thorn;e nedis, and it sal gette
&thorn;e all &thorn;at &thorn;e wantes.  And &thorn;arfor when &thorn;ou sal ryse agayns &thorn;e gronde of
syn in generale or ellis agayne any speciale syne, hynge fast apon &thorn;is desire, and
sete &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;i thogth mare opon god wham &thorn;ou desires, &thorn;an opon &thorn;e syn
&thorn;e whilke [&thorn;ou] reproues.  For if &thorn;ou do swa, &thorn;an feghtes god for &thorn;e, and he
sal destrue syn in &thorn;e.  &THORN;ou sal mekyl soner com til &thorn;i purpose if &thorn;ou do swa,
&thorn;an if &thorn;ou lefe &thorn;i meke desire to god pryncypaly and wile set &thorn;i hert anly


<PB N="1: 106">

agaynes &thorn;e styryng of syne, als &thorn;of &thorn;ou wald destrue it be mastery of &thorn;i-self.
&THORN;ou sal neeuer swa bryng it aboute.  Bot doe as I hafe sayd, &amp; better if &thorn;ou
may, and I hope by &thorn;e grace of god Ihesu &thorn;ou sal make &thorn;e deeuell aschamyde,
&amp; all swylk wyked stiryngs &thorn;ou sal breke away, &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal nogth mykel dere &thorn;e.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>On the name of Iesus<NOTE>The first half of this text is taken from  chapter  nine (sic Cambridge Dd V.64) of <TITLE>The Form of Living</TITLE>; see the Cambridge and Rawlinson  copies in the Rolle volume (p. 35 in Horstman's edition).</NOTE></HEAD>

<P>If &thorn;ou wille be wele with god and haf grace to rewyle &thorn;i lif rygth and com
to &thorn;e ioy of luf: &thorn;is name Ihesus fest it sa fast in &thorn;i hert &thorn;at it come neeuer
owt of &thorn;i thogth.  And when &thorn;ou spekis til hym and says &laquo;Ihesu&raquo; thurgth costome: It sal be in &thorn;i heer ioy, in &thorn;i mouth hony, in &thorn;i hert melody; ffor &thorn;e sal
thynke ioy to here &thorn;at name be neeuend, swetnes to speke it, myrgth &amp; sang to
thynke it.  If &thorn;ou thynke Ihesu contynuely and hald stably: It purges &thorn;i syne and
kyndeles &thorn;i hert, it claryfis &thorn;i sawle, remoues angers, dos away slawnes.  It
wondis in luf, ffulfillis of Charyte; it chases &thorn;e deeuell &amp; puttis out drede, it
opyns heeuene and makis a contemplatif man.  Haf in memorie Ihesu, for all vyces
&amp; fantoms it puttis fra &thorn;e lufer.  If &thorn;ou wil noth deceyue ne be deceyfde; If &thorn;ou
wile be wys and nogth vnwys; If &thorn;ou wile stand &amp; nogth fall: thynke on &thorn;is
name Ihesu contynuly.  It destruys all vices and vanytes.  It sawes charyte &amp; vertus in &thorn;e saul, and &yogh;ettes in sauour of heeuene and fulnes of goddis grace in
erthe.  Wha so lufs &thorn;is name Ihesus with-outene forgettyng, dies in woundirfull
melody, and es taken with angels &amp; brogth bifor hym &thorn;at he lufd.  &THORN;is name
Ihesus es abouene all names: to whilke all knees kneels, of heeuen &amp; erthe &amp; helle.  &para; Ete and drynke, slepe &amp; wake, speke &amp; hald silence, pray &amp; thynke,
wyrke, and all &thorn;at &thorn;ou dos doe it, in &thorn;e n&amacr;me of Ihesu, Saynt Paul bedis.  Gode
blisse you &amp; kepe you and gif you gud perseuerance, thurgthe &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;is
Ioyfull name Ihesu.  Amen.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Sentences from Gregory</HEAD>

<P>Gregor: Our lord til his chosin makis &thorn;e day scharpe: &thorn;at &thorn;ai delite nogth in &thorn;e
gate and forgete &thorn;e Ioy of heeuen.  If temptacyo&umacr;n pute vs nogth, we suld trow
&thorn;at we war of sum vertu.  Rygth-wysmen in als mykell mare verrayly eer kasten
out of &thorn;e luf of syne, In how mykell &thorn;ai er mare greuosely tourmentyde. / In
als mykell ert &thorn;ou mad mare vile to god, In how mykell &thorn;at &thorn;e semes mare
precyous to &thorn;i-self.  &THORN;e ner &thorn;ou ert to god, &thorn;at &thorn;e thynke &thorn;i-self vnwor&thorn;i. / It
es mare gloriows to ouer-come beand stil, &thorn;an answerand to haf victorie. / &THORN;e
mynd son scrythes in to wers, If it be nogth kepid stratly vndir strayte kypynge. /
It es gret comfort in suffrynge of yuele to thynke on god we haf had; &thorn;e memore
of gode: [sal] temper &thorn;e payne of &thorn;e schourge, &amp; &thorn;e tourment of &thorn;e schour[g]e
byte &thorn;e gladnes of gode.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>How ane Ankares sal haf hir to &thorn;aim &thorn;at comes to hir</HEAD>

<P>Now &thorn;ou says &thorn;at &thorn;ou may noght kepe &thorn;e fra vanytese of heryng, ffor diuerse
men werldly and othir comes oft<MILESTONE N="60" UNIT="folio"> for to speke with &thorn;e and tellis &thorn;e talis,


<PB N="1: 107">

sum-tyme of vanyte.  And vnto &thorn;is I say &thorn;at &thorn;at commyng &amp; comunyng with &thorn;i
eeuenecristene es nogth mykell agaynes &thorn;e, bot helpis &thorn;e sum-tyme, if &thorn;ou wirke
wisely; ffor &thorn;ou may assay &thorn;are-be &thorn;e mesure [&thorn;i] of charyte to &thorn;i eeuene-cristene,
whethir it be mykel or litil.  &THORN;ou ert bonden als ylke a man &amp; womane es to luf
&thorn;i eeuenecristene pryncypaly in &thorn;i hert, and als-swa in dede for to schew hym
takynyngs of luf and charyte as reson askis, in &thorn;i mygth &amp; &thorn;i knawynge.  Now
sythen it es swa &thorn;at &thorn;ou aw nogth gaa oute of &thorn;i howse for to seke occasyone
how &thorn;ou mygth profite &thorn;i euencristene be dedis of mercy, be-cause &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert
enclosed: neeuer-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;ou ert bonden forto luf &thorn;aim all in &thorn;i hert, and to
&thorn;aim &thorn;at commes to &thorn;e, forto schewe &thorn;aim takynyngs of luf southfastly.  And
&thorn;arfore wha-so wile speke with &thorn;e, whate &thorn;at he be, in whate degre he be: &amp; &thorn;ou knawys nogth what he es, ne why he comes, be sone redy with a gud wile
forto wite whate es his wille; be nogth dayngerows ne suffre hym lang to abyd
&thorn;e, bot loke how redy &amp; howe glade &thorn;ou walde be If ane angele of heeuene
walde come &amp; spek with &thorn;e&mdash;swa redy &amp; swa bouxum be &thorn;ou in wile forto speke
with &thorn;i eeuencristene whene he comes to &thorn;e; ffor &thorn;ou wate nogth whate he
is ne whi he comes, ne whate nede he has of &thorn;e, ne &thorn;ou of hym, to &thorn;ou haf
assayd.  And other &thorn;ou be in prayer or in deuocyone &thorn;at &thorn;e thynke lath for to
breke of, ffor &thorn;e thynk &thorn;ou suld nogth lefe god for na mans speche: me thynke
nogth swa in &thorn;is case!  ffor if &thorn;ou be wyse, &thorn;ou sall nogth leue god bot &thorn;ou
sal fynd hym &amp; haf hym &amp; se hym in &thorn;i neuencristene als wele as in prayer,
bot on a nothir maner &thorn;ou sal haf hym.  If &thorn;ou couth wele luf &thorn;i eeuencristene,
it suld nogth hyndre &thorn;e forto spek with hym discretely.  Discrescyon sal &thorn;ou
haue in &thorn;is maner, as me thynk: Wha-sa comes to &thorn;e, aske hym mekly what
he wile: and if he come forto telle &thorn;e his dissese and forto be comfort of &thorn;i
speche, heer hym gladely and suffre hym say whate he wile for eese of his
awene hert; and whene he has done, comfort hym if &thorn;ou can gladely &amp; charytablely, and sone breke of; and &thorn;an after if &thorn;at he wald fall in til ydell talis o[f]
vanytes or othir menes dedis, a[n]ssuer hym bot litell ne fede hym nogth in his
speche, &amp; he sal sone be hirke &amp; sone tak his leue.  And if he be a nothir &thorn;at
comes forto ken &thorn;e, als a man of haly kyrke: heer hym lawly with reuerence for
his order, and if his speche comfort &thorn;e, aske of hym; &amp; make &thorn;e nogth forto kene
hym.  It fallis noth to &thorn;e forto ken a prest, bot in nede.  If his speche comfort
&thorn;e nogth, a[n]ssuer litill and he wile son take his lef.  If it be anothir man &thorn;at
comes forto gif &thorn;e his almos or ellis for to here &thorn;e speke or for [to] be kennyd of
&thorn;e: speke gudely, gladly, &amp; mekely to &thorn;aim all.  Reproue na man of his defautes:
it fallis nogth to &thorn;e.  And schortly for to say: als mykele as &thorn;ou consayuys &thorn;at
&thorn;ou suld profite to &thorn;i eeuenecristene namely gastly, if &thorn;ou can may &thorn;ou say, &amp; he wile take it; and of all [o]thir thyngs kepe silence als mykel as &thorn;ou may: and
&thorn;ou sal in a schort tyme haf bot litil prese &thorn;at sal lete &thorn;e; and &thorn;us me thynke.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">(St. Anselm's) Admonitio morienti</FOREIGN><NOTE>This piece is listed in the Manual of Writings in Middle English, vol. 7, as a text of Version B of <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">De Visitacione infirmorum</FOREIGN>.  The designation <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Admonitio morienti</FOREIGN> is retained here to avoid confusion with the text of <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">De Visitacione informorum</FOREIGN> given below from Univ. Coll. Oxford 97.</NOTE></HEAD>

<P>Saynt Ancelyne ersbiscop of Canty[r]bery says: &THORN;at a seke man languyssand to
&thorn;e dede, sulde<MILESTONE N="61" UNIT="folio"> of his prest &thorn;us be askide, and &thorn;us he answer.  &laquo;Brothir, es &thorn;ou


<PB N="1: 108">

glade &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal in crysten trouth dye?&raquo;  He answer, &yogh;a. .....  &laquo;Forthynkis &thorn;e &thorn;at?&raquo; &yogh;a. / &laquo;Has &thorn;ou wile to amend &thorn;e if &thorn;ou haf spase of lif?&raquo;  He sal answer, &yogh;a. &laquo;Trowys &thorn;ou &thorn;at Ihesu Cryst, goddis son, was borne of &thorn;e virgyne Marye and for &thorn;e dyede on gude fryday?&raquo;  Answer he, &yogh;a.  &laquo;Thanke[s] &thorn;ou hym for thir benefyces?&raquo; Answer he, &yogh;a.  &laquo;Trowys &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ou may nogth be safe bot be his dede?&raquo;  Say he, &yogh;a.  &laquo;For als lang as &thorn;i saule es yn &thorn;e, sete all &thorn;i trayst in &thorn;at dede allane, hafand trayst in no othir thynge; vmlappe &thorn;e all in &thorn;is dede.  Thynk nogth on &thorn;i wyfe ne of &thorn;i childer ne rychesce, bot allane of &thorn;e passione of Ihesu Cryst. And if our lord god wile deme with &thorn;e, say: ,lord, I sete &thorn;e dede of our lorde Ihesu Crist by-twyx me and my wikked dedis, and his meryte I offer for &thorn;e meryte &thorn;at I suld hafe &amp; has nogth'.  And say eftsons: ,lord, I sete &thorn;e dede of our
lord Ihesu crist [b]etwyx me and &thorn;i wryth'&raquo;.  &THORN;an sal he say thrys: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In manus tuas domine &amp;c.</FOREIGN>, and clerkis answerand acordandely: and &thorn;an he dyes sikirly.  &para; When
a seke man sal be en-vntyd, &thorn;e Crucifix suld be brogth and he sulde enowryn
it In &thorn;e wyrschipe of Ihesu Crist, &thorn;at bogth hym with many hard paynes and
schedyn[g]e of his precious blod &amp; for [hym] dyed on &thorn;e crosse.  Amen.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Sentences</HEAD>

<P>It was a saul and askyd clennes of saul of our lorde.  And he sayd to hir:
&laquo;Whate-sa &thorn;ou dose, luke I be &thorn;i cause.  Gif &thorn;e eghe of &thorn;i saul vnto me, and
be aned vnto me.  Luk nogth efter ylke a mans wile to do it, bot luk whilke
es myne &amp; do &thorn;at.  Deme nane of my creaturs bodyly ne gastly.&raquo;  A thogth of
a vertu es a dyke befor &thorn;e eghene of &thorn;e rygthwys domes-man: ffor when a
man vnthynkis hym of &thorn;at gud he has done, he hegys hym-self in hym, and
&thorn;an he fallis agaynes &thorn;e maker of mekenese.  Our lord Ihesus sayd to his
discipilis &thorn;is wordis: &laquo;Whene &yogh;e haf donne alle wele, says &thorn;at &yogh;e er vnprofytable seruandes&raquo;.  Amen.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Of the ten Commandments<NOTE>This text is an extract from The Lay Folks' Catechism (or  John Gaytrynge's Sermon).  It  is not to be confused with Rolle's short tract "Commentary on the Decalogue," also known by the name "On the Ten Commandments."</NOTE></HEAD>

<P>A nedefull thynge to knaw god all-mygthty, er &thorn;e tene Comandementis &thorn;at
god has gifen vs.  Of &thorn;e whilke tene &thorn;e thre &thorn;at er first aw vs haly to hald
onence oure god, and &thorn;e seeuene &thorn;at er efter, onence oure eeuencristene. / &THORN;e first
Comaundement charges vs &thorn;at we leue ne lowte ne fals goddis: and in &thorn;is
comaundement er forbodyne vs alkyn Mysbileues and all maumentrysce, all fals
enchauntementis [&] all so[r]ceris, all fals charmes &amp; all wycchecraftes, &amp; all fals
coniurisons and all wiccked craftis &thorn;at men of mysbileue trayst opone or hopes
any helpe In withoutene god all-myghty.  &THORN;e tothir Comandment bedis vs nogth
take in Idellchype ne in vayne &thorn;e name of oure gode, so &thorn;at we trowe nogth
in his name bot &thorn;at es stedfast; &thorn;at we say nogth In his name bot at es
southfast; &thorn;at we swere nogth be his name bot wirchipfully, and &thorn;at we neuene nogth
his name bot it be houely.  &THORN;e thryd Comaundement es &thorn;at we hald &amp; halow
our haly-day, &thorn;e son&macr;nday, &amp; all other &thorn;at fallis to &thorn;e &yogh;ere &thorn;at er ordayned to halowe thorow haly-kyrke; in whilke days all folke lered &amp; lawed aw to gif &thorn;aim

<PB N="1: 109">

gudely to goddis seruyse, to here and to say it efter &thorn;aire state es in wirchipe
of god all-mygthty and of his gud halowes; nogth &thorn;an forto tent to tary with &thorn;e
werlde, ne life in lykyng ne luste &thorn;at &thorn;e flesshe yhernnys, bot gudly to serue god in
clennes of life.  &THORN;e fierth biddes vs [do] wirschipe to fader and moder, nogth [anly]
to flesshely fader &amp; moder &thorn;at gettes &amp; fosters vs forth in &thorn;e werlde, bot to our
gastly fader &thorn;at has hede of vs &amp; teches vs to lif to hele of oure sauls, &amp; to
oure gastly moder &thorn;at es halykyrke,<MILESTONE N="62" UNIT="folio"> to be bouxsomm &thorn;are-to and saue &thorn;e
rygth of it, for it es moder of all &thorn;at cristenly lifs; and [als]-swa til ilke a man &thorn;at
wirschipful es forto do worchipe efter it es.  &THORN;e fift bedis vs &thorn;at we sal sla na
man, &thorn;at es at say, bodely, ne gastely nowthire; ffor als many we sla in &thorn;at we
may as we sclaunder or bakbitis or falsly defames or fandes to confound &thorn;aim
&thorn;at nogth seruyse, or withdrawes lyuelade fra &thorn;aim &thorn;at nede haues, If we be of
hafyng forto helpe &thorn;aim.  &THORN;e sext Comaundement forbidis vs to syn or for to
foly flesshly with any woman, oither sybbed or fremmed, weddid or vnweddide,
or any flesshly knawyng or dide haf with any, othir &thorn;an &thorn;e sacrament of
matermone excuse, &amp; &thorn;e law &amp; &thorn;e lare of haly kyrke teches.  &THORN;e seuent
Comaundement biddis vs &thorn;at we sal nogth stele: In &thorn;e whilke es forbydene vs all robbyng
&amp; reuyng, all wrangwys takyng or with-haldyng or hydyng or helyng of other
men guddis agaynes &thorn;aire wille &thorn;at has rygth to &thorn;aim.  &THORN;e aghtend biddis vs
&thorn;at we sal bere na fals wittenese ogayne oure eeuene-cristen: In whilke es
forbiden vs all maner of lesyng, fals conspiracy &amp; forsweryng, whathurgth oure
euencristen may lesse &thorn;aire catell, fayth [or] fauour, f&amacr;me or any thynge, whethir
it be in gastly or bodely guddis.  &THORN;e neyend Comaundement es &thorn;at we &yogh;ern[e]
nogth our neigthbur house: In whilke es forbidene vs all wrangwysse couaytes
of land or of lith or ogth els &thorn;at may nogth be liftted ne raysede fra &thorn;e grounde
als thyng &thorn;at es stedfast &amp; may nogth be sterede.  &THORN;e tenend &amp; &thorn;e last is
&thorn;at we &yogh;erne nogth &thorn;e wif of our neighbur ne of our eeuenecristene, ne &thorn;e
maydene ne his knaue ne his ox nor his asse: In whilke es forbidene vs to &yogh;erne
or to take any thyng &thorn;at may be sterede o[f] other men gud, als Robes and
Rychesce or other Catil, &thorn;at we haf na gud titil ne na rygth to; ffor what thyng
sa we gete or takis on other wys, we may nogth be assoiled of &thorn;e trespas bot
if we make a-sseth in &thorn;at we may to &thorn;aim &thorn;at we haf harmed withhaldand
&thorn;air guddis.  And in case &thorn;at we haf thurgth fals athes, als in assyses or other
enquestis, wyttandly or wylfully gert our eeuenecristen lesse &thorn;aire Patermoigne
or &thorn;aire heritage, or falsly be dissesed of land or of lithe, or fals deuorce be
made, or any man be dampned; of all we do &thorn;at we may vnto &thorn;e party, &yogh;it
may we nogth be assoild of &thorn;e trespas, bot of oure biscope or of hym &thorn;at has
his power&mdash;ffor swylke case es ryuely reserued til hym-self. || &THORN;is tene
Comaundementis &thorn;at er befor rekennede, er vnbilouked in twa of &thorn;e gospell: &THORN;e tane
es, &thorn;at we luf god ouer all thyngs; &thorn;e tothir, &thorn;at we luf our eeuencristene als
we do oure-selfe.  For god aw vs to luf haly with hert, with all our mygth, [with]
all our thogth, with worde &amp; with deide.  Our eeuenecristene alswa aw vs to luf
vnto &thorn;at ylke gud &thorn;at we luf our-self, &thorn;at es at say, welefare in body &amp; in saule,
and come to &thorn;at ylke blysse &thorn;at we thynke till.  Tyll &thorn;e whilke blysse brynge
vs Ihesus Cryst goddis sonne of heeuene, eeuer-mare with hym to dwell.  Amen.
</P></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="1: 110"><HEAD>Points best pleasing to God</HEAD>

<DIV3 N="Rawlinson C 285" TYPE="MS"> <HEAD>Ms. Rawl. C 285</HEAD>
<P>Will &yogh;e offe &thorn;ir poyntis lere, &thorn;at our lorde es leue and dere: How &thorn;at man couaytis whilke es our lord maast likynges.  &THORN;an sayd oure lord til &thorn;at man in &thorn;e erth leuand: &laquo;Till &thorn;e pouer almos donne, whils &thorn;ou lifs oft &amp; sone: &thorn;at payes me mare, &thorn;an &thorn;ou gaf grete hilles of gold after &thorn;i dede be any-kin lare.  Ilke tere of &thorn;i neghe for my passion, and for &thorn;i synnes &thorn;at<MILESTONE
N="63" UNIT="folio"> &thorn;ou has done: &thorn;at pays me, mare and &thorn;ou mouth in als mykel sorowe be, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mouth grete als mykel water als ware in &thorn;e see, for erthly guddes and erthli thynge.  Off &thorn;e seke


<PB N="1: 111">

haf pete and passion: &thorn;at paies me mare, and &thorn;ou war with als many stauys dongyne als men mouth bar, In a hundreth woddis grouand and wele mare.  Constreyne &thorn;i foule hert and &thorn;i wikkyd wille, and take mekely with-In &thorn;e clennese,


<PB N="1: 112">

pees, resone and skylle, and pute away &thorn;e foule syne &thorn;at of &thorn;i hert wille come: ffor forsakyng of preue wille and opyne es parfite religione: and paies god mare, and &thorn;ou fasted fourschore yhere water and brede and ilke a day &thorn;i bodily flesshe in blod gert fare.  Swetely suffre frawarde wordis for my sake, and when &thorn;i hert es mast gret late nogth with-schape, and in pees kepe &thorn;us &thorn;i saule: &thorn;is paies me mare, &thorn;an &thorn;ou sougth fourschore myle &thorn;i fete and schankes sa bare, &thorn;at breres and stanes &thorn;aim so retted &thorn;e blod rane eeuer ay-whare, and men by &thorn;at trase of blod mouth fynd whare &thorn;ou ware.  Loue &thorn;i neigthbur and &thorn;i eeuen-cristene, and speke &thorn;aim &thorn;e gud and &thorn;are-til eeuer-lastyne, and wille &thorn;aim &thorn;e gude, and turne &thorn;aim hale to gude: and &thorn;at paies our lord mare &thorn;at died opon  &thorn;e rode, and we and our spirit hilke a day In til heeuene fley, southly to saye.  Breke &thorn;i slape and wake with oryson, prayand with gud deuocyone: for &thorn;at es me mare payand, and &thorn;ou toke twell armed knyghtes, and sent &thorn;aim in til &thorn;e haly land, on sarsines to feigth.  What (&thorn;ou wile) hafe, fyrst of me &thorn;ou it crafe: and &thorn;at pai(s me, mare a)nd my moder and all halowys pray for &thorn;e.  Loue me (ouer all &thorn;in)gis soueraynly, and &thorn;i hert to me gif all haly: and &thorn;at paies me mare likand to my wille, and &thorn;ou Mountid vp clymmand on a hille, ffull of sharpe rasours kerwand &thorn;e sare, &thorn;at &thorn;i flesshe fra &thorn;e banys hynged ay-whare.&raquo;  Amen.  </P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a .1)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="1: 110"><HEAD>Ms. Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a.)</HEAD>

<P>Hit was an holi mon and bi-sou&yogh;te
god sende him grace such vertues for
to vse &thorn;at weore best to lyf and to
soule.  &THORN;enne apeered vr lord Ihesus
godes sone to him and seide: // &laquo;&YOGH;if &thorn;in
herte to me and &thorn;in almus to &thorn;e pore
mon for &thorn;e loue of me: and hit schal
lyke me betere &thorn;en &thorn;auh &thorn;ou &yogh;iue al
&thorn;e gold of &thorn;is world aftur &thorn;i day. //
Weop a ter wi&thorn; &thorn;in ei&yogh;e, &thorn;enk on my
passion: and hit schal lyke me bettere
&thorn;en &thorn;ow weope as muche watur as is
in &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; for anger and for teone of
los of worldes catel.  // Forbere a wikked
word of &thorn;in euen-cristen: and hit schal
lyke me bettere &thorn;en &thorn;ou beote &thorn;i-self
wi&thorn; as mony roddes as grouwe&thorn; on an
acre of londe.  // Keep &thorn;e out of dedly
synne wi&thorn; al &thorn;i mi&yogh;t: and hit schal
lyke me bettre &thorn;en &thorn;ou founde Ni&yogh;ene
knihtes werryng vppon Sara&yogh;ynes,
euer-more liggyng aboute my sepulcre.  //
Haue reu&thorn;e and pite of &thorn;in euencristne:
and hit schal lyke me bettre &thorn;en &thorn;ou
faste fourti wynter &thorn;reo dayes in &thorn;e
wike to bred and to watur.  // Visyte
&thorn;e pore and &thorn;e seke, spekyng alle
goodnes: and hit schal lyke me bettre
&thorn;en &thorn;ou go bare-foot to &thorn;e wei rennyng
blod on &thorn;i feete.  // Do no wrong to
no mon, nou&thorn;ur harm ne schome: and
hit schal lyke me bettre &thorn;en &thorn;ow eueri
day maade a newe churche.  // Tel to
me al &thorn;i wille, and leeue &thorn;at I am
almihti al goodnesse to fulfille: and hit
schal lyke me bettere &thorn;en &thorn;ou preyed
my moder and al &thorn;e halewes of heuene


<PB N="1: 111">

to preye for &thorn;e.  // Loue me wi&thorn; al
&thorn;in herte, to haue my blisse: and hit
schal lyke me bettere &thorn;en &thorn;ou made a
piler rechyng vp to heuene, stikyng ful
of rasours al &thorn;i bodi to renden on.&raquo;
</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="Harley 1704" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="1: 110"><HEAD>Ms. Harley 1704</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"><P>It was an holy man besought god
to send hym grace to teche soch vertues
for to vse that were best to lyf and to
soule.  / &laquo;Yef thyn hert to me and a
peny to the pore for the loue of me:
and it shall like me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou
yeue all the good of &thorn;is world after
thy day.  / Veppe a tere with thyn eye
&thorn;enkyng on my passione: &amp; it shall like
me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou wepte also moch
water as is in the see for anger or for
tene of los of worldis Catell.  / For-bere
a wicked word fro thyn euen-Cristen:
&amp; it shall like me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou bete
thy-self with all-so monye Roddis as
growen in an acre londe.  / Kepe the
oute of synne with all thi myght: and
it shall like me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou fynd IX
knyghtes werryng vppon the Sare&yogh;ens,
euer-more lying aboute my sepulcre:
&thorn;an &thorn;ou for to lie in synne.  / Haue
rewth and pite on thy euen-Cristene: &amp; it shal like me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou fastid
xl<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> wynter III dayes in the woke bred
and water.  / Visite the pore and the
sike, spekyng all goodnesse: and it shall
like me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou goo barefote
that &thorn;e waye renne blod after thy feet.  /
Do no wrong to no mane, nether harme
ne shame: and it shal like me better
&thorn;en &thorn;ou eueryday make a newe Chyrch.  /
Tell to me all thy will, and beleue wele
that I am al-myghti god and all
goodnesse to fulfill: and it shal like me
better &thorn;en my moder &amp; all alowene


<PB N="1: 111">

praydene for the.  / Loue me for me: and
it shall like me better &thorn;an &thorn;ou make a
piler Rechyng vp to heven, stiking full
of Rasoures all &thorn;i body to Rendyn
vppone.&raquo;</P><P>Flee perile and doute of deth, take
&thorn;e better for hope of mede: the blisse
of heven shalt &thorn;ou not misse, so &thorn;ou
wilt kepe the commaundementis of Crist.  /
Thou most forsake pride and all wickid
willis, yef &thorn;ou wilt kepe &thorn;e
commaundementis of Crist.  // I besech the, leue
brother, take to &thorn;e loue &amp; Charite, yef
thou wilt to heven flee.  // Here &thorn;ou
might lere the commaundementis x; ne
be &thorn;ou neuer so gret Clerke, &thorn;ou hast
gret nede for to lerne hem.  // Haue god
in worship.  Take not his name in
Idelship.  / Hold wele &thorn;i Holidaye.  Fader
and moder worship aye.  / Loke that &thorn;ou
nought stele, Ne no fals wetenesse thou
ne bere.  / Loke &thorn;ou ne sle non mane.
Do no foli by no womane.  / Desire not
thy neygbours wyff, Ne nothing that
&thorn;erto light.  / He that will kepe these
commaundementis he shal neuer die.  //
Leue frende, I beseche the, the VII.
dedely synnes that &thorn;ou flee, / yf &thorn;ou wilt
in heven be.  / Who so is taken &thorn;erin /
in hell shalbe his wonnyng.  // Pride /
Wrath / Envye, / Slouth / Glotenye, /
Lecherie / Couetise.  / He that is taken
&thorn;erin, sore may hym agrise.  // Man, take
Comfort to the, beholde and se the
vertues seuyne, that will bring the to
heuyne: // Mekenesse, Pacience, Charite /
Besinesse, Mesure, Chastite / Largesse
to hem that haue nede to the.  / He that
will kepe these vertuesse seuen: in heven
shal be his dwellyng, with oure lord
heven kyng.  AmeN.
</P></DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="1: 122"><HEAD>Against Boasting and Pride</HEAD>

<P>Greuous es &thorn;e vice of bostynge &amp; pride, and full perilous it es, ffor it castes
doun saules fra &thorn;e heygthnes of perfeccyone; and &thorn;arfor I wille &yogh;e wante first
&thorn;at vice of all o&thorn;ere.  &para; Bot &thorn;is vice has twa spices: &para; It falles to some alstite in bygynnynge of &thorn;aire turnynge to god, qwene &thorn;ai hafe done a litil whate<MILESTONE
N="69" UNIT="folio">
to god in fastynge or in gret bodely penaunce doynge or in mekelle almus gyfynge;
&thorn;ai suld &thorn;an feele mekyly of &thorn;aim-selfe, as if &thorn;ai had done ryght nogth or eells
&thorn;at &thorn;ai had castene away &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe gifene in almus: &para; &thorn;ai do nogth sa, bot
&thorn;e contrary, ffor &thorn;ai fele of &thorn;aim-selfe &thorn;at &thorn;ai er better &thorn;ane o&thorn;er, &amp; hegher in grace &thorn;ane &thorn;ai er &thorn;e whylke &thorn;ai gafe almus to; &thorn;is es pryde.  &para; Ano&thorn;er spice es &thorn;is: whene a mane es commene to hegth perfeccione &amp; arettis it nogth mekely to &thorn;e grace of gode bot to his aghene trayuell and to his aghene stody, &amp; sa sekes he ioy withoutene of men &amp; leefes verray ioy within of god.  &para; Wharefore,
my dere son&macr;s, on all wise flee &yogh;e &thorn;e vice of bost and pryde: &thorn;at &yogh;e fall nogth
in &thorn;e lake &thorn;at &thorn;e feend fell in for his pride.  &para; For-&thorn;i mekyll bysynes es for
to sete aboute &thorn;i thoghtes, &amp; aboute kypyng of &thorn;i hert.  &para; Be war &thorn;at na couetyse ne wykked luste ne vayne yhernyng ne ogth &thorn;at es agayne &thorn;e wille of god,
festene rote in &thorn;i hert: &para; ffor why, of swylke manere of rotis contynualy sprynges
out braunches of vayne ioy &amp; vnprofytabyll thoghtes &amp; fleschly desyres, &amp; &thorn;ay er &thorn;ane sa presand &amp; sa gredy &thorn;at whils we pray &amp; standes in &thorn;e sigth of god for to offere oure prayers &amp; oure gud thoghtes to god for heel of our saules, &thorn;ai
sese nogth for to tary vs anely, bot alswa &thorn;ai refe fra vs our-selfe, our mynde
&amp; our thogth, als prisoners; &thorn;at whene we seme standand in prayer with
our body, neuere-&thorn;eles we stray out with oure felynge &amp; our thogth &amp; er led
avaye with sere thynges als falls in our thoghtes.  &para; And &thorn;ar-for he &thorn;at wenes
&thorn;at he has forsakene &thorn;e werlde &amp; &thorn;e werkes of &thorn;e feende, It suffice nogth anly
in &thorn;at, &thorn;at he leefe his possessiouns &amp; his landes &amp; his werldly ryches &amp; all
werldly profehtes &thorn;at ere with-outene hym-selfe, &para; bot if he also forsake his
aghene vice &amp; cast fra hym his vayne fleschly wills &thorn;at are with-in hym, festynd
to hym by corrupcione of kynde, &amp; are waxene vp with hym fra his yhouthed.
&THORN;is it are of &thorn;e whylke saynt Paule says &thorn;us: &para; &laquo;Vayne yhernyngs &amp; noyous, &thorn;at gers men synke in endles dede&raquo;.  &para; For whi, he &thorn;at forsakys &thorn;is [werld], he forsakys &thorn;e feende with all his werkis.  &para; &THORN;e feend of hym-selfe may nogth dere vs, bot thurgth occacioune of syne &amp; a gate of wikkyd wille in our-selfe he entres &amp; crepis in preuely in to our hertes; &para; ffor als vertus ar of god, rigth sa are vices of &thorn;e feende, &para; and &thorn;arfor if vices festyne rotes in our hertis, sothly whilke
tyme &thorn;e feend commes &thorn;at es &thorn;aire prince, &thorn;ai gyf sted to hym as to &thorn;aire aghen
lorde, &amp; ledis hym to &thorn;e saule as to his aghene possessione.  &para; And &thorn;arfor swylke hertis may neuer hafe pes ne trew rest, bot &thorn;ay are trobled ay &amp; drouyd, &amp; ay ferred &amp; vnstable in &thorn;aim, &amp; now &thorn;ai are liftid vp in to vayne gladenese &amp; now &thorn;ay are castyne doune sodaynly in to vnprofytable sarynes;  &para; ffor whi, &thorn;ai hafe
with-in &thorn;aim a wykked ost, &thorn;at es &thorn;e feend wonnand in &thorn;aim; to hym &thorn;ai
gaife leefe thurgth lustis &amp; passiouns of syne for to entre in &thorn;aim.  &para; Rygth on
&thorn;e contrary wise a mane &thorn;at sothfastly has forsakene &thorn;e luf of &thorn;e werld: &thorn;at es
he &thorn;at has schorne &amp; cutte avaye all vices fra his hert &amp; leues na entre to &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 123">

fende thurgth schrewed wils for to come in to hym; &thorn;at flees all prid, brekes
doune wrethe &amp; malencoly, hates all maner of lesyngis, vggis with enuy, &amp; noth
anely wile nogth bakbite, bot he wil nogth suffre hym-selfe feele anes or supos
any euele of his eeuene-cristene, and haldes &thorn;e grace &amp; &thorn;e comfort of his
euene-cristene als his aghene, &amp; &thorn;aire disees arettis to his aghene desese.  &THORN;at kepis
&thorn;is &amp; o&thorn;er vertous like to &thorn;is, he stoppis out &thorn;e feend &amp; openes a place in his saule to &thorn;e haly gast: &thorn;e whilke, whene he es entred in, he lightenes &thorn;e saule
&amp; thurgth his blyssed presence comfortes; &amp; whils he es ofte wonnand &thorn;are-in,
it es ay ioy, gladenes &amp; gastly myrth, ay luf &amp; charite, paciens, gudenes, &amp; clennes, chastite &amp; o&thorn;er vertous &thorn;at are &thorn;e fruyte of &thorn;e haly gast.  &para; And &thorn;at es &thorn;at oure lord says in &thorn;e gospele: &para; &laquo;A gud tre may nogth make badde fruyte, ne an euele tree may nogth bryng forth gud fruyte.  Whate &thorn;at &thorn;e tree es, be &thorn;e
fruyte it es knawene&raquo;.  &para; &THORN;are er some &thorn;at semes as &thorn;ai had forsakene &thorn;e werld, bot &thorn;ai hafe na cure ne bysenes aboute &thorn;e clensyng of &thorn;aire conscience, &para; ne
&thorn;ai hafe na trauele to cutte avay vices &amp; fleschly passiouns fra &thorn;aire saule,
for to aray &thorn;aire saule in gud thewes &amp; in vertous; &thorn;ai haf na heigh &thorn;are-to,
bot all &thorn;aire stody es outward for to seme haly to &thorn;e sygth of &thorn;e werld; &amp; &thorn;ai
er besy for to visete haly men &amp; wyse men &amp; see &thorn;aim, &amp; for to here of &thorn;aim some gud wordis of edificatione: &thorn;at &thorn;ai mygth preche &amp; telle &thorn;e same wordis &thorn;at &thorn;ai<MILESTONE
N="70" UNIT="folio"> haue herd to o&thorn;er men with auauntynge and vayne glory of &thorn;aim, &thorn;at &thorn;ai
can sai sa wele.  And perchaunce some of &thorn;aim when &thorn;ai hafe herd or rede a
litele of haly write or has gettyne a litele cunnynge of techyng of haly faders,
alstite &thorn;ai make &thorn;aim-self doctours &amp; wille teche o&thorn;er men, nogth &thorn;at &thorn;ai hafe
fulfilled in werkes, bot &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf herd &amp; sene in bokes, &para; and sa &thorn;ai presome
of &thorn;aire aghene connynge &amp; despice o&thorn;er &thorn;at er synfull; &amp; &thorn;ai couete state or
prelacy, &thorn;at &thorn;ai mygth teche all men: &para; nogth knawand &thorn;is &thorn;at it es lesse
defaute to hym &thorn;at schynes in vertoues &amp; ouer-passis in conynge and yhit he dare
nogth teche, &thorn;an it es to hym &thorn;at es ouer-layde with passions &amp; vices &amp; he
presomes wilfully to teche o&thorn;er men of vertoues.  &para; Sa it semes &thorn;at &thorn;e state of
prelacy or of suffereynte, it es nogth for to fley vterly, ne it es na gates for to
aske ne to couete: bot all oure werkes &amp; all our bysenes es for to gif here-to
&thorn;at vices may be ripid out of oure saules, &amp; vertous mygth be gettyne in.  &para; &THORN;e
to&thorn;er es for to leeue to &thorn;e dome of god whayme he wille take to soueraynte &amp; gouernaunce, &amp; whame nogth; for he es nogth worthi &thorn;at profers hym-self
forth &thorn;erto, bot he &thorn;at god chesis &amp; takis.  &para; &THORN;e werke of a parfite seruaund of god es &thorn;is: &thorn;at he may offer a clene praier to god, hauand na thyng blameworhthi,
ne nane vnclennes, in his conscience.  &THORN;an may he pray frely, as our lord sais
in &thorn;e gospell: &para; &laquo;When &yogh;e stand for to pray, fforgifes your brether all &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf done agaynes &yogh;ou; ffor if &yogh;e forgif it nogth, youre fader in heeuene wile
nogth forgyfe &yogh;ou.&raquo;  &para; Ande &thorn;arfor, if we with a clene hert may stand be-fore our lorde, &amp; fre made be grace fra alle vice &amp; passiouns of &thorn;e saule befor neuende,
&thorn;an at arst may we see god, als mykele as it es possible for to se hym here: ffor
&laquo;clene of hert sal se god&raquo;; &para; and &thorn;an whene we pray, we sal sete &thorn;e egth of our saule in hym &amp; se hym &thorn;at es vnseable, nogth with bodely egth, bot in
thogth; nogth with lukyng of fleschly egth, bot be &thorn;e vnderstandenge of &thorn;e
saule illumyned thurgh grace.  &para; Luke &thorn;at a mane wene nogth &thorn;at he may


<PB N="1: 124">

hym-selfe se &thorn;e blyssed substance of &thorn;e godhed as it es; ne &thorn;at a man paynte hym
ane ymage for any schape of godhede; ffor whi, &thorn;are es na bodely schappe of
&thorn;e blyssed trinite.  Our blyssed vnseable god may be perseyued alanle be inly
vnderstandyng, &amp; he may be felid &amp; touched &amp; halsid anely thurgh a gastly
affeccione; bot he mai nogth fully be comprehendid, ne tellid be tonge, ne discried
be lyknes.  He passes alle fleschly felyng &amp; ymaginacioune.  And &thorn;arfor it
be-houes vs with all manere of reuerence &amp; with lufly drede come to &thorn;e presence
of god in our prayers, and in alle our gastly werkes, and sa printe in hym &thorn;e
gastly byhaldyng of oure saule &thorn;at what manere of schynynge or brygthnes,
light or fayrhede &thorn;at a saule may thynke or ymagyne, &thorn;at he feele ay god
abouene &thorn;is, &thorn;at may nogth be sene. |  &THORN;at may &thorn;e saule wele feele if it be
clene, as it es befor sayde, &thorn;at it be nogth occupid ne ouerlayd with fleschly
lustes.  And &thorn;arefor it nedis &thorn;aim &thorn;at forsakis &thorn;e werld &amp; makis &thorn;aim to folwe
Crist, fforto gif &thorn;aire trayuell, as it es befor sayd, &thorn;at &thorn;ai mygth folfile &thorn;at
Dauid sais &thorn;us: &para; &laquo;Cese &yogh;e, &amp; seese &thorn;at I am god.&raquo; &para; And &thorn;an, if &yogh;e come to &thorn;is knawynge of god &thorn;us with clennes of hert: after &thorn;at it es possible to a saule to receife &thorn;e knawyng of &thorn;e sacrement of god &amp; of heuenly preuetese; &amp; &thorn;e clenner &thorn;at &thorn;e saul es, &thorn;e ma thyngs god schewys hym; ffor he tellis to hym &thorn;an his preuetese for he es mad godis frend, as &thorn;ai ware to &thorn;e whilke oure
lord sais &thorn;us: &laquo;Now I tell &yogh;ou noth seruaundis, bot frenddes, ffor whi I make
knawene vnto &yogh;ou all &thorn;at I hafe herd of my fader&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;an what-sa he askis of god, as to a dere frend it es granttid; yha &amp; ouer-mare &thorn;e haly aungells &amp; all
blyssed spyretis lufes swylke a saule, ffor it es sette in luf &amp; parfite charite sa
stedfastly &thorn;at &laquo;no&thorn;er dede ne life ne aungels ne princes ne powers ne na other
creatourres may depart it fra &thorn;at es in Crist Ihesu&raquo;, as saynt Paule
sayd.  &para; And &thorn;arfor, dere brether, sen &yogh;e haue chosyne &thorn;e life of perfeccione for to plese god &amp; for to come to his lufe, &para; luke first bisely &thorn;at &yogh;e be mad strange &amp; ferre fra vice of prid &amp; of bostyng, &amp; fra all &thorn;e vice of &thorn;e saul, &amp; fra all fleschly delites.  &para; Fleschly delites I cal nogth anely daynteth metes &thorn;at men of &thorn;is werld takes for lust: bot I cal dayntes all thynge &thorn;at es takene of couetese &amp; fleschly yhernynge; al if it be vile in it-selfe &amp; of litele prise, as bred &amp; water; if it be takene for luste &amp; noth for nede of body, bot for to make a-seth to &thorn;e fleschly
yernyng, it es arettid as fleschly delites.  It nedis to a saule &thorn;erfor vse it-self
how it may be fere fra syne; sa says our lord, &thorn;us: &laquo;Entres by &thorn;e narow gate:
ffor wyde &amp; brade es &thorn;e way &thorn;at ledis to losyng: &para; Strayte &amp; narowe es it &thorn;at ledis to life&raquo;.  Large es &thorn;e way of &thorn;e saule when it makes a-seth to any fleschly desire &amp; folowes it.  &para; Bot strayte es &thorn;e way when it feghtes &amp; agayn-standes ylka fleschly desire &amp; ylka vicious sterynge.  It helpis mekell to<MILESTONE
N="71" UNIT="folio"> a saule forto gette &thorn;is perfeccioun: pryue dwellyng &amp; anely conuersacione; for it fallis oft thurgth conuersacione of men &amp; comynge &amp; gaynge of brether &amp; spekynge, a man es mad mare louse in abstinence &amp; in contenance &amp; in kepynge of his hert; &amp; swa sume-tyme thurgh occacione a man falls in custome &amp; in vse of fleschly delites;
&amp; sa er parfite men some-tyme drawene doune fra &thorn;aire perfeccione.  For-&thorn;i said
Dauid &thorn;us: &laquo;I flyed &amp; lengthed me &amp; dwelled in anely stede, &amp; layd hym &thorn;at saued me fra scorne of &thorn;e spyrite&raquo;. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Deo gracias amen.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<PB N="1: 125"><HEAD TYPE="text">Sayings of the Fathers</HEAD>

<P>Pray god &thorn;at he wil gif to &thorn;e compungcion &amp; wepyng in &thorn;i hert, with
mekenes, &amp; ay luke on &thorn;i nawene synnes, &amp; deme nogth other, bot be vnderloute
to all; ne haf na hamely frenschippe with wymen, ne with heritiks, ne with childer.
&para; Cutte away fra &thorn;e ouer-mykell triste, &amp; halde &thorn;i tonge, &amp; abstene &thorn;e fra wyne; &amp; whate a man spekes to &thorn;e, stryue nogth agayne hym for na cause, bot, if he
say wele, ac(c)o(o)rd with hym; If he say euyll, say to hym &thorn;us: &laquo;Brother, &thorn;ou
wate &thorn;at &thorn;ou says&raquo;, bot stryue nogth with hym: &amp; &thorn;an sal &thorn;i saul be restfull &amp; in pees of quiete conuersacioune.  Amen.
</P><P>&para; Saynt Agathon said &thorn;at with-outene kepyng a man sal nogth come to
vertoue.  &para; A haly fader sayd: &laquo;Haf mynd of &thorn;i last forthgayng &amp; forgette nogth &thorn;e endeles dome: &amp; &thorn;er sal na syne rest in &thorn;i saule&raquo;.  &para; Alswa he said &thorn;us: &laquo;For als mekill as our thoth es letted &amp; drawen doun fra contemplacione &amp; sigth of god, &thorn;arefor ere we ouercomene &amp; lede away as caytefs with maystry of fleschly passiouns&raquo;.  &para; Saynt Sincletica said &thorn;us: &laquo;All wille we de safe, bot for our necgligence &amp; our slawnes we fal &amp; fales fra saluacione: &THORN;arfor life we sobirly, wakirly, &amp; besely; ffor whi, be &thorn;e wy[n]do[u]es of oure fyue wittes, nyl we sa wile we, thefes comes in.  How may it be ells, bot a house sall nedis be blake &amp; soty with-in, If smoke syncce in ay fra with-outene at &thorn;e wyndouse &thorn;at er na tyme stokyne?  Rigth sa it es of oure saule, &amp; &thorn;erfore it nedis to be
ouer-all armyd with-in and with-outene agaynes oure gastly ennemys, for &thorn;ai come &amp; preses on vs fra with-outene at oure bodely wittes, &amp; &thorn;ai stirte &amp; ryses with-in
vs be ymaginacione of vayne thoghtes&raquo;.  &para; Saynt Arseyne says &thorn;us: &laquo;As na man may hurte hym ne harme hym &thorn;at es contenuelly beside &thorn;e kynge in his
presence: rigth sa may Sathanas nogth hurte ne harme vs if oure saule clefe
stabely to god in behaldynge of hym; ffor it es wrytene &thorn;us: ,Neigh &yogh;e to me
and I sal negh to &yogh;ow.'  Bot for als mekil as we oft-sithes liftes vp our-self to
pride &amp; has vayne ioy in our hertis, &thorn;erfor grace god withdrawes &amp; our enmy
ligthly rauysches oure wykked saule to syne &amp; drawe [it] doune in to schamefull
passions of lychery &amp; of fleschly vnclennes&raquo;.  &para; Saynt Machary was askid &thorn;us: &laquo;how sal a man pray?&raquo; &amp; he aunswerde &thorn;us: &laquo;It nedis nogth to spek mekil with voce in prayyng; bot lift vp &thorn;i hert to god, &amp; oft streke vp &thorn;i handes to hym &amp; say &thorn;us: ,Lord, as &thorn;ou wille &amp; as &thorn;ou wate, haf mercy on me!'  &para; And if fightyng of temptacione prese in to &thorn;i saule, say as Dauid did, &thorn;is worde:
Deus, in adiutorium meum intende: ,God, helpe me'.  And for he wate qwat
es spedfull til vs, &thorn;erfor he sal do with vs his mercy.&raquo;  &para; A fader said &thorn;us: &laquo;If a bro&thorn;er falle in any defaute, late hym pray fast, ffor assiduell prayer sone correctis a saule.&raquo;  &para; Alswa he said &thorn;us: &laquo;As it es inpossible &thorn;at a mane see his face in drouye water, rigth swa a saul, bot it be clennsed fra vnclene &amp; strange thoghtis, may nogth contemplatifely pray god.&raquo;  &para; Saynt Agathon said &thorn;us: &laquo;A parfite seruaund of god sal nogth suffre his conscience accuse hym-self in na thyng: and &thorn;an es it clene conscience.&raquo;  &para; A bro&thorn;er sayd to a fader &thorn;us: &laquo;I desire for to kepe my hert.&raquo;  &amp; he answerd &thorn;us: &laquo;How may we kepe our hert if our tonge


<PB N="1: 126">

haf ay &thorn;e yhate opyne?&raquo;  &para; A haly fader said &thorn;us: &laquo;I suffred neuer thogth rest in my hert &thorn;at grefd gode.&raquo;  &para; Alswa he sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;As knyghtis of &thorn;e emperoure, when &thorn;ay stand by-for hym, &thorn;ay suld luke on no&thorn;er syde, nother on &thorn;e rygth ne on &thorn;e lefte: rigth swa goddes seruaunde when he standes in &thorn;e sigth of god
&amp; his entent es alle tyme sette in &thorn;e dred of god, &thorn;are es na thyng &thorn;at may
hurte &amp; ouercome hym be malice of his aduersaries.&raquo;  &para; A fader said &thorn;us: &laquo;&THORN;e life of a parfit seruaund of god aw to be mad efter &thorn;e folowyng of aungels:
Rigth as in aungels es na syne, rigth swa in hym suld na syne endure, bot it
suld as tit be brynte &amp; waschid thurgth &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e haly gast, as stykkes
in &thorn;e fiere.&raquo;  &para; Alswa he said &thorn;us: &laquo;I hope, bot if a man kepe his hert,
he sal be forgetill ande rekles of all &thorn;at he heris; ffor whi: when &thorn;e enimy
fyndis a rekles hert vnkepid &amp; nogth tentyd to, als fast he bygyles it vonder slely,
&amp; nogth sodaynly, bot sokandly.&raquo;  &para; A fader sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;Sathanas has thre snarres &thorn;at gas bifor all o&thorn;er<MILESTONE
N="72" UNIT="folio"> synnes in a saule: &thorn;e first es forgetyng, &thorn;e secound
es rekleshed &amp; neclegence, &thorn;e thrid es luste or concupiscence; fforgetyng genders
neclegence, &amp; of neclegence es concupiscence caused, &amp; fra Concupiscence, when
it es seruyd, falls a man in to werke of all synes.  &THORN;arefore make we first &thorn;e
hert sobire, &thorn;at it cast away forgetyng: &amp; &thorn;an sal it noth falle in rekleshed; and
if it be nogth rekles, it sal wele eschew &amp; flee luste: and if he may eschewe
luste &amp; fleschly lykynges with &thorn;e help of goddis grace, he sal neuer fall in euyl
werke.&raquo;  &para; Saynt Ion sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;If a kynge wil take a cyte, he stoppis first &thorn;e water, &thorn;at &thorn;e vitayles may nogth come to &thorn;e cyte.  Rigth swa it es if a man
trauayll hym-self in fastyng &amp; in hunger: &THORN;e passione of gloteny sal perisch, &amp; his enmys &thorn;at perswys hym sal feble.&raquo;  &para; A bro&thorn;er said &thorn;us: &laquo;I am frele &amp; &thorn;e passione of lichery ouerledis me: what may I doo?&raquo;  A haly fader answerd &thorn;us: &laquo;At &thorn;e bygynnyng when &thorn;e steryng comes &amp; &thorn;ou feele &thorn;e feend speke in &thorn;i hert of lichery, answer hym nogth be flitand wordis, bot ryse vp &amp; pray god with mekenese &amp; with repentance, sayand &thorn;us: ,Ihesu goddis sone, hafe mercy
on me', &amp; stynte nogth.&raquo;  &para; A brother asked a fader: &laquo;how sal I doo?&raquo;  &amp; he answerd &thorn;us: &laquo;If &thorn;ou wil fynd rist in &thorn;is werld &amp; in &thorn;at o&thorn;er, say ylke a day: ,Whate am I?', &amp; deme nane&raquo;.  &para; A brother askid a fader how he suld wone in his congregacione.  And he answerde &thorn;us: &laquo;Rigth as on &thorn;e first day when &thorn;ou comes in, as meke &amp; as deuote, as sobire &amp; as paciente, rigth swa be all &thorn;e days of &thorn;i lyfe with &thorn;aime; &amp; tak na triste to &thorn;e of &thorn;i life: ffor whi, &thorn;are es na werse passione to &thorn;i saule &thorn;an trist in &thorn;i life &amp; fals sekyrnes, ffor whi, it es modir &amp; brynger forth of all o&thorn;er passions.&raquo;  &para; A brother said [to] a fader &thorn;us: &laquo;how may I be safe?&raquo; &amp; he answerde &thorn;us: &laquo;If &thorn;ou wille be safe: when &thorn;ou gase to any man, speke not fyrst til he aske &thorn;e.&raquo;  &para; Saynt Machary sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;If we vmbethynke vs of euyls &thorn;at has bene layd apon vs of men, &thorn;an cutte we away fra our mynd vertoue to thynke of god.  Bot if we thynke of euylls &thorn;at feendes doose to vs, &thorn;an sal we eschap alle temptaciouns.&raquo;  &para; A brother asked Pastor &thorn;us: &laquo;If I see a gud thyng, sal I tell it als fast?&raquo;  He answerd &thorn;us: &laquo;Wha sa answers or he be askyd, he doose foly; &thorn;arfor if &thorn;ou be askid, answer, ellis
be stile!&raquo;  &para; A fader sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;It nedis a saul &thorn;at wil conuersen after &thorn;e wil of Criste, for to lere trewly &thorn;at he can nogth, &amp; for to konne appertily &thorn;at he cane; &amp; if he wille nogth doo bath whene he may in tyme, he es gastly wode.&raquo;


<PB N="1: 127">

&para; Alswa: &laquo;&thorn;e bygynnyng of departyng fra god es when a man yrkes &amp; heuys with leryng &amp; heryng of goddis word: ffor when he has not appetite for to here &thorn;at
&thorn;e saul desires &amp; hungres, how lufs he god?&raquo;  &para; A fader said &thorn;us: &thorn;at hym thogth na thyng better in &thorn;is life &thorn;an a man ay blame hym-selfe &amp; reprehend
in all his werkes with-outene cesyng.  &para; Saynt Ion said &thorn;us: &laquo;Mekenes es &thorn;e
yhat to heuene-warde, &amp; our forne faders assaid be many tribulacions of
mekenes entred in to &thorn;e cyte of god.&raquo;  &para; A fader said &thorn;us: &laquo;A man &thorn;at neghes to god thurgth grace, &thorn;e mare clerely sal he see &amp; feele hym-self a synner; ffor
Ysaye &thorn;e prophete, when he saw god, &thorn;an cryed he &amp; sayd hym-self a wreche
&amp; vnclene.&raquo;  &para; A fader said &thorn;us: &laquo;Whene a thogth of pryde or of vayne-glory touchis &thorn;e, for to entre into &thorn;ine hert, raunsake wele &thorn;i consience if &thorn;ou haf kepid wele all &thorn;e bedyngs of god, If &thorn;ou luf &thorn;i enmys, If &thorn;ou be glade in &thorn;i
enmys wele-fare, If &thorn;ou be sary in his lessyng, If &thorn;ou knaw &amp; fele &thorn;i-self a
synner, a seruaund vnprofitable to &thorn;i lord god, &amp; werst of all synners; &amp; if &thorn;ou
feele of &thorn;i-self &thorn;at &thorn;ou has not &yogh;it amendid alle &thorn;i defautes in &thorn;e.  For witte
&thorn;ou wele &thorn;at swylke maner of thynkynge sall loese alle sterynges of pride.&raquo;
&para; Alswa he sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;If &thorn;ou fall in to syne thurgth temptacione of &thorn;ine enmy, blame neuer na o&thorn;er man for &thorn;i temptacioune bot anely &thorn;i-selfe, sayand &thorn;us:
,ffor myne awene preue syns &thorn;is temptacione be-fele me.'&raquo;  &para; Saynt Pastor sayd
&thorn;us: &thorn;at a mane sal honte gastly with-outene sekyng mekenes &amp; dred of god,
not as he drawes in &amp; blawes oute wynde at his nese-thrills.  &para; A bro&thorn;er askid
a fader: &laquo;how sal I wone in a place?&raquo;, and he answerd &thorn;us: &laquo;Haf whayntise with &thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be ay as a straunger, &amp; suffre nogth &thorn;i thogth haf maystry ouer &thorn;e whare-sa &thorn;ou be: &amp; &thorn;ou sal haf ryst.&raquo;  &para; Alswa he sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;If a man kepe wele his ordre &amp; his rewle, he sall nogth be troblyd.&raquo; &para; A bro&thorn;er sayd to a fader &thorn;us: &laquo;I see my-self &thorn;at my mynd es bente vp to god.&raquo;  And he answerd &thorn;us: &laquo;It es grete thyng &thorn;at, &thorn;at &thorn;i thogth be with god: bot &thorn;is es a grete[r] thyng, for to se &thorn;i-self vnder alle creatours &mdash; &thorn;at es mekenes; &amp; bodely trauayll helpes mekyll a saule &thorn;erto.&raquo;  &para; Saynt Sincletica sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;As it es inpossible a schype to be made with-outen<MILESTONE
N="73" UNIT="folio"> scharp tole, rigth sa es it inpossible a man to be sauf with-outene dred &amp; mekenes.&raquo;  &para; A fader was askid what es mekenes.  And he answerde &thorn;us: &laquo;If &thorn;ou forgife &thorn;i brother &thorn;at trespas agaynes &thorn;e or &thorn;at he aske forgifnes, &thorn;ou ert meke; and alswa mekenes es: if &thorn;ou doo gud to &thorn;aim &thorn;at dose &thorn;e harme. &amp; if a saule nogth come to &thorn;is perfeccioune, &thorn;an es it gud &thorn;at he flee &amp; kepe silence.&raquo;  &para; A fader sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;Qwen we er trauelde thurgth temptaciouns, &thorn;an er we mekyd; ffor our lorde seand our freelte, helpis &amp; defendis vs, ffor &thorn;an we crye to hym for helpe.  Bot whene we hafe ioy in our selfe, &thorn;an takis he away his proteccione fra vs, &amp; &thorn;an perische we.&raquo;  &para; Alswa he sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;Me had leuer be ouercommene with mekenes, &thorn;an for to ouercome prid.  &THORN;e heele of mane es &thorn;is, &amp; &thorn;at god askis of mane, &thorn;at a man caste all his synns befor god as if he wald offre &thorn;aim to god, &amp; late god do whate he wille.&raquo;  &para; A fader was askyd what he said of &thorn;aim &thorn;at said &thorn;ai saw aungles.  &amp; he answerde &thorn;us: &laquo;He es blyssed &thorn;at seese ay his awene syne.&raquo;  &para; A bro&thorn;er had &thorn;is condicione &thorn;at when any man dide hym any schame or dises in worde or in werke, sa mekel mare he lufde hym, &amp; ran to hym sayande &thorn;us: &laquo;Swylke maner men &thorn;at


<PB N="1: 128">

wille reproue, schame &amp; scorne o&thorn;er &amp; tell &thorn;aim &thorn;e soth, are sette in
conggregacion for-cause of correccioune, &amp; sa &thorn;ai prophete til o&thorn;er, of all &thorn;ai hurte &thorn;aim-selfe.  Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at flateres &amp; blysses men, &thorn;ay confound &thorn;aire sauls; for &thorn;e prophete says &thorn;us: ,My pupill, &thorn;ai dyssayue &yogh;ou &thorn;at says &thorn;at &yogh;e er blyssyde.'&raquo; &para; Saynt A[n]tton sayd: &laquo;If we may wyne our bro&thorn;er fra syne, &thorn;ane wyne we god; &amp; If we sclaundre our brother, we syne in Criste.&raquo;  &para; A fader says &thorn;us: &laquo;&THORN;are es na thynge better &thorn;an lufe ne mare, &thorn;at a man wille for lufe gife his awene life for his bro&thorn;er: &amp; &thorn;at es fulfillid on &thorn;is maner.  If a bro&thorn;er here a heuy worde of another brothere vnwysely sayd: If he stryfe with hym-selfe for to suffre it paciently, &thorn;at he disese nogth his bro&thorn;er agayne, &thorn;ofe he mygth do it;
or ells, if he take harme in any thyng of his bro&thorn;er: If he &yogh;eld agayne ay gud
wordes, gude chere, gude werkes to his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at dysesid hym, In charite nogth
feynand: sothly he gifs his life &amp; his saule for his brother.&raquo;  Amen.  Ihesus.  Amen.
</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<PB N="1: 129"><HEAD>Quotations from Bonaventura, R. Rolle &amp;c.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Rawlinson C 285" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD TYPE="main">Ms. Rawl. C 285</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Bone-Auenture.</HEAD><MILESTONE
N="39b" UNIT="folio">


<P>  &laquo;Continuel meditacione of &thorn;e passione of Cryste sall rewle a man in spekynge,
in thynkynge, in wyrkynge, and rayse hym into gastly felynge, and to couete to


<PB N="1: 130">

be haldene vile and to be dispysede.  His ded gyfs vs lyfe, his wondis helys vs,
his blod weschese &amp; makes vs qwyte, &thorn;e openynge of his syde with &thorn;e spere is
til vs entre to ioyne our hert to his hert.  And forthy I wile ay dwell in &thorn;e
wondys of hys handes a[n]d of his fete and of his syde continuely, &amp; &thorn;are speke til
his herte, and aske qwate I wile haue.  &THORN;ou man, trow &thorn;at I say.  If &thorn;ou oftsyth
afforce &thorn;e to entre into Criste thurgth his strayte wondys: &thorn;ou sall nogth anely
fynd ryste in saule, bot alswa &thorn;i body sal fynde wonderfull
swetenese.  Forthy I wylle clethe me in &thorn;e wondes &amp; &thorn;e passione &amp; &thorn;e reproues of Ihesu Cryste als in a clethynge, and &thorn;an his passione in als mekyll as me nedys, sall feght for me agayne &thorn;e flesche, &thorn;e werld, &amp; &thorn;e fend, &amp; all myn ennemys.  It war inpossibile &thorn;at if I war wele transfourmed in to Crist crucyfyede, &thorn;at Ine suld be his hayere in heuene.  For-&thorn;i drede &thorn;e, &thorn;e passione is sofferayne refuyte to eschew all euyls, &amp; to purchase all godes.  It is paradyse of delyces.  It rayses our thogth abouen
all erdly lykynge, and anely to ioy in Ihesu Cryste&raquo;.  Saynt Bernarde says: &laquo;Whate
es swa spedfull to hele &thorn;e wondes of &thorn;e conscience &amp; to clense &thorn;e sygth of &thorn;e
mynd, als assyduell thogth of Cryste wondys?&raquo;
</P><P>Ricard: &laquo;&THORN;e passione of Ihesu Criste confondes &thorn;e fend.  It destruys his dysaytes
&amp; his gilders.  It slokkens fleschly temptaciouns.  It clarifyse &thorn;e mynd to couete
anly Ihesu Criste lufe.  Festen in &thorn;i hert &thorn;e mynd of his passione: I wate na
thynge &thorn;at swa inwardly sal take &thorn;i hert to couete goddys lufe, and to desire &thorn;e
ioy of heuen, &amp; to despice vanites of &thorn;is werld, as stedfaste thynkynge of &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 131">

myschefe &amp; &thorn;e wondes, &amp; of &thorn;e ded of Ihesu Crist.  It wile rayse &thorn;i thogth abouen erdly likynge, &amp; make &thorn;i hert brynnand in Crystis lufe, &amp; purchase in till &thorn;i saule delitabilite &amp; sauoure of heuene.&raquo;
</P><P>&laquo;Thorowe &thorn;e passione &amp; &thorn;e wondys of Ihesu Criste we haue parfite inherdynge to gode.&raquo;  Bone-Auenture says til our lauedy saynt Mary: &laquo;Leuedy, it is vnpossibile to inter in to &thorn;e wondys of &thorn;i sone &amp; nogth inter in to &thorn;i hert: for &thorn;e wondys er sete to be ay in &thorn;i hert, as &thorn;e erres of &thorn;e wondes sal euermare be in &thorn;e body of &thorn;i sone.  Leuedy, it is swete to here speke of &thorn;e, &amp; swetter to thynke on &thorn;e:
bot allerswettest to inter in to &thorn;i hert, thorow &thorn;i son&macr; wondys.&raquo;
</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="Cambridge Dd V. 55" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="1: 129"><HEAD TYPE="main">Ms. Cambridge Dd V. 55</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub"> Bone-Aventure</HEAD><MILESTONE
N="93" UNIT="folio"><P>&laquo;COntynuel meditacion of &thorn;e passyon of Criste sal rewle a man in spekynge,
in thynkyne, in wyrkynge, and rayse hym into gastly felynge, &amp; to couete to


<PB N="1: 130">

be halden vile &amp; to be dispised.  Hys dede gyfes vs lyfe, hys woundys helis vs,
hys blode weschys vs &amp; makes vs qwyte, &thorn;e openynge of hys syde with &thorn;e
spere is till vs entre to Ioyne oure herte to hys herte.  And forthy I well dwelle
in &thorn;e woundys of hys handys and of hys fete and of his side contynuly, &amp; &thorn;ar
speke til hys herte, &amp; aske qwat I wil haue.  &THORN;ou man, trowe &thorn;at I say: If &thorn;ou
oftsythe afforse &thorn;e to entre in to Criste thorow hys strayte woundys, &thorn;ou sal
[noght] onely fynde riste in saule, bot alswa &thorn;i body sal fynde wondyrfulle swetenes.
Forthi I wille clethe me in &thorn;e woundes &amp; &thorn;e passyon &amp; &thorn;e reproues of Ihesu
Criste as in a clethynge, and &thorn;an hys passyon, in als mykel as me nedis, sal
fey&yogh;te for me agayn &thorn;e flesche, &thorn;e werlde, &amp; &thorn;e fende, &amp; alle myn ennemyes. It ware inpossible &thorn;at if I ware wele transformyd in to [Crist] crucifyed, &thorn;at Ine sulde be hys ayer in heuen.  For-&thorn;i drede &thorn;e; passio is sufferayne refute to eschew
alle yuilis &amp; to purchase alle gudes.  It is paradyse of delices.  It rayses oure
thou&yogh;te abouen alle ertheli lykynge, &amp; anely to Ioye in Ihesu Criste&raquo;. / Seynt
Bernarde says: &laquo;Qwat is so spedeful to hele &thorn;e woundys of &thorn;e conscience &amp; to
clense &thorn;e sy&yogh;the of &thorn;e mynde, as assyduell thou&yogh;the of Criste woundys?&raquo; Ricard hermete: &laquo;&THORN;e passyon of Ihesu Criste woundes &thorn;e fende, it distroyes his dissaytis &amp; hys gyldirs, it slokkens fleschely temptacions.  It clarifies &thorn;e mynde to couete anly Ihesu Criste lufe.  Festen in &thorn;in herte &thorn;e mynde of hys passyon: I wate na
thynge &thorn;at swa inwardly sal take &thorn;in herte to coued goddis lufe, and to desyre
&thorn;e Ioye of heuen, &amp; to dispyse vanytes of &thorn;is werlde, as stedefaste thynkkynge


<PB N="1: 131">

of &thorn;e myschefe &amp; &thorn;e woundes &amp; of &thorn;e dede of Ihesu Criste.  It wyl rayse &thorn;i
thou&yogh;te abouen erthely lykynge, &amp; make &thorn;i hert brynnande in Cristis luffe, &amp; purchase in til &thorn;i saule delitabilite &amp; sauour of heuen.&raquo;  &laquo;Thorowe &thorn;e passyon &amp; &thorn;e woundis of Ihesu Criste we hafe parfyte in-herdynge to god.&raquo; Bone-Auenture says til oure lady Seynt Mari: &laquo;levedi, it is vnpossible to enter in to &thorn;e woundys of &thorn;i sone &amp; nou&yogh;t enter in to &thorn;i herte: for &thorn;e woundys er set to be ay in &thorn;i herte, as &thorn;e erres of &thorn;e woundes sal euermore be in &thorn;e bodi of &thorn;i
sone.  Levedi, it is swete to here speke of &thorn;e, &amp; swetter to thynke on &thorn;e: bot alther swetteste to enter in to &thorn;i hert thorowe &thorn;i sone woundys&raquo;.  Ihesus Amen.
</P></DIV3>
</DIV2>

</DIV1><DIV1 N="Harley 1022" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="[1: 157]"><HEAD>Treatises of Ms. Harley 1022</HEAD><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Narrationes Legendariae</FOREIGN><NOTE>These two short English exempla appear in the MS alongside others in Latin.</NOTE></HEAD><MILESTONE
N="1b" UNIT="folio"><P>Cesarius tels &thorn;at a prest &thorn;at had cure of sawle, sagh a woman clade in sere
clethyngs, &amp; hade a long tayle &thorn;at scho drogh after here: in &thorn;e qwilk he sagh
a multitude of blake fendes, makand &thorn;e Imawe with &thorn;ere mowth, playand with
hende, &amp; os fyshes with-in &thorn;e nete lepande. &amp; he bade here stand still; &amp; sythen he cald &thorn;e folke, &amp; coniurede &thorn;e fendes &thorn;at &thorn;ai sulde note flee; &amp; he
praede to gode &thorn;at &thorn;e ffolk mote se &thorn;am. &amp; so &thorn;ai dyde.  &THORN;en &thorn;at wommane
sagh &thorn;at &thorn;e fendes desewede here &thorn;oro pryde of clethynge: scho &yogh;ode hom &amp; chawngyd here clothes; &amp; fro &thorn;at tyme scho was ensawmp(ul) of meknes.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In libro de dono timoris:</FOREIGN> A holy woman in France rawiste in spret sagh a Cownteyse, to wome scho was full homle, be drane to hell with deuls; &thorn;e wilk Cowntes made dull &amp; cryde: &laquo;Wo es me! wo es me, wrech! for I was chaste enogh, abstinent &amp; almesfull; &amp; for othere ynge I ame note dampned, &thorn;en for sere a-tyre, &thorn;at I lufude ouere-mekill, &amp; I left not wen I [was] beden&raquo;.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<PB N="1: 158"><HEAD>The Rule of the Life of Our Lady<NOTE>A translation of material from the <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Meditationes vitae Christi</FOREIGN>, chap. 3</NOTE></HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio">
<P>About &thorn;o mayden of qwam oure lord Ihesu Crist toke flesch &amp; blode, we may
vmthynke vs of hir lyfe.  Of qwilk &thorn;ou sal wit &thorn;at qwen sche was thre &yogh;ere alde, hir
fadur &amp; hir modur offerd hir in &thorn;o temple, &amp; &thorn;ar scho dwelled in &thorn;at degre vnto
fourtene &yogh;ere. &amp; qwat scho did &thorn;are, we may wite be reuelacions &thorn;at scho schewde


<PB N="1: 159">

to a deuout seruande of hyrs, men trow it was seint Eli&yogh;abeth, qwas fest we syng
solemply.  In qwilk reuelacions emang o&thorn;er [er] contened &thorn;ere &thorn;at folows. /
Scho sayd: &laquo;Qwen my fadur &amp; my modur left me in &thorn;o temple, I set in my hert
to haue god to my fadur: &amp; thoght deuoutle &amp; oft-tymes qwat thyng I myght


<PB N="1: 160">

do to goddys lykyng, so &thorn;at he walde vouch-saue to gyf me hys grace, and I
gert teche me &thorn;o law of my god.  &amp; of alle &thorn;o commandement&yogh; of goddis law &thorn;re
I kepyd namely in my hert, &thorn;at es: ,&thorn;ou sal luf &thorn;i lord god with alle &thorn;i hert,
with al &thorn;i saule, &amp; with alle &thorn;i thoght, &amp; with alle &thorn;i strenghes'. / Also: ,&thorn;ou sal luf &thorn;i neghbur as &thorn;i-selfe'. / Also: ,&thorn;ou sal hate &thorn;in enmy, &thorn;at es synne'. &THORN;es, scho sayde, I kepud in my saule, &amp; I set me for to gedur alle vertus &thorn;at
are conteynd [in &thorn;am]; &amp; sa I wil teche &thorn;e.  Forsoth, &thorn;at saule has na parfite vertu &thorn;at lufs noght [god] with alle his herte.  And of &thorn;is luf comes a[l] fulnes of grace.
&amp; aftur &thorn;at at &thorn;is fulnes is comen, it dwelles noght stil in &thorn;o saule, bot flowes as watur, [warne] it hates hys enmys, &thorn;at er vices &amp; synnes. / &THORN;erfor he &thorn;at wille haf grace standandly in hys possessione, hym behoues orden his hert to luf, &amp; hatredone.
&THORN;erfor I wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou do as I did.  I rase alle tymes at mydnyght, &amp; went before
&thorn;o auter of &thorn;o temple, &amp; with as mykel desire, as mykel wille, &amp; als grete
affection as I myght &amp; couth, I asked grace of alle-myghty [god] to kepe &thorn;a thre
comandementes of &thorn;o lawe: &amp; swa standand befor &thorn;o auter I made seuen
prayers til oure lorde, &thorn;o qwilk ere &thorn;ere.  Fyrst I asked grace &thorn;at I myght fulfille
&thorn;e commandement of lufyng, &thorn;at es: to luf hym with alle my hert &amp; forthurmore,
os is sayde before. / In &thorn;o secunde prayer I askyd grace &thorn;at I myght luf my
neghbur eftur &thorn;e wille &amp; plesyng of hym, &amp; &thorn;at he walde make me to luf alle
thynges &thorn;at he lufed. / In &thorn;o thrid prayer I asked &thorn;at he wald make me to hate
al thyng &thorn;at he hates. / In &thorn;o ferth prayer I askud mekenes, pacience, debonurte
&amp; myldenes, &amp; alle vertues be &thorn;o qwilk I suld be made gracious before hys
syght. / In &thorn;o fyft prayer I asked &thorn;at he wald make me [se] &thorn;at tyme in &thorn;o qwilk
&thorn;at haly virgyn sulde be borne &thorn;at suld bere goddys sone; &amp; I askyd &thorn;at he wald
kepe myne eghen &thorn;at I myght see hir, myn eres &thorn;at I myght here hir, my tunge
&thorn;at I myght looue hir, my hende &thorn;at I myght serf hir, my fete &thorn;at I myght
gang to hir seruyce, [my] kneese &thorn;at I myght worschepe goddis sone in hir
arme. / In &thorn;o sext I asked grace to be obedient to &thorn;o commandementes &amp; ordynance
[of] &thorn;o byschope of &thorn;o temple. / In &thorn;o seuent prayer I asked &thorn;at he walde
kepe &thorn;o temple &amp; alle his pepul to hys seruyce&raquo;.  &THORN;an Cristes
hand-mayden, qwen scho had hard &thorn;ere thynges, sayde: &laquo;O swete lady, ne were &&yogh;e not ful of grace &amp; of vertus?&raquo;  &THORN;an &thorn;o blyssud virgyne answerd: &laquo;Wit [for soth] &thorn;at I held me gylte, &amp; most vile, &amp; vnworthy &thorn;o grace of god, als &thorn;ou dos &thorn;i-selfe, &amp; &thorn;erfore I asked of hym grace &amp; vertu&yogh;&raquo;.  And ouer &thorn;at: &laquo;&THORN;ou trowes &thorn;at alle &thorn;e grace &thorn;at I had, &thorn;at I had it with-outen trauayle; bot it is not so.  For I say &thorn;e &thorn;at I had na grace ne gyft ne vertu of god with-outen grete trauayle, continuele prayer, brynnyng desire, depe deuocion, many teres, &amp; mykel tourmentyng; euermare thynkand, sayande, &amp; wyrkande thynges &thorn;at were plesand to hym als I couth &amp; myght&mdash;outaken &thorn;o grace of halowyng, &thorn;at I was halowed in my modur wombe&raquo;. And ouer &thorn;at scho sayd: &laquo;Wit tou for soth &thorn;at na grace comes in to any saule bot be prayer &amp; punysschyng of body; &amp; aftur &thorn;at we haue gyffen til god alle &thorn;at we may &thorn;of it be bot litel, he wil come in to our saule, bringand with hym sa hye gyftes, &thorn;at it semes &thorn;o saule to fayl in it-selfe, &amp; loses hys mynde &amp; has forgeten &thorn;at he did or sayde any thyng before plesande to god; &amp; also he semes til hys aghen sight mare foul &amp; mare worthy dispite, &thorn;an euer he was.&raquo;  Hedur lastes reuelacions.</P>

<PB N="1: 161">
<P>Sent Ierome writes of hir life on &thorn;is wyse.  He says, &laquo;&thorn;at blyssud virgyn
ordend to hir &thorn;is rewle, &thorn;at fro mornyng to vndron scho gaf hir to prayers,
&amp; fro vndron to none scho occupyed hir with weuyng wark, &amp; efturwarde fro
none scho went noght fra prayer til &thorn;o aungel appered til hir of qwase hande
scho was wont to take hir mete, &amp; so scho profited bettur &amp; bettur in wirkyng
&amp; in &thorn;o luf of god.  And it was swa &thorn;at in haly wakynges scho suld be funden
fyrst, in &thorn;o wysedome of &thorn;o lawe of god best lered, In mekenesse most meke,
In &thorn;o psalmes of Dauid most likande, In charite most gracious, In clennes mast
clene, &amp; in alle vertu most perfite.  Scho was stedfast &amp; vnremuabul, qwen scho
profit in bettur &amp; bettur.  Na man saw or harde hir euer wrath.  Ilk worde of
hir was so ful of grace, &thorn;at god was knawen in hir spech.  Scho lasted euermore
in prayer &amp; leringe of &thorn;o lawe of god.  &amp; scho was bysy about hir felause, &thorn;at
nane suld do wrang ne be proude agayn o&thorn;er.  &amp; scho blyssud god with-outen
sesyng; and for scho suld noght be takun fro &thorn;o louyng of god in haylsyng
of hir: qwat man so haylsed hir, scho gaf thankynges to god for &thorn;at haylsyng.
And of hir come fyrst &thorn;at holy men qwen &thorn;ei are haylsed &thorn;ei gyf louyng to
god.  &amp; of &thorn;o mete &thorn;at scho toke of &thorn;o aungel hand scho was fed ilk day; and
angels was sene to speke til hir, &amp; were buxome til hir als hir derlinges&raquo;.
Hedurto of Ierome.&mdash;&amp; in &thorn;o fourtende &yogh;ere &thorn;at blyssud virgyn was [spoused] to Ioseph be &thorn;e reuelacion of god, &amp; went agayn vnto Na&yogh;aret&mdash;in qwat maner it was
done, &thorn;ou may fynde in &thorn;o legende of hir natiuite.
</P></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<PB N="1: 162"><HEAD>A Tretyse of &thorn;e Stodye of Wysdom &thorn;at Men Clepen Beniamyn<NOTE>An abridged translation of Richard of St.-Victor's <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Benjamin Minor</FOREIGN></NOTE></HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="74" UNIT="folio">
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><P>A gret clerk &thorn;at man cals Richarde of Saynt Victore, in a bok &thorn;at he mas
of &thorn;e stude of wisdam, says &thorn;at two myghttes are in a mans saule, gyfyne of &thorn;e
fadere of hewen of whome all gude comes: &para; &thorn;e ton is reson, &para; &thorn;e tother is
affection: thorow reson we knawe, &para; and thorow affeccion we lufe.  Of reson
sprynges ryghtwise consales &amp; gastele wittes, &para; of affeccion sprynges hole desires
&amp; ordaynde felynges.  &para; And ryght os Rachel &amp; Lya wor both wyfes to Iacob, ryghtso mans saule for lyght of knawyng in &thorn;e reson, &amp; swetnes of luf in &thorn;e affeccion, is sposed vnto god.  &para; Be Iacobe is god vndurstanden, &para; be Rachel is vndurstanden reson, &para; be Lya affeccion.  &para; Aythere of &thorn;es wyfs toke &thorn;ame a mayden: Rachel tok Bala, &para; and Lya tok &YOGH;elpha.  &para; Bala was a gret ianglere, and &YOGH;elfa was ay dronkon and thryste.  Be Bala is vndurstanden ymaginacion, &thorn;e wilk is serwande to reson, os Bala to Rachell; be &YOGH;elfa is vndurstanden sensualite, &thorn;e wilk is
seruande to affeccion, os &YOGH;elfa was to Lya.  &para; And in so mekill are &thorn;es maydens
nedfull to &thorn;ar laydes, &thorn;at with-outon &thorn;am all &thorn;is warlde moghtnot serwe &thorn;am
to pay: ffor wy, with-outon ymaginacion reson may noght knaw, &para; and
with-outon sensualite affeccion may noght fele.  &para; And &yogh;ite ymaginacion cryse so
vnconandle in &thorn;e erse of oure hert, &thorn;at for oght &thorn;at reson here lady may do,
&para; &yogh;ite scho may not still here: &amp; &thorn;erfor oft-tymes wen we pray, so mone sere
fantasies of ill thogthes cryse in oure hertes, &thorn;at o no wise we may be oure oghon
myghtes dryf &thorn;am away.  &para; Ande &thorn;us is it wele prowede &thorn;at Bala is a foule
ianglere.  &para; Ande also sensualite is eweremore thryste, &thorn;at all at affeccion, here
lady, may forthe, may not sclokkune here thryst.  &para; &THORN;e drynk &thorn;at scho
desires is &thorn;e luf of fleshle, kyndle, &amp; warldle delites, of &thorn;e wilk ay &thorn;e more


<PB N="1: 163">

scho drynkes &thorn;e sarre scho thrystes, ffor wy, forto fill &thorn;e appetyt of &thorn;e
sensualite, all &thorn;is warlde may note suffyse: and &thorn;erfore is ite &thorn;at oft-tymes wen we
praye or thynk o god or gastle gudes, we walde fayn feill &thorn;e swetnes of luf in
oure sawle &amp; &yogh;ite may we note, so are we besy to fede &thorn;e concupiscens of oure
sensualite&mdash;for euermore it is gredele askande, and we haf a fleshle compassion
&thorn;erof.  &para; And &thorn;us is it wele prowede &thorn;ate &YOGH;elfa is ay dronkune &amp; &thorn;reste.  And os Lya consewed of Iacob &amp; broght forth seuen childer, &para; and Rachel consewed
of Iacob &amp; broght forth two childere, &para; [&] &YOGH;elfa conseuede &amp; broght forth two childer, &para; and Bala conseued of Iacob &amp; broght forth two childere: &para; rightso affeccion consewes &thorn;oro grace of gode &amp; brynges forth sewen vertu&yogh;, [os
sensualite conseues &thorn;oro grace of god &amp; brynges forth two vertu&yogh;], &para; also
&thorn;e reson &thorn;orou &thorn;e grace of gode consaues &amp; brynges forth two vertu&yogh;, &para; and os ymaginacion conseuese &thorn;oro &thorn;e grace of gode &amp; brynges forth two vertu&yogh; or
two behaldynges.  &para; And &thorn;e names of &thorn;es childer and &thorn;es vertu&yogh; sall be knawne
by &thorn;is fygure &thorn;at felouse:

&para; Hosband Iacob: Gode
Wyf Rachel: Reson
Maydyn Bala: Ymaginacion
Wyf Lya: Affeccion
Mayden &YOGH;elfa: Sensualite

Sons of Iacob of Lya are
&thorn;es sewen: Ruben: Dred
of payne.  Symeon: Soro
of syne.  Leuy: Hop o[f]
forgifnes.  Iudas: Luf of
ryghtwisnes.  Ysachare:
Ioy of inwarde swetnes.
&YOGH;abulon: Hatreden of
syne.  Dyna: Ordaynde
schame.

Sons of Iacob of &YOGH;elfa are
&thorn;es: Gad: Abstinens.
Assere: Paciens.

Sons of Iacob of
Rachelreson: Iosep: Discrecion.
Beniamin: Contemplacion.

Sons of Iacob of
Bala-imaginacion: Dan: Syght of
payn at come.  Neptalym:
Sight of ioy at come.

</P><P>&para; Here it is schewed of Iacob &amp; is wyfes, &thorn;are maydens, &amp; &thorn;are childere.
&para; Here it is to schewe o wate manere &thorn;ai were geten, &amp; in wate ordure.  &para; First of &thorn;e childer of Lya, for we rede &thorn;at cho consewede first.  &para; &THORN;e sons of Iacob
of Lya are notels bot ordaynd affeccions or felynges in a mans saule, for wy,
if &thorn;ai wore vnordaynd, &thorn;en were &thorn;ai note is sonse.  &para; &THORN;e sewen childere of Lya
are sewen vertu&yogh;, for vertu is not els bot a ordaynde &amp; a mesurde felyng of a
mans saule.  &thorn;en is mans felyng in saule ordaynde wen it is of &thorn;at yng &thorn;at it
suld be; &thorn;en is it mesurde wen it is so mekill os it sulde.  &para; &THORN;es felynges in a mans
saule may be now ordaynde &amp; now vnordaynde, now mesurde &amp; now vnmesurde:
&para; bot wen &thorn;ai are mesurde &amp; ordaynde, &thorn;en are &thorn;e[i] calde &thorn;e sons of Iacob.
</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Here it is to say how drede sprynges in a mans affeccion.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;e first child &thorn;at Lya consewed of Iacob is Ruben, &thorn;at is drede, and for&thorn;i
it is wreten in &thorn;e psalme: &laquo;begynnyng of wisdam drede of oure lorde.&raquo;  &para; &THORN;is is &thorn;e first feld vertu in a mans affeccion, with-out&omacr;n &thorn;e wilk non othere may be
hade.  &para; And &thorn;erfor woso desyres to haf sclyk a son, hym be-hose besile &amp; oft
behald &thorn;e eweles &thorn;at he has don; &para; he sall on o parte ynk &thorn;e gretnes of is gilt,
and on a nother party &thorn;e power of &thorn;e domesman.  Of sclyk a consideracion
spry[n]ges drede, &thorn;at is at say he &thorn;at Ruben, &thorn;at &thorn;orou reght is cald &laquo;&thorn;e sone
of syght&raquo;.  &para; For weterle is he blynde &thorn;at sese not &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at are to comme, and dredes not to syne.  &para; And wele is Ruben calde son of syght: ffor wen he


<PB N="1: 164">

was borne, is modere sayde: &para; &laquo;Gode has sen my meknes&raquo;, &amp; mans saule in slik consideracion of is old synes &amp; &thorn;e power of his domesman, begynes &thorn;en trule to se gode be felyng of drede, &amp; also to be sen of gode be rewardyng of pyte.
</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Here it is to say howe sorowe spryngese.</HEAD>

<P>Wyles Ruben waxes, Symeon is borne, for aftere dred it nedes &thorn;at soro
come sone.  For ay &thorn;e mor man dredes &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at he has deserwede, [&thorn;e]
bytterlier he sorose &thorn;e syne &thorn;at he has done.  &para; Lya in &thorn;e byrth of Symeon sayd:
&laquo;oure lorde has harde me ben hade in despit&raquo;, &para; and for&thorn;i is Symeon [cald]
&laquo;heryng&raquo;: For a man wen he bitterle sorose &amp; dispyse is olde syne, he begynnes to be herde of gode, &para; and also to here &thorn;is blissed sentence of godes oghon
mowth: &para; &laquo;Blissed be &thorn;ai &thorn;at sorou, for &thorn;ai sall be comforde.&raquo;  For in wat houre a synere sorows &amp; turnes fro is syne, he sall be sauf, &thorn;is witnes hole
wryte.  And also be Ruben is he mekede, &amp; be Symeon is he conuertede &amp; has
compuncioun of ters; &para; bot os Dauid witnes in &thorn;e psalme: &laquo;Hert contrit &amp; meked god salnot despise&raquo;, &amp; with-outon doute slik soro is trew comforth.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[&para; Here is to say of hop.]</HEAD>

<P>Bot i pray &thorn;e wat comforth may be to &thorn;o &thorn;at trule dredes &amp; bitterle sorose &thorn;er
olde synes, oght bot a trew hope of forgyfnes?  &THORN;e wilk is &thorn;e &thorn;ryd son of Iacob,
&thorn;at is Leuy, &thorn;e wilk is calde in &thorn;e store &laquo;a doyng-to&raquo;; for wen &thorn;e first two childer, drede &amp; sorou, are gifyne of gode to a mans saule, with-outon doute &thorn;e &thorn;ryde, &thorn;at is hope, sall not be delaide, bot he sall be don to, os &thorn;e store wittnes of Leuy
&thorn;at wen is two brether Ruben &amp; Semeon were gyffen to &thorn;are moder Lya, he &thorn;is
Leuy was done to.  &para; Take kepe o &thorn;is &thorn;at he was don to, &amp; not gyfen: &para; and
for&thorn;i is it sayde, &thorn;at aman sall not presume of hop of forgifnes befor-tym &thorn;at
his hert be mekede in drede &amp; conuertede ine sorowe&mdash;with-outon &thorn;es two hope
is presumpcion, &amp; were &thorn;er two are, hop is don to.  &para; And &thorn;us aftere sorow sone
comes comforth, [os] Dauid tels in &thorn;e psalme &thorn;at &laquo;after &thorn;e mekelnes of my sorow
in my hert, he says to oure lorde, [&thorn;y] comforthes haue gladed [my] saule&raquo;.
&para; And &thorn;erfor is it &thorn;at &thorn;e holygost is cald paraclitus, &thorn;at is comforthere, for he
vochessaufe to comforth a soreful gost.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Here is to say of [luffe].</HEAD>

<P>Fro now forth begynnes a maner of homelenes forto grofe be-twyx god &amp; manes saul, &amp; also a maner of kyndlyng of luf, in so mekill &thorn;at oft-tymes he
feles hym not only be viset of gode &amp; comford in is comyng, &para; bot oft-tymes
al-so he feles hym fild with anunspekabull ioy.  &THORN;is homlenese &amp; kyndlyng of
lufe first feld Lya wen, after &thorn;at Leuy was borne, scho cryde &amp; saide with a
gret ioy: &para; &laquo;Now sall my hosband be coupuld to me.&raquo;  &THORN;e trew spose of oure saule is gode, &para; and &thorn;en are we trule cupuld to gode, wen we dragh nere hym
be sothfast luf: &amp; reght os after hop comes luf, so after Leuy comes Iudas, &thorn;e
ferth son.  Lya in is birth cride &amp; sayd: &para; &laquo;Nowe sall i schryf to oure lorde&raquo;, &amp; &thorn;erfor in &thorn;e stori is Iudas calde &laquo;schryft&raquo;: &para; also man saule in &thorn;is degre of luf offers it clerle to gode and says: &laquo;now sall i scryf to oure lorde&laquo;; for befor &thorn;is felyng of luf in a mans saule all &thorn;at he dose is don more for agh &thorn;en for


<PB N="1: 165">

luf, &para; bot in &thorn;is state a mans saule feles gode so swet, so mercifull, so gud,
so curtas, tru &amp; kynd, so fathfull, so lufle &amp; so homle, &thorn;at &thorn;are lefes no yng
in hym, &para; might, wytte, kunyng or will, &thorn;atyn he offers it clerle, frele, and
homele to hym.  &para; &THORN;is schryft is not onle of syne, bot of &thorn;e gudnes of gode: gret
tokunyng of lufe is &para; wen a man tels to gode &thorn;at he is gode; of &thorn;is schryft
spekes Dauid in &thorn;e sautere &amp; says: &laquo;mas it knawn to gode, for he is gude&raquo;.&mdash;</P><P>&para; Nowe haf we sayde of &thorn;e faure sonse of Lya, &para; and after &thorn;es scho laft
beryng of childer till a nothere tyme.  And so a mans saule wenes &thorn;at it suffice
to it, wen it feles &thorn;at it lufs [&thorn;e trew godes].  &amp; so it is to saluacion, bot not
to perfeccion.  &para; For it fals to a perfite saule [both] to be enflawmede with &thorn;e fire
of luf in &thorn;e affeccion, &amp; also to be illumynde with lyght of knawyng in &thorn;e reson.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Here is to say of [doubull syght in ymaginacion].</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;us wen Iudas was borne, &thorn;at so to say, luf &amp; desire of vnsen trew gudes
is rysand &amp; waxand in a mans affeccion: &thorn;en cowates Rachell to bere some
childere, &thorn;at is to say, &thorn;en cowat&yogh; reson to knaw &thorn;o ynges at &thorn;e affeccion
feles.  &para; For [os] ite fals to Lya-affeccion forto luf, so it fals to Rachel-reson to
knawe.  Of Lya-affeccion sprynges ordand &amp; mesurde felynges, &para; and of
Rachel-reson sprynges reght conyng &amp; cleen vnderstandyng.  &amp; &thorn;e more &thorn;at Iudas
waxhes, &thorn;at is to say luf, &para; so mekill more desires Rachil beryng of childere, &thorn;at
is to say, reson stodys after knawyng.  &para; Bot wo is he &thorn;at wotnot how harde
it is &amp; nerhand vnpossibull to a fleshle saule &thorn;e wilk is &yogh;itte rude in gastele
studys, for to ryse in knawyng of vnseabull ynges, &amp; forto sete &thorn;e egh of
contemplacion in gastle ynges?  &para; Forwy, a saule &thorn;at is &yogh;it ruyde &amp; fleshle, knaws not &yogh;itt bot bodele ynges, &amp; no yng comes &yogh;itt to &thorn;e mynde bot seabull ynges. &amp; neuer&thorn;elese &yogh;ite it lokes inwarde os it may, &amp; &thorn;at at it maynot &yogh;ite se clerle be gastle knawyng, it thynkes be ymaginacion.  &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e cause wy Rachel hade first childer of her maydyn, &thorn;en of her-self: and so it is &thorn;at
all-if a mans saule maynot &yogh;it gete &thorn;e lyght of gostle knawyng in &thorn;e reson, &yogh;it it
ynk it swete to hald &thorn;e mynde of gode &amp; gastele ynges in ymaginacion.  Os be
Rachel is vnderstand reson, so be her maydyn Bala is vndurstane ymaginacion.
&para; And &thorn;erfor reson schewes &thorn;at it is more profetabull forto ynk on gastele
ynges wat so &thorn;a be, &yogh;e if it be in kyndelyng of oure desire with some fa[i]re
ymaginacion, &thorn;en it is forto ynk of vanites &amp; desewabull ynges of &thorn;e warlde.
And for&thorn;i of Bala wer borne &thorn;es two: &para; Dan &amp; Neptalym.  Dan is to say syght
of paynes to come, and Neptalym syght of ioy to come.  &para; &THORN;es two childer are
full nedfull &amp; spedfull to a werkand saule: &thorn;e tone, to putt don ill sugestions
of synes, be syght of payne &thorn;at is to come; &para; so it fals to &thorn;e tother brother
Neptalym for to rays vppe oure willes in werkyng of gude &amp; in kyndelyng of
holy desires, be syght of ioye &thorn;at is to come.  &para; And &thorn;erfor holy men wen &thorn;ai
are sterde to vnlefull ynges be inrysyng of any foule &thorn;oght: als oft &thorn;ai seten
befor &thorn;er mynde &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at are to come, &para; and so &thorn;ai scloknen &thorn;are
temptacion in &thorn;e begynnyng or it come to any foule delite in &thorn;are saule; and als ofte


<PB N="1: 166">

os &thorn;are deuocion &amp; &thorn;er lykyng in gode &amp; in gastle ynges seses and waxes cold
&mdash;als oft-tymes in &thorn;is lyf it fales for corupcion of &thorn;e flesh &amp; mone other skilles:
als oft &thorn;ai set befor &thorn;are mynde &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at is to come, &amp; so &thorn;ai kyndel[s] &thorn;er
will with holy desire, &amp; distrose &thorn;er temptacion in &thorn;e begynnyng or it come to any
hirkyng or hewenes of sclauth.  And for&thorn;i [&thorn;at] with Dan we dampne mone vnlefull
&thorn;oghtes, &thorn;erfor is he wel calde in &thorn;e stori &laquo;dome&raquo;, and also is fader Iacob sayd of hym &thorn;us: &laquo;Dan sall deme his folk&raquo;.  &amp; also it is sayde in &thorn;e stori wen Bala broght forth Dan, &para; Rachel sayde: &laquo;oure lorde has demed me,&raquo; &thorn;at is to say, oure lorde has euend me with my sistere Lya: &para; and &thorn;us says reson, wen &thorn;e ymaginacion has getyn &thorn;e syght of payne &thorn;at is to come, &thorn;at oure lorde has
ewende her with her sister affeccion; &para; and &thorn;us scho say[s]e, for scho ha[s]e
syght of payne in her ymaginacion, off &thorn;e wilk scho hade drede &amp; sorow in
here felyng.  &para; And &thorn;en after come Neptalym, &thorn;at is to say syght of [Ioye] &thorn;at
is to come: and in his byrth spak Rachel &amp; sayde: &laquo;I am made lik to my
sistere Lya,&raquo; &amp; for&thorn;i is Neptalym cald in &thorn;e stori &laquo;lyknes&raquo;.  &para; And &thorn;us says reson &thorn;at scho is made lik to hir sister affeccion, ffor were scho hade getyn hope &amp; luf of ioy to come in her felyng, scho ha[s]e getyn syght of ioy to come in here
ymaginacion.  &para; Iacob sayd of Neptalyme &thorn;at he was &laquo;a herte sende oute, gyfand
speches of farehede&raquo;.  &para; So it is &thorn;at wen we ymagyn of &thorn;e ioys of hewen, we say &thorn;at &thorn;or is faire in hewen; ful wondurfulle kyndyls Neptalym oure saule with holy
desyre, als oft os we ymagyn of &thorn;e worthines &amp; &thorn;e farehed of &thorn;e ioes of hewen.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Here it is to say of doubull [vertu in sensualite].</HEAD>

<P>Wen Lya sagh &thorn;at Rachel here sister made gret ioy of &thorn;es two basterdese
born of Bala her maydyne, &para; scho cald forth here madyne &YOGH;elfa, to pute to
hire hosband Iacob: &thorn;at scho moght mak ioy with here sister, hafand other two
bastardes getyn of here mayden &YOGH;elfa.  &para; And &thorn;us it is semle in a mans saule
forto be, &thorn;at fro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at reson has refrened &thorn;e gret ianglyng of
ymaginacion &amp; has puttude here to be vndurloute to gode, &amp; so to ber some frute in
helpyng of here knawyng, reghtso &thorn;at &thorn;e affeccion refrene &thorn;e lust &amp; &thorn;e &thorn;ryste
of &thorn;e sensualite &amp; mak here to be vndurlout to gode, &amp; so to bere some frut
in helpyng of here felyng.  &para; Bot wat frut may scho bere, oght bot &thorn;at scho
[lerne to] lyf a-temperely in eyse ynges, and paciently in vneyse ynges?  &para; &thorn;es
are &thorn;e childer of &YOGH;elfa, Gad &amp; Assere: Gad is abstinens, Assere is paciens.  Gad
is titter borne, &amp; Assere latter, &para; ffor first it nedes &thorn;at we be a-temperde in
oureself with discret abstinence, &thorn;at after we bere outward deseys in strenght of
paciens.  &para; &THORN;es are &thorn;e childer &thorn;at &YOGH;elfa broght forth in sorow, for in abstinens
&amp; paciens &thorn;e sensualite es [punyst in &thorn;e flesch; bot &thorn;at at es sorow to &thorn;e
sensualite] torne[s] to mekill comforthed &amp; blise to &thorn;e affeccion: and &thorn;erfor it
is &thorn;at wen Gade was borne, Lya cride &amp; saide: &laquo;happele&raquo;, &amp; for&thorn;i is Gad cald &laquo;happenes&raquo; or &laquo;selenes&raquo;; &para; and so it is wele sayd &thorn;at abstinens in &thorn;e sensualite is selines in &thorn;e affeccion, &para; ffor why ay &thorn;e lesse &thorn;at &thorn;e sensualite is delited in here luste, &thorn;e more swetnes feles &thorn;e affeccion in here lufe.  &para; Also after wen Asser was borne, Lya sayd: &laquo;&thorn;is sall be for my blyse&raquo;, &amp; for&thorn;i was Asser calde in &thorn;e stori &laquo;blyssed&raquo;; and so it is wele sayde &thorn;at paciens in &thorn;e sensualite is


<PB N="1: 167">

blise in &thorn;e affeccion, &para; ffor wy ay &thorn;e more deseys &thorn;at &thorn;e sensualite suffurs, &thorn;e more blisede is &thorn;e saule in &thorn;e affeccion.  &para; And &thorn;us be abstinens &amp; paciens we salnot only vndurstand a-temperaunce in mete &amp; drynke &amp; suffuryng of outwarde tribulacion, &para; bot also of all maner fleshle, kyndle, and warldle delite, &amp; all manere dyseys bodele or gastele, with-ine or with-outon, resonabull or
vnresonabull, &thorn;at be any of oure wittes tourment&yogh; or delites &thorn;e sensualite.  On &thorn;is wis bers &thorn;e sensualite frut in help of affeccion, here layde.  Mikell pese &amp; rest is in
&thorn;at saule &thorn;at nothere is dronkune in &thorn;e lu[st] of &thorn;e sensualite, ne grutche[s] in
&thorn;e payne &thorn;arof; &thorn;e first of &thorn;es is getyn be Gade, &amp; &thorn;e later be Asser.  &para; Here it is to wite &thorn;at firste was Rachel maydyn putte to &thorn;e husbande or &thorn;e madyn
of Lya: and for &thorn;is skill, for trule, bot &thorn;e iangelyng of ymaginacion, &thorn;at is
to say &thorn;e in-rennyng of vayn thoghtes, be ferst refrende, with-outon doute &thorn;e
lust of &thorn;e sensualite maynote be atemperde; &amp; &thorn;erfor wo-so will abstene hym
fro fleshle &amp; warldele luste, hym behose first seldome or neuer ynk any wayn
thoght.  &para; And also neuer in &thorn;is lyf may a man perfitle despyse &thorn;e eyse of
&thorn;e flesh &amp; noght drede &thorn;e dyseyse, bot if he haf bisele behalden &thorn;e medes
&amp; paynes &thorn;at are to come.  &para; Bot here it is to wite how with &thorn;es fawer sons of
&thorn;es two maydens &thorn;e cite of oure consciens is kepude wonderfule fro all
temptacion.  For ilk temptacion authere it ryses with-ine be &thorn;oght, or els with.outon
be some of oure fife wittes.  &para; Bot with-ine sall Dan &laquo;deme&raquo; &amp; dampne ill &thorn;oghtes be drede of payne, &para; ande with-outon sall Gade putt agayne fals delites
be vse of abstinens; Dan wakes with-in, &amp; Gad with-outon.  And also &thorn;are other
two brethere helpys &thorn;ame full mekill: &para; Neptalym makis pes within with Dan,
and Assere bydes Gad haf no drede of is enmyse.  Dan flays &thorn;e hert with
vgsomnes of hell, &para; and Neptalym cherisses it with hetynges of hewenle blys.
&para; Also Assere helpes is brother with-owt&omacr;n, so &thorn;at &thorn;orou &thorn;am both &thorn;e cite wall is not brokune: Gad haldes oute eys, &amp; Assere pursewes diseys.  Asser sone
desawes is enmy wen he brynges to mynde &thorn;e paciens of is fader(!) &amp; &thorn;e hetyng of
Neptalym, &amp; &thorn;us oft-tyms ay &thorn;e moe enmys &thorn;at he has, &thorn;e more mater he has
of ouercommyng.  &amp; &thorn;erfor it is &thorn;at wen he has owercommune his enmys, &thorn;at is to
say &thorn;e aduersites of &thorn;e warld, sone he turnes hym to hys brothere Gad, to help to
stroy his enmyse: &amp; with-outon fayle fro he be common, sone &thorn;ai turne bak &amp; flene. &para; &THORN;ere enmys of Gade are fleshle delites: bot trule fro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at a man haf pacience in &thorn;e payne of his abstinence, fals delite fyndes no wonyng-place in hym.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>How ioy of inwarde swetnes rises in a mans saul.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;us wen &thorn;e enmyse fleyse, &amp; &thorn;e cite of conscience is made pesebule, &thorn;en
begynnes a man to prof wat &laquo;&thorn;e hegh peise of gode is &thorn;at passes all mans witte&raquo;: &para; and for&thorn;i it is &thorn;at Lya left beryng ofe childere vnto &thorn;is tyme &thorn;at Gad &amp; Aser wor borne of &YOGH;elfa her maydyn.  For trule bot if it be so &thorn;at a man haf refrende &thorn;e luste of is fife wittes in is sensualite be abstinence &amp; paciens, he sall neuer feile inwarde swetnes &amp; trew ioy in gode &amp; gastele ynges in &thorn;e affeccion.  &THORN;is is Isachare &thorn;e fifte sone of Lya, &thorn;e wilk in stori is cald &laquo;mede&raquo;, ffor [&thorn;is] ioy is &thorn;e taste of &thorn;e blise of hewen, &thorn;e wilk is endles meyde of a deuote saule,
bygynnande here.  &para; Lya in &thorn;e byrth of &thorn;is childe sayd: &laquo;god has gyfyn me


<PB N="1: 168">

mede, ffor-&thorn;i &thorn;at i haf gifyn my maydyn to my hosband in beryng of childer&raquo;:
&para; and so it is &thorn;at [if] we gere oure sensualite bere frute in abstenyng it fro all
maner of fleshle, kyndle, &amp; warld[l]e delyte, and in frutfull suffuryng of all
fleshle &amp; warldle diseyse, &para; ffor&thorn;i oure lorde of is gret mercy gyfes vs ioy of
vnspekabull &amp; inwarde swetnes in oure affeccion, in erls of &thorn;e sowerayne ioy &amp; &thorn;e mede of &thorn;e kyngdam of hewen.  &para; Iacob sayd of Isachare &thorn;at he was &laquo;a
strang asse dwelland be-twyx &thorn;e termes&raquo;: and so it is &thorn;at a man in &thorn;is stat, &amp; &thorn;at feles &thorn;e erles of ay-lastand ioy in his affecion, is os a nasse, strang, &amp; dwelland be-tweyn &thorn;e termes, &para; For&thorn;i &thorn;at, be he newer so filede in gastele
gladnes &amp; ioye in gode, &yogh;itt for corupcion of &thorn;e fleshe in &thorn;is dedle lyf hym
behose bere &thorn;e charge of &thorn;e dedle body, os hungur, &thorn;ryst, sclep &amp; colde &amp; other mone, for &thorn;e wilk he is lykynde to a nasse os in body: &para; Bot [os] in saule
he is strong for to stroy alle &thorn;e passions &amp; &thorn;e lust&yogh; of &thorn;e flesh be pacience &amp; abstinence in &thorn;e sensualite, and be habundans of gastle ioy &amp; swetnes in &thorn;e
affeccion.  &para; And also a saule in &thorn;is state is dewelland be-twex &thorn;e termes of
dedely lyf &amp; vndedle.  He &thorn;at dwels be-twyx termes, has nerhand forsakene
dedlenes bot not fulle, &amp; has nerhande geten vndedlenes bot not fully: &para; For
wiles hym nedes &thorn;e gudes of &thorn;is warld os met &amp; drynk &amp; clethyng, os fals to
ilk a man &thorn;at lyffes, &yogh;itt is a foyte in &thorn;is dedely lyf; &amp; for gret habundans of
gastele ioy and swetnes in gode &thorn;at he fels not selden bot ofte, he has his
othere fote in &thorn;e vndedle lyfe.  &THORN;us i trow &thorn;at saynt Paule ferde wen he sayde:
&laquo;Wo sall delyuer me of &thorn;is dedle body?&raquo;  &amp; wen he sayde &thorn;us: &laquo;I cowet to be losede &amp; to be with Criste.&raquo;  &para; Ande &thorn;us dose &thorn;e saule &thorn;at feles Isachare in is affeccion, &thorn;at is to say &thorn;e ioy of inwarde swetnes &thorn;e wilk is vndurstanden be Isachare: it enforses it to forsak &thorn;is wreched lyf, bot it maynot; it cowates to enter &thorn;e blissed lyf, bot it maynot: it dos &thorn;at it may &amp; &yogh;itt it dwells be-twyx &thorn;e termes.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; How hatredyn of syn rysis in mans affeccion.</HEAD>

<P>Ande erfore is it &thorn;at after Isachare &YOGH;abulon is borne, &thorn;e wilk is to say
hatredyn of syne.  &para; And here it is to say &amp; witt wy &thorn;at hatredyne of syne is
nermore feld in a mans affeccion or &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at gastele ioy of inwarde swetnes
be feld in &thorn;e affeccion, &amp; &thorn;is is &thorn;e skill: &para; ffor or &thorn;is tyme was newere &thorn;e tru cause of hatredyne felde in &thorn;e affeccion.  For &thorn;e felyng of gastle ioy teches
a man wat syne harmes &thorn;e saule, and all after &thorn;at &thorn;e harme in &thorn;e saule is felede
mekill or lytyll, &thorn;are-after is &thorn;e hatereden mesurd more or less vnto &thorn;e harmande.
&para; Bot when a saule be grace of gode &amp; long trauele is comon to felyng of
gastle ioy in god, &thorn;at it fels &thorn;at syne has ben &thorn;e cause of &thorn;e delayyng &thorn;erof;
&para; and als wen he feles &thorn;at he maynot last allway in &thorn;e felyng of gastle ioy for
corupcion of &thorn;e flesh of &thorn;e wilk corupcion syn is &thorn;e cause: &thorn;en he ryses with a
strong felyng of hateredyne agayn alle syne &amp; &thorn;e kynde of syne.  &THORN;is felyng taght
Dauid vs to hafe were he says: &para; &laquo;Bes wroth &amp; wille &yogh;e not syne&raquo;, [&thorn;at is: bes wroth with syne, bot not], with &thorn;e kynde; &para; ffor kynde sters to &thorn;e deyde bot not to [syne].  &para; And here it is to witte &thorn;at &thorn;is wrath is not contrare to charite, &para; bot charite teches how it sall be hade both in a mans self &amp; in is ewen-criste[n]: &para; For a man suld not hat syne so &thorn;at he distroy his kynd, [bot so &thorn;at he distroy &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 169">

syne &amp; &thorn;e appetyte of syne in his kynde]; &para; and als anentes oure ewen-cristen, vs
ogh to hate syne in hym, &amp; to luf hym; and of &thorn;is hateredyn spekes Dauid in &thorn;e
psalme &amp; says: &laquo;with perfyte hateredyn i hatede &thorn;ame&raquo;, &amp; in another psalme he says &thorn;at &laquo;he had in hatredyn all wykked ways&raquo;.  &THORN;us is it wile prowede [wy] or &thorn;at &YOGH;abulon was borne, Iudas &amp; Isachare wor both borne: &para; For bot if a man haf had charite &amp; gastle ioy in is felyng first, he may on no wise feile &thorn;is perfyt hateredyn in his affeccion; for Iudas, &thorn;at is charite, teches vs how we sall hate
syne in oure-self &amp; in oure brethere, and Isachare, &thorn;at is gastele felyng of ioy
in gode, teches vs whi we sall hate syne in oure-self &amp; in oure brethere; Iudas,
i. charite, bydes vs hate syne &amp; luf &thorn;e kynde, ande Isachare i. gastle felyng,
stroy syne &amp; sawe &thorn;e kynde.  &amp; &thorn;us it fales forto be &thorn;at &thorn;e kynde may be made strong in gode &amp; gostle ynges be perfyte hatredyn &amp; stroyng of syne.  And herfor in &thorn;e stori is &YOGH;abulon calde &laquo;a dwellyng-stede of strenght&raquo;, and Lya in his birth seyd: &laquo;My hosband sall now dwell with me.&raquo;  &para; And so it is &thorn;at gode, &thorn;e trew hosband of oure saule, is dwelland in &thorn;at saule, strenthand it in &thorn;e affeccion with gastele ioy and swetnes in his luf, &thorn;at trauels bysyle to distroy syne in
&thorn;ame-self and in other be perfyte hateredyn of &thorn;e syne &amp; all &thorn;e kynde of syne.  And
&thorn;us is it at say how &YOGH;abulon is borne.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; How ordend schame ryses in a mans sawle.</HEAD>

<P>Bot all-&thorn;of &thorn;at a saule &thorn;oro grace feile in it perfite hateredyne of syne, wether
it &yogh;it may lyf with-outon syne?  nay, sekerle, &amp; for&thorn;i no man presume of
hymself, syne &thorn;e apustull says &thorn;us &thorn;at &laquo;if we say we haf no syne, we deceyf
oure-self, &amp; sothfastnes is not in vs&raquo;; &para; and also saynt Austyn says &thorn;at he dare say &thorn;er is non lyfand with-outon syne.  &para; And i pray &thorn;e, wo is &thorn;at &thorn;at synes note in ignorance?  &YOGH;e &amp; oft-syth it fals &thorn;at gode suffurs &thorn;oo men to fall grewosle be &thorn;e wilk he has ordaynd other mens errours to be regthede, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may lerne be &thorn;er oghon fallyng hou mercyfull &thorn;ai sall be in amendment of other.  &amp; for &thorn;i &thorn;at oft-tymes men fals grewosle in &thorn;e same synes &thorn;at &thorn;ai moste hate, &thorn;erfor
of hateredyn of syn springes ordeynd scham in a mans saule, &amp; so it is &thorn;at after
&YOGH;abulon was Dyna borne.  Os be &YOGH;abulon &thorn;e hatredyn of syne, so be Dyna we
vnderstande orden[d] scham for syne.  &para; Bot witt will: he &thorn;at feild nere &YOGH;abulon,
felde neuer &yogh;itt Dyna.  &para; Ill men haue a maner of scham, bot it is not &thorn;is ordeynd
scham, for whi, &amp; &thorn;ai hade perfytte scham of syne, &thorn;ai suldnote so customabull
do it with will &amp; awysment; &para; bot &thorn;ai schame more with a foule cloth o &thorn;are
body, &thorn;en with a foule &thorn;ought in &thorn;er saule.  Bot wat so &thorn;o be &thorn;at wenys &thorn;o has
getyn Dyna, ynk wethere &thorn;e wald schame als mekill &amp; a foul thoght were in &thorn;i
hert, os &thorn;e wald &amp; &thorn;o wore [mad to] stand naked befor &thorn;e kyng &amp; al is rewme;
&amp; sikerly, witte &thorn;o wele &thorn;at &thorn;o has not &yogh;itt getyn ordeynde schame in &thorn;i felyng, if so be &thorn;at &thorn;o haf les schame with &thorn;i foule herte &thorn;en with &thorn;i foule body, &amp; if &thorn;ou &thorn;ink more schame with &thorn;i foule body in syght of men &thorn;en with &thorn;i foule
hart in syght of &thorn;e kyng of hewen &amp; of all his angels &amp; &thorn;e holey santes of
hewene.&mdash;&para; Lo, now is it sayde of &thorn;e sewen childer of Lya be &thorn;e wilk are
vndurstane sewen maners of affeccions in a mans saule; &thorn;e wilk may be now
ordaynde &amp; nowe vnordynde, now mesurde &amp; now vnmesurde, bot wen &thorn;ai are


<PB N="1: 170">

ordaynde &amp; mesurd, &thorn;en are &thorn;ai vertu&yogh; &amp; wen &thorn;ai are vnordend &amp; vnmesurde, &thorn;en are &thorn;ai vices.  &para; &THORN;us behose a man haf warnes &thorn;at &thorn;ai be not onle ordende, bot also mesurde.  &THORN;en are &thorn;ai ordend wen &thorn;ai are of &thorn;at yng &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld be, &amp; &thorn;en are &thorn;ai vnordend wen &thorn;ai are of &thorn;at yng &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld not be; &amp; &thorn;en are &thorn;ai mesurde wen &thorn;ai are so mekill os &thorn;ai suld be, &para; &thorn;en are &thorn;ai vnmesurde wen &thorn;ai are more &thorn;en &thorn;a suld be.  &para; Forwhi, ouermekill drede brynges dispare, &amp; ouermekill soro kestes a man in bitternes &amp; hewenes of kynde &para; ffor &thorn;e wilk he is vnabull to resawe gostle comforth; &amp; ouermekill hope is presumpcion, &amp; vtragese luf is bot flateryng &amp; fagyng, &amp; vtragese gladnes is dissolucion &amp; wantonnes, &amp; vn-atempere hatredyn of syne is wodnes; &amp; on &thorn;is maner, if &thorn;ai be
vnordende &amp; vnmesurde, &thorn;en are [&thorn;ai] turned in to vices, &amp; &thorn;en lose &thorn;ai &thorn;e nam of vertu&yogh; &amp; maynot be acowntude with &thorn;e sons of Iacob, &thorn;at is to say God&mdash;for
be Iacob is vndurstane god, &amp; so it is schewed in &thorn;e figure befor.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Here it is to say of &thorn;e two sons of Rachel: Ioseph &amp; Beniamyn.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;us it semes &thorn;at &thorn;e vertu of discrecion is fulnedefull to be hade, with &thorn;e
wilk all othere vertus may be kepude &amp; gouernde&mdash;for withouton it all othere vertus
are turned to vices.  &para; &THORN;es is Ioseph, &thorn;at is latborne childe, bo[t] &yogh;itt is fadere
lufs hym more &thorn;en &thorn;am all: Forwy truly withouton discrecion may nawther
gudnes be getyn ne keppude, &amp; for&thorn;i no wonder of &thorn;at vertu be synglerle lufde.
&para; Bot wat wondur is of &thorn;is vertu be late getyn, wen we maynot wyne to no
perfeccion of discrecion without&omacr; mekill vse &amp; mone trawels of &thorn;es othere
affeccions command before?  &para; For first be-hose vs be hused in ilk a uertu be
&thorn;am-self &amp; gete &thorn;e profe of am all serele, or we may haf ful kunyng of am all
or eles cune deme sufficientle of am all; &amp; wen we vse vs besile in &thorn;es felynges
&amp; behaldy[n]ges befor-sayde, oft-tymes we fall &amp; oft-tymes we ryse, &thorn;en be oure oft fallyng may we lere how mekill warnes vs behose haf in &thorn;e getyng &amp; kepyng
of &thorn;es vertus: &amp; &thorn;us homwill be lang vse a saule is lede into full discrecion,
&amp; &thorn;en it may ioy in &thorn;e byrth of Ioseph.  &amp; befor &thorn;is vertu be consewed in a mans saule, all &thorn;at &thorn;es other vertus dos it is without&omacr; discrecion, &amp; for&thorn;i in als mekill os a man presumes &amp; enstresses hym in any of &thorn;es felynges beforsayd ouer
his myght &amp; oute of mesure, in so mekill &thorn;e foulere he fals &amp; fales of his purpose;
&amp; &thorn;erfor it is &thorn;at after am all &amp; last is Dyna borne, for oft after a sodeyn fal
comes sone schame.  &para; And &thorn;us after mone fallynges &amp; failynges, &amp; schame foloande, a man lers be &thorn;e prof &thorn;are is noyng better &thorn;en to be rewlede be counsell, &thorn;e
wilk is &thorn;e redist geytyng of discrecion.  &para; Forwy he &thorn;at dus all yng with
consaile, hym sall newere forynk it&mdash;ffor better liste &thorn;en lythere strenght.  &para; And
here is &thorn;e opon skill wy &thorn;at nawther Lya ne &YOGH;elfa ne Bala moght bere swilk a
child, bot onle Rachel, ffor os it is sayd before &thorn;at of reson comen reght
consailes &thorn;e wilk is verray discrecion, vndurstande be Ioseph &thorn;e first sone of
Rachel; &amp; &thorn;en at &thorn;e first bryng we forth Ioseph in oure reson wen all &thorn;at we
are sterde to do, we do it be consaile.  &para; &THORN;is Ioseph sall not onle knaw wate
synes we are most sterde to, bot also he sall knaw &thorn;e wakenes of oure kynde,
&amp; after &thorn;at aythere askes so sall he do remedy, &amp; sek consaile at wissere &thorn;en he


<PB N="1: 171">

&amp; do after &thorn;am, els is he not Ioseph Iacob sone borne of Rachel.  &para; And also [be]
&thorn;is ilk Ioseph is a man noght onle lernede to ethchew deseyt&yogh; of oure enmys, bot
als oft a man is lede be hym to perfite knawyng of hym-self: &amp; all after &thorn;at
a man knaws hym-self &thorn;arafter he profetes in knawyng of gode of wome he is &thorn;e
ymage &amp; lyknes, &amp; &thorn;erfor it is &thorn;at after Ioseph is Beniamyn born.  For os be
Ioseph discrecion, so be Beniamyn we vndurstand contemplacion.  &amp; both were &thorn;ai
borne of a modere &amp; getyn of a fadere, &para; ffor &thorn;oru &thorn;e grace of gode lyghtand
oure reson come we to &thorn;e perfit knawyng of oure-self, &amp; of gode, &thorn;at is to say after
&thorn;at it may be in &thorn;is lyf.  Bot lang after Ioseph is Beniamyne borne, ffor why,
trule bot if so be &thorn;at we huss vs besile &amp; lange in gostle trawels with wilk we
are lernede to knaw oure-self, &para; we may not be raysed into &thorn;e knawyng
&amp; contemplacion of gode.  He dose for noght &thorn;at lyftes vp his egh to &thorn;e sight
of gode, &thorn;at is not &yogh;itt abull to se hym-self.  For first a man suld lerne hym to
knaw vnseabull ynges of is oghen spirit, or he presumude for to knawe &thorn;e
vnseabull ynges of [&thorn;e] spirit of gode; and he &thorn;at knaws not &yogh;itt hym-self &amp; wenes
&thorn;at he has getyn somdel knawyng of &thorn;e vnseabull ynges of gode, i doute it
noght &thorn;atyn he is deceyfd; &amp; for&thorn;i i rede &thorn;at a man sek [first] besile forto knaw
hym-self, &thorn;e wilk is made to &thorn;e ymage of gode os in saule.  &amp; witt &thorn;o wele &thorn;at
he &thorn;at desirs forto se gode, hym behose clens his saule, &thorn;e wilk is os a myroure
in &thorn;e wilk all yngis are clerle sen wen it is clene; &amp; wen &thorn;e myroure is foule,
&thorn;en may &thorn;o se noyng clerle &thorn;erin: &amp; reghtso of &thorn;e saule wen it is foule, nather
&thorn;ou knaus &thorn;i-self ne gode.  &para; And wen &thorn;e candell brennes, &thorn;en may &thorn;o se
&thorn;iself &amp; &thorn;e candell be &thorn;e lyght &thorn;erof, &amp; othere ynges.  &para; Reghtso wen &thorn;i saule brennes in &thorn;e luf of gode, &thorn;at is wen &thorn;o feles continule &thorn;i hert desire &thorn;e luf of god, &thorn;en be &thorn;e lyght of his grace &thorn;at he sendes in &thorn;i reson, &thorn;o may se both
&thorn;in oghon vnworthines &amp; godes gret gudnes.  &amp; for&thorn;i clens &thorn;i myroure &amp; beyde &thorn;i candell to &thorn;e fire.  &para; And &thorn;en, wen &thorn;i myroure is clensed &amp; &thorn;i candell lyghted, &amp; it so be &thorn;at &thorn;ou weterle be-hald &thorn;erto, &thorn;en begynnes a manere of clerte of &thorn;e lyght of gode forto schyn in &thorn;i saule, &amp; a maner of a sone-beme &thorn;at is gostele to apere to &thorn;i gostle syght, &thorn;oro &thorn;e wilk &thorn;e egh of &thorn;i saule is opunde to behald god &amp; gostle ynges, hewen &amp; heuenle ynges, &amp; all maner gostle ynges;&mdash;bot &thorn;is syght is bot be tymes, wen god will woches-sawf forto gifit vnto a wyrkande saule, wils it is in batell of &thorn;is dedle lyf; bot affter &thorn;is lif sall it be ay lastand.
&THORN;is lyght schone in Dauid saule whils he sayd &thorn;us in &thorn;e psalme: &laquo;&para; Lorde, &thorn;e lyght of &thorn;i face is marked apon vs: &thorn;o has gyfyn faynnes with-ine my hert&raquo;.
&thorn;e light of godes face is &thorn;e schynyng of is grace, &thorn;at reformes in hus is ymage
&thorn;at has ben defoulede with &thorn;e merknes of syne.  &amp; &thorn;erfor a saule &thorn;at brennes in
desyre of &thorn;is sight, if it hope forto hafe &thorn;at at it desires, witt it wele &thorn;at it has
consawed Beniamyn.  &amp; &thorn;erfor what is more helfull &thorn;en swetnes of &thorn;is syght, or
wat softer yng may be felede?  Sikerle, none, &amp; &thorn;at wot Rachell full well,
&para; forwhy, &thorn;e reson s[e]ys &thorn;at in comparison of &thorn;is swetnes all other swetnes are
sowr &amp; bitter os gall forbi hony.  Newere&thorn;eles &yogh;itt may a man newere come to
sclik a grace be is oghon scleght, forwhy it is a gyft of gode with-out&omacr;n deserte
of man.  &para; Bot with-outon doute, of it be not desert of man, &yogh;it noman may tak
swilk grace with-outon gret stody &amp; brenna[n]de desire comande befor; &amp; &thorn;at wot


<PB N="1: 172">

Rachel fulwill, &amp; for&thorn;i scho multiplys here stody, &amp; [whettes her desyre] hekand
desyre vnto desire: so &thorn;at at &thorn;e last in gret habundans of brenande desire &amp; sorou of &thorn;e delayng of here desyre &para; Beniamy[n] is borne, &amp; is moder Rachel
deyse, forwhy, wat tyme &thorn;at a saule is rawyste abowf it-self be habundans of
desires &amp; in a gret multitud of luf, so &thorn;at it is enflawmed with &thorn;e light of &thorn;e
godhede, sekerle &thorn;endeyse all mans reson.  &para; And &thorn;erfor, wat-so he be &thorn;at desires
to come to contemplacion of god, lete hym lete for to gedire samen &thorn;e myght&yogh;
of his sawle, &amp; lete hym study forto refreyne &thorn;e outpassyng of is mynde, &amp; schape hym forto wone with hym-self os a kyng in is reme to wome &thorn;at non
of his sugetes wore contrari.  &THORN;en salto [vise &thorn;e] in &thorn;is maner: call samen &thorn;i
&thorn;oghtes &amp; &thorn;i desires &amp; mak of &thorn;am a kirk, &amp; lerne &thorn;e &thorn;erin to luf onle &thorn;is worde IHESU, so &thorn;at all &thorn;i desire &amp; &thorn;i thoght be set onle to luf Ihesu, &amp; &thorn;at vnseshandle os it may be here; so &thorn;at &thorn;o fu[l]fyll &thorn;at is sayd in &thorn;e psalme:
&laquo;lorde, i sall bles &thorn;e in kirkes&raquo;, &thorn;at is in thoght &amp; desire of &thorn;e luf of Ihesu.  &amp; &thorn;en in &thorn;is kyrk ofe &thorn;oghtes &amp; desires, &amp; in &thorn;is onhede of stodes &amp; of &thorn;e wil[les], loke &thorn;at all &thorn;i &thorn;oghte &amp; &thorn;i desires &amp; all &thorn;i studes &amp; all &thorn;i willes be onle sette in &thorn;e luf &amp; &thorn;e lofyng of Ihesu, with-outon forgetyng als [fer] forth os &thorn;o may be grace &amp; os &thorn;i frelte will suffure, eweremore mekand &thorn;e to praere &amp; to conseil, pacientle abydand &thorn;e wille of oure lorde, vnto &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;i mynd be rawyste abouf it-self to be fed with &thorn;e fare fode of angels in behaldyng of gode &amp; gostele ynges; so &thorn;at it be fulfild in &thorn;e &thorn;at is wretyne in &thorn;e psalme: &para; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ibi Beniamyn adolescentulus in mentis excessu,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: &laquo;Beniamyne &thorn;e &yogh;ong childe in rauyshyng of mynde of Ihesu.&raquo; .... Ihesu .... Ihesu .... Mercy Ihesu, graunt Mercy, Ihesu.
</P></DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Wythdragh &thorn;i &thorn;oght</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"><P>Wythdragh &thorn;i &thorn;oght fro &thorn;i gude dedys &amp; fro &thorn;ine ill dedys, and ynk &thorn;o
arte ewere in &thorn;e syght of gode &amp; in is presens, &yogh;e reght os &thorn;o art present to &thorn;i-self; and with all &thorn;i &thorn;oght onle offere &thorn;i body &amp; &thorn;i saule mekle to &thorn;e mercy of Ihesu os trature to is lorde, lastandle criande in hertle mynde: &laquo;Ihesu mercy, Ihesu mercy, Ihesu mercy&raquo;.
</P></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Thre pont&yogh;</HEAD><MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio"><P>Thre pont&yogh; &thorn;ere are &thorn;at kepen vs fro mone sotell deset&yogh; of &thorn;e foule fende
&thorn;at mone gostle men begils &thorn;orou preway pont&yogh; of pryde &thorn;at mysrewle &thorn;ere witte;
wilk are &thorn;es: Meknes, mercy, &amp; drede.  Meknes is a clothyng of all colorse,
for he enforses hym os fore &thorn;e tym to acorde hym to all condicions, for so may
he best passe to hald is oghon kynde.  Mercy is likende to whyte, for he clen&szlig; &amp; wesese away &thorn;e vgsome filth of syne.  Drede has colore of rede, for it is moste
ferdfull of all othere colores.  &THORN;es &thorn;re are calde &thorn;e lefra of oure lorde, &thorn;at he
cleths his childer ine or &thorn;ai may comme to hym; for &thorn;e gospell byddes: woso
lakse &thorn;is lyfray, kest hym into hell.  Bot meknes is a seker sarke &thorn;at vnder &amp; neghtes vs ogh to be: and sothle wo so lakes &thorn;is sark, gostle clethyngis ket&yogh; he
none, whi[l]k are vertu&yogh; to vndurstande.  &THORN;erfor meknes ogh neght to be, &amp; &thorn;en
mercy abofe on &thorn;at: for meke hert&yogh; &thorn;at bolne for woo, are comforthed full
mekill, mercy to call.
</P></DIV2>
</DIV1><DIV1 N="Cambridge Dd V.55" TYPE="MS">
<PB N="1: 173"><HEAD>Treatises of Ms. Cambr. Dd V. 55</HEAD>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Of Proper Will</HEAD>

<P>PRopyr wille &thorn;at is forsakyn &amp; made commen, &thorn;an is it acordant wyht goddis
wylle, and alle gode mens wille, and principaly ouer alle thynge till our
suffrayne[s] wil to whame we ere suget made ry&yogh;t als vn-to god, als &thorn;e reule of
religion askys.  &THORN;is comen wille is sothefastly called &thorn;e maste precious offerande
&amp; &thorn;e maste dere presande &thorn;at may be gyfen vn-to god; and &thorn;arefor it is
callyd erthely heuen, for qwy it herbers god.  It is goddis tempill, it is &thorn;e
chosen chambyr of Ihesu, it is &thorn;e hamely howse of &thorn;e haly gaste.  It is &thorn;e
kyndome of &thorn;e fadyr, it is &thorn;e herytage of &thorn;e sone, it is &thorn;e possessyone of &thorn;e haly
gaste.  &THORN;e fadyr als his kyngdome rewlis it, &thorn;e sone as his heritage gouerns it,
&thorn;e haligast as hys awen counceyls it.  [It] beris likenes of &thorn;e trinite: of &thorn;e faydyr
in fayrenes, of &thorn;e sone in mekenes, of &thorn;e haligast in gudenes.  &THORN;is comone
wille has Clerete of &thorn;e fadyr, Obedyens of &thorn;e sone, Conforth of &thorn;e haligaste.  &THORN;e
fadyr makes hym my&yogh;ti, &thorn;e sone makes hym wytti, &thorn;e haligast makes hym eyse;
swa &thorn;at alle hys ennemyes bodyly &amp; gastly ly&yogh;tly it ouyrcomes.  &THORN;e my&yogh;t &thorn;at is gyfen of &thorn;e fadyr.  &THORN;e witte &thorn;at is gyfen of &thorn;e sone.  It is swa parfyte &thorn;at alle


<PB N="1: 174">

&thorn;e wytte of &thorn;is werlde can nou&yogh;t teche it: for qwy, gastly wytte and
vndyrstandynge is tau&yogh;te of god be felyng, and naman may make a feler in gastly
wytte bot god &thorn;at is &thorn;e gyfer.  &THORN;e techyng of god is gyfen, and &thorn;at gyfynge
causyth felynge.  And in &thorn;is felynge is fully knawen &thorn;e difference of &thorn;ase men
&thorn;at ere tau&yogh;t of god&mdash;as &thorn;ase &thorn;at gyfe &thorn;am to parfyte lyuynge, and &thorn;ase &thorn;at
er tau&yogh;t of men&mdash;as &thorn;ase &thorn;at gyfes &thorn;am to comyn lyfe.  For alle &thorn;at clerkys may
lere of erthely men in body be heryng or seyng, goddis clerkys, qwilke ere callyd
parfyte men, has it in felynge &amp; tastyng.  Swa &thorn;at goddis clerkys, qwylys &thorn;ay
meke &thorn;am vndyr hys wande, ere neuyr begylyd.  For heryng &amp; seynge alle &thorn;ay
begylis, bot meke tastynge &amp; felynge may not begyle.  It is &thorn;e crafte of clergy
lered on &thorn;e boke be men to cun see writ wreten &amp; here it spoken: and goddis
clerkys has in felynge &thorn;at &thorn;ai haue in heryng, and alswa in tastynge &thorn;at &thorn;ay
haue in spekynge; &amp; is gyfen of &thorn;e haligast, &amp; settes &thorn;am in reste; swa &thorn;at
contrarius dedes does &thorn;am na disese, for it does &thorn;am comforte to be agayn-sayde ...
And &thorn;e cause of &thorn;at payne is propyr wylle, qwilke is called helle, for fendys
dwellys &thorn;erin; for na creature pyn&yogh; &thorn;e consciens bot fendes, to qwam we
gyfe leue anly thorow pride.  Qwa-swa herbers propyr wille &amp; haldys hym at
hame, he mone be dampned as traytour in &thorn;e dredeful daye of dome of god.
As be ensaimple &yogh;e may see in lawe of &thorn;e lande: As if a man wilfully resette
&thorn;e kynges felon, or mayntens hys traytour in hys awen kyngdome, he is traytour
or felon, and be &thorn;e lawe he sal be dampned.  On &thorn;e same maner &thorn;e lawe of
god dampnes propyr wylle: for he was hys bane and cause of hys dede.  Propyr
wille desyred hym, accused hym, demed hym, dampned hym, &amp; did hym to dede.
For qwyles Iudas had comyn wylle, na man did he dere: bot qwen hys wille
was made propyr, &thorn;an was his dede dy&yogh;th.  &THORN;erfor &thorn;e bane of god is callid
propyr wylle.  And qwa swa lufes it, hates god, ffor-sakand helpe of alle-holy
kyrke and &thorn;e vertus of heuen, alswa &thorn;e gyftes of &thorn;e haligaste, and alle &thorn;e
blyssed company &thorn;at in heuen es, and mas offerand of hym-selfe to &thorn;e fende
of helle.  For qwa sa settes hym-selfe bodili here in propyr wille, hys sete is
made gastly in helle with &thorn;e fendis; ffor interynge of propyr wil gyfes seysynge
of helle, and is kyndely calde Lucifer bedde.  Bot some men ere fouly bygylled
of &thorn;is propyr wylle and desayuyd as in smal thynges, &thorn;at it sal not dere.  &THORN;ese
men ere blyndyd with pride, &thorn;at &thorn;ay may nou&yogh;t see howe &thorn;ayr conscyence es
pynde for comen wilis gane; for na thynge bot propyr wyl is noriser of pride,
qwilke is &thorn;e maste preciouse homage and &thorn;e derest desire &thorn;at Lucifer lykes.
Meke men byndys &thorn;am vnto comyn will be counceyl thorowe &thorn;e haligaste: and
&thorn;at is obedience, &thorn;at maste payes god, for obedience is &thorn;e tresoure of &thorn;e trinite,
&thorn;at trewly kepes heuenly gyftes: for &thorn;e gyftes of heuen ere neuyrmare gyfen
bot til obedyente wylles.  And it is sorow to see or wite howe dedly &thorn;ay ere
encombyrde: ffor if &thorn;ai wene &thorn;ayr wylle be knawen bot anly to &thorn;am-selfe, it
cryande forsakes god, &thorn;at alle heuen heris.  And alswa it is called an outhorn
of helle: for it rayses a thowsande of fendes; for if it may be sayde &thorn;at &thorn;ay
haue Ioye in &thorn;ayr kynde, o&thorn;yr Ioye of vs haue &thorn;ai none bot of propyr wylle;
ffor be oure propyr wylle &thorn;ay dwelle in vs, &amp; be na thynge ellis.  And &thorn;is
myschefe fallis tille alle &thorn;ay &thorn;at forsakys counceyl &amp; wyll nou&yogh;t lene &thorn;arto,
wylke conceyl may be called &thorn;e ordenaunce and &thorn;e thechynge of discrete men.
&THORN;e ensaimple gaf Ihesu goddis sone of heuen, &thorn;at bande hym so thorowe mekenes


<PB N="1: 175">

vn-to comen wylle for &thorn;e saluacion of alle mankynde, so fully, so trewly, so
straytly, &thorn;at fra &thorn;e begynnyng of hys paynful passyon vn-to &thorn;e laste poynt of
hys dede neuyr he blenked anes to hys owen wylle.  For he was swa obedient
vn-til alle &thorn;e wylles &thorn;at desired to be safe, &amp; namely to hys fadyr wylle &thorn;at
walde it sulde be so, &thorn;at he .. nou&yogh;t agayns &thorn;ayr wyll &thorn;at accused hym to &thorn;e
dede, he saide nou&yogh;t agayns &thorn;am &thorn;at demed hym to &thorn;e dede, ne he did nou&yogh;t
agayns &thorn;am &thorn;at did hym to &thorn;e dede.  Bot mekely be hys chere and hys
countenaunce moghe alle men see, alswa be mekenes of hys eyesy&yogh;t &thorn;e qwylke
chaunged neuyr, for his beryng in hys paynys was euyr swa meke, &thorn;at he made
na scheuyng as hym yrked, bot as hym had felid na payn; swa was he fre of
wylle &amp; comen to alle.  Sen he dyd &thorn;us, do we so, for he has in &thorn;is kende
vs oure awen nede.  And qwa sa takes nou&yogh;t &thorn;is nede, &thorn;ay sal dwele ay in nede.
Ihesu helpe fra &thorn;at place &thorn;at euyrmore nede has.  Amen.  Amen.  Amen.
</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>(Walter Hilton's) Of Angels' Song</HEAD><DIV3
N="Cambridge Dd V. 55" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Cambridge Dd V. 55</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;ow &yogh;ernys perauentur gretely for to haue more knawynge &amp; wyssynge &thorn;an
&thorn;ou has of aungels sange and heuenly sown, qwat it is, &amp; on qwat wyse it is
perceyued &amp; felid in a manns soule, and how a man may be sekyr &thorn;at [it] is
trowe &amp; nou&yogh;t feyned, and how it is made be &thorn;e presence of &thorn;e gude aungel
&amp; nou&yogh;t be &thorn;e inputtynge of &thorn;e ille aungel.  &THORN;es thynges &thorn;ou wolde wyte of me.
Bot sothely I can nou&yogh;t telle &thorn;e for sekyr sothenes of &thorn;is mater.
Neuyr-&thorn;e-latter sumqwat as me thynke sal I schewe &thorn;e in a schort worde. // Wyte &thorn;ou
wele &thorn;at &thorn;o ende &amp; &thorn;e souerante of perfeccions standis in a verray oned of god
&amp; man saule be parfite charite.  &THORN;is oned &thorn;an is verraly made qwen &thorn;e my&yogh;tes
of &thorn;e saule ere reformed be &thorn;e grace to &thorn;e dygnite &amp; &thorn;e state of &thorn;e fyrst
condicione, &thorn;at is qwen &thorn;e mynde is stabild sadly, with-outyn chaungeynge and
vagacion, in god &amp; gastly thynges, and qwen &thorn;e reson is cherit fra alle werdly
&amp; fleschely behaldynge[s] and fra alle bodili ymagynacions, fygures &amp; fantasyes

<PB N="1: 176">

of creatures &amp; is illumyned be grace to be-hald god and gastly thynges, and
qwen &thorn;e wylle &amp; &thorn;e affeccion is purified &amp; clensed fra alle fleschely, kyndely,
and werldly loue &amp; is inflaumed with brennand lufe of &thorn;e haligast.  &THORN;is
wondyrful oned may nou&yogh;t be fulfilled parfitely, contynuelly, holyly in &thorn;is lyfe,
for corrupcion of &thorn;e flesche, bot anly in &thorn;e blis of heuen.  Neuyr-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;e
nerre &thorn;at a saule in &thorn;is presente lyfe may come to &thorn;is oned, &thorn;e mare parfit it
is, for &thorn;e mar &thorn;at it is reformed be grace to &thorn;e ymage and &thorn;e lykenes of hys
creatour here; on &thorn;is maner-wyse &thorn;e more Ioye &amp; blysse sal it haue in heuen.
Oure lorde is ane endeles beyng with-outyn chaungeynge, alle-myghyed
with-outyn fallynge, souerayn wysdome, lyght, sothenes with-outen errour or myrkenes;
soueryne godenes, loue &amp; pes &amp; swettenes; &thorn;an &thorn;e mare &thorn;at a saule is oned,
festened, conformed &amp; Ioyned to oure lorde, &thorn;e mare stabil &amp; my&yogh;ti it is, &thorn;e
mare wyse &amp; clere, gude &amp; pesible, lufende &amp; mare vertuose it is, &amp; so it is mare parfyt.  For a saule &thorn;at has be grace of Ihesu &amp; lange travayle of bodili
&amp; gastly excercyse ouyrcomen &amp; distroyed concupiscenci&yogh; &amp; passyons and vnskylfull steryngys with-inne hym-selfe &amp; with-outyn in &thorn;e sensualyte, &amp; is cled alle in vertus, [as] in mekenes &amp; myldenes, in pacience &amp; softenes, in gastly strenthe and ry&yogh;twysnes, in contynuaunce, in wysdome, in trouthe, hope &amp; charite, &thorn;an is it made parfyte as it may be in &thorn;is lyfe.  Mykyll confort it receyues of oure lorde,
nou&yogh;t anly inwardly in hys awen priue substaunce, be vertu of &thorn;e oned to owre
lorde &thorn;at lys in knawynge &amp; lufynge of god, in ly&yogh;t &amp; gastly brennynge of hym,


<PB N="1: 177">

in transformynge of &thorn;e saule in &thorn;e godhede, bot also many o&thorn;ir confortys,
sauoures, swetnes &amp; wondyrfull felyngys on sere maners, eftyr oure lorde
vouchesafe to visite his creatures here in erthe, and eftyr &thorn;e saule parfittily wayxit in
charite.  Some saule be vertu of charite &thorn;at god gyfs it es so clensed, &thorn;at alle
creatures, and alle &thorn;at he heris, or sees, or felis be any of hys wyttis, turnys hym
to conforte and gladnes, &amp; &thorn;e sensualite reseyues new sauoure &amp; swetenes in alle
creatures, and ry&yogh;t [as before] &thorn;e lykynges in &thorn;e sensualyte were fleschely, vayn,
and vicious for [&thorn;e] payne of &thorn;e original synne, ry&yogh;t so now [&thorn;ay ere] made gastly
&amp; clene with-outyn bytternes &amp; bytynge of conscience.  And &thorn;is is &thorn;e gudenes of
oure lorde, &thorn;at sythen &thorn;e saule is punysched in &thorn;e sensualyte, &amp; &thorn;e flesche is
par[ce]ner of [&thorn;e] payne, &thorn;at eftyrwarde &thorn;e saule be conforte in [hir] sensualite, &amp; &thorn;e flesche be felawe of Ioye &amp; confort with &thorn;e saule, nou&yogh;t fleschely, bot gastly, as he was felawe in tribulacion &amp; peyne.  &THORN;is is &thorn;e fredom &amp; &thorn;e lordechype, &thorn;e dyignite &amp; &thorn;e wyrchype &thorn;at a mans saule has ouyr alle creatures&mdash;&thorn;e qwilke dygnite he may recouer be grace here&mdash;&thorn;at ilke a creature sauour to hym as it is, and &thorn;at
is qwen be grace he sees, he heris, he felis, anly god in alle creatures.  On
&thorn;is maner-wyse a saule is made gastly in &thorn;e sensualyte be habundance of charite
&thorn;at is in &thorn;e substaunce of &thorn;e saule.  [Also] oure lorde conforte[s] a saule be aungels
sange.  Qwat &thorn;at sange is, it may nou&yogh;t be discried be na bodily lykenesse, for
it is gastly and abouen almaner of ymagynacion &amp; reson.  It may be felid &amp; perceyued in a saule, bot it may not be schewed.  Neuyr-&thorn;e-latter I speke &thorn;erof to


<PB N="1: 178">

&thorn;e as me thynke. / Qwen a saule is purified be lufe of god, illumyned be
wysdome, stabild be &thorn;e my&yogh;te of god, &thorn;an is &thorn;e eyghe of &thorn;e saule opynde to
behalde gastly thyngys, as vertuse &amp; aungels &amp; haly saulys, &amp; heuenly thyngys.
&THORN;an is &thorn;e saule habyl be cause of clennes to fele &thorn;e towchynge, &thorn;e spekynge
of gude aungels.  &THORN;is towchynge and spekynge is gastly, &amp; nou&yogh;t bodyly: ffor
qwen &thorn;e saule is lyfth &amp; rauysched out of &thorn;e sensualyte, &amp; out of &thorn;e mynde of
any erthely thyngis, &thorn;an in grete feruoure of lufe and ly&yogh;th of god, if oure
lorde vouchesafe, &thorn;e saule may here &amp; fele heuenly sown, made be &thorn;e presence
of aungels in louynge of god.  Nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;is songe of aungels es &thorn;e souerayne
Ioye of &thorn;e saule; bot for &thorn;e difference &thorn;at es atwyxe a mans saule in flesche
&amp; an aungell be-cause of vnclennes, a saule may nou&yogh;t here it bot be rauyschynge
in lufe, [&] nedyth for to be purified wele clene, and fulfilled of mykyl charite, or
it were abil for to here heuenly sown.  For &thorn;e souereyn &amp; &thorn;e essencial Ioye es in
[&thorn;e] lufe of god be hym-selfe &amp; for hym-selfe, and [&thorn;e] secundarie es in communynge
&amp; behaldynge of aungels &amp; gastily creaturis.  For ry&yogh;t as a saule in vndyrstandynge of gastly thyngis is oftesythes towchyd &amp; kenned thorow bodili ymaginacion ... &thorn;e sothefastenes of goddis priuetys, ry&yogh;t swa in &thorn;e lufe of god a saule be presence of aungels is rauyschyd out of mynde of alle erthely &amp; fleschely thynges in to an heuenly Ioye, to here aungelis songe and heuenly sowne, eftyr &thorn;e charite is
more or lesse.  Now &thorn;an thynke me &thorn;at &thorn;er may na saule fele verraly aungels
sange ne heuenly sowne, bot he be in parfyte charite.  And nou&yogh;t-forthy, alle


<PB N="1: 179">

&thorn;at be in parfyte charite ne has nou&yogh;t felid it, bot anly &thorn;at saule &thorn;at is sa
purified in &thorn;e fyre of lufe, &thorn;at alle erthely sauoure is brent out of it, &amp; all mene
lettynge atwyxe &thorn;e saule &amp; &thorn;e clennes of aungels is broken &amp; putte away fra it.
&THORN;an sothely may he synge a new songe, and sothely may he here a blyssefull
heuenly sowne &amp; aungels sange with-outyn deseyte or feynynge.  Oure lorde wat
qware &thorn;at saule is &thorn;at for habundance of brennande lufe is wurthy to here aungels
sange.  Qwa swa &thorn;an wylle here aungels sange, &amp; nou&yogh;t be deseuyd be feynynge
ne ymagynacion of hym-selfe, ne be illusyon of &thorn;e ennemy, hym behoues for
to haue parfite charite, &amp; &thorn;at is qwen alle vayn lufe &amp; drede, vayne Ioye &amp; sorowe is castyn out of &thorn;e hert, &thorn;at he lufes na thynge ... bot in god or for god.
Qwa swa my&yogh;t be grace of god go &thorn;is way, he sulde nou&yogh;t erre.  Neuyr-&thorn;e-latter
some men ere desayued be &thorn;ayr awen ymagynacion, or be illusyon of &thorn;e ennemy
in &thorn;is mater.  Some man qwen he has lange travalid bodili &amp; gastily in distroynge
of synnes and getyng of vertus, &amp; perauentur has geten be grace [a] somdele reste
&amp; a clerete in conscience, anon he leues prayers, redynges of haly wrytte, &amp; meditacions of &thorn;e passyon of Criste, &amp; &thorn;e mynde of hys wrecchednes, and or he
be called of god, he gedyrs hys wyttes be vyolence to seke &amp; to behald heuenly
thynges or hys eyghe be made gastly be grace, and ouertravailis be
ymagynacion[s] hys wyttes, and be vndiscrete travelynge turnes &thorn;e braynes in hys heued
&amp; forbrekes &thorn;e my&yogh;tes &amp; &thorn;e wittes of &thorn;e saule &amp; of &thorn;e body: &amp; &thorn;an for febelnes of &thorn;e brayn hym thynke &thorn;at he heris wondyrfull sownes &amp; sanges; and &thorn;at is


<PB N="1: 180">

na thynge ellis bot a fantasye caused of trobelynge of &thorn;e brayn &mdash; as a man
&thorn;at is in a fransy, hym thynke &thorn;at he heris &amp; sees &thorn;at nan o&thorn;ir man does, and
al is bot vanite &amp; fantasy of &thorn;e heued.  Or ellis it is be wyrkynge of &thorn;e ennemy
&thorn;at feynes swylke sownes in hys heringe.  For if a man haue any presumpcion,
in hiis fantasiis &amp; in his wyrkynges, &amp; &thorn;erby fallis in to indiscrete ymagynacion,
as it were in a frenesy, &amp; is nou&yogh;t kenned ne reuled of g[r]ace ne confortid be
gastly strenghe, &thorn;e deuel enters in be fals illumynacions &amp; fals sownes &amp; swetenes [&] deceyues a mans soule.  An[d] of &thorn;is fals grounde sprynges errours &amp; heresyes, fals prophecies, presumcions &amp; fals r[o]seynges, blasphemes &amp; sclaunderyngs, &amp; many o&thorn;ir myschefes.  And &thorn;arefor if &thorn;ou see any man gastly occupyed falle in any of &thorn;is synnys &amp; &thorn;ese deseytes, or in frenesis, wyte &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at he neuyr herde ne felid aungels songes ne heuenly soune: for sothely he &thorn;at veraly heris aungels sange, h[e] ys made soe wyse &thorn;at he sal neuyr erre be fantasye ne be
indiscrecion, ne be no sleythe of &thorn;e wyrkynge of &thorn;e deuel. / Also some men felis
in &thorn;ayr hertis, as it ware a gastly sowne &amp; swete sangys, in diuerse maners, &amp; &thorn;is is comenly gude, &amp; sometyme it may turne to disceyte.  &THORN;is soune is felid
on &thorn;is wyse: Some man settis &thorn;e thou&yogh;the of hys hert haly in &thorn;e name of Ihesu
&amp; stedfastly haldys it &thorn;erto, and &thorn;a[n] in schorte tyme hym thynke[s] &thorn;at name
turnys til hym to grete profete, conforte &amp; swetenes, and hym thynke &thorn;e name
sounes in hys herte delytably as it ware a sange, &amp; &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;is lykynge is
swa my&yogh;tty &thorn;at it draws in alle wyttes of &thorn;e saule &thorn;erto.  Qwo-so may fele
&thorn;is soune &amp; &thorn;is swettenes veraly in hys herte, wete he wele &thorn;at it is of god,


<PB N="1: 181">

and as longe as he is meke he sal nou&yogh;t be disceyued.  Bot &thorn;is is nou&yogh;t aungels
songe, bot it is a sange of &thorn;e saule be vertu of &thorn;e name, &amp; be towchynge of
&thorn;e gude aungell.  For qwen a saule offers hyr to Ihesu trewly, &amp; mekely puttis
alle hyr trayste and hyr desyre in hym, &amp; besyly kepes hym in hyre mynde, oure
lorde Ihesu, qwen he wyll, purges &thorn;e affeccion of &thorn;e saule, &amp; fyllys it &amp; fedys
it with swetenes of hym-selfe, &amp; makes hys name in &thorn;e felynge of &thorn;e saule as
hony, &amp; as sange, &amp; as any thynge &thorn;at is delitabil: &thorn;at it lykes &thorn;e saule euyrmore for to crye Ihesu, Ihesu; and nou&yogh;t only he has confort in &thorn;is, bot also in
psalmys &amp; ympnes &amp; antympnes of haly kyrke, &thorn;at &thorn;e hert synges &thorn;em swetly,
deuotly &amp; frely, with-outyn any travayle of &thorn;e saule or bitternes, in &thorn;e same toune
&amp; notes &thorn;at haly kyrke vses.  &THORN;is is gude &amp; of &thorn;e gyfte of god, ffor &thorn;e
substaunce of &thorn;is felynge lys in &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu qwilke is fed &amp; ly&yogh;ttynd be swylke maner of sanges.  Neuyr-&thorn;e-latter in &thorn;is maner felynge a saule may be desceyved
be vayn-glorye, nou&yogh;t in &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e affeccion synges to Ihesu &amp; loues Ihesu
in swetenes of hym, bot eftyrwarde, qwen it sesses, &amp; &thorn;e hert kelys of lufe of Ihesu,
&thorn;an entyris-in vayn-glorye.  Also some man is desceyued on &thorn;is wyse: He heris
wel say &thorn;at it is gude till haue Ihesu in hys mynde, or any o&thorn;ir gude worde of
god, &thorn;an he streynes hys herte my&yogh;ttly to &thorn;at name, &amp; be a custome he has it
nerehande alway in hys mynde.  Nou&yogh;t-forthy he felis nou&yogh;thyr &thorn;erby in hys
affeccion swetenes, ne ly&yogh;t of knowyng in hys resone, bot only a nakyd mynde
of god, or of Ihesu, or of Marie, or of any o&thorn;ir gude worde.  Here may be
desceyte, not for it is ille for to haue Ihesu in mynde on &thorn;is wyse, bot if he


<PB N="1: 182">

&thorn;is felynge &amp; &thorn;is mynde, &thorn;at is anly hys awen wyrkynge be custome, halde it a
special vysitacion of oure lorde &amp; thynke it mare &thorn;an it is.  For wyte &thorn;ou wele
&thorn;at a nakyd mynde or a nakyd ymagynacion of Ihesu or of any gastly thynge,
with-outyn swetenes of lufe in affeccyon, or with-outyn ly&yogh;te of knowynge in
resone, it is bot a blyndenes, &amp; a way to disceyte, if a man halde it in hys awen
sy&yogh;te mare &thorn;an it is.  &THORN;erfor I halde it sekyr &thorn;at he be meke in his awen
felynge, and halde &thorn;is mynde in regarde nou&yogh;t til he may be custome &amp; vsynge
of &thorn;is mynde fele &thorn;e fyre of lufe in hys affeccion, &amp; &thorn;e ly&yogh;t of knawynge in
hys resone.  Loe, I haue tolde &thorn;e in &thorn;is mater a lytyl as me thynke; nou&yogh;t
affermande &thorn;at &thorn;is suffys, ne &thorn;at &thorn;is is &thorn;e sothefastnes in &thorn;is mater.  Bot if &thorn;e
thynke it o&thorn;ir-wyse, or ellys any othyr man sauour be grace &thorn;e contrarye here-to,
I leue &thorn;is saynge and gyfe stede to hym; it suffys to me forto lyfe in trouthe
principaly, &amp; nou&yogh;t in felynge.  AMEN.
</P></DIV3>

<DIV3 N="Thornton  (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="1: 175"><HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="219b" UNIT="folio">
<P>Dere ffrende, wit &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at &thorn;e ende and &thorn;e soueraynte of perfeccione
standes in a verray anehede of godde and of manes saule by perfyte charyte.  &THORN;is
Ende &thorn;an es verrayly made whene &thorn;e myghtes of &thorn;e saule er refourmede by grace
to &thorn;e dignyte and &thorn;e state of &thorn;e firste condicione, &thorn;at es whene &thorn;e mynde es
stablede sadely with-owttene chaungynge and vagacyone in godde and gastely thynges,
and when the resone es cleryde fra all worldly &amp; fleschely behaldynges and
Imagy[na]cyones, fygurs and fantasyes of creatures and es illumenede with grace for to


<PB N="1: 176">

be-halde godde and gastely thynges, and whene &thorn;e will and &thorn;e affeccyone es
puryfiede and clensede fra all fleschely lustes, kyndely and werldly lufe and es
enflawmede with brennande lufe of &thorn;e haly gaste.  Bot &thorn;is wondirfull anehede may
noghte be fulfillede perfytely, contenually, ne hally in &thorn;is lyfe for corrupcyone of
&thorn;e flesche, bot anely in &thorn;e blysse of heuene.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lattere &thorn;e nerre &thorn;at a
saule in &thorn;is presente lyfe may come to &thorn;is anehede, &thorn;e mare perfite it es, ffor
&thorn;at it es refourmede by grace till &thorn;e ymage and &thorn;e lyknes of his creatour here,
one &thorn;is manere-wyse &thorn;e more ioy and blysse sall it hafe in heuene.  Oure lorde
godd es ane Endles beynge with-owttene chaungynge, all-myghtty with-owttene
faylynge, souerayne wysdome, lyghte, so[th]fastenes with-owttene errour or myrknes,
souerayne gudnes, lufe, pees and swetnes: &thorn;an &thorn;e mare &thorn;at a saule es anehede,
festened, confourmede &amp; ioynede to oure lorde godd, &thorn;e mare stabill it es &amp; myghty, &thorn;e mare wysse &amp; clere, gude, peyseble, luffande, and mare vertuous, and
so it es mare perfite.  For a saule &thorn;at haues by grace of Ihesu and lange
trauayle of bodyly &amp; gastely excercyse ouercommene and dystroyede concupyscens and
passiouns and vnskyllwyse styrrynges with-in it-selfe and with-owttene in &thorn;e
sensualite, and es clede in vertus as in mekenes and myldnes, in pacyence, in
sothefastnes, in gastely strenghe, and ryghtewisenes, in contynence, in wysdome,
in trouthe, hope, and charyte, &thorn;an es it made perfite als it may be in &thorn;is lyfe.
Mekill comforthe it reschayues of oure lorde, no&yogh;te anely inwardly in his preue
substance, be &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e anehede to oure lorde &thorn;at lyes in knaweynge and
and lufynge of godde, in lyghte of gastely brynnynge of hyme, in transfourmynge


<PB N="1: 177">

of &thorn;e saule in &thorn;e godhede, bot also in many o&thorn;er comforthes, &amp; sauours,
swettnes, and wondirfull felynges one sere maners, aftir oure lorde vouches-safe
to vesete his creatours here in erthe, and eftyre &thorn;e saule profytes and waxes in
charyte.  Some saule by vertue of charyte &thorn;at godde gyffes it es so clensede, &thorn;at
all creaturs in all &thorn;at he heris, or sese, or felis by any of his wittes turnes hyme
till comforthe and gladnes, and &thorn;e sensualite receyues newe sauour and swetnes
in all creaturs, and righte als before &thorn;e lykynges in &thorn;e sensualite ware fleschely,
vayne, and vecyous for &thorn;e payne of &thorn;e orygynalle synne, righte so nowe &thorn;ay ere
made gastely, and clene, with-owttene bitternes and bytynge of concyence.  And
&thorn;is es &thorn;e gudnes of oure lorde, &thorn;at sen &thorn;e saule es puneschede in the sensualite,
and &thorn;e flesche es pertynere of &thorn;e payne, that eftirwarde &thorn;e saule be comforthede
in hir sensualite, and &thorn;e flesche be felawe of &thorn;e ioye and comforthe with &thorn;e
saule, noghte fleschely, bot gastely, als he was felawe in tribulacione and payne.
&THORN;is es &thorn;e fredome &amp; &thorn;e lordchipe, dygnyte and &thorn;e wyrchipe &thorn;at a manes saule
hase ouer all creaturs, the whilke dygnyte he may receyue by grace here, &thorn;at
ilk a creature sauoure to hyme als it es, and &thorn;at es when by grace he sese, or he
heres, or he felys anely godde in all creaturs.  One &thorn;is maner-wyse [a] saule es
made gastely in &thorn;e sensualite by abowndance of charite &thorn;at es in &thorn;e substance
of the saule.  Also oure lorde comforthes a saule by aungells sange.  Bot what &thorn;at
sange es it may noghte [be] dyscryuede be no bodyly lyknes, for it es gastely and
abowne all manere of ymagynacyone and mans resone.  It may be perceyuede and
felide in a saule, bot it may noghte be spokene.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lattere I speke &thorn;are-of


<PB N="1: 178">

to &thorn;e als me thynke. / When a saule es puryfyede by &thorn;e lufe of godde, Illumynede
by wysedome, stabled by myghte of godde, than es &thorn;e eghe of &thorn;e saule opyned
to be-halde gastely thynges, as vertus, aungells and haly saules, and heuenly
thynges.  Thane es &thorn;e saule abill by cause of clennes to fele &thorn;e toucheynge, &thorn;e
spekynge of gude aungells.  This touchyng and spekynge es gastely, noghte bodyly:
ffor whene &thorn;e saule es lyftede and raysede owte of the sensualyte, and owte of
mynde of any erthely thynges, thane in gret feruoure of lufe and lyghte of godd,
if oure lorde vouche-safe, &thorn;e saule may here &amp; fele heuenly sownne, made by
&thorn;e presence of aungells in louynge of godde.  Noghte &thorn;at &thorn;is sange of aungells es
souerayne ioy of &thorn;e saule, bot [for &thorn;e] defference &thorn;at es by-twyxe a manes saule
in flesche and ane aungelle be-cause of vnclennes, a saule may noghte here it bot
by rauyschynge in lufe, and nedis for to be puryfiede full clene, and fulfillide
of mekyll charyte, are it ware abyll for to here heuenly sownne.  For &thorn;e souerayne
and &thorn;e Escencyalle ioy es in &thorn;e lufe of godde by hyme-selfe and for hyme-selfe,
and &thorn;e secundarye es in comonynge and byhaldynge of aungells and gastely
creaturs.  For ryghte as a saule in vndirstandynge of gastely thynges es ofte-sythes
touched and kennede thurghe bodyly ymagynacyone, by wyrkynge of aungells&mdash;as
E&yogh;echielle &thorn;e profete sawe in bodily ymagynacyoune &thorn;e sothefastnes of goddes
preuates&mdash;righte so, in &thorn;e lufe of godde, a saule be &thorn;e presence of aungelles es
raueschede owte of all mynde of erthely and fleschely thynges in to a heuenly
ioye to here aungells sannge and heuenly sownne eftir &thorn;at &thorn;e charite es mare or
lesse.  Nowe thane, thynke me, &thorn;at &thorn;er may no saule fele verreyly aungells sange
ne heuenly sowne bot it be in perfite charite.  And noghte for-thi all &thorn;at are in


<PB N="1: 179">

perfite charyte ne hase noghte felyde it, bot anely &thorn;at saule &thorn;at es [so] purede in &thorn;e
fyre of lufe of godde, &thorn;at all erthely sauoure es brynte owte of it, and all &thorn;e menes
lettande be-twyx &thorn;e saule and &thorn;e clennes of angells es brokene and put awaye
fra it.  &THORN;an sothely may he synge a newe sange and sothely may he here a blysfull
heuenly sowne and aungells sange with-owttene dessayte or feynynge.  Oure lorde
wate whare &thorn;at saule es &thorn;at for abowndance of brynnande lufe es worthi to here
aungells sange.  Wha-so &thorn;an will here aungells sange, and noghte be dyssayuede
by feynynge ne by ymagynacyone of hym-selfe, ne by illusyone of &thorn;e Enemy, hym
behoues hafe perfite charite, and &thorn;at es when all vayne lufe and drede, vayne ioy
and sorowe, es castene owte of &thorn;e herte, &thorn;at he lufes na thynge bot godde, ne
dredis na thynge bot godde, ne ioyes ne sorowes na thynge bot in godde, or of
godde.  Whoso myghte by &thorn;e grace of godde go &thorn;is way, he sulde noghte erre.
Neuer-&thorn;e lattere some mene ere disceyued by &thorn;aire awenne ymagynacyone, or by
illucyone of &thorn;e Enemy in &thorn;is matere.  Some mane whene he hase lange trauelde
bodyly and gastely in dystroynge of syn&macr;nes and getynge of vertus, and perauenture
hase getyne by grace a somdele ryste and a clerete in concyence, onone he leues
prayers, redyngs of haly writte, and medytacions of &thorn;e passione of Cryste, and &thorn;e
mynde of his wrechidnes, and, are he be callede of godde, he gedyrs his wittys
by violence to seke and to be-halde heuenly thynges, are his eghe be made
gastely by grace, and ouertrauells by ymagynaciouns his wittes, and by vndiscrete
trauellynge turnes &thorn;e braynes in his heuede, and forbrekes &thorn;e myghtes and &thorn;e
wittes of &thorn;e saule and of &thorn;e body; and &thorn;ane, for febilnes of &thorn;e brayne, hym
thynkes &thorn;at he heres woundirfull sownes and sanges: and &thorn;at es no thynge ells bot


<PB N="1: 180">

a fantasie caused of trubblyng of &thorn;e brayne, as a mane &thorn;at es in a frensye hyme
thynkes &thorn;at he herys or sese &thorn;at na no&thorn;er mane duse, and all es bot vanyte and
fantasie of &thorn;e heued.  Or elles by wyrkyng of &thorn;e enemy &thorn;at fenys swylke sownne
in h(is her)ynge.  For if a mane hase any presumpcione in his fantasies and in his
wirchynge, and &thorn;are-be falles in to vndiscrete ymagynacyone, as it ware a frensye,
and es noghte kennede ne rewlede of grace ne comforthede by gastely strenghe,
&thorn;e deuelle entirs &thorn;an by fals illumynacyons and fals sownnes and swetnes, and
dyssayues a mans saule.  And of &thorn;is false grounde sprynges errours and herysyes,
false prophesyes, presumpcyons and false rusyn&macr;gs, blasfemyes and sclandirynges, and
many o&thorn;er myschefes.  And &thorn;are-fore if &thorn;ou se any mane gastely ocupiede ffalle
in any of &thorn;ise synnes and &thorn;ise dissaytes, or in frensyes, wit &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at he herde
neuer ne felide aungells sange ne heuenly sowne.  For sothely he &thorn;at verreyly heres
aungels sange, he es made so wyse &thorn;at he sall neuer erre by fantasye ne by
indiscrecyone, ne by no sleghte of &thorn;e deuelle.  Also some men felis in theire hertes
as it ware a gastely sowne and swete sanges of dyuerse maners and &thorn;is es
commonly gude, and somtyme it may turne tyll dissayte.  &THORN;is sowne es felide one
&thorn;is wyse.  Some mane settis &thorn;e thoghte of his herte anely in &thorn;e name of Ihesu
and stedefastly haldis it &thorn;are-too, and in schorte tyme hym thynkes that &thorn;at name
turnes hyme till gret comforthe and swetnes, and hyme thynkes &thorn;at &thorn;e name sownnes
in his herte delitabely as it were a sannge, and &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;is lykynge es so
myghty &thorn;at it drawes in all &thorn;e wittes of &thorn;e saule &thorn;are-to.  Who-so may fele &thorn;is
sownne and &thorn;is swetnes verrayly in his herte, wite he wiele &thorn;at it es of godde, and


<PB N="1: 181">

als lange als he es meke he sall noghte be dissayuede.  Bot &thorn;is es noghte aungels
sange, bot it es a sannge of &thorn;e saule be vertu of &thorn;e name, and by touchynge of
&thorn;e gude aungelle.  For when a saule offirs it to Ihesu trewly &amp; mekely, puttande all
his traiste and his desyre in hym, and besily kepis [hym] in his mynde, oure lorde
Ihesu, whene he will, puris &thorn;e affeccioune of &thorn;e saule, &amp; fillis it &amp; fedis it with
swetnes of hym-selfe, and makes his name in &thorn;e felynge of &thorn;e saule as hony,
and as sange, and as any thynge &thorn;at es delitabill: so &thorn;at it lykes &thorn;e saule
euermare for to cry Ihesu Ihesu; and noghte anely he hase comforthe in this, bot also
in spalmes and ympnes and antym&macr;s of haly kyrke, &thorn;at &thorn;e herte synges &thorn;ame swetely,
deuotly and frely, with-owttene any trauelle of &thorn;e saule, or bitternes, in &thorn;e same
tyme and note&yogh; &thorn;at haly kyrke vses.  This es gude and of &thorn;e gyfte of godde,
ffor &thorn;e substance of &thorn;is felynge lyes in &thorn;e lufe of Ihesu whilke es fedde and
lyghtenede by swilke maner of sanges.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lattere in &thorn;is-maner felynge a
saule may be disceyuede by vayne glorye, noghte in &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e affeccione
synges to Ihesu and loues Ihesu in swetnes of hym, bot eftyrwarde, whan it cesses,
&amp; &thorn;e herte kelis of loue of Ihesu, thane entyrs in vayne glorie.  Also sum mane
es dessayuede on &thorn;is wyese: He heris wele say &thorn;at it es gude to haue Ihesu in
his mynde, or any o&thorn;er gude worde of godde, and &thorn;ane he streynes his herte myghtyly
to &thorn;at name and by a costome he hase it nerehande alway in his
mynde.  Noghte ffor-thi he felis nou&thorn;er &thorn;are-by in his affeccyoune swetnes, ne lighte of knawynge in his resoune, bot anely a nakede mynde of godde, or of Ihesu, or of Mary, or of any
o&thorn;er gude worde.  Here may be disceyte, noghte for it es ill to hafe Ihesu in mynde


<PB N="1: 182">

one &thorn;is wyse, bot if he this [felynge] and this mynde, &thorn;at es anely his awene wyrkynge
by custome, halde it a specyalle vesytacyone of oure lorde and thynke it mare &thorn;ane
it es.  For wite &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at a nakede mynde or a nakede ymagy[na]cione of Ihesu
or of any gastely thynge, with-owttene swetnes of lufe in &thorn;e affeccione, or
with-owttene lyghte of knawynge in resoune, es bot a blyndnes, and a waye to dessayte,
if a mane halde it in his awene [syght] mare &thorn;ane it es.  Thare-fore I halde it sekyre
&thorn;at he be meke in his awene felynge, and halde &thorn;is mynde in regarde noghte till
he mowe be custome and vsynge of &thorn;is mynde fele &thorn;e fyre of lufe in his affeccione
and &thorn;e lyghte of knawynge in his resone.  Loo, I haue tolde &thorn;e in &thorn;is mater a
lyttill as me thynke; noghte affermande &thorn;at &thorn;is suffisches, ne &thorn;at &thorn;is es &thorn;e
sothefastnes in &thorn;is mater.  Bot if &thorn;e thynke it o&thorn;er-wyse, or elles any o&thorn;er mane sauour by grace &thorn;e contrarye here-to, I leue &thorn;e saying and gyfe stede to hym.  It
sufficith to me for to lyffe in trouthe principally and noghte in felynge.
</P></DIV3>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>On Deadly and Venial Sin</HEAD>

<P>DEre brothyr, &thorn;ow walde gladly wyte qwilke is venial synne, and qwilke dedly
synne, for &thorn;e thynke qwen a man can knawe &thorn;e tane fra &thorn;e to&thorn;ir, he may be
&thorn;e more war for to flee &thorn;am.  Bot &thorn;e haly doctoure Seynt Austyn says: &laquo;it is
na venial synne &thorn;at itne may be dedely syn qwen it lykyth the; ne dedly
synne, &thorn;an it may be venial qwen it myslykede&raquo;.  Seynt Thomas Alqwyne sayde
&laquo;&thorn;at if a man be tempyd neuyr so harde; if &thorn;e wylle assent nou&yogh;t, be it neuyr
swa foule a sterynge it is na synne, or ellis bot venial synne.  If &thorn;e wylle haue
any lykynge in &thorn;e foule sterynge, be it neuyr swa lytil, &thorn;an it is a party venyal
synne.  If &thorn;e wyll assent with avysment &amp; walde doe &thorn;at wylful sterynge in dede
agayn gude conscience &amp; agayns &thorn;e reson, &thorn;an is &thorn;at steryng dedly synne, alle-if
it be nou&yogh;t fulfylled in dede&mdash;qwilke dedly synne may dampne a soule til endeles
payn, bot if contricion, confession, &amp; satisfaccyon wasche it, &amp; amendys makynge
be sufficiande penaunce&raquo;.  Seynt Gregor sayde be hym-selfe: &laquo;I may nou&yogh;t bot I fele vnleful steryngys of flesche: bot me thare nou&yogh;t, he sayed, assent bot I
wylle.  If I fele it, he sayd, &amp; assent not &thorn;erto, it does me na dere, bot it
lessens my penaunce in &thorn;e payne of purgatorye, &amp; incresys my meryt in &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 183">

blysse of heuen&raquo;.  Als ofte as any creatoure is tempyd &amp; na-wyse in conscience
wille assent, no [is] in wil to haue lykynge in synne: as ofte &thorn;ay wynne &thorn;am diuerse
degrece in heuen amange &thorn;e orders of aungells.  Qwo so walde nou&yogh;t be tempid,
&thorn;at opon &thorn;is wyse for &thorn;er agaynstandynge sulde be wele rewardid of god?  Thomas
Alqwyne sayde: &laquo;For to assent sodanly is venial synne: bot for to couete or assent
be avysment, &thorn;at is dedly synne&raquo;.  Als Thomas seyde: &laquo;Consentynge to &thorn;e dede of lychery is nou&yogh;t anly dampnable dedly synne; bot also consentynge &thorn;at has
luste &amp; lykynge in herte only with lusty wylle, &thorn;at is dedly synne&raquo;.  &THORN;at &thorn;is is sothe, it may be seen be goddis worde in &thorn;e gospel, &thorn;er he sayd &thorn;us: &laquo;If a
man see a woman for to couete hyr nowe, he hathe don lychery&raquo;.  Behalde how
he sayd &laquo;for to couete&raquo;, for if he sawe &amp; couete nou&yogh;t, it ware na synne, or ellis bot lytyl synne, or ellys venial synne.  Bot behalde howe he sayde &laquo;for to
couete hyr&raquo;: ffor qwen a creature sees anothyr, qwethyr so couetys othyr in
thou&yogh;tte &amp; walde assent in synne; alle-if &thorn;at wryched delite be nou&yogh;[t] in dede, it is dedely synne.  Alswa it is sayde &amp; wretyn: &laquo;It is not lefull to behalde &thorn;at
thynge qwylke is nou&yogh;t leful to be couete&raquo;.  Thomas sayde: &laquo;Qwen a mans herte is feruentyly sette opon god, alle thynges disp[le]ses hym &thorn;an &thorn;at my&yogh;te drawe
hym fra god&raquo;.  Alswa he sayde a ful gode worde &amp; a ful gracious: &laquo;Lette &thorn;i
wylle assente to na synne, be it neuyr sa lytylfor if &thorn;ou falle wylfully in til a
lytill synne, &thorn;ou sal, nyl &thorn;ou wylle &thorn;ou, falle in till a gretter&raquo;.  He sayde alswa
&thorn;at &laquo;feruente charite distroyed venial syn, &amp; &thorn;e sterynge of charite may be so
feruente in god, &thorn;at it may waste &amp; wasche away alle venial synne&raquo;.  Bot &thorn;ay
&thorn;at has nou&yogh;t &thorn;is charite, &thorn;ay dare maste baldly falle in venyal
synne.  Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at has &thorn;is charite, &thorn;ay dare nou&yogh;t doe for &thorn;e drede of god agayn gode conscience.  For, Thomas sayde, qwat thynge so is doen agayn conscience, it edifies
to &thorn;e pyne of helle, qwethyr so &thorn;e conscyens be trewe or fals, as &thorn;us.  If a
man thynke &thorn;at he walde doe a certeyn penaunce for &thorn;e lufe of god: if he doe
&thorn;at penaunce ageyn his conscience, he trispas; of hys conscience saye he my&yogh;t
doe penaunce, if he walde, for &thorn;e lufe of god: if he will nou&yogh;t, he does agayn
conscyence, &amp; he does synne.  Qwethyr so &thorn;e penaunce doeynge wer hyndrynge
or fortherynge to hym; if he did agayn conscience, he synnethe.  Bot &thorn;is synne
may sone be forgyfen of god, qwo so cries herthely aftyr goddis mercy.
</P></DIV2>
</DIV1> <DIV1 N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS"><HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><DIV2
TYPE="text">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">De vita cuiusdam puelle</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Alswa Heraclides &thorn;e clerke: telles &thorn;at a maydene forsuke hir Cete and satte
in a sepulcre, and tuke hir mete at a lyttill hole, ten &yogh;ere scho saghe neuer
mane ne womane, ne &thorn;ay hir face; bot stode at a hole and talde why scho was
enclosede, and said &thorn;at &laquo;a &yogh;onge man was tempede of my fairehede: ffor-thy
me warre leuere be als lange als I lyfe in &thorn;is sepulcre, &thorn;an any sawle &thorn;at es
made til &thorn;e lyknes of gode suld perichse by-cause of me&raquo;.  And whene men
askede hire how scho myghte swa lyffe; scho said: &laquo;Fra the begynnynge of the
day I gyfe me till praynge till forthe dayes; thane I wyrke with handes some
thynge, and alswa I wyrke in thoghtes, by patryarkes, prophetes, Appostilles,
Martyrs and confessours, and by-haldes &thorn;aire Ioye; and aftyrwarde I take my
mete; whene euene commys, with gret Ioye I lofe my lorde.  The ende of my
lyfe I habyde in gude hope and tholemodnes&raquo;.  &amp; loo, swa perfitly a womane
lyfede.  Richard herymyte reherces &thorn;is tale in Ensampill.
</P>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="1: 198"><HEAD>The Privity of the Passion:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bonaventura de mysteriis passionis Iesu Christi.</FOREIGN><NOTE>An abridged translation of the <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Meditationes vitae Christi</FOREIGN>, chaps. 74-92.  The ascription to Bonaventure is improbable.</NOTE></HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="179" UNIT="folio"><OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In Nomine Patris et Filii et Speritus Sancti Amen.</FOREIGN>
Here begynnes the Previte off the Passioune of owre lorde Ihesu.</OPENER>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<P>Who so desyres to ffynd comforthe and gostely gladnes in &thorn;e Passione and
in &thorn;e croysse of owre lorde Ihesu, hym nedis with a besy thoghte ffor to duell in
it and all o&thorn;er besynes forgette and sett at noghte: and sothely I trowe fully &thorn;at
who so wolde besy hyme with all his herte and all his mynde and vmbethynke hym
of this gloryus Passione and all the circumstance thare-off, It sulde bryng hym and
chaunge hyme In to a new state of lyfynge.  For he &thorn;at incerches it with depe
thoghte and with all hys hert lastandly, he sall fynde full many thynges thare-In
styrande hym to newe compassione, newe luffe, newe gostely comforthe, and
so sall he be broghte in to a newe gostely swettnesse.  [To gete &thorn;is state]
&thorn;at I speke of, I trowe &thorn;at a mane behoued to rayse vp all &thorn;e scharpenes of
his mynde &amp; opyne whyde the Inere eghe of his soule In to be-holdynge of
&thorn;is b[l]esside passione, and forgett &amp; caste be-hynd hyme for &thorn;e tyme all o&thorn;er
Ocupacyouns &amp; besynes; and that he make hym-selfe present in his thoghte as
if he sawe fully with his bodyly eghe all the thyngys &thorn;at be-fell abowte &thorn;e
crosse and &thorn;e glorious passione of oure lorde Ihesu; and &thorn;at noghte schortly &amp; passandly, bot lufandly, besely, habundandly, &amp; lastandly; noghte sturdandly, ne
with dullnes &amp; hevines of sperit.  &THORN;of euery man aughte with grett reuerance &amp; sadnes to thynk one all &thorn;e leuynge &amp; dedys of oure lorde Ihesu &thorn;at he wroghte
in erthe for man-kynde, neuer-&thorn;e-lesse mekyll more besyly, with mekill sadnes
&amp; deuocyone, awe hym to sett all his herte &amp; all his myghte abowte &thorn;is glorious
passione: ffor here-In he schewes moste lufe &amp; charite to vs, &thorn;e wilke aughte
to bryne all oure hertes in lufe to hym.  And ther-for sett thy-selfe, &thorn;at es &thorn;i
mynde, &thorn;er-to all holly: and be-holde noghte onely &thorn;e payne &amp; crucyfyenge of
thy lorde Ihesu whene he was done one the rode in &thorn;e oure of vndrone, bot
also fro begynnyng of his blisside passione, that es full of matere of pete &amp; compassione.  How mekill compassione, I pray &thorn;e, es it to be-holde &amp; thynke how
owre lorde Ihesu, &thorn;at es bothe verray gode and mane, fro &thorn;e oure of his takinge
at &thorn;e euene, to hye vndrone of &thorn;e morne when he was don&macr; on &thorn;e rode, was in
contenuell batell, and hugge sorowe, and bittire reprevynges, In many skornnynges
and vnresonabyll turmentes, with-owttyne any ryste or cessyng?  Ihesu, mercy, amen.
</P><P>Begynne nowe thy meditacyone at the be-gynnynge of Cristes passyone and
pursue it feruently to &thorn;e laste Ende: of the wilke I sall towche to &thorn;e a littill:
bot thow may vse theme more largelye, after god gyffes &thorn;e grace.  Be-holde
nowe besylye to euery poynte as if &thorn;ou were there bodyly: and be-holde hym
graythely as he rase vpe fro his super, whene he had Endide his Sermone, with
his disciples, and &yogh;ede with theme in to a &yogh;erde where he was ofte wounte to


<PB N="1: 199">

goo with theme.  Goo thow amange theme, &amp; be-holde how lufandly, how
felandly he gose with theme and spekes, &amp; steres theme to praye.  Be-holde also
how he hym-selfe gose fro theme a caste of a stone, and mekely and reuerently
he knelyde downn, prayand to his ffadir.  Abyde now a littill and see &thorn;e wondirs
of thy lorde god. / Now thi lorde Ihesu prayes.  We rede that he ofte-tyms
prayede, bot than he prayede for vs as oure advocate: bot now he prayes [for]
hym-selfe.  Haue therfore pete &amp; compassyone, and wondire of &thorn;e vnmesurabill
meknesse of hym.  For of-all it be sothe &thorn;at he be bothe gode and man, euene
to &thorn;e fadir of heuene, neuer-&thorn;e-lesse he forgettes as it were his godhede, and
prayes mekly as a man; he stode as a no&thorn;ire synnere, prayand to &thorn;e ffadire. /
Be-holde also in hym moste perfite obedience.  What prayede thy lorde Ihesu?
sothely he prayede his ffadire &thorn;at he sulde delyuer hym fro &thorn;e bittire houre of
dede, he couetyd noghte to dye, if it were plesyng to &thorn;e ffadire of heuene; and
neuer-&thorn;e-lesse his aughene fadire wolde noghte here hym.  This I saye aftire some
will &thorn;at was in Criste.  For &thorn;ou sall vndirstande &thorn;at &thorn;ere were many and dyuerse
willis in hym, as doctours say: there was In hym &thorn;e will of &thorn;e fflesche and &thorn;at
wolde one no manere suffyre dede; ther was also In hym &thorn;e will of sensualite
and &thorn;at gruchede and was afferde to suffire dede; ther was also in hym &thorn;e will
of &thorn;e resoune and &thorn;at was Obedyent &amp; consentande to dye; thare was also in
hym &thorn;e will of &thorn;e godhede &amp; &thorn;at commandedyd and ordaynede hym to dye.
And here sall &thorn;ou haue pete &amp; compassione, ffor his ffadire will owtterly that he
dye for oure gilte, and of-all he be his awghene begetyne sone, &yogh;itt will he not
spare hym bot gyffes hyme to &thorn;e dede for vs.  For &thorn;e ffadire of heuene louede
so mekill mankynde, &thorn;at was loste thurghe synne, &thorn;at for redempcione of mans
sawle he putt his aughne sone to &thorn;e dede.  And thene oure lorde Ihesus takes
mekly &thorn;is obedience, and fulfillis it mekly and reuerently. / Here may thow now
see &thorn;e vnspekeabill &amp; &thorn;e vnmesurabill charite, bothe of &thorn;e ffadire and of &thorn;e sone.
There-fore &yogh;eld we agayne pete, compassione, &amp; all manere luffe &amp; wirchyppe.
/ Owre lorde Ihesu prayede his fadire a longe while, and said: &laquo;My moste
mercyfull fadire, I be-seke the that &thorn;ou here my prayere, &amp; despise not my prayere.
Take hede to me, dere ffadire, &amp; here me: for I am heuyde in my trauayle, and
my spyrite es greued in me, and my herte es troublede in my-selfe: and
therefore bowe downne thyne ere to me, &amp; here &thorn;e voyce of my besekynge.  It was
likynge to &yogh;ow, ffadire, for to sende me in to &thorn;is werlde, &thorn;at I sulde make asethe
for mans trespas &thorn;at he did to vs: and as sone as &thorn;ou said thus, I said ,I go',
and as it es wretyne in &thorn;e spalme of me &thorn;at I sulde full-fill thy will, my gode,
so wold I.  &THORN;i sothefastenes I haue schewed to &thorn;e werlde, I haue bene pore
&amp; in manye trauelles fro myn &yogh;outhede, &amp; I haue fulfillide all thi will and done
all thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ou has bedyn me do.  And also what thynge &thorn;at es &yogh;it for to do
I am redy to full-fill it.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse, gud fadir, if it be plesande to &thorn;e, take
fro me &thorn;is bitter passione &thorn;at myne enemyse ordeyne for me.  Thow sees wele,
my dere fadir, howe grete ill &thorn;ey ymagyne agayne me, &amp; how grete falsenes
&thorn;ey put appone me, and all &thorn;eire concell es to do me to dede.  Bot, holy ffadir,
&thorn;ou knawes wele &thorn;at I dide neuer none of thire thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ey put one me,
and &thorn;at &thorn;ar es no wykkednes in my handes, bot I haue euer done &thorn;at was ple-


<PB N="1: 200">

sand to &thorn;e: and &thorn;ay do me ill agayne gude, &amp; hatredene for grett lufe &thorn;at I
schewede to &thorn;em; and my disciple &thorn;ai haue corupte to be &thorn;eire ledare to lose
me, and haue boghte me for thrytty plates.  And there-fore I pray &thorn;e, dere
fadire, &thorn;at thow take awaye fro me this bitter passione.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse if it be
othir-wyese plesande to &thorn;e, thy will be full-fillide.  Rise vpe nowe, ffadire, I
pray &thorn;e, and helpe me: for certes, &thorn;ofe-all they know me noghte for &thorn;i sone,
noghte-for-thy for alls mekill as I haue lyfede amonge theme with-owttyn&macr; any
trispas or gilte, and for many gude dedys &thorn;at I hafe done to them, &thorn;em aughte
noghte to be so fell &amp; crewell agaynes me.  Bot I pray the, ffadir, be noghte
ferre fro me: for why my tribulacione es nere, and &thorn;er es none &thorn;at will helpe
me.&raquo;  Whene owre lorde Ihesu had &thorn;us prayede, he come agayne to his disciples,
&amp; fonde &thorn;em slepande.  Bot he waked theme, &amp; bade &thorn;eme wake &amp; praye, &thorn;at &thorn;ey fall noghte in to temptacione, and comforthede &thorn;em.  &amp; went agayne fro &thorn;em as it were &thorn;e caste of a stone, &amp; mad the seconde prayere; &amp; &thorn;e thride tyme the same Orysone; and saide: &laquo;Rightewyse fadire, sen &thorn;ou owtterly ordeyned &thorn;at I sall suffire ded one &thorn;e crosse for mans saule, thy will be done.  Bot I recomand
to &yogh;owe my dere modir, &amp; my disciples, &thorn;e whilke I haue kept to &thorn;is tyme
whills I haue bene with theme: Bot holy fadir, kepe &thorn;eme now fro all ill&raquo;. /
Beholde in tyme of &thorn;is prayere how his precyous blode rane downe fro his blesside
body as watire habundandly in to &thorn;e grownde ffor gret angwysse &amp; drede &thorn;at
he hade of his bitter dede, and be-holde now here besyly in howe grett angwysse
&amp; trybulacyone &thorn;i lorde Ihesu whas sett in &thorn;is houre.  And be-holde also how
he prayed thrys, or he had any answere; and there-for suffire thowe paciently
all-&thorn;off &thorn;ou be noghte herde one-one. / And whene oure lorde hade &thorn;us prayede,
and was &thorn;us in &thorn;is grett angwysse: the angell seynte Michaell, a prynce of &thorn;e
heuennly courte, apperide to hym comforthande hym &amp; sayande thus: &laquo;Hayle,
my lorde Ihesu.  &yogh;our meke prayeng &amp; &yogh;our blody swetynge I haue offerde to &yogh;our
ffadir in &thorn;e syghte of all heuenly courte, and we all fell doune one knese
prayande hym to take awaye fro &yogh;owe &thorn;is harde passione.  And &yogh;oure ffadir
ansuerde &amp; said: ,My dere sone Ihesu knawes wele &thorn;at &thorn;e rawnssone &amp; saluacione of manes saule, &thorn;at we all desyre so gretly, may not be done &amp; made
withowttyne scheddynge of his blyssede blode: and &thorn;are-for, if it so be &thorn;at he will
&thorn;at mans saule be safe, hym be-houes to dy for it'&raquo;.  Then answ[e]rde oure lorde
Ihesu to &thorn;e angell: &laquo;The hele of mans saule all-gatt I couette, &amp; &thorn;ere-for I
seche rathere to dye &thorn;at mans saule myghte be safe, &thorn;an nott to dye if mans
saule solde be loste: and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e wyll of my ffadir be fullfillede&raquo;.  &THORN;en said
&thorn;e angell to hym: &laquo;Be &yogh;e &thorn;er-for of gude comforthe &amp; suffirs manly: for sone sall passe &yogh;oure disesse &amp; payne, &amp; &yogh;e sall aftir haf Ioye and Endles blise.  For &yogh;oure fadir es euer with &yogh;owe, and he [sal] kepe &yogh;our modir &amp; all &yogh;our disciplys&raquo;. And than owre lorde Ihesu, mekely and reu[er]ently receyuede &thorn;is comforthyng of &thorn;e angell, knowyng how thurghe takynge of owre dedlynes he was made lesse &thorn;en angell whilles he was in this vale of teres; and ryghte as he was ferde and
heuy as mane, righte [so] was he comforthede of &thorn;e angell wordes as mane, prayand
&thorn;e angell to recomande hym to his fadir and to all &thorn;e heuenly courte.  And so
&thorn;e angell toke his leue and went his waye agayne to heuene. / &THORN;ene owre lorde


<PB N="1: 201">

Ihesu rose vpe &thorn;e thryde tyme fro his prayere, all wete with blody swete.
Beholde hym nowe besyly how he wypis his visage, or ells wesches in &thorn;e [fonte]
of Cedrone, all full of angwysche and woo, and haue thowe grete pete of hyme
&amp; compassione, for he myghte noghte haue grett &amp; swett blode so largely
with-owttyne grett bitternesse of sorowe &amp; angwysche. / Be-holde &amp; see now besyli all &thorn;e doynges and disesse of &thorn;i lord Ihesu, how he come to his disciplys &amp; bad them slepe &amp; take theire ryste: and he wakede &amp; watchede as a gude
hirdeman ouer hys floke.  A full gret lufe of oure lorde!  sothely he [lufed] all his [to]
&thorn;e laste Ende of his lyfe, whene hym-selfe was sett in so grett angre &amp; &yogh;it he es
besy abowte &thorn;eire ryste.  Then [saw] he his Enemys come fro ferre with force
and armes, with lanternes &amp; staues, to take hym, and &yogh;itt he wolde noghte
wakkene his disciplis bot sufferde &thorn;eme slepe, to his Enemyse were nere at hym.
&THORN;ene wakkende he &thorn;eme &amp; bade &thorn;eme ryse: &laquo;ffor he &thorn;at has be-trayede me es now commene&raquo;.  And &thorn;an come Iudas &amp; kyssede Ihesu.  For it was &thorn;e manere of oure lorde &thorn;at whene he sent his disciples in any place, for to kysse &thorn;eme at &thorn;e
comyng-agayne: and &thorn;er-for Iudas gafe &thorn;e Iewes &thorn;at takene &thorn;at whame so he
kyssede, hym sulde &thorn;ey take and holde.  Bot Iudas come be-fore, as who say:
&laquo;I am not with &thorn;ise armede mene nor of theire knowyng; bot I kysse &thorn;e &amp; say
haile mayster&raquo;.  Be-holde here nowe oure lorde Ihesu and se how paciently and
how benyngly he resayuede &thorn;e haylsyng &amp; the kyssynge of &thorn;e traytoure; and how
he suffirde hym-selfe to be takene &amp; betyne &amp; dispoyllede, be ledde as a theeffe or
as a mysdoere &thorn;at no powere hade to helpe hym-selfe; ffor he hade more pete
&amp; compassione of his disciples &thorn;at flede awaye for ferde, &thorn;ene he hade of
hym-selfe.  Be-holde now wele how he es led forthe of &thorn;e wykked Iewes towarde
Ierusalem agayne &thorn;e hill hastyly, with grett payne, &amp; his handes boune be-hynd
hyme, boystously gyrdide in his kirtill all one, bare-heuede, &amp; bowande
downe-warde &thorn;e bake for werynesse &amp; gret hastynesse. / When he was presentede be-for Cayphas and o&thorn;er prynces &amp; prestes of &thorn;e lawe, &thorn;ay made myrthe and Ioy as dose a lyone whene he has getyne his pray.  They lede hym in to &thorn;eire chapetere-hous &amp; examende hym straytly; &thorn;ey procurede false wittnesse agayne hym; &thorn;ey dampnede
hym, despysede hym &amp; spytte in his faire face, they hillide his enghne &amp; bobbyd
hym, and with many dispysynges and repreuynges &thorn;ey trauelde hym hougely: and all
he suffirde pacyently with-owttene growchynge.  And here be-holde hym wele &amp; haue
thow compassione of hym. / At the laste whene &thorn;ey were wery for tourmentynge
of hym, they put hym in a presone, [&amp; bonde hym to a peler] of stone, &amp; lefte
with hym armede mene to kepe hym sekerly &thorn;at he sulde noghte passe away;
[&thorn;at] all &thorn;e nyghte myssaide, repreuy[n]ge hyme one &thorn;is manere: &laquo;Thow wenede &thorn;ou had bene wysere &thorn;ene oure prynce&yogh;: it was grette foly!  &thorn;e aughte noghte ones
to opyne &thorn;i mouthe agayne theme: how durste &thorn;ou be so hardy?  Bot now
schewes wele &thorn;i foly, now standes &thorn;ou as &thorn;ou has diseruede.  &THORN;ou erte worthy to
be dede, and with-owttyne dowte so &thorn;ou sall, be seker &thorn;erof&raquo;.  And thus they
trauelde hym all &thorn;at nyghte now one now an o&thorn;er.  Be-holde now &thorn;i lorde gode
how mekly he stode &amp; paciently sufferand all &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ey dide, &amp; ansuers noghte bot stode styll with-owttene any excusynge, &amp; [as] he had bene gilty mekly
enclynande his eghne downewarde: and haue here grete compassione of hym.  A,


<PB N="1: 202">

lorde Ihesu, in to whas handes ware &yogh;e takyne, &amp; how gret was &yogh;oure pacience!
/ And &thorn;us stode he all &thorn;e nyghte bownd to a peler, to &thorn;e morne.  In this tym
saynt Iohn&macr; wente to oure lady &amp; to hir felawghes, &thorn;er &thorn;ey were to-gedyre in
Marye Maudeleyne house, &amp; tolde &thorn;eme all &thorn;at was done to &thorn;eire lorde Ihesu
&amp; to [his] disciplis.  &THORN;en was &thorn;ere vnspekabill sorowes, wepynges &amp; cryenge&yogh;, and wryngynge of honde&yogh;, &amp; murnynge&yogh; with-owttyne mesure.  Be-holde &thorn;eme with grete compassione, ffor &thorn;ei are sette in grete angwisse &amp; in full mekill sorowe for &thorn;eire lofly lorde Ihesu, ffor they knewe wele &thorn;at he sulde be dede.
Then owre lady turnede hire to &thorn;e walle, prayande &thorn;e ffadire of heuene for hir
sone Ihesu, and saide: &laquo;Wirchipfull fadir of heuene, ffadir of mercy &amp; of pete, I
comend in to &yogh;oure hande&yogh; &amp; &yogh;our kepynge my moste dere sonne Ihesu, and I
beseke &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e be noghte cruelle to hym, for &yogh;e are to all othire benynge
&amp; mercyfull.  O endles fadire, whedire Ihesu my dere sone sall nowe be dede?
Sothely he did neuer ill to be dede fore.  Bot, rygtwhise fadyr of heuene, sene
&yogh;e will the redempcyone of manes saulle, I be-seke &yogh;owe lorde, &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde
ordeyne it one ano&thorn;er manere than this: ffor all thyng es possibill to &yogh;owe.  I
pray &yogh;ow, holy ffadire, if it be likynge to &yogh;owe, &thorn;at my dere sone Ihesu be nott
don to dede, bot delyuer &yogh;e hym fro dede &amp; ffro &thorn;e handes of synners, and gyfe
me hym agayne.  For he for obedience &amp; reuerence of &yogh;owe helpes nott
hym-selfe, bot forsakes hym-selfe witterly, as mane &thorn;at myght no&thorn;er helpe hyme-selfe
ne cowthe.  &THORN;ere-fore I pray &yogh;owe, if it plese &yogh;owe, &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde helpe hyme&raquo;. &THORN;us prayede owre ladye for hire dere sone with all &thorn;e affectioune and will of hire herte, &amp; with grett bitternesse and sorowe.  And &thorn;erfore haue now pete and
compassione of hire, &thorn;at was in &thorn;at grete trebulacione for hir dere sone Ihesu.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ad primam.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Arely at morne come agayne &thorn;e prynces and &thorn;e grette of &thorn;e Iewes &amp; toke
hyme owte of presone, &amp; bounde his hande&yogh; by-hynde hym, and repreuede hyme
&amp; bade hym, &laquo;Come forthe, thefe, come forthe to thy dome, ffor this daye sall
we make an ende of thy wykkednes, and nowe sall it be sene what all thy
wissedom profete&yogh; &thorn;e &amp; serues of&raquo;.  And &thorn;us despetously &thorn;ei lede hym forthe be-fore Pylate; and he folowede &thorn;eme as one Innocente lambe &thorn;at were lede to
sacrafice.  Whene his modire and seyn Iohne &amp; &thorn;eire felawes come t&ymacr;mly at morne
to see Ihesu, &thorn;ey mett hym in &thorn;e waye, and when &thorn;ey sawe hym so vnlawefully
and so dispetousely lede with so grette multitude, &thorn;are myghte no tonge telle &thorn;e
wo, &thorn;e sorowe, &thorn;at &thorn;ey hade ffor hym.  In &thorn;is metynge to-gedire, was gret sorowe
one bothe &thorn;e partyese, ffor owre lorde Ihesu hade gret sorowe for compassione
&thorn;at he hade of all his, &amp; pryncipally to his dere modire, ffor he knewe wele &thorn;at
hire sorowe was vnspekabill as towchynge hyme.  Be-holde &thorn;erfore besyly to
euery poynte, fore &thorn;ey are full of sorowe &amp; bytter compassione. / Thus &thorn;ey lede
hym furthe to Pilate; and &thorn;eise womene &thorn;at lofed hyme so tendirly &thorn;ey come
all o fferre, for they myghte noghte com nere hyme for thronge of &thorn;e Iewes.
Than the Iewes accusede hym in many poyntes, and Pilate sent hym to Herode.
And Herode was fayne of hyme, be-cause &thorn;at he couet o longe tyme to se hyme
wirke some wondirs; bot he ne myghte gete no meracle, nor worde, of hyme.
And &thorn;are-for Herode helde hym for a fole, &amp; in diresyoune &amp; skorne he clo&thorn;ede


<PB N="1: 203">

hyme in whytte as a fole &amp; sent hyme agayne to Pilate: and &thorn;en fro &thorn;at tyme
forwarde &thorn;ey helde hyme nott onely a mysedoere, bot also a fole.  Bot he sufferde all
&thorn;is full paciently withowttyne any gruchynge.  Be-holde now here, thow that wilde
be goddes luffere, how [when] he es lede to-warde and frowarde, how schamefully
&amp; how mekely he gose, his face Enclynede to &thorn;e erthewarde, and herande with
grett styllnes of herte &thorn;eire crynges [and] &thorn;eire repreuynge&yogh;, &amp; [suffrand] &thorn;eire
betynges and all manere vnclennes.  Be-holde also how his modire and all his
frendes stand all o ferre lokande, &amp; folowande &thorn;eme, with mekyll murnyng &amp; hertly sorowe. / Whene &thorn;ey hade broghte hyme agayne to Pilate, &thorn;is fell pepyll,
&thorn;ey accusede hym felly vncesynge: Bot whene Pylate couthe fynde no cause of
dede, he wolde haue delyuerede hyme, &amp; said to &thorn;eme: &laquo;I sall chastye hyme and
late hym goo&raquo;.  Then Pilate comandede theyme &thorn;at he sulde be betyne &amp; schorugede. / Thene &thorn;ey dispoylede owre lorde dispitousely with-owttene any pete
&amp; made hym nakyde, &amp; bande hys handis by-hynde hyme and feste hym till a
pelere; &amp; bett hym withe scharpe knotty schourges, a longe whyle.  And as some
doctours says, one euery knott was a scharpe hok of Iryne, &thorn;at with euery stroke
&thorn;ey rofe his tendyr flesche.  He stode naked be-fore theme a faire &yogh;onge mane
schamefull in schapp, and speciouse in bewte passande all erthely mene: he
sufferde &thorn;is harde paynefull betyng of thes wikkede mene in his tendireste flesche
&amp; clenneste.  Floure of all flesche and of all man kynde es nowe full of blo
betynges &amp; blody brystynnge&yogh;; one euery syde stremys downe &thorn;e kynges blode of
heuene fro euery parte of his blyssed body.  He es betyne and betyne agayne,
blester appone blester, and wonde appone wonde, to bothe &thorn;e beters &amp; &thorn;e
[be)-holders were wery, &amp; &thorn;ene &thorn;ei vn-bonde hyme.  Be-holde hym here mekly &amp; habondandly, and if &thorn;ou can haue here no compassione of &thorn;i lorde Ihesu, wete
&thorn;ou wele &thorn;i herte es hardere &thorn;ane &thorn;e stone.  Than was fullfillede &thorn;e profecy of
Ysaye the prophete, sayand thus: &laquo;We be-helde hym all owt-caste and vileste
of all mene, &amp; &thorn;er was in hym no&thorn;er fairenes nor bewte, bot he was lyke a
leprouse mane, smetyne &amp; cast downe fro gode&raquo;.  A, dere Ihesu, what whas he
&thorn;at was so hardy to dispoyle &amp; nakyn &thorn;e?  And how were &thorn;ey wele wers hardy
&thorn;at durste bynde &thorn;e so faste?  Bot sothely, most wikkedly were &thorn;ey hardy &thorn;at
du[r]ste so bett the!  Bot sothely &thorn;ou sone of ryghtwisenes, &thorn;ou with-drewe &thorn;i
bryghte beme, &amp; &thorn;erfore was myrknes ouere all &thorn;e werlde.  A, lorde Ihesu, what
made the to suffire all &thorn;is hard penance, tourmente&yogh; and payne&yogh;?  Sothely thynne
vnmesurabyll luffe &thorn;at &thorn;ou hade to vs, and owre grette wikkednes &thorn;at myghte
not be weschene awaye bot with &thorn;e precyouse licoure of &thorn;i precyouse blode.
A, lord Ihesu, weryede be &thorn;at gret wykkednes &thorn;at was &thorn;e cause &thorn;at &thorn;ou was
so felly tourmente! / When [they lesid hym fro &thorn;e pelere, he &yogh;ode abowte
sekande hys clothes &thorn;at ware castene here &amp; there where he was firste nakede.
Be-holde hym here besyly thus betyne &amp; all tremlynge for colde: for, as &thorn;e
gospell sais, &thorn;e wedire was colde.  Bot whene he sulde haue clede hym agayne
with hys aughene clothes, &thorn;ey wolde noght suffire hym; bot lede hym furthe all
nakede be-fore Pilate &amp; said to hym: &laquo;Sir, this traytoure mad hym-selfe a kynge:
and &thorn;erfore be-houes vs clo&thorn;e hym one kynges manere, &amp; corowne hyme&raquo;.  Then
they toke ane olde rede mantill, foule &amp; myschapene, &amp; clo&thorn;ed hym &thorn;erwith,


<PB N="1: 204">

&amp; toke a garlande of scharpe thornnes in stede of a corowne &amp; threste one his
hede, &amp; toke hym a septur in his hande, all for scorne.  Be-holde &thorn;ow now
besyli, &amp; haue &thorn;ou pete of, his gret paynes, &amp; &yogh;itt did he all &thorn;at &thorn;ey bade hym, &amp; suffers all &thorn;at &thorn;ey do to hym: he toke &thorn;e rede clothe, he bare &thorn;e croune of
thorne one hys heuede, &amp; toke &thorn;e septer in his hande; &amp; &thorn;ey knelyd be-fore
hym &amp; scornede hym &amp; calde hym kynge, &amp; all [he] sufferde &amp; spake righte
noghte agayne.  Be-holde hym nowe with compassione &amp; tendirnes of herte hou
his heued was thurghe-prikkede with scha[r]pe thornes thurghe his [blesside brayne,
and ofte-tyme &thorn;ey smote hyme with &thorn;e septure one &thorn;e heuede fore scorne &amp; dispite; and beholde his blyssede face all rynnande with rede blode.  A &yogh;ee
ouere-donne blynde wreches!  how dredfull &amp; ferdfull sall &thorn;at wirchipfull kynges
heuede apere agayne in his ryghtwyse dome, &thorn;at &yogh;e smote so felly and
dispetousely!  [&THORN;ey] scornede hyme &amp; dispysede hyme as he wolde haue bene a kynge
&amp; myghte nott; and all he sufferde pacyently as [he] hade bene &thorn;eire allere
seruande.  And &yogh;itte theme thoghte not &thorn;is ynoghe: bot for more scorne &amp; repreue
&thorn;ey gedyrde to-gedire all &thorn;e multitude of Iewes, &amp; broghte hym furthe be-fore
&thorn;eme thus scorne[d], weryng &thorn;e croune of thorne, and lede hym be-fore Pilate.
Be-holde now tendirly how he stode all aschamede, mekly bowynge his heuede,
be-fore so grete a multitude of folke roreynge and cryenge &laquo;do hym one &thorn;e crosse&raquo;, scornenynge [hym] as he hade bene a fole, and as all had bene bot foly &thorn;at he
hade spokene be-fore to &thorn;e prynces &amp; &thorn;e pharysens &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ey dighte hym
thus and broghte hym to &thorn;is plighte; and so nott allonely he sufferde of theme
[sorwe] and bodyly payne, bot also many repreuynges &amp; dispites.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>The meditacione of vndrone.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;en all &thorn;e multitude of Iewes come cryeng with gret voyce &thorn;at he solde be
crucifiede, and &thorn;us was he dampnede with-owttyne gylt of &thorn;at cursede domesmane
Pilate.  They hade for-getyne all his benefete&yogh; &thorn;at he hade donne to &thorn;eme, nor
they are noghte styrede to pete &thorn;of-all he be bot ane Innocent &amp; clene of
lyfyng; ne &thorn;ey will not lett for all &thorn;e paynes &amp; turmente&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ey haue done to hyme be-fore; bot they make Ioye &amp; myrthe &thorn;at &thorn;eire malicious Entente &amp; &thorn;eire wikkede will es fulfillede.  &THORN;ey scorned hym &amp; hastede hym to his dede. / Then they broghte hym [in] agayne, &amp; nakynd hym of his purpure; &amp; he stode nakede amonge
theme, &amp; soghte his aughene clothes &thorn;at were throwene abowte, &amp; clede hym
with gret schame before &thorn;eme all, &thorn;at scornned hym as he had bene vileste of
all men &amp; forsakene of god.  Be-holde here and wondire of his grete mekenes
and pacience, and conforme &thorn;e &thorn;ere-to and folowe as mekill as &thorn;ou may. / When
they had clothed hym, &thorn;ey led hym forthe with gret haste to his dede, and laid
one his bake, &thorn;at was so sore &amp; all full of wondes, the hevy crosse: and he as
a meke lambe paciently toke it and bare it forthe with mekill penance and
angwisse; and &thorn;ey led hym forthe be-twix two thefes, and &thorn;at was his felaschipe!
O god Ihesu, how mekyll schame &amp; velany did they to [&yogh;ow] the cursede Iewes,
&thorn;at mad &thorn;e kyng of trewe[t]he felawe to theues!  &amp; more schame [&yogh;e] hade &amp; more reprefe &thorn;en &thorn;e thefes: ffor they did &yogh;owe bere &yogh;oure owne crosse, &amp; &thorn;at rede we nott of &thorn;e thefes. / Be-holde hym here with gret pete &amp; compassione, how


<PB N="1: 205">

he wente stowpande with &thorn;at gret hevy byrdene &thorn;at he bare, &thorn;at was &thorn;e crosse.
Bot for as mekill as his sorowfull modire myghte nott com to hym for gret
thronge of pepull, scho wente be ano&thorn;er waye nerehand &amp; schortere, with seynt
Iohn&macr; &amp; hir felawes, &amp; mett hire sone comyng owt of &thorn;e cete.  And whene cho
sawe hir childe &thorn;us chargede with &thorn;is hevy birdene, &amp; he runne al ouere with
blode, cho fell in swunynge and nerehand was dede for sorowe; [n]or cho myghte
nott speke to hym a worde, nor he to hire, so was he hastede to his dede ... /
And whene he hade borne &thorn;at hevy crosse a gret while, so &thorn;at for werynes &amp; &thorn;e sore wondes &amp; sorenes he myghte no lenger bere it, he laid it downe: and
for they wold not tarye his dede fore ferdenes of changyng of Pilates sentence&mdash;
for he lete be-fore as he wolde hafe delyeuerde hyme: &thorn;ey made one take &thorn;e
crosse &amp; bere it forthe, &amp; lede Ihesu, bound as a thefe, to &thorn;e mounte of Calueri. /
Thynke &thorn;e nott &thorn;at all &thorn;is &thorn;at he suferde in &thorn;e owre of matyns, prime, &amp; vndrone, with-owttyne any more doynge one &thorn;e crosse had bene sorowe &amp; payne
Inoghe, bitternes, sorowe &amp; angwyse to h[e]re?  Certes, I trowe &yogh;is, &amp; mekill
sterynge to petouse compassione, &yogh;a &amp; bryngynge in to tendir and loueande
hertes gret matere of pacience.  And thus we haue saide in this partie what be-fell
in &thorn;ire thre howres.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>The Meditacione of Middaye.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;ere-fore whene oure lorde Ihesu whas thus velansly broghte to &thorn;at stynkande
place of Caluarye, thow may be-holde wykked werkes one ilke a syde.  Be-holde
theme &thorn;at stande beside, and with thi gostely eghe be-holde how some makes
&thorn;e crosse redy, some ordeynede &thorn;e nayles and some &thorn;e hamers, o&thorn;er some
bryng forthe ledders and o&thorn;er Instrumentes &thorn;at &thorn;ey hade ordeynede to do hyme
one the rode wyth.  Thane they nakynde hym agayne be-for all &thorn;e pepill and
rafe of bustously his clothes &thorn;at were drye &amp; bakene to his blessid body
all-abowte hyme in his blyssede blode, and so they drew ofe &thorn;e flesche &amp; &thorn;e skyne
with-owttyne any pete.  And sekerly &thorn;is was a gret payne and a vnsufferabill,
ffor there they renewede all his olde bryssynges &amp; his drye wondes, and &thorn;e
skyne &thorn;at be-fore was lefte one hym, &thorn;en was it alto-gedire rente of &amp; cleuyde
by hys clothes.  O whate sorowe &amp; woo trowestowe &thorn;at his modire hade whene
cho sawe hym thus farene with?  Scho had sorowe with-owttyne mesure and also
gret schame, whene cho sawe hym thus stande nakede &mdash; ffor &thorn;e fals Iewes lefte
nott so mekill one hyme as his preue clothes: and &thorn;erfore his sorowefull modire
wente in gret haste to hir sone &amp; halses hyme and hilles hym with the vaile of
hire heuede.  O lorde Ihesu, how mekill sorowe &amp; pete was thane in hire herte!
I hope cho myghte not speke to hym a worde for gret sorowe and tribulacione
of sperite.  Bot cho myghte no more helpe hyme nor do to hyme, bot &thorn;at cho
couerde hys preue membirs.  For they refte hym fro hire with gret Indignacione
and Enviousely, and as wode mene they threwe hym wyde opyne one &thorn;e crosse,
and strenede oute his armes with gret violence one euery side, and smote hym
thrughe bothe &thorn;e handes to &thorn;e crosse with gret nayles; &amp; whene &thorn;ey hade so
done, &thorn;ey went to his fete: &amp; &thorn;e holes of &thorn;e crosse were made so ferre &thorn;at
his fete myghte nott reche theme be a gret thynge: and &thorn;an &thorn;ay tuke rapes &amp;


<PB N="1: 206">

with gret violence &thorn;ey drewe owte his body &amp; his fete, to &thorn;ei were mete to &thorn;e
holes.  And aftere &thorn;at they reysede vpe &thorn;e crosse one Ende, as many as myghte
ley hande one, &amp; lett it fall downe in to a mortase of stone, was ordeyned &thorn;erfore:
and In this hevy fallynge all &thorn;e Ioyntes &amp; cenowes of his blesside body braste
in-sondire.  And whene he was thus sprede o-brode one &thorn;e crosse more straite
&thorn;an any parchemyne-skyne es sprede one &thorn;e harowe, so &thorn;at mene myghte tell
all &thorn;e blyssede bones of his body: thane rane fro hym one euery syde stremes
of blode owt of his blessede wondes.  For he was sett so straytly &thorn;at he myghte
nott remowe fote nor hande nor lyme of hym bot his blyssede hede; thies thre
nayles bare vpe &amp; sustente all &thorn;e weghte of hys body.  He sufferde mekill payne,
&yogh;a more &thorn;an herte may thynke or tunge tell.  He hangged by-twyx two thefes
as he &thorn;at hade bene fawty.  One euery syde was repreues and paynes.  And &yogh;it
whene he was so hard sette, &yogh;itt wolde &thorn;ey nott cesse of dispyssynge: Some
blasfemede hym &amp; said fy one hym &thorn;at distroyes, and o&thorn;er some saide: &laquo;Othire
mene saued he, bot hym-selfe he may nott helpe.  If he be goddes sone, late
hym come doune of &thorn;e crosse &amp; we sall trowe one hym&raquo;; and one many o&thorn;er
wyse &thorn;ey repreued hym all &thorn;e daye.  Also &thorn;e knyghtes &thorn;at crucyfied hym,
departede amonge&yogh; theme his clothes in his awene syghte. / And all &thorn;is &thorn;ey did in
presence of his sorowfull modir, whas sorow &amp; compassione was gretly &thorn;e cause
of encressyng of hir dere sones passione, and &thorn;e sones passione ekede &thorn;e modire
sorowe; ffor oure lady hange one &thorn;e Rode with hire dere childe in soule, and
rathere couett to dye with hym pene to lyfe ...  &THORN;er was also be-syd &thorn;e crosse
standyng by oure lady Iohn&macr; Ewangeliste, Marie Mawdelyne, &amp; o&thorn;er two Maries
oure lady systers, &amp; all &thorn;ese wepede full tenderly for oure lorde Ihesu; &thorn;ey had
gret compassione of oure lord Ihesu and also of his modire, &amp; as ofte was &thorn;eire
sorowe renuede as any new passione, myssayenge&yogh; or repr[e]ue was done to oure
lorde Ihesu &amp;c.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>A meditacyone off Non&macr;e.</HEAD>

<P>Owre Lorde Ihesu whilles he hang one &thorn;e crosse, to &thorn;e howre of his ded, he was
noghte Idill, bot he taughte gret perfeccione.  He spake seuene wordes, the wilke
we rede in &thorn;e gospell.  The fyrste was whene he prayede for theme &thorn;at did hym
to dede, sayeng: &laquo;Fadir, for-gyffe theme theire trespas, for they wate nott whate
they doo&raquo; ...  Thise wordes were takyne of gret pacience, perfite lufe &amp; charite, &amp; also schewenge of Ensampill of grette myldnes &amp; pete. / The secund worde was
when he spake to his modir of saynte Iohn&macr;, &amp; said: &laquo;Womane, be-holde &thorn;i
sone&raquo;.  He called hire not modir bot womane, &thorn;at cho sulde nott for tendirnes
of lufe haue more sorowe ne dissese. / The thryde worde was when he spake to
&thorn;e thefe &thorn;at hange be-syde hyme one &thorn;e crosse, &amp; said: &laquo;This daye sall &thorn;ou be with me in paradyse&raquo;.  A, this was a kynd worde, &amp; a swete worde, &amp; a worde to vs of gret comforthe, whene he &thorn;at was a theefe &amp; a mysdoere all his lyfe
to &thorn;e laste houre of his dede, and thane for he forthoghte hys synne &amp; beleuede
in oure lorde Ihesu, had forgyfnes.  Now, lorde, loued myght &thorn;ou be! / The
fferth worde was: <FOREIGN>Heloy heloy, lama&yogh;abatani:</FOREIGN> &THORN;at es to saye: &laquo;My god, my
gode, why hase &thorn;ou forsakene [me]?&raquo;  as who saye: &laquo;my fadir, &thorn;ou loues so


<PB N="1: 207">

mekill &thorn;e soule of mane &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase gyffene me to be dede for it, and so
semes it &thorn;at &thorn;ou has fo[r]-sakene me&raquo;. / The fyfte worde was: &laquo;I thryste&raquo;.  This was a bitter worde full of compassione bothe to his modir &amp; to seynt Iohn&macr; &amp; to all his frendis &thorn;at louede hym tendirly, and to vnpeteuose Iewes it was comforthe &amp; grete gladnes.  For &thorn;of it were so &thorn;at hym thrystede for &thorn;e hele of manes soule, neuer-&thorn;e-les in sothefastnes hym thrystede bodily; &amp; &thorn;at was no
wondyr, for thurghe scheddynge of hys precyouse blode so habundandly, &amp; for
grete angwyse &thorn;at he sufferde withowttyne cessynge fro &thorn;e thursedaye at euene
to &thorn;e ffrydaye at hey-none, he was all Inwardly drye and thristy.  And whene
&thorn;ise vnpetouse mene vmbethoghte theme in what thynge &thorn;ey myghte moste dere
hyme, they tuke aysell &amp; gall &amp; mengede to-gedir, and gafe hym to drynke.
/ The sexte worde was whene he saide: &laquo;It es all done&raquo;, as who say: &laquo;Fadyr, &thorn;e Obedience &thorn;at &thorn;ou bad me do, I haue fullfillede it; and &yogh;it, if &thorn;are be any more &thorn;at &yogh;e will &thorn;at I do, I am redy to fulfill it&raquo; ...  And thane he be-gane to langwesse as &thorn;e maner es agayne &thorn;e dede, now speryng hys eghne &amp; now
Openyng &thorn;eme, nowe bowynge his heuede downne one &thorn;e to syde and now one
&thorn;e to&thorn;er, and all hys strenghes &amp; all his myghte be-gane to faile: / &amp; &thorn;en said
he &thorn;e seuend worde, cryenge with a hye voyce &amp; a myghty, &amp; with teres wepynge sayeand: &laquo;Fader, I comende my sperite in to &thorn;i handes&raquo;; and thane, when he had said &thorn;is wordes, he &yogh;elde &thorn;e goste ... / O, dere frende, what sorowe trowes
thow vmlappede the soule of his dere modyre, when cho sawe hir dere sone so
paynefully fayle and dolefullye dye?  I trow &thorn;at for mekill payne and angwysse
scho was all slokenede in sorowe, and made as it were incencebill and as it
were halfe-dede, mekill more &thorn;ane thane whene cho mete hym in &thorn;e waye beryng
his crosse.  And what trowes thow &thorn;at Marie Maudeleyne dyde &thorn;at so mekyll
loued Ihesu?  what dyd sayne Iohn&macr;, moste bylouede of Ihesu of all his disciplys?
and what trowes &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;e to&thorn;er two systyrs of oure lady dyd?  What myghte
they do?  &THORN;ey where slokende and fulfillide with bitternes of sorow and made
dronkene with sobbynge and sygheyng, ffor all they wepide with-owttyne mesure. /
Be-holde now how thi lorde Ihesu honge dede one &thorn;e crosse for &thorn;i lufe.  All
&thorn;e multitude of &thorn;e folke where &thorn;ene gone home, bot onely oure lady &amp; hir
systers &amp; saynt Iohn&macr;; they duellide &amp; sett theme doune be-syde &thorn;e crosse, and
ofte &thorn;ey lokede one &thorn;eire lufe, abydand helpe how &thorn;ey myghte take hyme downe
&amp; bery hym.  Now, &amp; thow wolde wele &amp; avesyly be-holde &thorn;i lorde Ihesu, thow
may fynde &thorn;at fro &thorn;e crowne of &thorn;e heuede to &thorn;e sole of his fete &thorn;are was no
hole spotte lefte one hyme; nor lym nor party of his blyschede body &thorn;at ne it
was full of payne, passione, woo, angwysse, and sorowe. / Thow haste now herde
me reherse here &thorn;e manere of his crucyfyenge, his passione and his bitternes,
and his rewefull dede, the wilke he sufferde in &thorn;e houre of vndrone and of
none, aftyr &thorn;is littill wryttynge for sterrynge of deuocyone at &thorn;is tyme: and
therefor studye &thorn;ou devotely, mekly, and besyly for to clefe &thorn;erto, and take Ensampill
&thorn;arof as mekill as in &thorn;e es, thourghe &thorn;e helpe of &thorn;e mercy of Ihesu, and folowe
aftire.  And nowe I will reherse the schortely whate be-fell aftyr &thorn;at he was
dede at &thorn;e houre of none &amp;c.
</P></DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">

<PB N="1: 208"><HEAD>&para; Also at None &amp;c.</HEAD>

<P>Aftire &thorn;e houre of none the petefull modire of Ihesu oure lady saynte Marie,
saynt Iohn&macr;, Marie Maudeleyne, &amp; &thorn;e two systers of oure lady, &thorn;ey satt styll
abyddynge, &amp; be-holdynge with-owttyne cessynge oure lorde Ihesu so hangyng
be-twixe two thefes nakede &amp; so petousely woundede, so bitterly turment, so
schamfully done to dede, and vtterly for-sakene off all mene.  And as &thorn;ey satte
thus to-gedire, they sawe come fro &thorn;e Cete a grete companye of armede mene,
that where sente fro &thorn;e prynces of &thorn;e Iewes to take &thorn;eme downe &thorn;at hange one
&thorn;e crosse and bery &thorn;eme: that they solde nott hang one &thorn;e crosse one &thorn;e
grette sabot-daye.  Than oure lady &amp; hir companye rose vpe &amp; behelde theme,
ffor thene begane &thorn;eire sorowe all newe &amp; drede [&] ferdnes to begyne.  Oure lady
was &thorn;ane full ferde and couthe noghte bot turnede hire to hir sone as he hange
dede one &thorn;e Rode, and said to hym: &laquo;My dere sone, whareto come &thorn;ise mene
agayne?  what will &thorn;ey do to &thorn;e more?  haue &thorn;ey nott done &thorn;e to ded?  My dere
sone, I wend &thorn;ey hade fullfillede all &thorn;eire will of the: bot, me thynke, &thorn;ey will
not cesse to pursue [&thorn;e] dede.  My dere sone, I wate neuer whate I sall do, ffor
no&thorn;er I myghte haue &thorn;e leuynge nor I may not defende &thorn;e dede.  Bot I sall
come and stande be-syde the crosse at thy fete, my dere sone, and I beseke thy
dere fadire &thorn;at he make &thorn;eme to haue mercy one the and pete&raquo;.  And &thorn;an &thorn;ey
all fyve knelide downe to-gedire be-fore &thorn;e crosse of Ihesu, sore wepande. / Thane
come &thorn;eise wikkyde Iewes: &amp; whene &thorn;ey sawe &thorn;ise two thefes &thorn;at hang by oure
lorde one lyfe, &thorn;ey brake &thorn;eyre thees &amp; slewe theme all-owte, &amp; caste theme
vilancely in to a dyke.  And whene &thorn;ey come to oure lorde Ihesu, oure lady his
modire was a-drade &thorn;at &thorn;ey suld do so with oure lorde: scho fell downe one
hire knees, &amp; helde vp bothe hir handes tendirly wepynge, &amp; said: &laquo;Brethire, I
pray &yogh;ow for goddes lufe, &thorn;at &yogh;e do no more to my sone.  I am here his
sorowfull modire, &amp; &yogh;e knowe wele &thorn;at I greued &yogh;ow neuer ne trespaste agayne &yogh;ow; and &thorn;of-all my sone semed contrarie to &yogh;ow, &yogh;e haue now slayne hyme, and I
will for-gyfe &yogh;owe &thorn;e wronge &amp; &thorn;e trespas &thorn;at &yogh;e haue done, &amp; my dere son&macr;s dede, so &thorn;at &yogh;e do mercy with me &thorn;at &yogh;e breke not his lymmes, &thorn;at I may lye hym hole in his graue.  It nedis not &thorn;at &yogh;e breke his lymmes, fore &yogh;e see wele
he es dede and passede forthe&raquo;.  &THORN;en said Iohn&macr; &amp; Marie Maudeleyne &amp; oure
lady systers: &laquo;A, dere, whate doo &yogh;e?  why do &yogh;e knele, swete lady of heuene?
&yogh;e knele at &thorn;e fete of wikkede mene, and &yogh;e pray &thorn;eme &thorn;at no prayere will
here.  Wene &yogh;e to bow to &thorn;e mercy of creuell wikkede &amp; prowde mene?  Nay,
lady, it will not be, for meknes es abhomynabill to prowde mene, and thare-fore,
lady, &yogh;e trauell in vayne&raquo;. / And &thorn;an one of &thorn;eme &thorn;at hyghte Longeus, [&thorn;at] &thorn;at tyme whas prowde and wykkede, bot aftyre he was conuertede &amp; was a holy
martire: he tuke a longe spere &, dispysande oure lady prayere, ffersely and
with a fell herte he thriste oure lorde thorow-owte his swete herte, &amp; made a
greuose wonde: &amp; one-one rane owte blode &amp; watere.  Thane ffell his modyr in
swoune in Marie Maudelyne armes.  Than Iohn&macr; for gretnesse of sorowe tuk
herte to hyme &amp; saide: &laquo;&yogh;e wikkede mene, why do &yogh;e &thorn;us?  Se &yogh;e not wele he es dede?  Will &yogh;e also slee his sorowefull modyre?  Gose home and late vs bery
hym oure-selfe&raquo;.  Than, as god wolde, &thorn;ey went home.  And &thorn;ane they comforthede
oure lady &amp; sette hir vpe; &amp; &thorn;an askede scho &thorn;eme what &thorn;ey had done to hir


<PB N="1: 209">

sone; and &thorn;ey said, no more &thorn;an cho sawe.  &THORN;an syghede scho and be-helde
hir sone so dispetousely wondede.  Than dyede scho neghe fore sorowe.  How
ofte, thynke the that oure blyssed lady sufferde payne of dede?  Sothely, as ofte
as scho sawe any new payne or passione done to hire sonne.  And &thorn;erfore was
fulfillide &thorn;e prophecy of holy Semyone, &thorn;at said &thorn;e swerde of sorowe sulde
thurghe-perse hir herte. / Than sett they &thorn;eme downe by &thorn;e crosse agayne, &amp; wiste noghte what they myghte do.  For they myghte nott take downe &thorn;at body&mdash;
they had no myghte &thorn;are-to.  Ne awaye durste &thorn;ey noghte go and leue hym
one &thorn;e crosse; &amp; &thorn;er myghte they noghte abyde long, for nyghte com one theme:
and &thorn;us were &thorn;ey sette in grete perplexite and dowte what theme was beste to
doo.  A, mercyfull Ihesu, how myghte &yogh;e suffere &yogh;our owene modire, &thorn;e whilke
&yogh;e ches of all &thorn;e womene of &thorn;e werlde for to be myrrour and example to &thorn;e
werlde &amp; to be &yogh;our owene rystynge-place, to be &thorn;us pyned, trobulde, turment
&amp; disessede?  It es tyme &thorn;at cho hade som riste, &amp; &yogh;e wolde wyche-safe &amp;c.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; At the houre of Euensonge.</HEAD>

<P>Ano&thorn;er tyme &thorn;ey lokede &amp; saw come fro &thorn;e cete-warde a company.  Bot it
was Iosephe of Aromathy &amp; Nycodeme, &thorn;at come with Instrumentte&yogh; to take
downe &thorn;e blyssede body of oure lorde Ihesu Criste; and &thorn;ey broghte also with
&thorn;eme a hundrethe pounde of aloes &amp; of myre.  Than oure lady &amp; hir company
rose vpe with gret drede, and wend it hade bene any new schame of turmentrye.
A, dere god, how gret was &thorn;eire tribulacione &thorn;at day!  Than Iohn&macr; loked &amp; saide: &laquo;&yogh;ondire comes Ioseph &amp; Nycodeme&raquo;: and than oure lady was gretly
comforthede, &amp; thankede god &thorn;at had thoghte one &thorn;eme &amp; sent theme helpe &amp; socoure; &amp; bade Iohn&macr; &thorn;at he sulde goo agayne &thorn;eme &amp; kepe &thorn;eme.  And Iohn&macr;
in gret haste &amp; mette &thorn;eme; &amp; ilkone haylseste o&thorn;er with grete wepynge &amp; murnynge&mdash;for &thorn;er myghte none speke with o&thorn;er a longe while for tendirnesse
of compassione, &amp; mekillnes of sorowe &amp; wepynge.  Than Ioseph spake and askede
ware oure lady was, &amp; who was with hire, &amp; what all &thorn;e o&thorn;er disciplis of Ihesu did.  Thene Iohn&macr; tolde &thorn;eme of owre lady &amp; of hire companye; bot of Peter
&amp; of all &thorn;e o&thorn;er discyplis he couthe nott tell, ffor he had not herde tell of &thorn;eme
of all &thorn;at daye.  And whene &thorn;ey come nere at &thorn;e crosse, on-one &thorn;ey fell downe
one knees &amp; wyrchepyd oure lorde.  And &thorn;ene oure lady &amp; hyr company knelyd
downe &amp; with gret reuerence resayued &thorn;eme and wyrchipede &thorn;eme, &amp; &thorn;ey knelyd agayne.  And &thorn;ene said oure ladye to &thorn;eme: &laquo;&yogh;e do wele &thorn;at &yogh;e haue mynde of oure lorde &amp; &yogh;our mayster, ffor he loffede &yogh;owe full mekill; and I tell &yogh;ow I haue full grete comforthe of &yogh;our commynge, ffor we wist nott be-fore what we myghte do: &amp; &thorn;erfore gode thanke &yogh;ow&raquo;.  Than they ansuerde &amp; saide: &laquo;We sorowe &amp; murne with all oure hertes for all &thorn;at es done to hyme, &amp; fayne wolde we haue helpene hyme, bot we myghte not with righte ouere-come wikkednesse; neuer-&thorn;e-les &thorn;is littill servise sall we do to oure lorde&raquo;.  Than rose &thorn;ey vpe &amp; mad &thorn;eme redy to take hyme downne. / Thane Iosephe sett vpe a leddere one &thorn;e ryghte syde, and drew owt &thorn;e nayle of his ryghte hande, with gret trauayle, ffor it was full faste dreuene in &thorn;e tree, and &thorn;e nayle was boystous of it-selfe; [and be-tuke it to.  Iohn&macr; &amp; bade hyme &thorn;at oure ladye sulde noghte see it, ffor ferde of swounynge].  &THORN;ene


<PB N="1: 210">

Nychodeme wente vpe one &thorn;e lefte syde &amp; toke owte &thorn;at nayle, &amp; be-tuke it to Iohn&macr;. &THORN;ene Nichodeme com doune &amp; went to &thorn;e fete, &amp; Ioseph bare vpe &thorn;e body of Ihesu.  A, Iosephe, wele was the &thorn;at so myghte holde &thorn;e blyssede body of Ihesu!
Than tuke oure lady &thorn;at o hande &thorn;at hange downwarde, with gret reuerence, &amp; putt it till hire face, &amp; be-helde it &amp; kyssed it with many teres &amp; sore syghynges.
When &thorn;e nayle of &thorn;e fete was pullyd owte, Ioseph come softely doune, &amp; &thorn;ene &thorn;ey all toke his blyssede body, &amp; laide it downe one &thorn;e grownde.  &amp; our lady tuke his heuede one hyre kne, &amp; Marie Maudeleyne his fete, where scho hade
fune before-tyme ffull mekill grace; all &thorn;e to&thorn;er [stode] abowte hyme, and made
mekyll mone, waymentyng &amp; wepynge, as it hade bene &thorn;eire owune getyne childe.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Att Complyne.</HEAD>

<P>Aftire they hade stande lange &thorn;us wepynge a gret while, Ioseph come to oure
lady and prayed hire &thorn;at scho wolde suffere them to dighte &thorn;e body and bery it.
Then saide oure lady: &laquo;Nay, gud frendis, takes nott fro me my sone [so sone],
bot rathere bery me with hym&raquo;.  Scho wepid with-owttyne comforthe, scho
be-helde &thorn;e wondes of his hende &amp; fete &amp; syde, nowe one &amp; nowe one o&thorn;er, scho be-helde his lufly face defoulled with spittynge &amp; brissede blode, his heuede
prikkede with scharpe thornnes: &thorn;ere was &thorn;ene no wepynge, no be-holdynge,
no kyssynge, &thorn;at myghte fill hire ...  Bot it drewe nere nyghte, &amp; Iohn&macr; prayede
hire &thorn;at scho wolde voche-saue to suffere Iosephe &amp; Nychodeme to dyghte &thorn;e
body of Ihesu &amp; graue it: &laquo;ffor &thorn;ey myghte lightely, he said, if &thorn;ey tariede longe, fall vndire daungere of &thorn;e Iewes&raquo;.  Thene scho, as wyse lady &amp; discrete,
vmbethoghte hyre how scho was be-takyne to &thorn;e kepynge of Iohn&macr;: scho blyssede
hire sone &amp; sufferde theme to do with hym what so &thorn;ey wolde.  Thene Ioseph
&amp; Nychodeme be-gane to lape hyme in sendell, as &thorn;e manere was of Iewes to be
beryede.  Bot oure lady held styll his heuede in hir lape, to dyght it hir-selfe;
and Marie Maudeleyne his fete, and prayed theme &thorn;at scho myghte dight his
fete where scho had fune mercy and grace.  Thene scho tuke his fete and helde
&thorn;eme, &amp; swounnede nere for sorowe, &amp; &thorn;e fete &thorn;at scho weschede be-fore with teres of compunncione, aftyrwarde&yogh; scho weschede theme wele better with teres
of deuocyone &amp; bitter compassione.  Scho sawe his fete so dulfullye woundede
&amp; drye bakene in blode, &thorn;at scho wept full tendirlye; scho desyrede to dye for
sorowe, bot scho ne myghte.  Scho wolde fayne haue anoyntede all his body and
lappede it, bot scho had no powere &thorn;erto; scho myght no more do, scho
weschede his fete with teres of hir eghne, &amp; wyped theme with hir here&yogh;, scho
halsede &thorn;eme &amp; kissed &thorn;eme, lapped &thorn;eme &amp; dyghte theme one &thorn;e beste manere &thorn;at scho couthe.  Then whene all &thorn;e body was dyghte, &thorn;ey lokede to oure lady
&thorn;at scho sulde dyghte &thorn;e heuede, and &thorn;ane begane they to wepe all newe.
Oure lady sawe &thorn;at [scho] ne myghte no lengare tarye: scho kyssede hir dere sone
and said to hym: &laquo;My dere sone, now holde I &thorn;e dede one my kne: A, how
hard es &thorn;e departynge of &thorn;e &amp; me!  Mery &amp; Ioyefull was oure lyfe to-gedire,
withowten&macr; greuance or offence of any o&thorn;er, &thorn;ofe-all &thorn;ou be &thorn;us ded and spilte,
my dere sone, withowttene gylte.  Trewly, my dere sone, serued I &thorn;e and &thorn;ou
me: bot in &thorn;is bataile thy fadire wold nott helpe, &amp; I myghte not in no kynde,


<PB N="1: 211">

and &thorn;ou spylte &thorn;i-selfe for man-kynde.  O dere lorde, how herde and paynefull
was &thorn;at byenge!  I am fayne for &thorn;e lufe of manns saule; bot for &thorn;i sorow &amp; &thorn;i
bitter ded I pynede with-owttene mesure, ffor I knewe, dere sone, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
neuere synned ne trespassede agayne mane &amp; &thorn;erfore arte &thorn;ou done to ded.
Now, my dere sone, es oure felachipe twynnede, now be-houes me parte fro the.
I thy moste sorowfull modire now sall I bery &thorn;e my dere sone; and aftyrwarde
whedire sall I wende?  where sall I duell?  how sall I lyfe with-owttyne the?  I
wolde fayne be beried with the, &thorn;at where so thowe were, I myghte be with
the.  Bot sene I may noghte be grauene with &thorn;e in body, my soule sall I leue
in graue with the; I comende it to &thorn;e.  A, my dere sone, how bittire es this
departynge!&raquo;  &amp; &thorn;us with a floude of teres sche weschede his vesage, mekill better &thorn;ene Maudeleyne did his fete.  Scho wypede his face, &amp; kissede his mouthe and
his eghne, &amp; wonde his blyssede heuede In a sudarye, and besyly dighte it as it
sulde be; at &thorn;e laste scho crossede hyme and blyssed hyme.  And &thorn;ene &thorn;ey all
rose vp &amp; knelide be-fore hyme, honourede hym &amp; kyssede his fete, &amp; tuke vp
his body &amp; bare it to his graue.  Owre lady helde vp his heued, &amp; Maudeleyne
his fete, &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er went in-myddis berynge vp his body.  For &thorn;e [graue] was not
ferre fro &thorn;e [place] &thorn;at he was crucifiede [in]; in &thorn;e wilke [graue] they beriede hyme
with grett reuerence kneland, gretande with many bitter teres, sadde sobbynges
&amp; sorowfull syghynges.  And whene he whas thus laide in his graue, his modire
blyssede hyme &amp; halssede hyme &amp; fell apone hire dere sone; &amp; &thorn;ene Iohn&macr; &amp; hir sisters lyftede hir, vp &amp; couerde &thorn;e graue with a grett stone...
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"> <HEAD>A meditacione [after] complyn; &amp; o&thorn;er thynge&yogh; of his beryeng.</HEAD>

<P>Whene Ioseph of Aromathy had fulfillede his office, he said to oure lady:
&laquo;Fore goddes sake, &amp; for &thorn;e luffe of &yogh;our dere sone Ihesu my lorde &amp; my mayster, &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde vochesaffe to come home to my house!  I knowe wele, lady, &thorn;at
&yogh;e haue no house of &yogh;oure aghene, &amp; all &thorn;at I haue it es at &yogh;oure will&raquo;.  And Nychodeme prayede hir one &thorn;e same manere.  A, lorde Ihesu, how grete
compassione es this!  the qwhene of heuene has nott so mekill to be herberde Ine o
nyghte; and all &thorn;e sorowfull dayes of hir wedowhede hir be-houes to ly vndire
o&thorn;er mens hillynge.  &amp; wele may &thorn;is be calde dayes of hir wedowede to hire:
ffor hir dere sone oure lorde Ihesu was to hir bothe spouse &amp; sone, ffadire &amp; all
o&thorn;er gude, and &thorn;erfore, whene scho for&yogh;ode hyme, scho for&yogh;ode also all o&thorn;er
gude with hyme.  And &thorn;erfore was scho thane in wedowede sothefastly, &amp; had
no duellynge-place to come too.  Then scho Enclynede mekely to &thorn;eme, thankand
&thorn;eme of &thorn;eire gud will, &amp; said how scho was be-takyne to Iohn&macr; &amp; &thorn;are[fore]
scho myghte nott do bot at Iohn&macr;es ordynance.  And &thorn;en Iohn&macr; answerde &amp; saide &thorn;at he wolde lede hire to &thorn;e mownt Syone, where oure lorde Ihesu soupede
&thorn;e nyghte before with his disciplis.  Then Ioseph and Nychodeme toke &thorn;eire
leue at oure lady, &amp; wirchipede &thorn;e sepulcre, &amp; &yogh;ode home: and Iohn&macr; &amp; oure lady bode styll at &thorn;e graue.  After, whene it begane to drawe to nyghte, Iohn&macr;
said to oure lady: &laquo;It es nott honeste &thorn;at we duell here ouer-longe, or &thorn;at we
come to &thorn;e cete be nyghte: and &thorn;erfore, if it be lykynge to &yogh;owe, go we hens&raquo;.
Then oure lady rose vp, &amp; &thorn;ey bothe knelyd downe to-gedire at &thorn;e sepulcre


<PB N="1: 212">

&thorn;en oure lady halsede &thorn;e sepulcre and blyssett it, &amp; said: &laquo;My dere sone, I may
no lengare duelle nowe with &thorn;e: I recomende &thorn;e to thy ffadyre&raquo;.  Than scho
lifte vp hir eghne to &thorn;e heuene-warde &amp; prayede to &thorn;e fadir, sayande: &laquo;Endles
ffadire, I recomende to &yogh;owe my dere sone Ihesu, &amp; myne aghene soule, &thorn;e wilke I
lefe here with hym&raquo;, &amp; thene be-gane &thorn;ey two [to go].  Whene scho come for-gayne &thorn;e crosse, scho knelide downe one hir knes &amp; honoured &thorn;e crosse, &amp; said: &laquo;Here dyede my dere sone &amp; here was his preciouse blode schede&raquo;, &amp; so did all hir felawes.  Here may thowe thynke &thorn;at oure lady was the fyrste body that
wirchippede the crosse ....  righte as scho was &thorn;e firste .. tellyng and reherseynge of &thorn;e
wordes &amp; dedis of &thorn;eire swete lorde Ihesu. / Oure lady was euer-more pesefull
&amp; quiete in sperite, ffor scho hade euermore certayne hope &thorn;at he sulde sone
ryse vp agayne, and in &thorn;at saterday was all &thorn;e faythe of holy kyrke in hir alone
&mdash;and &thorn;erfore es the saterday specyally wirchepde in &thorn;e honoure of owre lady.
Neuer-&thorn;e-lese scho myghte nott be merye nor glade, be cause of vmbethynkynge
of &thorn;e bitter dede of oure lorde Ihesu hir dere sone. / At euene, aftere &thorn;e sonne
settynge, whene it was lefull to wyrke, Marie Maudeleyne, Marie Iacobi &amp; Marie
Salome, oure lady systyrs, wente to by spycery to make oynement of.  Be-holde
&thorn;ene nowe how besyly &thorn;ey wente with hevy chere in manere of wedouse, and
come to a man &thorn;at was wele willy to &thorn;eire lorde &amp; gladly &amp; willyly fulfillede
&thorn;eire desyre, &amp; &thorn;ey boghte of hym spyceryse &amp; payede hyme &thorn;erfore; &amp; come home &amp; ordeynede &thorn;is onyment.  Be-holde besyly &thorn;ise womene how trewly &amp; besily, how deuoutly on &thorn;e best maner &thorn;at &thorn;ey cane they trauelle in theire
lordes servyse, with many teris &amp; sore sygheynges.  Owre lady &amp; &thorn;e appostilles
stode all &amp; be-helde &thorn;eme; and all &thorn;at nyghte &thorn;ey abode at home.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>How oure lorde went to hell: fyrste aftire his ded.</HEAD>

<P>Be-holde now what owre lord Ihesu dide one &thorn;e Saterday.  As sune as he was
dede, he wente downe to hell to owre holy ffadyrs &thorn;at ware in lymbo to tyme
of his resureccione.  &amp; &thorn;ene were &thorn;ey all in grete Ioye: for &thorn;e syghte of gode es
perfite Ioye.  &THORN;ere was also &thorn;e thefe &thorn;at oure lorde hangynge one &thorn;e crosse
said thus to, &laquo;this daye sall &thorn;ou be with me in paradyse&raquo; &mdash; ffor paradyse es
caulde &thorn;e syghte of gode; ffor as sune after &thorn;e passione of oure lorde bothe
&thorn;e thefe &amp; all &thorn;e holy ffadirs &thorn;at ware in lymbo saw &thorn;e Ioye of gode as he es.
Be-holde now here &thorn;e mekill mercy &amp; &thorn;e gudenes of oure lorde &thorn;at wolde
descende downe to hell, and &thorn;e vnmesurabill charite &amp; mekenes &thorn;at he schewede
in his dyenge.  He myghte hafe sent one of his angells to &thorn;eme [to] hafe vesette
his seruande&yogh; and takene theme owtt of hell and presente theme to hyme whe&thorn;ere
hyme had lykede: Bot his gret charite &amp; his mekenes, myghte noghte suffire hyme
bot &thorn;at he sulde algate dye, and &thorn;erfore he come in his aghene persone lorde of
all thynge&yogh;, and vesett theme not as seruande&yogh; bot as his frendes; and was &thorn;are
with theme to &thorn;e sondaye at morne.  Thane the holy ffadirs made mekill Ioye
of his comynge: thene where they in contenuele loueynge in ympnys and gostely
sanges.  When &thorn;ey felde his moste helefull comynge, they rane agayne hym
Ioyeand and sayande: &laquo;Blischyde be oure lorde gode of Israel, for he has vesette
vs &amp; boghte his pepill&raquo; ...  And &thorn;ofe-all &thorn;ese wordes be noghte pleynly contenede


<PB N="1: 213">

in &thorn;e gosepell, neuer-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;e gosepell beris witnesse &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu
dyd many thynges &thorn;at &thorn;e Euangeliste&yogh; wrote noghte ...
</P><P>&THORN;ou may also thynke &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu aperid firste to his blischide modir
oure lady aftire his resureccione: and in siche Meditacione&yogh;, aftire &thorn;e gret
compassione &thorn;at &thorn;ou had of his dede &amp; his bitter passyone, sall &thorn;i saule be fede
with swettnes of his glorious resureccione, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou sall be turnede in to lufe
of thy lorde Ihesu Cryste, &thorn;at lyues &amp; regnes with-owttene ende Amen.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>The rysyng vp of owre lorde Ihesu, and how he apperid firste to his modire, oure lady saynte Marie amen.</HEAD>

<P>When oure lorde Ihesu had dispoylled hell &amp; takene Adam &amp; Eue &amp; all o&thorn;er
holy ffadirs &amp; sett &thorn;em in paradyse &mdash; &thorn;at es a place of delite, where Ennoke
&amp; Hely dwellis: he toke leue at theme, &amp; said he wolde go &amp; take agayne his
body and rayse it agayne to lyue.  Then come he with gret haste to his graue,
one &thorn;e sonndaye herely at morne; and toke agayne his blissede body owt of &thorn;e
graue, &amp; wente forthe thurghe his aghene myght. / &THORN;at same houre, herly at morne,
Marie Maudeleyne &amp; hir two sisters asked leue at oure lady &amp; went with &thorn;eire
oynementes to &thorn;e sepulcre-warde.  Bot owre lady bod styll at home, and prayede
to &thorn;e ffadire of heuene, sayand: &laquo;Fadir of mercy &amp; pite, &yogh;e knowe wele &thorn;at my sone es dede and was schamfully hangede be-twyx thefes, &amp; I helpede to bery
hyme with my handes.  I knowe wele &thorn;at &yogh;e are of myghte &amp; powere to restore
hym agayne to me hole and sonde: and &thorn;erfore haue mercy of me: I beseke
&yogh;our hye mageste &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde gyffe me hyme agayne.  A, lorde, where es he?
why taries he thus longe fro me?  send hym to me I pray &yogh;owe, for my soule
may noghte ryste to I haue hym.  A, my dere swete sone, what es comene one
the?  whate dose thow?  why taryes &thorn;ou so longe?  I pray the, my dere sone,
duell noo langare fro me.  For &thorn;ou said thi-selfe &thorn;ou sulde ryse &thorn;e thyrd daye:
&amp; &thorn;is es &thorn;e thyrde daye, my dere sone.  Noghte &yogh;ysterday, bot be-fore
&yogh;isterday, was &thorn;at ill day, &thorn;at bitter day, &thorn;at wrechid day, the day of sorow &amp; of myrknesse, &thorn;e day of twynnyng &amp; of bitter dede.  &THORN;er-fore, my dere sone, &thorn;is
day es &thorn;e thred day.  There-fore, Ryse vp now, my Ioye and all my
comforthe, &amp; come agayne to me: ffor ouer all thyng desyre I to se &thorn;e.  I pray
&thorn;e &thorn;at thyne agayne-come glade me whame &thorn;i departynge hase mekyll
myscomforthed, &amp; solace me with thi blissede presence whame thyne absence hase
mekill hevyde.  Come agayne now, &thorn;ou my wele-belouede sone.  Come, my lorde
Ihesu.  Come, &thorn;ou onely my hope.  Come to me, my dere childe&raquo;.  And whylles
scho prayed thus with louely teres: sodeynly come oure lord Ihesu in clothes
whyte as any snawe, his fface schynyng as &thorn;e sone, all specyouse, all gloryouse
&amp; all full of Ioye, and said to his modire: &laquo;Haile, holy modire&raquo;.  And as sonne
scho turnede hir &amp; said: &laquo;Art &thorn;ou my dere sone Ihesu?&raquo;  &amp; with &thorn;at scho knelid downne &amp; wirchyped hym: and he lowly Enclyned and toke hir
vp, &amp; said: &laquo;My dere modire, &yogh;a, I am &yogh;our sone, &amp; I am resyne, &amp; I am with &yogh;ow&laquo;.  &THORN;en rose they vp to-gedire, &amp; scho halsede hym &amp; kyssede hyme, and tendirly and loueandly lened one hyme, and he tendirly &amp; mekly helde hir vpe.  Aftirwarde &thorn;ey stode to-gedire, and euer scho behelde one his fface, and


<PB N="1: 214">

&thorn;e wondis in his heuede &amp; in his fete, &amp; aftire one all his blyssede body, &amp; askede hym if all his payne &amp; his disesse were passede a-waye fro hym.  Thene
said he: &laquo;&YOGH;a, my dere modire, I haue ouer-comene sorow &amp; wo, and I sall no
more fele &thorn;er-of: bot I am, &amp; sall be, in Endlesse Ioye &amp; blysse&raquo;.  &THORN;en said
oure lady: &laquo;Now blyssede be thy ffadire, my dere sone, &thorn;at hase thus gefene
the to me; in heuene &amp; erthe prayssede and magnyfiede be his holy name, in
worlde of worldes with-owttyne Ende Amen&raquo;.  Then stode &thorn;ey to-gedire with
gret Ioye and gladnese of herte, holdande &thorn;eire speche all In Ioye &amp; in
delite of lufe; and oure lorde Ihesu tolde hys modire how he had delyueride his
pepyll owt of hell, &amp; all &thorn;e meracles &amp; &thorn;e wondirs &thorn;at he had done &thorn;ire thre
dayes.  Lo &thorn;is es now a Ioyfull gladsumnes &amp; a merye paske!
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; How Maudeleyne &amp; hir systers com to &thorn;e sepulcre.</HEAD>

<P>Marie Maudeleyne &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;er two Maries come arely at morne to &thorn;e sepulcre
with &thorn;eire Oynementes, as I said be-fore.  With-owtyn&macr; &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;e Cete
they vmbethoghte &thorn;em of &thorn;e paynes &amp; affliccyounes &amp; passiones of &thorn;eire
maystere, and In euery place &thorn;at &thorn;ey knewe &thorn;at he had sufferde any specyall payne
&thorn;ey knelyde doune kyssyng &thorn;e grownde, sorowynge &amp; sygheynge to-gedire:
&laquo;Here mette we with hyme berynge his crosse whene his modire swounede for
sorowe.  And here turnede he hym agayne to &thorn;e womene of Ierusalem.  And
here laid he downe his crosse for werynes, and oppone &thorn;is stone lenede he
hym a lyttill.  And here was it &thorn;at &thorn;ey schot hym forthe so felly &amp; so cruelly
and spytte in his face, and garte hym hye so fast.  Here dispoyllede &thorn;ey hyme
&amp; nakynd hyme, and here did they hym one &thorn;e crosse&raquo;, and &thorn;ene with gret
wepyng and sorowynge &thorn;ey ffell to &thorn;e grownde &amp; wyrschiped &thorn;e crosse &amp; kyssed it &mdash; ffor it was all rede of &thorn;e precyouse blode of oure lorde Ihesu.
Aftir &thorn;at, &thorn;ey rose vp &amp; wente to &thorn;e sepulcre, and said to &thorn;eme-selfe: &laquo;Who sall remow vs &thorn;is stone fro &thorn;e dore of &thorn;e monement?&raquo;  And whene &thorn;ey come &thorn;ey fonde &thorn;e stone leyd one syde, and ane angell sittande &thorn;ere-one, &thorn;at said to theme: &laquo;Dred &yogh;ow nott, he saide; &yogh;e seke Ihesu of Na&yogh;areth &thorn;at was crucyfyede: he es resyne, he es noghte here&raquo;.  And &thorn;ey seande &thorn;ey were dissayuede of &thorn;eire purpos, for they wende to hafe found &thorn;e body of Ihesu, &thorn;ey toke no
tennt to &thorn;e angell worde, bot come agayne all affrayed to &thorn;e discyples &amp; tolde
&thorn;eme &thorn;at &thorn;eire lordes body was takyne awaye.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Rynnyng to &thorn;e graue &amp;c.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;ene Petir &amp; Iohn&macr; ran to &thorn;e graue, as sayne Luke sais.  Be-hold &thorn;em wele
how &thorn;ey rane; and Maudeleyne &amp; hir felawes rane with theme.  All rane &thorn;ey to
seke Ihesu &thorn;eire lorde, &thorn;eire herte &amp; &thorn;eire saule.  &THORN;ey rane ffull trewly, full
lastandly, full besyly.  Whene &thorn;ey come at &thorn;e graue, they fonde noghte bot
the sudarye &amp; &thorn;e clothes &thorn;at he was wound Ine.  Haue nowe pete &amp; compassione
of &thorn;eme, for &thorn;ey were in full gret tribulacione &amp; thoght for &thorn;eire lorde.  &THORN;ey
soghte hym, bot &thorn;ey fonde hyme noghte, ne &thorn;ey wiste neuer what they myghte
doo; thare-fore Petir &amp; Iohn&macr; went home sore wepynge agayne for sorowe.


<PB N="1: 215">

Bot &thorn;e thre Maries bode still at &thorn;e graue, &thorn;ey come &amp; loked In to &thorn;e graue:
&amp; &thorn;ey sawe two angells sittande in whytte clothes, &thorn;at said to &thorn;eme: &laquo;Where-to seke &yogh;e &thorn;e lyfand with &thorn;e dede?&raquo;  Bot they toke no kepe to &thorn;e angells wordes, nor to no visyone of &thorn;e angells, bot of &thorn;e lorde of angells.  &THORN;ene two Maries with-drewe &thorn;eme a littill, &amp; satt downe sore wepynge.  Bot Marie Maudeleyne wist not what scho myghte doo, ffore with-owttyne hire mayster myght scho not lyfe, and &thorn;are couthe scho nott fynd hym, ne scho wist neuer whare to seke
hyme; and &thorn;are-fore stode scho styll at &thorn;e graue wepyng, eft &amp; efte lokyng
in to &thorn;e graue, for euer wende scho haue sene hym &thorn;are whare sche beryed
hyme.  &amp; efte scho saw [&thorn;e] angells sytt one &thorn;e graue, &amp; saide: &laquo;Womane, why wepis &thorn;oue?  what sekes &thorn;ou?&raquo;  And scho ansuerde &amp; saide: &laquo;ffor they haue takene my lorde awaye, &amp; I wate neuer where &thorn;ey haue done hyme&raquo;.  Se now here a wondirfull wirkynge of luf: a littill be-fore herd sche &thorn;e angell say &thorn;at
he was resyne, &amp; efte of o&thorn;er two &thorn;at he lyfed, and &yogh;itt had scho no mynde of
all &thorn;is, bot said: &laquo;I wote neuer whare they haue done hym&raquo;.  All &thorn;is reklessnes of all owtward thynges &amp; also of &thorn;e angell wordes was cause[d] of &thorn;e gret loue &amp; desyre &thorn;at scho had to hir mayster &amp; hir lord Ihesu; ffor scho couthe noghte
ells speke, here ne thynke, bot of oure lorde Ihesu.  Whene scho had thus a
long tym wepyd, &amp; toke no kepe to &thorn;e angells: hir loue &amp; hir mayster Ihesu
myght no lengare with-holde hym fro hire.  Than oure lorde Ihesu said to his
modire &thorn;at he wolde go to comforthe hir.  And owre lady was wele payed
&thorn;er-of &amp; said: &laquo;Go, my blyssyde sone, one my blyssyng, &amp; comforthe hir: ffor
mekill es &thorn;e luffe &thorn;at scho luffes the, and mekill was &thorn;e sorowe &thorn;at scho had
for the &amp; for thy dede.  I pray the, my dere sone, &thorn;at &thorn;ou com sone agayne
to me&raquo;.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; How oure lord Ihesu appered to Maudeleyne.</HEAD>

<P>Owre lorde Ihesu come &thorn;ene to &thorn;e gardyne where his graue was, and mett
&thorn;are with Marie Mawdeleyne, &amp; said to hir: &laquo;Womane, why wepes &thorn;oue?&raquo;
And &yogh;itt scho knewe hym nott, bot wend he had bene a gardenere, &amp; as womane
full of thoghte scho answerde hym and said: &laquo;Sir, if &thorn;ou haue takyne hym awaye,
tell me where &thorn;ou has hyde hyme and I sall take hym&raquo;.  Be-holde here how
wepandly, how mekly, &amp; how deuotly scho prayed hym to tell hir to hyme &thorn;at
scho soghte: scho hoped euer to here some new tythynge&yogh;, of hyme &thorn;at was hir
lufe.  Than oure lorde calde hir by hir name hamly and said: &laquo;Mari&raquo;.  Than
wakynd scho at his voyce as owte of a ded slepe, knowynge his swet voyce, and
with gret Ioye scho saide: Rabony, &thorn;at es to say Mayster; &laquo;Lorde, scho said,
&yogh;e are he &thorn;at I seke; why haue &yogh;e &thorn;us long layned &yogh;our-selfe fro me?&raquo;  And than scho rane &amp; ffell downe at his fete &amp; wold hafe kyssed &thorn;eme.  Bot oure
lorde Ihesu rayssede hir vp to heuenly lufe &amp; gostely, &thorn;at scho sulde no more
seke hym here in erthe ffleschely [be fleschely] affeccyone, onely behauldand
his manhede as pure mane only, bot &thorn;at scho sulde lufe hym gostely be gostely
affeccione, be-haldyng hyme as god in mane; and &thorn;are-fore said he to hire:
&laquo;Mari, touche me nott, for &yogh;it haue [I] nott styed vp to my ffadir&raquo;, as who say:
in &thorn;is forme of man &thorn;at &thorn;ou sees with thi bodily eghe, am I nott euene to my


<PB N="1: 216">

fadir, bot lesse &thorn;an he, &amp; &thorn;erfore touche me nott soo: &laquo;Bot go saye to my
Brethire &thorn;at I stye to my ffadir and &yogh;our ffadir, my gode &amp; &yogh;our gode.  Said I
noghte to &thorn;e before &thorn;at I suld ryse vp &thorn;e threde day?  why sekes &thorn;ou me in my
graue?&raquo;  Than answred scho: &laquo;Sothely, dere mayster, I haue [had] so mekill sorow
&amp; murnynge ffor &yogh;oure bitter passione and dede, &thorn;at I had forgetyne all thyng bot
onely &yogh;oure body &thorn;at was ded, and &thorn;e place &thorn;at I berid &yogh;ow Ine; and &thorn;erfore
ordeyned I &thorn;is Oynement this mornenyng to hafe anoynte &yogh;oure body with.
Blyssed be &yogh;oure hye worthynes &thorn;at vochede-saffe to ryse agayne and come to
vs!&raquo;  Than stode to-gedire Ihesu &amp; his dere luffe with gret Ioye &amp; gladnes:
Scho be-helde hym full verreyly and besyly, and askede hym of many thynges,
and he answerd gladly to all hir askynges.  Thare was &thorn;ene a Ioyefull standynge:
ffore if-all oure lorde bad hyr scho sulde nott touche hyme, I may nott trowe
bot &thorn;at scho aftyrwarde towched hyme full tendirly or scho &yogh;ede, bothe kyssand
his hende &amp; his fete ...  Whene &thorn;ey had &thorn;us standene spekyng to-gedire, oure lorde
said hym burde goo &amp; comforthe mo of his brethire &amp; frendes.  Than changede
all hir chere, for scho wolde neuer haf gone fro hyme; than said scho to hym:
&laquo;Lorde, me thynke &yogh;oure lyfynge may nott be here amonge vs as it has bene.
Bot I pray &yogh;owe, dere lorde, &thorn;at &yogh;e fore-gett me not.  Haue mynde of all
kyndnes &amp; gudnesse &thorn;at &yogh;e haue done to me, &thorn;at [&thorn;ei] neuer be loste in me, and
thynke [of] &thorn;e grete ho[m]lynesse &amp; luf &thorn;at &yogh;e haue had to me&raquo;.  And &thorn;en he bad hir &thorn;at scho suld nott drede; &laquo;bot be faythefull and stabill, ffor I sall euer-more be with the&raquo;.  Thane scho toke his blyssyng and he went forthe; &amp; scho come to hir felawes &amp; tolde theme all &thorn;at scho had herde &amp; sene.  Thane were &thorn;ey glade of his vp-rysesyng: bot be-cause &thorn;ey hade nott sene hym, they went with
hir murnynge.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>How owre lorde apperide to [&thorn;e] thre Maries.</HEAD>

<P>Als theis thre Maries &yogh;ede to-gedir be &thorn;e waye, owre lorde Ihesu apperide
to theme and said: &laquo;Hayle &yogh;e&raquo;.  &THORN;ene made &thorn;ey mekill Ioye, and fell downe &amp; hillede his fete.  Thane be-helde they hyme Ententyfely, and askede of hym
dyuerse thynges, and reseiued of hyme myghte and grace, and &thorn;ey mad also
gret Ioye &amp; myrthe.  &THORN;ene bade oure lorde Ihesu &thorn;at &thorn;ey sulde go to his
brethire &amp; byde them goo to Galile, for there suld &thorn;ey see hyme as he tolde &thorn;eme
be-fore.  Be-holde here &thorn;at &thorn;e mayster of meknes calde his disciples brethire;
&thorn;is vertue of Mekenesse dwelles euer-more with hyme.  Bot if &thorn;ou will haue
vndirstandynge and gostely comforthe of &thorn;is &thorn;at I haue saide, the nedis to be
present in euery stede and euery dede in thy saule as if &thorn;ou where there
sothe-fastely in body; and one &thorn;e same manere in that &thorn;at I sall say.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; How oure lorde appered to Iosephe of Aromathye.</HEAD>

<P>Whene owre lorde Ihesu was gonne fro &thorn;e thre Maries before-saide, he
apperid to Ioseph of Aromathy &thorn;at berid hyme.  For &thorn;e Iewes had takene hyme
for oure lorde sake, &amp; sperde hyme in a house and sellede &thorn;e dores with grete
besynes &thorn;at he suld noghte passe awaye: ffor aftire &thorn;eire sabot-day &thorn;ey had
ordeyned to sle hyme.  Thare-ffore oure lorde Ihesu apperid to hym &amp; sett hym


<PB N="1: 217">

in his awene house in Aromathie, and braste selys and lokkes. / &amp; &thorn;ene he apperide
to Iames the les, &thorn;at [had] made a vowe &thorn;at he sulde neuer ete mete to he sawe
owre lorde resyne.  Thane said oure lorde Ihesu till hym, and till o&thorn;er, &thorn;at &thorn;ey
suld sett a borde: and he toke brede and blyssed it, and gafe &thorn;eme, sayande:
&laquo;Etes now, my dere brethire, and make &yogh;e mery: ffor &thorn;e sone of Marie es
resyne ffro ded&raquo;.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; How oure lorde apperid to Symone Petire.</HEAD>

<P>Whene Marye Maudeleyne and hir ffelawes were comene home and had tolde
&thorn;e disciples &thorn;at oure lorde was resyne and howe he had spokene with theme:
Petir was hevy &thorn;at he hade noghte sene his lorde Ihesu: and for mekylnes of
lufe he myghte no langare abyde, bot &yogh;ede forthe allone to &thorn;e sepulcre-warde&mdash;
ffor he wiste neuer ells where to fynde hyme.  And as he wente, owre lorde
appered to hyme in &thorn;e waye, saynge: &laquo;Pese be to &thorn;e, Symone&raquo;.  Thane Petir
bett hym-selfe one &thorn;e breste and fell downe to &thorn;e grownde with bitter teres and
said: &laquo;Lorde, I knowelage my trespas, ffor I forsoke &yogh;owe and ofte-tymes denyed
&yogh;ow&raquo;; and Efte fell downe and kissede oure lordes fete.  Bot oure lorde
mercyfully toke hym vp and bad hym drede hym nott, &laquo;for all &thorn;i synne es forgyfene
&thorn;e; I knewe wele, as I tolde &thorn;e be-fore.  And &thorn;erfore go nowe and stabill &thorn;i
felawes and thi bre&thorn;ire, and triste sekerly &thorn;at I hafe ouercomene dede&raquo;.  And
Petir behelde hym fulbesyly, and all his lymms and his wondes, and fell downe
to &thorn;e grownde &amp; wepid full tendirly.  Bot owre lorde toke hym vp &amp; comforthed hyme, and gafe hym hys blyssynge and partede fro hyme.  And Petir
come agayne to oure lady and to &thorn;e discyples, and tolde theme all to-gedire. /
Thow sall vndirstande &thorn;at &thorn;e apparecione made to owre lady es noghte wretyne
in &thorn;e gospell, &amp; &thorn;erfore I sett it be-fore all o&thorn;er, &amp; so semys it &thorn;at holy kyrke holdes it, as it es more [fully] schewede in the legent of his resureccione.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"> <HEAD>How owre [lord] Ihesu appered to two disciples goand to &thorn;e castell of Emaus.</HEAD>

<P>Alls two disciples of Ihesu went to &thorn;e castell of Emaus all dismayed ffor &thorn;eire
mayster and hevy for chawnces &thorn;at were fallene: owre lorde apperide to &thorn;eme
in liknes of a pylgryme, &amp; &yogh;ede with theme spekyng wordes of hele, as &thorn;ou redis
more fully in &thorn;e gospell.  At &thorn;e laste &thorn;ey garte hym come In with &thorn;eme: and
as [&thorn;ey] satt at &thorn;e supere, &thorn;ey knewe hym in brekyng of brede; &amp; on-one he
vanyste awaye fro &thorn;em ... &amp; &thorn;en &thorn;ey rose vp &amp; &yogh;ede to Ierusalem &amp; tolde to o&thorn;er disciples what had be-fallene &thorn;eme in the waye and [how] they knewe hyme
in brekyng of brede. / As &thorn;ey stode to-gedire spekynge of owre lorde: he come
and stode in-myddes &thorn;eme, &amp; said: &laquo;Pese be with &yogh;ow&raquo;.  &THORN;ene all his disciples fell downe to &thorn;e grownde, knowlageynge theyre trespas &thorn;at &thorn;ey had so vnkyndly forsakyne hym, &amp; welcomede hym with gret reuerence and gladnes.  Then said
oure lorde to &thorn;eme: &laquo;Ryse &yogh;e vp, my dere brethire, for all &yogh;oure synnes are
forgeffene &yogh;ow&raquo;.  He stode homly among &thorn;eme, schewyng &thorn;e wondes of his
handes &amp; fete &amp; side; &thorn;ene he Opynde &thorn;eire gostely wittys &thorn;at &thorn;ay myghte
vndirstande holy writt &amp; knowe &thorn;e prevetes of his passione &amp; his resurreccione.
Than askede he &thorn;eme if they had any mete, &amp; &thorn;ey broghte forthe be-fore hym


<PB N="1: 218">

fische &amp; a hony-cambe; and he blew one &thorn;eme and gafe &thorn;eme &thorn;e holy goste.
Be-holde how all &thorn;ese thynges were of gostely Ioye &amp; gladnes.  Than were
&thorn;e disciples glad &amp; fayne &thorn;at &thorn;ey hade sene owre lorde; &thorn;en mad &thorn;ey Ioye &amp; myrthe be-fore hym, &thorn;at be-fore were hevy &amp; sary.  [With how] glade chere
trowes &thorn;ou &thorn;ey leyde be-fore hyme mete, how gudly &amp; how faythefully &thorn;ey
serued hyme, how Ioyefull &amp; Iocund &thorn;ey stode be-fore hyme!  Be-holde also
oure lady &thorn;ere, fore all &thorn;e disciples were gadirde to hire for socoure &amp; comforthe.
Be-holde hire nowe with glade semlande seynge all &thorn;is, &amp; homly sittand by
hir dere sone &amp; servynge hyme full loueandly.  Owre lord Ihesu toke gladely
servese of hire handes, &amp; wirchipped hyre reuerently be-for his disciples.  I pray
&thorn;e forgett nott Mari Mawdeleyne, &thorn;at wele-beluffed discypulas of Ihesu, &amp; apostolas
of all &thorn;e appostles, how scho one hir olde manere satt at hir lordes fete deuoutly
heryng his wordes, &amp; what &thorn;at scho myght do scho dide with gret gladnes [&] with
all &thorn;e affeccione of hir herte.  A, how blyssefull was &thorn;ene &thorn;at house, in the
whylke satt bothe god &amp; man, with his modire qwhene of heuene, &amp; all his o&thorn;er dere derlynges!  Gret Ioye was &thorn;ene to be with &thorn;eme.  Thynke &thorn;e nott here a
gret comforthe?  Sothely I trow &yogh;is, if &thorn;ou hafe any lufe or deuocyone. / Bot
oure lorde duelte nott with theme bot a while, for it was late whene he come
to &thorn;eme.  Bot I trow &thorn;ey prayede hyme of his gret meknesse &thorn;at he sulde not
so sone go fro &thorn;eme.  Hopes &thorn;ou nott &thorn;at Marie Maudeleyne helde hym still
by &thorn;e skyrtte full tristily [&] with a gret reuerent hardines, &thorn;at he sulde noghte so
sune go fro hire?  Owre lorde Ihesu stode amonges theme clede with clothes of
glory bryghtere thane &thorn;e sonne, whittere &thorn;an the snawe.  At &thorn;e laste oure lorde
Ihesu toke leue at his modire &amp; scho also of hyme, and he blischede theme all,
and went forthe; and &thorn;ey all fell don one knes and prayede hym with gret
reuerence &amp; desyre of his sune agayne-comynge.  And so &thorn;ey duellede in gret
desyre aftire &thorn;eire mayster &amp; lorde agayne-comynge, whome &thorn;ey were wonnte
so mekill be-fore to haue at theire liste. / Thow may se now how oft &thorn;ou hase
had &thorn;is daye pasche &mdash; ffor ilke of &thorn;eis apperynges es calde a pasche.  Bot
perauenture &thorn;ou hase herde &thorn;eme, bot &thorn;ou felde no gladnes, nor gostely
comforthe of Cristes passione.  I trow sothefastly &thorn;at if &thorn;ou couthe pete &amp; compassione of his passione, and had &thorn;i herte and &thorn;i mynd gedirde to-gedire &amp; nott
distracte abowte in &thorn;e werlde abowte o&thorn;er thynges &amp; o&thorn;er fantassies, &thorn;at &thorn;ou
sulde fele in euerylkone of &thorn;es apperynges a newe feste gostely and a new
pasche.  And euery sononday suldes &thorn;ou hafe so, If &thorn;ou wolde one ffryday
before with hole mynde &amp; feruent deuocyone hafe sorowe and pete of Cristes
passione; ffor &thorn;e appostell sais: &laquo;if we be felawes of Cristes passione&raquo;, haueuyng pete &amp; compassione of his pyne and disese &thorn;at he sufferde here for vs, &laquo;than one &thorn;e same manere sall we be felawes of gostely comforthe&raquo; and Endles Ioye the wilke he has ordeyned to all &thorn;o &thorn;at here hertly luffes hym with all &thorn;eire myghte. &THORN;e whilke Ioye &amp; comforthe he graunt vs &thorn;at with his precious blode boghte
vs, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ihesus Christus Amen.  Amen.  Amen.</FOREIGN><FOREIGN>Pur Charite.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV3>
<TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit Bonauenture de mysteriis Passionis Ihesu Christi.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<PB N="1: 219"><HEAD>The Mirror of St. Edmund<NOTE>A translation of the Latin text known variously as the <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Speculum religiosorum, Speculum ecclesie</FOREIGN> or <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Speculum sancti Edmundi</FOREIGN>.  Horstman has inserted roman numerals in brackets to indicate the chapter divisions in the Latin original.</NOTE></HEAD><DIV3
N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="folio"><OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Incipit Speculum sancti Edmundi Cantuar[iensis] Archipiscopi in Anglicis.</FOREIGN>  Here begynnys The Myrrour of seynt Edmonde &thorn;e Ersebechope of Canterberye.</OPENER>

<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P>[I.] <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Videte vocacionem vestram.</FOREIGN>  This wordes sayse saynte Paule in his pistyll, and thay are thus mekill to saye one ynglysche: &laquo;Seese &yogh;owre callynge&raquo;.  This
worde falles till vs folke of religioune: and &thorn;at sais he till excite vs till
perfeccyone.  And ther-fore, what houre &thorn;at I thynke of my-selfe one nyghte or on
day, on a syde hafe I gret Ioye, and on ano&thorn;er syde gret sorowe.  Ioy for &thorn;e
haly religione, sorowe and confusyone for my febill conuersasione.  And &thorn;at es
na wondire, for I hafe gret enchesone.  Als &thorn;e wyese man saise in his sermone;
he sais, &laquo;to com to religione es souerayne perfeccyone, and there-In noghte perfitly
to lyffe es souerayne dampnacyone&raquo;.  And thar-for &thorn;are es na turne of &thorn;e way
bot ane to come in congregacyone, &thorn;at es, to drawe to perfeccione, [&] als &thorn;ou
will &thorn;i saluacyone, to leue all &thorn;at es in this worlde and all &thorn;at &thorn;er-to langys, and
sett thi myghte to lyffe perfitly.  [II.] To lyffe perfitly, as sayne Bernarde vs kennys,
&thorn;at es to lyffe honourabilly, mekely, &amp; lufesomly.  Honourabilly als to god: &thorn;at
&thorn;ou sett thyne Entente to do hys will; &thorn;at es [to] say: in all thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ou sall
thynke in hert or say with mouthe or doo in dede with any of &thorn;i fyve wyttes
alls with seynge of eghe, herynge of Ere, smellynge of neese, suellynge of throtte,
towchynge of hande, gangand or standande, lygand or sittande, thynke at &thorn;e
begynnynge if &thorn;at it be goddes will or noghte.  And if it be goddis will, do it
at thy powere; and if it be noghte hys will, do it noghte for to suffre &thorn;e dede.
Bot now may &thorn;ou aske mee: &laquo;what es goddes wyll?&raquo;  I say &thorn;e his will es na no&thorn;er
thynge bot &thorn;i halynes; als &thorn;e appostill [sais] in his pystill: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Hec est voluntas dei: sanctificacio vestra,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;&thorn;at es goddes will &thorn;at &yogh;e be haly&raquo;.  [III.] Bot
now may &thorn;ou aske me: &laquo;What mase man haly?&raquo;  I say &thorn;e, twa thynges with-owttene ma, &thorn;at es, kwaweynge and lufe.  Knaweyng of sothefastnes, and lufe of gudnes. Bot to &thorn;e knaweynge of godde &thorn;at es sothefastnes, ne may &thorn;ou noghte come
bot be knawynge of thi-selfe; ne &yogh;it to &thorn;e luf of godde may &thorn;ou noghte come
bot thurghe &thorn;e lufe of thynne evyne-crystyne.  To &thorn;e knaweyng of &thorn;i-selfe may


<PB N="1: 220">

&thorn;ou come with besy vmbythynkynge; and to &thorn;e knaweynge of godde thurghe
pure contemplacioune.  To &thorn;e knaweynge of &thorn;i-selfe &thorn;ou may come one &thorn;is
manere: Thynke besely and ofte what &thorn;ou erte, what &thorn;ou was, and what &thorn;ou
sall be.  Fyrste als vn-to &thorn;i body.  &THORN;ou erte now vylere &thorn;ane any mukke.  &THORN;ou
was getyne of sa vile matire and sa gret fylthe &thorn;at it es schame for to nevynne,
and abhomynacyone for to thynke.  &THORN;ou sall be delyuerde to tades and to neddyrs
for to ete. / What &thorn;ou has bene and what thow erte, now sall &thorn;ou als to &thorn;i
saule, thynke; ffor what &thorn;ou sall be &thorn;ou may noghte wyete nowe.  Vmbethynke
&thorn;e nowe how &thorn;ou has done gret synn&macr;s and many, and how thow has lefte gret
gudnes and many.  Thynke how lange &thorn;ou hase lyffede and what thow has
rescheyuede, and how &thorn;ou has dyspende it.  For ilke an houre &thorn;at &thorn;ou has noghte
thoghte one godde, &thorn;ou has it tynte.  For &thorn;ou sall &yogh;elde resoune of ilke ane
ydill thoghte, of ilke ane ydill dede, of ilke ane ydill worde.  And righte as &thorn;ou
has noghte ane hare of thi heuede &thorn;at it ne sall be gloryfyede if swa be &thorn;ou
be safede, righte swa sall eschape nane houre &thorn;at it ne sall [be] accountede.
A Ihesu mercy!  If all &thorn;is worlde ware full of smalle powdire, wha sulde be
sa qwaynte &thorn;at he sulde or moghte Iugge ilke a [atom (or mot?)] by
&thorn;ame-selfe, and twyne ilke ane fra o&thorn;er?  Certis na [mane].  Bot &thorn;e saule es a
thowsande sythes gretter &thorn;an all &thorn;is worlde, if it ware a thowsande sythes
gretter &thorn;an it es; and it es [all] full of dyuerse thoghtes, lykynges and &yogh;ernynges:
wha moghte &thorn;an thus seke his herte &thorn;at he moght knawe all &thorn;at es &thorn;are-In or
thynke it?  See nowe, my dere hertly frende, howe &thorn;ou has gret nede of knawynge
of thi-selfe! / Sythene aftyrwarde take gude hede whate &thorn;ou erte nowe als vn-to
&thorn;i saule: howe &thorn;ow has littyll of gude in the, and littill of witte, and littill of
powere: ffor &thorn;ou &yogh;ernys ilke a daye &thorn;at at noghte avayles the, and euer-mare
ouer-lattly &thorn;at at may availe the.  Dere frende, &thorn;ou erte dessayfede sa ofte
with vayne Ioye, nowe trauelde with drede, nowe erte &thorn;ou lyftede one lofte with
false trayste.  See now on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde &thorn;ou erte [sa] chaungeabill, &thorn;at at &thorn;ou will
doo to-day &thorn;ou will noghte to-morne; and ofte-sythes &thorn;ou erte anoyede eftire
many thynges, and turment if &thorn;ou hafe thaym noghte, and sythen when &thorn;ou has
&thorn;ame at &thorn;i will &thorn;an erte &thorn;ou of thaa thynges annoyede.  Thynke &yogh;itt one &thorn;e
to&thorn;er syde how &thorn;ou erte lyghte to fande, frele to agayne-stande, and redy to
assente. / Of all &thorn;ese wrechidnes now has &thorn;e delyuerede Ihesu &thorn;i spouse, and
delyuers &thorn;e ylke day mare and mare.  For whene &thorn;ou was noghte, he mad &thorn;e, in
saule aftire his awene lyknesse and his ymage, and &thorn;i body made of foule stynkande
skyume of &thorn;e erthe whare-of es abhomynacyone to thynke; he mad &thorn;e in witte
and in membirs sa nobill and sa faire &thorn;at nane cane deuyse.  Thynke now besyly
&yogh;e &thorn;at has fleschely frendis and kynredyne, why &yogh;e luffe &thorn;ame sa derely and sa
tendirly.  If &thorn;ou say &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes &thorn;i fadire or &thorn;i modire for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ou erte
of &thorn;aire blude and flesche getyne: Sa are &thorn;e wormes &thorn;at comes of &thorn;ame day
be day.  On a no&thorn;er syde &thorn;ou has no&thorn;er of &thorn;ame body ne saule, bot &thorn;ou &thorn;an
has of god thurghe thayme.  For whate sulde &thorn;ou hafe bene if &thorn;ou had duellyde
swilke as &thorn;ou was of thayme when &thorn;ou [was] genderide in fylthe and in syne?  One
&thorn;e to&thorn;er syd, if &thorn;ou lufe brethire or systers or o&thorn;er kynredyne, for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ay
are of &thorn;e same flesche of fadir or of modire and of &thorn;aire blude: by &thorn;e same skyll


<PB N="1: 221">

solde &thorn;ou lufe a pece of &thorn;aire flesche if it [ware] schorne a-waye, and &thorn;at solde
be errour gret with-owttene mesure.  &YOGH;yfe &thorn;ou say &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes &thorn;ame for-thi
&thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe fleschely fegure in lyknes of mane, and for-thy &thorn;at &thorn;ay haue saule
ryghte als &thorn;ou has: &thorn;an es &thorn;i bro&thorn;er fleschely na nerre &thorn;an ano&thorn;er, bot in als
mekill als &thorn;ou and he hase bathe [of] a fadire and a modire fleschely the begynnynge
of &thorn;i flesche, &thorn;at es, a lyttill filth stynkande and full to see.  Thare-fore &thorn;ou sall
lufe hym of whaym all &thorn;i fairenes commes; and &thorn;ou sall lufe gastely ilk a mane,
and flee fra now forthwarde to lufe fleschly.  [IV.] And swa sall &thorn;ou doo certaynly
if &thorn;ou conabilly thynke of gudes &thorn;at he has done gudly for &thorn;e, and mare sall
doo if &thorn;ou lufe hym Enterely.  For als I saide at &thorn;e begynnynge, when &thorn;ou was
noghte he made &thorn;e of noghte;&mdash;and whene &thorn;ou was tynte he fande &thorn;e, and whene
&thorn;ou was peryschede he soghte &thorn;e, and whene &thorn;ou was saulde with syne &thorn;an he
boghte &thorn;e, and whene &thorn;ou was dampnede &thorn;an he sauede &thorn;e.  And whene &thorn;ou
was borne in syne he bapty&yogh;ede &thorn;e; and sythene aftirwarde whene &thorn;ou synnede
sa foully and sa ofte, &thorn;an he sufferde &thorn;e so frely and habade thynne
amendemente sa lange, and sythene rescheyuede &thorn;e sa swetly, and &thorn;e has sett in sa
swete a falachipe.  And ilke a day when &thorn;ou mysdose &thorn;an he reprofes &thorn;e, and
whene &thorn;ou repentis &thorn;e &thorn;an he forgyffes the, and when &thorn;ou erris &thorn;an he amendis
&thorn;e, and when &thorn;ou dredis &thorn;e &thorn;an he leris &thorn;e, and whene &thorn;ou hungers &thorn;an he
fedis &thorn;e, and when &thorn;ou erte calde &thorn;ane he warmes &thorn;e, and whene &thorn;ou has hete
&thorn;an he kelis &thorn;e, and when &thorn;ou slepis &thorn;an he saues &thorn;e, and whene &thorn;ou ryse&yogh;
vpe &thorn;an he vphaldes &thorn;e, and euer-mare when &thorn;ou erte at male-eese &thorn;an he
comforthes &thorn;e.  [V.] Thyre gudnes and many o&thorn;er hase done vn-to &thorn;e thi swete spouse
Ihesu Criste.  And &thorn;e swettnes of his herte sall &thorn;ou thynke euer-mare and euer
speke &thorn;are-of, and euer-mare lofe hym, and euer thanke hym, and &thorn;at bath
nyghte &amp; day, if &thorn;ou oghte kane of lufe.  And &thorn;are-for, whene &thorn;ou ryses of
&thorn;i bedde at morne, or at mydnyghte, thynke als-tite how many thowsand mene &amp; womene ere perischede in body or in saule &thorn;at nyghte.  Some in fyre, some in
o&thorn;er manere, als in water or one lande.  Some robbide, woundide, slayne, dede
sodanly with-owttyne sacramentis and fallyne in-till dampnacione ay-lastande.
Thynk alswa how many thowsande &thorn;at nyghte are [fallyn] in perill of saule, &thorn;at
es to say in dedly syne, als in glotony, lechery, Couetyse, in manes-slaynge and in
many o&thorn;er folyes.  And of all &thorn;ise illes the has delyuered thy swete lorde Ihesu,
with-owttene &thorn;i deserte.  What seruyce hase &thorn;ou done wharefore he hase
&thorn;us-gate keped &thorn;e, and many o&thorn;er loste and forsakene?  For sothe if &thorn;ou take gud
kepe how gret gude he has done &thorn;e on ilk a syde, &thorn;ou sall fynd hym ocupiede
aboute &thorn;i profet als he did nane o&thorn;er thynge bot anely ware Entendande to &thorn;e
and to &thorn;i hele, als if he had forgetyne all &thorn;is worlde for to be anely intendande
vn-to &thorn;e.  &para; And when &thorn;ou hase &thorn;is thoghte, lyfte vpe thy handis and thanke
thi lorde of &thorn;is and of all o&thorn;er gudes, and say one &thorn;is manere: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Gracias tibi ago domine Ihesu Criste, qui me indignum famulum tuum N. in hac nocte vel die
custodisti, protexisti, visitasti, sanum saluum &amp; incolumem ad hanc horam pervenire
fecisti; et pro aliis vniuersis beneficiis tuis que michi tua sola pietate contulisti, qui
viuis &amp; regnas deus &amp;c.</FOREIGN>  This Orysone es &thorn;us to say one ynglysche: My lorde Ihesu Criste, grace I &yogh;elde and thanke &thorn;e &thorn;at me thyne vnworthy seruande &thorn;ou hase


<PB N="1: 222">

kepid, couerde and vesete in &thorn;is nyghte (or in &thorn;is day), hale, safe, and wemles
vn-to &thorn;is tyme &thorn;ou hase made to come, and for all o&thorn;er gudes and benfetis &thorn;at
&thorn;ou hase geffyne me anely thurghe &thorn;i gudnes and &thorn;i pete, &thorn;ou &thorn;at lyffes and
regnes endles, Amen&raquo;.  Dere frende, in &thorn;is same manere sall &thorn;ou say when &thorn;ou
ryse&yogh; at morne, and when &thorn;ou lygges downe at evyne. / And whene &thorn;ou has done
swa, &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou besyly thynke how &thorn;ou hase spende &thorn;at day (or &thorn;at nyghte),
and pray god of mercy of &thorn;e ill &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase done, and of &thorn;e gude &thorn;at &thorn;ou
hase lefte vn-till &thorn;at tyme.  And dere frende, do na thynge in &thorn;is lyfe till &thorn;ou
commend &thorn;i-selfe and thi frendis qwykke and dede in the handis of thi swete
lorde Ihesu Criste, and say one &thorn;is manere:
</P><LB><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In manus tuas, domine, &amp; sanctorum angelorum tuorum, commendo in hac nocte
(vel die) animam meam et corpus meum, et patrem et matrem, fratres et sorores,
amicos, familiares, propinquos, parentes, benefactores meos, et omnem populum
catholicum.  Custodi nos, domine, in hac nocte (vel die), per merita &amp; intercessionem
beate Marie et omnium sanctorum, a viciis, a concupis[c]enciis, a peccatis et
temptacionibus diaboli, a subitania et inprovisa morte, et a penis inferni.  Illumina cor
meum de Spiritu sancto &amp; de tua sancta gracia: et fac me semper tuis obedire
mandatis, &amp; a te nunquam separari permittas; qui viuis &amp; regnas deus &amp;c.</FOREIGN>
And &thorn;is orysone es &thorn;us mekill to saye: &laquo;Lorde Ihesu Criste, in &thorn;i handis and
in &thorn;e handis of thyne haly angells I gyffe in &thorn;is nyghte (or in &thorn;is day) my
saule and my body, my ffadir and my modire, my brothire and my systirs, frendis
and seruandes, neghtburs and kynredyne, my gude-doers, and all folke righte
trowande.  Kepe vs, lorde, in &thorn;is nyghte (or &thorn;is day), thurgh &thorn;e gud dedis and &thorn;e
prayere of &thorn;e blyssed maydene Marie and all thi halous, fra vices and fra wykked
&yogh;ernynge&yogh;, fra synns and fra fandynges of &thorn;e deuell, fra sodayne and [vn]-avysede
dede, and fra &thorn;e paynes of helle.  Lyght my herte of the haly gaste, and of thi
haly grace.  Lorde, &thorn;ou make me to be bouxsome euer-mare to &thorn;i byddynges,
and suffire me neuer-mare to twyne fra the, endles Ihesu, lorde in trynite.  Amen&raquo;. /
My dere frende, if &thorn;ou hafe &thorn;is manere, &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou hafe verray knaweynge of
thi-selfe, ffor thus sayse haly writte: &laquo;If &thorn;ou traiste one thy-selfe, to &thorn;i-selfe &thorn;ou sall be takyne, and &yogh;if &thorn;ou trayste one gode and noghte one &thorn;i-selfe, to god
&thorn;ou sall be gyffene&raquo;.  And this maner of consederasyone es callede medytacyone,
[and] by &thorn;is maner of knawynge of &thorn;i-selfe &amp; by &thorn;is maner of medytacyone sall
&thorn;ou come to &thorn;e knaweynge of gode by haly contemplacyone.  [VI.] Wiet &thorn;ou &thorn;at
&thorn;are es thre manere of contemplacyone: The fyrste es in creaturs.  The to&thorn;er
es in haly scripture.  The thirde es in gode hyme-selfe in his nature.  Thow
sall wyet &thorn;at contemplacyone es na no&thorn;er thynge bot thoghte of godde in gret
lykynge in saule, and to se his gudnes in his creaturs.  His gudnes in his creaturs
may &thorn;ou see one &thorn;is manere.  Thre thynges pryncypaly ere in gode, &thorn;at es to
say Myghte, Wysdome, and Gudnes.  Mighte es appropirde to godd &thorn;e ffadire,
Wysdome to god &thorn;e Son&macr;, Gudnes to god &thorn;e Haly gaste.  Thurgh goddes myghte
ere all thynges made, and thurgh his wysdome ere all thynges meruailously
ordaynede, and thurgh his gudnes ilke a day ere all thynges waxande.  His
powere may &thorn;ou see by &thorn;aire gretnes and by thaire makynge; his wysdome by
&thorn;aire fairenes [&] &thorn;aire ordaynynge, his gudnes may &thorn;ou see by &thorn;aire Encressynge.


<PB N="1: 223">

&THORN;aire gretnes may &thorn;ou see by &thorn;aire foure partynges, &thorn;at es to saye by &thorn;aire
heghte and by &thorn;aire depnes and by &thorn;aire largenes and by &thorn;aire lenghe.  His
wysdome may &thorn;ou see if &thorn;ou take kepe how he hase gyffene to ylke a creature
to be.  Somme, he hase gyffene to be anely with-owttene mare, als vn-to stanes.
Till o&thorn;er, to be &amp; to lyffe, als to grysse and trees.  Till o&thorn;er, to be, to lyffe,
to fele, als to bestes.  Till o&thorn;er, to be, to lyffe, to fele and with resone to
deme, als to mane and to angells.  For stanes erre, bot &thorn;ay ne hafe no&yogh;te
lyffe ne felys noghte ne demes noghte.  Trees are, [&] &thorn;ay lyffe, bot &thorn;ay fele
noghte ...  Mene are, &thorn;ay lyffe, &thorn;ay fele and &thorn;ay deme, and &thorn;ay erre with
stanes, &thorn;ay lyffe with trees, &thorn;ay fele with bestes, and demys with angells.
Here sall &thorn;ou thynke besyly &thorn;e worthynes of manes kynde, how it ouer-passes
ilke a creature.  And &thorn;are-fore saise saynt Austyne: &laquo;I wald noghte hafe &thorn;e stede
of ane angelle if I myghte hafe &thorn;e stede &thorn;at es purvayede to mane&raquo;.  Thynk also
&thorn;at mane es worthy gret schenschipe &thorn;at will noghte lyffe eftyre hys degre and
eftire his condicyone askis.  For all &thorn;e creaturs in &thorn;e worlde ere made anely for
mane.  &THORN;ase &thorn;at ere meke, ere made for thre skylles: ffor to helpe vs at trauayle,
als nate, oxene, kye, and horse; ffor to couer vs &amp; clethe vs, als lyne and wolle
and lethire; ffor to fede vs and vphalde vs, als bestes, Corne of &thorn;e erthe, ffysche
of &thorn;e see.  And &thorn;e noyande creaturs, als ill trees and venemous bestes; &thorn;e wylke
are made for thre thynges: ffor oure chastyyng, for oure amendement, and for
oure kennynge.  We ere chastied and puneschet when we ere hurte.  And &thorn;at
es gret mercy of godde &thorn;at he will chasty vs bodyly &thorn;at we be noghte punescht
lastandly.  We erre amendid when we thynke &thorn;at all &thorn;ese ere broghte vs for
our syne; ffor whene we see &thorn;at sa lyttill creaturs may noye vs, &thorn;ane we thynke
one oure wrechidnes, and &thorn;ane we ere mekyde.  We ere Eftirwarde kende, for-&thorn;i
&thorn;at we see in &thorn;ise creaturs &thorn;e wondirfull werkes of god oure makere; ffor mare
vs availes till oure ensampill and Edifycacione &thorn;e werkes of &thorn;e pyssmowre, &thorn;an
dose &thorn;e strenghe of &thorn;e lyone or of &thorn;e bere.  Als-swa, righte als I haue said of
bestes, reght swa vndirstande of trees; and when &thorn;ou hase donne on &thorn;is manere,
Raise vp thy herte vn-till godde, and thynke how it es grete myghte to make
all thynges of noghte and to gyffe &thorn;am to bee, and grete wysdome to ordayne
&thorn;am in sa gret fairenes, and gret bounte to multyply &thorn;ame ilk a day for oure
prowe.  A, mercy godde, how we are vnkynde!  We dispende all [&thorn;]is creaturs
and he &thorn;am makes!  We confound &thorn;ame and he &thorn;ame gouernes!  We distruy &thorn;ame
ilke a day and he &thorn;am multyplies!  And &thorn;are-fore say till hym in thi herte:
&laquo;Lorde, for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte &thorn;ay ere, and for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte fayre &thorn;ay are faire, and for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte gude &thorn;ay are gude.  With gud ryghte &thorn;ay loue &thorn;e, and Onoures &thorn;e, and gloryfyes &thorn;e, all thy creatures, O blyssed godd in trinyte!  With
gud ryghte &thorn;ay loue &thorn;e for &thorn;aire gudnes, with gud ryghte &thorn;ay anourene &thorn;e for
thaire fairenes, with gud righte &thorn;ay gloryfye &thorn;e for &thorn;aire profet, all &thorn;i creaturs,
blyssed trinyte!  of whame all thynges ere thurgh his powere made; thu[r]gh whaym
all thynges are thurgh hys wysdome gouernede; in whaym all thynges are thurgh
his bounte multipliede; till hym honour and louynge with-owttene [ende].  Amen&raquo;.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">IIa. pars.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>[VII.] &THORN;E to&thorn;er degre of contemplacyone es in Haly wryte.  Bot nowe may &thorn;ou
say to me: &laquo;I &thorn;at knawes na letters, how may I euer-mare com to contemplacyone


<PB N="1: 224">

of haly writte?&raquo;  Now, my dere frende, vndirstande me swetely and I sall say
perchance to &thorn;e: all &thorn;at es wretene [may be tald].  If &thorn;ou kane noghte vndirstand haly
writt, here gladly &thorn;e gud &thorn;at mene saise &thorn;e; and whene &thorn;ou heres haly wryte ow&thorn;er
in sermone or in preue collacyone, take kepe als-tyte if &thorn;ou here oghte &thorn;at may
availe &thorn;e till edyfycacyone, to hate syne and to lufe vertue, and to dowte payne
and to &yogh;erne Ioye, to dispyse &thorn;is worlde and to hye to blysse, and whate &thorn;ou
sall doo and whate &thorn;ou sall lefe, and all &thorn;at lyghtes &thorn;inne vndyrstandynge in
knawynge of sothefastnes, and all &thorn;at kyndills &thorn;i lykynge in brynnynge of charite;
ffor of &thorn;ise twa gudnes es all &thorn;at es wretyne in preue or in apperte.  Owte of
haly writte sall &thorn;ou drawe and cune witte whilke are &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes,
and &thorn;e seuene vertus, and &thorn;e ten comandementis, and &thorn;e tuelfe artycles of &thorn;e
trouthe, and &thorn;e seuene sacramentis of haly kyrke, and &thorn;e seuene gyftis of &thorn;e
haly gaste, and &thorn;e seuene werkes of mercy, and &thorn;e seuene vertu&yogh; of &thorn;e gospell,
and &thorn;e seuen prayers of &thorn;e <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">pater noster</FOREIGN>.</P><LB><P>[VIII.] &THORN;ir are &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes: Pryde, and Envy, Ire, Slouth, Couetyse,
Glotony, and Lechery.  Pryde es lufe of vnkyndly heghynge, and &thorn;ar-of comes
&thorn;ir seuen: Vnbouxomnes agayne god or agayne souerayngne, &thorn;at es to say, to
lefe &thorn;at &thorn;at es commandyd and to do &thorn;at that es defendyde.  The to&thorn;er branch
of pride es Surquytry, &thorn;at es, to vndirtake thyng ouer his powere, or wenys to
be mare wyse &thorn;an he es, or better &thorn;an he es; and auaunte&yogh; hym of gude &thorn;at he
hase of o&thorn;er, or of ill &thorn;at he hase of hym-selfe.  The thrid braunche of pride
es Ypocrisye, &thorn;at es whene he feynys hym to hafe gudnes &thorn;at he hase noghte,
and hydes &thorn;e wykkednes &thorn;at he hase.  The ferth braunch of pride es Despyte of
thyne euencristene, &thorn;at es when man lesses gudnes of o&thorn;er, for-thi &thorn;at hym-selfe
suld seme &thorn;e bettir.  The fyfte braunche [es Arrogance], &thorn;at es when man makes
lyknes betwyx his awene wykkednes and o&thorn;er mens wikkednes, &thorn;at his awene
may seme &thorn;e lesse.  The sexte braunche of pryde es Vnschamefulnes, &thorn;at es
when men hase noghte schame of ill ded aperte.  The seuen[d]e braunche of pryde
es Elacione, &thorn;at es when a man hase heghe herte, &thorn;at he will no&yogh;te suffire to
felawe ne mayster.  Dere frende, &thorn;ou sall wit &thorn;at thre thynges ere whare-of a man
Enprides hym, &thorn;at es to say: of &thorn;e gude&yogh; &thorn;at he hase of kynde, als fairenes or
strenghe or gude witte or nobille kynredyne.  The to&thorn;er thyng es &thorn;at man
hase of purchase, als cunnynge, grace, gud loos, or dygnyte or office.  The thirde
thynge es erthely thynge or erthely gude, als clethynge, houssynge, Rente&yogh;,
possessione, Men&yogh;e, horssyng, and honour of &thorn;is worlde.  Pride makes man to
be of gret herte and heghe, to despyse his euencristene, and to &yogh;erne heghenes
and maystry ouer o&thorn;er.  &para; The to&thorn;er dedly syne es Envy.  And &thorn;at es Ioye of o&thorn;er
mens harme, and sorowe of o&thorn;er mens welefare.  And &thorn;at may be in herte with
lykynge, or in mouth with bakbyttynge, or in werke with of mens gudnes
wyth-drawyng or ells with ill procurynge.  Envye mase man to hafe &thorn;e herte hevy of
&thorn;at he sese o&thorn;er men mare worthi &thorn;an he in any thyng.  &para; The third dedly syne
es Wrethe, &thorn;at es ane vnresonabyll temperoure of herte; and of it comes stryfes
and contekes, schamefull and dyuerse wordes and denyouse, and wikked sclandirs.
&para; The ferthe dedly syne es Slouthe, and &thorn;at mase manes herte hevy and slawe


<PB N="1: 225">

in gude dede, and makes mane to yrke in prayere or halynes, and puttes man in
wykkednes of wanhope, for it slokyns &thorn;e lykynge&yogh; of gastely lufe.  &para; The fyfte
dedly syne es Couetyse, and &thorn;at es ane vnmesurabill luffe to hafe erthely gudes,
and it destroyes &amp; blyndes manes herte.  And &thorn;are-of commes tresones, ffalse
athes, wykked reste, Malice and hardnes of herte agaynes mercy.  &para; The sexte
dedly syne es Glotony, and &thorn;at makes mane to serue and to be bouxome till
wykked lykynges of &thorn;e flesche, &thorn;e whilke man suld maister and ouercome with
mesure.  Of glotony commes vayne Ioy, lyghtnes, and littill vndirstandynge.  &para; The
seuen[d]e dedly syne es Lecherye, and &thorn;at mase manes herte to melte, and to playe
thare &thorn;are his herte lykes and heldes, and &thorn;at with-owtene gouernynge of
resoune.  Of lechery commes blyndynge of herte, In prayere vnstabilnes, and
fulle-hastynes, lufe of hym-selfe, hatredene of godde, lufe of &thorn;is worlde, vgglynes
and whanhope of &thorn;e blysse of heuene.  &para; Dere frende, thire are &thorn;e seuene dedly
synnes; and wele ere &thorn;ay callid dedly synnes, ffor Pride twynnes fra man his
godde, Envy his euencristene, Ire hym-selfe twynnes, Slouthe hym tourmentes,
Couetyse hym begyles, Glotony hym dessayues, and Lecherye hym in thraledome
settis....  [X.] Nowe hase &thorn;ou herde &thorn;e seuene sekenes of manes saule.  &para; Sythene
aftirwarde commes &thorn;e souerayne leche and takes &thorn;ere medcynes, and waresche
mane of &thorn;ese seuene seknes and stabills hym in &thorn;e seuene vertue&yogh;, thurgh &thorn;e
gyftes of &thorn;e haly gaste.  &THORN;e whilke are &thorn;ese: &para; &THORN;e gaste of wysdom and
vndirstandynge, &thorn;e gaste of consaile and of stalworthenes, &thorn;e gaste of cunnynge and
of pete, and &thorn;e gaste of drede of godde Almyghty.  Thurghe &thorn;ese gyftes oure
lord Ihesu lerres mane all &thorn;at he hase myster [of] till &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at es callid actyfe,
and til &thorn;e lyfe called contemplatyfe.  And se how; firste mane suld lefe &thorn;e euyll
and do &thorn;e gude; lefe &thorn;e euyll, &thorn;at teches vs &thorn;e gaste of drede of godde
almyghty, and do &thorn;e gude leres vs &thorn;e gaste of pete.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at twa thynges
are &thorn;at lettis vs to do gude, &thorn;at es at saye welefare and tribulacione of &thorn;is
worlde, ffor welefare desayues vs with losengery, tribulacyone with hardnes of
noyes &amp; dysses: for-&thorn;i sall &thorn;ou despyse &thorn;e welefare of &thorn;is worlde &thorn;at &thorn;ou be
noghte &thorn;er-with dessayuede, and &thorn;at leres &thorn;e &thorn;e gaste of cunnynge; and &thorn;ou
sall stallworthly suffire tribulacyone &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noghte ouercommene, and &thorn;at
teches vs &thorn;e gaste of stallworthenes.  And &thorn;ire foure suffice till &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at es
callid actyfe.  And &thorn;e to&thorn;er thre fallys to &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at es callid contemplatyfe;
ffor thre maners [are] of contemplacione.  Ane es in creaturs, and &thorn;at leres &thorn;e gaste
of vndyrstandynge.  The to&thorn;er es in haly writte whare &thorn;ou sese whatte &thorn;ou [sal]
doo &amp; what &thorn;ou sall lefe, and &thorn;at leres &thorn;e the gaste of consaile.  The thirde
manere es in godde hym-selfe, and &thorn;at leres vs &thorn;e gaste of wysdome.  Now &thorn;ou
sese thurgh &thorn;e gyftes of Ihesu how he es besy abowte oure hele.  [XI.] Eftire &thorn;is
sall &thorn;ou wiete whilke ere &thorn;e tene comandementis.  &para; &THORN;e firste comandement es
&thorn;is: &laquo;Thow sall wirchip&macr;e bot a godde &thorn;i lorde, and till hym anely &thorn;ou sall
serue&raquo;.  &THORN;at es at say: wyrchipe hym with righte trouthe, serue vn-till [hym] anely
with gude werkes.  Here sall &thorn;ou thynke if &thorn;ou hafe lelly serued godde &amp; wirchiped
godde; if &thorn;ou hafe seruede hym ouer all thynge; if &thorn;ou hafe &yogh;olden hym &thorn;at
that &thorn;ou hyghte, if &thorn;ou hafe done le[l]e penance, and if &thorn;ou hafe &yogh;oldyne
hym &thorn;at that &thorn;ou hyghte hym in &thorn;i cristyndome, that was, to forsake &thorn;e deuelle


<PB N="1: 226">

and all his werkes and in god lelly to trowe.  And thurghe &thorn;is commandement
es mane ordaynede ynence god &thorn;e ffadire.  &para; [In] &thorn;e to&thorn;er commandement es
defendide to take goddes name in vayne; and lying and falsenes &thorn;are-in es defendide;
and thurghe &thorn;is commandement es man ordaynede ynence godde &thorn;e Sone, &thorn;at
saise hym-selfe &laquo;I am sothefastnes&raquo;.  &para; &THORN;e thirde commandemente es, &laquo;vmbythynke &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;i haly-dayes&raquo;, &thorn;at es to saye, in &thorn;ine awene herte to kepe &thorn;e in riste and pees, with-owttene seruage of syne or of bodyly dedis.  And &thorn;is commandement ordaynes mane to reschayfe &thorn;e Haly gaste.  &THORN;ise thre
commandementes lerres mane how-gates he sall hafe hym ynence godde &thorn;e trynite, to
whas lyknes he es made in saule. / &THORN;e o&thorn;er seuene commandementes leres man
how he sall hafe hym ynence his euencristene.  &para; &THORN;e firste es: &laquo;&THORN;ou sall honour &thorn;i fadire and &thorn;i modire&raquo; fleschely and gastely, and &thorn;at in twa maners, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be bouxom to thaym in reuerence and honour, and [&thorn;at] &thorn;ou helpe &thorn;ame at thy powere in all thynge&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe myster [of].  &laquo;&THORN;at &thorn;ou be of lange lyfe in erthe&raquo;; ffor if &thorn;ou will be of lange lyfe, it es resone &thorn;at &thorn;ou honoure thayme of whaym &thorn;ou hase &thorn;e lyfe; ffor he &thorn;at will noghte honoure hym thurgh whaym he es, it es noghte righte &thorn;at he be mare &thorn;a[t] he es.  &para; &THORN;e to&thorn;er commandement es &thorn;is: &laquo;&THORN;ou sall sla na man&raquo;.  Here sall &thorn;ou wyt &thorn;at slaughter es of many maneres: ffor &thorn;er es manes-slaghter of hand, of tunge, of herte.  Mannes-slaynge of hande es when a mane slaes ano&thorn;er with his hande&yogh;, or when he duse hym in bandis of dede, als in presone, or in o&thorn;er stede &thorn;at may be enchesone of his
dede.  Manes-slaynge of tunge es in twa maneres, thurghe commandement or
thurghe enticement.  Manes-slayng of herte es alswa one twa maners, &thorn;at es,
whene mene &yogh;ernys and couaytes ded of o&thorn;er, and when he suffyrs man to dy and
will noghte delyuer hym if he hafe powere.  &para; &THORN;e thirde commandement es &thorn;is:
&laquo;&THORN;ou sall do na lechery&raquo;; and &thorn;at es ryghte; wha-sa will hafe &thorn;e lyfe with-owttene corupcyone in &thorn;e Ioy of heuene, hym byhoues kepe his lyfe &thorn;at es dedly
with-owttene corupcione of body.  &para; &THORN;e ferthe commandement es &thorn;is: &laquo;&THORN;ou sall do na thyfte ne na falsenes&raquo;; and &thorn;at es ryghte, ffor he &thorn;at will safe o&thorn;er menes lyfe he sall noghte do away &thorn;at that moghte his lyfe sustayne.  &para; &THORN;e fyfte
commandement es &thorn;is: &laquo;&THORN;ou sall noghte bere false wittnes agaynes thyne euen-cristyne&raquo; with hym &thorn;at will noye hym or sla hym; and &thorn;at es ryghte, ffor he &thorn;at will noghte sckathe his euencristyne he sall noghte consente ne na consaile gyffe to do hym ill.  &para; &THORN;e sexte commandement and &thorn;e seuende er &thorn;ir: &laquo;&THORN;ou sall noghte couaite &thorn;i neghtboure wyfe&raquo;, &laquo;ne &thorn;ou sall noghte couaite his house ne nane of his gude wrangwysly&raquo;; ffor he &thorn;at hase wykked will and ill Entente in his herte, he may noghte lang with-hald hym fra wykkide dede; and &thorn;erfore if &thorn;ou will noghte do lecherye &thorn;ou sall noghte consente to mane ne to womane &thorn;at it duse, and if &thorn;ou
will noghte stele &thorn;ou sall noghte couayte o&thorn;er mennes thynges in &thorn;i herte.  Dere
frende, &thorn;ir are &thorn;e ten commandementes &thorn;at god gafe till Moyses in the mounte
of Synay.  The thre fyrste er pertenande to &thorn;e lufe of god, and the to&thorn;er seuene
to &thorn;e lufe of &thorn;i-selfe and of thynne euene-crystyne.  [XII.] Now, efter, sall &thorn;ou wyt
whilke ere &thorn;e seuene vertue&yogh;, &thorn;at es to saye &para; Trouthe, Trayste, and Lufe,
Wysedome and Rightwysenes, Mesure and Force.  Of &thorn;e same matire er &thorn;e seuene vertus
&thorn;at &thorn;e tene commandementis, bot &thorn;is es &thorn;e varyance be-twyx thaym: The tene
commandementis kennes vs what we sall do, and &thorn;e seuene vertus kennes vs how we


<PB N="1: 227">

sall doo.  The thre fyrste, &thorn;at es to say Trouthe, Trayste and Lufe, ordaynes the
how &thorn;ou sall lyfe als to godde, &thorn;e to&thorn;er foure how &thorn;ou sall ordayne thyne awene
lyfe &thorn;at [&thorn;ay] sall lede till &thorn;e Ioye of heuene.  Dere frende, the awe to wyte &thorn;at
we ere all made for ane ende, &thorn;at es to say, for to knawe godde, to hafe hym,
and to lufe hym.  Bot thre thynges er nedefull at puruaye till oure cu[m]ynge [to
gud ende], that es, to wyte whedyr we sall ga, and &thorn;at we wyll comme thedyre,
and &thorn;at we hafe trayste to com thedyre; ffor grete foly ware it to begyne &thorn;e
thynge mane may noghte ende.  &YOGH;itte one &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde, &thorn;e mane &thorn;at will wyele
doo, hym nedide to hafe wysdome, myghte, and will, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;at he konne
[wele] doo, and &thorn;at he may doo, and &thorn;at he wyll doo.  Bot for-&thorn;i &thorn;at we hafe
noghte cunnynge, myghte, ne will of oure-selfe, for-&thorn;i hase godde gyfene vs trouthe
for to fulfill &thorn;e defaute of oure [cunnynge; trayste, for to fulfill &thorn;e defaute of oure]
myghte; sothefaste lufe, for to ordayne oure will to &thorn;e tane and to &thorn;e to&thorn;er.
Trouthe ordaynes vs to godde &thorn;e Sone to whayme es appropyrde Wysdome, Trayste
till godde &thorn;e ffadyre to whaym es appropyrde myghte, Lufe to &thorn;e Haly gaste till
whayme es appropyrde gudnes.  And &thorn;are-[fore] trouthe makes vs to hafe knawynge
[of god]; and &thorn;at knaweynge vs sayse &thorn;at he es wondyrfull ffre es he &thorn;at one &thorn;is
manere and &thorn;us largely gyffes of his gudnes, and of &thorn;at comes trayste; and [of] &thorn;at
knawynge &thorn;at sais &thorn;at he es gude, commes &thorn;e thyrde sothefastnes, &thorn;at es lufe,
ffor ylke a thynge luffes kyndely &thorn;e gude.  [XIII.] Dere frende, here sall &thorn;ou wyte
whilke are &thorn;e twelue artycles of &thorn;e trouthe.  &para; The firste es &thorn;is: &thorn;at godde es ane in hym-selfe and thre in person&macr;s, with-owttene begynnynge and with-owttene
Endynge, and &thorn;at all thynges made of noghte with his worde.  &para; &THORN;e to&thorn;er artecle
es, &thorn;at goddes sone tuke flesche and blode of &thorn;e blyssed maydene Marie and was
borne of hire sothefaste godde and sothefaste mane.  &para; &THORN;e thirde es, &thorn;at he was
dede and grauene, noghte for nede, bot for to by vs of his fre will.  &para; The ferthe
artecle es, &thorn;at &thorn;e same Ihesu rase fra dede to lyfe, and we sall ryse alswa.  &para; The
fyfte artecle es, &thorn;at &thorn;e same sothefaste god and mane steighe vp in till heuene in
manhed and godhede, and we sall steighe vp alswa thurgh his grace.  [XIV.] &para; &THORN;e
sext artecle es Baptyme, &thorn;at mase mane clene of syne &thorn;at he drawes of kynde,
and gyffes grace to clense.  &para; The seuende artecle es Confirmacione, &thorn;at confermys
&thorn;e haly gaste one mane &thorn;at es cristenede.  &para; &THORN;e aughtened artecle es Penance,
&thorn;at duse awaye all maner of syne, dedly and venyall.  &para; &THORN;e nynde es &thorn;e sacrament
of &thorn;e Auter, &thorn;at confermys &thorn;e penante, and gyffes hym force &thorn;at he fall noghte
efte in syne, and vphaldes hyme and reconsailles hym.  &para; &THORN;e tende artecle es
Ordyre, &thorn;at gyffes powere till &thorn;ayme &thorn;at are ordeynede to do &thorn;aire Offece and
to do &thorn;e sacramentis.  &para; &THORN;e elleuende artecle es Matrimone, &thorn;at defendis dedly
syne in werke of generacyone by-twyx mane and womane.  &para; &THORN;e twelfed artecle
es Enoyntynge, &thorn;at mene Enoyntes &thorn;e seke in perell of dede, for alegeance of
body and saule.  [XV.] Dere frende, aftyre sall &thorn;ou wyt whilke are &thorn;e foure vertus
cardynalles, thurgh whilke all manes lyfe es gouernede in &thorn;is worlde, &THORN;at es &para;
Cunnynge and Rightwisnes, Force and Mesure.  Of &thorn;ir foure saise &thorn;e haly gaste in
&thorn;e buke of Wysdome &thorn;at &thorn;are es na thynge mare profytabill till man in erthe.  And
se nowe, whare-fore.  Wha-sa walde any thynge wele do, firste hyme byhouys &thorn;at he
konne chese &thorn;e ill fra &thorn;e gude, and of twa gud chese &thorn;e bettire: &amp; &thorn;is vertu es called


<PB N="1: 228">

cunnynge.  Si&thorn;en &thorn;ou sal lefe &thorn;e ill &amp; do &thorn;e gude, &amp; do &thorn;e greter gude] and leffe &thorn;e lesse gude: and &thorn;is es the vertu &thorn;at es callede ryghtwysnes.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at
twa thynges lettes mane to do wele and lefe &thorn;e yll, &thorn;at es at say welefare of
&thorn;is worlde, for it dessayfes hyme with false vanytes, &thorn;e to&thorn;er es tribulacyone, to
putt hym downe with many scharpnes: agaynes welefare sall &thorn;ou hafe mesure &thorn;at
&thorn;oue be noghte ouer-hye: and &thorn;is vertu es called temperance.  And agayne
aduersyte sall &thorn;ou hafe hardynes &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noghte castene downne: and &thorn;at
vertue es callyde fforce or strenghe.  [XVI.] &para; Here-eftyre sall &thorn;ou wyte whylke
are &thorn;e seuene werkes of mercy.  &para; The firste werke of Mercy es, to gyffe mete
to &thorn;e hunngry.  The to&thorn;er es to gyffe drynke to &thorn;e thrysty.  The thirde es to
clethe &thorn;e nakede.  &THORN;e ferthe es to herbere &thorn;e herberles.  &THORN;e fyfte es to vesete
&thorn;am&macr;e &thorn;at ere in presoune.  The sexte es to comforth &thorn;e seke.  The seuende
[es] to bery &thorn;e dede.  Thyse are &thorn;e seuene werkes of mercy &thorn;at are langande to
&thorn;e body.  Bot nowe may &thorn;ou say to me: &laquo;how sulde I &thorn;at es in Relygyone, and
noghte hase to gyffe at ete ne at drynke, ne clathes to &thorn;e nakede, ne herbery to
&thorn;e herberles, ffor I am at o&thorn;er mens will and noghte at myne awene?  ffor-thi
ware it better &thorn;at I ware seculere, &thorn;at I myghte do &thorn;ire werkes of mercy&raquo;.  / A,
dere frende, be noghte begylede.  Better it es to hafe pete and compassione in
&thorn;i herte of hym &thorn;at hase mysese and wrechednes, thane &thorn;ou hade all &thorn;is worlde
to gyffe for charyte; ffor it es bettir wyth compassione to gyffe &thorn;i-selfe, als &thorn;ou
erte, &thorn;an it es to gyffe &thorn;at that &thorn;ou hase.  There-fore, dere frende, gyffe thi-selfe,
and &thorn;an gyffes &thorn;ou mare &thorn;an es in all &thorn;is worlde.  Bot now may &thorn;ou say me
one &thorn;is manere: &laquo;Sothe it es &thorn;at it es better to gyffe hyme-selfe &thorn;an it es to
gyffe of his: bot better es &thorn;e tane and &thorn;e to&thorn;er &thorn;an es ane be it-selfe, for lesse
es a gud &thorn;an twa&raquo;.  It es noghte swa; ffor whethire es better be callede godde,
or his seruande?  Thow wate wele &thorn;at [it] es better to be callede godde.  Bot &thorn;ase
&thorn;at suffirs hunngere, thryste, caulde and defaute, and o&thorn;er wrechidnes and
mysese, calles oure lorde Ihesu Criste &laquo;hym-selfe&raquo;, ffor he saise &thorn;us in &thorn;e gosepelle: &laquo;What als &thorn;ou dyde to &thorn;e leste of myne, &thorn;ou did to me&raquo;...  Saynt Barnarde says: &laquo;Thire pure hase noghte in erthe, ne thire riche hase noghte in heuene&raquo;; and &thorn;are-fore if &thorn;e Riche will it hafe, thaym byhoues bye it at &thorn;e pure.  / Now wate I wele &thorn;ou couaytes to wyte whilke are verray pure, and whilke noghte.  Now herkene with deuocyone.  Sume are &thorn;at hase reches and lufes thaym, and &thorn;ase are &thorn;e haldande &amp; &thorn;e couaytourse of &thorn;is worlde.  Othere are &thorn;at hase &thorn;ame noghte bot thay luffe thayme, and &thorn;ay walde hafe thayme gladly, and &thorn;ase are &thorn;e wrechide beggers of &thorn;e worlde, and &thorn;e false folke in religyone, and &thorn;ase are als riche and richere &thorn;ane
&thorn;e o&thorn;er [in will].  And of thame Ihesu saise in &thorn;e gospelle &thorn;at &laquo;lyghtere it ware a camelle to passe thurghe a nedill eghe, &thorn;an &thorn;e riche to come in to &thorn;e blysse of
heuene&raquo;.  Sume are &thorn;at hase reches bot thay lufe thaym noghte, noghte-for-thy &thorn;ay
will wele hafe &thorn;ame: and &thorn;ase are &thorn;e gud mene of &thorn;e worlde &thorn;at dispendis wele
that at &thorn;ay hase.  Bot fone are of &thorn;ase!  &YOGH;it are o&thorn;er &thorn;at hase noghte reches,
ne lufes noghte thaym, ne will noght hafe &thorn;ame: and &thorn;ase are &thorn;e gude folke &thorn;at
are in religione, and &thorn;ase are sothefastely pure, and &thorn;airs es &thorn;e Ioye of heuene,
ffor &thorn;at es the benysone of &thorn;e pure.  Than it behufes &thorn;at &thorn;e riche hafe &thorn;e
reuer[s]e of &thorn;at benysone; and &thorn;are-fore may I say &laquo;Blyssede be &thorn;e pouer for &thorn;aires es &thorn;e kyngdome and &thorn;e Ioye of heuene&raquo;.  And swa may I say of &thorn;e riche for


<PB N="1: 229">

&thorn;airs es pyne of helle.  Alswa pouer &thorn;ay are &thorn;at hase pouerte and lufes na
reches, and pouer &thorn;ay are &thorn;at hase reches and lufes pouert.  [XVII.] Now aftire
&thorn;is, awe &thorn;e to wyte whylke are &thorn;e seuene prayers of &thorn;e <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at duse away all ill and purchase all gude.  And &thorn;ase seuene prayers er contende in &thorn;e
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN> &thorn;e whilke oure lorde Ihesu Criste kennde till his discyples how &thorn;ay
[suld] pray godde &thorn;e ffadire, and sayd thaym one &thorn;is manere: &laquo;Whene &yogh;e sall
praye, one &thorn;is wyese sall &yogh;e say: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster qui es in celis &amp;c.</FOREIGN>&raquo;  <SEG
ID="addedmatter"><NOTE>The following section, enclosed in seg tags, does not appear in the Vernon MS copy.</NOTE>Now, my frende, wit &thorn;ou &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu Cryste kennes vs in &thorn;e gospelle to make &thorn;is prayere.  And &thorn;are-fore I walde at &thorn;ou wyste at &thorn;e begynnynge whate es
prayere or orysone, and sythyne &thorn;at &thorn;ou vndirstande &thorn;e prayere of &thorn;e <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>.  / Prayere or Orysone es noghte elles bot &yogh;ernyng of saule, with certayne
trayste &thorn;at it commes &thorn;at &thorn;ou prayes.  And in &thorn;at trayste vs settis Ihesu Criste
whene he kennes vs to calle godde &laquo;oure fadyre &thorn;at es in heuene&raquo;; ffor in hym
sall man hafe certayne trayste &thorn;at he may and will all gudnes gyffe &thorn;at oure
saule kane &yogh;erne and mekill mare, &thorn;e whilke es betakynde by &thorn;ise wordes: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Qui es in celis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say &laquo;&thorn;e whilke es in heuene&raquo;; ffor if godde will call
hym-selfe oure fadyre, &thorn;an he makes vs to wiet &thorn;at he lufes vs als childyre, and at
he will gyffe vs all &thorn;at we hafe myster of.  Bot certanly, if all &thorn;e lufe &thorn;at euer
had fadire or modire vn-to &thorn;aire childyre, or all o&thorn;er lufes of &thorn;is worlde, ware
gedirde to-gedyre in a lufe, and &yogh;it &thorn;at lufe ware multipliede als mekill als manes
herte moghte thynke, &yogh;it it moghte na-thynge atteyne to &thorn;e lufe &thorn;at godde oure
fadyre hase vn-till vs, &thorn;are whare we are hys enmys.  And &thorn;at sall we wele see
thurgh &thorn;e grace of godde, If we se one what manere he es oure ffadyr and
whatt he hase done for vs.  Wit &thorn;ou &thorn;at whene god made all creaturs of noghte,
we rede noghte &thorn;at he made any creature till his lyknes bot mane allane; and
&thorn;are-fore godd he es, and makere of all thynges of &thorn;e worlde, bot he es noghte
&thorn;aire fadyre; bot vn-till vs, thurghe his awene myghte full of mercy, es he godde
and makere and ffadyr, ffor &thorn;at oure saule es lelly lyke vn-till &thorn;e lyknes of &thorn;e
ffadyr, and &thorn;e sone, and &thorn;e haly gaste, &thorn;at ere hallyly a godde and persons thre.
And all &thorn;is werlde he hase made to serue man, whils mane will duelle in his lele
lufe als his awene childyre.  Bot als-tyte als we twyne fra &thorn;at lele lufe, for lufe
of &thorn;is lyfe, or for any o&thorn;er thynge, we losse &thorn;e lordechipe of &thorn;is worlde, and
becommes thralles dreryly to &thorn;e deuelle, &thorn;are we ware before fre, and ayers of
&thorn;e erytage of &thorn;e kyngdome of heuene and to welde &thorn;e welthe of &thorn;is werlde.
Allas [I] may saye, Allas, allas, what here es a sorowfull chaunge, wha-sa it
vndyrstode!  Wit &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at here es gret lykynge of lufe,&mdash;when godd &thorn;at es
with-owttyne begynnynge and es with-owttene chaungeyng and duellys with-owttyne
Endynge, for he es al&thorn;ir-myghtyeste and al&thorn;ir-wyseste, and alswa al&thorn;ire-beste &thorn;at
mannes herte may noghte thynke, in whaym es lufe and Ioy endles,&mdash;here, I say, es
takyne of gret lufe, &thorn;at he deyned hym to make vs till his awene lyknes righte
als we had bene his awen chosene childyre, and moghte hafe lefte vs to be a
littill vyle matire als we ware made of oure modyr, &thorn;at vile es to neuene; or he
moghte hafe made vs at his will [lik] any-kyne o&thorn;er bestis, and &thorn;ane had we dyede
to-gedire bathe body and saule.  Bot when he hade made vs man and gafe vs
&thorn;e saule to his awene lyknes&mdash;louede and luffede be &thorn;at lorde!&mdash;for to be ayers of
&thorn;e Erytage of heuene, and lyfe in &thorn;at gret Ioye with-owttene Ende, now es na


<PB N="1: 230">

herte sa harde &thorn;at it na moghte nesche and lufe swylke a godde with all his
myghte, and his herte suld melte, filled of Ioy, If it thoghte sothely of &thorn;at
grace &thorn;at oure lorde hase done till vs by-fore all o&thorn;er creaturs.  And &yogh;itt did
he mare thurghe his mekill mercy.  For whene we ware thurghe oure sorowfull
syne twynnede fra godde oure sweteste ffadire, and become thralles to &thorn;e ill
gaste, than he, thurghe hys maste mercy, sente his awene sonne, &thorn;at with hym es
godde in his godhede, for to take flesche and blode of &thorn;e virgyne Marie, Maydene
and modyr, lastand in Ioy; and one &thorn;is manere did he &thorn;e dede: In state of
thralle tuke he oure flesche to suffre &thorn;e gylteste pouerte and schame and noyes
and paynnes &thorn;at neuer dyd ill ne na maner of syne, and sythene delyuerde hym
till &thorn;e vileste dede and &thorn;e schamefulleste &thorn;at man moghte thynke, to delyuer vs
wreches of sorowfull bandis, and of &thorn;e pynand presone puttid in hell, and to
make vs to comme till &thorn;e heghe heuene, whare we sall be als kynges corounde
in blyse, if we do &thorn;e will of &thorn;at swet lorde &thorn;at for vs ordeynede hym to dye
one &thorn;e crosse als &thorn;ofe he had bene a wykkid thefe.  Dere ffrende, nowe hase
&thorn;ou here twa thynge&yogh; in &thorn;e whylke godde hase schewede vs &thorn;at he es oure
fadire and &thorn;at he lufes vs als his awene childyre, &thorn;are we are agayne hyme with
oure wykked syne.  The firste es &thorn;at he made vs till his awene lyknes, and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er es &thorn;at he boghte vs fra presoune with his precyouse dede of his manhede.
For &thorn;e fyrste es man haldene till hym for to lufe hym with all his herte.  Bot
&thorn;an may &thorn;ou aske: &laquo;What sall I do hym for &thorn;e to&thorn;er thynge?  ffor if I sall with
pouerhede lofe godde &thorn;e ffadyr and lufe hym and serue hym with all my saule and
with all my herte in all thynges for-&thorn;i &thorn;at he made me of noghte and gafe me
saule aftir his awene lyknes, als it was commandyd in &thorn;e alde lawe be-fore godde
was borne and be-com man for vs: what moghte I now do hym whene he for me
wrechid synnere sa mekill hym lawede &thorn;at he walde becomme mane, and he gafe
hym to me whene he thurghe his sweteste mercy walde dye for me, and of &thorn;e
maste noyouse and &thorn;e maste vile dede &thorn;at euer was thoghte?  I wate neuer
what I may say here, ffor if I myghte lyffe a hundrethe &yogh;ere, and if I moghte in
&thorn;at tym ilk a day at a tyme dye als vile ded als he for me dide, &yogh;it ne ware it
noghte ynence his gret gyfte, when he es sothely said goddes sonne of heuene,
and gafe hym-selfe till vs &thorn;at tynte was thurgh syne and put in to &thorn;e pyne of
helle and &thorn;are in &thorn;e dispytte of hym seruede to &thorn;e deuelle.  How sulde we
&thorn;ane &yogh;elde hym &thorn;e gude gret gyfte whene he walde sende his awene sone to be
pynede for oure syne?&raquo;  Now I sall lere the, if god gyffe me grace, how oure
dere ffadir askes nane o&thorn;er store bot that we with herte knawe oure awene
ffebillnes and oure wrechidnes &thorn;at we hafe for oure awene syne.  Thane sall we
be in bitternes of penance, and crye till hym faste mercy, &thorn;at he vs saue for
his haly name, ffor of oure-selfe hafe we noghte hym for to &yogh;elde.  &THORN;are-fore said
the prophete in &thorn;e psalme: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quid retribuam domino pro omnibus que retribuit michi?
Calicem salutaris accipiam et nomen domini invocabo &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;What sall I &yogh;elde to god for all his gud gyftes &thorn;at he me gyffes als lorde with-owttene my deserte?
The coppe of hele I sall take and calle &thorn;e name of my lorde&raquo;.  The cope of
hele whare-of dranke oure lord Ihesu oure saueour, &thorn;at es the bytternes of &thorn;e
penance in his grete pynes; and &thorn;at man in all his thoghte&yogh; calles gode&yogh; name,
&thorn;at sothefastely knawes &thorn;at he hase noghte of hym-selfe bot sorowe and syn&macr;ne.


<PB N="1: 231">

And wit thow &thorn;at if sothefastenes be sett faste in thi saule, &thorn;e mare &thorn;at &thorn;ou
knawes &thorn;e for wrechide and febyll, &thorn;e mare sall &thorn;ou meke &thorn;e and calle one hys
mercy.  And &thorn;us it was of oure swete lady maydene and modyr, ffor scho had
mare of grace &thorn;ane any in this lyfe man or womane &thorn;at euer was borne,
tharefore scho helde hir lesse and lawere &thorn;an any o&thorn;er wyghte, and mare cryede
scho mercy &thorn;an any o&thorn;er man, whene sothefaste goddes sone lighte in hir
wambe.  / My dere frende, se now aftirwarde why oure lorde Ihesu kennes vs in &thorn;e
gospelle to say &laquo;oure ffadire&raquo; and noghte &laquo;my ffadir&raquo;.  For by &thorn;at, will he kenne vs &thorn;at we suld gedyre all men with vs in oure prayers; ffor all ere oure brethire, crystende and vncristende mene, ffor &thorn;at all of a gouernaylle hafe we a ffadyr; and
&thorn;at &thorn;ou may &thorn;is thynge thurghe &thorn;e grace of godd clerelyere see, gyffe gude
Entente till &thorn;at at I say.  Hym calles &thorn;ou thi fleschely bro&thorn;er &thorn;at hase his body
of &thorn;e same mane and womane of whaym &thorn;ou hase thyne: thane sall &thorn;ou wele
halde hym &thorn;i bro&thorn;er &thorn;at hase his saule of &thorn;e same fadir of heuene of whaym
&thorn;ou hase &thorn;i saule, and of swylke a kynd, and of swylke a lyknes; ffor als wele
made godde ilke mane till lyknes of &thorn;e trinyte als he did &thorn;e; and &thorn;is bro&thorn;erhede
mare suld we lufe and mare dere halde, &thorn;an &thorn;e bro&thorn;erhede of &thorn;e flesche, in
als mekill als &thorn;e saule es mare nobyll &thorn;an &thorn;e flesche, and in als mekill als godde
oure fadir of heuene es mare nobill and mare for to lufe &thorn;an oure fleschly fadir.
And &thorn;at suld we do if we saghe als clerely with oure gastely eghe, als we do
with oure bodyly eghe.  Bot for-thy &thorn;at we see noghte bot with &thorn;e fleschely
eghe, als it ware bestes, we hafe na knawynge ne na lufe bot of &thorn;at bro&thorn;erhede
&thorn;at commes of &thorn;e flesche stynkande and foule.  Allas, allas!  what sorowfull thynge
thus hase blyndid vs!  Certis na thynge mare blyndis manes saule &thorn;ane lufe of
erthely thynge &thorn;at son&macr;e takes Ende.  For-&thorn;i behufes mane lefe his propire will if
he will perfitly knawe &thorn;e lufesomest bro&thorn;erhede whare-of now mekill I hafe spokene,
ffor whate-sa-euer we hafe in body or in saule of gudnes or of fairenes, we hafe it
of oure fadyr of heuene, godde, &thorn;at es till vs fadir, and Euenly till all his creaturs;
noghte anely for his makynge of noghte, ne for his gouernyng of his grace, for
his purchasynge &thorn;at he made of vs &thorn;at ware tynt childir, with his flesche and his
blode &thorn;at he for vs gafe, als saynt Austyne &thorn;e nobill clerke witnes.  He sayse, &laquo;&thorn;e
ffadir gaffe his Sone thurgh whaym he walde by vs thralles; he gafe &thorn;e Haly
gaste thurgh whayme he walde purchase &thorn;e thralles in his childire.  &THORN;e sonn
he gafe in pryse of raunsone, &thorn;e haly gaste in preuelege of purchase; and
&thorn;arfore &thorn;e ffadir kepis hym-selfe in Erytage till his childir &thorn;at he purchase&raquo;.  And &thorn;are-fore, dere frende, na mane sall mystrayste of &thorn;e lufe of his swete ffadirhede
and of his dere pete, ffor mare es his mercy &thorn;ane all oure wykkednes; ffor wha
sa calles till hym with all his herte, with-owtene faile he will here hyme, for
he es full of mercy.  And &thorn;are-fore, als I be-fore saide, with &yogh;ernynge of saule
and certayne trayste, calle appone hym trewely with all thi herte.  He es &thorn;i ffadir
pereles &thorn;at purchacece&yogh; &thorn;e pees; and saye traystely till hyme als hym-selfe vs
lerede: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster qui es in celis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say &laquo;Oure ffadir &thorn;at es in heuene&raquo;;
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">sanctificetur nomen tuum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;halyed be &thorn;i name&raquo;; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">adueniat regnum tuum,</FOREIGN> &laquo;it come &thorn;i kyngedome; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">ffiat voluntas tua sicut in celo et in terra,</FOREIGN> &laquo;&thorn;i will be donne swa in erthe als it es in heuene&raquo;; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis hodie,</FOREIGN> &laquo;oure ylke day brede &thorn;ou gyffe vs to-day&raquo;; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">et dimitte nobis debita nostra sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus nostris,</FOREIGN> &laquo;and forgyffe vs oure dettis als we for-


<PB N="1: 232">
gyffe our dettours&raquo;; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">et ne nos inducas in temptacionem,</FOREIGN> &laquo;and suffire vs noghte be ledde in to fandyngis&raquo;; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">set libera nos a malo</FOREIGN>, &laquo;bot delyuer vs fra all ill thyngis&raquo;. Amen, &thorn;at es to say, Swa mot it be.</SEG>   Now, my dere frende, &thorn;ou sall wyt &thorn;at &thorn;is Orysone passes all o&thorn;er prayers pryncypally in twa thynges, &thorn;at es to say, in worthynes and in profyte.  In worthynes, for &thorn;at god hym-selfe mad it; and for-thi do &thorn;ay gret schame and gret vnreuerence till Ihesu goddes sone &thorn;at takes &thorn;ame till wordis ry[m]and and curius, and leues &thorn;e prayere &thorn;at he vs kennede, &thorn;at wate all &thorn;e will of godde &thorn;e ffadire, and &thorn;e whilke orysone commes mare till his plesynge, and whate thynges &thorn;e wrechede caytyfe hase myster at pray fore.
Alswa, als I hafe sayde, he wate anely all &thorn;e ffadir wyll, and he wate all oure
nede.  And &thorn;are-fore a hundrethe thousande er dyssayuede with multyplicacione of
wordes and of Orysouns; ffor when &thorn;ay wene &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe grete deuocyone, &thorn;ane
hafe &thorn;ai a fulle fleschely lykynge, ffor-thy &thorn;at ilk a fleschely lykynge delytes &thorn;ame
kyndely in swylke turnede langage.  and &thorn;are-fore I walde &thorn;at &thorn;ou war warre,
ffor I say &thorn;e sykerly &thorn;at it es a foule lychery for to delyte &thorn;e in r&ymacr;mes and
slyke gulyardy.  &YOGH;it one a no&thorn;er syde saynt Austyne and saynt Gregore and o&thorn;er
halowes prayede als was &thorn;aire lykynge.  I blame noghte [&thorn;aire] prayers; bot I blame
&thorn;ase &thorn;at lefes &thorn;e prayere of godde &thorn;at hym-selfe made and lerede vs for to pray,
&thorn;at es [&thorn;e] <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>, and takes &thorn;ame till &thorn;e Orysons of a synfull saynte whare &thorn;ay
fynde it wrettene; ffor oure lorde Ihesus hym-selfe sayse in the gosepelle: &laquo;When &yogh;e
will praye: prayes noghte with many wordes, bot prayes one &thorn;is manere: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster &amp;c.</FOREIGN>&raquo;  &para; Dere frende, &yogh;it sall &thorn;ou wit, one ano&thorn;er syde, &thorn;at &thorn;e <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>
passes all o&thorn;er prayers in [sufficience], ffor &thorn;are-in es contende all thynge&yogh;, what
sa we hafe myster of, till &thorn;is lyfe or till &thorn;e to&thorn;er; ffor we praye &thorn;are-In godde
&thorn;e ffadyr &thorn;at he delyuer vs of all illes, and &thorn;at he gyffe vs all gudes, and &thorn;at
he make vs swylke &thorn;at we may neuer do ill, ne &thorn;at we may noghte fayle of
gude.  And [se] now, all &thorn;e ille &thorn;at vs greues, ou&thorn;er es it ille &thorn;at es done, or it es
ille for to come, or elles it es ille &thorn;at we suffire nowe.  Of &thorn;at ille &thorn;at es donne
and passede, we praye oure swete lorde &thorn;at he delyuer vs &thorn;er-of whene we say
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dimitte nobis debita nostra &amp;c.</FOREIGN>  We pray hym delyuer vs of ill &thorn;at es for to come, whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">et ne nos inducas in temptacionem</FOREIGN>.  Of illes &thorn;at we suffire nowe, we praye hyme &thorn;at he delyuer vs whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">set libera nos a malo</FOREIGN>.  &para; &YOGH;it, dere ffrende, on ano&thorn;er syde, wit &thorn;ou &thorn;at all maner of gude &thorn;at es, ou&thorn;er it es erthely gude, or gastely gude, or gude lastande endles; ffor erthely gude we praye whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis hodie</FOREIGN>; ffor gastely gude we praye whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">ffiat voluntas tua sicut in celo et in terra</FOREIGN>; ffor endles gude we praye when we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">adueniat regnum tuum</FOREIGN>; and confermyng of all &thorn;is we praye, whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">sanctificetur nomen tuum</FOREIGN>.  &para; Now, my dere frende, &thorn;ese ere seuene prayers of &thorn;e Ewangelle &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu Criste kennede till his dyscypills.  And &thorn;ou sall wit &thorn;at &thorn;ese foure wordes &thorn;at comes be-fore, &thorn;at es to wit <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster qui es in celis</FOREIGN>, leres vs how we sall praye, and what oure-selfe sall be in
prayere.  For we sall in ylke ane Orysone haue foure thynges, &thorn;at es to say, Perfite lufe till
hym till whaym we praye, and certayne trayste to haue &thorn;at at we praye fore,
and stabill trouth in hym in whaym we trowe, and sothefaste mekenes of &thorn;at
that of oure-selfe na gude we haue.  Perfite lufe es vndi[r]standene in &thorn;is worde


<PB N="1: 233">

<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater</FOREIGN>, ffor ilke a creature kyndly lufes his ffadir.  Certayne trayst es contende
in &thorn;is worde <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">noster</FOREIGN>, ffor if he be ours, &thorn;an may we sekerly trayst in hym &thorn;at he
es haldene till vs.  Stabill trouthe es takene in &thorn;ise wordes <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Qui es</FOREIGN>, ffor whene we say <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">qui es</FOREIGN>, &thorn;an graunt we wele &thorn;at godde es &thorn;at we neuer sawe, and &thorn;at es
ryghte trouthe, ffor trouthe es na no&thorn;er thyng bot trowyng of thyng &thorn;at may
noghte be sene.  Sothefaste mekenes es betakynde in &thorn;is worde <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In celis</FOREIGN>, ffor when we thynke how he es heghe in Ioy, and how we are here lawe in besynes,
thane we are mekide.  Bot whene we hafe festenede &thorn;ere foure thynges in oure
hertes, &thorn;an may we hardyly praye and saye with all oure affeccyone <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sanctificetur nomen tuum</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es to say &laquo;haly be &thorn;i name&raquo;; als wa [say], stabill &thorn;i name, &thorn;at es
ffadir, in vs, &thorn;at we be one &thorn;at manere &thorn;i childire &thorn;at we do na thyng &thorn;at be
agaynes &thorn;i will, and &thorn;at euer-mare we doo &thorn;at at commes to &thorn;i plesynge, thurgh
grauntynge of &thorn;i grace.  And for-thi &thorn;at we may noghte euer-mare do &thorn;at
perfitely whyls we ere in &thorn;is caytifede worlde, &thorn;are-fore pray we &thorn;us and sayse
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adueniat regnum tuum</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;it come till vs &thorn;i kyngdome, &thorn;at we regne
in &thorn;e, Ihesu, in &thorn;is lyfe thurgh thi grace, and &thorn;ou in vs in &thorn;e to&thorn;er lyfe thurgh
Ioy&raquo;.  And &thorn;is ilke we praye for &thorn;ase &thorn;at are in purgatorie.  And for-thi &thorn;at we
neuer-mare may hafe parte with Ioye of heuene if we do noghte thi will in erthe,
&thorn;are-fore we praye thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fiat voluntas tua sicut in celo et in terra,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;thi will be donne als in heuene swa in erthe&raquo;; als wa say, make vs to do &thorn;i wyll, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;ou gyffe vs grace to do all &thorn;at &thorn;ou commandes, and to lefe all &thorn;at &thorn;ou defendis; and &thorn;at swa in erthe als in heuene, &thorn;at es to say, als Michaelle and Gabrielle and Raphaelle, Cherubyne and Seraphyne, and all &thorn;e o&thorn;er angells and archangells, ... and all &thorn;ase &thorn;at are Ordeynede to &thorn;e endles lyfe in Ioy in ilke a
kynde, in ilke ane ordire, and in ilke ane elde, thi wille duse.  And for-thi &thorn;at
we may noghte do &thorn;i will whills we lyffe in &thorn;is body if &thorn;ou ne sustayne vs
noghte, &thorn;are-fore say we &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis hodie,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;Oure ilke day brede &thorn;ou gyffe vs to-day&laquo;; als wa say, &thorn;ou gyffe vs fforce in body and in saule, and hele if it be &thorn;i will of &thorn;e tane and offe &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  And here es for to wit &thorn;at &thorn;are es thre maners of brede: &thorn;a[re] es bodyly brede, &thorn;at es to say ffode and clethynge, &thorn;are es brede gastely, &thorn;at es to say of haly wrytte &thorn;e leryng; and &thorn;are es &thorn;e brede of Eukaryste, &thorn;at es &thorn;e grace in &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e autere, for to comforthe &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;e tane and &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  Bot for-thi &thorn;at we ere worthi na gudnes whills we ere bowndene in synne, &thorn;are-fore say we &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Dimitte nobis debita nostra sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus nostris,</FOREIGN> &thorn;is es to say, &laquo;fforgyffe vs oure dettis als we forgyffe oure dettours&raquo;.  &THORN;ou sall wyt &thorn;are oure synns byndis oure dettours to pynne, &thorn;are-fore we pray Ihesu to forgyff vs synnes, &thorn;at es to say, all &thorn;at we hafe synnede in thoghte in worde and in dede; and &thorn;at ryghte als we for-gyffe till &thorn;ase &thorn;at hase mysdone agaynes vs.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at a lyttill vs helpes to hafe forgyfnes of syne, if we may noghte kepe vs fra syne,
&thorn;are-fore pray we &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem,</FOREIGN> and &thorn;is es to say, &laquo;lede vs no&yogh;te in to na fandyngis&raquo;; als-wa say, suffere vs noghte be ouer-commene in fandynge&yogh; of &thorn;e deuell ne of &thorn;e flesch ne of &thorn;e werlde.  And noghte allanly we pray &thorn;at we be delyuered of all euyll fandynge&yogh;, bot alswa we pray &thorn;at we be delyuered of all ill thynge, whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Set libera nos a malo,</FOREIGN> and &thorn;is es to say, &laquo;Bot delyuer vs of all ill thyngis&raquo;, &thorn;at es, of body and of saule, of syne and of


<PB N="1: 234">

pyne ffor syne, &thorn;at now es or sall be.  Say we <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amen</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es to say, Swa be it! And for-thi sayse oure lorde Ihesu Criste in &thorn;e gospelle: &laquo;what-sa &thorn;ou prayes my fadir in my name he sall do it&raquo;, and &thorn;er-fore say at &thorn;e Ende <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Per dominum nostrum Iesum Christum filium tuum &amp;c.</FOREIGN>  And now, my dere frende, vndirstande noghte
&thorn;at &thorn;ou sall say &thorn;i Pater noster with mouthe als I hafe it here wretyne be-fore
&thorn;e.  Bot say all-anely &thorn;e nakede lettir with &thorn;i mouthe, and thynke in &thorn;i herte
of this &thorn;at I hafe said here, of ilke a worde by it-selfe; and rekk noghte &thorn;of
&thorn;ou ne multyply many Pater nosters; ffor it es better to say a Pater noster with
gude deuocyone &thorn;ane a thousande with-owttene deuocyone; ffor &thorn;us sais saynte Paule
appertly: he sayse, &laquo;me ware leuer say fyve wordes in herte deuotely, &thorn;ane fyve
thousande with my mouthe with-owttene lykynge&raquo;.  And one &thorn;e same manere sall
&thorn;ou say and do at thyne offece in &thorn;e qweire, for swa sayse &thorn;e prophete: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Psallite sapienter,</FOREIGN> and &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;Synges and versy wyesly&raquo;.  To say or to synge
wyesly, &thorn;at es, &thorn;at thi herte be one &thorn;at at &thorn;ou saise, and one &thorn;at at o&thorn;er saise,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou here it besyly; ffor if &thorn;i body be at thi seruyce, and &thorn;i mouthe speke
one a wyse, and thi herte thynke of wrechidnes, caytefly &thorn;an es &thorn;ou twynnede,
[and] when &thorn;ou swa es twynnede, &thorn;ou tynes &thorn;e mede of &thorn;i seruyce; ffor &thorn;e awe to
serue godde with all &thorn;i herte, with all thi saule, and with all &thorn;i vertu, and swa
&thorn;ou may pay &thorn;i godde.  Bot &thorn;are es many thynges &thorn;at ere cause of swylke
wrechede twynnynge, als mete, drynke, Reste, clethynge, layke, discorde, Thoghte,
laboure, hethynge.  These makes hippynge, homerynge of medles momellynge.
And &thorn;are-fore take kepe what oure lorde Ihesu Criste saise in &thorn;e gospelle: &laquo;ffirste,
he saise, sekes &thorn;e kyngdome of heuene, and all &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe myster of sall be
gyffene &yogh;owe with-owttyne any askynge&raquo;.  Thare-fore, dere frende, &thorn;ou sall wit what &thorn;ou sall hafe in &thorn;e blysse of heuene.  [XVIII.] Wit &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou sall hafe
seuene gyftes in body and seuene in saule, &thorn;at es to say: Fairenes in body
with-owttyne fylth, Lyghtenes with-owttyne slewth, Force with-owttene ffeblesce, Frenes with-owttene thralledome, Lykynge with-owttene noye, Lufelynes with-owttyne envye, Hele with-owttyne sekenes, Lange lyfe with-owttyne ende.  Thou sall hafe in saule:
Wysedome with-owttene ygnorance, Frenchipe with-owttene hateredyne, Accorde
with-owttene discorde, Myghte with-owttene wayknes, Honour with-owttene dishonour,
Sekirnes with-owttene drede, Ioy with-owttene sorowe.  Bot &thorn;e wreches in helle,
all &thorn;e reuerce, both in body and in saule, &thorn;at es to say: Fylth with-owttyne
fairenes, Slouthe with-owttene lyghtenes, Feblesce with-owttene force, Thraledome
with-owttene freenes, Angwyse with-owttene lykynge, Sekenes with-owttene hele, Ded
with-owttene ende.  Thare sall be in &thorn;air saules: Ignorance with-owttyne
wysdome, Hatredyne with-owttene lufe, Discorde with-owttene accorde, Feblesce
with-owttene powere, Schame with-owttene honour, Drede with-owttene sekernes, and
Sorowe with-owttene Ioy.  And for &thorn;is sall &thorn;ou seke with all &thorn;i myghte &thorn;at &thorn;ou
may wyne &thorn;e Ioye of heuene; ffor &thorn;are es sa gret Ioye and sa mekill swettnes, &thorn;at
if &thorn;ou myghte lyffe fra &thorn;e begynnynge of &thorn;e worlde vn-till &thorn;e ende and hafe all &thorn;e
lykynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou couthe ordeyne, &yogh;it &thorn;ou sulde with gret ryghte lefe all &thorn;ase, for to
be a day in &thorn;e Ioy of heuene. // And thus endys &thorn;e to&thorn;er degre of contemplacyone,
&thorn;at es to say &thorn;e contemplacione of haly writte; of &thorn;e whylke if &thorn;ou take gud kepe
in &thorn;i herte, it sall be lyghte vnto &thorn;e ilke a worde to halde.  One ane o&thorn;er syde,
&thorn;ou hase mater to speke vn-to &thorn;e clerke&yogh;, be &thorn;ay neuer sa wyse, or to lewede


<PB N="1: 235">

men be &thorn;ay neuer so ruyde.  [To] &thorn;e clerkes &thorn;ou mofe som matirs of &thorn;is, and
[aske] at &thorn;ou may lere more.  And whene &thorn;ou spekes till sympill mene and ruyde,
gladly &thorn;ou lere &thorn;ame [&] with swettnes.  For &thorn;ou hase enoghe whare-of &thorn;ou may
speke, and how &thorn;ou sall &thorn;i lyfe amende and gouerne, and o&thorn;er mennes alswa.
</P><P>[XIX.] &THORN;e thirde degre of contemplacyone es in Godde hym-selfe.  And &thorn;at may
be on twa maners, &thorn;at es, with-owttene in his manhede, and In, in his godhede
so blyschede.  For &thorn;us saise saynt Austyne: &laquo;ffor-&thorn;i be-come godde mane, ffor to
make mane to se godde in his kynde; ffor whe&thorn;er-som he &yogh;ode with-in or
with-owttene, euer-mare moghte man fynde pasture, with-owttene, thurgh consederacyone of his manhede, with-in thurghe contemplacyone of his godhede&raquo;.  Of his manhede, sall &thorn;ou thynke thre thynge&yogh;: &thorn;e meknes of his Incarnacyone, &thorn;e swetenes of his conuersasione, and &thorn;e grete charite of his passione.  Bot &thorn;is may &thorn;ou noghte do all att anes, and &thorn;are-fore hafe I twynned the thaym by &thorn;e seuene houres of
&thorn;e daye &thorn;at &thorn;ou saise in &thorn;e kyrke, swa &thorn;at nane houre passe the &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne
sall be swetely ocupyede in &thorn;i herte.  Bot nowe for to do &thorn;is, &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou wit
&thorn;at till ilke ane houre of &thorn;e daye es dowbyll medytacyone, ane of his passyone, and
ano&thorn;er of &thorn;e to&thorn;er sesone.  [XX] &para; Now, dere frende, before matyns sall &thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e swete byrthe of Ihesu Cryste al&thorn;er-fyrste, and sythyne eftyrwarde of his
passione.  Of his byrth, sall thou thynke besyly &thorn;e tyme, and &thorn;e stede, and &thorn;e
houre &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu Criste was borne of his modir Marie.  &THORN;e tyme was in
myd-wyntter, whene it was maste calde, &thorn;e houre was at mydnyghte, &thorn;e hardeste
houre &thorn;at es, &thorn;e stede was in mydwarde &thorn;e strete, in a house with-owttene
walles; in clowtis was he wondene and als a childe was he bundene, and In a
crybbe by-fore ane Oxe and ane Asse &thorn;at lufely lorde layde was, for &thorn;are was na
no&thorn;er stede voyde.  And here sall &thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e kepynge of Marye and
hir childe, and of hir spouse Ioseph&mdash;wat Ioye Ihesu [hym] sente.  Thou sall
thynke also of &thorn;e hyrdes &thorn;at saw &thorn;e takyne of his byrthe, and &thorn;ou sall thynke
of &thorn;e swete felachip&macr;e of angells, and rayse vpe thi herte and synge with &thorn;ame
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gloria in excelsis deo &amp;c.</FOREIGN> / Of &thorn;e passione, sall &thorn;ou thynke how &thorn;at he was at
swylke a tyme of &thorn;e nyghte betrayed of his descyple, and takene als a traytoure,
and bowndene als a thefe, and ledde als a felone ... [XXI.] &para; Be-fore pryme, &thorn;ou
sall thynke of &thorn;e passione of Ihesu and of his Ioyfull ryssynge.  Of his passyone
sall &thorn;ou thynke how &thorn;e Iewes ledde hym in to &thorn;aire counsaile, and bare false
wytnes agayne hym, and put appone hym &thorn;at he had saide blasefeme, &thorn;at es
sclandyre in godde, and &thorn;at he had said &thorn;at he suld haue distroyede &thorn;e temple
of godde and make agayne ano&thorn;er with-in the thirde day; and &thorn;ane &thorn;ay bygane to
dryfe hym till hethynge and to fulle hym als a fule, and spite one hyme in
dispyte in his faire face; and sythyne thay hide his eghene, and gafe hyme bofetes
grete and sythene asked hyme whate he was &thorn;at hym smate; and sythene &thorn;ay
ledde hym dreryly to &thorn;e dede, and &yogh;itt neuer he sayde till thaym anes why &thorn;ay
swa dyde.  Many othyre wykkydnes &thorn;ay dide hym, &thorn;at lange ware to telle. / &YOGH;itt
before pryme sall &thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e haly rysesynge: &thorn;at at &thorn;at tyme of &thorn;e daye
Ihesu Ioyfully rase fra dede to lyfe, whene &thorn;at he hade destruyede helle and
delyuerede haly sawles owte of &thorn;e powere of &thorn;e deuelle...  [XXII.] &para; &YOGH;itt be-fore vndrone sall &thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e passione and of &thorn;e witsondaye.  Of &thorn;e passione sall &thorn;ou thynke


<PB N="1: 236">

how &thorn;at tyme oure lorde Ihesu Cryste dispytousely was dyspuylede nakkynde, and
bowndene till a tree in Pylate house, and swa wykkedly scourgede and don&macr;gene,
&thorn;at of his swete body fra &thorn;e heued till &thorn;e fute noghte was lefte hale...  And at
&thorn;at ilke houre &thorn;ou sall thynke of &thorn;e witsonnday, how &thorn;[at] tyme of &thorn;e day oure
lorde Ihesu Criste sente &thorn;e haly gaste till his disciples in liknes of fyre and of
tunnges, in takynnynge &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde hafe abowndance in worde, and brynnynge
in lufe; and &thorn;at ryghte es &thorn;e purueance of oure lorde puruayde: ffor in twa
maners &thorn;e wykked gaste be-gylede mane in paradyse, &thorn;at es to saye, with wykkede
entycement of his tunge, and with &thorn;e caldnes of his venyme, and for-&thorn;i come &thorn;e
haly gaste in lyknes of tung agayne &thorn;e Entycement of &thorn;e deuelle, and in fyre for
to distruye &thorn;e caldnes of his venyme.  [XXIII.] &para; Be-fore myddaye sall &thorn;ou thynke
of &thorn;e annunciacyone and of Ihesu passione.  Of &thorn;e annunciacione sall &thorn;ou thynke
of &thorn;e grete mercy of oure lorde Ihesu Criste, whi &thorn;at he walde be-comme mane,
and ffor vs suffire &thorn;e dede in &thorn;at swete manhede, sene he moghte hafe boghte vs
agayne on o&thorn;er manere.  And &thorn;at dyde he, for till drawe till hyme &thorn;i luffe; ffor if
ane hade bene &thorn;i maker, and ano&thorn;er thi byere, and hade sufferde in [his] body
es all oure sorowe for to by all oure lufe, than hade noghte oure trouthe bene anely
in ane.  Off &thorn;e passione sall &thorn;ou thynke, at &thorn;at houre how oure lorde Ihesu was
done one &thorn;e Crosse be-twyx twa thefes, ane one his ryghte syde and ano&thorn;er one
his lefte syde, and hym-selfe &thorn;ay hangede be-twix &thorn;ame twa, alls mayster of thefes.
[I ne wate what I may say here]; ffor if all &thorn;e sekenes of &thorn;is werlde and all &thorn;e
sorowe ware in &thorn;e body of a mane anely, and &thorn;at man myghte consayfe alls
mekill noye and angwysce and sorowe in his body als all &thorn;e mene of &thorn;is werlde
moghte thynke, &yogh;itt it ware full littill or els noghte to regarde of &thorn;e sorowe &thorn;at
he sufferde for vs ane houre of &thorn;e daye...  [XXIX.] &para; Before non&macr;e sall &thorn;ou thynke of
&thorn;e passione and of &thorn;e gloriouse ascencione.  Of &thorn;e passione sall &thorn;ou thynke &thorn;at at
swylke a tyme of &thorn;e daye dyede &thorn;e makere of lyfe for &thorn;i lufe.  And here sall
&thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at Ihesu spake one &thorn;e crose, and of &thorn;e foure takynns
&thorn;at be-felle in his dede.  The fyrste worde was &thorn;is &thorn;at he spake: &laquo;Fadire, forgyffe
&thorn;ame &thorn;is syne, for &thorn;ay wate noghte whate &thorn;ay doo&raquo;.  The to&thorn;er worde was &thorn;is &thorn;at he said to &thorn;e thefe: &laquo;For sothe I say the, &thorn;is day sall &thorn;ou be with me in paradyse&raquo;.  The thirde was &thorn;at he saide to his modire of sayne Iohn&macr; his cosynne:
&laquo;Womane, lo &thorn;are thi sone&raquo;; and to &thorn;e discyple saide he: &laquo;Manne, lo &thorn;are thy Modire&raquo;.  The ferthe worde &thorn;at he saide was this: &laquo;Godde, my godde, whi hase &thorn;ou lefte me &thorn;us?&raquo;  The fyfte was: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Scicio,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;I haf thriste&raquo;.  The sexte worde was this: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In manus tuas domine &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> whilke es for to saye: &laquo;Fadir, in to &thorn;i hanndis I gyffe my sawle&raquo;.  The seuende worde was &thorn;is: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Consummatum est,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Now es &thorn;e prophecye fulfillede&raquo;: and with &thorn;at worde he helde his hede downne and gafe &thorn;e gaste.  Now &thorn;e takynns &thorn;at ware in his dede ere &thorn;ire: ffirste all &thorn;e erthe bygane to tremble, and &thorn;e vaile of &thorn;e temple braste in-twa and felle doune, &thorn;e stanes raue in-son&macr;dire, &thorn;e graues opynede and &thorn;e dede men rase;
and &thorn;e sonne with-drewe his lyghte fra &thorn;e werlde fra myddaye to non&macr;e. / Of &thorn;e
ascencione sall &thorn;ou thynke &thorn;at swylke a tyme of &thorn;e daye wente vpe oure lorde Ihesu
Criste in till &thorn;e mounte of Olyuete, seande his discyples and his swete modire
Marie; how he steighe in till heuene, and sett hym one [his] ffadir righte hande,
and how his dysciples turnede agayne into &thorn;e Cete and ware in fastynge and in


<PB N="1: 237">

prayere vntill &thorn;e commynge of &thorn;e haly gaste, and &thorn;are ware to-gedire a hundreth
and twentty in a house for to abyde &thorn;e commynge of &thorn;e haly gaste, als oure lorde
commande &thorn;ame before.  [XXV.] &para; Before euensange sall &thorn;ou thynke of Ihesu passione
and of his supere.  Of &thorn;e passione sall &thorn;ou thynke how Ioseph of Aramathy
purchaste Ihesu body of Pilate, and how &thorn;ey come to &thorn;e crosse &thorn;are he hange, and
&thorn;ay brakke &thorn;e twa thee-banes of &thorn;e twa thefes.  And &thorn;are was a knyghte redye
with a spere, and perchede &thorn;e syde of Ihesu, and smate hym to &thorn;e herte; and
als-sone come rynnande downe &thorn;e precyouse blode and watire.  And &thorn;at was &thorn;e
Rawnsone of &thorn;e whilke I before spake &mdash; louede be &thorn;at lorde!  And &thorn;ane
Ioseph tuke hym downe of &thorn;e crosse, for-&thorn;i &thorn;at na bodye sulde duelle on &thorn;e
crosse in so hye a daye als was one &thorn;e morne. / Of &thorn;e supere of Ihesu sall &thorn;ou
thynke how &thorn;at tyme he gafe his precyouse flesche and his blude in lyknes of
brede and of wyne &thorn;at we may see, and it es sothefastely flesche and blude of
Ihesu Criste &thorn;at we may noghte see with bodyli eghene.  &THORN;e thirde thynge es
gastely, &thorn;e grace &thorn;at we rescheyue whene we take &thorn;at flesche and &thorn;at blude.
We se &thorn;are lyknes of brede and of wyne and it es noghte, bot we trowe &thorn;at
&thorn;are es sothefastely &thorn;e flesche and &thorn;e blude of Ihesu Criste.  And noghte-forthi
&thorn;e lyknes of flesche ne may we noghte see.  And &thorn;are-fore &thorn;are whare we
sulde hafe vgglynes als vn-till oure body for to ete flesche and drynke blude of
mane, oure lorde Ihesu Criste turnede his flesche and his blude in liknes of brede
and of wyne, for to comforthe oure bodily witte thurghe swylke fude als we ere
wonnte for to see, and alswa for to helpe oure trouthe, thurghe &thorn;at &thorn;at we see
a thynge and trowes ano&thorn;er.  And &thorn;are-fore, dere frende, whene &thorn;ou sall gaa
for to reschaife &thorn;at swete flesche and &thorn;at blude of Ihesu thi saueour, luke at &thorn;ou
haue verray contricyone and repentance and clensynge of thi syne in thi herte,
ffor &thorn;are &thorn;ou ressayfes in sacrament reghte als &thorn;ou ressayfede hyme in flesche
and blude, bescede be &thorn;at grace!  [XXVI.] &para; Be-fore complyne sall &thorn;ou thynke how
&thorn;at Ioseph and Nicodemus wande Ihesu body in faire schetis, and enoynte it with
precyouse oynementes, and laide it in a monumente of stane, and [&thorn;e Jewes] sett &thorn;aire
seles apone &thorn;e stane, and knyghtes &thorn;at sulde it kepe.  The to&thorn;er thynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou
sall thynke in &thorn;e same tyme es &thorn;is: how Ihesus in &thorn;e daye of supere, when he
had souppede, he &yogh;ode in till a gardyne with his discyples, and felle downe in
Orysoune, and byganne for to swete one swylke manere &thorn;at &thorn;e droppis of blode
droppede of his blyssede face vn-till &thorn;e erthe.  [XXVII.] // Now hase &thorn;ou matire and
manere for to thynke of goddis manhede.  And eftirwarde sall &thorn;ou wit how &thorn;ou
sall thynke one hym in his heghe godhede.  &para; To &thorn;at, sall &thorn;ou wit &thorn;at godde
temperde swa his knaweynge fra &thorn;e begynnynge of mankynde, &thorn;at he walde noghte
all hally schewe hym to mane, ne all hally hele hyme fra mane; ffor if he hade
all hally schewede hym to mane, &thorn;an hadde trouthe noghte bene worthe and
mysbileue had noghte bene &thorn;ane ouercomene, ffor trouthe es of thynge &thorn;at may
noghte be sene, &thorn;an &thorn;at at I see es noghte trouthe; and if he had all hallily
helede [hym] fra mane, &thorn;an had trouthe noghte bene helpede, and mysbileue hade
bene excusede; and for-thi &thorn;ane walde he in party schewe hyme, and in party hele
hyme.  Bot now may &thorn;ou aske me in how many maners he walde schewe hyme.  I
say in twa maners, ane with-In, ano&thorn;er with-owttene.  With-In he schewede hyme
thurgh reuelacyone and thurgh resoune; with-owttene, thurgh halye writte and
thurgh creaturs.  Thurgh reuelacyone, whene he schewede hym till any folke thurgh


<PB N="1: 238">

inspiracione and thurghe myracle.  By resoune commes he till &thorn;e knawynge of mane
one &thorn;is manere: Ilke a mane may wele see in hym-selfe &thorn;at he es, and &thorn;at
he hase bene, bot he may wele wit &thorn;at he hase noghte bene ay, and f[ro]
&thorn;at he wate wele &thorn;at sume-tyme he begane for to be, &thorn;an was &thorn;are sume tyme
whene he was noghte.  Bot whene he was noghte, &thorn;an moghte he one na wyese
make hyme-selfe, and &thorn;is seghes mane in [ilk] creature, ffor he sees ilke a day sume
ga and sume come; ffor-&thorn;i, sene ilke thynges erre, and &thorn;ay erre noghte of
thayme-selfe, &thorn;are-fore it be-houes nede &thorn;at &thorn;are be ane to gyffe all thynges to be,
&thorn;at es to saye, of whaym alle thynges are; thare-fore it behoues of force &thorn;at
he thurghe whaym alle thynges erre, be with-owttene begynnynge: ffor if he hade
begynnyng, thane it behoufede &thorn;at he had begynnyng of sume o&thorn;er, &thorn;ane had he
noghte bene &thorn;e firste autour and &thorn;e firste begynnyng of all thynge&yogh;.  Bot &thorn;are
was nathynge before hyme; &thorn;an he come of na no&thorn;er, &thorn;ane hade he neuer na
begynnynge.  And &thorn;are-fore it be-houfes one all maner of &thorn;e werlde &thorn;at &thorn;are be
a thynge &thorn;at neuer hade begynnynge.  And whene resone of mane sese of force
&thorn;at it may na no&thorn;er-wysse be, &thorn;an he begynnys for to trowe stabilly &thorn;at a
thynge [es] with-owttene begynnynge, &thorn;at es awtour and makere and
gouernere of all thynges &thorn;at ere.  And hym calles mene Godde by this skill, ffor &thorn;is
worde <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deus</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es to say Godde, commes of a worde of grewe &thorn;at es called <FOREIGN>theos</FOREIGN>, and &thorn;at es als mekill for to say als ane anely Godde.  And &thorn;at betakyns &thorn;is worde
Godde.  [XXVIII.] And, dere frend, &thorn;ou awe to wit &thorn;at &thorn;are ne es bot a Godde ...
And &thorn;ou awe to wit &thorn;at na gude may faile to godde, bot for-thi &thorn;at swete thynge
and gud thynge es comforthe of felaschepe, &thorn;an may noghte godde be
with-owttene gudnes of felaschipe.  Than behouede it nede &thorn;at &thorn;are ware many
person&macr;s in godde, &thorn;e hegheste gudnes.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at felyschepe may noghte
be be-twyx faere &thorn;ane twa, &thorn;are-fore behoues it be &thorn;at in godde be at &thorn;e leste
twa person&macr;s; and for-thi that felyschipe es littill worthe whare &thorn;are es nane
alyance ne lufe, ffor-thi it behoues &thorn;at &thorn;e thirde persone ware in godde, &thorn;at ware
the alyance and &thorn;e lufe be-twyx the twa.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at anehede es gude and
manyhede alswa, &thorn;are-fore it behouede nede &thorn;at anehede and manyhede bathe
ware in godde.  And by &thorn;is skill commes mane to &thorn;e knaweynge of godde, &thorn;at he es
a godde in hyme-selfe, and thre in persones.  And &thorn;is ilke may mane see in
hym-selfe; ffor he sese at &thorn;e begynnynge &thorn;at he hase in hym-selfe Powere, and
sythene eftir powere he hase Wysdome.  And sythene begane he for to lufe &thorn;at
wysdome, and &thorn;an begynnes he for to knawe apertely &thorn;at &thorn;are es in &thorn;e saule
mighte, and of &thorn;at myghte commes wysdome, and of thayme bathe comes Lufe; and
when mane sese &thorn;at it es one swylke manere in hym, of &thorn;at awe hyme to wit
&thorn;at one swylke maner awe it to be in godde &thorn;at es abouene hyme, &thorn;at es to say,
&thorn;at in godde es myghte, and of &thorn;at commes his wysdome, and of powere and
wysedome bathe comes lufe.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at of &thorn;e fyrste person&macr;e commes &thorn;e to&thorn;er, and owte of thayme bathe comes &thorn;e thyrde, ffor-thi calles he &thorn;e firste person&macr;e godde &thorn;e ffadire, &thorn;e to&thorn;er godde &thorn;e Sonne, &thorn;e thirde godde &thorn;e Haly gaste.  And for &thorn;at it [was] wonnte to be thus in-manges mene, &thorn;at &thorn;e ffadir was mare ffebill &thorn;an &thorn;e sonne for his elde, and &thorn;e sonne mare vnwyse &thorn;an &thorn;e ffadire for his &yogh;outhe,


<PB N="1: 239">

and for &thorn;at a man sulde noghte wene &thorn;at it ware swa of godde: thare-fore es
powere appropirde to godde &thorn;e ffadir, wysdome to godde &thorn;e Sonne; and for-&thorn;i &thorn;at
&thorn;is worde Gaste sownnes sumwhate in to fellenes, ffor-&thorn;i es swetnes, lufe, and
gudenes appropirde to &thorn;e Haly gaste.  Oppone &thorn;is maner commes mane firste to &thorn;e
knaweynge of his godde, how he es with-owttene begynnynge, and whi he es
called godde, ane in substance and thre in persones, and whi &thorn;e firste persone es
callede godde &thorn;e ffadir, &thorn;e to&thorn;er, godde &thorn;e sonne, &thorn;e thyrde godde &thorn;e haly gaste,
and whi powere es appropirde to godde &thorn;e ffadir, &amp; wysdome to godde &thorn;e sonne,
and gudnes to godde &thorn;e haly gaste.  In swylke manere sall &thorn;ou knawe &thorn;i godde.
[XXIX.] ... The fyrste degre of contemplacione es, &thorn;at &thorn;e saule be ledde agayne to
&thorn;e selfe, and gedire it all with-In &thorn;e selfe.  The to&thorn;er degre es, &thorn;at man see whate
he es swa gedyrde to-gedire.  The thirde degre es, &thorn;at he lefte hym-selfe abouen
hym-selfe, and payne hym for to luke one his godde in his awene kynde.  Bot till [&thorn;e]
selfe may he neuer-mare comme, vn-till he hafe lerede to re[freine] ilke a bodyly
ymagynacyone erthely and gastely &thorn;at commes to his awene herte ow&thorn;er of herynge
or of tastynge or of sweloynge or of any o&thorn;er bodily wite, to refuse it and to
defule it, &thorn;at it may see the selfe swylke as it es with-owttene &thorn;e bodye.  &para;
Tharefore, dere ffrende, take gud hede how &thorn;e saule es wondirfull in &thorn;e selfe: and
howe it es ane in &thorn;e kynde, and noghte-forthi &yogh;it it duse dyuerse thynges: ffor
&thorn;e selfe, it sese &thorn;at at &thorn;ou sese with thyne eghne, heris with thyne eres, swelowes
with thi mouthe, smelles with &thorn;i nese, and alswa &thorn;at at &thorn;ou touches with all &thorn;i
membris.  &para; Thynke &yogh;it Eftyrwarde howe &thorn;i saule es grete, &thorn;at all-anely with a
thoghte it may comprehende heuene and erthe and all &thorn;at in thayme are, if &thorn;ay
ware a hundreth falde grettere &thorn;ane &thorn;ay are or may be.  &para; When manes [saule] es
[swa] grete and swa nobill &thorn;at na creature may vndirstande it perfitly: thane grete
and nobill es he &thorn;at swa nobill thynge made of noghte!  He es abouene all thynge,
and with-In all thynge, and with-owttene all thynge, and be-nethe all thynge.
He es abouene all thynge, all thynge gouernande; be-nethe all thynge, berande all
thynge; with-in all thynge, ffulfillande all; with-owttene all thynge, abowte-gangande
all.  &para; Swylke manere of contemplacione Engendyrs in mane ffaste trouthe and
sekire deuocyone.  &para; Eftir &thorn;is sall &thorn;ou thynke howe &thorn;at he es large; ant &thorn;at may
&thorn;ou see one many maners.  See at &thorn;e begynnynge howe &thorn;at he es large of
erthely gude, how he gyfes his gudes als wele to &thorn;e ille als to &thorn;e gude, in alle
thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ou sese in erthe.  Sythene efterwarde see howe &thorn;at he es large for
to fforgyffe; ffor if a mane hym ane hade donne alls mekill ille als alle &thorn;e men of
&thorn;is werlde moghte doo, &yogh;itt sulde he be mare redy be &thorn;e hundrethe parte for
to fforgyffe hym, &thorn;an &thorn;at caytife sulde bee for to aske of hym forgyfenes ....
[XXX.] &para; Nowe, my dere ffrende, if &thorn;ou lyfe Efter &thorn;is kennynge, &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou lyfe
honourabily: and &thorn;at es &thorn;e fyrste parte of oure sermone &thorn;at I touchede at &thorn;e
begynnynge.  &para; And eftir &thorn;at sall &thorn;ou studye to lyffe lufely, als to thyne euencrystene, and vntill &thorn;at sall &thorn;ou sette all hally &thorn;i myghte to lufe and for to be lufede. Thou sall lufe all mene in godde, &thorn;at es at say, anely in gudnes, and noghte for
&thorn;aire fairenes of bodye for to lufe, ne for force, ne for na no&thorn;er bodily vertu;
ffor &thorn;ay &thorn;at lufes in swylke manere, &thorn;ay lufe noghte for goddes sake; and for to
lufe mane in godde, es na no&thorn;er thynge bot for to lufe hyme for any thynge &thorn;at
may noghte be lufede with-owttene godde, als for gudnes or for rightewysnes or


<PB N="1: 240">

for sothefastenes.  If we [be] gude, &thorn;ane hafe we na frende bot gude, ne nane
Enemy bot ill, and &thorn;ar-fore &thorn;ase &thorn;at er gude sall we lufe for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ay er
gude, and &thorn;e ille sall we lufe for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ay may be gude: in &thorn;is manere lufe[s]
&thorn;ou nathynge bot gudnes, sene &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes all thynges for gudnes.  And if &thorn;ou
will be lufede, schewe thi-selfe lufely.  Ife &thorn;ou will be lufely, resayfe these thre
wordes with-owttene forgetynge: Do &thorn;at at man biddis &thorn;e or praies &thorn;e &thorn;at gude
es; Take &thorn;at at mane gyffes &thorn;e and gruche noghte; And &thorn;at at men will say &thorn;e,
suffire it mekely and wrethe the noghte.  If &thorn;ou lyfe thus lelely, &thorn;an lyfes thou
lufely.  &para; Dere syster and frende, s[i]&thorn;ene eftirwarde sall &thorn;ou studye for to lyffe
mekely.  And to &thorn;is sall &thorn;ou cwne wit &thorn;at &thorn;are are twa maners of mekenes.  The
tane commes of sothefastenes, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er commes of charite.  &THORN;e firste may &thorn;ou
hafe [by] knaweynge of thi-selfe: ffor thou may noghte in na manere of &thorn;is werlde
see &thorn;i-selfe whate &thorn;ou artte in sothefastenes, if &thorn;ou be noghte mekyde.  The to&thorn;er
manere of meknes may &thorn;ou hafe if thou thynke of &thorn;e meknes of Ihesu Criste, how
&thorn;at he mekid hym &thorn;at neuer dyde syne; and swylke mekenes commes clenely of
charyte.  &para; Now, my dere syster and ffrende, wate &thorn;ou whate it es to lyffe honourabili,
lufely, and mekely: and &thorn;at es to lyffe perfitly.  &para; Now oure swete lorde Ihesu Criste
gyffe vs grace swa godde for to honour, and oure euenecristene for to lufe, and
oureselfe for to meke, &thorn;at we may for oure honourynge be honourede, and for oure lufe
be lufede, and for oure mekenes be lyftede vp in to &thorn;e heghe blysse of heuene,
&thorn;at he boghte vs to Ihesu with his swete blude and his preciouse passione.  Amen.
</P></DIV4><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit speculum sancti Edmundi cantuariensis Archiepiscopi.
Dulce nomen domini nostri Ihesu Christi sit benedictum in secula seculorum.  Amen.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>
