<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>How Mon schal loken his staat.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum primum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E word of &thorn;e Apostele ffalle&thorn; to Men of Religion and to alle gode cristene
men: &laquo;Seo&thorn; &thorn;e stat wherto &yogh;e beo&thorn; clept&raquo;.  &THORN;is he sei&thorn;, ffor to drawe vs to perfeccion.  And &thorn;erfore, what-time I &thorn;enke on my-self, bi day or bi niht, on on half I haue gret Ioye, and on a no&thorn;ur half gret Serwe.  Ioye, for &thorn;e grete
Religion and godnesse &thorn;at he ha&thorn; schewed to me and to Monkynde; Serwe, for
&thorn;e wikked liuinge in me, and feble conuersacion.  For whi?  &thorn;us sei&thorn; Eusebie
in a Sarmoun: &laquo;Cum to Religion, is a souereyn perfeccion; not parfytliche liuen
is a souereyn da[m]pnacion&raquo;.  &THORN;erfore &thorn;e beste &thorn;ing is whose liue&thorn; in Religion,
drawe he to &thorn;e lyf of perfeccion as he wilne&thorn; his sauacion, and leue al &thorn;at is
in &thorn;e world &amp; al &thorn;at &thorn;er-to falle&thorn;, and &yogh;iue al his power to liue parfyt lyf.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>What is to liuen parfyt lyf.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum secundum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Parfytliche liuen, as seint Bernard sei&thorn;, is to liuen Honorabliche,
Loueredenliche, and Mekeliche.  Honurabliche as to God, &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;iue &thorn;in entent to don
his wille, &thorn;at is to siggen to don alle &thorn;e dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt don wi&thorn; honden,
&thorn;enken wi&thorn; herte, or speken wi&thorn; Mou&thorn;, to honour of God, and nou&yogh;t a&yogh;eyn
his wille don wi&thorn; eny of &thorn;i fiue wittes, as wi&thorn; Si&yogh;t of e&yogh;en, Herynge of Eren,
Swolewynge of Tonge, Smellynge of Neose, Touchynge of honden, Gon or
stonden, Liggen or sitten.  &THORN;enk at &thorn;e biginnyng of euerich &thorn;ing, &yogh;if hit beo
godes wille or hit beo not.  &YOGH;if hit beo his wille, do hit wi&thorn; al &thorn;i mi&yogh;t.  &YOGH;if
hit beo nou&yogh;t, do hit not ffor to suffre de&thorn;. / But now wol men aske: &laquo;What
is godes wille?&raquo;  His wille nis non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing bote vre holynesse; and &thorn;at sei&thorn;
&thorn;e Apostle: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hec est voluntas dei: sanctificacio vestra,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to seyen: &laquo;Godus wille is &thorn;at we ben holi&raquo;.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>What &thorn;ing make&thorn; mon holi.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum III.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Two &thorn;inges wi&thorn;-outen mo make&thorn; mon holi, &thorn;at is to witen Knowynge and
Loue.  Knowynge of so&thorn;nesse, and Loue of godnesse.  But to knowyng of God
&thorn;at is so&thorn;nesse, ne mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou not comen but &thorn;orw knowynge of &thorn;i-self; no to
&thorn;e loue of God &thorn;at is goodnesse, ne mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou not comen bot &thorn;orw loue of &thorn;i
nei&yogh;ebore.  To &thorn;e knowyng of &thorn;y-self mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou comen wi&thorn; ofte &thorn;enkynge; to
&thorn;e knowyng of God: wi&thorn; clene contemplacion.  To &thorn;e knowynge of
&thorn;i-self &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t comen in &thorn;is Manere: &THORN;enk inwardliche and ofte what &thorn;ou art, what &thorn;ou were, and what &thorn;ou schalt ben.  Furst as to &thorn;i bodi, after as to &thorn;i soule.


<PB N="1: 242">

As to &thorn;i bodi: &thorn;ou art vilore &thorn;en a dongehul.  &THORN;ou were geten in so gret ful&thorn;e
&thorn;at hit is schome to seye, and wlatful to &thorn;enken.  &THORN;ou scha[l]t be mete to fyle
todes and wormes.  What &thorn;ou hast ben and what &thorn;ou art, nou take god hede
as to &thorn;i soule&mdash;what &thorn;ou schalt ben, ne mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou not &thorn;enken.  &THORN;enk &thorn;at &thorn;ow
hast don gret wikkednesses and monye, and leued mony godnesses and grete.
&THORN;enk hou longe &thorn;ou hast liued, and how mony goodnesses &thorn;ou hast receyued,
and hou &thorn;ou hast hem spendet; ffor whi?  eueri houre &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast not &thorn;ou&yogh;t on
god, &thorn;ou hast forloren.  &THORN;ou schalt &yogh;elde reson of eueri idel word and eueri Idel
&thorn;ouht and eueri Idel dede; and also &thorn;er nis not an her on &thorn;in hed &thorn;at ne schal
ben glorifyed &yogh;if hit be so &thorn;at &thorn;ou be saaf, also &thorn;er ne schal
a-skapen non houre &thorn;at ne schal be rikned to &thorn;e.  A, Ihesu, Merci!  &YOGH;if al &thorn;e world weore ful of smale pouder, who mi&yogh;te ben so slei&yogh; &thorn;at mi&yogh;te departen vche [mot] bi him-self and taken from o&thorn;er?  Certes, non.  And &thorn;e soule of Mon is grettore &thorn;en al
&thorn;e world, &thorn;ei&yogh; hit were a &thorn;ousend to gret; and is al ful of diuerse &thorn;ou&yogh;tes,
willes and desyres; who mi&yogh;te &thorn;enne so sechen his herte &thorn;at [he] mi&yogh;te knowen
al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; don and &thorn;ou&yogh;t?  Se now, goode Bro&thorn;er, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast gret
mester to knowyng of &thorn;i-self.  Aftur tac good hede what &thorn;ou art now as to &thorn;i
soule.  &THORN;ou hast luitel good in &thorn;e, luitel wit, or streng&thorn;e: for whi?  &thorn;ou
desyrest al day &thorn;at &thorn;e helpe&thorn; nou&yogh;t, and seldene or no tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e may helpen.
&THORN;ou art often deceyued, now &thorn;orw [to] grete serwe, now &thorn;orw veyne glorie; now
art &thorn;ow trauayled of fere, now artou houen an hei&yogh; &thorn;orw fals hope.  On o&thorn;er
half &thorn;ou art so chaungeable, &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt to-day &thorn;ou wolt not to-morwe.
And also &thorn;enk what-maner &thorn;ou art bisi and turmented aboute mony &thorn;inges &yogh;if
&thorn;ou hem ne haue; and whonne &thorn;ou hem hast, &thorn;en artou anuyed and ful of hem.
&THORN;enk &yogh;it on o&thorn;ur maner &thorn;at &thorn;ou art liht to tempten, and feble forte
&yogh;eynstonden, and redi to concenten.  Of alle &thorn;eose wikkednesses &thorn;e ha&thorn; delyuered
&thorn;i swete lord, &amp; schal delyueren eueri day more and more, &yogh;if &thorn;ou hit not fordo.

</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e godnesse of vre lord, &amp; hou mon schal spenden his tyme <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap. IIII.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Whonne &thorn;ou were nouht, &thorn;enne he made &thorn;e, in soule after his owne liknesse,
and &thorn;i bodi of foul roten and stinkinde fom, &thorn;at is abhominacion to &thorn;enken.  He
made &thorn;i wittes and &thorn;i Membres so noble and so feire &thorn;at no mon may deuysen.
&THORN;enk &yogh;it inwardliche, &thorn;ou &thorn;at louest &thorn;i fader and &thorn;i Moder so tenderliche, and
whi &thorn;ou louest hem so derwor&thorn;lich.  &yogh;if &thorn;ou sigge &thorn;at &thorn;ou louest &thorn;i ffader and
&thorn;i Moder for &thorn;ou art geten of heore flesch and of heore blood: also ben &thorn;e
wormes &thorn;at waxen of hem eueri day.  On o&thorn;ur halue &thorn;ou hast of hem nei&thorn;er
bodi ne soule, but of god &thorn;orw hem; for whi?  what were &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;ou heddest
dwelled in &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast of hem, whon &thorn;ou weore geten in ful&thorn;e and in synne?
On o&thorn;ur half, &yogh;if &thorn;ou louest Bro&thorn;ur or Suster or kin for &thorn;ei ben of &thorn;e selue
flesch or blod &thorn;at &thorn;ou art: [wi&thorn;] &thorn;e selue skile scholdest &thorn;ou louen a pece of
&thorn;e flesch of ffader or Moder &yogh;if hit were awei coruen; and &thorn;at were a gret
wodnesse out of mesure!  &YOGH;if &thorn;ow sigge &thorn;at &thorn;ou louest hem for &thorn;ei han &thorn;e flesch
formed in liknesse of mon, and for &thorn;ei han soule as hast &thorn;ou: &thorn;enne is &thorn;i fleschlyche
bro&thorn;ur no nerre &thorn;en a no&thorn;er, but in as muche as &thorn;ou and he han of on
fleschlich fader &thorn;e biginnyng of &yogh;oure flesch, &thorn;at is, a luytel stunch and ful&thorn;e.


<PB N="1: 243">

Loue him &thorn;enne ffrom whom alle goodes comen; and loue alle men gostliche,
and stunte herbi-forward to louen fleschliche.  &YOGH;if &thorn;ou &thorn;enke inwardliche of &thorn;e
goodnes &thorn;at he ha&thorn; do &thorn;e, and schal do &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt loue him enterliche, hit
schal sture &thorn;e him to loue &thorn;e more hertiliche.  For whi?  as I haue
i-seid bifore, whon &thorn;ou ne were, he made &thorn;e of nou&yogh;t: and whonne &thorn;ou were loren,
he sou&yogh;te &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou weore sold to synne, he bou&yogh;te &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou weore
dampned, he sauede &thorn;e.  Whon &thorn;ou were boren in synne, he cristnede &thorn;e; and
afturward whon &thorn;ou sungedest so ofte and so foule, &thorn;enne he suffrede &thorn;e so
freoli &amp; abod longe, and receyuede &thorn;e to his merci, and &thorn;e putte &thorn;orw his
grace in to his swete couent.  And eueri day, whon &thorn;ou dost mis, he snibbe&thorn;
&thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou sungest, he for&yogh;iue&thorn; hit &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou doutest, &thorn;en he teche&thorn;
&thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou errest, he a-Mende&thorn; &thorn;e.  Whon &thorn;ou hungrest, he fede&thorn; &thorn;e;
whon &thorn;ou art cold, he hete&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou hast hete, he kele&thorn; &thorn;e.  Whon &thorn;ow
wakest, he saue&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou slepest, he loke&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou risest, he
susteyne&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou wost fallen, he redresse&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou sittest, he
abyde&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou gost, he lede&thorn; &thorn;e; whon &thorn;ou turnest, he went &thorn;e.  Whon
&thorn;ou gost mis, he a&yogh;eyn-calle&thorn; &thorn;e; and euere whon &thorn;ou art vuel at ese, he
comforte&thorn; &thorn;e.  &THORN;eose godes, and mony mo, vre swete lord ha&thorn; don to &thorn;e.
Wherfore in swetnesse of &thorn;in herte &thorn;ou schalt euere on him &thorn;enke, of him speke,
him &thorn;onken, him preisen, niht and day, &yogh;if &thorn;ow const ouht of loue.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>How &thorn;at Mon schal spenden his tyme.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum quintum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Furst, whon &thorn;ou risest of &thorn;i bed in Morwe-tyde and at Mid-niht, &thorn;enk hou mony
&thorn;ousend Men han ben perisch &thorn;at niht in bodi and soule, summe in fuir and summe
in water, [summe] in [o&thorn;er] diuerse manere as in s&eacute;&eacute; and in lond; summe Robbede
and summe I-woundede, summe slayn, summe dede sodeynliche wi&thorn;-outen schrift,
wherfore &thorn;ei be fallen in to peyne wi&thorn;-outen ende.  &THORN;enk also how mony
&thorn;ousend men ben fallen &thorn;at niht in to peril of soule, &thorn;at is to siggen in to dedly
synne, as in Lecherie, Couetyse, and in o&thorn;ur mony-maner folyes.  Of alle &thorn;eose
wikkednesses &thorn;e ha&thorn; dilyuered vre swete lord, wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;i diseruyng.  For whi?
what seruise hastou do to him wherfore he ha&thorn; so loked &thorn;e, &amp; mony o&thorn;ure
forsaken &amp; laft?  &YOGH;if &thorn;ou take good hede hou gret good god ha&thorn; don to &thorn;e
on alle halue, &thorn;ou schalt fynden him ocupyed abouten &thorn;e as &thorn;ei he dude non
o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing but were tendynge onliche to &thorn;e and to &thorn;in hele; and &thorn;ou schalt
seon him, for to loken &thorn;e, al so tentyf and bisi as he hedde for&yogh;eten al &thorn;e
world for to taken kepe onliche in &thorn;e.  And whonne &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ouht &thorn;us, tak
vp &thorn;in hond and &thorn;onke &thorn;i lord of &thorn;is and of alle o&thorn;ur goodnesse, in &thorn;is manere:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Gracias tibi ago, domine Ihesu Christe, qui me miserum &thorn;eccatorem in hac nocte
custodi[sti], &thorn;rotexisti, visitasti, sanum, saluum, et [incolumem] ad hanc horam
&thorn;eruenire fecisti, et &thorn;ro vniuersis alijs beneficijs tuis, que michi tua sola bonitate
contulisti.  Qui cum &thorn;atre &amp; s. s. u. &amp; regnas deus:</FOREIGN>
</P><P>&laquo;&THORN;Onkynge I make to &thorn;e, my lord Ihesu Crist, &thorn;at me synful wrecche euer to
&thorn;is tyme lokedest, defendest, visytest, hol, saue and vnbroken to &thorn;is tyme
madest comen, and for alle &thorn;ine o&thorn;ure gode dedes &thorn;at to me &thorn;orw &thorn;in onliche
godnesse hast wrou&yogh;t; &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e ffader and &thorn;e holy gost liuest and regnest god
euermore wi&thorn;-outen ende.  A.M.E.N.  Amen.&raquo;
</P>

<PB N="1: 244">
<P>In &thorn;e selue manere schaltou seyen whon &thorn;ou risest in Morwe-tyde, and whon &thorn;ou
gost to bedde a-niht.  At Mid-niht &thorn;ou schal seyen <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">ad hanc horam</FOREIGN> &laquo;to &thorn;is houre&raquo;, but in Morwe-tyde &thorn;ou schalt seyen <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">ad principium huius diei</FOREIGN> &laquo;to &thorn;e begynnynge of &thorn;is dai&raquo;, and at niht <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">ad finem huius diei</FOREIGN> &laquo;to &thorn;e endynge of &thorn;is dai&raquo;. / And whon &thorn;ou hast don &thorn;us, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken inwardliche hou &thorn;ou hast dispendet &thorn;e tyme from morwe-tyde &thorn;at &thorn;ou ros til &thorn;ou go to bedde a-niht; and also from &thorn;i liggynge to &thorn;i rysynge; and preye god Merci of &thorn;e wikkednesses &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don, and of &thorn;e godes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast leued &thorn;at dai, or &thorn;at niht; and do no &thorn;ing to &thorn;is lyf, til &thorn;ou haue bitaken &thorn;i-self and &thorn;i frendes, quike and dede, in to &thorn;e hondes of vre swete lord Ihesu Crist, &amp; sei &thorn;us:
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In manus tuas, domine, et sanctorum angelorum tuorum comendo in hac die animam
meam &amp; corpus meum, parentes, fratres sorores, cognatos, amicos, familiares,
benefactores meos, et omnem populum chatholicum.  custodi nos in hac die, per Merita &amp; intercessionem beate Marie &amp; omnium sanctorum, a vicijs &amp; concupiscencijs prauis,
temptacionibus diaboli, a subitanea &amp; inprouisa morte, &amp; a penis inferni.  illumina
cor meum de spiritu sancto et de tua sancta gracia, fac me tuis semper obedire
mandatis, et a te nunquam separari permittas.  Qui viuis &amp; regnas deus per omnia
s[ecula] seculorum.  Amen.</FOREIGN>
</P><P>&laquo;IN to &thorn;in hond, lord, and of &thorn;yn holy Angeles I beo-take in &thorn;is dai my soule
and my bodi, ffader and Moder, Bre&thorn;eren Sustren, Sibbe and frende, and alle
myne gode-doeres, and alle cristene folk.  Loke vs to-day, &thorn;orw &thorn;e meede and
&thorn;e preyeres of blessed Marie and of alle halewes, from vices and wikkede
couetises, fondynges of &thorn;e deuel, and from sodeyn and vn-war de&thorn;, and from &thorn;e
peynes of helle.  Lihte myn herte of &thorn;e holigost and of &thorn;in holi grace, make me
euer-more Boxum to &thorn;i comaundemens, and neuere suffre me be parted from
&thorn;e; &thorn;at liuest and regnest god wi&thorn;-outen ende.  Amen.&raquo;
</P><P>And whon &thorn;ou gost to bedde at niht, &thorn;er as &thorn;ou seist in &thorn;e Morwetide <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In hac die</FOREIGN> &laquo;in &thorn;is day&raquo;, sei &thorn;enne <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In hac nocte</FOREIGN> &laquo;in &thorn;is ni&yogh;t&raquo;. / &YOGH;if &thorn;ou do in &thorn;is manere, &thorn;enne schaltou hauen trewe knowyng of &thorn;i-self.  For whi? &thorn;us sei&thorn; &thorn;e holi [writ]: &laquo;&yogh;if &thorn;ou affye &thorn;e o &thorn;i-self, &thorn;ou schalt be delyuered to &thorn;i-self; &yogh;if &thorn;ou affye &thorn;e in god, &thorn;ou schalt be taken to god&raquo;.  &THORN;is Manere of consideracion of &thorn;i-self, and in &thorn;is &thorn;enkyng schalt &thorn;ow come to &thorn;e knowyng of God.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Whuche-Manere Mon schal knowe God in eueri Creature.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap.  sextum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;reo Maners ben of Contemplacion: &thorn;e ffurste is in Creatures, &thorn;e secounde
in Holy writ, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde in God self and in his kuynde.  Contemplacion nis non
o&thorn;er &thorn;ing but siht of &thorn;e godnesse of god.  &THORN;e goodnesse of god in his
creatures, &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t se in &thorn;is Manere.  &THORN;reo &thorn;inges ben in god: Miht, Wisdam, and
Godnesse.  Miht is turned to god &thorn;e Fader, Wisdam to god &thorn;e Sone, Goodnesse
to god &thorn;e Holigost.  &THORN;orw his Miht, ben alle &thorn;inges formed, &thorn;orw his Wisdam
ben wonderliche ordeynet, &thorn;orw his Goodnesse ben eueri day Multiplyede.  His
miht maihtou seon &thorn;orw heore gretnesse and &thorn;orw heore formyng, his Wisdam
mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou sen &thorn;orw heore feirnesse and &thorn;orw heore ordynaunce, his Godnesse
&thorn;orw heore vertues and &thorn;orw heore multipliing.  His Mihte &thorn;orw heore gretnesse
mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou seon in heore foure departynges, &thorn;at is to witene, &thorn;orw heore hei&yogh;nesse,


<PB N="1: 245">

and heore depnesse, and &thorn;oru heore brodenesse, and heore longenesse.  His
Wisdam mai&yogh;t &thorn;ow sen &yogh;if &thorn;ou take good heede how he ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen to eueri
creature beoing: To summe, beoing wi&thorn;-oute more, as to stones; to summe beoing
and liuing, as to treon; to summe beoing, liuing, and felyng, as to beestes;
to summe being, liuing, felyng, and vnderstonding, as to Angeles and to Mon.
[Stones] hauen beoing, but &thorn;ei nei&thorn;er liuen, felen, ne vnderstonden.  Herbes
hauen beoing &amp; liuing but &thorn;ei felen not].  Beestes ben, liuen, and felen, but
&thorn;e[i] haue no resoun.  Men haue beoinge wi&thorn; stones, Liuynge wi&thorn; herbes, ffelynge
wi&thorn; Beestes, Resoun wi&thorn; Angeles.  &THORN;us &thorn;ou maiht seon &thorn;e dignite of Monkuynde&mdash;
and &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Austin: &laquo;I wolde not haue &thorn;e godnesse of Angel, and I
mihte haue &thorn;e goodnesse &thorn;at is ordeyned to Mon&raquo;.  &THORN;enk also &thorn;at Mon is wor&thorn;i
gret confusion &thorn;at wol not liuen as his condicion aske&thorn; in his degre.  For whi?
alle &thorn;e creatures of &thorn;is world ben maad onliche for Mon, ffor &thorn;reo enchesons:
ffor to helpen vs of trauayle, ffor to clo&thorn;en vs, ffor to feeden vs.  &THORN;e nuyaunt
Creatures, as wikkede herbes and venimouse beestes, ben maad for &thorn;reo &thorn;inges:
ffor vre chastyng, ffor vre amendyng, ffor vre teching.  We ben punissched
and chastised whon we ben hurt: and &thorn;at is a gret Merci [of god], &thorn;at he wole
chastisen vs now in bodi, &thorn;at we beo not wi&thorn;-outen ende punissched in soule.
We ben amendet whon we &thorn;enken &thorn;at al &thorn;is is comen vs &thorn;orw vre sunne; ffor
whi? whon we sen &thorn;at so luitel creatures mowen vs greuen, &thorn;enne we &thorn;enken
on vre feblesse, &amp; ben meke.  We ben tau&yogh;t in &thorn;at &thorn;at we seon in suche
creatures &thorn;e wonder werkes of vre Creatour; ffor more edificacion to vs is &thorn;e trauayle
of &thorn;e nuy&yogh;ere &thorn;en &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of &thorn;e Beore or of &thorn;e Lyoun.  Also as is seid
of Beestes, also vndurstond of herbes; and whon &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ou&yogh;t of &thorn;eose
Creatures, hef vp &thorn;in herte to &thorn;i creatour, and &thorn;enk &thorn;at hit is gret power to maken
such &thorn;inges of nou&yogh;t, and gret wisdam to ordeynen hem, and gret goodnesse to
encresen hem eueri day in to so gret noumbre.  Sei to &thorn;i lord &thorn;erfore in &thorn;in
herte: &laquo;For &thorn;ou art, &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei ben; ffor &thorn;ou art feir, &thorn;erfore are &thorn;ei feir; ffor &thorn;ou art good, &thorn;erfore are &thorn;ei goode.  Wi&thorn; good riht &thorn;e honouren alle creatures,
&thorn;ei herien, &thorn;ei glorifyen for heo[re] prow, blessed God in Trinite!  Of whom ben
alle &thorn;inges &thorn;orw his pouwer maade, and gouernede &thorn;orw his wisdam, &amp; &thorn;orw
his bounte multipliede.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ipsi honor &amp; gloria in secula s.  amen.</FOREIGN>&raquo;
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>How Mon mai seo Godes wille in Holi writ.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E secounde degre of Contemplacion is in Holi writ.  But nou schalt &thorn;ou asken
&thorn;at art of luitel lettrure: &laquo;On what manere mi&yogh;t I euere comen to contemplacion
of holi writ?&raquo;
</P><P>Now vnderstond and I schal telle &thorn;e.  &yogh;if &thorn;ou konst not vndurstonde &thorn;at is
writen: here ble&thorn;eliche &thorn;e gode &thorn;at mon sei&thorn;.  Whon &thorn;ou herest out of holi writ,
in a comuyne prechinge or in priue seyinge: tak hede anon &yogh;if &thorn;ou herest ou&yogh;t
&thorn;at mai auayle &thorn;e to edificacion, to hate synne and loue vertues, and doute peyne
and desiren ioye, to dispisen &thorn;is world, touward &thorn;e to&thorn;ur hi&yogh;en, what &thorn;ou
schalt don and what &thorn;ou schal leuen, and al &thorn;at mai lihten &thorn;in vnderstondynge,
in knowynge of so&thorn;nesse, and al &thorn;at warme&thorn; &thorn;i wille [&] affeccion, in hete of
charite; ffor whi? of &thorn;eose two goodes ben al &thorn;at is writen in holi writ, priueli


<PB N="1: 246">

or aperteli.  Out of holiwrit &thorn;ou schalt witen and knowen w&yogh;uche ben &thorn;e
seuene dedliche synnes, &amp; heore Braunches; &thorn;e seuene blessynges of &thorn;e Ewangelie;
&thorn;e seuene &yogh;iftus of &thorn;e holigost; Godes ten Comaundemens; &thorn;e seuene vertues:
Be-leeue, Hope, Loue, Qweyntise, Riht, Atemprenesse, and Streng&thorn;e; &thorn;e twelue
articles of &thorn;e be-leeue; &thorn;e seuene Sacramens; seuene dedes of Merci; seuene
preieres of &thorn;e Pater noster; &thorn;e seuene druweries in bodi, &amp; seuene in soule; &thorn;e
seuene peynes of helle, and Ioyes of heuene.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E seuene dedli synnes ben &thorn;eose: Pruide, Wra&thorn;&thorn;e, Envye, Accidie, Couetise,
Glotonie, and Lecherie.  Pruide is loue of oune hei&yogh;nesse; of him waxen &thorn;eose
seuene Braunches: Vnbuxumnesse a&yogh;eyn God and a&yogh;eyn Souereyn, &thorn;at is to
siggen: leuen &thorn;at is comaundet, or don &thorn;at is defendet.  &THORN;e secunde is
Auauntynge: whon a Mon a-vaunte&thorn; him of good &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of a no&thorn;er, or of an
vuel &thorn;at he ha&thorn; of him-self.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde is Ypocrisye: whon mon make&thorn; him
hauen good &thorn;at he ha&thorn; nouht, and hut &thorn;e wikkednesse &thorn;at he ha&thorn;.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e
is Despit: whon a mon blame&thorn; a no&thorn;eres godnesse, for him-self scholde seme
&thorn;e betere.  &THORN;e .v. is Arrogauns: whon mon make&thorn; comparison bitwene his
wikkednesse and an o&thorn;ures, so &thorn;at his may semen &thorn;e lasse.  &THORN;e .vi. is Boldnesse: whon
he ha&thorn; no schome of open synne.  &THORN;e seuen&thorn;e is Elacion: whon Mon Ioye&thorn;
of his wikkednesse.  &THORN;reo &thorn;inges ben wher-of mon ha&thorn; pruide: of godes &thorn;at he
ha&thorn; of kuynde, as ffeirnesse, streng&thorn;e, god wit, cunrade.  &THORN;e secounde, of godes
&thorn;at he ha&thorn; of purchas, as science, vertues, good loos, grace, or dignite.  &THORN;e
&thorn;ridde is, of worldliche godes, as clo&thorn;ing, housyng, Rentes, Meyne, horsyng and
o&thorn;er hauyng.&mdash;Off Envye [waxen]: ben glad of o&thorn;ures harm, and sori of o&thorn;ures
goode; and &thorn;at mai ben in herte &thorn;orw wille, or in Mou&thorn;e &thorn;orw detraccion, or in
dede &thorn;orw wi&thorn;-drawyng of gode or procuryng of vuel.  Off Ire waxen: manaces,
vileyne wordes, scornynges, &amp; Blasfemies.  Off Accidie waxen: heuinesse,
Malice, Whonhope, Necligence aboute godes comaundemens, bisi &thorn;ouht aboute
&thorn;inges defendet.  Off Couetyse wexen: tresouns, ffals o&thorn;es, feble reste, and hard
herte for to don dedes of Merci.  Off Glotenie waxen: veyn gladnesse, Lecherie,
ful&thorn;e, muche speche, and feble vnderstondyng.  Off Lecherie woxen: Blyndnesse
of herte, in preyeres vnstudefastnes, fol-hastinesse, loue of him-self, hate of god,
loue of &thorn;is world, fere and wonhope of &thorn;e world &thorn;at is to comen.  &THORN;eose ben
&thorn;e dedly synnes seuene; and wel ben I-callet dedly, ffor whi? &thorn;e &thorn;reo furste
despoylen &thorn;e synful wrecche, and &thorn;e feor&thorn;e falle&thorn; him doun, &thorn;e fyf&thorn;e caste&thorn; him out, &thorn;e sixte deceyue&thorn; him, &thorn;e seue&thorn;e puite&thorn; him in to vuel seruage.  For whi?
Pruide dispoyle&thorn; mon of God, Envye of his bro&thorn;er, Ire of him-seluen; Accidie
him falle&thorn;, Auarice &thorn;rowe&thorn; him out, Glotonye deseyue&thorn; him, Lecherie put him
in to &thorn;hraldam.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of seuene Blessynges of &thorn;e Ewangelye.</HEAD>

<P>REmedies a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes lei&thorn; vr lord Blessynges seuene in &thorn;e
Ewangelie, and sei&thorn; &thorn;us: &laquo;Blessed be &thorn;e meke of spirit, for heoren is &thorn;e ioye
of heuene&raquo;: &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyn Pruide, &thorn;at dispoyle&thorn; mon of god.  &laquo;Blessed be &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 247">

deboners, to his bro&thorn;er, for &thorn;ei schulen haue blessed er&thorn;e euerlastand&raquo;: &thorn;at is
a&yogh;eyn Envye, &thorn;at reue&thorn; from mon his bro&thorn;er.  &laquo;Blesset beo &thorn;ei &thorn;at wepen,
for &thorn;ei schulen be cumforted&raquo;: &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyn Wra&thorn;&thorn;e, &thorn;at bi-reue&thorn; mon him-self. &laquo;Blesset beo &thorn;e Merciful, &thorn;at han Merci of o&thorn;ure, for God wole haue Merci of hem&raquo;: &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyn Couetyse, &thorn;at ha&thorn; of no mon Merci ne pite.  &laquo;Blesset ben &thorn;ei &thorn;at han hunger aftur rihtfulnesse, for &thorn;ei schulen be fed&raquo;: &thorn;at is a&yogh;ein Slou&thorn;e and negligence.  &laquo;Blesset ben &thorn;ei &thorn;at han clannesse of herte, for &thorn;ei schullen seo &thorn;e face of god&raquo;: &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyn Glotonye, &thorn;at &thorn;enke&thorn; al-wey of ffleschliche lustes.  &laquo;Blessed ben &thorn;e peisybles, for &thorn;ei schulen be cald godes children&raquo;: &thorn;at is a&yogh;eyn Lecherie, for whi? lechour mai not han reste nor pees of herte.  A&yogh;ein Prude, Mon schal han in his herte and in his mou&thorn; and in his dedes, studefast mekenes.  A&yogh;eyn Envye, Ioye in herte of o&thorn;ur mennes wel-fare, and serwe of o&thorn;ures harm, and loue to alle men.  A&yogh;eyn Wra&thorn;&thorn;e, suffring and symplenes. A&yogh;ein Sleu&thorn;e, li&yogh;t herte in godes seruise and in alle goode dedes.  A&yogh;eyn Couetyse, &yogh;iuynge wi&thorn; gode herte to pore men.  A&yogh;eyn Lecherie, Chastite of bodi, of herte, of tonge, of ei&yogh;e.  A&yogh;eyn Glotonye, Mesure of him-seluen, in Mete and
drinke, nomeliche of drinke, ffor &thorn;orw to muche drink mony mon ha&thorn; losen his
lyf, and mony Maiden hire Maidenhod; of hit come&thorn; mony o&thorn;ur wikkednesses.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene &yogh;iftes of &thorn;e holigost.</HEAD>

<P>NOw &thorn;ou hast seuene Manere seknesses, and heore medecynes,.  [After
come&thorn; &thorn;e souereyn leche and take&thorn; his medecynes], &thorn;at sauen mon from &thorn;e
seuene vices and confermen him in [&thorn;e] seuene vertues, &thorn;orw &thorn;e &yogh;ifte[s] of &thorn;e
holigost, &thorn;at ben &thorn;eose: &THORN;e spirit of wit, and of vnderstondynge, &THORN;e spirit of
counseil, and of streng&thorn;e, &THORN;e spirit of connynge, and of pite, &THORN;e spirit of drede
of god.  &THORN;orw &thorn;eose seuene &yogh;iftes teche&thorn; vre lord what mon ha&thorn; mester [of] to &thorn;e
lyf bodilyche and to &thorn;e lyf gostliche.  And seo in what manere.  Furst mon moot
leue wikkednesse: and &thorn;at vs teche&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of drede of god; and do &thorn;e goode:
&thorn;at vs teche&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of pite.  And for tweyne &thorn;inges ben &thorn;at lette&thorn; mon to
don good, &thorn;at is to witen Weole and Wo of &thorn;is world&mdash;Weole wi&thorn;-halt him
wi&thorn; faytinge, Wo, wi&thorn; hardnes: &thorn;erfore, &thorn;ou schalt dispisen &thorn;e weole of &thorn;is
world, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not disseyued: and &thorn;at &thorn;e teche&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of cunnynge; and
&thorn;ou schalt suffren hardnesse, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not ouercomen: and &thorn;at &thorn;e teche&thorn; &thorn;e
spirit of streng&thorn;e.  &THORN;eose foure suffisen to &thorn;e lyf bodiliche.  &THORN;e o&thorn;ure fallen to
&thorn;e lyf gostliche.  For whi? &thorn;reo Maners ben of contemplacion: on in Creatures,
and &thorn;at teche&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of vnderstondyng; ano&thorn;ur in Holi writ, where &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t
seo what is to don &amp; what &thorn;ou schalt not don: and &thorn;at &thorn;e teche&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of
counseil; and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde maner is in God self: &thorn;at &thorn;e teche&thorn; &thorn;e spirit of wit.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e ten Comaundemens and of heore Sufficience.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E ffur[s]te Comaundement is: &thorn;at Mon schal wi&thorn; gret Mekenes seruen and
honouren God ouer alle &thorn;ing.  &THORN;e secunde is: &thorn;at mon schal not taken Godes nome
in veyn, in Idel o&thorn;es; Monnes speche schal ben to o&thorn;ur &laquo;Hit Is, Hit Is; Hit
nis, Hit nis: &YOGH;e &YOGH;e, Nai Nay&raquo;.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde Comaundement is: &thorn;at Mon schal
halewe his hali-day, wi&thorn; holy werkes: heren deuoutliche wi&thorn;-outen Iangeling


<PB N="1: 248">

Masse and Matins and o&thorn;er houres, and not leuen to rysen, for no colde ne
for no sleep ne for no swot&mdash;ffor &thorn;e more gref &thorn;at mon ha&thorn; to risen, &thorn;e more
schal ben his meede &yogh;if he rise; and whon &thorn;ou art at &thorn;i mete, of such goodes
as God ha&thorn; &thorn;e lent &yogh;if ble&thorn;eliche &thorn;erof to &thorn;e pore, and after Mete &thorn;onke God
of alle his gode &yogh;iftes; and afturward not gon to tauerne nor to wrastelynges
nor to Carolynges, nor to o&thorn;ur veyn pleyes of vanite&mdash;ffor of such pleyes comen
ofte mis-happes and dedly synnes. / &THORN;eose &thorn;reo Comaundemens ordeyne&thorn;
mon and teche&thorn; hou he schal hauen him a-nontes god in trinite, to whos
liknesse he is formed in soule.  &THORN;e to&thorn;ure seuene ordeyne&thorn; mon and teche&thorn; hou he
schal hauen him anentes his bro&thorn;ur.  &THORN;e ffurste is: &laquo;&thorn;ou schalt honouren Fader
and Moder&raquo;, ffleschliche and gostliche, In twei maneres: &thorn;ou schalt bouwe to
heom &amp; don hem reuerence, and helpen hem in alle &thorn;inges aftur &thorn;i pouwer &yogh;if
&thorn;ei han mester; &laquo;&thorn;at &thorn;ou beo of long lyf&raquo;, &thorn;at is to seyen, wi&thorn;-outen ende liuinde&mdash;and &thorn;at is riht, &yogh;if &thorn;ow wolt haue long liuynge, &thorn;at &thorn;ou honoure hem
of whom &thorn;ow heddest biginnynge to liuen.  &THORN;e secounde Comaundement is:
&laquo;&thorn;ow schalt sle no mon&raquo;.  &THORN;reo Maners ben of Slauht: &thorn;er is slauht of hond,
whon a Mon sle&thorn; a no&thorn;ur, or putte&thorn; him in stude of sleinge, as in prison, or in
o&thorn;er stude where for to ben slayn.  Slauht of tonge; &thorn;at is in two maners: be
comaunding, or of tysinge.  Slauht of herte mai ben also in two maners: as
whonne he disyre&thorn; or coueyte&thorn; a no&thorn;ures de&thorn;, or whon he suffre&thorn; a mon dyen
and wol not helpen him and delyueren him &yogh;if he haue pouwer.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde
Comaundement is: &laquo;&thorn;ou schalt do no lecherie&raquo;.  And &thorn;at is riht, whose wole hauen heuene &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen rotyng or stynk, &thorn;at he loke his soule beo not roten
nor stynkinde.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e Comaundement is: &laquo;&thorn;ou schalt do no &thorn;ef&thorn;e, nor
falshede&raquo;.  And &thorn;at is riht, whose loue&thorn; a no&thorn;er, &thorn;at he bi-reue him nou&yogh;t &thorn;at he loue&thorn; or scholde him seruen.  &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e Comaundement is: &laquo;&thorn;ou schalt not beren fals witnesse to harm of &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur&raquo;.  And &thorn;at is ri&yogh;t; whose wol not
falsliche greuen his bro&thorn;er him-self, he schal not concenten to ano&thorn;er &thorn;at wole
him greuen, nor helpen, nor counseil &yogh;iuen.  &THORN;e sixte Comaundement is: &laquo;&thorn;ou
scha[l]t not coueyten &thorn;i bro&thorn;er wyf&raquo;, nor his seruaunt; nor no mon, &thorn;ou &thorn;at art
wommon, nor non o&thorn;er wommon &thorn;ou &thorn;at art mon.  &THORN;e seuen&thorn;e Comaundement
is: &laquo;&thorn;ou schalt not coueyten &thorn;i bro&thorn;ures &thorn;ing&raquo;.  &THORN;eose tweyne comaundemens acorden to tweyne biforen: &laquo;&thorn;ow schalt don no lecherye&raquo;, &laquo;ne &thorn;ou schalt don no &thorn;ef&thorn;e&raquo;; ffor whi? hose ha&thorn; an vuel wille and coueyte&thorn; faste in herte, he mai not longe holden him from wikkede dede in wikkede occasions; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou &thorn;at wolt not don no lecherie, loke &thorn;ou haue &thorn;erof no couetyse; and &thorn;ou &thorn;at wolt not Robben nor stelen, coueyte not in herte non o&thorn;er monnes &thorn;ing.  &THORN;eos ben &thorn;e ten Comaundemens &thorn;at god &yogh;af Moyses.  &THORN;e &thorn;reo ffurste fallen to &thorn;e loue of God, &thorn;e [o&thorn;ure] seuene to &thorn;e loue of &thorn;i bro&thorn;er.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of seuene vertues and of heore Sufficience.</HEAD>

<P>Afftur anon most &thorn;ou knowen &thorn;e seuene vertues: Be-leeue, Hope, Loue,
Qweyntise, Riht, Streng&thorn;e, and A-temprenesse.  &THORN;e &thorn;reo furste, &thorn;at is to witen
Be-leeue, Hope, and Loue, ordeyne&thorn; &thorn;e hou &thorn;ou schalt lyuen as anentes God.
&THORN;e o&thorn;er foure ben cleped vertues Cardinals: to ordeynen &thorn;i-self hou &thorn;ou schalt


<PB N="1: 249">

lyuen here ffor to comen to [&thorn;e ioye] wi&thorn;-outen ende.  &THORN;ow wost wel, we ben
maad for &thorn;is ende, &thorn;at is to witen: to knowen god, hauen him, and louen him.
But &thorn;reo &thorn;inges ben nedful to comen to &thorn;i[s] ende: &thorn;at is to witen: Connynge
whoder &thorn;ou schalt gon, and wille to cu[m]en, and hope for to cu[m]en.  On o&thorn;er
halue, hose wole wel don a &thorn;ing, him bi-houe&thorn; &thorn;reo &thorn;inges: Connynge, Pouwer,
and Wille; &thorn;at is to sei&yogh;en: &thorn;at he con don hit, and mowe, and wole.  But
for we han not of vre-self connynge, pouwer, no wille, &thorn;erfore God ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen
vs Be-leeue, ffor to fulfillen &thorn;e de-faute of vre vncunnyngnesse; Hope, fforte
fulfullen &thorn;e defaute of vre feblenesse; Loue, for to ordeynen vre wille to &thorn;at on or
to &thorn;at o&thorn;er.  Be-leeue ordeyne&thorn; vs to God &thorn;e Sone, to whom is a-titlet cunnynge;
Hope to God &thorn;e Fader, to whom is a-tytlet streng&thorn;e; Loue to God &thorn;e Holygost,
to whom is a-tytlet godnesse.  And &thorn;erfore, Be-leeue make&thorn; vs haue knowyng of
God; and &thorn;at knowinge sei&thorn; to vs &thorn;at he is wonderliche corteis &thorn;at in such
manere and so largeliche &yogh;iue&thorn; vs of his godes: and of &thorn;at be-leeue come&thorn; Hope:
and of &thorn;at knowynge &thorn;at he is go[o]d, come&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde vertue, &thorn;at is Loue, ffor
whi? eueri &thorn;ing loue&thorn; kyndeliche &thorn;e goode.&mdash;Wi&thorn; &thorn;e foure o&thorn;ure vertues, &thorn;at
ben vertues cardinals, is al a Monnes lyf gouerned in &thorn;is world; &thorn;at ben:
Qweyntise, Riht, Streng&thorn;e, and A-temprenesse.  Of &thorn;eose foure sei&thorn; &thorn;e holi gost
in &thorn;e Book of wisdam, &thorn;at &thorn;er nis no &thorn;ing more profitable to mon in eor&thorn;e.  Heere
now, wherfore.  Whose wole wel don, ffurst hit beo-houe&thorn; &thorn;at he cunne chesun
&thorn;e gode from &thorn;e wikke, and of tweye goode &thorn;e betere to chesun.  &THORN;e gode
fro &thorn;e wikke, teche&thorn; vs Riht.  Leuen &thorn;e lasse goode for &thorn;e more, vs teche&thorn;
Qweyntise.  And for twey &thorn;inges letten mon to don wel, &thorn;at is to seyen, worldus
weole, &thorn;at deceyue&thorn; mon wi&thorn; fals swetnesse, and aduersite &thorn;at ouurcome&thorn; mon
wi&thorn; grete and mony hardnesses or wi&thorn; grete burstus: a&yogh;eyn weole &thorn;ou schalt
haue Mesure, &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo not to muche houen an hei&yogh; and deceyued wi&thorn; fals
swetnesse, and &thorn;at vertu is clept A-temprenesse; a&yogh;ein aduersite schalt &thorn;ou haue
hardynesse of corage, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not feld wi&thorn; &thorn;is hardnesse, and &thorn;is vertu is
cald Streng&thorn;e.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e twelue articles of &thorn;e Fei.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E ffurste poynt of holy be-leeue is: Fader and Sone and Holy gost, &thorn;eose
&thorn;reo persones ben on God, wi&thorn;-outen begynnynge and wi&thorn;outen endynge, &thorn;at
made heuene and eor&thorn;e of nou&yogh;t.  &THORN;e secunde point of be-leeue is: &thorn;at Godes
sone tok flesch and blod of &thorn;e Mayden Marie, and of hire was boren Ihesu Crist,
verrey God and verrey mon.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde poynt is: &thorn;at god and &thorn;e virgynes sone
Marie was pyned and crucifyed and suffrede de&thorn; on &thorn;e crois, and in sepulcre was
leyd, in to helle his soule descended wi&thorn; his godhede and tok out &thorn;e soules &thorn;at
hedden in heore lyf don his wille.  &THORN;is passion he suffrede wi&thorn; his oune wille,
ffor to diliueren from helle alle &thorn;at heere don his wille.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn; poynt is:
&thorn;at Ihesu Crist in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day verrei god and verrei mon Ros from de&thorn; to liue
in flesch and bodi glorifyed; schewynge him ofte to Marie Maudeleyn and to his
disciples, and spac wi&thorn; heom; and &thorn;orw &thorn;at Resurrexion, wi&thorn; &thorn;is bodi &thorn;at we han
in &thorn;is world we schullen risen fro de&thorn; to lyue.  &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e point is: &thorn;at vre lord
Ihesu Crist, God and Mon, stei&yogh; in to heuene, and &thorn;orw him schulen we, [if we]


<PB N="1: 250">

be not cumbred wi&thorn; no dedly synne whon we passen henne.  From &thorn;enne he sende
&thorn;e holigost to hise apostles; and fro &thorn;enne at &thorn;e day of doom in his monhed
schal comen to Iuggen wi&thorn; his apostles eueri mon aftur his werkes.  &THORN;E seuene
&thorn;at comen after, ben &thorn;e seuene sacramens of holichurche, &thorn;at ben remedie
to mon of alle-manere synne.  &THORN;e furste is Cristendom, &thorn;at make&thorn; mon clene of
&thorn;e synne &thorn;at he drau&yogh;&thorn; of ffader and moder.  &THORN;e secunde is Confirmacion, &thorn;at
conferme&thorn; &thorn;e holygost in Mon or wommon &thorn;at is cristned.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde is Penaunce,
&thorn;at do&thorn; awei eueri maner of synne.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e is &thorn;e sacrement of &thorn;e Auter,
&thorn;at conferme&thorn; &thorn;e penaunt and &yogh;iue&thorn; him streng&thorn;e &thorn;at he ne &yogh;eyn-falle, and
reconsyle&thorn; him.  &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e is Ordre, &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; pouwer to ordeyne[d] to don heore
Offys and make &thorn;e sacrement.  &THORN;e sixte is Matrimoyne, &thorn;at defende&thorn; dedli synne
in waxing of generacion.  &THORN;e seuen&thorn;e is Vnccion, &thorn;at is don to &thorn;e seke in
remedie of bodi and soule.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene dedes of Merci.</HEAD>

<P>Affter &thorn;ow most witen w&yogh;uche ben &thorn;e dedes of Merci.  &THORN;e ffurste is: &yogh;iuen
&thorn;e hungri mete.  &THORN;e secunde, &yogh;iue drynke to &thorn;e &thorn;hrustfol.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde is, clo&thorn;en &thorn;e nakede.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e is, herborwe &thorn;e housles.  &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e, visyten &thorn;e prison neode.  &THORN;e sixte is, cumforte &thorn;e seke.  &THORN;e seuen&thorn;e is, to burie &thorn;e dede. / &THORN;eose ben &thorn;e dedes of Merci &thorn;at fallen to monnes bodi.  But now mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou sei&yogh;en &thorn;at art in Religion: &laquo;I haue no power to &yogh;iue mete nor drinke nor clo&thorn;inge nor herborwe, nor visyten nor cumforten &thorn;e prison nor &thorn;e seke, ffor I am al in
o&thorn;ures pouwer and not in myn oune.  &THORN;erfore hit weore bettre I weore at myn
owne wille, and don &thorn;is dedes of Merci, &thorn;en ben in Religion.&raquo;  Ne be not
deceyued: hit is bettre haue compassion and pite in herte of him &thorn;at is Meseyse,
&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;ou heddest al &thorn;e world to &yogh;iuen for charite, ffor better is &yogh;iuen
holliche compassion of &thorn;i-self, &thorn;en of &thorn;yn god.  &YOGH;ef &thorn;i-seluen, and &thorn;ou &yogh;euest more &thorn;en al &thorn;e world.  But nou &thorn;ou wolt seien: &laquo;So&thorn; hit is &thorn;at hit is bettre &yogh;ift to &yogh;iuen &thorn;i-seluen &thorn;en &thorn;yn: But bo&thorn;e were bettre &thorn;en on; ffor on good is lasse &thorn;en tweyne.&raquo;  Hit is not so; ffor whi?  Whe&thorn;ere is better be called god, or ben
called his seruaunt?  To ben called god.  And &thorn;o &thorn;at suffren Cold, hunger and
defaute and o&thorn;ur meseises here, he calle&thorn; heom him-self; ffor he sei&thorn; in &thorn;e
Ewangelie: &laquo;Al &thorn;at &yogh;e don to &thorn;e leeste of myne, &yogh;e don hit to me.&raquo;  On o&thorn;ur halue: whe&thorn;er is beter, to Iuggen or ben I-Iugget?  Certes, Iuggen.  And &thorn;at
schullen &thorn;e pore: &thorn;ei schullen Iugge &thorn;e riche; also Ihesu sei&thorn; in &thorn;e Ewangelie:
&raquo;&YOGH;e &thorn;at han alle &thorn;ingus forsake for &thorn;e loue of me: at &thorn;e day of dome whon i
sitte in &thorn;e see of my Mageste, &thorn;enne schul &yogh;e sitten vppon &thorn;e xii tronos and
Iuggen [&thorn;e] .xii. linages of Israel.&raquo;  On o&thorn;er halue: whe&thorn;er is bettere han &thorn;e Ioye
of heuene in possescion, or in be-hotyng?  Certes, in possession.  And &thorn;at haue
&thorn;e pore of spirit, ffor, as Ihesu sei&thorn; in &thorn;e Ewangelie, &laquo;heoren is &thorn;e Ioye of
heuene&raquo;.  He sei&thorn; not &laquo;here schal ben&raquo;, but &laquo;here is&raquo;; &thorn;at is to vnderstonden: also siker mouwe &thorn;e pore ben of &thorn;e Ioye of heuene, as mon is of &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at is in his hondes.  And &thorn;erfore sei&thorn; seint Bernard: &laquo;&THORN;e pore han nou&yogh;t in eor&thorn;e, ne &thorn;e riche han nou&yogh;t in heuene&raquo;; and &thorn;erfore, &yogh;if &thorn;e riche wolen hit haue, &thorn;ei moten hit bugge at &thorn;e pore.  Now I wot wel &thorn;ow disyrest muche to witen w&yogh;uche


<PB N="1: 251">

ben verrey pore, and w&yogh;uche nou&yogh;t.  Now here wi&thorn; deuocion.  Summe ben &thorn;at han
richesse, and louen hit: &thorn;o ben &thorn;e Couetouse of &thorn;is world; and summe ben &thorn;at
hauen hem not, but &thorn;ei louen hem and wolde gladliche hauen hem: &thorn;o ben &thorn;e
wrecches of &thorn;e world, and &thorn;e fals religious, and [&thorn;ei] ben also riche as &thorn;e o&thorn;ere
or ricchore, [in wil].  And &thorn;ei ben [&thorn;o] of whom Ihesu sei&thorn; in &thorn;e Ewangelie &thorn;at
&laquo;hit weore lihtore to a chamaile gon &thorn;orw &thorn;e ei&yogh;e of an nedele, &thorn;en &thorn;e riche entre in to &thorn;e ioye of heuene&raquo;.  Summe [han] riche[s], but &thorn;ei louen hit not, al-&thorn;au&yogh; &thorn;ei [wol wele] h[it] han: &thorn;o ben &thorn;e gode men of &thorn;is world &thorn;at dispenden &thorn;at &thorn;ei han wel; and o&thorn;ure &thorn;er ben &thorn;at han nou&yogh;t of richesse, nor louen hit, nor &thorn;ei sechen
not to hauen hit: &thorn;o ben &thorn;e holy men of Religion; and &thorn;ei ben verreiliche pore,
and heoren is &thorn;e Ioye of heuene.  &THORN;at is &thorn;e blessyng of pore.  &THORN;enne bihoue&thorn;
hit &thorn;at &thorn;e riche haue &thorn;e contrarie of &thorn;e blessynge.  And &thorn;erfore I mai siggen:
&laquo;Blessed ben &thorn;e pore, for heoren is &thorn;e Ioye of heuene&raquo;, &thorn;enne may I siggen:
&laquo;Waried ben &thorn;e riche, for heoren is &thorn;e peyne of helle.&raquo;  Riche ben &thorn;at han
richesse and louen hit, [or &thorn;at han hit not but louen hit and coueyten hit].
Pore ben &thorn;at han pouerte and louen hit and coueyten hit, or &thorn;at han richesse
and louen al-wei pouert.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene preyeres of &thorn;e <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster.  Cap. xv.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Aftur &thorn;ou most knowen w&yogh;uche ben &thorn;e seuene preyeres of &thorn;e <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at fordon alle wikkednesses and bringen alle godnesses; &thorn;at vre lord Ihesu Crist
tau&yogh;te his disciples how &thorn;ei scholden prei&yogh;e god &thorn;e fadur, &amp; seide hem &thorn;us:
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster qui es in celis: Fader vre &thorn;at art in heuene.  Sanctificetur nomen
tuum:</FOREIGN> Halewed be &thorn;i nome.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adueniat regnum tuum:</FOREIGN> Come &thorn;i regne.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fiat uoluntas tua, sicut in celo et in terra:</FOREIGN> &THORN;i wille be don in eor&thorn;e as in heuene.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis hodie:</FOREIGN> Vre eueridayes bred &yogh;if vs &thorn;is day.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et dimitte nobis debita nostra, sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus nostris:</FOREIGN>
For&yogh;if vs vre dettes, as we for&yogh;iuen vre dettoures.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem:</FOREIGN> And do us not in to fondynge.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Set libera nos a malo:</FOREIGN> But diliuere vs of wikkednesse.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Amen:</FOREIGN> So beo hit.  &THORN;is orison sourmounte&thorn; alle o&thorn;ure orisouns,
in dignite and in profyt.  In Dignite: for God him-self made hit; and &thorn;erfore
he do&thorn; gret schome and gret vnreuerrence to god &thorn;at take&thorn; him to Rymede
wordes &amp; queynte, and leue&thorn; &thorn;e wordes and &thorn;e preyere &thorn;at he vs tauhte, &thorn;at
wot al &thorn;e wille of god &thorn;e fader, and w&yogh;uch orison him best paye&thorn;, and of w&yogh;uche
&thorn;inges we wrecches han most neode and mester to preyen&mdash;ffor whi? as I
haue i-seyd, he wot onliche al godes wille and al vre nedfulnesse.  And &thorn;erfore
ben an hundred &thorn;ousend men deceyuet &thorn;orw multiplicacion of orisouns; ffor whon
&thorn;ei wenen han deuocion, &thorn;ey han a foul fleschliche wille, ffor eueri fleschliche
corage delyte&thorn; him kuyndeliche in turned langage and rymed.  And &thorn;erfore beo
war!  ffor I seye &thorn;e forso&thorn;e, hit is a foul lecherye to delyten in such Rymynge.
On o&thorn;er halfe seynt Austin and seint Gregori and o&thorn;ur seyntes preiden after
her affeccion.  [I] blame not heore orisons; bote I blame hem &thorn;at leuen &thorn;e
preyere &thorn;at god him-self maade and tau&yogh;te, and holden hem to &thorn;e orisoun of a
symple seint, wher-so he ha&thorn; founden hit writen.  For-&thorn;i, bad God in &thorn;e
Ewangelie: &laquo;Whon &yogh;e preyen, ne preye&thorn; not in mony wordes, bote sei&thorn; &thorn;us, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater


<PB N="1: 252">

noster</FOREIGN>&raquo;.  On o&thorn;er halue, &thorn;is Orisoun passe&thorn; alle o&thorn;ure orisouns in [sufficience]:
ffor &thorn;er-Inne is contenet al &thorn;at we han mester [of] to &thorn;is lyf or to &thorn;at o&thorn;er; ffor
we preyen God &thorn;e ffader &thorn;at he delyuere vs of alle wikkednesse, and &thorn;at he &yogh;eue
vs alle goode, and &thorn;at he make vs suche &thorn;at we mowen neuer don vuel nor
faylen of goode.  And seo what manere.  Al &thorn;e wikkednesse &thorn;at vs greue&thorn;,
&thorn;at is to siggen, ou&thorn;er hit is wikkednesse &thorn;at is passet, ou&thorn;er &thorn;at is to comen,
or &thorn;at is present now.  Of &thorn;at is passet, we preyen vr lord &thorn;at he vs delyuere
whon we siggen <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dimitte nobis debita nostra, sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus
nostris.</FOREIGN>  Of &thorn;at is to comen: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem.</FOREIGN>  Of &thorn;at we suffre now, whon we siggen <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Set libera nos a malo.</FOREIGN>  On o&thorn;er halue, what good so hit be, ou&thorn;er hit is Bodili goode, or gostly goode, [or good] wi&thorn;-outen ende. Bodily goode preye we whon we siggen <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis
hodie.</FOREIGN>  Gostly good, whon we seyen <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fiat voluntas tua, sicut in celo &amp; in terra.</FOREIGN>
Good wi&thorn;-outen ende, whon we seyen <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adueniat regnum tuum.</FOREIGN>  Confirmacion of al &thorn;is, whon we siggen <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sanctificetur nomen tuum.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;eose ben &thorn;e seuene preyeres of &thorn;e Ewangelye &thorn;at Ihesu tauhte his disciples.  And &thorn;ou schalt wel witen &thorn;at &thorn;e foure wordes &thorn;at comen beforen, &thorn;at is to witen <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster qui es in celis,</FOREIGN> techen vs hou we schullen preyen, and w&yogh;uche we schulen ben in
preyere.  For whi?  we schul hauen foure &thorn;inges in orison, &thorn;at is to witen:
Parfyt loue anentes him &thorn;at we prei&yogh;e&thorn; to, and certeyn hope to hauen &thorn;at we
asken, and studefast be-leeue in whom &thorn;at we hopen, and so&thorn;fast mekenes, of
&thorn;at we no good han of vre-self and fer ben from his hei&yogh;nesse &thorn;at we leeuen
and louen and hopen.  Parfyt loue is conteynet in &thorn;is word, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater:</FOREIGN> ffor whi? eueri Creature loue&thorn; kuyndeliche his ffader.  Certeyn hope is vnderstonden in
&thorn;is word <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Noster:</FOREIGN> ffor whi?  &yogh;if he beo vre, &thorn;en mowe we homeliche seyen and
hopen &thorn;at he is holden to vs.  Studefast bi-leeue is vnderstonden in &thorn;is word
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui es:</FOREIGN> ffor whi?  whon we seyen <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Qui es,</FOREIGN> we leeuen &thorn;at god is, whom we neuer se&yogh;en; and &thorn;at is ri&yogh;t beleeue, ffor fei&thorn; is non o&thorn;er &thorn;yng but leeuyng of &thorn;ing &thorn;at may not been se&yogh;en.  So&thorn; Mekenesse is vnderstonden in &thorn;is word <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In celis:</FOREIGN>
ffor whi?  whon we &thorn;enken &thorn;at he is hei&yogh;, and &thorn;at we ben lowe, &thorn;enne beo we
meke.  // Whonne we han &thorn;ese foure &thorn;inges studefastliche in vre herte, &thorn;en
mowe we hardiliche preyen and siggen wi&thorn; gret wille: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sanctificetur nomen tuum,</FOREIGN>
Halewed beo &thorn;i nome; &thorn;at is to siggen: A-ferme &thorn;i nome, &thorn;at art fader, in vs,
&thorn;at we mowen ben in such manere &thorn;i children, &thorn;at we don euere &thorn;i wille, and
&thorn;at no &thorn;ing beo in vs o&thorn;er &thorn;en beo al to &thorn;i paye.  And for we mowe not
don &thorn;is parfytli while we ben in &thorn;is wrecchede world, &thorn;erfore we preyen,
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adueniat regnum tuum:</FOREIGN> Come to vs &thorn;i regne, &thorn;at &thorn;ou regne in vs in &thorn;is lyf &thorn;orw grace, and [we in &thorn;e] in heuene wi&thorn; Ioye.  And &thorn;e selue we preyen for hem &thorn;at ben in purgatorie.  And for we mowen neuer han &thorn;e Ioye of heuene but we don &thorn;i wille in eor&thorn;e, we seyen, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fiat voluntas tua sicut in celo et in terra;</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to siggen, &YOGH;if vs grace to don al &thorn;at &thorn;ou comaundest, and leuen al &thorn;at &thorn;ou
defendest; and &thorn;at in er&thorn;e as in heuene, &thorn;at is to siggen: As Michael, Gabriel,
Raphael, Angeles and Archangeles, Prophetes, Apostles, Martires, Confessours,
Virgines don &thorn;i wille in heuene, also mote don &thorn;e Ordres &thorn;at ben in eor&thorn;e, &thorn;at
is to witen &thorn;e Pope, &thorn;e Cardinals, Bisschopes, Abbotes, Priores, and alle heore


<PB N="1: 253">

sogettes, Erchedeknes, Officials, Denes, Parsouns, Vikers, Prestes, and alle
Ordres; &thorn;e Kynges, &thorn;e Princes, Duykes, Erles, Barouns, Riche Pore, Lettrede and
Vnlettrede, and [al] &thorn;ei &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bouht in eueriche [regne], in eueriche Ordre,
and in eueriche Lynage, and Age.  And for we mowe not don &thorn;i wille nor liuen
in &thorn;is Bodi, but &yogh;if &yogh;e vs susteyne, we seyen, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis hodie;</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to seyen, &YOGH;if vs streng&thorn;e of bodi and of soule, and hele of
bo&thorn;e; &thorn;at is to witen, &thorn;reo maner of bred: bodiliche, as mete and clo&thorn;,
gostliche as holy writ, and &thorn;e bred of Eukarist, to cumforten &thorn;e ton and &thorn;e
to&thorn;ur kynde.  And for we be wor&thorn;i no good while we beo&thorn; in synne, we seyen,
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et dimitte nobis debita nostra, sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus nostris;</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to siggen, For-&yogh;if vs (vre misdedes, as we for&yogh;iuen vren(!); &thorn;at is to siggen,) al &thorn;at we han synget wi&thorn; word, wi&thorn; dede, wi&thorn; &thorn;ou&yogh;t; as we for&yogh;iuen to hem &thorn;at han mistaken a&yogh;eynes vs. And for hit is luitel wor&thorn;h for to han for&yogh;iuenesse, but &yogh;if we mowen aftur loken vs from synne, we sigen, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem;</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at is to siggen, Ne soffre not &thorn;at we ben ouer-comen wi&thorn; fondynge of &thorn;e feend,
of &thorn;e fflesch, ne of &thorn;e world.  (Ac &thorn;ou schalt not preyen &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not tempted,
but &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo not ouurcomen in temptacion.)  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Set libera nos a malo:</FOREIGN> And not only of temptacion, bote delyuere vs of vuel, of bodi and of soule, of seknesse of
synne and of pyne, &thorn;at nou is or &thorn;at is to come.  Amen.&raquo;  And for god sei&thorn; in
&thorn;e Ewangelie: &laquo;Al &thorn;at &yogh;e preyen my ffader in my nome, &thorn;at he schal don&raquo;; &thorn;erfore we seyen at &thorn;e ende of eueri orison in holi chirche, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Per dominum nostrum Iesum Cristum, filium tuum, Qui tecum uiuit et regnat deus, per omnia
secula seculorum amen,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to siggen: &laquo;&THORN;orw vre lord Ihesu Crist, &thorn;i sone, &thorn;at
wi&thorn; &thorn;e liue&thorn; &amp; regne&thorn; god, world wi&thorn;outen ende, be hit so&raquo;. / Vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt not seyen wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e al &thorn;at I haue heer writen: but sey onliche &thorn;e bare lettre [wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e], and &thorn;enk in &thorn;in herte of &thorn;at I haue put here vppon eueri word bi him-self.  And make no fors ffor to multeplyen mony <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Pater noster</FOREIGN>; ffor whi? on is more wor&thorn; wi&thorn; deuocion and entendement, &thorn;en a &thorn;ousend wi&thorn;outen
entendement; and seint Poul sei&thorn;: &laquo;[I] hedde leuere siggen fyue wordes wi&thorn;
deuocion in myn herte wi&thorn; entendement, &thorn;en fyue &thorn;ousend wi&thorn;outen entendement&raquo;. IN &thorn;e selue manere &thorn;ow schalt don &thorn;in offys in Qweor; ffor whi?  &thorn;us sei&thorn; &thorn;e
prophete: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Psallite sapienter,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Singe and versele Godes seruise wysliche&raquo;.  Wysliche
syngen and reden, is forte [&thorn;inken] wi&thorn; herte &thorn;at mon sei&thorn; wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e.  For whi?
&yogh;if &thorn;i bodi is in qweor of chirche and &thorn;i lippes in &thorn;e sauter, and &thorn;yn herte in
&thorn;e chepyng, &thorn;ow art wrecchedliche departed.  And [for] God sei&thorn;: &laquo;Seeche&thorn;
furst Godes Reyne, and &thorn;at &yogh;e han mester of &thorn;e world schal be send &yogh;ow&raquo;:
&thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schalt witen what &thorn;ou schalt han in &thorn;e Ioie of heuen.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e seuene drueries in bodi, and seuene in &thorn;e soule.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;Ow schalt han seuene druryes in bodi, and seuene in soule.  &THORN;ow schalt han
in bodi: Feirnesse wi&thorn;outen fuilyng, Streng&thorn;e wi&thorn;outen feblenesse, Freonesse
wi&thorn;outen &thorn;raldam, Lihtnesse wi&thorn;-outen heuynesse, Wille wi&thorn;-outen wernyng or
a&yogh;eyn-standyng, Hele wi&thorn;-outen seknesse, Long lyf wi&thorn;-outen ende.  &THORN;ow schalt
haue in soule: Wisdam wi&thorn;outen vnconnyng, Sikernesse wi&thorn;-outen feyntnes,


<PB N="1: 254">

Ioye wi&thorn;-outen serwe, Loue wi&thorn;-outen hate, Acord wi&thorn;-outen discord, Honour
wi&thorn;outen dispisyng.  BOte wrecches in helle schulen han &thorn;e reuers, in bodi and
in soule; &thorn;at is: Foulnesse wi&thorn;-outen feirnesse, Feblenesse wi&thorn;-outen streng&thorn;e,
and so of al o&thorn;ure. / And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schalt don al &thorn;i power to han &thorn;at Ioye.
For whi?  hit is so gret Ioye and so gret swetnesse &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;test liuen ffro
&thorn;e begynnynge of &thorn;e world to &thorn;e endynge, and han alle &thorn;e desyres &thorn;at &thorn;ou
cou&thorn;est de-vysen, be good skil &thorn;ou schuldest wi&thorn; good wille leten al &thorn;at, to
ben o day in &thorn;e Ioye of heuene. // &THORN;us ende&thorn; &thorn;e secunde degre of
Contemplacion, in Holi writ; wherof and &thorn;ou take good hede, hit schal ben liht for &thorn;e
to holden eueri sarmoun.  On o&thorn;ur halue, &thorn;ou hast ma[t]ere of spekyng to
Clerkes ben &thorn;ey neuere so wyse, and to lewede, ben &thorn;ei neuere so boystes.
Whon &thorn;ou spekest to wyse, meue summe of &thorn;eose materes, and aske.  And whon
&thorn;ow spekest to symple, teche hem ble&thorn;eliche and sweteliche.  For
whi?  &thorn;ou hast inou&yogh; wherof to speken, and hou &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;in owne lyf leden &amp; o&thorn;ure amenden.&mdash;
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion of God.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E &thorn;ridde degre of Contemplacion is in God self; and may beo in two Maners:
Wi&thorn;-outen, in his Monhede, and wi&thorn;-Innen in his hei&yogh;e Godhede.  For
whi?  &thorn;us sei&thorn; seint Austin: &laquo;&THORN;erfore bicom God Mon, to maken Mon seon God in his nature; ffor whi?  where Mon go&thorn; Inne or oute, alle dayes and alle tymes he
may fynden fedyng of God, inward &thorn;orw Contemplacion of his Godhede, outward
&thorn;orw Consyderacion of his Monhede&raquo;.  Off his Monhede, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enke &thorn;reo
&thorn;inges: &THORN;e Mekenesse of his Incarnacion, and &thorn;e swetnesse of his Conuersacion,
and &thorn;e charite of his Passion.  But &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t not don &thorn;is at ones: &thorn;erfore I
haue distynktet hem bi [&thorn;e] houres of &thorn;e day &thorn;at &thorn;ou syngest at Chirche; &thorn;at non
houre &thorn;e passe &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne haue &thorn;in herte ocupyed.  &THORN;at to don, &thorn;ou schalt witen
&thorn;at eueri houre ha&thorn; double &thorn;enkyng: on of &thorn;e Passion, ano&thorn;er of o&thorn;er seson.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion before Matynes.</HEAD>

<P>BI-fforen Matynes, &thorn;ow schalt &thorn;enken enterliche &thorn;e tyme, &thorn;e stude, and &thorn;e
houre whonne god was born.  &THORN;e tyme was in [mid-]wynter, whon hit was caldest.
&THORN;e houre was at Midniht, &thorn;e hardeste houre &thorn;at is.  &THORN;e stude was in-middes
&thorn;e wey; in an hous wi&thorn;-outen walles I-wounden in cloutes and bounden wi&thorn; a
lyste, bi-foren an Oxe and an Asse was [he] leid in a Cracche, for &thorn;ei hedde non
o&thorn;er place.  &THORN;ou schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e bisynesse &thorn;at Marie hedde of hire child;
of Ioseph, hire spouse, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken, hou &thorn;at he hedde gret
Ioye.  &THORN;enk of &thorn;e schepherdes deuocion, and of &thorn;e swete cumpaygnye of &thorn;e Angeles: and hef vp &thorn;in herte and synge wi&thorn; heom <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Gloria in excelsis deo.</FOREIGN> / Of &thorn;e passion, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken how &thorn;at tyme of &thorn;e niht he was bi-trayet of his disciple, and taken as a traytor, and bounden as a &thorn;ef, and lad as a feloun.  And &thorn;enk
how he proferede him-self to his enemys, and custe him &thorn;at trayede him, and
callede him his frende; and how he defendede his disciples to drawen eny
wepne, and how he helede &thorn;e Ere of his enemy.  And how his disciples flowen
for fere and laften him one wi&thorn; his enemys.  And hou &thorn;ei bounden him and
ladden him bifore Anne, and &thorn;ere he was examynet &amp; boffeted; and for he


<PB N="1: 255">

onswerde not after heore wille, he was lad bi-foren Caiphas; and &thorn;er forsok
seynt Peter him &thorn;rie.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion be-fore Prime.</HEAD>

<P>BI-ffore Prime, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e Passion and of &thorn;e
Resurrexion.  Of &thorn;e passion, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken hou &thorn;e Iewes ladden him to heore counseil, and how &thorn;ei fals witnesse beeren him an honde, and Blasfemie, and hou &thorn;at he hedde reneyed &thorn;e peple of Galyle to Ierusalem: and scorned him in diuerse maners, and
spitten in his face; and hudden his face, and smiten him, and beden him propheten
and tellen who him smot.  Bute for al &thorn;at swete Ihesu suffrede, he seide neuere
&laquo;whi do &yogh;e so?&raquo;, bote as a lomb &thorn;at is lad to slen, also he bar hym and spac not a&yogh;eyn.  O&thorn;ur monye dispites &thorn;ei duden him, whuche weore longe to telle. / Of
&thorn;e Resurrexion, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken &thorn;at such tyme ros Ihesu Crist from de&thorn;e to
lyue, aftur &thorn;at he hedde distruied helle &amp; delyuered &thorn;e soules &thorn;at weren hise
from &thorn;e pouwer of &thorn;e feend.  And &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken also of his swete schewynges:
how he aperede &thorn;at day fyue tymes and fif tymes afterward.  Furst to Marie
Magdaleyn, whon heo wende he hedde I-beon a gardyner.  &THORN;e secunde tyme to
hire and to o&thorn;er wimmen in &thorn;e wey, whon he grette hem and seide <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Auete</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at is to siggen &laquo;God loke &yogh;ou&raquo;.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde tyme to seint Peter&mdash;but we haue not &thorn;e maner.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e tyme to tweyne disciples touward &thorn;e Castel of Emaus,
whon &thorn;ei wenden he hedde ben a pilgrym, and whonne &thorn;ei knewen him in
brekynge of bred.  &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e tyme to ten o&thorn;ure disciples whon seynt Thomas
was absent: whon he stod a-middes hem and seide <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pax vobis,</FOREIGN> and schewede hem his hondes and feet, for &thorn;ei wenden &thorn;ei hedden seyen a spirit.  &THORN;e sixte tyme, whon seynt Thomas was wi&thorn; hem: and bad him putten his hond in his
syde.  &THORN;e seue&thorn;e tyme he aperede to seint Peter and to seint Ion and to seint
Iake &amp; to Natanael whon &thorn;ei fisscheden in &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; &thorn;at is cald Tiberiadis, and eet wi&thorn; hem &amp; askede seint Peter wher he louede him more &thorn;en &thorn;e
o&thorn;ere.  &THORN;e eihte&thorn;e tyme on &thorn;e Mount of Galilee, whon he comaundede hem gon &thorn;orw &thorn;e world and Bapti&yogh;en &thorn;e peple In &thorn;e Fader nome and Sone and
Holygost.  &THORN;e Ny&thorn;e tyme he apeerede to his disciples &thorn;e day &thorn;at he steih in to heuene, whon &thorn;ei weren at &thorn;e mete, and snibbede heom for heore misbileeue and hardnesse
of herte.  &THORN;e Ten&thorn;e tyme to heom &thorn;e selue day, whonne he ladde heom out
of &thorn;e Cit&eacute;&eacute; in to &thorn;e Mount of Olyuete, and Comaundede hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei dwelleden
in &thorn;e Cite til &thorn;ei weoren clo&thorn;ed of &thorn;e vertu of god, and &yogh;af hem his sweete
blessynge, and de-parted from hem in to heuene, and sit on &thorn;e riht half of
his Fader.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion biforen Terce.</HEAD>

<P>BI-ffore terce, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e Passion and of &thorn;e Comynge of &thorn;e
holigost.  Of &thorn;e passion: hou Ihesus was such tyme dispoylet al naked and
bounden to a piler in Pilatus hous, and beoten him &thorn;at from his hed to his feet
was not laft on hol stude.  &THORN;enk also hou Pilat sende him to Heroudes, and he
forleet him and clo&thorn;ed him in whit, in signe &thorn;at he heold him a fool, and
sende him a&yogh;eyn to Pilat.  And Pilat wolde haue lete him gon, but furst he wolde


<PB N="1: 256">

chastisen him in &thorn;e Manere &thorn;at &thorn;ei duden &thorn;eues &thorn;at scholden be leten gon: and
his knihtes token him, and gedereden to-gedere &thorn;e peple for to be-holden him,
and duden on him a Mantel of red, &amp; &yogh;[e]uen him a staf in stude of Ceptre, and
a Coroune of &thorn;ornes on his hed, and kneleden biforen him and gretten him.
Bote for al &thorn;is, wolde not &thorn;e Iewes leten him beo quyt, but Pilat, for to payen
hem, dilyuerede hem [a &thorn;eef] and tok hem Ihesus to crucifyen wi&thorn;outen gult. /
&THORN;ou schalt also &thorn;enken &thorn;at such tyme of &thorn;e day sende vre lord &thorn;e holygost to
his disciples in liknesse of ffuir [&amp; tonges], &thorn;at fulde hem of wordes and langages,
and loue.  And &thorn;at was &thorn;e rihte ordinaunce of God; ffor whi? in two Maners
deceyuede &thorn;e wikkede gost ffurst Mon in Paradys, wi&thorn; tonge, &amp; wi&thorn; coldnesse of
his venym, and &thorn;erfore com &thorn;e holigost In tonge a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e entisement of &thorn;e
deuel, In fuir for to destruy&yogh;en &thorn;e coldnesse of his venyn.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion biforen Midday.</HEAD>

<P>BI-fforen Midday, &thorn;ow schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e Annunciacion and of &thorn;e Passion.  Of
&thorn;e Annunciacion, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken [of] &thorn;e Merci of vr lord, &thorn;at he wolde bi-come
mon, and suffre de&thorn; in his Monhede for vs, while &thorn;at he mihte in o&thorn;ur manere
han delyuered vs.  Bute al he dude &thorn;is to vs for to drawen &thorn;e loue of vs.  For
whi?  &yogh;if on hedde iben vre Creatour, and ano&thorn;er vre Saueour, &thorn;enne we mihten
more han loued vre buggere &thorn;en vre make[re]; and &thorn;erfore wolde vre Creatour ben
vre Saueour, and suffren in his bodi alle vre serwes, for to buggen al vre loue.
Off &thorn;e Passion &thorn;ow schalt &thorn;enken &thorn;at such tyme he was don on &thorn;e crois,
bitwene twey &thorn;eues, as &thorn;ou&yogh; he hedde ben heore Mayster.  And &thorn;erfore I not
w&yogh;at I may siggen: ffor &thorn;ei&yogh; alle &thorn;e seknesses and alle &thorn;e serwes of &thorn;is world
weore in O Monnes bodi, and &thorn;at mon mihte receiuen also mony anguissches
and also muche serwe in his bodi as alle &thorn;e men of &thorn;is world, hit were not but
luytel or as nou&yogh;t to regard of &thorn;e serwe &thorn;at he suffrede for vs in on houre of
&thorn;e day.  For whi?  &yogh;if I mi&yogh;te liuen an hundred &thorn;ousen[d] &yogh;er and dyen eueri day
a &thorn;ousend tymes for him of &thorn;e selue de&thorn; &thorn;at he di&yogh;ede for me, &yogh;it hit scholde
not amounten to &thorn;e serwe &thorn;at he suffrede in his bodi.  &THORN;enne may sum Mon
seyen &thorn;at &thorn;e serwe &thorn;at he suffrede for vs on &thorn;e Crois was grettore &thorn;en &thorn;e
peyne of helle is, in so luytel tyme: ffor w&yogh;i?  no Creature mi&yogh;te so muche
soffren as Ihesu, for &thorn;er hedde non so gret vertu in him; but sum creature may
suffren &thorn;e peines of helle: &thorn;enne is &thorn;e peyne of helle lasse for &thorn;e tyme &thorn;en
&thorn;e peyne of Ihesu.  I sei not &thorn;is certeynliche, for sum mennes concience.
And &thorn;erfore he seide in Ieremie: &laquo;Alle &yogh;e &thorn;at passen bi &thorn;e weye, take&thorn;
kepe to me and seo&thorn; wher &thorn;er be eny serwe lyk my serwe&raquo;.  Certes nay,
&thorn;er was neuer serwe to &thorn;e serwe of vre swete lord Ihesu Crist.  And also
&thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of vre swete ladi seynte Marie, what anguissche heo hedde
whon heo stod bi his ri&yogh;t syde, and receyuede &thorn;e disciple for &thorn;e Maister,
and &thorn;e seruaunt for &thorn;e lord, Ion &YOGH;ebedeus sone ffor Ihesu Godes sone.  And
&thorn;erfore heo may sei&yogh;en of hire-self so as Noemi seide: &laquo;ne calle&thorn; me not swete
luitel or eni del, but calle&thorn; me bitter herbi-for&thorn;ward, for whi?  of bitternesse
me ha[&thorn;] fult and of gret serwe god &thorn;at is al mi&yogh;tful&raquo;.  &THORN;e selue heo seide in
hire song of loue: &laquo;Ne haue no merueile &thorn;at i am blo, for &thorn;e sonne ha&thorn; dis-


<PB N="1: 257">

colurd me so&raquo;.  &THORN;erfore sei&thorn; on Englisch &thorn;is in Maner of pite: &laquo;Nou go&thorn; &thorn;e sonne bi &thorn;e wode, me rewe&thorn; Marie &thorn;i feire rode; Nou go&thorn; &thorn;e sonne vnder
tre, me rewe&thorn; Marie &thorn;i sone and &thorn;e.  Nou &thorn;ou hast, Mayden, feled &thorn;e scharpe
poynt of &thorn;at swered &thorn;at &thorn;e prophete Symeon made to &thorn;e mencion [of], &thorn;e day
of purificacion; nou &thorn;ou hast receyued &thorn;at &thorn;e bi-hete Anne &thorn;e prophetesse&raquo;.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion bifore Non.</HEAD>

<P>BI-fore Noon, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e Passion &amp; of &thorn;e Ascencion.  Of &thorn;e
passion, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken &thorn;at such tyme of &thorn;e day di&yogh;ede &thorn;e makere of lyf, for
&thorn;i loue.  &THORN;enne &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at he spac on &thorn;e Crois, and
of ffoure signes &thorn;at fellen in his dy&yogh;ing.  &THORN;e ffurste spekyng was &thorn;is: &laquo;Fader,
for&yogh;if hem heore trespas, for &thorn;ei wite not what &thorn;ei don&raquo;.  &THORN;e secunde was &thorn;at he seide to &thorn;e goode &thorn;ef: &laquo;Forso&thorn;e I sigge &thorn;e, &thorn;ou schalt in to paradys &thorn;is day wi&thorn; me&raquo;.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde was &thorn;at he spac of his Moder to seint Ion: &laquo;Seo &thorn;er &thorn;i Moder&raquo;, and to his Moder of his disciple: &laquo;Seo &thorn;ere &thorn;i sone&raquo;.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e was: &laquo;I haue &thorn;hurst&raquo;.  &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e: <FOREIGN>Eloi, Eloi, lama&yogh;abatany,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to siggen: &laquo;Mi God, mi God, whi hast &thorn;ou laft me?&raquo;  &THORN;e sixte was: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Consummatum est,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to siggen: &laquo;Now hit is fulfild&raquo;.  &THORN;e seuen&thorn;e was: &laquo;Fader, into &thorn;in honden I betake my spirit&raquo;.  Foure signes &thorn;er weren: &thorn;at al &thorn;e eor&thorn;e bi-gon to quaken; &thorn;e Veil of &thorn;e Temple clef a-two, and &thorn;e stones; &thorn;e graues openede, and &thorn;e dede arisen to lyue; &thorn;e sonne wi&thorn;-drow his liht from &thorn;e world, from Midday til Noon. / Of &thorn;e Ascencion &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken &thorn;at such tyme vre lord on &thorn;e Mount of Olyuete beforen his Moder and his disciples stei&yogh; in to heuene.  And &thorn;ei turned in to &thorn;e Cite, &amp; were dwellyng &thorn;er-Inne in fastinge and in preyeres, til &thorn;ei weore fuld of &thorn;e holigost, as ur lord hedde comaunded hem.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion bi-foren Euensong.</HEAD>

<P>BI-fforen Euen-song, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of &thorn;e Soper &amp; of &thorn;e Passion.  Of &thorn;e
Passion &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken hou Ioseph of Aramathie eode to Pouns Pilat and
preiede him to &yogh;iuen him &thorn;e bodi of vre lord Ihesu Crist, and he &yogh;af hit him.
And &thorn;enne &thorn;e Iewes comen to &thorn;e crois and broken &thorn;e hupes of &thorn;e twei &thorn;eoues;
and on of &thorn;e knihtes tok a spere and smot Ihesu to &thorn;e herte: and anon com
out blod &amp; watur.  And Ioseph tok &thorn;e bodi &amp; buriede hit.  And &thorn;e Iewes setten
&thorn;e knihtes to waken hit, ffor his disciples schulde not stelen hit and seyen falsli
to &thorn;e peple &thorn;at he weore risen from de&thorn; to lyue. / Of &thorn;e Ceene &thorn;ou schalt
&thorn;enken hou vre lord &yogh;af his flesch and his blod &thorn;at time in liknesse of bred
&amp; wyn, in confirmacion of vre fei&thorn;.  For we seon &amp; leeuen gostliche, &thorn;at we
mouwe not seon bodiliche.  And &thorn;erfore, whon &thorn;ou schalt receyue &thorn;at bodi, tak
hit also as &thorn;ou receiuedest hit out of Ihesu Cristes syde.  And &thorn;at tyme he wusch
his disciples feet, and Comaundede hem to louen vchon o&thorn;ur, and taken ensaumple
of him mekeliche [to] seruen vchone o&thorn;er.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion bi-foren cumplyn.</HEAD>

<P>BI-fforen Cumplin, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken hou Ioseph &amp; Nichodemus wounden Ihesu
bodi in feire schetes and enoyneden hit wi&thorn; precious oynemens. / &THORN;e secounde
&thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken on, is &thorn;is: ?&thorn;at &thorn;i swete lord Ihesu Crist &thorn;e day of


<PB N="1: 258">

&thorn;e Ceene, whon he hedde I-souped wi&thorn; his disciples, he eode from hem wi&thorn;
Peter and Iacob and Ion, and eode wi&thorn; heom in to a cortelage, and &thorn;ere from
heom he eode a stones cast and leide him to preye, &thorn;at &thorn;e swot of him ferde
as dropes of blod rennynde to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Contemplacion of God and of his deite.</HEAD>

<P>NOw &thorn;ou hast &thorn;e Manere to &thorn;enken on god in his Monhede.  (N)ow, &thorn;ou schalt
witen hou &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken on him in his he&yogh;e godhede.  And &thorn;ou schalt
vnderstonden &thorn;at God Mesurede so his knowynge [fro] &thorn;e biginnynge of mankynde, &thorn;at
he nou&thorn;ur al schewed him, nor al hud him; ffor whi?  &yogh;if he hedde al schewed
him, &thorn;enne hedde &thorn;e bileeue serued of nouht.  For ffei&thorn; is not but of &thorn;ing &thorn;at
mai not ben se&yogh;en; &thorn;enne, &thorn;at I leeue and seo, nis not fei&thorn;.  And &yogh;if he hedde
al hud him, &thorn;enne hedde fei&thorn; ben but misbeleeue.  And &thorn;erfore he wolde
sum schewen &amp; sum huyden.  In ffoure Maners he ordeynde to schewen him:
Two Maners inward, and two outward.  Inward: &thorn;orw gostly schewyng &amp; &thorn;orw
reson.  Outward: wi&thorn; holy writ &amp; &thorn;orw creatures.  &THORN;orw gostly schewyng,
whon god schewede him to mon &thorn;orw inspiracion of &thorn;e holygost, or &thorn;orw
Miracle.  &THORN;orw reson schewede god him to mon in &thorn;is manere: Eueri mon mai
wel sen in him-self &thorn;at he is, &thorn;at is to vnderstonden &thorn;at he ha&thorn; be[ing], and
&thorn;at he ha&thorn; not ben euere; and vppe &thorn;at he may witen &thorn;at he begon sum tyme
to ben.  &THORN;enne sum tyme was, &thorn;at he was not; &thorn;enne he mi&yogh;te in none manere
maken him-self, &thorn;enne hit bihoue&thorn; nede &thorn;at eueri mon come of o&thorn;ur &thorn;en of
him-self.  &THORN;e selue may mon seon in vche creature, ffor he mai seon eueri day
summe comen and summe gon.  And &thorn;erfore, for alle &thorn;inges ben, and ben not
of hem-self, &thorn;erfore behoue&thorn; hit nede &thorn;at o &thorn;ing beo &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; to alle &thorn;inges
for to ben: &thorn;at is to seien, of whom alle &thorn;inges ben.  &THORN;enne behoue&thorn; hit neede
&thorn;at he &thorn;orw whom alle &thorn;inges ben, be wi&thorn;oute bi-ginnyng.  For whi?  &yogh;if he
hedde biginnyng, hit bihouede &thorn;at he hedde hit of ano&thorn;er and &thorn;enne weore
he not &thorn;e biginnere nor &thorn;e makere of alle &thorn;inges, and &thorn;erfore hit bihoue&thorn;
nede &thorn;at he of whom alle &thorn;inges ben, be biforen alle &thorn;inges, and no &thorn;ing
biforen hym; and &yogh;if no &thorn;ing weore biforen him, &thorn;enne come&thorn; he not of ano&thorn;er;
&thorn;enne hedde he neuer bigynnying: ffor whi?  eueri &thorn;ing &thorn;at ha&thorn; biginnyng ha&thorn;
hit of ano&thorn;er, ffor whi &thorn;ing &thorn;at is not may not &yogh;iuen beoing to him-self for to
ben.  And &thorn;erfore hit bihoue&thorn; on alle maners &thorn;at o &thorn;ing be &thorn;at neuere hedde
biginnyng.  And whon Reson of mon seo&thorn; &thorn;at hit may non o&thorn;er wyse ben,
&thorn;enne he bigynne&thorn; to leeuen studefastliche &thorn;at on &thorn;ing is wi&thorn;outen bigynnyng,
&thorn;at is makere, ordeynere, and gouernere of alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at han ben or ben or
schul ben.  And &thorn;at &thorn;ing is cald god; ffor &thorn;is resun: ffor &thorn;is word god come&thorn;
of a word of Gru &thorn;at hi&yogh;te theym and is as muche to siggen as &laquo;formen&raquo; or
&laquo;norisschen&raquo;, and &thorn;erfore he is called god for he norissche&thorn; alle &thorn;ing and
formed alle &thorn;ing.  After &thorn;is come&thorn; Reson of Mon and sei&thorn; &thorn;at hit behoue&thorn;
nede &thorn;at on god beo and no mo: ffor whi?  &yogh;if two goddes weoren, hit bi-houe&thorn;
nede ben to muchel in bo&thorn;e, and to luitel, al at ones; &thorn;erfore hit bihoue&thorn; &thorn;at
&thorn;er be not but on god.  On o&thorn;ur halue: no good may God wonten, and &thorn;erfore,
for noble &thorn;ing and good is &thorn;e cumfort of cumpanye, &thorn;enne may not god ben
wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;e goodnesse of cumpanye: &thorn;enne hit behoue&thorn; nede &thorn;at persones


<PB N="1: 259">

ben in god.  And for cumpanye may not ben in lasse &thorn;en of tweyne, &thorn;erfore
hit bihoue&thorn; nede &thorn;at &thorn;er ben in god at &thorn;e leste tweyne persones.  And for
cumpaynye is luitel wor&thorn; &thorn;er is not &thorn;e byndynge of loue, &thorn;erfore hit bihoue&thorn;
&thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ridde persone beo in god, &thorn;at be &thorn;e linage of &thorn;e o&thorn;er tweyne.  And
for [unite] is go[o]d and cumpaynie also, &thorn;erfore hit behoue&yogh; nede &thorn;at bo&thorn;e be
in god almihti.  For-[&thorn;i] he is &thorn;reo persones and o god.  &THORN;e selue may eueri
mon sen in him-self: For whi?  he may seo wel, at his furste begynnyng he hedde
in him-self pouwer, aftur pouwer cunnynge, and aftur he bigon to louen &thorn;at
cunnynge.  In &thorn;is Manere may mon seon aperteliche &thorn;at he hedde in soule miht,
and of &thorn;e mi&yogh;t come&thorn; connynge, and of hem bo&thorn;e come&thorn; loue.  And whonne
mon se&thorn; &thorn;at hit is so in him-self, he may wel leeuen &thorn;at hit is so in God
almihti &thorn;at is muche abouen him; &thorn;at is to seyen: &thorn;at in God is miht, and of
&thorn;at come&thorn; his connynge and wisdam, and of hem bo&thorn;e come&thorn; loue.  And for
&thorn;e secunde persone come&thorn; of &thorn;e furste, and of hem bo&thorn;e &thorn;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;erfore is
&thorn;e forme icald God &thorn;e Fader, &thorn;e secunde God &thorn;e Sone, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde God &thorn;e
Holigost.  And for hit is [so] among vs &thorn;at &thorn;e ffader is feblere &thorn;en &thorn;e sone for elde,
and &thorn;e sone not so wys as &thorn;e ffader for &yogh;ou&thorn;e: ffor men scholde not &thorn;e selue
trouwen of God almihti, &thorn;erfore is pouwer apropre[d] to God &thorn;e Fader, wisdam
to God &thorn;e Sone; and for &thorn;e nome of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde s[oun]e&thorn; g[a]stli, &thorn;erfore is
apropred to him loue and swetnesse.  In &thorn;is Manere com mon furst to &thorn;e knowyng
of his creatour, how he is wi&thorn;-outen begynnynge, and whi he is called god, on
in substance and &thorn;reo [in] persones, and whi &thorn;e ffurste is called Fader, &thorn;e
secunde &thorn;e Sone, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;e Holigost.  In &thorn;is manere &thorn;ou schalt knowen &thorn;i
god.  Such manere of knowyng is foundement of Contemplacion. / And &thorn;erfore,
whon &thorn;ou hast in &thorn;is Manere stablised &thorn;in herte in ri&yogh;t fei&thorn;, and studefast hope,
and parfyt loue, &thorn;en &thorn;ou schalt heuen vp &thorn;in herte in hei&yogh; contemplacion of &thorn;i
Creatour.  &THORN;e soule wolde fayn sen god &thorn;orw Contemplacion in his owne nature,
but hit may not: and &thorn;enne hit turne&thorn; to his oune degres bi w&yogh;uche hit may
mounten to &thorn;e Contemplacion of God, &thorn;at hit may furst seon and knowen his
oune nature, and after &thorn;e nature &thorn;at is abouen hit.  But &yogh;if &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t be &thorn;orw
worldlich &thorn;ou&yogh;tes sprad wyde, hit may neuere him-self nor his kuynde wel seken,
ffor whi?  as fele [foule] &thorn;ou&yogh;tes as he is lad wi&thorn;, [wi&thorn;] so fele stoppynges he is blent. &THORN;e ffurste degre of &thorn;is-manere contemplacion is &thorn;at &thorn;e soule turne to him-self and gedere him al wi&thorn;-Inne him-self.  &THORN;e secunde degre is &thorn;at he seo what he is
whon he is so gedered to-gedere.  &THORN;e &thorn;ridde degre is &thorn;at he heue hire-self
abouen hire-self and enforce hire to sen god hire creatour in his oune kynde.
But to hire-self ne mai he neuer-more comen til &thorn;at he haue lerned forte
&yogh;einstonden and wi&thorn;holden alle Manere of ymaginacions bodili or worldli or heuenely;
al &thorn;at come&thorn; to his herte [of] siht, or heringe, or touchinge, or smellynge, or
of eny bodiliche wit, refusen or defoulen, &thorn;at he seo hire-self such w&yogh;uch &thorn;at
he is al wi&thorn;outen &thorn;e bodi. / Tac &thorn;erfore good heede &thorn;at [&thorn;e] soule is wonderful in
hire-self: hou hee is on in hire kuynde, and do&thorn; diuerse &thorn;inges, ffor whi?  &thorn;e
selue he seo&thorn; at &thorn;e E&yogh;en, here&thorn; at &thorn;e Eren, touche&thorn; wi&thorn; honden, swolewe&thorn;
wi&thorn; Mou&thorn; smelle&thorn; wi&thorn; neose.  &THORN;enk also &thorn;at heo is gret, &thorn;at of o &thorn;ou&yogh;t mai


<PB N="1: 260">

comprehende heue[n] and eor&thorn;e and al &thorn;at &thorn;er-inne is, &thorn;ei&yogh; [&thorn;ei] were a &thorn;ousend
grettore &thorn;en &thorn;ei mouwe ben. / &YOGH;if monnes [soule] beo so gret and so noble &thorn;at no
creature may attenden hit parfytliche: hou gret and hou noble is he &thorn;at so noble
&thorn;ing made of nou&yogh;t!  So gret: he is abouen alle &thorn;inge, beneo&thorn;en alle &thorn;inge,
and wi&thorn;-Inne alle &thorn;inge, and wi&thorn;-outen alle &thorn;inge.  He is abouen alle &thorn;ynge:
gouernynde; bine&thorn;en alle &thorn;inge vp-berynde; wi&thorn;-Inne alle &thorn;yng, fulfillynde;
wi&thorn;-outen alle &thorn;ynge, vironynde.  Such Maner of contemplacion ge[n]dere&thorn; in Mon
studefast bileeue &amp; siker deuocion.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e largesse of God.</HEAD>

<P>Affter &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken &thorn;at he is la[r]ge; and &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t sen in mony
maners.  Loke at &thorn;e ffurste &thorn;at he is large of wordly goodes, &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; his goodes
also to wikke as to goode, of alle-manere &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben in eor&thorn;e.  After &thorn;enk
hou he is large for to [for]-&yogh;iuen; ffor whi?  &yogh;if a Mon hedde I-don also monie
wikkednesses as al &thorn;e men in &thorn;e world, &yogh;it he wolde beo rediore forte for&yogh;iuen be
&thorn;e hundreddel, &thorn;en we scholden be to aske for&yogh;iuenesse.  Also &thorn;ou scha[l]t &thorn;enken
&thorn;at he is large of gostlich goodes, &thorn;at is to seyen of his vertues: ffor whi?  who
ha&thorn; on, he ha&thorn; alle.  &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e, &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken &thorn;at he is large of his
goodes pardurables, to alle &thorn;at wollen ri&yogh;tfolliche asken h[e]m.  For w&yogh;uche-manere
mi&yogh;t he don from vs &thorn;at &thorn;at he a-moneste&thorn; vs to asken?  on o&thorn;er halue he
wole &yogh;iuen vs gret mede so &thorn;at we wolen asken him; ffor he sei&thorn;: &laquo;Pre&yogh;e&thorn; me &yogh;iuen ow &thorn;e Ioye of heuene and I schal &yogh;iuen ou alle worldliche &thorn;inges wi&thorn;-outen askynge&raquo;.  &THORN;is Contemplacion of his largesse make&thorn; in mon certein hope.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e swetnesse of God.</HEAD>

<P>Affter &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;enken of his swetnesse, of his bounte, and of his ffeirnesse.
For to don &thorn;is, &thorn;ou schalt taken good hede of &thorn;e grete swetnesse, of gret bounte,
and of gret feirnesse &thorn;at is in bodiliche creature.  Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;enne &thorn;at suche &thorn;ingus
ben &thorn;at delyten bodilyche si&yogh;t for heore feirnesse, and &thorn;e swolewynge for heore
goodnesse, and &thorn;e smellynge for heore swetnesse, and so alle o&thorn;ure monnes
wittes: hou gret beute, swetnesse, and bounte [mot be in gostly creature &thorn;at neuer
schal haue ende, if such bounte, swetnesse &amp; beute be] in such &thorn;ing &thorn;at to-dai
is and to-morewe is nout.  On o&thorn;ur halue, &yogh;if gret beute, swetnes, and bounte
be in Creature, hou muche beute, swetnesse, and bounte mot ben in vre
Creatour!  &THORN;is Manere of Contemplacion make&thorn; in mon to louen his Creatour.  After,
whon &thorn;ou hast in &thorn;is Manere se&yogh;en &thorn;i Creatour in si&yogh;t of his creatures, put out
of &thorn;in herte vche bodilyche ymaginacion, and lift &thorn;in on entendement a-bouen
alle resun of Mon: [&] &thorn;er &thorn;ou schalt fynden so gret swetnesse, and so gret priuite,
&thorn;at non may felen but he &thorn;at hit ha&thorn; preued.  And &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt witen hit wi&thorn;
teching, go to him &thorn;at ha&thorn; proued hit be assaying.  And &thorn;ei&yogh; I wrecche hedde
I-proued hit, I mi&yogh;te not telle wi&thorn; mou&thorn;, no I mihte not &thorn;enken wi&thorn; herte; &thorn;e
&thorn;ing is so priue &thorn;at hit passe&thorn; al-maner &thorn;ouht.  And &thorn;erfore I holde my speche,
and riht is &thorn;at I do: ffor whi?  &thorn;is teche&thorn; not tonge, bute onliche grace.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>To lyuen Honorabliche, Loueredenliche, and Meokeliche.</HEAD>

<P>NOw &thorn;ou hast &thorn;reo Maners of Contemplacion: on is in creatures, a no&thorn;ur in
holi writ, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde in God self and in bo&thorn;e his natures.  &YOGH;if &thorn;ou liue aftur &thorn;is


<PB N="1: 261">

teching, &thorn;enne schaltou liuen honurabliche&mdash;[&] &thorn;at is &thorn;e furste parti of vre sarmoun
&thorn;at we toucheden at &thorn;e biginnyng. / After &thorn;is, &thorn;ou schalt studien to liuen
Amiabliche, as a-nentes &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur.  And &thorn;at to don, &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;iuen al &thorn;in entente and al &thorn;i streng&thorn;e forte louen and to be loued.  &THORN;ou schalt louen alle men in
god, &thorn;at is to seyen onliche for bounte, not for feirnesse of bodi ne for good
synginge or for such-maner &thorn;inges, ffor whi?  feirnesse of bodi, or streng&thorn;e, or
o&thorn;ur-maner vertues bodiliche, mouwen be loued wi&thorn;-outen God.  And &thorn;erfore,
louen mon in god, nis not elles but louen him for sum &thorn;ing &thorn;at may not be
loued wi&thorn;-outen God, as for bounte, or for riht, or for so&thorn;nes: ffor whi?  ffor
&thorn;eose &thorn;inges mai&yogh;t &thorn;ou not louen mon, but &yogh;if &thorn;ou loue god.  And &thorn;erfore whon &thorn;ou louest mon for bounte or for rihtfulnesse or for so&thorn;nesse, &thorn;enne &thorn;ou louest him in
god, ffor whi?  God is bounte, riht, and so&thorn;nesse.  &YOGH;if we ben goode, we haue no loue
but God, and non Enemy but synne: and &thorn;erfore we schulen loue &thorn;e goode for
&thorn;ei ben goode, and &thorn;e wikke for &thorn;ey mowen be goode.  In &thorn;is manere louestou
not but bounte, si&thorn;en &thorn;ow louest alle men for bounte.  &YOGH;if &thorn;ow wolt beon loued,
schew &thorn;e amyable: and &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt ben louereden, hold &thorn;eos &thorn;reo wordes: Do
&thorn;at me bidde&thorn; &thorn;e, smartliche; Tac &thorn;at me &yogh;iue&thorn; &thorn;e, wi&thorn;-outen grucchinge
gladliche; Soffre &thorn;at men sei&thorn; to &thorn;e, Mekeliche.  &YOGH;if &thorn;ow lyue &thorn;us louyndeliche,
&thorn;enne liuest &thorn;ow amyableliche. / After &thorn;ow schalt fynden to lyuen Mekeliche.
&THORN;ow schalt vnderstonden and witen &thorn;at &thorn;er beon twey Maners of Mekynge: On
come&thorn; of So&thorn;nesse, ano&thorn;er of Charite.  &THORN;e ffurste &thorn;ou may&yogh;t han &thorn;orw knowynge of &thorn;i-self: ffor &thorn;ow mai&yogh;t not seon &thorn;i-self so&thorn;liche w&yogh;uch &thorn;ow art, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne schald be Meked.  &THORN;e secounde Maner &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t seon and han, &yogh;if &thorn;ow &thorn;enke ofte of &thorn;e Mekenesse of Iesu Crist, how he Meked him &thorn;at neuer synne dude;
and &thorn;is Mekyng come&thorn; clanliche of Charite. / Now &thorn;ou wost what is to liuen
Honurabliche, Amyabliche, and Mekeliche; and &thorn;at is, liuen Parfytliche.  Vre
lord Ihesu Cryst graunte vs God so honouren, vre Bre&thorn;eren louen, and Vre-self
Meken, &thorn;at we mouwen for vre honouring ben honoured, ffor vre loue ben loued,
and for vre Meokyng beon hei&yogh;ed, in &thorn;e Ioye of heuene &thorn;at is ordeyned to vs.
AMen.  Ihesus graunt hit vs, amen.
</P></DIV4></DIV3>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text"> <HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Tractatus de dominica oracione secundum ....  &amp;c.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="209b" UNIT="folio">
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pater noster qui es in celis.</FOREIGN>  In all the wordes &thorn;at er stabillede and sett to say in erthe, &thorn;an es &thorn;e Pater noster &thorn;e beste, and &thorn;e hegheste and &thorn;e halyeste. For god hym-selfe made it, and commandide it to his appostills for to say, and to all &thorn;a &thorn;at in hyme trowede.  And &thorn;are-fore sene godde hym-selfe made it, &thorn;an awe it maste of all othire Orysouns to be Oysede in all-haly kyrke; and vs awe for to witte and certanly to vndirstande whate &thorn;is Orysone es to say and
what it be-menes, be-fore all o&thorn;er Orysounes.  For swylke may &thorn;ay be when
&thorn;ay say it, that it es mare to thaire skathe &thorn;ane to &thorn;aire gude.  And &thorn;arfore
sall I say &yogh;ow and make &yogh;ow to vndirstande what &thorn;e letter es to say and bemenys. /
When we say oure Pater noster, &thorn;an make we oure requestis till godde.  In &thorn;e firste requeste &thorn;an say we thus: &laquo;Owre ffadir &thorn;at es in heuene, blessede and


<PB N="1: 262">

halowede be &thorn;i name&raquo;.  Bot it are many when &thorn;ay say &thorn;aire Pater noster, &thorn;ay call godde &thorn;aire ffadire and with wrange &thorn;ay call hyme &thorn;aire ffadire, ffor &thorn;ay are noghte goddes sonnes thurghe na gude werkes &thorn;at &thorn;ay do, ne thurghe na
gude lyfe &thorn;at &thorn;ay lede, wharefore gode knawes thaym noghte for his sonnes, ffor
syne &thorn;at &thorn;e deuelle hase putte in thayme.  The wykkede mane &thorn;at dispyses godde
and his commandementes, and [takes] to &thorn;e werkes &thorn;at falles to &thorn;e deuelle, he
es noghte goddes sone bot &thorn;e deuelles sonne, als oure lorde hym-selfe saide to
&thorn;e Iewes &thorn;at made na tale of hyme: &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vos, Inquit, ex parte diaboli estis,</FOREIGN> &laquo;&YOGH;e are of &thorn;at ffadir &thorn;at es &thorn;e deuelle&raquo;.  &THORN;ane hase he myster &thorn;at will &thorn;at godde here his prayere, &thorn;at he do swylke werkes &thorn;at god of his grace wyll knawe hyme for hys sonne; &thorn;an may he ryghte say his Pater noster and call gode his
ffadire, and &thorn;ane will godde here hyme and do &thorn;at that he askes hym son&macr;e, if he
see &thorn;at it be [gud] for hyme &thorn;at at he askes hym.  And if he be noghte godde
sonne, ne godde knawes hyme noghte for his sonne, godd will noghte here his
prayers, ffor haly writt saise, &thorn;at es to say godd hym-selfe: &para; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Deus peccatores non audit,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say, &laquo;Godde heres noghte &thorn;e synfull mene&raquo;.  We sall
vndirstande &thorn;at &thorn;ay er synfull &thorn;at gyffes neuer tale of godde, bot gladlyer duse &thorn;e
werkes of &thorn;e deuelle &thorn;an goddes commandementes.  &THORN;are-fore ilke a mane amende
hym and lede haly lyfe whare-thurghe he may be-comme goddes sonne, and &thorn;an
will godde here hyme and his prayere, and &thorn;an he may hardely say these wordes
&laquo;Owre fadir &thorn;at es in heuene: halowede and blyssede be &thorn;i name&raquo;.  Es noghte
godde name ay blyssede and haly?  &YOGH;is, in hym-selfe may he noghte mare be
blysside ne halowede &thorn;ane he es.  Bot &thorn;ane sall &yogh;e vndirstande &thorn;at whene we
say &laquo;blyssede be &thorn;i name&raquo;, we praye noghte gode &thorn;at his name be blyssede in
hym-selfe, bot in thayme in whayme it es noghte &yogh;it blissede, and in thaym in
whaym it es noghte ynoghe blissede.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sanctificetur nomen tuum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say &laquo;Lorde godde, thi nam be blissede in &thorn;e hertes of paynymmes i. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">paganorum</FOREIGN>, and Iewes, and in &thorn;e mystrowande, and in all &thorn;a &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase puruayde to be safede,
&thorn;at &thorn;ay stalleworthlere trowe in &thorn;e and &thorn;e mare loue &thorn;e and knawe &thorn;e for
&thorn;aire godde and lorde of all thynge.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Adueniat regnum tuum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Com-to &thorn;i kyngdome&raquo;.  God es kyng and gouernes euere his kyngdome, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia ipse gubernat omnes creaturas suas que sunt in celo et in terra, in mari et in
omnibus abissis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;he gouernes all his creaturs &thorn;at er in heuene,
in erthe, and in &thorn;e see, and in all &thorn;e werlde&raquo;: and noghte-ffor-thi if he be
kynge and his kyngdome es all tymes, and regnes ay, neuer-&thorn;e-lesse we praye
hym &thorn;at he comme to his kyngdome, ffor it es many a mane in erthe &thorn;at trowes
&thorn;at god regnes noghte, bot wate wele &thorn;at &thorn;e deuelle regnes thurghe synne: and
whene we say <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">adueniat regnum tuum</FOREIGN>, &thorn;an praye we god &thorn;at he destruye &thorn;e deuelles kyngdome and his folke, and &thorn;at he put in &thorn;aym &thorn;e lawe and &thorn;e gudnes and the halynes &thorn;at he hase donne in vs and in &thorn;aym &thorn;at hym luefes, in whayme he rengnes thurghe grace.  And &yogh;it praye we to hyme whene we say <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">adueniat regnum tuum</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at he come at &thorn;e endynge of &thorn;is worlde: &thorn;at his Enemys may
see and trowe &thorn;at he es verray gode kynge alweldande; and at hally kyrke namely
sall be heghede in heuene and in erthe, and hir sonnes and doghters&mdash;&para; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quando fenito hoc seculo solus deus regnat, quia ipse erit omnia in omnibus cum euanuerint


<PB N="1: 263">

omnes principatus et potestates et virtutes, nec amplius angelus angelo vel homo
homini out demon demoni dominabitur.  &para; Fiat voluntas tua sicut in celo et in terra,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es to say: &raquo;&THORN;inne awene will be donne in erthe als it es donne in heuene&raquo;.
Lordynges, in heuene es goddes wylle donne perfitely, &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quia Angeli Archangeli Principatus Potestates Virtutes Troni Dominaciones Cherubyn Cyraphyn, Patriarche et Prophete, Apostoli Martires Confessores Virgines, et omnes electorum anime obediunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;ffor Angells, Archangells &amp;c., and all &thorn;e sawles &thorn;at er
in heuene before gode, er bowande till hyme, and perfitely wirkes his will and
duse his commandemente&yogh;&raquo;.  Bot it er many in erthe &thorn;at duse &thorn;e thyng &thorn;at god
walde noghte ware done: and &thorn;are-fore pray we whene we saye <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">ffiat volu[n]tas tua &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es &laquo;lorde god, als &thorn;a &thorn;at er in heuene duse thi will perfitely ffor
&thorn;e gret gudnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase gyffene to thayme in heuene, swa &thorn;ou gyffe vs grace
to clense vs of syne and do &thorn;i will in &thorn;is werlde, &thorn;at we may se &thorn;i face with
thynne appostells, erchebechopes and bechopes, prestes, and all &thorn;e ordirs of
haly kirke&raquo;.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis hodie,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;&thorn;ou gyffe vs to-day oure ilke a day brede&raquo;.  Mane, &thorn;at es of twa naturs, &thorn;at es to say of bodyly and of gastely, hase myster of twa maners of brede: of bodyly brede and of gastely brede.  To &thorn;e saule &thorn;is gastely brede es &thorn;e lerynge and &thorn;e
techeynge and &thorn;e vndirstandynge in &thorn;e commandementes of godde, whare-thurghe
&thorn;e saule es kennede an[d] lyffes.  &THORN;e to&thorn;er brede es to &thorn;e hele of body, and &thorn;at
aske we gladly.  Bot aske we bathe, and &thorn;ane sall we fare wele.  Bot aske we
mare and oftere &thorn;e brede of saule, &thorn;an &thorn;e brede of body: ffor whene &thorn;e body
hase &thorn;at that it will, and &thorn;e saule dyes for hungere, &thorn;at es to say es noghte
kennde als it aughte to be, &thorn;ane sall bathe &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saule wende to &thorn;e
fyre of helle.  Bot and it be louede and fedde with gud techynge and duse
&thorn;are-Eftyr &thorn;at it awe to doo, &thorn;an sall bathe &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saule Entir in to &thorn;e
Ioye of heuene &thorn;at aye sall laste.  &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et dimitte nobis debita nostra sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus nostris,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;and forgyffe vs oure mysdedis als
we forgyffe to &thorn;aym &thorn;at hase mysdone vs&raquo;.  Here may we here &thorn;at we &thorn;at will
at godde forgyffe vs oure synnes, &thorn;at vs behuffes forgyffe &thorn;aym &thorn;at hase mysdone
vs, &thorn;at es to saye if he or &thorn;ay &thorn;at hase mysdone will come and aske mercy
and hete resonabill amendment; bot if we &thorn;an forgyffe &thorn;aym, in vayne say we
oure Pater noster.  For if we say it and will noghte forgyffe, &thorn;ane say we it to
oure awene scathe, and &thorn;are ware vs better sitt still &thorn;an pray god one &thorn;is manere,
till &thorn;at tym &thorn;at we will forgyffe als vs awe for to do.  Forgyffe we &thorn;ane to o&thorn;er
when &thorn;ay aske vs forgyffenes and hetes and offirs amendement, if we will &thorn;at
godd forgyffe vs oure synn&macr;s: ffor oure lorde saise in &thorn;e gospell: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Eadem mensura qua messi fueritis remecietur vobis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;with &thorn;e same mesure &thorn;at &thorn;ou
mesure to o&thorn;er, sall be mesurede to the&raquo;.  &para; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Suffere vs noghte swa ferre to be assayede, sa ferre to be temped,
&thorn;at we be ledde in to ill dedis&raquo;.  For &thorn;e deuell es abowte nyghte and day for to
luke if he may take any mane and bryng hyme in to any ill thoghtes or dedis.
He assayes &thorn;e gude mene and womene, als monkes or chanouns or heremytes, or
perfit Non&macr;nes &amp; gude womene, and many o&thorn;er Relegeous and vertuouse mene
and womene, pure and riche, for to drawe theyme vn-till ill dedis or ill thoghtes,


<PB N="1: 264">

ffor he walde ger &thorn;ame fall in syne.  Bot &thorn;e gude mene and womene defendis
&thorn;ame stallworthely fra hym and his werkes and his wyles with ffastynges, Orysones,
gud meditacyones, and o&thorn;er gud dedis: and forthi ressayfe &thorn;ay &thorn;e corounne of
lyfe &thorn;at god hase highte to all &thorn;at hyme luffes.  &para; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Set libera nos a malo,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Delyuer vs of all euyles, of body and of saule, &thorn;at es fra wikkydnes of &thorn;e werlde, and of &thorn;e to&thorn;er &thorn;at es fra s&ymacr;nne, and of &thorn;e thirde &thorn;at es fra &thorn;e
paynes of helle&raquo;.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Amen,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say &laquo;witterly forsothe, with-owttene any
defaute&raquo;, and affermes all &thorn;e thynges &thorn;at we aske godde in oure Pater noster:
with-owtene defaute Oure ffadir &thorn;at es in heuene blissede be thi name; and
with-owttene any defaute Come-to thi kyngdome; with-owttene any defaute Done be
thi will in erthe als in heuene; with-owttene any defaute Gyffe vs to-day oure
ilke day brede; withowttene any defaute fforgyffe vs oure syn&macr;nes als we forgyffe
thayme &thorn;at hase synnede in vs, &thorn;at es to say trespaste agaynes vs; with-owttene
defaute Suffere noghte &thorn;e deuelle to assaye vs ne lede vs in to temptacione ne
in to nane ill dedis; with-owttene any defaute Delyuer vs fra all ill.  And ffadir
endeles, with-owttene any delaynge gyffe vs &thorn;e gudenes of lyffe and hele of oure
saules &thorn;at es thi-selfene.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Que nobis prestare dingneris qui vivis &amp; regnas &amp;c. Explicit.</FOREIGN>
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Benedicta sit sancta trinitas.  Amen.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>(Walter Hilton's) On the Mixed Life</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a. 1)" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a.1)</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="353" UNIT="folio">
<OPENER>Here beginne&thorn; a luitel Boc &thorn;at was writen to a worldli lord to teche him hou
he schulde haue him in his state in ordeynd loue to god and to his euencristene.</OPENER><DIV4
TYPE="section">
<P> Whi gode desyres neode&thorn; to be reuled be discrecion, &amp; medeful werkes to be
  wrou&yogh;t in &thorn;e ordre of charite: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca[p]<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>. primo.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at &thorn;e lyf of Marie and Martha menged to-gedere is acordyng to hem &thorn;at are
  in hi&yogh; degre <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. ii<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>To whom actif lyf a-corde&thorn;, &amp; to whom contemplatyf <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. iii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>Hou medled lyf longe&thorn; speciali to prelates of holychurche &amp; also to worldly lordes
  &thorn;at rulen o&thorn;ur men <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. iiii<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>Hou vre lord Ihesu Crist &amp; holy men in hei&yogh; degre schewed ensaumple in lyuing
of medlet lyf <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. v<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>

<PB N="1: 265">

To whom medled lyf is most a-cordyng, &amp; to whom contemplatyf is most medeful <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. vi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>Here hit is schewed what lyf is most a-cording to him &thorn;at &thorn;is bok was maad to
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. vii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at men schulde vse medlet lyf as a man schulde haue him to Crist &amp; to his limes <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. viii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at sum-tyme schulde a lord leue gostli ocupacion &amp; gladli &yogh;eue him to medeful
  worldli werkes <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. ix<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>

<PB N="1: 266">

How be ensaumple of Iacob &amp; his two wyues men schal ruile hem ri&yogh;t in medlet
  lyf <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. x<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at contemplacion shulde be had in desyre, &amp; actyf werkes in vse wi&thorn;outen
  anger and vnskilful drede <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xi<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at nedful worldli werkes kyndel gostli desyres, proued be bodili ensaumple
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>
How be mekenes &amp; diuerse gode werkes is &thorn;e loue of god norissched in diuerse
  mennes hertes <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xiii<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
How &thorn;e desyr of loue wate&thorn; al synne &amp; is a gret cri&yogh;ing in &thorn;e eres of vr lord
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>What desyre is, &amp; siker swetnes <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xv<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>What difference is be-twixe desyre &amp; &thorn;e loue of god <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xvi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN><LB>
Hou desyre may euer be lastyng in habyte, &amp; not in workyng, &amp; hou mekenes wi&thorn;-oute schewe&thorn; &thorn;is disyr <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xvii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>How aftur &thorn;i sleep &thorn;ou schalt quiken &thorn;in herte wi&thorn; preieres &amp; gode &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &amp;   put away vuel &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &thorn;at letten deuocion <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xviii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>Hou ordeyned &thorn;enkyng of &thorn;in owne synnes and of o&thorn;ur mennes norisschen &thorn;i desyr to god <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xix<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at diuerse &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of &thorn;e manhed of vre lord discretly vsed norissche&thorn; &thorn;i desyr
  to god <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xx<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t of moni vertues norissche&thorn; &thorn;i desyr to god <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t of diuerse seyntes &amp; of heore vertues norissche&thorn; &thorn;i loue to god <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e merci of vre lord schewed to synful men norissche&thorn; &thorn;i desyr to god <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e wrecchednes of men, &amp; of &thorn;e ioyes of heuene norissche&thorn; &thorn;i desyr to god <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxiiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>How desyre of worldly worschipe, and &thorn;e desyr of heuen, is meeded at &thorn;e last
  ende <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxv<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>Hou discrecion is nedful in &thorn;enkyng and preying, and hou hit is sum-tyme to
  passe from &thorn;at on to &thorn;at o&thorn;er <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>. xxvi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>How a man schal haue him in &thorn;enkyng of &thorn;e passion of vre lord Ihesu. Whon
  deuocion laste&thorn; &amp; whon hit passe&thorn; away <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>. xxvii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
<LB>Hou a man schal haue him warli in &thorn;ou&yogh;t and desire &amp; wysely vse &thorn;e grace &thorn;at
  god ha&thorn; &yogh;eue to him <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxviii<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN>
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&THORN;e Prologe.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;e grace &amp; &thorn;e goodnes of vr lord Ihesu &thorn;at he ha&thorn; schewed to &thorn;e in
wi&thorn;drawyng of &thorn;in herte from loue &amp; lyking of worldli vanyte &amp; vse of fleschli
synnes, &amp; in turnyng of &thorn;i wille enterli to his seruise &amp; his plesaunce, bringe&thorn;


<PB N="1: 267">

in to myn herte muche matere for to loue him in his merci, and also hit stere&thorn;
me gretly for to streng&thorn;e &thorn;e in &thorn;i gode purpos &amp; in &thorn;i gode worching &thorn;at &thorn;ou
hast be-gunne, for to bringe hit to a good ende &yogh;if &thorn;at i coude, principali for
god, and also for tender affeccion of loue w&yogh;uch &thorn;ou hast to me &thorn;ou&yogh; i be a
wrecche &amp; vnwor&thorn;i.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  Whi gode desyre neode&thorn; to be ruled be discrecion, and medeful werkes to be wrou&yogh;t in ordre of charite.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo primo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>I knowe wel &thorn;e desyre of &thorn;in herte, &thorn;at &thorn;ou coueytest gretli for to serue vr
lord be gostli ocupacion al hol[i] wi&thorn;-oute lettyng or troublyng of worldli bisynes:
&thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t be grace come to more knowyng [&] gostly felyng of go[d] &amp; gostly
&thorn;inges.  &THORN;is desyr is good as I hope, &amp; of god, for hit is charite, speciali set
in to him.  Neuer&thorn;eles hit is to refreyne and to rule hit be discrecion as a&yogh;eynes
outwarde doyng, aftur &thorn;e state &thorn;at &thorn;ou art in, ffor charite vnruled turne&thorn;
sumtyme to vice.  And &thorn;erfore hit is seid in holi writ: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ordinauit in me caritatem,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at is to say: &laquo;Vre lord &yogh;af to me charite set in ordre &amp; in rule, &thorn;at hit schulde not be lost &thorn;orw myn vndiscrecion&raquo;.  Riht so &thorn;is charite &amp; &thorn;is desyr &thorn;at vre lord of his merci ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen to &thorn;e, is for to rule &amp; to ordeyne hou &thorn;ou schalt pursue hit, aftur &thorn;i de-gree aske&thorn;, and aftur &thorn;e liuyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast vsed
before &thorn;is tyme, and after &thorn;e grace of vertu &thorn;at &thorn;ou nou hast.  &THORN;ou schalt not
vtturli folwe &thorn;i desyre for to leue ocupacions &amp; bisynes of &thorn;e world w&yogh;uch are
nedeful to vse in rulyng of &thorn;i-sel[f] &amp; of al o&thorn;ur &thorn;at are vnder &thorn;i keping, &amp; &yogh;eue &thorn;e hol[i] to gostly occupacion in preyers &amp; meditacions as hit were a Monk or a
frere or eny o&thorn;ur mon &thorn;at were not bounde to &thorn;e world be children &amp; seruauns
as &thorn;ou art: for hit falle&thorn; not to &thorn;e; &yogh;if &thorn;ou do so, &thorn;ou kepest not &thorn;e ordre of
charite.  Also, &yogh;if &thorn;ou woldest vtterli leue gostli occupacion, nomeli aftur &thorn;e
grace &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &yogh;euen to &thorn;e, &amp; sette &thorn;e holliche to bisynes of &thorn;e world, to
fulfillyng of actif lyf, as fully as a-no&thorn;ur &thorn;at neuer feled deuocion, &thorn;ou leosest
&thorn;e ordre of charite: for &thorn;i stat aske&thorn; for to do bo&thorn;e, in diuerse tymes.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  &THORN;at &thorn;e lyf of Marie &amp; Martha menged to-geder is acording to hem &thorn;at are in hei&yogh; degre.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo secundo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;ow schalt medle &thorn;e werkes of actif lyf wi&thorn; gostly werkes of contemplatyf
lyf, and &thorn;en dost &thorn;ou wel.  For &thorn;ou schalt o tyme wi&thorn; Martha be bisy ffor to
ruile &amp; gouerne &thorn;in houshold, &thorn;i children, &thorn;i seruauns, &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebors, and &thorn;i
tenauntes;&mdash;&yogh;if &thorn;ei do wel, cumforte hem &thorn;erin &amp; help hem; &yogh;if &thorn;ei don vuel, tech hem to amende hem, &amp; chastise hem.  And &thorn;ou [schalt] also loke &amp; knowe wysli &thorn;at &thorn;i &thorn;inges &amp; &thorn;i worldly godes be ri&yogh;tly kept be &thorn;i seruauntes, gouerned &amp; trewely dispendet: &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;e more plenteuousli wi&thorn; hem fulfille &thorn;e dedes of merci to &thorn;in euencristen.  A no&thorn;ur tyme &thorn;ou schalt wi&thorn; Marie leue &thorn;e bisynes of &thorn;e world &amp; sitte doun at &thorn;e feet of vr lord be mekenes in preyers &amp; holy &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &amp; in contemplacion of him as he &yogh;eue&thorn; &thorn;e grace.  And so schalt &thorn;ou


<PB N="1: 268">

go from &thorn;at on to &thorn;at o&thorn;ur meedfulli &amp; folfille bo&thorn;e: &amp; &thorn;enne kepest &thorn;ou wel &thorn;e ordre of charite.  Neuer&thorn;eles, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne haue no wonder of &thorn;is &thorn;at I say,
&thorn;erfore I schal tel &amp; declare to &thorn;e a luytel of &thorn;is matere more openli.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>To whom actyf lyf a-corde&thorn;, &amp; to whom contemplatif.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. iii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;ow schalt vnderstande &thorn;at &thorn;er is &thorn;reo maner of liuinges: On is actyf,
ano&thorn;ur contemplatyf, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is maad of bo&thorn;e &amp; is medled lyf.  Actyf lyf
alon longe&thorn; to worldly men &amp; wymmen whuch are lewed, fleschly, &amp; boistous in
knowyng of gostly occupacion, ffor &thorn;ei fele no sauour ne deuocion be feruour
of loue as o&thorn;ur men don, &thorn;ei can no skile of hit, and &yogh;it neuer&thorn;eles &thorn;ei han
drede of god &amp; of &thorn;e peynes of helle &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei fle synne, and &thorn;ei haue
also desyre for to plese god &amp; for to come to heuene, &amp; a good wille to heore
euencristne.  To &thorn;ise men hit is nedeful &amp; spedeful to vse werkes of actyf lyf
as bisili as &thorn;ei may, in help of hem-self &amp; of heore euencristen: for &thorn;ei can not
elles do.  Contemplatyf lyf alone longe&thorn; to such men or wymmen &thorn;at for &thorn;e
loue of god forsaken al open synnes of &thorn;e world &amp; of heore flesch, &amp; al
bisynes, charges &amp; gouernaunce of worldly godes, and maken hem pore &amp; naked,
in to &thorn;e bare nede of &thorn;e bodili kuynde, and fleen from souereynte of o&thorn;ur men
to &thorn;e seruise of god.  To &thorn;ise men hit longe&thorn; for to trauayle &amp; ocupye hem
[inwardli] for to gete &thorn;orw &thorn;e grace of vr lord clannes in herte &amp; pees in
conscience be distruyng of sinnes &amp; receiuyng of vertues, and so forto come to
contemplacion; &thorn;e w&yogh;uche clannes may not be had wi&thorn;-oute gret exercise bodili &amp; continuel trauayl of spirit in deuoute preiers, feruent desyres and gostly meditacions.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  How medled lyf longe&thorn; speciali to prelates of holichirche &amp; also to worldly lordes &thorn;at rule o&thorn;er men.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo iiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E &thorn;ridde lyf, &thorn;at is medlet, longe&thorn; speciali to men of holy churche, as to
prelates and to o&thorn;ur curates, &thorn;e w&yogh;uche han cure &amp; souereynte ouer o&thorn;ur men
for to kepe &amp; rule hem, bo&thorn;e heore bodies &amp; principali here soules, in fulfillyng
of &thorn;e dedes of merci, bodily &amp; gostly.  To &thorn;ise men hit longe&thorn; sum-tyme to
vse werkes of actyf lyf, in help &amp; in sustinaunce of hem-self &amp; of her soiettes &amp; of o&thorn;ure also, and sum-tyme [forto] leue al bisynes outward and &yogh;iue hem for a tyme
to preyers, meditacions, redynges of holi writ, &amp; to o&thorn;er gostly ocupacions, after
&thorn;ei fele hem disposed.  Also hit longe&thorn; generali to sum temporal men &thorn;e w&yogh;uche
han souereynte wi&thorn; muche hauyng of worldly godes, and also han as hit were
a lordschipe ouer o&thorn;ur men to gouerne &amp; susteyne hem, as a fader ha&thorn; ouer his
children, a Maister ouer his seruauntes, and a lord ouer his tenauntes; &thorn;e w&yogh;uche
men also han receyued of &thorn;e &yogh;ift of vr lord grace of deuocion, &amp; in parti sauour
of gostli ocupacion.  To &thorn;ise also longe&thorn; &thorn;is medled lyf, &thorn;at is bo&thorn;e actyf &amp; contemplatyf.  For &yogh;if &thorn;ise men stondynge &thorn;e charge &amp; &thorn;e bond &thorn;at &thorn;ei han
take, wolde leue vtturly &thorn;e bisynes of &thorn;e world, &thorn;e w&yogh;uche ou&yogh;te skilfulli be
vsed [in] fulfillyng of heor charge, and hol[i] &yogh;eue hem to lyf contemplatyf, &thorn;ei do


<PB N="1: 269">

not wel, for &thorn;ei kepe not &thorn;e ordre of charite.  For charite, as &thorn;ou knowest, li&thorn;
bo&thorn;e in loue of god &amp; of &thorn;in euen-cristne, and &thorn;erfore hit is resonable &thorn;at he
&thorn;at ha&thorn; charite vse bo&thorn;e in worchinge, now &thorn;at on now &thorn;at o&thorn;ur.  For he &thorn;at
for &thorn;e loue of god in contemplacion leue&thorn; &thorn;e loue of his euen-cristen [&amp; do&thorn;
not to hem] as him ou&yogh;te whon he is bounden &thorn;erto, he fulfille&thorn; not charite.  Also
on &thorn;e contrarie wyse who so ha&thorn; so gret reward to werkes of actyf lyf &amp; to
bisynes of &thorn;e world &thorn;at for loue of his euencristen he leue&thorn; gostli ocupacion
vtterliche, aftur god ha&thorn; disposed him &thorn;erto, he fulfille&thorn; not fulli charite.  &THORN;is
is &thorn;e seying of seynt Gregore.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  Hou vre lord Ihesu Crist &amp; holi men in hei&yogh; degre schewed ensaumple of medled lyf in lyuyng.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo v<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Oure lord for to stere sum men to vse &thorn;is medled lyf, tok vpon him-self &thorn;e
persones of such maner of men, bo&thorn;e of prelates &amp; curates of holy chirche, &amp; of
o&thorn;ur suche as are disposed as I haue seid, and &yogh;af to hem ensaumple be his
owne worchyng &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulde vse &thorn;is medled lyf as he dude.  O tyme he
comuned &amp; medled wi&thorn; men, schewyng to hem his dedes [of] merci: ffor he tau&yogh;t
&thorn;e vnkonnyng be his preching, he visyted &thorn;e seke &amp; heled hem of heor sores,
he fedde &thorn;e hungri, &amp; cumforted hem &thorn;at were sori.  Ano&thorn;ur tyme he lafte &thorn;e
conuersacion of al worldly men, &amp; of his disciples also, &amp; went alone in to desert
vpon &thorn;e hulles, &amp; contyn[u]ed al &thorn;e ni&yogh;t in preyers as &thorn;e gospel sei&thorn;.  &THORN;is medled lyf schewed vr lord in him-self to ensaumple of hem &thorn;at han take &thorn;e staat &amp; &thorn;e charge of &thorn;is medled lyf, &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulde o tyme &yogh;eue hem to bisynes of
worldly &thorn;ynges in resonable nede, &amp; to werkes of actyf lyf in profyt of heor
euencristne w&yogh;uch &thorn;ei haue cure of; ano&thorn;ur tyme &yogh;eue hem hol[i] to contemplacion be deuocion, in preyer &amp; in meditacion.  &THORN;is lyf led[d]en &amp; vse[de]n &thorn;is holy bisschops herbifore w&yogh;uch hedden cure of mennes soules &amp; mynistracion of temporel godes. For &thorn;ise holy men left not vtterli &thorn;e ministracion ne &thorn;e loky[n]g &amp; &thorn;e disp[end]yng of worldli godes, ne &yogh;af hem hol[i] to contemplacion, as muche grace as &thorn;ei had in contemplacion: but &thorn;ei lafte ful of[t] her oune rest in contemplacion, whon
&thorn;ei hedde leuere han ben stille &thorn;erat, for loue of heor euen-cristen, and entermetede
hem wi&thorn; worldli bisynes in helpyng of heor soiettes: &amp; so&thorn;li &thorn;at was charite.
For wysli &amp; discretli &thorn;ei departed heore [lyuyng] in two: O tyme &thorn;ei fulfilled &thorn;e
lower partye of charite be werkes of actyf lyf, for &thorn;ei were bounde &thorn;erto be
takyng of heore prelacie, ano&thorn;ur tyme &thorn;ei fulfilled &thorn;e hi&yogh;ore partye of charite in
contemplacion of god &amp; of gostly &thorn;ingus be preyers &amp; meditacions&mdash;&amp; so &thorn;ei hedde ful charite to god &amp; to her euencristen, bo&thorn;e in affeccion of here soule wi&thorn;-inne and in schewyng of bodili dedes wi&thorn;-oute.  O&thorn;ur men &thorn;at were only contemplatyf and were fre from al suche cures &amp; prelacies, &thorn;ei hedde ful charite to god &amp; to heore euencristen, but hit was only in affeccion of heore soule, nou&yogh;t euer outward in schewyng, and in hap so muche hit was &thorn;e more ful inward &thorn;at hit was not
letted be outward dedes; ffor &thorn;ei mi&yogh;t not, ne hit neded not, ne hit fel not to hem.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">

<PB N="1: 270"><HEAD>To whom medled lyf is most a-cordyng, and to whom contemplatyf lyf is most medeful.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo sexto.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>But &thorn;ise men &thorn;at were in prelacie, &amp; o&thorn;ure also &thorn;at were hole temporel men,
hedde ful charite in affeccion wi&thorn;-inne &amp; also in worchyng wi&thorn;-oute: &amp; &thorn;at is
propurli &thorn;is medled lyf, &thorn;at is maad bo&thorn;e of actyf lyf &amp; of contemplatif lyf.  And
so&thorn;li to such a man &thorn;at is in spiritual souereynte as prelacye, in cure &amp; gouernaunce
of o&thorn;ure as prelates &amp; curates are, or in temporal souereynte as worldly lordes &amp; maistres are, I holde &thorn;is medled lyf best &amp; most bihoueli to hem, as longe as
&thorn;ei are bounde &thorn;erto.  But [to] o&thorn;ure, &thorn;at are fre &amp; not bounde to temporal
ministracion ne to spiritual, I hope &thorn;at lyf contemplatif alone, &yogh;if &thorn;ei mi&yogh;t come
so&thorn;fastly &thorn;erto, were best &amp; most medeful, most feir &amp; most spedeful, &amp; most wor&thorn;i to hem for to vse &amp; to holde, &amp; not forto leue hit wilfulli for non
out-ward werkes of actyf lyf, but &yogh;if hit were in gret nede &amp; gret releuyng &amp; cumfortyng of o&thorn;ur men, ou&thorn;ur of her bodies or of her soules.  &THORN;en, &yogh;if ned aske,
at &thorn;e preyer &amp; &thorn;e instaunce of o&thorn;ure, or elles at &thorn;e biddyng of heore souereyns,
I hope hit is good to hem for to schewe outward werkes of actyf lyf for a tyme
in helpyng of heore euencristene.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">

<PB N="1: 271"><HEAD>Here hit is schewed what lyf is most a-cordyng to [him] &thorn;at &thorn;is bok was mad to.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo septimo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Be &thorn;is &thorn;at I haue seid &thorn;ow may in partye vnderstande w&yogh;uch is o lyf &amp; w&yogh;uch
o&thorn;ur, &amp; w&yogh;uch acorde&thorn; most to &thorn;i staat of liuinge.  And so&thorn;li, as me &thorn;inke&thorn;, &thorn;is medled lyf a-corde&thorn; most to &thorn;e.  For se&thorn; vre lord ha&thorn; ordeyned &thorn;e &amp; set &thorn;e in &thorn;e stat of souereynte ouur o&thorn;ur men as muche as hit is, and lente &thorn;e
abundaunce of worldli godes for to rule &amp; susteyne speciali alle &thorn;o &thorn;at are vnder
&thorn;i gouernaunce &amp; &thorn;i lordschipe in &thorn;i mi&yogh;t &amp; &thorn;i cunnyng; and also &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al aftur &thorn;ou hast receyued grace of &thorn;e merci of vre lord for to haue sum-what knowyng of &thorn;i-self &amp; gostli desyr &amp; sauour of his loue: I hope &thorn;at &thorn;is lyf &thorn;at is medled is best &amp; most acordyng to &thorn;e for to trauayle in.  And &thorn;at is forte departe wysli &thorn;i lyuynge in two: o tyme to &thorn;at on, and ano&thorn;ur tyme to &thorn;at o&thorn;ur.  For, wite &thorn;ou wel, &yogh;if &thorn;ou leue nedful bisynes of actyf lyf, &amp; be recheles &amp; take no kepe of &thorn;i worldly godes, hou &thorn;ei be kept &amp; spended, ne haue no force of &thorn;i soiettes &amp; of &thorn;in euencristen, be cause of desyre &amp; wille &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast only for to &yogh;eue &thorn;e to gostly ocupacion, wenyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou art &thorn;erbi excused: &yogh;if &thorn;ou do so, &thorn;ou dost not wysli. What are alle &thorn;i werkes wor&thorn;, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei be bodili or gostli, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei be don ri&yogh;tfulli &amp; resonably, to &thorn;e worschipe of god &amp; at his biddyng?  so&thorn;li, ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  &THORN;at men schulde vse medled lyf as a mon schulde haue him to Crist &amp; to his lymes.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. viii.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;en, &yogh;if &thorn;ou leue &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou art bounde to be wei of charite in ri&yogh;t
&amp; in resun, and wolt holli &yogh;iue &thorn;e to an o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing wilfulli as hit were for more
plesaunce to god w&yogh;uch &thorn;ou art not bounde to fully: &thorn;ou dost not worschipe


<PB N="1: 272">

discretly to him.  &THORN;ou art bisy to worschipe his hed &amp; his face, &amp; array hit fayre
&amp; curiously, but &thorn;ou leuest his bodi, his armes &amp; his feet, al ragged &amp; rent &amp; takest no kepe &thorn;erof.  &amp; &thorn;enne worschipest him nou&yogh;t: ffor hit is a vilenye to a
mon for to be curiousli arrayed vpon his hed wi&thorn; perre &amp; precious stones, &amp; al
his bodi be naked &amp; bare as hit were a beggere.  Riht so hit is, gostly, no
worschipe to god &thorn;at his hed be keuered, &amp; leue his bodi bare.  &THORN;ow schalt
vnderstande &thorn;at vre lord Ihesu Crist as man is hed of a gostly bodi, &thorn;e w&yogh;uche
is holy chirche.  &THORN;e limes of &thorn;is bodi are al cristen men.  Summe are armes, and
summe are feet, and summe are o&thorn;ur limes, aftur diuerse worchynges &thorn;at &thorn;ei vse
in here liuing.  &THORN;enne &yogh;if &thorn;ou be bisy wi&thorn; al &thorn;i mi&yogh;t for to aray his hed, &thorn;at
is for to worschipe him-self be mynde of his passion or of his o&thorn;ur werkes in
his manhede be deuocion &amp; meditacion of him, and for&yogh;etest his feet, &thorn;at are &thorn;i
children, &thorn;i seruauns, &thorn;i tenans &amp; al &thorn;in euencristen, &amp; letest hem spille for defaute of keping, vnarayed, [vnkept], &amp; not tended to as hem ou&yogh;te for to be; &thorn;ou plesest him nou&yogh;t, &thorn;ou dost no worschipe to him.  &THORN;ou makest &thorn;e to cus his mou&thorn; be deuocion of gostly preyere, but &thorn;ou tredest vpon his feet &amp; defoulest hem, in as
muche as &thorn;ou wolt not tende to hem for necclygence of &thorn;i-self of w&yogh;uche &thorn;ou
hast take cure.  &THORN;us me seme&thorn;.  Neuer&thorn;eles &yogh;if &thorn;ou &thorn;inke &thorn;at hit is not so&thorn;,
for hit were a fayr[er] offys to worschipe &thorn;e hed of him, as be ocupied al day in
meditacion of his manhede, &thorn;en forto go lower to o&thorn;ur werkes &amp; make clene his


<PB N="1: 273">

feet, as for to be bisy bo&thorn;e in &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; in dede aboute [&thorn;e] helpe [of] &thorn;in
euen-cristen in tyme: me &thorn;inke not so as vn-to &thorn;e.  For so&thorn;li he wol cun &thorn;e more
&thorn;onk for meke wasschyng of his feet whon &thorn;ei are ri&yogh;t foule &amp; stynking vpon
&thorn;e, &thorn;en for al &thorn;e preciouse peyntyng &amp; araying &thorn;at &thorn;ou can make aboute his
hed be mynde of his monhede.  For hit is fayr inou&yogh; &amp; nede&thorn; not muche to be
arrayed of &thorn;e.  But his feet &amp; his o&thorn;er lymes, &thorn;at are &thorn;i soiettes &amp; &thorn;in
euen-cristen, are sum-tyme vuel aray&yogh;ed and hadde nede to be loked &amp; holpe be
&thorn;e, namely se&thorn; &thorn;ou art bounden &thorn;erto; and for hem wol he cun &thorn;e moche &thorn;ank,
&yogh;if &thorn;ou wole mekely &amp; tenderly loke to hem.  For &thorn;e more louh seruise &thorn;at &thorn;ou
dost to &thorn;i lord for &thorn;e loue of hym or to eny of his lymes whon neode &amp; ri&yogh;twysnes aske&thorn; hit, wi&thorn; a glad &amp; a meke herte, &thorn;e more plesest &thorn;ou him;
&thorn;inking &thorn;at hit were inou&yogh; to &thorn;e for to be at &thorn;e leste degre &amp; lowest state se&thorn;
hit is his wille &thorn;at hit be so.  For hit seme&thorn; to me, se&thorn; he ha&thorn; put &thorn;e in &thorn;at
state for to trauayle &amp; serue o&thorn;er men, &thorn;at hit is his wille &thorn;at &thorn;ou schulde
fulfille hit in &thorn;y miht.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>&THORN;at sum-tyme schulde a lord leue gostli ocupacion and gladli &yogh;eue him to meedful worldli werkes.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo ix<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>&THORN;is ensaumple I say to &thorn;e, not for &thorn;ou dost [not] &thorn;us as I say, for i hope &thorn;ou
dost &thorn;us &amp; better: But I wolde &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuld do &thorn;us gladli, and not forto &thorn;inke
lo&thorn; for to leue sum-tyme gostly ocupacion &amp; entermete &thorn;e wi&thorn; worldly bisines, in
wys kepyng &amp; dispendyng of &thorn;i worldli godes, in good rule of &thorn;i seruauntes &amp; &thorn;i tenauntes, &amp; in o&thorn;ur gode dedes doyng to al &thorn;yn euencristen in &thorn;i mi&yogh;t; but
&thorn;at &thorn;ou schuld do bo&thorn;e werkes in diuerse tyme wi&thorn; a good wille, &thorn;at on &amp; &thorn;at


<PB N="1: 274">

o&thorn;ur, &yogh;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t; as, &yogh;if &thorn;ou heddest ben in preyer &amp; ben ocupied gostli, &thorn;ou schalt after certeyn tyme breke of &thorn;at &amp; &thorn;ou schalt bisili and gladli ocupie &thorn;e in sum bodily ocupacion vn-to &thorn;in euencristen.  Also, whon &thorn;ou hast be bisy
outward a while wi&thorn; &thorn;i seruantus or wi&thorn; o&thorn;er men profitably, &thorn;ou schalt breke of
&amp; turne a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;i preyeres &amp; &thorn;i deuocion after god &yogh;iue&thorn; &thorn;e grace.  And so schalt &thorn;ou put awei be grace of vr lord sleu&thorn;e, ydelnes, &amp; vayn rest of &thorn;i-self, &thorn;at come&thorn; vnder colour of contemplacion &amp; lette&thorn; &thorn;e sum-tyme from medefull &amp; spedeful ocupacion in outward bisynes, and &thorn;ou schalt be euer wel ocupied
ou&thorn;ur bodili or gostli.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Hou be ensaumple of Iacob &amp; of his two wyues men schal rule hem ri&yogh;t
in &thorn;e medled lyf.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cao. x<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wole do wel, &thorn;ou schalt do gostli as Iacob dude bodily.  Holi writ
sei&thorn; &thorn;at Iacob, whon he began to serue his mayster Laban, he coueyted Rachel
his Maistres dou&yogh;tur to his wyf for hir fayrhede, and for hire he
serued.  But whon he wende for to haue I-had hire to his wyf, he tok Lia first, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur
douhtur, in stude of Rachel, and afterward he tok Rachel, and so he hedde bo&thorn;e
at &thorn;e last.  Be Iacob in holy writ is vndurstande an ouurgoer of synnes.  Be &thorn;ise
two wimmen are vnderstande, as seint Gregore say&thorn;, two lyues in holy chirche:
Actyf lyf &amp; Contemplatyf lyf.  Lia is [as] muche for to say as &laquo;trauaylous&raquo;, &amp; be-tokne&thorn; actyf lyf; Rachel be-tokne&thorn; &laquo;si&yogh;t of beginnyng&raquo; &thorn;at is god, &amp; be-tokne&thorn; lyf contemplatyf.  Lia was fruiteful, but heo was sore-ei&yogh;ede.  Rachel was bareyn, but heo was fayr &amp; loueli.  &THORN;enne riht as Iacob coueited Rachel for hire fairhede
&amp; neuur&thorn;eles he hedde hire nou&yogh;t whon he wolde, but first he tok Lia, &amp;
 after-


<PB N="1: 275">

ward hire: riht so vche mon, turned be &thorn;e grace of compunccion so&thorn;fastli from
synnes of &thorn;e world &amp; of &thorn;e flesch to &thorn;e seruise of god &amp; clennes in good
lyuynge, ha&thorn; gret desyre &amp; gret longynge for to haue Rachel, &thorn;at is for to haue
rest &amp; gostli swetnes in deuocion &amp; contemplacion, for hit is so fair &amp; so loueli; &amp; in hope forto haue &thorn;at lyf only, he dispose&thorn; him for to serue vre lord wi&thorn;
al his mi&yogh;tes.  But ofte whon he wende for to haue had Rachel, &thorn;at is rest in
deuocion, vre lord suffred him furst to be assayed wel and trauayled wi&thorn; Lia,
&thorn;at is ou&thorn;ur wi&thorn; grete temptacions of &thorn;e world or of &thorn;e deuel, or elles wi&thorn;
o&thorn;ur worldly bisynes, bodili or gostly, in help of his euen-cristen.  And whon
he is wel trauayled wi&thorn; hem &amp; nei&yogh;hand ouercome, &thorn;en vr lord &yogh;eue&thorn; him Rachel, &thorn;at is grace of deuocion &amp; rest in concience; &amp; so hol bo&thorn;e Rachel &amp; Lia.  So schalt &thorn;ou do aftur ensaumple of Iacob, tak &thorn;e &thorn;i[s] two lyues actyf &amp; contemplatyf, sen god ha&thorn; sent &thorn;e bo&thorn;e, vse hem bo&thorn;e, &thorn;at on &amp; &thorn;at o&thorn;ur.  Be &thorn;at o lyf &thorn;at is actyf, &thorn;ou schalt bringe for&thorn; fruit of moni gode dedes in help of &thorn;in euen-cristen.  And be &thorn;at o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou schalt be maad feir &amp; bri&yogh;t &amp; clene in behaldyng souereyne bri&yogh;tnes, &thorn;at is god, beginnyng of al &thorn;at is mad.  And &thorn;en schalt &thorn;ou be so&thorn;fastly Iacob and ouurgoere and ouercomere of alle synnes.  And aftur &thorn;is be &thorn;e grace of god &thorn;i name schal be chaunged, as Iacobus name was turned in
to Israel.  Israel is as muche forto say as &laquo;a mon seoyng god&raquo;.  &THORN;en &yogh;if &thorn;ou be furst Iacob &amp; discretly wol vse &thorn;ise two lyues in tyme, &thorn;ou schalt aftur be Israel, &thorn;at is verrey contemplatif.  For ou&thorn;ur in &thorn;is lyf he wole diliuere &thorn;e and make


<PB N="1: 276">

&thorn;e freo of &thorn;i charge &amp; &thorn;i bisynes w&yogh;uch &thorn;ou art bounde to, or elles aftur &thorn;i[s] lif fulli in &thorn;e blis of heuen whon &thorn;ou comest &thorn;ider.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  &THORN;at contemplacion schulde be had in desyr, and werkes of actyf lyf in vse wi&thorn;-outen anger &amp; vnskilful drede.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ca<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>LIf contemplatyf is feir &amp; medeful, and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schalt euer haue hit in
desyr.  But &thorn;ou schalt haue in vsyng muche &thorn;e lyf actyf, for hit is needful &amp; spedful.  And &thorn;erfore, &yogh;if &thorn;ou be put fro &thorn;i rest in deuocion whon &thorn;e were leuest
to be &thorn;erat, be &thorn;i children, be &thorn;i seruantes, or be eny of &thorn;in euencristen, for
here profyt or ese of here hertes skilfulli asked, be not angri wi&thorn; hem, ne heuy,
ne dredful as &yogh;if god wolde be wro&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou left him for eny o&thorn;ur
&thorn;ing&mdash;ffor hit is not so.  But li&yogh;tli leue of &thorn;i deuocion whe&thorn;er hit be in preyer
or meditacion, and go do &thorn;i dette &amp; &thorn;i seruise to &thorn;in euencristen, as redili as &yogh;if
vre lord him-self bad &thorn;e do so.  And suffre mekely for his loue wi&thorn;-oute
grucchyng &yogh;if &thorn;ou may, &amp; disese &amp; troublyng of &thorn;in herte be-cause of medlyng wi&thorn; such bysynes.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  &THORN;at nedful worldli werkes kundel gostli desyres, proued be bodili ensaumple. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo duodecimo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>HIt may fal sum-tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e more troubled &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ben outward wi&thorn;
actyf werkes, &thorn;e more brennyng desyr &thorn;ou schalt haue to god, &amp; &thorn;e more cler
si&yogh;t of gostly &thorn;inges be grace of vre lord in deuocion whon &thorn;ou comest &thorn;erto.
For hit fare&thorn; &thorn;er-bi as &yogh;if &thorn;ou hedde a luite Cole and &thorn;ou wolde make a fir
&thorn;er-wi&thorn; &amp; make hit brenne.  &THORN;ou woldest furst lei &thorn;erto stikkes and ouerhule &thorn;e cole, and &thorn;ou&yogh; hit seme for a tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldest sleke &thorn;e cole wi&thorn; stikkes, neuer&thorn;eles whon &thorn;ou hast beden a while &amp; aftur &thorn;at i-blowen a while, anon


<PB N="1: 277">

springe&thorn; out a gret flaume of fuire, ffor &thorn;e stikkes are turned in to fuire.  Riht
so hit is gostli; &thorn;i wille &amp; &thorn;i desyre &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast to god, hit is as hit were a
luitel cole of fire in &thorn;i soule, ffor hit &yogh;iue&thorn; to &thorn;e sumwhat of gostli hete &amp; of
gostli li&yogh;t; but hit is ful luitel, ffor ofte hit waxe&thorn; cold &amp; turne&thorn; to fleschli rest,
&amp; sum-tyme in to idelnes.  &THORN;erfore hit is good &thorn;at &thorn;ou put &thorn;erto stikkes, &thorn;at
are goode werkes of actyf lyf.  And &yogh;if so be &thorn;at &thorn;ise werkes as hit seme&thorn; for
a tyme lette &thorn;i desyr &thorn;at hit may not be so clene ne so feruent as &thorn;ou wolde,
be not ouer-dredful &thorn;erfore, but a-byd &amp; suffre a while, &amp; go blowh at &thorn;e fuire,
&thorn;at is, ffurst do &thorn;i werkes and go &thorn;en al-[one] to &thorn;i preyers &amp; &thorn;i meditacions,
and lift vp &thorn;in herte to god and prei him of his godnes &thorn;at he wole accepte
&thorn;i werkes &thorn;at &thorn;ou dost to his plesaunce.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  Hou be mekenes &amp; diuerse gode werkes is &thorn;e loue of god norisched in mony mennes hertes.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo xiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Hald &thorn;i werkes as nou&yogh;t in &thorn;in owne si&yogh;t, but only of &thorn;e Merci of him.  Knowe
mekely &thorn;i wrecchednes &amp; &thorn;i frelte, and arette so&thorn;fastli al &thorn;i gode dedes to him
in as muche as &thorn;ei are gode, and in as muche as &thorn;ei are vuel, not don wi&thorn; al
&thorn;e circumstaunce &thorn;at are nedful to a good dede, for defaute of discrecion, put
hem to &thorn;i-self.  And for &thorn;is mekenes schal al &thorn;i dedes turne in to a flaume of
fuir, as stikkes leid vpon &thorn;e cole.  And so schal &thorn;e gode dedes outward not
hynder &thorn;i deuocion, but ra&thorn;ur mak hit more.  Vre lord sei&thorn; &thorn;us in holi writ:
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ignis in altari meo semper ardebit &amp; sacerdos surgens mane subiciet ligna ut ignis
non extinguatur:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is to say: &laquo;ffuir schal euer brenne in myn auter, and &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 278">

prest risyng at morewe schal put vnder stikkes, &thorn;at hit go not out.&raquo;  &THORN;is fuir is
loue &amp; desyr to god in soule, &thorn;e w&yogh;uche loue nede&thorn; to be norisched &amp; kept be
leying to of stikkes &thorn;at hit go not out.  &THORN;ise stikkes are of diuerse matere:
sum are of o tre, sum of an o&thorn;er.  A mon &thorn;at is lettred &amp; ha&thorn; vnderstandyng in
holy writ, &yogh;if he haue &thorn;is fuir of deuocion in his herte, hit is good to him for
to gedere him stikkes of holi .... writ &amp; norissche &thorn;e fuir wi&thorn; hem.  Ano&thorn;ur man
vnlettred mai not so redili haue at his hand holy writ &amp; doctors sawes, and
&thorn;erfore hit nede&thorn; to him to do mony gode dedes outward to his euencristne &amp; kendele
&thorn;e fuir of loue wi&thorn; hem.  And so hit is good &thorn;at vche man in his degre do
aftur he is disposed, &thorn;at he gete him stikkes of o &thorn;yng or of o&thorn;ur, ou&thorn;ur preiers
or gode meditacions or redyng in holy writ, or gode bodili worchyng, for to
norissche &thorn;e disyr of loue in his soule, &thorn;at hit ne be not slekked.  For &thorn;e affeccion
of loue is tendre, &amp; li&yogh;tli wol vanissch away, but &yogh;if hit beo wel kept and be
gode dedes bodili or gostly beo continuely norissched.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  How &thorn;e fuir of loue waste&thorn; alle synne and is a gret cri&yogh;ing in &thorn;e eres of god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xiiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Now &thorn;en se&thorn;&thorn;e vre lord ha&thorn; sent in to &thorn;in herte a luytel sparkel of his blessed
fuire &thorn;at is him-self as holy writ sai&thorn;&mdash;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deus noster ignis consumens,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is, &laquo;vre lord is fuire wastyng&raquo;&mdash;ffor as bodili fyr waste&thorn; al bodili &thorn;ing &thorn;at may be wasted, ri&yogh;t so gostli fuir, &thorn;at is god, waste&thorn; al maner of synne where so hit falle&thorn;, and &thorn;erfore vre lord is likned to a fuir wastyng&mdash;I preye &thorn;e norissche &thorn;is fuire &thorn;at


<PB N="1: 279">

is not elles but loue &amp; charite.  &THORN;is ha&thorn; he sent in to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e as he sei&thorn; in
&thorn;e gospel: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ignem veni mittere in terram, ad quid nisi vt ardeat:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is, &laquo;I am come to sende fire in to &thorn;e er&thorn;e, and wharto, but &thorn;at hit schulde brenne?&raquo; &THORN;at is: god ha&thorn; sent fuire of loue, &thorn;at is a god disyre &amp; a gret wille to plese him, in to a monnes soule, and to &thorn;is ende, &thorn;at a man schulde knowe hit &amp; kepe hit, norissche hit &amp; streng&thorn;e hit &amp; be saued &thorn;erbi.  &THORN;e more desire &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast to him, &thorn;e more is &thorn;is fuir of loue in &thorn;e.  &THORN;e lasse &thorn;at &thorn;is disyre is, &thorn;e lasse is &thorn;is fuire.  &THORN;e mesure of &thorn;is disyr hou muche hit is, in &thorn;i-self or in eny o&thorn;ur knowest &thorn;ou not ne no man of him-self, but god only &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; hit.  And
&thorn;erfore dispose &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to striue wi&thorn; &thorn;i-self as &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolde wyte hou muche &thorn;i disyr is, but be bisy for to disyre as muche as &thorn;ou mai, but not to wite &thorn;e
mesure of &thorn;i disyre.  Seint Austin sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e lyf of vche good cristene mon is a
continuel desyr to god.  And &thorn;at is a gret vertue, ffor hit is a gret cri&yogh;ing in &thorn;e
eres of god; &thorn;e more &thorn;ou desyrest &thorn;e hi&yogh;ore &thorn;ou cri&yogh;est, &thorn;e better &thorn;ou prayest,
&thorn;e wyslier &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>What disyr is, &amp; siker swetnes.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>. [x]v<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>And what is &thorn;is desyr?  So&thorn;li, no&thorn;ing but a lo&thorn;ing of al &thorn;is worldly blisse &amp; of al fleschli lyking in &thorn;in herte, &amp; [a] quemeful longyng wi&thorn; a tristi &yogh;ernyng to
heuenly ioye &amp; endeles blis.  &THORN;is, &thorn;inke&thorn; me, may be cald a desire to god.  &YOGH;if
&thorn;ou haue &thorn;is disire, as I hope sikerli &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast, I prey &thorn;e kepe hit wel &amp; norissche hit wysli, and whon &thorn;ou schalt praye or &thorn;enke, mak &thorn;is desyr begynnyng
&amp; endyng of al &thorn;i werk.  And forte encresce hit loke after non o&thorn;ur felyng in


<PB N="1: 280">

&thorn;i wittes, ne seke aftur non o&thorn;ur bodili swetnes nou&thorn;ur souning ne sauoryng, ne
wonderful li&yogh;t, ne si&yogh;t of angeles, ne of vre lord him-self as to &thorn;i si&yogh;t wolde
a-peere to &thorn;e bodily, charge hit but luytel: but &thorn;at al &thorn;i bisynes be &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t
fele so&thorn;fastli in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t a lo&thorn;ing &amp; a ful forsakyng of al maner of synne &amp; of vnclennes, wi&thorn; a gostli si&yogh;t of hit hou foul, how vggli &amp; hou pyneful hit is; and
&thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t haue a mi&yogh;ti desyryng to vertues, to mekenes, to charite, &amp; to &thorn;e blisse of heuen.  &THORN;is, &thorn;inke&thorn; me, were gostly cumfort &amp; gostly swetnes in a
monnes soule, as to haue clennes in conscience from wikkednes of al worldly
vanite wi&thorn; stable trou&thorn;e, meke hope, and ful desyr to god.  Hou-so-euere
hit be of o&thorn;ur cumfortes &amp; swetnes, me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at swetnes syker &amp; so&thorn;fast &thorn;at is feled in clennes of concience be mi&yogh;ti forsakyng &amp; lo&thorn;ing of al sinne &amp; be inward si&yogh;t, wi&thorn; feruent desyre of gostly desyres.  Al o&thorn;ur cumfortes
or swetnes or eny o&thorn;ur maner of felyng, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei helpe &amp; lede to &thorn;is ende,
&thorn;at is clannes in conscience &amp; gostly desyre of god, are not fulli syker forto
reste vpon.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>What difference is be-twixe desyr &amp; &thorn;e loue of god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. [x]vi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>But nou askest &thorn;ou whe&thorn;er &thorn;is desyre be &thorn;e loue of god.  As to &thorn;is, I say
&thorn;at &thorn;is desyre is not propurli loue, but hit is a begynnyng &amp; a tastyng of loue.
For loue is propurli ful couplyng of &thorn;e louer &amp; &thorn;e loued to-geder as god &amp; a
soul in on.  &THORN;is couplyng may not be had fully in &thorn;is lyf, but only in disyre &amp; longyng &thorn;erto; as &yogh;if a man loue a no&thorn;ur w&yogh;uch is absent, he disyre&thorn; gretly his


<PB N="1: 281">

presence, for to haue &thorn;e vse of his loue &amp; his lykyng.  Ri&yogh;t so gostli, as longe
as we are in &thorn;is lyf, vre lord is absent from vs, &thorn;at we may nou&thorn;ur se him ne
fele him as he is, and &thorn;erfore we may not haue &thorn;e vse of his loue here in ful
likyng.  But we may haue a desyre &amp; a gret &yogh;ernyng forte be present to him,
forte se him in his blisse, &amp; fulli to be oned to him in loue.  &THORN;is desyr may we
haue of his &yogh;ift in &thorn;is lyf.  Be &thorn;e w&yogh;uche we schal be saaf, ffor hit is loue
vnto him as hit may be had here.  &THORN;us seide seint Poul: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Scientes quia dum sumus in hoc corpore peregrinamur a domino, per fidem enim ambulamus et non per speciem; audemus autem &amp; bonam voluntatem habemus magis peregrinari a corpore &amp; presentes esse ad deum; et ideo contendimus, siue absentes siue presentes, placere illi.</FOREIGN>
Seint Poul sei&thorn; &thorn;at as longe as we are in &thorn;is bodi we are pilgrimes fro vre lord,
&thorn;at is, we are absent fro heuene in &thorn;is exile; we go be trou&thorn;e &amp; not be si&yogh;t,
&thorn;at is we leue in trou&thorn;e, not in bodili felyng; we dar &amp; haue a good wille to
be absent fro &thorn;e bodi &amp; be present to god, &thorn;at is, we for clennes in conscience
&amp; siker trou&thorn;e of saluacion dar desire to be absent fro vr bodi be bodili dede &amp; presente to vre lord.  Neuer&thorn;eles, for we may not &yogh;ut, &thorn;erfore we striue, whe&thorn;er
we be present or absent, for to plese him, and &thorn;at is, we striue a&yogh;eyn synnes of
&thorn;e world &amp; likingus of &thorn;e flesch be desyr of him, for to brenne in &thorn;is desyre alle
&thorn;yng &thorn;at lette&thorn; vs from hym.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>How werkes wi&thorn;-outen schewen &thorn;is desyr.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulo xvii<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&YOGH;it askest &thorn;ou: &laquo;Mai a man haue &thorn;is desyre in his herte contynuely&raquo;?  &THORN;e &thorn;inke&thorn; nay.  As to &thorn;is, I may say as me &thorn;inke&thorn;, &thorn;at &thorn;is desyr may be had as for &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 282">

vertu &amp; &thorn;e profyt of hit in habite continuely, but not in worchyng ne in vsyng;
as be &thorn;is ensaumple.  &YOGH;if &thorn;ou were seek, &thorn;ou schuldest haue as vche mon ha&thorn; a
kuyndeli desyr of bodily hele continueli in &thorn;in herte, what-so &thorn;ou dedest, whe&thorn;er
&thorn;ou sleped or waked, but not euer iliche; ffor &yogh;if &thorn;ou slepe, or elles wakyng &thorn;enkest
of sum worldly &thorn;inges, &thorn;en hast &thorn;ou &thorn;is desyre in habyte, nou&yogh;t in worchinge.
But whon &thorn;ow &thorn;enkest on &thorn;i syknes and on &thorn;i bodili hele, &thorn;en hast &thorn;ou hit in
vsyng.  [Right] so hit is gostly of &thorn;e disyre of god.  He &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;is desyr of &thorn;e
&yogh;ift of god, &thorn;ou&; he slepe or elles &thorn;enk not on god but on worldly &thorn;inges, &yogh;it
he ha&thorn; &thorn;is desyr in habite of his soule, til he synne dedli.  But whon he &thorn;enke&thorn;
on god or on clannes of lyuing or of &thorn;e ioyes of heuene, &thorn;en worche&thorn; his disyre
to god as longe as he kepe&thorn; his &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; his entent for to plese god, ou&thorn;ur in
prayere or in meditacion, or in eni good dede of actyf lyf.  &THORN;en is [it] good &thorn;at
al vre bisynes be forto stere &thorn;is desyr &amp; vse hit be discrecion, nou in o dede &amp; nou in a no&thorn;ur, after we are disposed &amp; han grace &thorn;erto.  &THORN;is desyr is rote of
al &thorn;i worchyng: ffor wite &thorn;ou wel, what good dede &thorn;at hit be &thorn;at &thorn;ou dost for
god, bodili or gostli, hit is an vsyng of &thorn;is desyr; and &thorn;erfore whon &thorn;ou dost a
good dede, or preiest or &thorn;enkest on god, &thorn;enk not in &thorn;in herte doutyng whe&thorn;er
&thorn;ou disyrest or nou&yogh;t, for &thorn;i dede schewe&thorn; &thorn;i disyre.  Sum are vnkunnynge &amp; wene &thorn;at &thorn;ei desyre not god but &yogh;if &thorn;ei were euur cri&yogh;inge on god wi&thorn; wordes
of heore mou&thorn;, or elles in her herte be desyring wordes, as &yogh;if I seide &thorn;us:
&laquo;A, lord, bring me to &thorn;i blisse&raquo;, &laquo;Lord mak me saaf&raquo;, or such o&thorn;ure.  &THORN;ise wordes


<PB N="1: 283">

are gode whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei be souned in &thorn;e mou&thorn; or elles formed in &thorn;e herte, ffor &thorn;ei
sture a mannes herte to &thorn;e desyring of god.  But neuer&thorn;eles, wi&thorn;-oute eny such
wordus, a clene &thorn;ou&yogh;t of god or of eny gostli &thorn;ing, as of vertues or of &thorn;e
man-hede of Crist or of &thorn;e ioyes of heuene or of &thorn;e vnderstandynge of holi writ, wi&thorn;
loue, mai be better &thorn;en such wordes.  For a clene &thorn;ou&yogh;t of god is a so&thorn;fast
disyr to him, and &thorn;e more gostli &thorn;at &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t is, &thorn;e more is &thorn;i disyr, and
&thorn;erfore be &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t in doute ne in weere whon &thorn;ou preyest or &thorn;enkest on god or
elles dost eny outward dede to &thorn;in euencristen, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou disyrest him or nou&yogh;t:
for &thorn;e dede schewe&thorn; hit.  Neuer&thorn;eles, &yogh;if hit be so &thorn;at al &thorn;i gode dedes bodili
or gostli are schewed of &thorn;i disyr to god, &yogh;it is &thorn;er a diuersete be-twixe bodili &amp; gostli dedes.  For &thorn;e dedes of contemplatyf lyf are propurli &amp; kuyndeli &thorn;e
worchyng of &thorn;is desyr, but outward dedes are not so, and &thorn;erfore whon &thorn;ou preyest
or &thorn;enkest on god, &thorn;i disire is more hol, more feruent, &amp; more gostly, &thorn;en whon
&thorn;ou dost o&thorn;ur dedes to &thorn;in euen-cristen.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Hou after &thorn;i slepe &thorn;ou schalt quiken &thorn;in herte wi&thorn; preyeres and gode
&thorn;ou&yogh;tes &amp; put awai vuel &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &thorn;at letten deuocion.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xviii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Now &yogh;if &thorn;ou aske hou &thorn;ou schalt kepe &thorn;is disyre &amp; norissche hit, a luitel I
schal telle &thorn;e, nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt vse &thorn;e same forme al-wei as I say, but &thorn;at
&thorn;ou schalt haue &thorn;erbi, &yogh;if ned be, sum wissyng forto rule &thorn;e in &thorn;in ocupacion.
For I may not, ne i can not, telle &thorn;e fulli what is best euer to &thorn;e for to vse.
But i schal sei to &thorn;e sumwhat as me &thorn;inke&thorn;.  In nihtes, aftur &thorn;i sleep, &yogh;if &thorn;ou
wole ryse for to serue &thorn;i lord, &thorn;ou schalt fele &thorn;i-self furst fleschli heui, &amp;  sum-


<PB N="1: 284">

tyme lusti: &thorn;en schalt &thorn;ou dispose &thorn;e for to preye or for to &thorn;enke sum good
&thorn;ou&yogh;t for to quiken &thorn;in herte vn-to god, and forto sette al &thorn;i bisynes furst for
to drawe vp &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t from worldli vanytes &amp; from veyn ymaginacions fallyng in
to &thorn;i mynde, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mai fele sum deuocion in saying, or elles, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wole
&thorn;enke of gostly &thorn;inges, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not muche letted wi&thorn; such veyne &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of
&thorn;e world &amp; of &thorn;i flesch in &thorn;i &thorn;enkyng.  &THORN;er are moni maner of &thorn;enkynges,
w&yogh;uch are best to &thorn;e I can not say; but I hope &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ou felest most
sauour in &amp; most rest for &thorn;e tyme, is best for &thorn;e.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  How ordeind [&thorn;ou&yogh;t] of &thorn;in owne synnes and of o&thorn;er mennes norrissche&thorn; &thorn;i desyre to god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo xix<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>&THORN;ow may, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wole, sum-tyme &thorn;enk of [&thorn;i] synnes be-fore done, &amp; of &thorn;i
frelete &thorn;at &thorn;ou fallest in vche day, &amp; aske merci &amp; for&yogh;iuenes for hem.  Also aftur &thorn;is &thorn;ou mai &thorn;enke of &thorn;e synnes &amp; &thorn;e wrecchednes of &thorn;i euencristen bodili &amp; gostli wi&thorn; pite &amp; compassion of hem, &amp; cri&yogh;e merci &amp; for&yogh;iuenes of hem as tenderli as &yogh;if &thorn;ei were &thorn;in oune; &amp; &thorn;at is a good &thorn;ou&yogh;t, ffor i telle &thorn;e for so&thorn;e &thorn;ou may make o&thorn;ur mennes synnes a precious oynement for to hele &thorn;in oune soule wi&thorn;, whon &thorn;ou hast mynde of hem.  &THORN;is oynement in hit-self is precious &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e spicerie in hit-self be not clene, ffor hit is triacle maad of venym [for to distroye venym], &thorn;at is to sai &thorn;yn oune synnes &amp; o&thorn;ur mennes also brou&yogh;t in to &thorn;y mynde; &yogh;if &thorn;ou beete hem wi&thorn; serwe of &thorn;in herte &amp; pite &amp; compassion, &thorn;ei turne in to triacle w&yogh;uch make&thorn; &thorn;i soule hol from pride &amp; envie, &amp; bringe&thorn; loue &amp; charite to &thorn;in euencristen.  &THORN;is &thorn;ou&yogh;t is good sum-time to haue.
</P></DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="chapter">

<PB N="1: 285"><HEAD>&THORN;at fele &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of &thorn;e monhede of vre lord discretli vsed norische&thorn; &thorn;e desyr to god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xx<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Also &thorn;ou may haue mynde of &thorn;e manhede of vre lord, In his bur&thorn;e or in
his passion or in eny of his werkes, and fede &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t wi&thorn; gos[t]ly ymaginacion
of hit, for to sture &thorn;in affeccion to more loue of him.  &THORN;is &thorn;ou&yogh;t is good, and
nameli whon hit come&thorn; freli of godes &yogh;ift wi&thorn; deuocion &amp; feruour of &thorn;e spirit.
Ac &yogh;if a man may not li&yogh;tli haue sauour ne deuocion in hit, I halde hit not
spedeful &thorn;enne to a mon for to prese ouur-muche &thorn;er-vpon as he wolde gete hit be
maistrie; for he schal mowe breke his hede &amp; he schal neuer be &thorn;e nerre.
&THORN;erfore me &thorn;inke&thorn; as to &thorn;e [it] is good to haue in mynde his manhede sum-tyme,
and &yogh;if deuocion &amp; sauour come wi&thorn;-al, kepe hit &amp; folewe hit for a tyme, but
lef of sone &amp; hang not ouur longe &thorn;er-vpon.  Also &yogh;if deuocion come not wi&thorn;
mynde of &thorn;e passion, striue not ouer-muche &thorn;er-aftur; tac esyli &thorn;at wol come,
&amp; go for&thorn; to sum o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou&yogh;t.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;tes of fele vertues norissche&thorn; &thorn;i desyr to god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo xxi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Also o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &thorn;er are &thorn;at are more gostli, as for to &thorn;enke of vertues, and
forto se be li&yogh;t of vnderstandyng what &thorn;e vertu of mekenes is and hou a mon
schulde be meke; and also what is pacience and clennes, ri&yogh;twysnes, chastite
&amp; soberte, &amp; such o&thorn;ere, and how a man schulde gete &thorn;ise vertues; and be suche
&thorn;ou&yogh;tes for to haue gret disyr &amp; longyng to &thorn;is vertues for to haue hem, and
also for to haue a gostli si&yogh;t of &thorn;e &thorn;reo principal vertues: of trou&thorn;e, hope, &amp; charite.  Be &thorn;e si&yogh;t &amp; &thorn;e disyre of &thorn;ise vertues a soule schulde mow fele gret


<PB N="1: 286">

cumfort &yogh;if he hedde grace of vre lord, wi&thorn;-oute w&yogh;uch grace a mannes &thorn;ou&yogh;t
is half blynd, wi&thorn;-oute sauour of gostli swetnes.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  &THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t of diuerse seyntes &amp; of heore vertues norische&thorn; &thorn;i loue to god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap<HI REND="sup">o</HI>. xxi<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Also for to &thorn;enke of &thorn;e seyntes of vre lord, as of Apostles, of Martires,
Confessours &amp; holy Virgynes, be-hald inwardli here holi liuynge, &thorn;e grace &amp; &thorn;e
vertues &thorn;at vre lord &yogh;af hem heere liuinge, and be &thorn;is mynde for to sture &thorn;in
owne herte to take ensaumple of hem to better lyuyng.  And also &thorn;e mynde of
vr ladi seynte Marie aboue al o&thorn;ur seyntes; for to seo bi gostli ei&yogh;e &thorn;e
habundaunce of grace in hir holi soule whon heo was here lyuynge, &thorn;at vr lord &yogh;af
hire alone passyng al o&thorn;ure creatures; ffor in hire was fulhede of alle vertues
wi&thorn;-oute wem of synne.  Heo hadde ful mekenes &amp; parfyt charite, and fulli wi&thorn;
&thorn;eose &thorn;e beute of al o&thorn;ur vertues, so hole &thorn;at &thorn;er mi&yogh;t no steryng of pride,
envye, ne wra&thorn;&thorn;e ne fleschli lykyng, ne of no maner of synne entre in to hire
herte ne defoule &thorn;e soule in no partye of hit.  &THORN;e behaldyng of &thorn;e fairhede of
&thorn;is blessede soule schulde gretli stere a monnes herte in to gostly cumfort.  And
muche more &thorn;en aboue &thorn;is &thorn;e &thorn;ink[yng] of &thorn;e soule of vre lord Ihesu, &thorn;e w&yogh;uch
was fulli oned to &thorn;e godhede, passynge wi&thorn;-oute comparison vre ladi &amp; al
o&thorn;ur creatures.  For in &thorn;e persone of vre lord Ihesu are two kyndes: &thorn;at is, god
&amp; mon, fulli oned to-geder.  Be &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;is blessed onyng w&yogh;uch may not
be seid ne conseyued be mannes witte, &thorn;e soule of Ihesu receiued &thorn;e fulhede of
wisdom &amp; loue &amp; al godnes, as &thorn;e apostelle sei&thorn;: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Plenitudo diuinitatis habitauit in ipso corporaliter:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is, &thorn;e godhede was oned fulli to &thorn;e monhede in &thorn;e soule


<PB N="1: 287">

of Ihesu and so be &thorn;e soule dwelled in &thorn;e bodi.  &THORN;e mynde of &thorn;e manhede of
vre lord vpon &thorn;is wyse, &thorn;at is forto be-holde &thorn;e vertues &amp; &thorn;e passyng grace of
&thorn;e soule of Ihesu, &amp; &thorn;at schulde be cumfortable to a monnes soule.  And also
mynde of &thorn;e mi&yogh;t, &thorn;e wisdam, &amp; &thorn;e godnes of vre lord in al his creatures; ffor
in as muche as we mai not seo god fulli in him-self here lyuyng, &thorn;erfore we schal be-halde him, loue him &amp; drede him, &amp; wondure his mi&yogh;t &amp; his wisdam &amp; his godnes, in his werkes &amp; in his creatures.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  &THORN;at &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e merci of vr lord schewed to synful men norrische&thorn; &thorn;i desyr to god.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulo xxiiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>Also for to &thorn;enke of &thorn;e merci of vr lord &thorn;at he ha&thorn; schewed to &thorn;e &amp; to me
&amp; to alle synful caytyfs &thorn;at han be cumbred in synne, sperred so longe in &thorn;e
deueles prison; hou vre lord suffred vs paciently in vre synne and tok no veniaunce
of vs as he mihte ri&yogh;tfulli haue don, &amp; put vs to helle, &yogh;if his merci hedde nou&yogh;t
letted him; but for loue he spared vs, he hedde pite of vs, &amp; sente his grace
in to vre hertes &amp; called vs out of vre synne, and be his grace ha&thorn; turned vre
wille hol to him, &amp; for his loue for to forsake al maner of synne.  &THORN;e mynde of
his merci &amp; his godnes made wi&thorn; o&thorn;ur circumstaunces mo &thorn;en i con or may
reherce nou, bringe&thorn; into a soule gret trust in vre lord &amp; ful hope of saluacion,
and hit cundele&thorn; &thorn;e desyr of loue mi&yogh;tily to &thorn;e ioyes of heuene.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t of [&thorn;e] wrecchednes of men &amp; of &thorn;e ioyes of heuene norissche&thorn;
&thorn;i desyr to god.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulo xxiiii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Also for to &thorn;enke of &thorn;e wrecchednes, &thorn;e mescheues and &thorn;e pereles bodili &amp; gostli &thorn;at falle&thorn; in &thorn;is lyf; and aftur &thorn;at for to &thorn;enke of &thorn;e ioyes of heuene, hou


<PB N="1: 288">

muche blisse &thorn;er is &amp; hou muche ioye: ffor &thorn;er is no synne ne sorewe ne passion
ne pyne ne hungur ne &thorn;rist, sore ne seknes, doute ne drede, schame ne
schend-schipe, ne defaute of mi&yogh;t, ne lakkyng of li&yogh;t, ne wantyng of wil; but &thorn;ere is
souereyne fairnes, li&yogh;tnes, streng&thorn;e, freodam, holy(!) lykyng euur lastyng, wisdom,
loue, pees, worschipe, sikernes, rest, ioye &amp; blisse inow&yogh; wi&thorn;-outen ende.  &THORN;e
more &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest &amp; felest &thorn;is wrecchednes of &thorn;is lyf, &thorn;e more feruently schalt &thorn;ou desyre &thorn;e ioye &amp; &thorn;e rest of &thorn;e blisse of heuen.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Hou &thorn;e desyre of worldli men and &thorn;e desyr of heuene is meded at &thorn;e last
ende.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulo xxv<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Moni men are coueytous of worldli worschipes &amp; er&thorn;li riches, and &thorn;enken ni&yogh;t
and day, slepyng &amp; wakyng, hou &amp; be what maner &thorn;ei mi&yogh;te come &thorn;erto, and
for&yogh;ete&thorn; &thorn;e mynde of hem-self, &amp; of &thorn;e peynes of helle &amp; of &thorn;e ioyes of heuene. So&thorn;li &thorn;ei are not wyse, &thorn;ei are like to &thorn;e children &thorn;at rennen after a boterflye, and for &thorn;ei loken not to heore feet, &thorn;ei falle sum-tyme &amp; breken here leges. What is al &thorn;e pompe of &thorn;is world in richesse or iolyte but a boturflye?  So&thorn;li,
not elles, &amp; muche lasse.  &THORN;erfore i pre&yogh;e &thorn;e be &thorn;ou coueitous of &thorn;e ioyes of
heuene, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt haue worschipe &amp; richesse &thorn;at schal euur laste.  For at &thorn;e
last ende whon worldly coueytous men fayle, &thorn;ei bringe no&thorn;ing in here handes,
for al heore worschipes &amp; here richesses are torned in to nou&yogh;t saue serwe &amp; pyne; &thorn;en schal al heuenly couetous men &thorn;at forsaken treweli al vayne worschipes
of &thorn;is world, or elles &yogh;if &thorn;ei haue worschipes and richesses &thorn;ei sette not her
lykyng ne here loue in hit, but in drede, in mekenes, in hope &amp; in serwe sum-tyme


<PB N="1: 289">

&thorn;ei abyde &thorn;e merci of god pacientli: &thorn;ei schal &thorn;en haue fulli &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue
coueyted, ffor &thorn;ei schal be &thorn;enne corouned as kynges &amp; set vp wi&thorn; vre lord
Ihesu in &thorn;e blis of heuen.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  Hou discrecion is nedeful in &thorn;enkyng &amp; preying, &amp; hou hit is sum-tyme for
to passe fro &thorn;at on to &thorn;at o&thorn;er.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulo xxvi<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Also &thorn;er are mony o&thorn;ur meditacions, mo &thorn;en I con say, &thorn;e w&yogh;uche vr lord
putte&thorn; in to a monnes mynde for to sture &thorn;e affeccion &amp; &thorn;e resun of &thorn;e soule
to lo&thorn;e wi&thorn; vanites of &thorn;is world &amp; for to desyre &thorn;e ioyes of heuene.  &THORN;ise wordes I say to &thorn;e, not as I hed fulli schewed &thorn;e maner of meditacions as &thorn;ei are in a
mannes soule, but I touche hem a luitel to &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou scholde be &thorn;is luytel
vnderstande &thorn;e more.  Notfor&thorn;i me &thorn;inke&thorn; hit is good to &thorn;e &thorn;at whon &thorn;ou
disposest &thorn;e for to &thorn;enke on god as I haue before seid, or on eny o&thorn;ur wyse, &yogh;if
&thorn;in herte be dul &amp; merk &amp; &thorn;ou felest nou&thorn;ur wit ne sauour ne deuocion for to
&thorn;enke, but only a naked desyre &amp; a weyk wille, &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolde fayn &thorn;enke on
god, but &thorn;ou can nou&yogh;t: but &thorn;an I hope &thorn;at hit is good to &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou striue
not ouer-muche wi&thorn; &thorn;i-self, as &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolde be &thorn;in owne mi&yogh;t ouercome &thorn;i-self, ffor &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t li&yogh;tli so falle in to more merknes, but &yogh;if &thorn;ou were sleih in &thorn;i worchynge.  And &thorn;erfore I halde hit &thorn;en most syker to &thorn;e for to say &thorn;i Pater noster or &thorn;in Aue or elles &thorn;i matyns, or for to rede on &thorn;i sauter, ffor &thorn;at is
euermore a syker standart and wol not fayle, who so wole cleue &thorn;erto he schal
not erre, and &yogh;if &thorn;ou may be preying gete deuocion, &thorn;an, &yogh;if &thorn;is deuocion be
only in affeccion, &thorn;at [is] in a gret desyre to god wi&thorn; gostli dilyt, hold for&thorn; &thorn;i
saying, brek not li&yogh;tli of, ffor ofte hit falle&thorn; &thorn;at praying wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e gete&thorn; &amp;

<PB N="1: 290">

kepe&thorn; feruour of deuocion, &amp; &yogh;if a mon cese of saying deuocion vanissche&thorn; a-way.
Neuer&thorn;eles &yogh;if deuocion of preyer bringe to &thorn;in hert a gostly &thorn;ou&yogh;t of [&thorn;e] Monhede of vr lord, or of eny o&thorn;ur before-seid, and &thorn;is &thorn;ou&yogh;t schulde be letted be &thorn;i seying, &thorn;en mai &thorn;ow cese of &thorn;i saying &amp; ocupie &thorn;e in meditacion, til hit pas
a-wai.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  Hou a man schal haue him in &thorn;enkyng of &thorn;e passion of vre lord Ihesu; whon deuocion lastes &amp; whon hit passe&thorn; a-way.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cap. xxvii<HI REND="sup">o</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>But of certeyn &thorn;inges &thorn;e bi-houe&thorn; be war in &thorn;i meditacion.  Sum schal I
telle &thorn;e.  On is, whon &thorn;ou hast had a gostli &thorn;ou&yogh;t ou&thorn;ur in ymagining of &thorn;e
monhede of vre lord or of such o&thorn;ur bodili &thorn;inges, &amp; &thorn;i soule ha&thorn; be fed &amp; cumforted &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; hit passe&thorn; away, be hit-self, be not ouer-bisy for to kepe
hit stille be maistrie, for &thorn;enne hit schal turne &thorn;e to pyne &amp; to bitternesse.  Also
&yogh;if hit passe not a-way but dwelle&thorn; stille in &thorn;i mynde wi&thorn; a trauayle of &thorn;i-self,
&amp; &thorn;ou for cumfort of hit wol not leue hit, &amp; &thorn;erfore hit reue&thorn; &thorn;e fro &thorn;i slepe ani&yogh;tes, or elles a-dayes from o&thorn;er gode dedes, &thorn;is is not wel, &thorn;ow schalt wilfulli breke of whon tyme aske&thorn;.  &YOGH;e sum-tyme whon &thorn;ou hast most deuocion and
were lo&thorn;est forto leue hit, as whon hit passe&thorn; resonable tyme or elles &yogh;if hit
turne to eny disese of &thorn;in euencristen, but &yogh;if &thorn;ou do so elles dost &thorn;ou not
wysliche as me &thorn;inke&thorn;.  A worldli mon or a wommon &thorn;at fele&thorn; not per auenture
deuocion twy&yogh;es in a &yogh;ere, &yogh;if he feled be grace of vr lord gret compunccion
of his synnes, or elles a mynde of &thorn;e passion of vr lord, &thorn;ou&yogh; he were put
fro his slepe &amp; his rest a ni&yogh;t or two or &thorn;re til his hed oke, hit is no force,


<PB N="1: 291">

for hit come&thorn; to hem but selden.  But to &thorn;e, or to ano&thorn;ur man &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;is
maner of worchynge in costume, as hit were vch o&thorn;er day, hit is spedful for to
haue discrecion in &yogh;oure workyng, nou&yogh;t fulli forto folwe hit as muche as wol
come.  And I halde &thorn;at hit is good to &thorn;e for to vse &thorn;is maner in what deuocion
&thorn;at &thorn;ou be, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hange not longe &thorn;er-vpon, ou&thorn;ur forto putte fro &thorn;e &thorn;i mete
or &thorn;i slepe in tyme, or forto [di]sese any o&thorn;ur man vnskilfuli.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnia tempus habent:</FOREIGN>
Al &thorn;ing ha&thorn; tyme.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>  Hou a mon schal haue [him] warli in &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; disire, &amp; wisli vse &thorn;e grace
&thorn;at god ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen to hym.  <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulo xx<HI
REND="sup">o</HI> octauo.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Ano&thorn;ur &thorn;ing is &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;e be-houe&thorn; be war of.  &yogh;if &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t be ocupyed in ymaginacion of &thorn;e monhede of vr lord or in eny such o&thorn;er, and aftur &thorn;is &thorn;ou
art bisy wi&thorn; al &thorn;i disyre of &thorn;in herte for to seke knowyng or felyng more gostly
of &thorn;e godhede, prese not ouur-muche &thorn;er-in, ne suffre not &thorn;in herte falle fro &thorn;e
disyre as &yogh;if &thorn;ou were a-bydyng or gapyng aftur sum queynte sturyng, or sum
wonderful felyng, o&thorn;ur &thorn;en &thorn;ou hast had.  &THORN;ou schalt not do so.  Hit is inou&yogh;
to &thorn;e, &amp; to me, for to haue desyre and longyng to vre lord, and &yogh;if he wole of
his grace, ouer &thorn;is desyre, sende vs of his gostly li&yogh;t [&amp; open] vre gostli e&yogh;en
for to seo &amp; knowe more of him &thorn;en we haue had bifore be comon trauayle,
&thorn;onke we him &thorn;erof, and &yogh;if he wol not so, for we are not &yogh;it meke inou&yogh;,
or elles we are not disposed be clennes of lyuyng on o&thorn;ur sydes forte receyue
his grace, &thorn;en schal we mekely knowe vr owne synnes &amp; vre wrecchednes, &amp; hald vs payed wi&thorn; &thorn;e disyre &thorn;at we aue to him, &amp; wi&thorn; vre comon &thorn;ou&yogh;tes


<PB N="1: 292">

&thorn;at may li&yogh;tli falle vnder vre ymaginacions, as of vre synnes, &amp; of Cristes passion,
or of such o&thorn;ur; or elles wi&thorn; preyers of &thorn;e sauter, or of sum o&thorn;er, &amp; loue him
wi&thorn; al &yogh;oure hertes &thorn;at he wole &yogh;eue vs &thorn;at. // &YOGH;if &thorn;ou do o&thorn;ur-wyse, &thorn;ou mai&yogh;t li&yogh;tli be bigyled be &thorn;e spirit of errour, ffor hit is presumpcion &thorn;at a man be his oune wit schulde prese ouer-muche in to knowyng of gostli &thorn;inges, but he feled
plente of grace.  For &thorn;e wyse mon sei&thorn;: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Scrutator maiestatis opprimetur a gloria,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at is forte sai: &laquo;Ronsaker of &thorn;e mi&yogh;t &amp; of &thorn;e maieste wi&thorn;-oute gret clannes &amp; meknes schal be ouurleyd &amp; oppressed of him-self.&raquo;&mdash;
</P></DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)" TYPE="MS">
<HEAD>Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)<NOTE ID="n5">The beginning is missing in the Thornton text.</NOTE></HEAD><MILESTONE
N="223" UNIT="folio">
<P>...mene &thorn;at ware in prelacye, and o&thorn;er also &thorn;at ware haly temporalle mene, had
full charite in affeccione with-in and also in wirkynge with-owttene; and &thorn;at
es propirly &thorn;is mellide lyfe &thorn;at es made bathe of actyfe lyfe and of contemplatyfe
lyfe.  And sothely for swilke a mane &thorn;at es in spirituelle soueraynte as in
prelacye, in cure, in gouernance of o&thorn;er, as prelates bene, or in temporalle
soueraynte, as werldly lordes and maysters bene, I halde &thorn;is mellide lyfe beste
and maste by-houely to &thorn;ame, als lange als &thorn;ay ere bowndene &thorn;erto.  Bot to
o&thorn;er &thorn;at ere fre and noghte bowndene to temporale mynystracyone ne to
spiritualle, I hope &thorn;at lyfe contemplatyfe allane, if &thorn;ay myghte come sothefastely
&thorn;areto, were beste and maste spedfull, maste medfull and faire, and maste worthi
to &thorn;ame for to vse and to halde, &amp; noghte for to leue wilfully for nane
owtwarde werkes of actyfe lyfe, bot if it ware in gret nede at gret releuynge &amp; comforthynge of o&thorn;er mene ou&thorn;er of &thorn;aire body or of &thorn;aire saule.  Thane, if
nede aske, at &thorn;e prayere and instaunce of o&thorn;er, or elles at &thorn;e byddynge of o&thorn;er
gouernance, I hope it es gude to &thorn;ame for to schewe owtwarde werkes of actyfe
lyfe for a tyme in helpynge of &thorn;aire euencristene. / By this that I hafe saide &thorn;ou


<PB N="1: 271">

may in party vndirstande whilke es a lyfe and whilke es o&thorn;er, and whilke
accordis maste to thi state of lyffynge.  And sothely, as me thynke, this Mellid
lyfe accordis maste to &thorn;e.  For sene owre lorde hase ordaynede &thorn;e and sett
&thorn;e in &thorn;e state of soueraynte ouer o&thorn;er als mekill als it es, and lent &thorn;e
habowndance of werldly gudes for to rewle and sustene specyaly all &thorn;ose &thorn;at are vndire
thi gouernance and thi lordchipe after thi myghte &amp; thi cunnynge; and also
after thou hase ressayuede grace of &thorn;e mercy of oure lorde godde for to hafe
sumwhate knaweynge of thi-selfe, and gastely desyre and sauour of his lufe:
I hope &thorn;at &thorn;is lyfe &thorn;at es mellide es beste, and accordes maste to &thorn;e for to
trauelle &thorn;e &thorn;are-in.  And &thorn;at es to depart wyesly thi lyffynge in two: a tyme
to &thorn;e tane, and ano&thorn;er tyme to &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  For wiet &thorn;ou wele, if &thorn;ou leue
nedfull besynes of actyf lyfe, and be rekles and take na kepe of thi werldly gudes
how &thorn;ay &thorn;ay be spendide and kepide, ne hafe no force of thi sugetis and of
thyne euencristene bycause of desire and will &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase anely for to gyffe &thorn;e
to gastely ocupacyone, wenande &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte therby excusede &mdash; if &thorn;ou do so,
&thorn;ou dose noghte wysely.  Whate are all thi werkes worthe, whethire &thorn;ay be
bodyly or gastely, bot if thay be done ryghtefully and resounabyly, to &thorn;e wirchipe
of godde and at his byddynges?  Now sothely righte noghte.  &para; Thane, if &thorn;ou
leue &thorn;at thynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte bowndene to, by way of charite, apone righte and
resone, and will hally gyffe &thorn;e to a no&thorn;er thynge, wilfully as it ware, for mare
plesance of hym, whilk &thorn;ou arte noghte bowndene to, thou dose noghte


<PB N="1: 272">

wirchipe discretly to hyme.  Thou erte besy to wirchipe his heuede and his
face, and aray it faire and curyusly; bot &thorn;ou leues his body and &thorn;e armes
and &thorn;e fete raggede and rente and takes no kepe &thorn;are-of.  And &thorn;an &thorn;ou
wirchipis hyme noghte.  For it es a velany a mane for to be curyously arrayede
apone his heuede with perre and precyous stanes, and all his body be nakide and
bare as it ware a beggere.  Righte so, gastely, it es no wyrchipe to godde
for to couer his heuede and leue his body bare.  Thou sall vndirstande &thorn;at
oure lorde Ihesu Criste, as mane, es heuede of a gastely body, whilke es
haly kirke.  The membris of this body are all cristene mene.  Some are
armes, and some are fete, and some ere o&thorn;er membris aftire sundre wirkynges
&thorn;at &thorn;ay vse in thaire lyffynge.  Than if &thorn;ou be besy with all &thorn;i myghte for to
arraye his heuede, &thorn;at es, for to wirchipe hyme-selfe by mynde of his passione
or of his o&thorn;er werkes in his manhede by deuocyone and meditacione of hyme,
and forgetis his fete, &thorn;at ere thi childire, thi seruante&yogh;, thi tenantes and
all thyne euencristyne, and latis &thorn;ame spill for defaute of kepynge, vnarayede,
vnkepide, and noghte tente to as &thorn;ame aughte for to be: thow pleses hyme
noghte, ffor &thorn;ou duse no wirchipe to hyme.  Thou makes &thorn;e for to kysse his
mouthe by deuocyone and gastely prayere, bot &thorn;ou tredis apone his fete and
defoules &thorn;ame, in als mekill als &thorn;ou will noghte tente to thayme for neclygence
of &thorn;i-selfe of whilke &thorn;ou hase takyne cure.  &para; This me thynke.
&para; Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse if &thorn;ou thynke &thorn;at &thorn;is es noghte sothe, for it ware a fayrere Offyce to wyrchipe &thorn;e heuede of hyme, as for to be alday Ocupiede in meditacyone of his
manhede, &thorn;an for to go lawere to o&thorn;er werkes and make clene his fete, as for


<PB N="1: 273">

to be besy bathe in thoghte and dede aboute &thorn;e helpe of thyne euencristene in
tyme: me thynke noghte so as vnto &thorn;e.  &para; Sothely he will cune the more
thanke for meke waschehynge of his fete whene &thorn;ay ere righte foule and stynkyng
appone the, &thorn;an for all &thorn;e precyouse payntynge and &thorn;e arraynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou kane
make aboute his heuede by mynde of his manhede.  For it es faire enoghe and
nedis noghte mekill to be arrayede of &thorn;e.  Bot his fete and his o&thorn;er membris,
that ere thi sugetts and thyne euencristyne, ere sumtyme euyll arrayede and had
nede for to be lukede to and holpyne by &thorn;e, &amp; namely sene &thorn;ou erte bowndene
&thorn;are-to; and for thaym will he cun the mekill thanke, if &thorn;ou will mekely and
tendirly luke &thorn;ame.  For &thorn;e mare lawe seruyce &thorn;at &thorn;ou duse to &thorn;i lorde, for lufe
of hyme, vn-to any of his membris whene nede and rightwysnes askes, with a
glade meke herte, the mare plese&yogh; &thorn;ou hyme: thynkand &thorn;at it ware enoghe for
&thorn;e for to be at &thorn;e leste degre &amp; laweste state sen it es his will at it be so.
For it semys, sen he hase putt &thorn;e in &thorn;at state for to trauelle and serue o&thorn;er
mene, &thorn;at it es his will &thorn;at &thorn;ou suld fulfill it at thi myghte. / This ensample I say
to &thorn;e, noghte for &thorn;ou duse noghte &thorn;us as I say&mdash;ffor I hope &thorn;ou duse &thorn;us and
better: bot for I walde &thorn;at &thorn;ou sulde do &thorn;us gladly, and noghte [lathe] for to
leue sumtyme gastely ocupacyone and entermete &thorn;e with werldly besynes in wyse
kepynge and dispendynge of thi werldly gudes, and gud rewlynge of &thorn;i seruantes
and &thorn;i tenantes, and in o&thorn;er gude werkes doynge vn-to all &thorn;inne euencristene at
&thorn;i myghte; bot &thorn;at &thorn;ou sulde doo bathe in dyuers tyme with a gud will, &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 274">

tane and &thorn;e to&thorn;er, if &thorn;ou myghte; as, if &thorn;ou hade prayede and bene ocupiede
gastely, &thorn;ou sall aftir certayne tyme breke of &thorn;at and &thorn;ou sall besyly and
gladly ocupye &thorn;e in some bodily ocupacione vnto thyne euene-cristene; also
when &thorn;ou hase bene besye owtwarde a while with thi seruantes or with o&thorn;er
mene profytabily, &thorn;ou sall breke offe and come agayne to &thorn;i prayers and thi
deuocyone after godde gyfs &thorn;e grace, and so sall &thorn;ou put away by grace of
oure lorde sleuthe, ydilnes, and vayne riste of thi-selfe &thorn;at comes vndir
coloure of contemplacione and lettes &thorn;e sumtyme fra medfull and spedfull
ocupacione in owtwarde besynes, and &thorn;ou sall be ay wele ocupiede ou&thorn;er bodyly or
gastely. / Thare-fore if &thorn;ou will do wele &thorn;ou sall [do] gastely as Iacob dide bodily.
&para; Haly write saise &thorn;at Iacob whene he begane for to serue his Mayster Labane,
he couete Rachelle his mayster doghter to his wyfe for hir fairehede, and for
hir he seruede.  Bot whene he wende to hafe hade hire to his wife, he tuke
firste Lya &thorn;e to&thorn;er doghter in stede of Rachelle, and aftirwarde he tuke Rachelle,
and so he hade bathe at &thorn;e laste. / By Iacob in haly writt es vndirstande ane
ouerganger of synnes.  By &thorn;ise two wymmene ere vndirstandene, as sayne Gregor
saise, two lyfes in haly kyrke: actyfe lyfe, and contemplatyfe.  Lya es als
mekill at say as &laquo;trauyliouse&raquo;, and betakyns actyfe lyfe; Rachelle, &laquo;syghte of begynnynge&raquo;, &thorn;at es godde, and betakyns lyfe contemplatyfe.  Lya was frwtefull,
bot scho was sare-eghede.  Rachelle was faire and lufely, bot scho was
barrayne.  Than righte as Iacob couetid Rachelle for hir fairehede and
neuer-&thorn;e-lesse he had hir noghte whene he walde, bot firste he tuke Lya and aftirwarde


<PB N="1: 275">

hir: righte so ilk mane turnede by grace of compu[n]ccyone sothefastely fra synnes
of &thorn;e werlde and of &thorn;e flesche vnto &thorn;e seruyce of godde and clennes of gude
lyffynge, hase gret desyre and gret langynge for to hafe Rachelle, &thorn;at es, for
to hafe ryste and gastely swetnes in deuocyone and contemplacione, for &thorn;at es so
faire and so lufely; and in hope for to hafe &thorn;at lyfe anely, he disposes hym
for to serue oure lorde with all his myghtes.  Bot ofte whene he wenes for to
hafe Rachelle, &thorn;at es riste in deuocyone, oure lorde suffers hym firste for to be
assayede wele and trauelde with Lya, &thorn;at es, ou&thorn;er with gret temptacions of &thorn;e
werlde or of &thorn;e deuelle, or ells with o&thorn;er werldly besynes bodily or gastely in
helpyng of his euencristyne.  And whene he es wele trauelde with &thorn;ame and
nerhande ouer-commene, than oure lorde gyffes hym Rachelle &thorn;at es grace of
deuocyone and riste in concience.  And so hase he bathe Rachelle and Lya.
So sall &thorn;ou do after ensaumple of Iacob: take &thorn;ise two lyfes actyfe and
contemplatyfe, sen godde hase sett the bathe, &thorn;e tane and &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  By &thorn;e taa lyfe,
&thorn;at es actyfe, &thorn;ou sall brynge furthe fruyte of many gude dedis in helpe of
thyne euencristene.  And by &thorn;e to&thorn;er &thorn;ou sall be made and bryghte and
clene in &thorn;e behaldynge of souerayne bryghtnes &thorn;at es godde, begynnynge and
ende of all &thorn;at es made.  And &thorn;an sall &thorn;ou be sothefastly Iacob and ouerganger
and ouercommere of all synnes, and after by &thorn;e grace of godde thi nam sall
be chaungede, as Iacobe name was turnede in to Israel.  Israel es als mekill
at say als &laquo;a mane seande godde&raquo;.  Than if &thorn;ou be firste Iacob and discretly will vse &thorn;ise two lyfes in tyme, &thorn;ou sall be aftir Israel, &thorn;at es verray contemplatyfe.
Ou&thorn;er in &thorn;is lyfe he will delyuer &thorn;e and make &thorn;e free fra charge of besynes


<PB N="1: 276">

whilke &thorn;ou ert boundene to, or ells after &thorn;is lyfe fully in &thorn;e blysse of heuene when
&thorn;ou commes thedire.  &para; Contemplatife lyfe es faire and medfull, and &thorn;are-fore
&thorn;ou sall aye hafe it in desyre.  Bot &thorn;ou sall hafe in vsesynge mekill &thorn;e lyfe
actyfe, for it es so nedfull and so spedfull.  And &thorn;are-fore if &thorn;ou be putt fra thi
reste [in] deuocyone whene &thorn;e ware leueste be still &thorn;ar-at, by thy childire, thy
seruantes, or by any of thyne euencristene, for &thorn;aire profyte or ese of &thorn;aire
hertes skilfully askide: be noghte angry with &thorn;ame, ne heuy, ne dredfull, as
if godde wald be wrathe with the &thorn;at &thorn;ou lefte hym for any o&thorn;er thynge, ffor
it es noghte so; bot lyghtly &thorn;ou leue of thi deuocyone whe&thorn;er it be in prayers
or in meditacyons, and goo do thi dett and &thorn;i seruyse to &thorn;ine euencristene, als
redily as if oure lorde hym-selfe bade &thorn;e do so.  And suffire mekely for his
lufe with-owttene gruchynge if &thorn;ou may, and dissese and trubblynge of &thorn;i herte
by-cause of mellynge with swilke besynes.  For it may fall sumtyme &thorn;at &thorn;e
trubylyere &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase bene owtwarde with actyfe werkes, the mare brynnande
desyre &thorn;ou sall hafe to godde, and &thorn;e more clere syghte of gostely thynges by
grace of owre lorde in deuocyone whene &thorn;ou comes &thorn;are-to.  For it faris
&thorn;er-by as if &thorn;ou hade a littili cole and &thorn;ou walde make a fyre &thorn;are-with and ger
it bryne.  Thow wald fyrste lay-to stykkes and ouer-hille &thorn;e cole, and if it
semyd as for a tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou sulde qwenche &thorn;e cole with &thorn;i stykkes,
neuer-&thorn;e-lesse whene &thorn;ou hase habedyne a while and after blawes a lyttill, onane


<PB N="1: 277">

sprynges a grete flawme of fyre: for &thorn;e stykkes ere turnede to fyre. / Righte so,
gastely, thi will and thi desyre &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase to godde, it es as it ware a littill
cole of fyre in &thorn;i saule, ffor it gyffes to &thorn;e sumwhate of gostely hete and
gostely lyghte; bot it es full lyttill, ffor ofte it waxes colde and turnes to
fleschely riste, and sumtyme in to ydilnes.  For-&thorn;i it es gude &thorn;at &thorn;ou putte
&thorn;are-to stykkes, &thorn;at ere gud werkes of actyfe lyfe.  And if so bee &thorn;at &thorn;ire
werkes as it semes, for a tyme lette thi desyre &thorn;at it may noghte be so clene
ne so feruente as &thorn;ou walde, be noghte to dredfull &thorn;are-fore, bot habyde
and suffire a while, and go blawe at &thorn;e fyre, &thorn;at es: firste do thi werkes
and go &thorn;ane allane to &thorn;i prayers and thi medytacyons, and lyfte vpe thi herte
to godde, and pray hym of his gudnes &thorn;at he will accepte thi werkis &thorn;at &thorn;ou
duse to his plesance. / Halde &thorn;oue &thorn;ame as noghte in thyne awene syghte, bot
anely at &thorn;e mercy of hyme.  Be aknowe mekely thi wrechidnes and thi frelte,
and arett all thi gude dedis sothefastly to hyme in als mekill als &thorn;ay ere gude;
and in als mekill als &thorn;ay ere badde, noghte done with all &thorn;e circumstance
&thorn;at ere nedfull vn-to gude dedis, for defaute of discrecione, put thame vn-to
thi-selfe.  And for &thorn;is meknes sall all thi dedis turne in to flawme of fyre, as
stykkes laide apone &thorn;e cole.  And so sall gud dedis owtewarde noghte hyndire
thi deuocyone, bot ra&thorn;er make it mare. / Oure lorde sayse in haly write &thorn;us:
&para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Ignis in altare meo semper ardebit et sacerdos mane surgens subiciet ligna vt
ignis non extynguatur:</FOREIGN> &laquo;ffyre, he sayse, sall bryne in myne autir, and &thorn;e priste


<PB N="1: 278">

rysande at morne sall put vndire stykkys &thorn;at it be noghte qwenchede&raquo;.  This fire
es lufe and desire to godde in saule, whilke lufe nedis to be nureschede and
kepide by la&ymacr;nge-to of stykkis &thorn;at it goo noghte owtte.  Thise stykkes ere of
dyuerse matire: some ere of a tre and some er of ano&thorn;er.  A mane or a womane
&thorn;at es letterede and hase vndirstandynge in haly writt, if he hafe &thorn;is desire of
deuocyone in his herte, it es gude vn-to hyme for to gedire hyme stekkis of haly
ensaumpills and saynges of oure lorde by redynge&yogh; of haly write, and noresche
&thorn;e fyre with thayme.  Ano&thorn;er mane or a womane vnletterede may noght so redyly
hafe at his hand haly writt and doctours sawes, and forthi it nedis to hym to
do many gud werkis owtewarde to his euene-cristyne and kyndill &thorn;e fire of lufe
with thame.  And so it es gude ilke mane in his degre, aftir he es disposede,
&thorn;at he gette hym stykkes of a thyng or of o&thorn;er, ou&thorn;er prayers or gude
meditacyons or redynges in haly writt, or gude bodily wyrkynges, for to nuresche
&thorn;e desire of lufe in his saule, &thorn;at it be noghte qwenchede.  For &thorn;e affeccyone
of lufe es tendir, and lyghtly will vanysche awaye, bot if it be wele kepide
and by gud dedis bodyly or gastely contenualy nureschede.
</P><P>Now &thorn;ane sene oure lorde hase sente in to thi herte a littill sparke of his
blysside fire &thorn;at es hyme-selfe, as haly writt saise: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Deus noster ignis consumens
est:</FOREIGN> &laquo;Oure lorde es fyre wastande&raquo;&mdash;ffor as bodily fyre wastes all bodily thynge
&thorn;at may be wastyde, righte so gastely fyre, &thorn;at es godde, wastis all maner of
syne whare-so it fallis, and for-thi oure lorde es lykkende to fyre wastande &mdash;
I pray &thorn;e hertly, dere syster(!), noresche &thorn;is fire.  This fire es noghte ellis bot


<PB N="1: 279">

lufe and charyte; &thorn;is hase he sent in till erthe as he saise in the gosepelle: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ignem veni mittere in terram, et ad quid nisi vt ardiat?</FOREIGN>  &laquo;I am commene, he saise, for to send fyre of lufe in till erthe, and whare-to [but] &thorn;at it suld bryne?&raquo; That es, godde hase sent fire of lufe &thorn;at es gude desyre and a grete will vn-to plese hyme in to manes saule, and vn-to &thorn;is ende &thorn;at a mane suld knawe it, kepe it, noresche it, and strenghe it; and be sauede thare-by.  The more
desire &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase vn-to hyme, &thorn;e more es this fyre of lufe in the.  The lesse
&thorn;at thi desire es, &thorn;e lesse es &thorn;is fire.  The mesure of &thorn;is desyre how mekill
it es, no&thorn;er in thi-selfe ne in na no&thorn;er knawes &thorn;ou noghte, ne no mane of
hym-selfe, bot godde allone &thorn;at gyffes it; and for-thi dispuyte noghte with
&thorn;i-selfe as if &thorn;ou wolde knawe how mekill thi desire es, bot be besy for to desyre
als mekill als &thorn;ou may, bot noghte for to wete &thorn;e mesure of thi desyre.  Sayne
Austyne saise &thorn;at &thorn;e lyfe of euerilk a gude cristyne mane es a contenuelle
desire to godde, and &thorn;at es of a gret vertue, ffor it es a gret crying in &thorn;e
erris of godde.  &THORN;e more &thorn;at &thorn;ou desires &thorn;e heghere &thorn;ou cries, &thorn;e better
&thorn;ou prayes, &thorn;e wyseleere &thorn;ou thynkis. / And what es &thorn;is desire?  Now, sothely,
na thyng bot a lathynge of all &thorn;is werldis blysse, of all fleschely lykynges in thi
herte, and a qwemfull langynge with a thristy &yogh;ernyng to heuenly Ioye and
endles blysse.  This, thynke me, may be callid a desire of godde.  If &thorn;ou hafe
&thorn;is desire, as I hope sekirly &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase, I pray the kepe it wele and noresche
it wysely: and whene &thorn;ou sall pray or thynke make &thorn;is desire begynnynge of
all &thorn;i werke.  For to encresse it, luke after na no&thorn;er .... bodily swetnes, no&thorn;er


<PB N="1: 280">

sownyng, ne sauourynge, ne wondirfull lyghte, ne aungells syghte, ne if oure
lorde hym-selfe as vn-to &thorn;i syghte walde appere to &thorn;e bodily, charge it bot a
lytill; bot at all thi besynes be &thorn;at &thorn;ou myghte fele sothefastly in thi thoghte
a lathynge and a full forsakynge of all maner of syne and of vnclennes, with
a gastely syghte of it how foule, how vggly and how paynfull &thorn;at it es;
and at &thorn;ou myght hafe a myghty desyrynge to vertus, to mekenes, to charite,
and to the blysse of heuene.  / This, thynke me, ware gastely comforthe
and gostely swetnes in a mans saule, as for to hafe clennes in concience fra
wikkidnes of all werldly vanyte, with stabill trouthe, meke hope, and full desyre
to godde.
</P><P>How so euer it es of o&thorn;er comforthes and swetnes, me thynke &thorn;at swetnes
sekire and sothefaste &thorn;at es felid in clennes of concyence by myghty forsakynge
and lathyng of all syne and by inward syghte, by feruent desyre of gastely
thyngis; and o&thorn;er comforthes or swetnes or any o&thorn;er maner of felynge, bot if
&thorn;ay helpe and lede to &thorn;is ende, &thorn;at es, to clennes in conscience and gastely
desyre of godde, ere noghte full sekire for to riste one.  / Bot now may &thorn;ou aske
whe&thorn;er this desyre be lufe of godde.  As vnto &thorn;is, I say &thorn;at &thorn;is desire es noghte
propirly lufe, bot it es a begynnynge.  For lufe propirly es a full cuppillynge
of &thorn;e lufande and &thorn;e lufed to-gedyre, as godde and a saule, in to ane.  This
cuppillyng may noghte be had fully in this lyfe bot anely in desyre and langynge
&thorn;are-to; as if a mane lufe ano&thorn;er whilke es absente he desyris gretly his presence,


<PB N="1: 281">

for to hafe &thorn;e vys of his lufe and his likynge.  Righte so, gostely, als lang als
we erre in &thorn;is lyfe oure lorde es absente fra vs, &thorn;at we may no&thorn;er se hym ne
here hyme ne fele hym als he es, and &thorn;are-fore we may noghte hafe &thorn;e vis
of his lufe here in fulfilling.  Bot we may hafe a desyre and a gret &yogh;ernynge for
to be present to hym, for to se hym in his blysse, and to be anede to hym in
lufe.  This desyre may we hafe of his gyfte in &thorn;is life; by &thorn;e whilke we sall
be safe, ffor it es lufe vnto hyme as it may be hade here.  Thus sayne Paule
saide: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Scientes quoniam dum sumus in hoc corpore peregrinamur a domino, per
fidem enim anbulamus et non per speciem; audemus autem et bonam voluntatem
habemus magis peregrinari a corpore et presentes esse ad deum, Et ideo contendimus
siue absentes siue presentes placere illi.</FOREIGN>  Sayne Paule sais &thorn;at &laquo;als lange als we ere in &thorn;is body, we ere pilgrymes fra oure lorde&raquo;, &thorn;at es, we ere absent fra heuene in &thorn;is exile; &laquo;we go by trouthe, noghte by syghte&raquo;, &thorn;at es, we lyff in trouthe, noghte in bodily felynge; &laquo;we dare and hase gud will to be absent fra &thorn;e body and be present to godde&raquo;, &thorn;at es, we for clennes in concyence and sekire trouthe of saluacyone dare desyre gastely absence fra oure body by bodily dede and be present to oure lorde; &laquo;Neuer-&thorn;e-les, for we may noghte &yogh;itt, &thorn;erfore we stryfe whe&thorn;er we be absent or present for to plese hyme&raquo;, and &thorn;at es, we stryfe agayne synnes of &thorn;e werlde and lykynges of &thorn;e flesche by desyre to hyme, for to bryne in &thorn;is desire all thynges &thorn;at lettes vs fra hyme.  &para; &YOGH;it askes &thorn;ou whe&thorn;er a mane may haue &thorn;is desire contenuelly in his herte or noghte.  &THORN;e thynke nay. / As to &thorn;is, I may say as me thynke, &thorn;at &thorn;is desire may be hadde as for &thorn;e vertu


<PB N="1: 282">

and profite of it in habyte contenualy, bot noghte in wyrkynge ne vsesynge; as
by &thorn;is ensample.  If &thorn;ou ware seke, &thorn;ou sulde haue as ilke mane hase a kyndly
desire of bodily hele contenualy in thi herte, what so &thorn;ou dide, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou
slepe or &thorn;ou wake, bot noghte ay ylyke: ffor if &thorn;ou slepande(!) or elles wakande
thynke of sum werldly thynge &thorn;an hase &thorn;ou &thorn;is desire anely in habite, noghte
in wyrkynge.  Bot whene &thorn;ou thynkes of &thorn;i seknes and of &thorn;i bodily hele, &thorn;an
hase &thorn;ou it in vssynge. / Righte so, gostely, es it of desire to godde.  He &thorn;at
hase &thorn;is desyre of &thorn;e gyfte of godde, &thorn;ofe he slepe or ells thynke noghte of
godde bot of werldly thynges, &yogh;it he hase &thorn;is desyre in habyte of his saule, vntill
he syne dedly.  Bot whene he thynkes of godde, or of clennes of lyffynge,
or of &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene, than wirkkis his desyre als lange als he kepis his
thoghte and his entente to plese godde, ou&thorn;er in prayere or in meditacyone, or
in any o&thorn;er gud dede of actyfe lyfe.  Thane es it gude &thorn;at all [our] besynes be
for to stire &thorn;is desire and vse it be discrecyone, now in a dede now in a-no&thorn;er,
after we ere disposede and hase grace to.  This desire es rute of all thi
wirkkynges: ffor wete &thorn;ou wele whate gude dede it be &thorn;at &thorn;ou dose for godde, bodily
or gostely, it es ane vsynge of &thorn;is desyre; and &thorn;erfore when &thorn;ou duse a gude
dede, or prayes or thynkis of godde, thynk noghte in thi herte doutande whe&thorn;er
&thorn;ou desires or noghte, ffor &thorn;i dede schewes thi desyre. / Sum ere vnkonande and
wenes &thorn;at &thorn;ay desire noght godde bot if &thorn;ay be ay criande o[n] godde with wordis
of &thorn;aire mouthe, or ells in theire hertis by desyrand wordes, as if &thorn;ay said
thus: &laquo;A, lorde, brynge me to thi blysse&raquo;, &laquo;Lorde, make me safe&raquo;, or swylke o&thorn;er.  The wordis ere gude whe&thorn;er &thorn;ay be sownned in &thorn;e mouthe, or ells


<PB N="1: 283">

fourmede in &thorn;e herte, ffor &thorn;ay stire a mans herte to &thorn;e desyrynge of godde.
Bot neuer-&thorn;e-les, with-owttene any swylke wordes, a clene thoghte of godde or
of any gostely thynge, as of vertu&yogh; or of &thorn;e manhede of Criste, of &thorn;e Ioyes
of heuene, or of vndirstandynge of haly writte, with lufe, may be bettire &thorn;an
slyke wordis.  For a clene thoghte of godde es sothefaste desyre to hyme, and
&thorn;e mare gastely &thorn;at thi thoghte es, &thorn;e mare es thi desire, and for-thi be &thorn;ou
noghte in dowte ne in were when &thorn;ou prayes or thynkes one godde or ells
duse any owtwarde dedis to thyne euencristyne, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou desyres hyme or
noghte, ffor thi dedis schewes it.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les, if it be so &thorn;at all thi gude
dedis bodyly and gastely ere a schewynge of thi desire to godde, &yogh;it es &thorn;er a
dyuersite by-twix gastely &amp; bodily dedis: ffor dedis of contemplatyfe lyfe er
propirly and kyndly wirkyng of &thorn;is desire, bot owtwarde dedis ere noght so,
and forthi whene &thorn;ou prayes or thynkes one godde, thi desire to godd es mare
hale, mare feruent, and mare gastely, &thorn;an whene &thorn;ou duse o&thorn;er dedis vn-to thyne
euencristyne.
</P><P>Now &thorn;an if &thorn;ou aske how &thorn;ou sall kepe this desire and norische it, a littill
I sall tell the, noghte for &thorn;ou sall vse &thorn;e same fourme all-way as I say, bot
for &thorn;ou sall hafe, if nede be, some wyssyng for to rewle the in thyne ocupacyone.
For I may noghte, ne I cane noghte, tell the fully what es beste ay to &thorn;e
for to vse.  Bot I sall say to &thorn;e sumwhate as me thynke. / One nyghtis, aftir
thi slepe, if &thorn;ou will ryse for to serue thi lorde, thow sall fele thi-selfe firste


<PB N="1: 284">

fleschely heuy, and sumtyme lusty.  Than sall &thorn;ou dispose the for to pray or
for to thynke some gude thoghte for to qwykkyne thi herte to godde, and sett
all thi besynes firste forto drawe vp thi thoghte fra werldly vanytes and fra vayne
ymagynacyouns fallande in to thi mynde, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may fele sum deuocyone in
thi sayinge, or ells, if &thorn;ou will thynke of gostely thynges, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noghte
letted with swylke vayne thoghtes of &thorn;e werlde or of &thorn;e flesche in thi thynkynge.
Thare are many maners of thynkynges, whilke ere beste to &thorn;e I cane noghte
say; bot I hope &thorn;e whilke &thorn;ou felis maste sauour in and maste riste for &thorn;e
tyme it es beste for the. / Thow may if &thorn;ou will sumtyme thynke ouer thi synnes
be-fore donne, and of thi freeltes &thorn;at &thorn;ou fallis in ilke day, and aske mercy
and forgyfnes for thayme. / Also aftir this &thorn;ou may thynke of synnes and of
wrechidnes of thyne euencristene bodily and gastely with pete and compassione
of thayme, and cry mercy and forgyfnes for thayme als tendirly als iff &thorn;ay ware
thyne awene; and &thorn;at es a gude thoghte: ffor I tell &thorn;e for sothe &thorn;ou may make
o&thorn;er mens synnes a precyouse oynement for to hele with thyne awene saule,
when &thorn;ou hase mynde of thaym.  This oynement es precyouse all-if &thorn;e spycery
in it-selfe be noghte full clene: ffor it es triacle made of venyme for to distroye
venyme, &thorn;at es to say thyne awene synnes and o&thorn;er mens also broghte in to &thorn;i
mynde.  If &thorn;ou bete &thorn;ame wele with sorowe of herte, pete, and compassione,
&thorn;ay turne vn-to triacle whilke makes thi saule hale fra pryde and envye, and
brynges in lufe &amp; charite to thyne euencristene.  This thoghte es gude sumtyme


<PB N="1: 285">

for to hafe. / Also &thorn;ou may hafe mynde of &thorn;e manhede of oure lorde, in his
byrthe, or in his passione, or in any of his werkes, and fede thi thoghte with
gastely ymagynacyone of it, for to stirre thyne affectione to mare lufe of hyme.
This thoghte es gude and spedfull, namely when it commes frely of goddes
gyfte with deuocyone and feruour of &thorn;e sperite.  Elles, if a mane may noghte
lightly hafe sauour ne deuocyone in it, I halde it noghte spedfull &thorn;ane to a
mane for to prese to mekill &thorn;are-till as if he walde gete it by maystry; ffor he
sall mowe breke his heuede and his body and he sall neuer be &thorn;e nerre.
For-thi me thynke vn-to &thorn;e it es gude for to hafe in mynde his manhede
sumtyme, and if deuocyone and sauour cume with-alle, kepe it and folowe it for
a tyme, bot leue of sone and hyng noghte to lange &thorn;are-appone.  Also if
deuocyone cum noghte with mynde of &thorn;e passione, stryue noghte ne prese to
mekill &thorn;are-after.  Take esyly &thorn;at will cume, and go furthe to some o&thorn;er
thoghte. / Also o&thorn;er &thorn;ar bene &thorn;at ere mare gostely, as for to thynke of vertus,
and for to se by lyghte of vndirstandynge what &thorn;e vertu of mekenes es and
how a mane sulde be meke.  Also what es pacyence and clennes,
rightwysnes, chastyte, and sobirte, and swylke o&thorn;er, and how a man sulde gete all
thiese vertus, and by swylke thoghtes for to hafe gret desire and langgyng to
&thorn;ise vertus for to hafe thayme, and also for to hafe a gastely syghte [of &thorn;e
thre principal vertus, of trouthe, hope &amp; charite.  Be &thorn;e sighte] and &thorn;e desyre
of &thorn;ise vertus a saule sulde mowe fele grete comforthe if a mane had grace of


<PB N="1: 286">

oure lorde, with-owtene whilke grace a mans thoghte es halfe blynde,
with-owtene sauour of gastely swetnes. / Also for to thynke of &thorn;e sayntes of owre
lorde, of Appostills, Martirs, Confessours and haly Virgyns, byhalde inwardly
thaire haly lyffynge, &thorn;e grace and &thorn;e vertus &thorn;at oure lorde gafe &thorn;ame here
liffande, and by &thorn;is mynde for to stirre thyne awene herte to take ensaumpill
of &thorn;ame vn-to better lyffynge. / Also the mynd of oure lady saynt Marie abowne
all o&thorn;er sayntes; for to see by gostely eghe &thorn;e abowndance of grace in hire
haly saule whene scho was here lyffande, &thorn;at owre lorde gafe hir allane passande
all o&thorn;er creatours.  For in hir was fullhede of all vertus with-owttyne weme
of synne.  Scho had full mekenes and perfit charite, and fully with &thorn;ise &thorn;e bewte
of all o&thorn;er vertus, so hally &thorn;at &thorn;are myghte no styrrynge of pride, envie, ne
wrethe, ne fleschely lykynge, ne no manere of syne enter in till hir herte ne
defoule &thorn;e saule in no party of it. / The behaldynge of &thorn;e fairehede of &thorn;is
blyssid saule sulde stirre a mans herte vnto gostely comforthe gretly, and mekill
mare &thorn;ane abowne &thorn;is &thorn;e thynkynge of &thorn;e saule of Ihesu oure blyssid lorde,
the whilke was aned fully to &thorn;e godhede, passand with-owttyne comparisone
oure ladye and all o&thorn;er creaturs.  For in &thorn;e persone of Ihesu er two kyndis, &thorn;at
es godde &amp; mane, fully anede to-gedir.  By &thorn;e vertu of this blysfull anynge,
whilke may noghte be saide ne consayuede be manes wit, the saule of Ihesu
ressayuede &thorn;e fulhede of wysedome and lufe and all gudnes, as &thorn;e appostill
saise: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Plenitudo diuinitatis inhabitauit in ipso corporaliter:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &thorn;e godhede


<PB N="1: 287">

was anede fully to &thorn;e manhede in &thorn;e saule of Ihesu, and so by &thorn;e saule duellide
in &thorn;e body.  &THORN;e mynde of &thorn;e manhed of oure lorde on &thorn;is wyse, &thorn;at es forto
behalde &thorn;e vertus and &thorn;e ouer-passande grace of &thorn;e saule of Ihesu, sulde be
comfortheabill to a mans saule. / Also mynd of &thorn;e myghte, of &thorn;e wysedome, &amp; &thorn;e gudnes of oure lorde in all his creaturs; ffor in als mekill als we may noghte
see godde fully in hym-selfe her lyffande, ffor-thi we sall be-halde hym, lufe
hym and dred hym, and wondire hys myghte and his wysdome and his
gudnes, in his werkes and his creaturs. / Also for to thynke of &thorn;e mercy of oure
lorde &thorn;at he hase schewed to &thorn;e, and to me, and to all synfull kaytyfes &thorn;at
hase bene combirde in synne, speride so lange in &thorn;e deuells presone; how oure
lorde sufferde vs pacyently in oure syne and tuke na vengeance of vs as he
myghte ryghtfully hafe donne and putt vs till helle, if his mercy had noghte
lettide hyme; bot for lufe he sparede vs, he had pete of vs, and sente his
grace in till oure hertes and callid vs owte of oure syne, and by his grace hase
turnede oure will hally to hyme for to hafe hyme and for his lufe to forsake
all maner of syne.  The mynde of &thorn;is mercy and &thorn;is gudnes, made with o&thorn;er
circumstance mo &thorn;an I cane or may reherse now, brynges in to my saule grete
triste in oure lorde and full hope of saluacyone, and it kyndylls desire of lufe
myghtily to &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene. / Also for to thynke of &thorn;e wrechidnes, &thorn;e
myscheues and &thorn;e perills, bodily and gastely, &thorn;at fallis in &thorn;is lyfe; and after
&thorn;at for to thynke of &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene, how mekill blysse &thorn;are es and how


<PB N="1: 288">

mekill Ioye: ffor &thorn;are es no syne, no sorowe, no passione, no payne, no hungre,
no thriste, no sare, no sekenes, no dowte, no drede, no schame, no schenchipe,
no defaute of myghte, ne lakkynge of lyghte, no wanttyng of will; bot thare es
souerayne fairenes, lyghtnes, strenghe, ffredome, hele, lykynge ay-lastande,
wysedome, lufe, pees, wirchipe, sekirnes, ryste, Ioy and blysse with-owttene ende.
The more &thorn;at &thorn;ou thynkis and felis &thorn;e wrechidnes of &thorn;is lyfe, the more feruently
sall &thorn;ou desire &thorn;e Ioye and &thorn;e riste of &thorn;at blyssede lyfe. &para; Many meme er
couetouse of werldly wyrchips and erthely reches, and thynkes nyghte and day,
dremande and wakande, how and what-maner &thorn;ay myghte wyne &thorn;are-to, and
forgetes &thorn;e mynde of thayme-selfe, of &thorn;e paynes of helle and of &thorn;e Ioyes of
heuene.  Sothely &thorn;ay are noghte wyse, thay ere lyke vn-to &thorn;e childir &thorn;at rynnes
aftire buttyrflyes, and for &thorn;ay luke noghte to thaire fete, &thorn;ay fall somtyme and
brekes &thorn;aire legges.  What es all &thorn;e wirchipe and &thorn;e pompe of &thorn;is werlde in
reches and Iolyte bot a buttirflye?  Sothely noghte elles, and &yogh;itt mekill lesse.
Thare-fore I praye &thorn;e be &thorn;ou couetouse of &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene, and &thorn;ou sall hafe
wirchipe and reches &thorn;at euer-more sall laste.  For at &thorn;e laste ende whene werldly
couetouse mene brynges no gud in thaire handis, for all &thorn;e wirchipes &amp; rechese
er turned to noghte saue sorow and payne, thane sall heuenly couetous mene, &thorn;at
forsakes trewly all vayne wyrchips of &thorn;is werlde, or ells if &thorn;ay hafe wirchips &amp; reches &thorn;ay sett noghte &thorn;aire lykynge ne &thorn;aire lufe in thayme, bot ay in drede, in
meknes, in hope, and in sorowe sumtyme [pay] habydes &thorn;e mercy of godde pacient-


<PB N="1: 289">

ly, &thorn;ay sall &thorn;ane hafe fully &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe couetid, ffor thay sall be coround as
kynges and sitt vpe with oure lorde Ihesu in &thorn;e blysse of heuene. / Also &thorn;ar are
many o&thorn;er meditacyons mo &thorn;an I kan say whilke oure lorde puttis in to a mans
mynde for to stirre &thorn;e affeccyone and resone of &thorn;e saule to lathe vanytes of &thorn;is
werlde and for to desyre &thorn;e Ioyes of heuene. / These wordis I saye to &thorn;e, noghte
as I had fully schewede &thorn;ese maners of meditacions as &thorn;ay ere wroghte in a manes
saule: bot I touche thaym to &thorn;e a lyttill, for &thorn;ou sulde by &thorn;is littill vndirstande &thorn;e
more. / Noghte-for-thi me thynke it es gude vn-to &thorn;e &thorn;at when thow dispose&yogh; &thorn;e
for to thynke of godde as I hafe before saide, or one o&thorn;er wyse, if thi herte be
dulle and myrke and felis no&thorn;er witt ne sauour ne deuocyone for to thynke, bot
anely a naked desyre &amp; a wayke will, &thorn;at &thorn;ou walde fayne thynke of godde bot
&thorn;ou cane noghte&mdash;&thorn;an I hope it es gud to &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou stryue noghte to mekill with
thi-selfe, as if &thorn;ou walde by thyne awene myghte ouer-come thi-selfe, for &thorn;ou
myght lightly ffall so in to more myrknes, bot if &thorn;ou ware &thorn;e more slye in thi
wirkynge; and for-thi I hald it &thorn;an moste sekyre vn-to &thorn;e for to say thi Pater
noster and &thorn;ine Aue maria, or &thorn;i matyns, or ells for to rede apone thi sauter,
for &thorn;at es euer-mor a sekyr standarde &thorn;at will noghte faile, who so may cleue
&thorn;er-to he sall noghte erre, and if &thorn;ou may by prayeynge gete deuocyone,
thane, if &thorn;i deuocyone be anely in affeccione, &thorn;at es in a grete desire to godde
with gastely delyte, halde furthe thi saynge &amp; brek noghte lyghtely off, ffor [oft]
it ffallis &thorn;at praynge with &thorn;e mouthe getis and kepis feruour of deuocione, and


<PB N="1: 290">

if a mane cesse of saynge, deuocyone vanysche away.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les if deuocione
of prayere brynge to thi herte gastely a thoghte of &thorn;e manhed of oure lorde,
or of any o&thorn;er before-said, and &thorn;is thoghte sulde be lettide by &thorn;i saynge,
&thorn;an may &thorn;ou cesse of saynge and Ocupye &thorn;e in meditacyone, vntill it passe away.
&para; Bot of certayne thynges the by-houes be warre in &thorn;i meditacione.  Sum sall
I tell &thorn;e. / Ane, &thorn;at whene &thorn;ou hase had a gastely thoghte ou&thorn;er in
ymagynynge of &thorn;e manhede of oure lorde or of swylke bodily thynges, and &thorn;i saule
hase bene fedde and comforthed &thorn;er-with, and passes away by &thorn;e-selfe: be
&thorn;ou noghte to besy for to kepe it still by maystry: ffor it sall &thorn;an turne to pyne
and to bitternes. / Also if it passe noghte away bot duellis still in thi mynde
by any trauell of &thorn;i-selfe, and &thorn;ou for comforthe of it will noghte leue it,
and &thorn;er-fore it reuys the fra &thorn;i slepe on nyghtys, or elles one dayes fra o&thorn;er
gud dedis, &thorn;is es noghte wele, thou sall wilfully breke of whene [tyme] askis,
&yogh;a sumtyme whene &thorn;ou hase maste deuocyone and ware latheste for to leue it, as
whene it passes resonabill tyme or ells it turnes to disesse of thyne euencristene,
Bot if &thorn;ou do so elles &thorn;ou dusse noghte wysely as me thynke.  A werldly mane
or womane &thorn;at felis noghte peraunter deuocyone twys in a &yogh;ere, if he felid by &thorn;e
grace of oure lorde gret compunccyone for his synnes, or ellis by a mynde of
&thorn;e passione of oure lorde, &thorn;ofe he ware put fra his slepe a nyghte or two or
thre vn-till his heued werke, it es na force, for it commes to &thorn;ame seldome;


<PB N="1: 291">

bot to &thorn;e, or to a-no&thorn;er mane or womane &thorn;at hase this maner of wirkynge in
custome as [it] ware ilke o&thorn;er day, it es spedfull for till hafe discrecyone in &yogh;our
wyrkynge, noghte fully fall &thorn;er-to for to folow it als mekill als will come.  And
I halde &thorn;at it es gud to &thorn;e for to vse &thorn;is maner in what deuocyone &thorn;at &thorn;ou be,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou hyng noght to lange &thorn;are-appone ou&thorn;er for to put &thorn;e fra thi mete or
thi slepe in tyme, or for to disesse any o&thorn;er mane vnskilfully.  The wyse mane
sayse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnia tempus habent,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;all thyngis hase tyme&raquo;. / Ano&thorn;er thyng es this &thorn;at &thorn;e by-houys be warre off.  If thi thoghte be ocupied in ymagynacyone of &thorn;e manhede of owre lorde or in any swilke o&thorn;er, and after this &thorn;ou erte besy with all &thorn;e desire of thi herte for to seke knawynge or felyng more gastely of &thorn;e godhede: prese noghte to mekill &thorn;ar-after, ne suffire noghte thi herte fall fra &thorn;e desire as if &thorn;ou ware abydande or gapand aftir sum qwyent stirrynge, or sum wondirfull felynge vthire &thorn;an &thorn;ou hase had.  Thou sall noghte do so.  It es ynoghe to me and to &thorn;e for to haue desyre &amp; langynge to oure lorde, and
if he will of his fre grace, ouer &thorn;is desire send vs of his gostely lyghte and
opyne oure gostely eghene for to se &amp; knawe more of hyme &thorn;an we hafe had
before by comone trauell, thanke we hym &thorn;ar-of; and if he will noghte, for
we er &yogh;it noghte meke ynoghe, or ells we er noghte disposede by clennes of
lyffynge in o&thorn;er sydis for to ressayue his grace, than sall we mekly knawe oure
awene syne and wrechednes, and hald vs payed with &thorn;e desyre &thorn;at we hafe to


<PB N="1: 292">

hyme, and with oure comone thoghtes &thorn;at may lyghtly fall vndir oure
ymagynacione, as of oure synns, or of Cristes passione, or of swilke o&thorn;er, or ells
with prayers of &thorn;e sauter, or sum o&thorn;er, and loue hym with all oure hert &thorn;at he
will gyff vs &thorn;at. / If &thorn;ou do o&thorn;erwyse, &thorn;ou may lyghtly be by-gyled by &thorn;e
spiryte of errour, ffor it es presumpsione a mane by his awene wytt for to prese
to mekill in to knawyng of gastly thynges, bot if he felid plente of grace: ffor &thorn;e
wyse man saise &thorn;us: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Scrutator maiestatis opprimetur a gloria,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to say: &laquo;Raunsaker of &thorn;e myghte of godde and of his maieste with-owttene gret clennes and meknes sall be ouerlayde and oppresside of hym-selfe&raquo; &amp;c.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">explicit.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
