<PB N="1: 264"><HEAD>[Additional material from printed editions]<NOTE
ID="n6">The early printed editions and some late MSS add extra material at the beginning and end, reproduced by Horstman primarily from Julian Notary's 1507 edition.</NOTE></HEAD>


<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD TYPE="main">[Beginning]</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ed. J. Notary, 1507</HEAD><OPENER>This is a deuout boke compyled by mayster Walter Hylton to a deuout man
in temperal estate, how he sholde rule hym.</OPENER> <HEAD>&para; How a man &thorn;at wol be ghostly must fyrst vsen moche bodyly exercyse
in penaunce and destroyenge of synne: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cap. Primum.</FOREIGN>
</HEAD><P>  DEre brother in Cryst, two maner of states there are in holy chyrche by &thorn;e
whiche crysten soules plesen god &amp; geten hem the blysse of heuen; that one is
bodyly, &amp; that other is ghostly.  Bodyly werkyng longeth pryncypally to worldly


<PB N="1: 265">

men &amp; wymen the whiche lefully vsen worldly goodes, &amp; wylfully vsen worldly
besynes.  Also it longeth to all yonge begynnynge men the whiche comen newe
out of worldly synnes to the seruyce of god; for to make hem able to ghostly
werkyng &amp; for to breke downe the vnbuxumnes of the body by dyscrecyon [and
suche] bodyly werkynge, &thorn;at it myght be suple &amp; redy, &amp; not mekyl contraryous
to the spyryte in ghostly werkynge.  For [as] saynt poul sayth, as woman was made
for man &amp; not man for woman, ryght so bodyly werkynge was made for ghostly
&amp; not ghostly for bodyly.  Bodyly werkynge goth before &amp; ghostly comyth after;
as saynt Poul sayth: &para; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non prius quod spirituale, sed quod animale, deinde [quod] spirituale.</FOREIGN>  And this is a cause why it behoueth to be so: for we are borne in synne and corrupcyon of the flesshe by the whyche we are soo blynded &amp; so ouerlayed &thorn;at we haue neyther the ghostly knowyng of god by lyghte of vnderstondynge, ne ghostly felynge of hym by clene desyre of louynge. &amp; therfore we may not sodeynly sterte out of this derke nyght of this flesshly corrupcyon into &thorn;at ghostly lyght; for we maye not suffre it ne bere it for syknes of ourself, no more than we may with our bodyly eyen whan they are sore beholde the
lyght of the son. &amp; therfore we must abyde &amp; werke be processe of tyme.
Fyrst by bodely werkes besily tyl we be dyscharged of this heuy burden of synne
whiche lettyth vs fro ghostly werkyng; &amp; tyl our soule be somwhat clensed fro
grete outwarde synnes &amp; abled to ghostly werke.  By this bodily werkynge [that]
I speke of mayst thou vnderstonde al maner of god werkis &thorn;at thy soule doth
by &thorn;e wyttes &amp; &thorn;e membris of thy body, vnto thyself as in fastyng, waking, &amp; in
restraynyng of flesshly lustes by penaunce doyng, or to thyn euencristen be
fulfyllyng of &thorn;e dedes of mercy bodyly or ghostly, or vnto god be sufferynge of al
bodely myscheues for &thorn;e loue of ryghtwysnes. / Al thyse werkes done in trouthe
by charyte plesen god; withoute whiche they are nought.  Than who so desyreth
for to be occupyed ghostly, it is syker &amp; profitable to hym &thorn;at he be fyrst wel
asayed a longe tyme in this bodely werkynge, for thyse bodely dedes are a token
&amp; a shewyng of moral vertues, withouten whiche a soule is not able for to werke
ghostly.  Breke down fyrst pryde in bodely beryng &amp; also within thin hert
thynkyng, bostyng &amp; praysyng of [thyselfe and of thy dedis, presumyng of]
thyself [&] vayn lykyng in thyself of onythyng &thorn;at god hath sent to the bodely
or ghostly.  Breke downe also enuye &amp; yre ageynst thyn euencrysten whether


<PB N="1: 266">

they be riche or pore, gode or bad, that thou hate hym not ne haue dysdeyne of
hym wylfully neyther in worde ne in dede.  Also breke downe couetyse of worldly
good, &thorn;at thou for &thorn;e holdyng [or] getyng or sauyng of it offende not thy
conscyence, ne breke not charyte to god &amp; to thyn euencrysten for loue of ony
worldly good, but &thorn;at thou getyst to kepe it &amp; spende it without loue &amp; vayn
lykyng of it, as resyn asketh, in worshyp of god &amp; helpe of thyn euencrysten.
Breke downe also as mekil as thou mayst flesshly lykynges eyther of accydye or
bodyly ese, gloteny or lechery; &amp; than whan thou hast ben wel traueyled &amp; wel
asayed in all suche bodely werkis, than mayst thou by grace ordeyne the to
ghostly werkyng.  The grace &amp; &thorn;e goodnes &amp;c.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section"> <HEAD>[Conclusion]</HEAD><P>And therfore the wyse man sayth in an other place on this wyse: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Altiora te ne quesieris, et fortiora te ne scrutatus fueris</FOREIGN>, that is <ADD
N="ed. Richard Pynson, 1516">for</ADD> to saye: &raquo;hygh thynges that are aboue thy wytte and thy reason seke not, &amp; greate thynges that are aboue thy myght ransake not&laquo;.  By these wordes the wyse man forbedeth not vtterly for to seke and ransake ghostly and heuenly thynges, but he forbyddeth vs that as longe as we are flesshely and not clensed fro vayne loue of the worlde, that we take not vpon vs by our owne trauayle ne by our owne wytte for to ransake or to fele ghostly thynges; <ADD
N="ed. Richard Pynson, 1516">ne thoughe we fele ghostlye thyngys</ADD> and grete feruour of &thorn;e loue of god so moche [that] we set at nought all erthly thynges and vs thynketh that we wolde for goddes loue forsake all the Ioyes and [all] the welth of this worlde, yet are we not <ADD
N="ed. Richard Pynson, 1516">anone</ADD> able to redy for to seke and beholde ghostly thynges that are aboue vs, vntyll our soule be made sotyll &amp; tyll it be made sadde &amp; stable in vertues by processe of tyme and encreasynge of grace.  For as saynt Gregory sayth: no man sodenly is made souerayne in grace, but fro lytell he begynneth and by processe wexeth vntyll he be perfyte.</P><TRAILER>AMEN.<LB>&para; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Explicit vita mixta.</FOREIGN></TRAILER></DIV4></DIV3>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text"> 
<DIV3 TYPE="text"><PB N="1: 321">
<HEAD TYPE="main">The Abbey of the Holy Ghost</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="MS">Ms. Thornton (Lincoln Cath. 91)</HEAD><MILESTONE
N="271" UNIT="folio">
<OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Religio Sancti Spiritus, Religio Munda.</FOREIGN></OPENER>

<P>Off the abbaye of saynte Spirite, that es in a place that es callede conscyence.
A dere brethir and systirs, I see &thorn;at many walde be in religyone bot &thorn;ay may
noghte, owthir for pouerte or for drede of thaire kyne or for band of maryage,
and for-thi I make here a buke of &thorn;e religeon of &thorn;e herte, &thorn;at es, of &thorn;e abbaye
of the holy goste, that all tho &thorn;at ne may noghte be bodyly in religyone, &thorn;at
&thorn;ay may be gostely.  A Ihesu mercy, whare may &thorn;is abbay beste be funded
and &thorn;is religione?  Now certis, nowhare so wele als in a place &thorn;at es called
Conscyence; and who so will, be besy to funde &thorn;is holy religione, and &thorn;at may


<PB N="1: 322">

ilke gud cristyne mane and woman do &thorn;at will be besy &thorn;er-abowte.  And at &thorn;e
begynnynge, it es by-houely &thorn;at &thorn;e place of thi conscience be clensed clene of
syne; to &thorn;e wilke clensynge &thorn;e haly goste sall sende two maydyns &thorn;at ere
conande, the one es callede Rightwysnes, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er es called Luffe of Clennes;
thiese two sall cast fro &thorn;e conscience and fro &thorn;e herte all maner of fylthe of
foule thoghtes and desyris.  / Whene &thorn;e place of &thorn;e conscience es wele clensed,
than sall &thorn;e grownde be mad large and depe; and this two maydenes sall make:
&thorn;e one es callede Mekenes, &thorn;at sall make &thorn;e grownde depe thorowe lowlynes
of hir-selfe, the to&thorn;er es callede Pouerte, &thorn;at makis it large &amp; wyde abowne;
&thorn;at castis ouer ylke a halfe &thorn;e erthe owte, &thorn;at es to say, alle erthely lustes &amp; worldely thoghtes ferre fro &thorn;e herte, &thorn;at if &thorn;ay hafe erthely gudis with luffe &thorn;ay
forgete &thorn;ayme for &thorn;e tyme &amp; castis no lufe to &thorn;ame, nor hase noghte ne settis
noghte for &thorn;at tyme &thorn;aire hertes no-thynge one &thorn;ame&mdash;and thies ere callede
pure in spyrite, of whame god spekes in &thorn;e gospelle &amp; sayse &thorn;at thaires es &thorn;e
kyngdome of heuene, be thies wordes <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Beati pauperes spiritu, quoniam ipsorum est rignum celorum</FOREIGN>.  Blyssed es &thorn;ane &thorn;at religyone &thorn;at es fun&macr;dide in pouerte and in
meknes.  This es agaynes many religyous &thorn;at are couetous and prowde.  / This
abbaye also sall be sett on a gud reuer, and &thorn;at sall be &thorn;e reuer of teres; for
swylke abbayes &thorn;at ere sett one swylke gude ryuers, &thorn;ay are wele at ese, and &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 323">

more dylecyous duellyng es &thorn;er.  One swylke a reuer was Mary Mawdelayne
fowndide, ffor-thy grace and rechesse come all to hir will.  And for-thi sayde
Dauid thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fluminis impetus letificat ciuitatem,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye &laquo;the gude reuer mase &thorn;e cete lykande&raquo;; for it es clene, sekyr, &amp; ryche of all gude marchandyse.  And so &thorn;e reuer of teris clenses goddis cete, &thorn;at es mannes saule &thorn;at es goddes cete; and also &thorn;e holy man sayse of fylthe of synne &thorn;at it brynges owte &thorn;e reches of vertus and of alle gude thewes.  / And when &thorn;is grownde es made, &thorn;an sall come a dameselle, Bowsomnes, on &thorn;e tone halfe, and dameselle Miserecorde one &thorn;e to&thorn;er halfe, for to rayse &thorn;e walles one heghte, and to make &thorn;am stalworthe: with a fre hert largely gyfande to &thorn;e pure &amp; to &thorn;ame &thorn;at myster hase; ffor whene we do any gud werkes of charite thorow &thorn;e grace of gode, also ofte-sythis
als we &thorn;am do in &thorn;e lufe and &thorn;e louynge of god and in gud entent, als many
gud stonys we laye one owre howssynge in &thorn;e blysse of heuene, festenande
togedir with &thorn;e lufe of gode and oure euene-crystene.  We rede &thorn;at Salomone made
his howssynge of grete precyouse stones: thiese precyous stones are almos-dedis
and werkes of mercy &amp; holy werkes; &thorn;at sall be bowdene togedir with
qwykelyme of lufe &amp; stedfaste byleue, and for-thi sayse Dauid, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnia opera eius in fide,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye, &laquo;alle his werkes be done in stedfaste byleue&raquo;; and als a walle
maye not laste with-owttene syment or mor[ter], also no werkes &thorn;at we wyrke are
noghte worthe to god nor spedfull till oure sawles, bot &thorn;ay be done in the lufe


<PB N="1: 324">

of god and in trewe by-leue; ffor alle &thorn;at &thorn;e synfull dose, alle es loste. / Sythene
dameselle Sufferance and damesell Forte sall rayse &thorn;e pelars, &amp; vndirsett &thorn;ame so
strangly &thorn;at no wynde of wordes, angre o[r] stryffe, fleschely nor gastely, sowre
ne swete, caste &thorn;ame downe. / A, dere brethir and systers, &yogh;itt by-houys &thorn;e
cloystyre be made, one foure corners; and it es callede &laquo;cloyster&raquo; for it closys and
stekys, and warely sall be lokkede.  My dere bre&thorn;er and systyrs, wylke of
&yogh;ow as will halde this gastely religyone &amp; be in ryste of sawle &amp; in swetnes of
hert, halde &thorn;e with-Ine &thorn;e cloyster, and so sparre &thorn;ou &thorn;e &yogh;ates, and so warely
kepe &thorn;ou &thorn;e wardes of &thorn;i cloyster, &thorn;at non o[t]er fandynge&yogh; nor euylle
styrrynges hafe in-gate in the &amp; make &thorn;e thy sylence forto [breke] or styrre the
to synne; steke thyne eghne fro fowle syghtes, thyne heres fro foule herynges,
thy mouthe fra foule speche, and thyne herte fra foule thoghtes. / Scrifte sall
[make] thi chapitir, Predicacione sall make thi fratour, Oracione sall make thi
chapelle; Contemplacione sall make thi dortoure, &thorn;at sall be raysede one heghte
with heghe &yogh;ernynge and with lufe-qwykkynynge to gode, and &thorn;at sall be owte
ofe worldly noyse and of worldly angyrse and besynes als fere furthe als &thorn;ou may
for &thorn;e tyme thorow grace for &thorn;e tyme of prayere.  Contemplacione es a deuote
rysynge of herte with byrnynge lufe to god to do wele, and in his delites Ioyes


<PB N="1: 325">

his saule, and somdele ressayues of that swetnes &thorn;at goddis chosene childir sall
hafe in heuene. / Rewfulnes sall make the fermorye, Deuocione sall make &thorn;e celere,
Meditacion sall make the gernere. / And when all &thorn;e howses bene made, &thorn;an
behoues &thorn;e holy gaste ordeyne &thorn;e couent of grace &amp; of vertu; and &thorn;an sall &thorn;e
holy gaste &thorn;at &thorn;is religyone es of, bee wardene and visiture.  The whilke god &thorn;e
ffadir funded thorow his powere, ffor &thorn;us saise Dauide: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fundauit eam altissimus,</FOREIGN>
and this es to saye: &laquo;the heghe gode &thorn;e ffadyr ffundide this relegyone&raquo;; the Sone thurgh his wysedome &thorn;an ordayned it, als sayne Paule witnes it: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Que [sunt], a deo ordinata sunt,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;alle &thorn;at es of god, the Sone it rewlis &amp; ordaynes&raquo;;
the Holy goste &yogh;emys it and vesettes it, and &thorn;at saye [we] in holy kyrke whene we
saye &thorn;is: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Veni creator Spiritus,</FOREIGN>with <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Qui paraclitus diceris,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es for to saye: &laquo;come &thorn;ou god &thorn;e haly gaste, and thyne &thorn;ou vesete, and fulfill &thorn;ame with grace&raquo;. / And than the gude lady Charite, als scho &thorn;at es most worthy by-fore alle o&thorn;er, sall be abbas of this sely abbaye.  And also als &thorn;ay &thorn;at are in relegyone sall do no thynge, ne saye thynge, ne gange in to no stede, ne take no gyfte
with-owttene leue of &thorn;e abbasse, also gastely sall none of swylke thyngys be done
with-owttene leue of charite; ffor thus commandes sayne Paule: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnia vestra in caritate fiant,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es: &laquo;what so &yogh;e do or saye or thynke with herte, alle &yogh;e mon


<PB N="1: 326">

do in charite&raquo;.  A, dere Bre&thorn;er and systirs, whate here es harde comandement!
Bot it es [notfull] to oure sawles &thorn;at oure thoghtes &amp; oure wordes &amp; oure
werkes be onely done for lufe.  Wayleawaye, if I durste saye!  for many are in
religione, bot to fewe relegious &thorn;at &thorn;ay ne done &thorn;e comandment of saynte
Paule, or &thorn;e concelle of &thorn;e gud lady Charite &thorn;at es abbesse of this cely relegyone;
and for-thi &thorn;ay lose mekill tyme, and losses &thorn;aire mede, and ekes thaire payne
gretly, bot if &thorn;ay amende &thorn;am.  Whare-fore, leue bre&thorn;er and systirs, bese
euermore wakire and warre, and in all &yogh;oure werkes thynke depely &thorn;at whate-so &yogh;ee
doo be it done in &thorn;e lufe of gode and for &thorn;e lufe of [god]. / &THORN;e lady Wysdome sall
be prioresse, for scho es worthi, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nam prior omnium creat[ur]ar[um] est sapiencia,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es: &laquo;al&thorn;er-firste es Wysedome made&raquo;, and thurgh &thorn;e lare and &thorn;e concele of &thorn;is prioresse sall we do alle &thorn;at we do; and this sayse Dauid: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnia in sapiencia fecisti,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase made &thorn;ou hase made wysely&raquo;. / The gud lady Meknes &thorn;at aye elyke makis hir-selfe lowly and vndir alle o&thorn;er, sall be supprioresse: hir sall &yogh;e honoure and wirchipe with bouxomnes.  A Ihesu,
blyssede [es] &thorn;at abbaye and cely es &thorn;at religione, &thorn;at hase so haly ane abbas as
Charyte, a prioresse as Wysedome, a supprioresse as Mekenes.  A, dere bre&thorn;er
and systirs, blyssede and cely are &thorn;ay; &thorn;at es to saye, those saules are cely &thorn;at
haldis &thorn;e comandment of &thorn;e abbas lady Charite, and &thorn;e techynge of &thorn;e priores
lady Wysdome, and the concele of &thorn;e suppriorese lady Mekenes.  For who-so es


<PB N="1: 327">

bouxome to thir thre ladyse, and &thorn;aire lyffe rewlis aftir &thorn;aire techynge, the
ffadir, the Sone, the Holy goste, &thorn;am sall comfurthe with many gostely Ioyes, and
&thorn;am helpe and socoure in alle fandinges [&] angirs &thorn;at &thorn;ay ne be noghte
ouer-comene; &thorn;am thare drede no wrenkis ne no wylis of the fende, for why god es
with &thorn;ame and standis aye by &thorn;ame als a trewe kepere &amp; a strange; and ffor-&thorn;i
says Dauid thus: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Dominus protector vite mee, a quo trepidabo?</FOREIGN>  als if he sayd: &laquo;god es my champyone staleworthe and trewe, &thorn;at for me &thorn;at es so wayke and so vnmyghtfull, agaynes myne enemyse hase vndirtane for to fyghte: whame thare
me &thorn;ane drede ? now trewly, righte none&raquo;.  We rede in a buke of Danyele &thorn;at
a myghtfull [kyng] was &thorn;at mene callede Nabogodhonosore, &thorn;at sett in [his]
reme thre mene &thorn;at solde do &amp; ordayne and stabyll als baylyes alle &thorn;e rewme,
so &thorn;at &thorn;e kynge herde no noyse ne no playnte, bot &thorn;at he myghte be in pese
&amp; in Ioye &amp; in ryste in his rewme.  And righte so &thorn;e rewme of &thorn;e sawle &thorn;at
thiese thre baylyes are Ine, and &thorn;e religione &thorn;at thies thre prelates are Ine, &thorn;at
es Charite, Wysedome and Mekenes, thare es pese, ryste and lykynge in saule &amp; comforthe in lyfe. / Damesele Discrecyone, &thorn;at es witty and be-[fore]-ware, sall
be tresorere; scho sall hafe in hir kepynge alle, and &yogh;ernely luke &thorn;at all go
wele. / Orysone salle be chaunterese, &thorn;at with hertly prayers sall trauele daye &amp; nyghte.  And whate Orysone es, &thorn;e holy mane sayse: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio est deo sacrificium, angelis solacium, diabolo tormentum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye: &laquo;Orysone es a louely sacrafice


<PB N="1: 328">

to god, solase and lykynge to angells, and turment to &thorn;e fende&raquo;.  It witnes in &thorn;e
lyfe of saynte Barthilmewe &thorn;at it es turment to &thorn;e fende: for &thorn;e fende cryede
to hym and sayde: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Bartholomee, ince[n]dunt me oraciones tue,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye: &laquo;Bartilmew, thi prayers byrnys me&raquo;.  And &thorn;at [it] es lykynge to angels, saynte [Austyn] wytnes it and sayse: &laquo;Whene we praye with deuocyone of hert, the angels standis byfore [vs] daunsesande &amp; playeande, and beris oure prayers vp, and present &thorn;ame to &thorn;e ffadir of heuene; &thorn;e whilke prayers oure lorde commandes
to wryte in &thorn;e buke of lyfe&raquo;.  [zt;it it] es sacrafyce to god, [zt;is ane] of &thorn;ame &thorn;at
hym moste payes, and for-thi he askes vs it &thorn;er he sayse thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sacrificium laudis honorificabis me,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye: &laquo;zt;e salle wyrchipe [me] with sacrifice of louynge&raquo;. /
Iubilacio, hir felowe, sall helpe.  And what Iubilacione es, a seynt it telles and
sayse &thorn;at &laquo;Iubylacione es a grete Ioye &thorn;at es consayuede in teris thorow brynnande
luffe of spirite, &thorn;at may noghte be in all schewede no in alle hyde&raquo;; als it fallis
somtyme of tho &thorn;at god hertly lufes; &thorn;ere efter &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe bene in prayere
and in orysone, &thorn;ay are so lyghte &amp; so lykande in god, &thorn;at whare so &thorn;ay go &thorn;er
hertes synges murnynge songes of lufe-longynge to &thorn;aire lefe, &thorn;at &thorn;ay zt;erne with
armys of lufe semlyly to falde, and with gastely mourny[n]ge of his gudnes swetly
to kysse; and zt;it vmwhile so depely &thorn;at wordis &thorn;am wanttis; for luf-longynge so


<PB N="1: 329">

ferforthe rauesches thorow hertis &thorn;at somtyme &thorn;ay ne wote noghte whate &thorn;ay
do. / Deuocione es celeresse, &thorn;at kepis &thorn;e wynnes, bothe &thorn;e white and &thorn;e rede,
with depe vmbythynkynge of &thorn;e gudnes of god, &amp; of &thorn;e paynnes &amp; of &thorn;e anguyse
&thorn;at he tholede, and of the Ioyes &amp; &thorn;e delytes of paradyse &thorn;at he hase ordayned
to his chosene. / Penance sall be kychynnere, &thorn;at with grete besynes trayuells
daye &amp; nyghte for to plese alle, and ofte swetis with bitter teris for angyre of
hir synnes.  Scho makes gud metis, &thorn;at es many bitter sorowes alle for hir gyltezt;,
and theys metis fedis &thorn;e saule; bot scho sparis hir-selfe thorow abstynence and
etys bot littill, ffor do scho neuer so mekill ne so mony-folde of gud werkes, ay
semys scho hir-selfe vnworthy and synfull. / Atemperance serue[s]e in the fratour,
&thorn;at scho to ylkone so lukes &thorn;at mesure be ouer-alle, &thorn;at none ouer-mekill nere
ouer-lyttill ete ne drynke. / Sobirnes redis at the borde the lyues of the haly
ffadirs, and synges and reherces whate lyfe &thorn;at &thorn;ay lede, for to take gud
ensampille to do als &thorn;ay dyd, and &thorn;ere-thorowe slyke mede to wyne als &thorn;ay now
hafe. / Pete es spensere, &thorn;at dose seruesse to gud all &thorn;at scho maye.  And Mercy
hir syster sall be ambynowre, &thorn;at gyffes to alle, and noghte kane kepe to hir-selfe. /
The lady Drede es portere, &thorn;at kepis besyly &thorn;e cloyster of &thorn;e herte &amp; of &thorn;e
conscience, &thorn;at chases owte alle vnthewes and calles In alle gud vertus, &amp; so


<PB N="1: 330">

speres &thorn;e zt;atis of &thorn;e cloyster &amp; &thorn;e wyndows, &thorn;at none evylle hafe none Ingate
to &thorn;e herte thorowe &thorn;e zt;atis of &thorn;e mouthe ne thorowe &thorn;e wyndows of &thorn;e
eghne nere of &thorn;e eris. / Honeste es maystresse of &thorn;e nouyce, and teches &thorn;am
alle curtasye, how &thorn;ay sall speke and gange and sytt and stande, and how &thorn;ay
sall bere &thorn;ame with-owttene and with-Ine, howe to god, how to mane, so &thorn;at
alle &thorn;at &thorn;ame sese of &thorn;am may take ensampill of alle gudnes and alle gud
thewes. / Dameselle Curtasye sall be hostelere, &amp; &thorn;ay &thorn;at com[es] and bydes
scho sall &thorn;am resafe hendely, so &thorn;at ylke one may speke [gud] of hir.  And for-thi
&thorn;at now&thorn;er sall be by &thorn;ame one emange the gestes&mdash;ffor it myghte falle &thorn;at
damesele Curtasye solde be oure-balde &amp; ouer-hardy,&mdash;for-thi sall scho hafe a
felawe damesele Symplese, for &thorn;ay two alyede to-gedir thorowe felawchipe are
sekyre and semande; for &thorn;e tone with-owttene &thorn;e to&thorn;er vmwhile es littill worthe:
for ouer-grete symplesse may make of &thorn;e symple a sott or ouer-nyce, and
ouer-grete curtasye may be somewhile o&thorn;er to lyghte chere or to glade, or ouer-balde
for to paye &thorn;e gestes; bot fayre and wele, &amp; with-owttene fandynge of blame,
may &thorn;ay do &thorn;aire offece bothe to-gedir. / Damesele Resone sall be puruerere,
ffor scho sall ordayne with-In &amp; with-owttyne so skilfully &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne be no
defaute. / Damesele Lewte sall be fermoresse, &thorn;at sall trauelle abowte &amp; besely serue
&thorn;e seke.  And for-&thorn;i sen &thorn;at in &thorn;e fermory of this religyone are moo seke &thorn;ane


<PB N="1: 331">

hole, mo febyll &thorn;ane wighte, and es ouer-grete trauelle to serue &thorn;am alle
hyrone, ffor-thi sall scho hafe a felawe, damesele Largesse, &thorn;at sall see full wele to
ylkone after &thorn;at &thorn;am nedis. / Damesele conande and wysse &thorn;at es callede
Meditacyone or Poleschesy, es garnere: scho sall gedyre and sembyll gude whete and
o&thorn;er gud cornnes to-gedir, and &thorn;at fully, with grete plente, thorow &thorn;e whilke alle
&thorn;e gud ladyse of &thorn;e howse may hafe &thorn;aire sustenance.  Meditacione es in gud
thoghtes of god, &amp; of his werkes, and of his wordes, and of his creaturs, and of
his pa&ymacr;nes &thorn;at he tholede, and of his grete lufe &thorn;at he had and hase to &thorn;ame
for whayme he tholede.  This garnere had &thorn;e gud kyng Dauid, ffor-&thorn;i was he
ay riche &amp; in plente; and for-thi he sayse in &thorn;e psaltyre: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In omnibus operibus tuis meditabar ... die ac nocte,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es to saye: &laquo;Lorde, in thi lawe I thynke nyghte
and daye&raquo;.  This es begynnynge of all perfeccione whene mane settis and stabylls
his herte in depe thynkynge on god &amp; on his werkes; ffor ofte es better a gud
thoghte in haly meditacyone &thorn;an many wordes sayd in prayere, ffor &thorn;e holy
thoghtes in meditacione cryes in goddes eris.  Ofte it falles &thorn;at &thorn;e herte es so
ouer-tane and so raueschede in holy meditacyone &thorn;at it wote noghte what it dose,
heris nor sayse, or seys, so depely es &thorn;e herte festenede in god and in his werkes
&thorn;at wordis hym wanttis: and &thorn;e stillere &thorn;at he es in slyke meditacione the
luddere he cryes in goddis eris; and &thorn;erfore sayd Dauid thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quoniam tacui, dum


<PB N="1: 332">

clamarem tota die,</FOREIGN> as if he sayd: &laquo;Lorde, lo here the whills myne herte was in
depe thoghtes in the and of thi werkes, it cryed one the in holy medytacyons,
and was stylle as beynge domme&raquo;.  And &thorn;er sayse &thorn;e glose, &laquo;the grete cryes &thorn;at we crye to god &thorn;an are oure grete desyres and oure grete &yogh;ernynges&raquo;.  And this sayse saynte Denyse, &thorn;at sayse: &raquo;When &thorn;e herte es lyfte and raueschede to &thorn;e lufe of god with gelouse &yogh;ernynges, he ne may sownde with worde &thorn;at &thorn;e herte
thynkis&raquo;.  This holy Meditacione &thorn;at es &thorn;e gernare &thorn;at kepis &yogh;erely &thorn;e whete &thorn;at es rede with-owte and white with-Ine, &thorn;at hase &thorn;e syde clouene, of &thorn;e whilke
men mase gud brede: &thorn;at es called Ihesu Criste, &thorn;at with-owttene was rede of
his awene blode, and whitte with-Ine thorow his awene mekenes and clennes of
lyfe, and hade his syde clouene with a spere; this es &thorn;e brede &thorn;at we ressayue
and etis in &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e altyr.  And wele &thorn;ou weite &thorn;at the gerner sall
be abowne &thorn;e selare: also sall be meditacione before deuocione; and for-thi
Meditacione sall be gernare, Deuocione celerrere, and Pete penetancere.  Of thiese
thre sayse &thorn;e profete Dauide: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">A ffructu frumenti, vini, et olei sui, multiplicati sunt,</FOREIGN>
&thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;Of the fruyte of &thorn;e whete and wyne and oyle &thorn;ay ere fulfillede&raquo;. In &thorn;e alde lawe in many stedis gode takis to his chosene thiese thre; &laquo;Serue me, he sayse, wele, &amp; I sall gyffe &yogh;owe plente of whete and wyne &amp; oyle&raquo;.  Plente of whete, es hertly to thynke one &thorn;e croyce and euer haffe &thorn;e passyone of Ihesu Crist hertly in mynde: this es meditacione.  Plente of wyne, &thorn;at es &thorn;e welle of teres, wele for to wepe: this es deuocione.  Plente of oyle, &thorn;at es for to hafe


<PB N="1: 333">

delyte and sauoyre in god: and this es comforthe.  For &thorn;e oyle gyffes odoure to
metis, and lyghtes in &thorn;e kyrke, and byrnys in the lampe; also whene goddis
seruandes hase depely thoghte with schire herte on gode &amp; on his werkes, with
lufe-longynge to &thorn;ame, &thorn;ane hase god pete of &thorn;ame, and sendis &thorn;am petance of
comforthe and of gastely Ioye.  And th[u]s gyffes [&thorn;am], at &thorn;e begynnynge meditacione,
and &thorn;is es &thorn;e whete &thorn;at god hyghttes vs; than sendis god sone after &thorn;e wyne,
&thorn;at es plente of teris and deuocyone &thorn;at men consayues in medytacyone; and
after &thorn;e wyne of swete teris than sendys he &thorn;e oyle of consolacione &thorn;at gyffes
&thorn;ame sauour &amp; lyghtnes [&thorn;aire] knaweliggynge, and schewes to &thorn;am of his heuenly
priuatyse &thorn;at es hide fro &thorn;ame &thorn;at folowes fleschely desyris and gyffes &thorn;ame-selfe
alle to &thorn;e wysedome of &thorn;e worlde and his fantasyse, and so enflawmes &thorn;am with
&thorn;e blysse of his lufe &thorn;at &thorn;ay taste somedelle &amp; fele how swete he es, how gud
he es, how luffande he es&mdash;bot noghte alle fully.  I wote wele &thorn;at none may
fele it fully bot if his herte solde bryste for lykynge of Ioye.  Sayne Austyne
telles of a preste &thorn;at, whene he herde any thynge of god &thorn;at lykynge ware Ine,
he wold be so raueschede in Ioye &thorn;at he walde fall downe and lygge als he
ware dede; and also in &thorn;at tyme if men layde byrnande fyre to his flesche
nakide, he felid it no more &thorn;an dose a dede corse.  Sayne Bernarde spekes of


<PB N="1: 334">

&thorn;e wordis of Iob &thorn;er he sayse <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Abscondit lucem in manibus</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es at say &laquo;god hase lyghte hyde in his handis&raquo;: &laquo;&THORN;ou wote wele, he &thorn;at hase a candill lyghte bytwene his handis, he may hyde it &amp; schewe it at his owenne will.  So dose oure lorde to his chosene.  Whene he will he opynis his handes and lyghtenes &thorn;am with heuenly gladnes; and whene he will, he closis his handis and withdrawes &thorn;e lykynge &amp; &thorn;e comforthe fro &thorn;ame&raquo;.  He wille noghte &thorn;at &thorn;ay fele it fully aye, bot here he gyffes &thorn;ame as for to taste &amp; sauour somedele how swete he es, how gud he es, als Dauid sayse <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Gustate et videte quoniam suauis est dominus</FOREIGN>, als if god sayd to vs, ,be &thorn;is comforthe and this lykynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is schorte tyme
hase of me, &thorn;ou may taste &amp; fele how swete, how gude I ame to my chosyne
in my blysse in &thorn;e werlde with-owttene ende'; and &thorn;us he dose for to drawe vs
fro werldly besynes and &thorn;e lykynge &thorn;er-of, and for to enflawme oure hertes
with lufe-&yogh;ernynges, ffor to wyne and to hafe &thorn;e lykynge of &thorn;at Ioye alle at &thorn;e
full, in body and saule with hym for to be euer-more with-owttene ende. / A
dameselle wyse &amp; wele taghte &thorn;at mene calles Gelosye, &thorn;at es ay wakyre and
besy euer ylyke wele for to do, sall kepe &thorn;e orloge, and sall wakkyne &thorn;e o&thorn;er
ladyse &amp; make &thorn;ame arely to ryse and go &thorn;e wyllylyere to &thorn;aire seruysse.  &THORN;er
es orloges in towne &thorn;at wakyns mene to ryse to bodily trauayle, &amp; &thorn;at es &thorn;e
[coke]; and &thorn;er es orloges in &thorn;e cete &thorn;at wakynnes &thorn;e marchauntes to wende
abowte &thorn;aire marchandyce: &thorn;at es &thorn;e [wayte] &thorn;at blawes daye.  And &thorn;er es orloges


<PB N="1: 335">

in relegione, of contemplacione.  And this es of this holy relegyone &thorn;at es fundede
of &thorn;e haly gaste, and &thorn;is es Ielosy, and this es sauoyre of perfeccione.  &amp; ofte
it falles in relegione, before &thorn;at &thorn;e orloge falles or any belles rynges, goddes
gostely seruandes are lange wakenede be-fore, and hase wepede by-fore god, and
hase waschene &thorn;ame with &thorn;aire teris, and &thorn;aire spyrit hase vesete(!) with deuote
prayers and gastely comforthe.  And why rose &thorn;ay so arely &amp; so tymly?  witterly,
for &thorn;e orloge of lufe and damesele Ielosye had wakened &thorn;ame before &thorn;e tyme
&thorn;at &thorn;e handmade orloge felle.  A, dere bre&thorn;er and syster[s], sely ar tho sawles
&thorn;at &thorn;e lufe of god and longyng till him wakyns, and slomers noghte no slepis
noghte in slowthe of fleschly lustes!  For-thi he sayse in Canticis: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Ego] dormio et
cor meum vigelat,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;when I slepe bodily my flesche for to ese &amp; ryste, my herte es ay wakyre in gelosy and in lufe-&yogh;ernynge to gode&raquo;.  That saule
&thorn;at &thorn;us wakes to god, [may] thynke [with] hole conscyence &thorn;at werldly mene thynke,
and &thorn;at es this: <FOREIGN>Ieo ay le quer a-loche, rauayle par amours</FOREIGN>, &thorn;at es at saye: &laquo;Myne herte es styrte fro me, wakened with lufe&raquo;.  Whate es this &thorn;at mase &thorn;e herte fro &thorn;e flesche to wake, and for &thorn;at es it as it were fremde to hym?  wittirly, Ieloussye with lufe-teres &amp; murnynge, with lufe-longynge consayuede in deuote vprysynge of herte.  // When this abbaye was alle wele ordaynede and goddes will seruede in ryste &amp; in lykynge &amp; in pese of saule: than come a tyrante of &thorn;e lande thorowe


<PB N="1: 336">

his powere and did in this holy abbaye ffoure doghtyrs &thorn;at he hade, &thorn;at were
lothely &amp; of euyll maners, &thorn;at &thorn;e fende was fadir of thiese doghtirs.  &THORN;e firste
of &thorn;is foule barne-tyme highte Envye, the to&thorn;er highte Pride, the thirde
highte Gruchyn[g]e, the ferthe highte False demynge of o&thorn;er.  Thiese foure doghetirs
&thorn;an hase &thorn;e tyraunt, &thorn;e deuell of helle, for euyll will &amp; malese, done in this
holy abbaye, and &thorn;ay with &thorn;aire foule vnclennes &thorn;e couent hase greuede and
harmede, so &thorn;at &thorn;ay no riste ne no pese may hafe, nyghte nor daye, nor
lykynge in saule.  And when &thorn;e gud lady Charite saw this &thorn;at was abbas, and the
lady Wysdome &thorn;at was prioresse, and &thorn;e lady Mekenes supprioresse, and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er gude ladyse of this holy abbaye, that the holy abbaye was in poynte for
to worthe to noghte thorowe &thorn;e wykkydnes of thir foure, than range the
chapetour belle and gedirde &thorn;am alle to-gedyr, and asked concele whate was beste
to do.  And than lady Dyscrecyone &thorn;ame concelde &thorn;at &thorn;ay solde alle falle in
prayere to &thorn;e Holy goste, &thorn;at of this abbay es vesetour, &thorn;at he haste hym for
to come, as &thorn;ay grete myster hade, thare for to help and vesete with his grace.
And &thorn;ay all at hire consaile with grete deuocyone of herte vn-to hym songe alle
with a swete steuene <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Veni creator spiritus</FOREIGN>.  And also sone &thorn;e holy goste come
at &thorn;aire desyrynge, and &thorn;am comforthede with his grace, and chasede owte &thorn;e
fowle wyghtes, &thorn;ose lothely fendis doghetirs, and clenesede &thorn;e abbaye of all &thorn;e


<PB N="1: 337">

fylthe, and ordayned it and restorede better &thorn;ane it was by-fore. / Now I pray
&yogh;ow all in charite of god, &thorn;at all &thorn;a &thorn;at of this relegione redis or heris, &thorn;at &thorn;ay
be bouxome with all &thorn;aire myghte, and suffire &thorn;at &thorn;e gud ladys be-fore namede
do &thorn;aire offece ilke daye gastely with-In &thorn;aire hertes; and luke ylkone wysely
&thorn;at he ne do no trispase agayne &thorn;e rewle ne &thorn;e obedyence of &thorn;is relegione and
of &thorn;ase [suferaynes].  And if thorow vnhape falle &thorn;at any of thiese foure fendis
doghetirs seke one any wyse any Ingate for to hafe with-in &yogh;oure hertis for to
duelle, or Ingate hase wonne and with &yogh;ow duellis, [dose] after &thorn;e concelle of
&thorn;e lady Discrescione and gyffe &yogh;ow to deuocione with hertly prayers, in hope of
goddes helpe and of his socoure, and &yogh;e sall be delyuerde thurgh &thorn;e mercy of
oure lord Ihesu Criste there, blyssede mot he be with-owttene ende.  Amen.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit Relegio sancti Spiritus Amen.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="text"> <HEAD>The Charter of the Abbey of the Holy Ghost</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ms. Laud misc. 210</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="136" UNIT="folio">
<DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P>HEre is &thorn;e book &thorn;at speki&thorn; on a place &thorn;at is I-clepid &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy
gost &thorn;e whiche schulde be foundid in clene conscience; in whiche abbeye, as &thorn;e
book telli&thorn;, schulde dwellen xxix gostly ladyes, among whiche Charite is &thorn;e
abbesse, Wisdome priouresse, Mekenes suppriouresse; &thorn;er is also Pouerte &amp; Clennesse, Temperaunce &amp; Soburnesse, Penaunce &amp; Buxumnesse, Schrifte &amp;  Ri&yogh;t-


<PB N="1: 338">

wysnesse, Predicacion &amp; Stabulnesse, Sufferaunce &amp; Symplenesse, Misericord &amp; Largenesse, Resoun &amp; Reufulnesse, Meditacion &amp; Orisoun, Deuocion &amp; Contemplacion, Leaunce &amp; Iubilacion, Honeste &amp; Curtesye, Drede &amp; Ielusye.  &THORN;e fader of heuene is founder of &thorn;is abbeye, &amp; &thorn;e holy gost is wardeyn &amp; visitour, as &thorn;e booke telli&thorn;.  But na&thorn;er&thorn;eles &thorn;ou&yogh; it be so &thorn;at an abbeye haue neuere so good [a] founder or a visitoure, but &yogh;if he haue also goode dedis &amp; charteres of here places where-&thorn;orou &thorn;ei mowe kepen here londis, rentys &amp; fraunchises,
oftesi&thorn;es per auenture &thorn;ei schulden ben mysserued &amp; suffren mochel persecucion of
here enemyes &amp; of false men.  &amp; &thorn;at se y wel &thorn;at &thorn;is holy abbesse &amp; here
couent han many false enemyes &thorn;e whiche wolden distroye here abbeye &amp; byreue
hem of her possessiouns, &amp; &thorn;at were me ful lo&thorn;.  &amp; &thorn;erfore y make here a book
&thorn;at schal be clepid &laquo;&thorn;e Chartre of &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost&raquo;, In whiche I schal tellen first whan &amp; where &amp; of whom &thorn;is abbeye was first I-foundid, si&thorn;en I schal tellen hou &amp; in what tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e holy abbeye was destroyed &amp; hou &thorn;e abbesse &amp; [&thorn;e] prioresse &amp; alle here couent were dryuen ou&yogh;t of her ordre, &amp; afterward I schal tellen hou &amp; in what manere &thorn;e abbeye was made newe a&yogh;en &amp; hou &thorn;e abbesse &amp; al here couent kemen a&yogh;en to here ordre, &amp; al&thorn;er-last I schal tellen hou almi&yogh;tty god ha&thorn; put his owen foure dou&yogh;tren in &thorn;is holy abbeye a&yogh;ens &thorn;oo foure foule feendis dou&yogh;tren &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e holy gost kacchid a-wey for &thorn;ei weren so foule, as &thorn;e book of &thorn;is abbeye telli&thorn; at &thorn;e laste ende.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<OPENER>Here begynni&thorn; &thorn;e forseyd chartre.</OPENER>

<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sciant presentes &amp; futuri &amp;c.</FOREIGN>: Weti&thorn; &yogh;e &thorn;at ben now here, &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;at schulen
comen after &yogh;ou, &thorn;at almi&yogh;ti god in trinite, fader &amp; sone &amp; holy gost, ha&thorn; &yogh;ouen &amp; graunted &amp; wi&thorn; his owne word confermed, to Adam, &thorn;e first man &thorn;at euere


<PB N="1: 339">

was, &amp; to Eue his wyf, &amp; to here heyres, a lytel preciouse place &thorn;at is clepid
Conscience, &thorn;at lii&thorn; in here soules by-twixen a place &thorn;at is clepid Resoun, &thorn;e
whiche knowe&thorn; good &amp; wykke, on &thorn;at o sydde, and a place &thorn;at is I-clepid
Synderisys, &thorn;e whiche steri&thorn; a man to good &amp; grucchi&thorn; a&yogh;ens wykke, on &thorn;at
o&thorn;ere sydde; whos on ende is fastened be &thorn;e grace of god, &thorn;orou whiche euerey
man may don&macr; wel &yogh;if he wylle; &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;er ende li&thorn; in ioye &amp; mer&thorn;e of &thorn;e soule, [&yogh;if] hit be clene out of &thorn;e fil&thorn;e of synne. / &THORN;is holy place almi&yogh;ty god &yogh;af hit to Adam forseyde &amp; [to] his wyf &amp; to here eyres, clenelich a-di&yogh;t wi&thorn;-outen any synne; in &thorn;e whiche he hym-self made a noble hous of religioun, &thorn;at is
clepid &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, in &thorn;e whyche he put manye gostly ladyes,
&thorn;at is to seye gode vertues, amonge whiche he made damysel Loue &amp; Charite
abbesse, &amp; dame Wyt &amp; Wysdome priouresse, &amp; dame Mekenesse &amp; Lownesse supprioresse; &amp; walled &thorn;e abbeye so wel abouten, so wel wi&thorn; swyche myght &amp; swyche streng&thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne schulde neuere no wycked &thorn;yng no wycked &thorn;ou&yogh;t haue mi&yogh;t to an entrid amonge &thorn;at holy couent, &yogh;if &thorn;e forseyd Adam &amp; Eue his wyf hadden hem-self wold.  He &yogh;af hem also &thorn;e lordschip of heuene &amp; of er&thorn;e &amp; of al &thorn;e worlde, to mayntene wi&thorn; &thorn;e noble ladyes in here holy couent, so
ferfor&thorn;e &thorn;at alle &thorn;e fysches in &thorn;e see, &amp; alle &thorn;e briddes in &thorn;e eirye, &amp; alle &thorn;e bestes of &thorn;e londe schulde han ben buxum to hem &amp; to alle here eyres
eueremore, &yogh;if Adam &amp; his wyf hadde kept hem out of synne to here ende.
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">[Habendum et tenendum]</FOREIGN>: To hauen &amp; to holden &thorn;is preciouse place wi&thorn; &thorn;e noble abbeye
&amp; al &thorn;e holy couent, to &thorn;e forseyde Adam &amp; to Eue &amp; to alle here eyres,
frelyche &amp; pesybelyche wi&thorn;-outen grucchyng of any man euere-more, &amp; &thorn;er-wi&thorn;-al ioye &amp; blisse &thorn;at neuere schulde han had ende: for &thorn;e seruyse &amp; &thorn;e customes


<PB N="1: 340">

&thorn;at longen &thorn;er[-of] to &thorn;e chef lord of &thorn;e fee, and &thorn;at was no more but a
wi&thorn;stondyng &thorn;e temptacion of &thorn;e fende &amp; of his wif, whyche ne leste nou&yogh;t bo[t]e fully &thorn;e spase of a myle weye.  And almi&yogh;ty god schulde han waraunted to Adam
&amp; to Eue his wyf &amp; to here eyres &thorn;at preciouse place wi&thorn; &thorn;e noble abbeye &amp; al &thorn;e holy couent, for to haue dwelled euere-more in more Ioye &amp; blysse &thorn;an
any tunge may telle; &amp; also no&thorn;er he ne none of her eyrys schulde neuere haue
suffred woo ne peyne, no &thorn;ei schuld neuere haue dy&yogh;ed: but whan almi&yogh;ty god
hadde seye best tyme he schulde han taken hem vp wi&thorn; body &amp; soule in to &thorn;e
blys of heuene, &thorn;er to han lyued wi&thorn;-outen ende: &yogh;if sely Adam &amp; hys wyf hadde
kept hem wi&thorn;-outen synne o day to &thorn;e ende&mdash;alas, why ne hadde &thorn;ei do so?
<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hijs testibus:</FOREIGN> Of &thorn;is bere&thorn; witnesse aungel &amp; man, heuene &amp; er&thorn;e, sone &amp; mone
&amp; al &thorn;e sterris, &amp; euerey creature &thorn;at euere was maade for man.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Data apud paradisum &amp;c.</FOREIGN>: &thorn;e date was &yogh;ouen at paradyse, on &thorn;e first day &thorn;at euere man
was made, In &thorn;e &yogh;eer of &thorn;e reigne of al-mi&yogh;ti god kynge of alle kynges, whos
kyngdom neuere by-gan ne neuer schal haue ende.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit carta. Memorandum quod primo die incarnacionis hominis &amp;c.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<P>&yogh;e schullen vndurstonden &thorn;at &thorn;er was a fals tyrant apostata &thorn;at hy&yogh;te Satanas,
&thorn;e whiche was summe-tyme prioure of &thorn;e aungels ordre in &thorn;e blisse of heuene;
&thorn;e whiche for his pride ran out of his blysful ordre in to &thorn;e sorowful errowre
of &thorn;e peyne of helle.  And &thorn;o he hadde gret envie wi&thorn; &thorn;e abbesse of &thorn;e
abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; wi&thorn; alle here couent, &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren so wel wi&thorn;
god &amp; hadden so gret lordschipe: he be-&thorn;ou&yogh;t hym of a caast of gyle hou he
mi&yogh;t distroye &thorn;e noble abbeye &amp; hou he my&yogh;t do &thorn;e religiouse abbesse wi&thorn; al
here fayre couent remeuen out of here ordre, as he dide out of his.  He cam
in &thorn;e lickenesse of an addre to &thorn;e abbeye &yogh;aatys &amp; wolde haue comen


<PB N="1: 341">

inne.  &amp; &thorn;e porter &thorn;at men clepen Drede as &thorn;at o&thorn;ere book sei&thorn;, was not
&thorn;er redy&mdash;for &yogh;if he hadde ben &thorn;er redy he schulde not haue comen yn, as
god &yogh;if &thorn;at he hadde; and &thorn;at sei&yogh;y Eue &thorn;at he was &thorn;ere, &amp; as a greet
fool leet hym inne.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde &thorn;at false schrewe to Eue: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cur precepit vobis deus,</FOREIGN> why, he seyde, for-bad god &thorn;at &yogh;e schulden not eten of &thorn;e apples &thorn;at
growen on &thorn;e tree &thorn;at stant amyddys paradys?&raquo;  &amp; &thorn;an seyde sche: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ne forte moriamur,</FOREIGN> last, &yogh;if we eten &thorn;erof, we schulden dy&yogh;en&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;an seyde he:
&laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nequaquam moriemini sed eritis sicut dii &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> nay, nay, he sei&thorn;, &yogh;e schul not dy&yogh;en, god almi&yogh;ty wot wel &thorn;at what tyme &thorn;at &yogh;e eten &thorn;erof &yogh;e schul ben as goddis bo&thorn;e knowand good &amp; wicked; but god wolde not &thorn;at &yogh;e weren as wyse as he, &amp; &thorn;erfore he forbed &thorn;at &yogh;e schulden not eten of &thorn;e apples&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;at seiy Eue &thorn;at sche schulde be so wyse, &amp; was bo&thorn;e coueytous &amp; lykerouse as comenliche wymmen ben; sche sei&yogh;e &thorn;e apples were fayre to here si&yogh;t &amp; delicious to &thorn;e mo[u]&thorn;e: scho wente to &thorn;e tree &amp; took awey an appul &amp; eete &thorn;erof, &amp; &yogh;af Adam &thorn;e o&thorn;ere deel, &amp; he eete &thorn;erof also.  In &thorn;e mene tyme &thorn;at Adam &amp; his wif eten
of &thorn;is applen, &thorn;at foule fals tiraunt wi&thorn; his foure turmentours, &thorn;at is to seye
Pride &amp; Glotonye, Coueytise &amp; Folye, wenten in to &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; beren a-wey al &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;er was.  Sykerly I dar wel seye &thorn;ei beren a-wey
mo precious iewelys &thorn;an al &thorn;is world is wor&thorn;e; &thorn;ei baren also away &thorn;e chartre
&thorn;at god almi&yogh;ty &yogh;af hem to holde bi here place,&mdash;&amp; &thorn;erfore nei&thorn;er he ne his wyf ne noon of here eyres fro &thorn;at day in to &thorn;is day hadde no ri&yogh;t to chalenge &thorn;e
lordschip of &thorn;is world ne &thorn;e blisse of heuene, but onlyche in &thorn;e mersy of god.


<PB N="1: 342">

&amp; not only &thorn;oyse false &thorn;eues broken &thorn;us &thorn;is holy abbeye &amp; beren away here
goodys, but &thorn;ei deden a more cruel dede &amp; a more reuful: &thorn;ei drouen awey
dispitousliche out of &thorn;at abbeye &thorn;e faire abbesse &amp; &thorn;e priouresse &amp; al here holy couent, so ferfor&thorn; &thorn;at it was fyue &thorn;ousande fyue hundrid &amp; &thorn;re &amp; &thorn;ritty &yogh;er after &thorn;at or euere &thorn;ei mi&yogh;ten comen a&yogh;en alle to-geders as parfi&yogh;tliche as &thorn;ei weren beforn. / And whan Adam &amp; his wyf hadden eten of &thorn;at apple, he loked on here &amp; scho on hym, &amp; &thorn;anne perceyued &thorn;ei first &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren bo&thorn;e robbed &amp; naked.  Hem &thorn;ou&yogh;te greet schame of hem-seluen &thorn;at &thorn;ei ferden so, &amp; wenten &amp; tokene leeues of a fige-tre to hyden wi&thorn; here priueyteys, for &thorn;ei ne hadden noon o&thorn;ere clo&thorn;es&mdash;for &thorn;at tyme were no furred gounnes ne pricked paltokys! &THORN;ei deden hem to &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, &thorn;at is to seye here conscience, &amp; wolde han had summe helpe &thorn;er: &amp; &thorn;ei seen al &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;er was [ago],
&amp; hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t grete schame; for &thorn;ei mi&yogh;t aforhande han faren &thorn;ere wele merye. &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;ei wenten for&thorn; to on &thorn;at wonede &thorn;ere-by-syde, to on &thorn;at men clepyd Wit, &amp; axed hym where &thorn;e prioures &amp; &thorn;e abbesse were, where &thorn;ei ben be-comen. &amp; &thorn;an seyde Wit: &laquo;&thorn;e abbeye is distroyed dispitousliche, &amp; al &thorn;e couent is runnen aweye sorufully, for &thorn;i folye and for &thorn;i wyues&raquo;.  &laquo;Hou so?&raquo;  seyde &thorn;ei.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde Wit: &laquo;Whil &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;i wyf eten of &thorn;e appul &thorn;e abbeye was distroyed wi&thorn; foure false &thorn;eues, &amp; &thorn;e abbesse &amp; &thorn;e priouresse &amp; al &thorn;e couent breke here ordre &amp; runne aweye, and seyden as &thorn;ei wenten &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulden no more comen a&yogh;en to-gedere as &thorn;ei weren first, &thorn;is fyue &thorn;ousande &yogh;ere &amp; more, &amp; al was for &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;i wyf eten of &thorn;at appul&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;an Adam &amp; his wyf hadden moche


<PB N="1: 343">

sorowe as no woundur was, &amp; seyden iche to o&thorn;ere: &laquo;Alas, alas, what schul we
don&macr;?  we ne han now&thorn;er clo&thorn;es to don&macr; on, ne hous for to dwellen inne, &amp; &thorn;erto &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here faire couent &thorn;at weren oure beest frendis han forsakene
vs &amp; ben goon aweye; so weylewey &thorn;e while &thorn;at euere we eten &thorn;e appel!&raquo;  &amp; asswy&thorn;e aftyrward &thorn;ei harden god hou he spak to hem as he wente in paradyse;
&amp; &thorn;ei weren aschamed of hem-seluen &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren naked, &amp; also &thorn;ei weren
agast of hym, &amp; stirten vndre a tree for to han hid hem.  &amp; god com &amp; sy&yogh;e
hem &amp; seyde: &laquo;O Adam, Adam, where art &thorn;ou?&raquo;  &laquo;A, lord, quo&thorn; Adam, I harde &thorn;i woyse in paradyse, &amp; I was a-schamed &thorn;at I was naked, &amp; &thorn;erfore I hidde me&raquo;.  &laquo;O Adam, quo&thorn; oure lord, ho told [&thorn;e] &thorn;at &thorn;ou were naked, any &thorn;ing ellys but &thorn;at &thorn;ou ete of &thorn;e appul a&yogh;en my for-beddyng?  Ho ha&thorn; broken &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy goost, Adam, &amp; who ha&thorn; boren aweye al &thorn;at &thorn;er was?  where is &thorn;e fair abbesse, Adam, &amp; here couent &thorn;at I took &thorn;ee to kepen&mdash;wheder ben &thorn;ei went?&raquo;  &laquo;A, lord, quo&thorn; Adam, &thorn;e woman &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;eue me to my wyf let in a fals schrewe at &thorn;e abbeye &yogh;atys, &thorn;at bad here eten of an appul &thorn;at hange on a tre in paradyse, &amp; he seyde scho schulde wexen as wyse as god; &amp; sche took hit doon &amp; ete &thorn;erof, &amp; &yogh;af me &thorn;at o&thorn;ere deel; &amp; y wolde not displesen here &amp; ete &thorn;erof also.  &amp; in &thorn;at mene wile &thorn;at fals &thorn;ef wi&thorn; o&thorn;er maner schrewes of his assent wenten in to &thorn;e abbeye &amp; broken [hit] adoun &amp; beren away al &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;er was, &amp; dryuen away &thorn;e abbesse &amp; &thorn;e priouresse &amp; al &thorn;e couent I wot neuere whedur&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;e whyle he told god &thorn;is tale he wepte for sorowe.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde god to Eue: &laquo;Woman, why let &thorn;ou inne &thorn;at fals &thorn;ef?  &amp; whi ete &thorn;ou of &thorn;at appul?&raquo;  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde scho: &laquo;A, lord, he cam to me in &thorn;e lickenesse of an eddre &amp; bygylid me wi&thorn; faire false wordes, &amp; I let hym inne &amp; dede as he me bad, alas, alas &thorn;e while &thorn;at euere knewe I hym&raquo;!  &amp; scho wepte for sorowe also,


<PB N="1: 344">

as I blame here not.  &THORN;an seyde god to here: &laquo;For &thorn;ou lete Inne &thorn;at schrewe &amp; dedest as he &thorn;e bad, &amp; ete of &thorn;at appul, &thorn;ou schalt bere &thorn;i childeren wi&thorn; mochel
gronyng &amp; kare, &thorn;ou &amp; alle &thorn;e wymmen &thorn;at schul come after &thorn;e, saue on; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou haddest not so don&macr;, wymmen schulden neuere han hadde no manere of
peyne in berynge of child.  &THORN;ou schalt euere-more also, he seyde, ben vndur
mannus heste, &amp; he schal be &thorn;i mayster&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne scho hadde mochel sorowe. &amp; &thorn;an seyde god to Adam: &laquo;For &thorn;ou ete of &thorn;e appul at &thorn;i wyfes byddyng a&yogh;ens myn heste, &amp; for &thorn;ou lete &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost so fouliche ben distroyed &amp; lete &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here couent rennen aweye out of here ordre &amp; &thorn;ou ne woost neuere whider, &thorn;is schal be &thorn;i penaunce: &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;is day or euen ben
dryuen out of paradyse in to er&thorn;e, &thorn;at is a-cursid for &thorn;i synne; &thorn;er-inne schalt
&thorn;ou dwellen wi&thorn; mochel sorowe &amp; mochel woo alle &thorn;e dayes of &thorn;i lyf, &amp; er&thorn;e schal bringe &thorn;e for&thorn; &thorn;ornes &amp; brambles, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt eten gresse &thorn;at growe&thorn; on &thorn;e er&thorn;e.  In swynke &amp; in swete of &thorn;i visage &thorn;ou schalt eten &thorn;i bred, til &thorn;ou turnest a&yogh;en to &thorn;e er&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou com fro; for whi, &thorn;ou were mad but of er&thorn;e &amp; in to er&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt turne a&yogh;en&raquo;.  &amp; as-swi&thorn;e afturward god bad a aungel dryue Adam &amp; his wyf out of &thorn;e blisse of paradyse in to &thorn;e wrechid world, &amp; bad hem goon &amp; sechen &thorn;ere &thorn;e abbesse of &thorn;e holy gost, &amp; seyde ne&thorn;er he nor his wyf ne noon of here ospryng schulde neuere comen a&yogh;en in to &thorn;e blysse of paradyse ne in to heuene neuer, til &thorn;ei han mad a&yogh;en &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost as wel as it was beforn, &amp; til &thorn;ei hadden also brou&yogh;t a&yogh;en wi&thorn; hem &thorn;e abbesse &amp; [&thorn;e] priouresse &amp; al here fayre couent in as good pli&yogh;t as hit was be-forn&macr; or &thorn;ei wenten out.  &amp; &thorn;anne went god &amp; mad Adam &amp; hys wyf ey&thorn;er a cote of le&thorn;er, &amp; cast hem out of paradyse, &amp; &thorn;at was a pytouse si&yogh;t forso&thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;at is so&thorn;e.  &amp;


<PB N="1: 345">

&thorn;us kemen &thorn;ei for&thorn; in to &thorn;is wrecchid world, wi&thorn; mochel sorowe &amp; kare, &amp; &thorn;erof was no woundur.  &amp; &thorn;enne wente Adam in &thorn;is world in mochel sorowe
&amp; woo IX hondred &amp; XXX [&yogh;er] &amp; sou&yogh;te &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here couent &thorn;at weren so goon awaye, &amp; he wolde also han had sumwhat where-wi&thorn; he mi&yogh;te haue a&yogh;en &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost; and he mi&yogh;t neuere fynde nou&yogh;t &thorn;erof in al &thorn;at long tyme.  &amp; Adam hadde mochel sorowe, &amp; fel seke &amp; died, &amp; his wyf bo&thorn;e; &amp; here soules wenten to helle, &amp; &thorn;at was grete pyte.  &amp; not oneliche &thorn;ei alone, but al &thorn;o &thorn;at comen of hem, &thorn;e whyche kemen aftur &thorn;at be foure &thorn;ousande sex hundred &amp; foure &yogh;er, wenten to helle euerychone&mdash;so longe was Adam in helle, &amp; &thorn;at was for &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, &thorn;at is to seyn here conscience, was not mad a&yogh;en as fayre ne as clene as it was be-forn&macr;.  &THORN;us was Adam &amp; his wyf in helle many &thorn;ousande &yogh;eer in mochel sorowe &amp; kare: til alle-mi&yogh;ty god hadde pyte of her soules &amp; sente adoun his swete sone &amp; bad hym goon &amp; sechen &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here couent&mdash;for he wiste bettere where &thorn;ei weren &thorn;an Adam wyste.
&amp; he cam doun in to &thorn;is world and sou&yogh;te hem here wel bisyly &thorn;re &amp; &thorn;ritty &yogh;eer, &amp; at &thorn;e last he fond hem hangyng on &thorn;e rode-tree.  He took hem doon&macr; &amp; lad hem in to helle, to speken wi&thorn; Adam &amp; his wyf.  &amp; whan Adam sau&yogh; hym comen, lord &thorn;at he was glade!  &amp; &thorn;er Crist goddis sone of heuene mayd a&yogh;en &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, betere &thorn;an euere hit was, &amp; took out of helle Adam &amp; his wyf, &thorn;e abbesse &amp; &thorn;e priouresse &amp; al here holy couent, &amp; ladde hem wi&thorn; hym a&yogh;en hom in to paradise, &amp; &thorn;er was mochel ioye &amp; blisse at here comyng-hom.&mdash;But hou &amp; in what manere Crist fonde &thorn;is abbesse &amp; her couent, I schal tellen &yogh;ow as-swi&thorn;e &yogh;if &yogh;ee wolen abydde, &amp; hou &thorn;e abbesse of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; alle her couent were foundon&macr; &amp; brou&yogh;t hom a&yogh;en al hole.
</P>
<P>Aftur &thorn;at Adam &amp; his wyf weren dede, &thorn;er comen many wyse men,
patriarches &amp; prophetes &amp; o&thorn;ere men bo&thorn;e, &thorn;at hadden mochel sorowe for &thorn;e abbeye


<PB N="1: 346">

of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; for al &thorn;e couent &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren so goon&macr; awaye: &amp; &thorn;ei wenten &amp; sou&yogh;ten after hem in many soundry cuntrees as longe as &thorn;ei lyueden: but vndre hem alle, for nou&yogh;t &thorn;ei couden don&macr;, mi&yogh;t &thorn;ei neuere fynde hem.  &amp; &thorn;er were amonges o&thorn;ere, foure gode men &amp; trewe, &thorn;at is to weten Dauid &amp; Salomon, Ysaie &amp; Ieromye, &thorn;at weren abou&yogh;te day &amp; ni&yogh;t to maken &thorn;is abbeye &amp; to sechen vp &thorn;is couent; &amp; for &thorn;ei mi&yogh;ten not han here wille, somme of hem maden mochel sorowe &amp; mone, &amp; I pray &yogh;ou listeni&thorn; what &thorn;ei seyden.  Dauid seyde: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Laboraui clamans, rauce facte [sunt] fauces mee &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> I haue, he seyde, so runne &amp; cried aftir hem, &thorn;at my chaules aken &amp; ben woxen al hose&raquo;; &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Domine inclina celos tuos &amp; descende &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> &amp; &thorn;erfore, lord, he sei&thorn;, bowe doun &thorn;in heuennes &amp; come doon&macr;, &amp; help me for to sechen &thorn;is abbesse &amp; here couent &thorn;e whyche myn herte loue&thorn;;
for I may not fynde hem&raquo;.  Sei&thorn; Salomon: &laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Circuibo ciuitatem per vicos &amp; plateas &amp; queram quem diligit anima mea,</FOREIGN> I schal, he sei&thorn;, risen vp &amp; wenden al abou&yogh;ten &thorn;e citee be weyes &amp; be stretys &amp; I schal sechen &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here couent &thorn;e
whyche myn herte loue&thorn;&raquo;.  &laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quesiui &amp; non inueni &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> a, he sei&thorn;, I sou&yogh;te hem &amp; I ne founde hem nou&yogh;t; I cryed &amp; noon of hem wolde here, non answere me wi&thorn; word&raquo;.  &THORN;anne spake [he] mornan[d]liche &amp; seyde: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Reuertere, reuertere sunamitis, reuertere, reuertere &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> a, torne a&yogh;en, turne a&yogh;en &thorn;ou sely swete wyi&yogh;t, &amp; let vs
see &thorn;e&raquo;; &laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Wulnerasti cor meum soror mea sponsa mea, wulnerasti cor meum in
vno ictu oculorum tuorum &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> a, &thorn;ou hast woundid myn hert &thorn;ou fayre sistur, &thorn;ou fayre spouse, &thorn;ou hast woundid myn herte wi&thorn; a twynkelyng of &thorn;in ei&yogh;e&raquo;.
&amp; he seyde ouer &thorn;at: &laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">In lectulo meo quesiui per noctes quem diligit anima mea; quesiui &amp; non inueni &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> I haue sou&yogh;t any&yogh;ttis in my bed &thorn;at couent whyche my soule loue&thorn;; I haue sou&yogh;t wi&thorn; al my my&yogh;t &amp; I may not fynden hem&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;an spak he
to &thorn;e o&thorn;ere maydens &thorn;at dwelleden &thorn;er-bysyde, &amp; seyde: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Adiuro vos filie Ierusalem,

<PB N="1: 347">

si inueneritis dilectum meum (i. conuentum illum), an[n]uncietis [ei] quia amore langueo
&amp;c.,</FOREIGN> I pray &yogh;ou specialiche &yogh;e maydens of Ierusalem, &yogh;if &yogh;e fynden owhere &thorn;e
abbesse of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; here couent, &thorn;at &yogh;e wil sayn &thorn;at I am seke for
loue-longyng of hem&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;us Salomon &thorn;e kyng mad mochel mone.  But &yogh;it fonde he hem no&yogh;t, &amp; &thorn;anne seyde he &thorn;us: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Mitte domine sapienciam tuam, i. filium, de celis sanctis tuis, qui mecum sit &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> lord god, he sei&thorn;, sende doun out of &thorn;i holy heuenes &thorn;i owne dere sone, &thorn;at he mi&yogh;t be wi&thorn; me &amp; helpe me for to maken a&yogh;en &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost in as good plit as it was &amp; schulde ben&raquo;.  But for al &thorn;at he coude crien, goddis sone ne cam nou&yogh;t &yogh;it.  &amp; &thorn;an wente Isaye &thorn;e prophete &amp; sou&yogh;te &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here couent many dayes &amp; fele, &amp; he fonde hem nou&yogh;t; &amp; &thorn;anne he seyde &thorn;us: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vtinam dirumperes celos &amp; descenderes,</FOREIGN> wolde god, he seyd, &thorn;ou woldest bresten heuene &amp; come adoon, &amp; helpen vs for to maken a&yogh;en &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; fynden vp &thorn;e couent &thorn;at is &thorn;us goon aweye&raquo;. &amp; &thorn;anne wente Ieromye &thorn;e prophete &amp; sou&yogh;te hem also; &amp; for he mi&yogh;te not fynde hem, he made a reuful mone &amp; seyde &thorn;us: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ve michi misero, quoniam addidit dominus dolorem dolori meo; laboraui in gemitu meo,</FOREIGN> wo me wrecche, he sei&thorn;, &thorn;at god ha&thorn; eked more sorowe to my sorowe; I haue trauayled wi&thorn;-outen reste in sikynge &amp; in kare &amp; I ne may not fynden &thorn;at I seke&raquo;.  &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Virgines deiecit in terram, pol[l]u[it] regnum: virgines abierunt in captiuitatem; audierunt quia ingemesco ego &amp; non est qui consoletur me, idcirco ego plorans,</FOREIGN> alas, he seyde, &thorn;e feende ha&thorn; drowen a-way &thorn;e virgines &amp; made foule here kyngdome, &thorn;e virgines
ben went away in to &thorn;e wrecchid world.  &THORN;ei harden me wel hou I sikede &amp; made mochel mone, &amp; &thorn;er was noon of hem &thorn;at wolde counforte me wi&thorn; a word;
&amp; &thorn;erfore I haue so wept for sorowe &thorn;at myn eyen ben in poynt to faylen me&raquo;.
&laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quis dabit capiti meo aquam &amp; oculis meis fontem lacrimarum, &amp; plorabo [die]
ac nocte] interfeccionem filic populi mei,</FOREIGN> a, he sei&thorn;, who schal &yogh;euen me water


<PB N="1: 348">

to myn heued, &amp; who schal &yogh;euen a welle of terris to myn eyen, &amp; I schal
wepen for &thorn;e maydens &thorn;at ben &thorn;us goon&macr; away, bo&thorn;e day &amp; ni&yogh;t&raquo;.  &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cui comparabo te, cui assimulabo te filia Ierusalem? cui [exequabo te, &amp; consolabor] te,
[virgo] filia Syon? magna velud [mare est contritio tua; quis medebitur tui?],</FOREIGN>
a, &thorn;ou noble abbesse, he sei&thorn;, to whom may I licken &thorn;e, to whom may I assemble
&thorn;e &thorn;ou dou&yogh;ter of Ierusalem? a, &thorn;ou noble priouresse, to whom may I euen &thorn;e
&thorn;ou mayden &amp; dou&yogh;ter of Syon? a, &thorn;ou holy couent, he sei&thorn;, hou may I counforte
&thorn;e? me &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;i sorowe is as grete as a see: a, &thorn;ou sely couent, who shal
ben &thorn;i helpe?&raquo;  &laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Cecidit corona capitis nostri, ve nobis quia peccauimus,</FOREIGN> I ne can nou&yogh;t ellis seyn, he sei&thorn;, but, &thorn;e fairest flour of al oure garlond is fallen away; alas, alas &amp; weloway, &thorn;at euere we dede synne&raquo;.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Hou god ordened a waye to sauen man.</HEAD>

<P>&amp; whan almi&yogh;ty god had hard &thorn;us &thorn;es prophetis, wi&thorn; many o&thorn;ere men, ma[k]e
mochel mone wi&thorn; reuly chere many &thorn;ousand &yogh;eer for &thorn;e destruccion of &thorn;e abbeye
of &thorn;e holy gost: he had grete pyte of hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei ferden so, &amp; &thorn;at mannus
soule was &thorn;erfore in prisone of &thorn;e pyne of helle, &amp; schulde haue ben &thorn;er
wi&thorn;outen ende.  He be-&thorn;ou&yogh;t hym hou he mi&yogh;t best don&macr; to delyueren mannus soule
out of &thorn;at sory prisoun, &amp; hou he mi&yogh;t fynde vp &thorn;e abbesse of &thorn;e abbeye of
&thorn;e holy gost &amp; maken a&yogh;en here couent faire &amp; wel as it was be-forn&macr;.  He
ordeyned a counseil of &thorn;e holy trinite in &thorn;e blisse of heuene, of &thorn;e fadur &amp; of
&thorn;e sone &amp; of &thorn;e holy gost, &amp; seyde: &laquo;&yogh;e weten wel, he seyde, we maden mannus soule to oure lickenesse, &amp; token hym for to kepen in his owne conscience &thorn;e
abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, &amp; he for his folye let beren out of &thorn;e abbeye al &thorn;e
good &thorn;at &thorn;er was, &amp; let &thorn;e abbesse &amp; here couent rennen away out of her
ordre, &amp; &thorn;erfore he was taken &amp; put in to prisoun of &thorn;e pyt of helle.  &amp; &thorn;ere ha&thorn; he been now foure &thorn;ousand &yogh;er sexe hundred &amp; more, &amp; &thorn;at is grete pitee;


<PB N="1: 349">

me &thorn;enki&thorn; hit were a good dede to don&macr; &thorn;e abbesse &amp; al here couent comen
a&yogh;en to here ordre, &amp; maken a&yogh;en &thorn;e abbeye as wel as euere hit was, &amp; delyuere mannus soule out of &thorn;at sory prisone; he ha&thorn; ben in &thorn;at prisoun longe I-now,
haue we pitee on hym, he is as hit were on of vs, maked to oure lickenesse&raquo;.
&amp; alle &thorn;e holy trinite graunted &thorn;at it schulde so be.  But, he seyde, who &thorn;at
shulde don&macr; swyche a dede, hym be-houed for to be swyche on &thorn;at were
be-holden for to don&macr; hit, &amp; also &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te don&macr; it; but, &thorn;er was no &thorn;ing &thorn;at was by-holden to delyueren mannus soule but onliche man, no &thorn;er was no &thorn;ing
&thorn;at mi&yogh;te delyuere hym but &yogh;if it were god; &amp; &thorn;erfore who so schulde do &thorn;at
dede he most be bo&thorn;e god &amp; man: &amp; so mi&yogh;t it noon be but &yogh;if it were oon of
&thorn;e &thorn;re persones in &thorn;e holy trinite; almi&yogh;ty goddis sone schulde come doun in to
&thorn;is world, &amp; ben I-born of a mayden &amp; becomen man, &amp; maken a&yogh;en &thorn;at abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, &amp; dien for &thorn;e loue of man on &thorn;e harde rode-tree, &amp; so
delyuere mannus soule out of &thorn;e peyne of helle.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Here now hou goddys dou&yogh;tren pleteden for mannus soule aforn&macr; here fadur.</HEAD>

<P>And &thorn;anne were al-mi&yogh;ty goddis dou&yogh;tren &thorn;ere, &thorn;at is to seye Mercy &amp; Treu&thorn;e, Ri&yogh;tfulnesse &amp; Pees, &thorn;e whiche harden seyen &thorn;at mannus soule schulde be delyuered out of helle-pyne, &amp; &thorn;ei comen alle to-gedir aforn god al-mi&yogh;ty.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde Tru&thorn;e &thorn;us: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ecce enim veritatem dilexisti,</FOREIGN> A, lord, scho seyde, &thorn;ou hast &yogh;it eueremore loued wele me &thorn;at am &thorn;i dou&yogh;tre, and &thorn;anne, seyde Tru&thorn;e, I pray &thorn;e for-sake nou&yogh;t me.  &thorn;ou seydest &thorn;at what-tyme &thorn;at man ete of &thorn;at appul, &thorn;at he schulde dieye &amp; gon&macr; to helle; &thorn;erfore &yogh;if &thorn;ou delyuerest man &thorn;anne out of &thorn;at prisoun, &thorn;ou destroyest me, &amp; &thorn;at were no skil, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia veritas domini manet in eternum,</FOREIGN> for whi goddys treu&thorn;e schulde dwellen euere-more wi&thorn;-outen ende.


<PB N="1: 350">

&THORN;erfore, leue lord, scho seyde, lat man be stille in helle, &amp; forsake nou&yogh;t me&raquo;. &amp; &thorn;anne seyde Mercy: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">O pater misericordiarum &amp; deus tocius consolacionis, qui consolaris nos in omni tribulacione nostra,</FOREIGN> A, &thorn;ou fader of mercy, scho seyde, &amp; god of al confort, &thorn;ou &thorn;at confortes alle &thorn;ing in anger &amp; in woo, haue mercy of mannus soule &thorn;at li&thorn; bounden in prisoun &thorn;at is helle, &amp; brynge h[i]m in to blisse.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quoniam dixisti, in eternum seruabo illi misericordiam,</FOREIGN> for why, scho seyde, &thorn;ou seydest &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldest kepe to hym &thorn;i mercy wi&thorn;-outen ende.  &amp; &thorn;erfore, &yogh;if &thorn;ou be trewe, &thorn;ou schalt haue mercy of mannus soule&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde Ri&yogh;tfulnesse: &laquo;Nay, nay, scho sei&thorn;, it may not ben so: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia iustus dominus &amp; iusticias dilexit,</FOREIGN> for whi, lord, scho sei&thorn;, &thorn;ou art ri&yogh;tful &amp; &thorn;ou louest ri&yogh;tfulnesse; &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou ne mayst not ri&yogh;tfulliche sauen mannus soule, it is ri&yogh;t &amp; skil &thorn;at it haue as it ha&thorn; disserued.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Dominum qui se genuit dereliquit, &amp; oblitus est dei creatoris sui,</FOREIGN> he forsoke god &thorn;at ha&thorn; for&thorn;e-Ibrou&yogh;t hym, &amp; he, lord, for-&yogh;at &thorn;e
&thorn;at maydest hym of nou&yogh;t; &amp; &thorn;erfore it is skil &amp; resoun &thorn;at he &thorn;at ha&thorn; forsaken &thorn;e lord of al pitee &amp; mercy, &thorn;at he neuere haue of &thorn;e nei&thorn;er pitee no mercy. &amp; &thorn;erfore, leue lord, scho sei&thorn;, lat mannus soule be stille as it is, for &thorn;at is
skil &amp; resoun; &amp; ellis me &thorn;enki&thorn; &thorn;ou hast forsaken me, &amp; &thorn;at schuldest &thorn;ou not don&macr;: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia iusticia eius manet in seculum seculi,</FOREIGN> for why, holy wryt sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;i ri&yogh;tfulnesse schal lasten in to &thorn;e worldis ende&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde Mercy to Ri&yogh;tfulnesse: &laquo;A, leue suster, let ben &amp; seye not so, it were nei&thorn;er ri&yogh;t ne skil &thorn;at god schulde kepen &thorn;e &amp; forsaken me: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia misericordia eius super omnia opera eius,</FOREIGN>
for why only goddis mercy is abouen al his werkes, <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et misericordia eius ab eterno &amp; vsque in eternum,</FOREIGN> &amp; goddis mercy was wi&thorn;-outen begynnyng &amp; schal ben wi&thorn;-outen endyng.  &amp; &thorn;erfore, &yogh;if god for-soke me, he schulde forsake bo&thorn;e my sister Tru&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;at were nei&thorn;er ri&yogh;t ne tru&thorn;e.  &amp; &thorn;erfore, leue lord, scho sei&thorn;, to
sauen vs alle &thorn;re, haue &thorn;ou on mannus soule bo&thorn;e mercy &amp; pitee&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne


<PB N="1: 351">

seide Pees to here &thorn;re sistren: &laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Pax domini exsuperat omnem sensum &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> Goddis pees ouergo&thorn; eueriche maner wiit.  &THORN;ou&yogh; it be so, sche seiyt, &thorn;at Tru&thorn;e sei&thorn; a grete skile why mannus soule schulde not be saued, &amp; Ri&yogh;tfulnesse sei&thorn; also,
neuer&thorn;eles me &thorn;enke&thorn; &thorn;at Mercy sei&thorn; al&thorn;erbest, &thorn;at man schulde be saued, for
why ellys, scho sei&thorn;, schulde god forsaken &yogh;ow al &thorn;re, bo&thorn;e Mercy, &amp; Ri&yogh;tfulnesse [&amp; Treu&thorn;e], &amp; &thorn;at were grete reu&thorn;e.  &amp; not only, sche seyde, he schulde &thorn;us forsaken &yogh;ou &thorn;re, but he schulde also forsaken me: for why as longe as man soule is in helle, &thorn;er schal ben discord bytwene &yogh;ou &thorn;re: Ri&yogh;tfulnesse &amp; Tru&thorn;e schol willen to haue hym so &thorn;ere stille, &amp; Mercy schal willen to haue hym oute;
so &thorn;at pees schal ben amongys &yogh;ou forsaken.  &THORN;ere schulde also, &yogh;if man were
stille in helle, ben a discord by-twene god &amp; man, by-twene aungel &amp; man,
by-twene man &amp; man, by-twene man &amp; hym-self: so &thorn;at I, &thorn;at am pees, schulde a
ben forsaken ouer-al, &amp; &thorn;at were no resoun.  &amp; &thorn;erfore do&thorn; after my conseil,
seide Pees, &amp; praye we alle to-geders to god &thorn;at is prince of pees, &thorn;at he wole
maken pees &amp; acord by-twixen &yogh;ou &thorn;re, by-twyne hym-self &amp; man, by-twyne man &amp; aungel, &amp; by-twene man &amp; man, &amp; ordeyne sich a weye &thorn;at he mi&yogh;t kepen vs stille alle foure, bo&thorn;e Mercy &amp; Tru&thorn;e, Ri&yogh;tfulnesse &amp; Pees&raquo;.  &amp; h[e]m &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at scho seyde best, &amp; prayden alle to &thorn;e fadur of heuene &thorn;at he schulde so don&macr;. And he seyde: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ego cogito cogitaciones pacis &amp; non affliccionis &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> I &thorn;enke, he seyde, &thorn;ou&yogh;tis of pees &amp; not of wickednesse.  I schal, he sei&thorn;, kepe &yogh;ou stille alle foure, &amp; I schal sauen mannus soule &amp; brynge hym to blisse.  I schal also, he sei&thorn;, fynden vp &thorn;e abbesse of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; maken a&yogh;eyn here couent &amp; here place, betere &thorn;an euere it was&raquo;.  &amp; whan his dou&yogh;tren harden &thorn;is, &thorn;ei were glad &amp; myrie: and as-swi&thorn;e <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Misericordia &amp; veritas obuiauerunt sibi, iusticia &amp;c.,</FOREIGN>


<PB N="1: 352">

&laquo;Mercy &amp; Tru&thorn;e metten hem to-gedere, Ri&yogh;tfulnesse &amp; Pees weren kyste &amp; maad at on&raquo;.
</P></DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Hou Crist is founder of &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost.</HEAD>

<P>And &thorn;anne as-swi&thorn;e almi&yogh;tty god &thorn;e fader sente doun in to &thorn;is world his
owne sone to be-come man for vs &amp; for to sechen &thorn;e abbesse of &thorn;e holy gost
&amp; here holy couent, &thorn;at is to seyn loue &amp; charite, &amp; o&thorn;ere goode vertues.  &amp; &thorn;e first day he cam &amp; founde a lady of &thorn;at abbeye &thorn;at is clepid Clennesse: for why
he was conceyued wi&thorn;-outen any knowelechyng of synne of man &thorn;oru vertu of
&thorn;e holy gost, &amp; born&macr; of a clene virgyne &thorn;at neuere mi&yogh;t synnen.  &thorn;is clennesse he founde whyle &thorn;at he was wi&thorn;-inne his moders wombe, and here he kepte
&thorn;ere wi&thorn; hym nyne &amp; &thorn;ritty wekes &amp; a day: &amp; &thorn;anne was he born of his moder in an olde broken hous at Beedlem tounnys ende, &amp; leyde in an asse maunger
on a litil hei&yogh;e.  &amp; &thorn;er founde he ano&thorn;er lady of &thorn;e selue abbeye &thorn;at is Pouerte:
for why his moder hadde noon o&thorn;ere schetis to wynde hym Inne, but took a
keuerchef of here heued, &amp; kytte an olde kirtel &amp; made &thorn;erof clo&thorn;is, &amp; wond
&thorn;er-Inne &thorn;ere child for colde, &amp; leyde hym on a wisp in an oxe-stalle&mdash;I trowe
&thorn;ere was pouerte I-now!  &THORN;is pouerte &amp; &thorn;is clennesse he ladde for&thorn; wi&thorn; hym til
he was twelue &yogh;er olde, &amp; whan he was twelue &yogh;er olde &amp; more, he wente wi&thorn;
Ioseph &amp; his moder to Ierusalem&mdash;for &thorn;ei weren wont to weynden &thorn;eder eueryche
&yogh;er to offren &thorn;er on estreday; &amp; whanne &thorn;ei hadden offred, &amp; wenten a&yogh;en hom, lytel Ihesu here sone lefte stille &thorn;ere &thorn;re dayes in Ierusalem &amp; wente in to &thorn;e
temple among &thorn;e maystres of &thorn;e lawe: &amp; &thorn;ere he fonde [ii ladyes] of &thorn;e selue
hous &thorn;e whyche ben clepid Ri&yogh;twisnesse &amp; Wisdom.  &amp; whanne Marie &amp; Ioseph weren comen hom &amp; wisten neuere where swete Ihesu was be-comen, &thorn;ei weren


<PB N="1: 353">

in mochel sorowe for &thorn;e swete childe, &amp; wenten a&yogh;en to Ierusalem to sechen
hym: &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ei founden hym s[i]ttande in &thorn;e temple among &thorn;e doctoures of
&thorn;e lawe disputyng wi&thorn; hem.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde his moder to hym: &laquo;A, sone, scho
sayde, what hast &thorn;ou don&macr;?  I &amp; &thorn;i fader Ioseph han sou&yogh;t &thorn;e &amp; hadden mochel sorowe for &thorn;e&raquo;.  &laquo;Hou is it, he sayde, &thorn;at &yogh;ee han sou&yogh;t me?  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nesciebatis quia in his que patris mei sunt oportet me esse?</FOREIGN> wiste &yogh;e not, he seyde, &thorn;at I most be besy abou&yogh;ten my fadres nedys?  He sente me in to &thorn;is cuntre to sechen &thorn;e couent of &thorn;e holy gost, &amp; &thorn;erfore I wente amonge &thorn;e maystres in to &thorn;e temple, &amp; &thorn;er haue I founden tweyen ladyes of &thorn;e couent, Ri&yogh;twisnesse &amp; Wisdam, for why, now can I more good &thorn;an &thorn;ei euerychon&macr;&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne wente he hom wi&thorn; hem in to Na&yogh;aret, &amp; &thorn;ere he founde a no&thorn;er of &thorn;e selue couent &thorn;at hi&yogh;te
Buxumnesse: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Quia erat subditus illis,</FOREIGN> for why he was lowe of herte &amp; buxum to his moder in al maner &thorn;ing.  &amp; &thorn;anne wente he for&thorn; seuentene &yogh;er &amp; an half, &amp; euery day he fond at his owne bord two o&thorn;er ladyes of &thorn;e selue abbeye, &amp; &thorn;at weren &thorn;ese: Temperaunce &amp; Soburnesse.  &amp; he hadde hem wi&thorn; hym in to desert to sechen mo of here felawys: &amp; &thorn;ere he fond o&thorn;ere two ladyes, &thorn;at is Penaunce &amp; here felaw &thorn;at is clepid damyseil &thorn;e Fort.  Penaunce he fonde &thorn;ere, for why he fasted fourty dayes for loue of mannus soule wi&thorn;-outen mete or drynke.  &amp; whanne he hadde fasted fourty dayes &amp; fourty ny&yogh;ttys, he was for-hungred &amp; lust to eten; &amp; &thorn;ere cam &thorn;e self schrewe to hym &thorn;at cam to Eue in to &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, &amp; wolde han ouercomen hym wi&thorn; glotonye as he dede Eue, &amp; led hym to an hep of stonys &amp; bad hym &yogh;if he were goddis sone he schulde make &thorn;e stonys loues &amp; ete of hem I-now.  &amp; &thorn;anne founde he &thorn;ere &thorn;e lady damysel &thorn;e Fort, &thorn;orow whyche he wi&thorn;-stode my&yogh;tiliche &thorn;e fondyng of &thorn;e fend;


<PB N="1: 354">

&laquo;<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Non in solo pane viuit homo set de omni verbo &amp;c.</FOREIGN>, Man lyue&thorn; not onlyche in bred, he sei&thorn;, but be eueryche word of god&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne bar &thorn;e fend hym from &thorn;ennys to Ierusalem &amp; sette hym on &thorn;e pynacle of &thorn;e temple, &amp; wolde han ouer-comen hym wi&thorn; pride &amp; wi&thorn; veyn-glorye &amp; seyde: &laquo;&yogh;if &thorn;ou be goddis sonne, skippe adoun &amp; take no sor, &amp; men shulle praysen &thorn;e &amp; seyen &thorn;ou hast don&macr; a grete maistrye&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;ere also he wi&thorn;-stode his fondyng &thorn;orow vertu of damysele &thorn;e Fort &amp; seide: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non temptabis dominum deum tuum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;ou schalt not tempten &thorn;i lord god, he sei&thorn;; it is no nede &thorn;at I skippe doun, I may go doun be ano&thorn;ere waye wel I-now&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne ladde he hym to an hie&yogh; hille &amp; schewede hym alle &thorn;e richesses of &thorn;is world, &amp; wolde haue ouer-comen hym &thorn;orou&yogh; coueytise &amp; seyde: &laquo;I schal &yogh;eue &thorn;e alle &thorn;e goode &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt knele doun &amp; do me worschip&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;ere he wi&thorn;-stood hym my&yogh;tiliche wi&thorn; damysele &thorn;e Fort &amp; seide: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vade retro satanas, dominum deum tuum [adorabis] &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> fy on &thorn;e, satanas, he seyde, &amp; turne a&yogh;en to helle; men schuld worschip almi&yogh;ty god &amp; no wi&yogh;t ellys&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e fals schrewe was aschamed of hym-seluen &thorn;at he was so ouercomen wi&thorn; damysele Fort, [&] ran a&yogh;en to helle as an olde schrewe.  &amp; &thorn;anne went Ihesu Crist in to &thorn;e lond of Galilee: &amp; &thorn;ere fond he o&thorn;er two sustren of &thorn;e self hous, &thorn;at is to seye Schrifte &amp; Predicacion.  &THORN;ere prechid Crist first, &amp; &thorn;anne seyde he to &thorn;e folk of &thorn;e cuntre: &laquo;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Penitemini &amp; credite &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> schriue&thorn; &yogh;ou, he sai&thorn;, &amp; do&thorn; penaunce, &amp; bee&thorn; of good byleue, &thorn;e kyngdome of heuene nei&yogh;e&thorn; faste&raquo;.  &amp; he wende for&thorn;e to &thorn;e see-syde &amp; &thorn;erre he sei&yogh;e seynt Petre &amp; Andrew his bro&thorn;ere leggynge &thorn;ere nettys in &thorn;e see to taken fisch; &thorn;ei were bo&thorn;e pore fischers.  &amp; Crist seyde to hem: &laquo;Come&thorn;, he seyde, &amp; folowe&thorn; me, &amp; I make &yogh;ou


<PB N="1: 355">

fyscheres of men&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;ei lette here boote be stille in &thorn;e see &amp; wente for&thorn; wi&thorn; Crist.  &amp; he wente alitel for&thorn;ere, &amp; founden seynt Iames &amp; seynt Ioou his bro&thorn;ere in a no&thorn;ere boote drawynge here nettys wi&thorn; &yogh;ebedee here fadere; &thorn;ei were also fischeres.  &amp; Crist bad hem also comen &amp; folowe hym, &amp; &thorn;ei letten here fader &amp; al &thorn;at &thorn;ei hadden be stille in &thorn;e boote &amp; wenten wi&thorn; hym.  &amp; on a day as &thorn;ei wenten alle to-gedere be &thorn;e weye, seynt Petre seyde to Crist: &laquo;Lord, he seyde, what schul we haue of &thorn;e &thorn;at han forsaken alle &thorn;at we hadde &amp; folowen &thorn;e &thorn;us in pouerte?&raquo;, and as-swi&thorn;e Crist fonde ano&thorn;er suster of &thorn;at hous &thorn;at is clepid Largesse, &amp; seyde: &laquo;For so&thorn;e, &yogh;e &thorn;at han forsaken al &thorn;at &yogh;e hadden &amp; han folowed me, &yogh;e schullen han a houndred-fold so myche &thorn;erfore, &amp; &thorn;erto &thorn;e blisse of heuene&raquo;; &thorn;is was a grete largesse!  &amp; &thorn;anne cam he on a day fro &thorn;e mounte of Olyuete in to &thorn;e temple of Ierusalem to prechen &thorn;ere, &amp; &thorn;e while he was prechynge, &thorn;e phariseus brou&yogh;ten to hym a woman &thorn;at was founden in bed wi&thorn; ano&thorn;er man &thorn;an here hosebounde, &amp; seyde[n] to hym &thorn;us: &laquo;Lo, maister, &thorn;is woman was ri&yogh;t now taken in spousebreche: what schulle we don&macr; wi&thorn; here?  Moyses bidde&thorn; vs in oure lawe we schulde stone such to &thorn;e dee&thorn;&raquo;.  &amp; Crist knewe wel &thorn;e falshed of hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei deden [so] to tempten hym, &amp; he stowped doun &amp; wrot wi&thorn; his fynger on &thorn;e grounde alle &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at euere hadden &thorn;e pharaseus donn, so &thorn;at eche of hem mii&yogh;t seen hou synful o&thorn;ere was, &amp; &thorn;anne he seyde to hem &thorn;us: &laquo;Si&thorn;en hit is so &thorn;at &thorn;us woman schal be &yogh;oure lawe be stoned to &thorn;e dee&thorn;, &thorn;erfore whiche of &yogh;ow &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen synne, caste on here &thorn;e firste stoon&raquo;: and &thorn;ei weren alle aschamed of hem-seluen &amp; wenten oute at &thorn;e dore eche on after o&thorn;ere &amp; leten Crist stonden alone wi&thorn; &thorn;e woman; and &thorn;ere comen to hym two o&thorn;ere ladyes of &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, Misericord &amp; Reufulnesse, &amp; &thorn;an seide Crist to &thorn;e woman: &laquo;Woman, he seyde, where ben &thorn;in enemyes? ha&thorn; any


<PB N="1: 356">

man condempned &thorn;e to &thorn;e dee&thorn;?&raquo;  &laquo;Nay, lord, scho seyde, noman&raquo;.  &laquo;No I ne schal nou&yogh;t condempne &thorn;e; go faare wel, &amp; be of wil neuere-more to do synne&raquo;. Here was grete misericord &amp; grete reufulnesse, for why, &thorn;e most gylt scho hadde don&macr; was a&yogh;enus hym.  &amp; aftirward on a day &thorn;e pharaseus senten here dissiplis to Crist &amp; wolden hauen taken hym in his wordis, &amp; askede hym &yogh;if &thorn;ei mi&yogh;ten bi goddis lawe &yogh;eue tribute to &thorn;e emperoure.  &amp; Crist knewe wel here malice, &amp; seyde: &laquo;A, &yogh;e ypocrytis, what nede is hit to tempten me? lete me seen a peny of &yogh;oure mony&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;ei schewed hym on.  &amp; &thorn;anne seyde Crist: &laquo;Whos coyn is &thorn;is?&raquo;  &amp; &thorn;anne seyden &thorn;ei to Crist: &laquo;&thorn;e emperours&raquo;.  &amp; &thorn;ere fond Crist ano&thorn;ere syster of &thorn;e noble abbeye &thorn;at is clepid Resoun, &amp; seyde: &laquo;&YOGH;eldi&thorn; to &thorn;e emperour &thorn;at by-longe&thorn; to hym, &amp; &yogh;eldi&thorn; to god &thorn;at bi-longe&thorn; to hym&raquo;; &amp; &thorn;at is resoun.
On a day afturward as Crist wente by &thorn;e way by hym-self &amp; as he &thorn;ou&yogh;te of
mannus soule &amp; on &thorn;e abbeye of &thorn;e holy gost, he founde a no&thorn;er suster &thorn;at is
clepid<ADD N="MS Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a.1)"><MILESTONE
N="360" UNIT="MS Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a.1) folio">Gelesye: and &thorn;enne tok he priueliche his twelue apostles and wente touward
Ierusalem &amp; seide to hem &thorn;us: &laquo;Ichaue al &thorn;is two and &thorn;ritti &yogh;er and more ben aboute to helpe monnes soule and for to seche &thorn;e abbesse and hire Couent &thorn;e
whuche wenten out of &thorn;e abbei of &thorn;e holygost, and ichaue founden sixtene of
hem; and now wol I go to Ierusalem and ben I-bounden and I-bete, and ben
honged and drawen, and dye for loue of monnes soule, to sechen vp &thorn;at o&thorn;ur
del of &thorn;e holy Couent&raquo;.  &THORN;is was a gret gelesye and a gret loue!  &para; And &thorn;enne
wente &thorn;ei for&thorn; to Ierusalem.  And as &thorn;ei weore &thorn;ere on an euen at heore soper,
