<DIV1 N="Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a.1)" TYPE="MS">

<PB N="2: 340"><HEAD> Pieces of Ms. Vernon (Bodl. Eng. poet a.1)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>Forms of Confession<NOTE ID="n9">Numerous confessional texts bearing this name exist.  The  version recorded in the Vernon MS is listed in the Manual of Writings in Middle English, vol. 7 as Prose Version R.</NOTE></HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="366" UNIT="folio"><L>Heer is a good Confession</L>
<L>&thorn;at teche&thorn; mon to sauacion,</L><L>how &thorn;at mon schal schriuen him here</L>
<L>To techen him wel &thorn;e Maneere.</L><DIV3 TYPE="section"><P>I knowleche me gulti and &yogh;elde me to God Almihti, and to his blessed Moder seynte Marie, and to al &thorn;e holy cumpanye of heuene, and to &thorn;e mi gostliche fader here in godes stude, of alle &thorn;e sunnes &thorn;at ich haue greuousliche sunged Inne, ffrom &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at I was bore in to &thorn;is day, as in word, in werk, in wille, in &thorn;ou&yogh;t, in speche, in delytyng, in concentyng, and in dede-doing.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>Furst and foreward, I knowleche me gulti in &thorn;e seuene dedly synnes; principaliche in Pruide, [&] in alle &thorn;e circumstaunces of pruide:  In veyn glorie, holdynge me betere &thorn;en I am, in clo&thorn;inge, in spekynge, in strong beoinge, in feynynge, in Connynge; in pruyde of herte and of bodi, in vuel berynge to god &amp; to myn euencristne, inobedient to god &amp; to holychirche; in alle &thorn;e spices &thorn;at suwen pruide I knowleche me gulti, and beo-seche God of Merci.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>IN Envye I knowleche me gulti:  Regoiesyng ofte-tyme of myn euencristene harmes, serwyng of heore gode dedes doyng; also in Bakbyting hem, also in heryng schrewede wordes of myn euencristne, ra&thorn;er makyng hem more &thorn;en lasse in as


<PB N="2: 341">

muche as in me is; in alle &thorn;e spices &thorn;at touchen envye I knowleche me gulti, and crie God Merci.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>IN Wrathe I &yogh;elde me gulti:  Ofte-tyme beryng wrathe in myn herte a&yogh;eyn myn euencristne, and haue maad vnsau&yogh;t disyring for to beo venged on hem; in hatyng hem, in scorning hem, in striuyng a&yogh;eyn hem, hauyng dedeyn of hem, in lauhwhyng hem to scorn, in wra&thorn;&thorn;e beryng in myn herte a&yogh;eynus him o&thorn;erweys &thorn;en I scholde; and in alle &thorn;e spices of wraythe I knowleche me gulti, and crie God Merci.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><P>Also i crie god merci of Slou&thorn;e in Godes seruise:  Not heryng hit deuoutliche as I scholde do, not hauynge delyt in godes seruise in Matyns, in Masse, in prechinge of godes word, but proudliche entryng in to godes hous; in slepyng, in slomeryng, not risyng to here masse and Mateyns whon I wel mi&yogh;t, as I weore holden to do; in such sleu&thorn;e and in alle &thorn;e spices of sleu&thorn;e I knowleche me gulti, and crie god Merci.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>Also I crie god Merci &thorn;at I haue sunged in Couetise:  Coueyting to haue worldly goodes, not holde me payed of &thorn;e stat &thorn;at god ha&thorn; sent me, but desyred for to beo at beter astat, at more worschupe of &thorn;e world; in deseyt and disseyung of myn euencristen, in forswering, not paynge my dettes &thorn;at I ou&yogh;te to paye, ne helpe him &thorn;at ha&thorn; nede; and in alle &thorn;e spices of couetise I knowleche me gulti, [&] Cri&yogh;e God Merci. Also I crie God Merci &thorn;at I haue sunged in Glotonie:  Ofte-tyme eten and drunken out of tyme, haue lykynge in dilicious metes and drinkes, and eten and dronken more &thorn;en I schulde, and also eten and drunken ofte whon I hedde no wille &thorn;erto; and in alle &thorn;e spices of Glotonye I knowleche me gulti, and crie god Merci.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><P>Also I crie God Merci &thorn;at I haue sunged in Lecherie:  In lechours &thorn;ou&yogh;tes, disyryng wimmen, in chirche, in chepyng, ofte whon I seo feire wimmen beholden hem disyringe for to haue dalyaunce wi&thorn; hem, in cluppyng, in cussyng, in vnclene touching; ofte-tyme stured to &thorn;e foule synne, and in &thorn;ou&yogh;tes and ymaginacions of lecherie, and &thorn;enke ofte-tyme of &thorn;e membre of mon and wommon, and what lykynge hit is to haue dalyaunce wi&thorn; hem; and ofte-tyme concentyng to &thorn;at foule synne, &thorn;at neore hit more for sclaundre of &thorn;e world &thorn;en for drede of god . . . I crie God Merci in polucions of niht or tymes slepyng or wakyng diuersliche, not wel con telle wher hit come of eny fore-&thorn;ou&yogh;t of Mon or wommon, or of eny sorfet of mete or drinke.  And of alle suche vnclene &thorn;ou&yogh;tes and ymaginacions of lecherie I crie God Merci in circumstaunces and spices &thorn;at touche&thorn; lecherie; and to seuen dedly synnes I knowleche me gulti and biseche god Mer(ci).
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&THORN;e ten Comaundemens.</HEAD><P>
Also I knowleche me gulti in brekyng of [&thorn;e] Ten Comandemens:  Not worschuped on God of whom al goodnesse come&thorn; wi&thorn; al myn herte, wi&thorn; al my &thorn;ou&yogh;t and deede.  I crie God Merci and of for&yogh;iuenesse.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 342"><P>Also I crie God Merci &thorn;at I haue taken his blessed nome in Idelnesse &yogh;eorne and ofte, and also I-swore bi his herte and his blood and bi alle his membres, as wel fals as trewe, bo&thorn;e in soburnesse and in hastite.  I cri&yogh;.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>Also I cri&yogh;e God Merci &thorn;at I haue not holden myn haly-dayes as I scholde do, in goinge to Churche to here Masse and Matynes; I preye god of for&yogh;iuenes &thorn;at on &thorn;e sonenday and o&thorn;er haly-dayes I go ra&thorn;er to tauerne and ale-hous, fihtyng and bakbityng myn euencristne, ra&thorn;er speking bi hem euel &thorn;en good. I cri&yogh; g. Mer.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><P>Also I cri&yogh;e God Merci &thorn;at I haue not worschupet Fader &amp; Mooder as I schulde do, wi&thorn; goode preyers &amp; almusdedes not biddyng for hem as I schulde do.  I crie God Merci.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><P>Also I crie God Merci &thorn;at I haue coueyted feire wimmen whon I seo hem, disyring hem for to haue heom and for to sunge wi&thorn; hem, a&yogh;eynes godes comaundemens, &thorn;at god comaunde&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;at I schal do no folye bi no wommon.  I cri g. Mer.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>Also I crie God Merci of &thorn;ef&thorn;e, takyng o&thorn;er &thorn;inges &thorn;en myn oune a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e wille of him &thorn;at owe&thorn; hit.  I Crie God Merci.</P><P>Also I crie God Merci of ffals witnesse beryng, sleing myn euencristne wi&thorn; bacbyting, seying behynden hem worse &thorn;en I wolde biforen hem.  I cri g. Mer.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><P>Also I crie god Merci &thorn;at I haue I-sunged in couetyse of &thorn;e world, ofte-tyme coueyted for to beo at betere astate &thorn;en I am, and coueyted worldly richesse; and &yogh;if I seo my neih&yogh;ebor haue eny &thorn;ing &thorn;at I haue not, desyring for to haue hit; and &yogh;if he haue a feir wyf or a seruaunt, desyring hem, doing a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e comaundement of god:  ffor whi:  he sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel 'Coueyte not &thorn;i neih&yogh;ebores wyf ne nout &thorn;at his is'.  Of &thorn;e whuche I Cri&yogh;e God Merci.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head"> VII dedes of Merci</HEAD><P> Also I crie God Merci &thorn;at I haue not folfuld &thorn;e seuen deedes of Merci:  Not visyted hem &thorn;at ben in prison, not fed hem &thorn;at ben hongri, not &yogh;iuen drinke to &thorn;e &thorn;hursti, not clo&thorn;ed &thorn;e naked, not visyted hem &thorn;at ben bedreden; nou&thorn;er wi&thorn; peny ne wi&thorn; half peny.  I crie god Merci, doinge a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e gospel wher God reherse&thorn; '&thorn;at &thorn;at &yogh;e do&thorn; to &thorn;e leste of mine, &yogh;e do to me'.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head"> &thorn;e fyue wittes.</HEAD><P> Also I crie God Merci &thorn;at I haue euel dispendet my fyue wittes:  what wi&thorn; e&yogh;en se&yogh;en, wi&thorn; ffeet i-gon, wi&thorn; honden hondlet, wi&thorn; Neose smulled, wi&thorn; Eren herd, wi&thorn; mou&thorn; spoken, wi&thorn; herte I-&thorn;ou&yogh;t, wi&thorn; al my bodi mis-wrou&yogh;t.  Of &thorn;eos defautes, and of alle o&thorn;ure &thorn;at I haue mad a&yogh;eyn god, and myn euencristne, I crie god Merci, and his dere Moder seynte Marie, and al &thorn;e cumpanye of heuene, and &thorn;e, my gostliche fader in godes stude, &thorn;at &yogh;e be my witnesse at &thorn;e day of dome, seoinge my sunnes and my defautes holdynge hem stille and not schewyng hem, but be Ioye of hem and of me sungere, as god sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at Ioye


<PB N="2: 343">

schal be to godes angeles vppon a sungere penaunce doing.  He hit graunte &thorn;at liue&thorn; and regne&thorn; God amen. &mdash;</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head"> &thorn;e X comaundemens.</HEAD><P> &laquo;How mony Comaundemens be&thorn; &thorn;er?&raquo;  Ten.  &laquo;Whuche Ten?&raquo;  God Comaunde&thorn; me to loue him wi&thorn; al myn herte, wi&thorn; al myn soule, wi&thorn; al my &thorn;ou&yogh;t, wi&thorn; al my streng&thorn;e.  Also he bidde&thorn; me to take nou&yogh;t his nome in veyn.  &para; He bidde&thorn; me halewe myn hali-day.  &para; He bidde&thorn; me worschupe my Fader and my Moder. &para; He bidde&thorn; me &thorn;at I sle no mon.  &para; Ne &thorn;at I do no lecherie.  &para; Ne &thorn;at I stele not.  &para; Ne bere no fals witnesse.  &para; Ne &thorn;at I coueyte &thorn;e hous of [m]y neih&yogh;ebore.  &para; Ne his wyf, &para; Ne his seruaunt, &para; Ne his Oxe, &para; Ne his Asse, ne alle &thorn;inges &thorn;e whuche ben of him.  &para; &laquo;Whon louest &thorn;ou god wi&thorn; al &thorn;in herte?&raquo; Whon I queme him wi&thorn; al &thorn;e vnderstondynge of my be-leeue.  &para; &laquo;Whon louest &thorn;ou god wi&thorn; al &thorn;i soule?&raquo;  Whon al my wille is I-set to loue &thorn;at he loue&thorn;, and to hate &thorn;at he hate&thorn;.  &para; &laquo;Whon louest &thorn;ou god of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t?&raquo;  Whon I wi&thorn; al my muynde &thorn;enke what is his plesaunce.  &para; &laquo;Whon louest &thorn;ou god wi&thorn; al &thorn;i streng&thorn;e?&raquo;  Whon myn vnderstondyng and my wille and my muynde are wel set o werk doinge &thorn;e wille of my god.  &para; &laquo;Whon takest &thorn;ou &thorn;e nome of god in veyn?&raquo;  Whon I nempne God or eny creature &thorn;orw Idel speche or costumable sweryng.  &para; &laquo;Whon halewes &thorn;ou not &thorn;in haly-day?&raquo;  Whon I &thorn;enke not bisyliche in &thorn;e haly-day of my sunnes, doing not &thorn;e werk of Merci to my neodi neih&yogh;ebors.  &para; &laquo;Whon vnworschupestou &thorn;i Fader and &thorn;i Moder?&raquo;  Whon I wilfuliche greue hem, or leue to helpen hem or to counseyle hem, or, &yogh;if &thorn;ei ben dede, &yogh;if I preye not for hem bisyliche in clannesse of lyf.  For preyeres of wilful synners are abhominable bi-fore god.  &para; &laquo;Whon slest &thorn;ou eny mon?&raquo;  Whon I smite eny mon or hurte him wher&thorn;orw he dye, or wrongfoliche reue him his lyflode, or his gode name.  &para; &laquo;Whon dest &thorn;ou lecherye?&raquo;  Whon I of my wilful lust misvse, or coueyte to misvse, my kuyndely limes of gendrure.  &para; &laquo;Whon stelest &thorn;ou &thorn;i neih&yogh;ebores godus?&raquo;  Whon I eny &thorn;ing take of his vnwitynge of him a&yogh;eynes his wille.  &para; &laquo;Whon berest &thorn;ou fals witnesse?&raquo;  Whon I &thorn;orw malyce or drede or fauour or mede sei o&thorn;erwyse of myn nei&yogh;hebore &thorn;en I knowe &thorn;at is trewe, or wolde &thorn;at he seide of me.  &para; &laquo;Whon coueytest &thorn;ou &thorn;i neih&yogh;ebores hous?&raquo;  Whon I coueyte vn-mouable &thorn;ing of his wrongfoly &thorn;e w&yogh;uche is necessarie to him.  &para; &laquo;Whon coueytest &thorn;ou his wyf?&raquo;  Whon I &thorn;orw cluppyng or cussyng or eny &yogh;ifte &yogh;euyng or bi-hotyng am aboute to turne &thorn;e loue of my neih&yogh;ebores wyf from him to me.  &para; &laquo;Whon [coueytest] &thorn;ou &thorn;i neih&yogh;ebors seruaunt?&raquo; Whon I knowe &thorn;at &thorn;e seruaunt of myn neih&yogh;ebor is nedful to him and I tyse him &thorn;orw word or &yogh;ifte, I coueyte him wi&thorn; wrong.  &para; &laquo;Whon coueytest &thorn;ou his Oxe or his Asse?&raquo;  Whon I coueyte eny mouable &thorn;ing from myn neih&yogh;ebore o&thorn;erwyse &thorn;en I wolde he dude from me.  &para; And si&thorn;en alle &thorn;e comaundemens of God stonden in trewe obedience to him:  he &thorn;at offende&thorn; in on, is maad &thorn;orw his vn-obedience gulti of alle, as sei&thorn; seint Iame; and hose &thorn;at wilfuliche breke&thorn; &thorn;e comaundement of god, he deserue&thorn; his cors, ete he drinke he, wake he slepe he, in hous and out of hous, in toun and out of toun, as godes lawe sei&thorn;.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 344"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&para; &laquo;W&yogh;uche are &thorn;e seuene dedli synnes?&raquo; &mdash; Pruide, Envye, Ire, Slou&thorn;e, Couetyse, Lecherie, Glotonye.</HEAD><P>  &laquo;Whon is a Mon proud?&raquo;  Whon he wol not ben knowen such as he is. &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a Mon in Envie?&raquo;  Whon he grucche&thorn; in his herte and ha&thorn; dedeyn of his nei&yogh;hebors encresyng, and of &thorn;e welfare of his enemy, or is glad of his enemys vuel-fare.  &para; &laquo;Whon is a Mon wro&thorn;ful?&raquo;  Whon he &thorn;orw his wra&thorn;&thorn;e bisye&thorn; him to venge his owne cause, folfullynge his malicios desyr in word or in dede, harmynge his bro&thorn;er wi&thorn;-outen drede of god.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a Mon in slou&thorn;e?&raquo;  Whon he is Idel in doinge good, or ocupie[d] aboute vnfructuous &thorn;ing.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a Mon in couetise?&raquo;  Whon he coueite&thorn;, for worldes fame &amp; lust, &thorn;ing &thorn;at is not necessarie for him ne his, or whon he halt him not apayed of &thorn;e goodes &thorn;at god ha&thorn; him sent.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a mon in lecherie?&raquo;  Whon he &thorn;orw Idelnesse wi&thorn; lusti felyng of his flesch norissche&thorn; hit &amp; suffre&thorn; hit to haue maystrie of his spirit, ledyng hit, in wille or werk, to do &thorn;e sunne of lecherie.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a mon in Glotonye?&raquo;  Whon he &thorn;orw vndescret etynge or drinkynge vndispose&thorn; him-self to serue his god, for ful wombe make&thorn; empti soule; ffor wher glotenye &amp; dronkenesse regne&thorn;, may no wisdam beo.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&para; &laquo;Whuche are a Monnes fyue wittes?&raquo;&mdash;Heering, Seoing, Smellyng, Tastyng, and Touching.</HEAD><P> &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a Mon in heeryng?&raquo;  Whon he wilfoliche leeue&thorn; &thorn;at he schulde heere, and &yogh;iue&thorn; herynge to &thorn;at he schulde not heere.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a mon in his siht?&raquo;  Whon his ei&yogh;e is vnstable be-holdyng diuerse &thorn;ing, and lusti wher&thorn;orw he is ofte tempted to do synne bo&thorn;e in lust and couetyse; ffor hose ha&thorn; a liht ei&yogh;e and an vnstable, schal han a Merk bodi ful of sunne.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a Mon in smellynge?&raquo;  Whon he &thorn;orw delicat smel after his pouwer folfulle&thorn; &thorn;e lust of his flesch.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a mon in tastyng?&raquo;  Whon he &thorn;orw tast of mete or dryng lede&thorn; him wher-&thorn;orw he is not disposed to trauayle to serue his god.  &para; &laquo;Whon sunge&thorn; a mon in touching?&raquo;  Whon he wilfuliche of his delyt touche&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;ing &thorn;at are defendet hem bi godes lawe and Reson.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&para; &laquo;Whuche are &thorn;e seuen werkes of Merci?&raquo;</HEAD><P>
 &para; &THORN;e ffurste is:  ffeede &thorn;e hungri, &thorn;at is him &thorn;at ha&thorn; nou&thorn;er streng&thorn;e ne Miht ne wit ne good wherwi&thorn; to susteynen him-self.  &para; &THORN;e secounde bodily werk of Merci is:  to &yogh;iue drynke to &thorn;e &thorn;ursti, &thorn;at ha&thorn; not, as is before seid, to buye him drinke wi&thorn;.  &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde werk of Merci is:  to clo&thorn;e &thorn;e naked.  &para; &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e werk of Merci is:  to herborwe &thorn;e herborweles.  &para; &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e is:  to cumforte &thorn;e seke.  &para; &THORN;e sixte is:  to visyte &thorn;e pore prisoner.  &para; And &thorn;e seue&thorn;e is: to burie &thorn;e pore dede.  &para; And &yogh;if endeles mede schal folwe &thorn;es werkes of Merci, hem bi-houe&thorn; beo don in charite, to &thorn;e distruccion of vices, and to &thorn;e encres of vertues.  &para; &THORN;er nis no mon &thorn;at ha&thorn; wherwi&thorn;, &thorn;at may ben excused but &yogh;if he releue his neodi nei&yogh;&yogh;ebore aftur his pouwer wi&thorn; his bodily goodes.  Muche more is vche mon endetted, and specialiche prestes, to departe wi&thorn; &thorn;e neodi heore gostly tresour, &thorn;at is, to do &thorn;e gostly werkes of Merci.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 345"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&para; Heer be&thorn; &thorn;e gostli werkes of Merci.</HEAD><P>  &THORN;E ffurste gostly werk of Merci [is]:  &thorn;at a Mon teche &thorn;e vncunnynge, &thorn;at is to seye, To teche &thorn;e viciouse mon gode vertues, be-nyme him vices after his pouwer. &para; &THORN;e secounde gostly wer[k] of Merci is:  to counsayle &thorn;e wilysum to kepe &thorn;e rihtwysnesses of god.  &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde gostli werk of Merci is:  to chastise &thorn;e rebel bi word or bi dede or beo wi&thorn;-drawyng from him &thorn;e occasion of his sunne wherwi&thorn; his sunne is meyntened.  &para; &THORN;e ffeor&thorn;e gostli werk is:  to cumforte &thorn;e sori to beo pacient in aduersite.  &para; &THORN;e ffyf&thorn;e gostly werk is to for&yogh;iue, &thorn;at we in vre owne cause desyre no vengeaunce.  &para; &THORN;e sixte werk of gostly Merci is: to teche &thorn;e vnpacient to suffre muchel aduersites.  &para; And &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e is:  to teche men to preye hertiliche for &thorn;e conuercion of enemyes &amp; also for &thorn;e perseueraunce of frendes.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&laquo;Whuche are &thorn;e foure principal vertues?&raquo;</HEAD><P> &THORN;e ffurste Is Rihtwysnesse.  &para; &THORN;e secounde is Temperaunce.  &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde is Prudence.  &para; And &thorn;e ffeor&thorn;e is Streng&thorn;e.  &para; &laquo;Wher-Inne stonde&thorn; Rihtwysnesse?&raquo; In Iust demynge.  &para; &laquo;Wher-in stonde&thorn; Temperaunce?&raquo;  In mesurable Etyng and Drinkyng, ... Spekyng, Sleping, and trauaylyng.  &para; &laquo;Wher-Inne stonde&thorn; Streng&thorn;e?&raquo; In mihti wi&thorn;-stondyng of temptacion, continueliche seruyng God.  God &yogh;iue vs grace to serue God.  Amen.
</P>
</DIV3></DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD>A Talkyng of &thorn;e Love of God</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="367" UNIT="folio"><OPENER> Heer Is a tretys: A talkyng of &thorn;e loue of God.</OPENER><P>&THORN;is tretys Is a talkyng of &thorn;e loue of God; and is mad forto sturen &dot; hem &thorn;at hit reden:  to louen him &thorn;e more, and to fynde lykyng &dot; and tast in his loue. Hit falle&thorn; for to reden hit &dot; esyliche and softe, so as men may mest &dot; in Inward felyng &dot; and deplich &thorn;enkyng &dot; sauour fynden; and &thorn;at not beo-dene, but biginnen and leten &dot; in what paas so men seo&thorn; &dot; &thorn;at may for &thorn;e tyme &dot; &yogh;iuen mest lykynge; and whon men ha&thorn; conceyued &dot; &thorn;e maters wi&thorn; redyng:  Inward &thorn;enkyng &dot; and deoplich sechyng &dot; wi&thorn;-outen eny redyng &dot; vppon &thorn;e selue maters, and of such o&thorn;ere &dot; &thorn;at god wol senden &dot; hose wole sechen, schal &yogh;iuen inward si&yogh;t &dot; and felyng in soule &dot; and swetnes wonderful, &yogh;if preyere folwe.  But hose wole in Meditacion &dot; swete fruit fynden:  hit mot be taken in wone &dot; wi&thorn; &thorn;reo poyntes &thorn;at folewen:  affyaunce, and continuaunce, and louh herte and clene; &thorn;at he truste sikerliche &dot; to fynden &thorn;at he seche&thorn;, and &thorn;at his &thorn;ou&yogh;t beo harde iset &dot; and ful bisyliche I-kept, and holden him-self vn-wor&thorn; &dot; out of godes &yogh;ifte, and wlate on him-seluen &dot; &thorn;orw siht of his ful&thorn;e.  &para; Men schal fynden lihtliche &thorn;is tretys in Cadence &dot; after &thorn;e bigynninge &dot; &yogh;if hit beo riht poynted; &amp; Rymed in sum stude;


<PB N="2: 346">

to beo more louesum &dot; to hem &thorn;at hit reden.  God &yogh;iue vs grace &dot; so for to rede: &thorn;at we mowen haue heuene &dot; to vre Mede.  Amen.
</P><P>Ihesu so&thorn; God, Godes sone; Ihesu so&thorn; God so&thorn; mon, mon Maydens child. Ihesu myn holy loue, mi siker swetnesse.  &para; Ihesu myn herte, my sele, my soule-hele.  Ihesu, swete Ihesu; Ihesu, deore Ihesu; Ihesu, almihti Ihesu.  Ihesu mi lord, my leof, my lyf; myn holy wey, myn hony-ter.  Ihesu, alweldinde Ihesu:  Ihesu &thorn;ou art al &thorn;at I hope.  &para; Ihesu mi Makere &dot; &thorn;at me madest of nou&yogh;t, and al &thorn;at is in heuene &dot; and in eor&thorn;e.  &para; Ihesu my Buggere &dot; &thorn;[at] bou&yogh;test me so deore, wi&thorn; &thorn;i stronge passion &dot; wi&thorn; &thorn;i precious blod, and wi&thorn; &thorn;i pyneful de&thorn; on Roode. &para; Ihesu my Saueour &dot; &thorn;at me schalt sauen, &thorn;orw &thorn;i muchele Merci &dot; &amp; &thorn;i muchele mi&yogh;t.  Ihesu my weole &amp; al my wynne:  Ihesu &thorn;at al my blisse is inne.  &para; Ihesu also &thorn;at &thorn;ou art &dot; so feir and so swete, &yogh;it art &thorn;ou so louelich &dot; louelich and louesum, &thorn;at &thorn;e holy angeles &dot; &thorn;at euere &thorn;e biholden:  ben neuere folle &dot; to loken on &thorn;i face.  &para; Ihesu &thorn;ou art al feir, whon &thorn;e sonne a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e:  nis bote a schade, and schome&thorn; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;i brihte leor &dot; of hire &thorn;esternesse.  &para; &THORN;ou &thorn;at &yogh;iuest hire liht &dot; and al &thorn;at liht haue&thorn;:  Lihte my &thorn;ester herte.  Graunte &thorn;at &thorn;i brihtnesse &dot; clanse my soule:  &thorn;at is vnseliche, wi&thorn; sunne foule I-fuiled.  Lord mak hire wor&thorn;i:  to &thorn;i swete wonynge.  Cundele me wi&thorn; &thorn;e blisse:  of &thorn;i brenninde loue.  &para; Swete Ihesu my leoue lyf, Let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt, and lere me for to loue &thorn;e, &amp; mak me for to serue &thorn;e &dot; louynde lord:  so &thorn;at onliche &thorn;i loue &dot; be euer al my lyking, my &thorn;ou&yogh;t and my longyng; amen, Ihesu heuene kyng. &para; Swete lord wo is me &dot; &thorn;at I am &thorn;e so fremde:  Bote also &thorn;ou hast bodiliche &dot; torned me from &thorn;e world, torn me also herteliche &dot; to &thorn;e &dot; lord of so&thorn; loue, and studefast beo-leeue; &thorn;at I haue no mong, felau&yogh;schupe ne speche, ne non o&thorn;er tellyng &dot; wi&thorn; no worldliche &thorn;ing.  For wel ichot lord, &thorn;at fleschlich loue and gostlich, er&thorn;liche loue and heuenlich:  mowe none wyse &dot; bedden in a brest. &para; Hose-euere haue longe defaute of gostly cumfort &dot; and heuenly mur&thorn;es:  hit is for&thorn;i &thorn;at he haue&thorn; &dot; or &thorn;at he wilne&thorn; to haue:  cumfort of eor&thorn;e &dot; &thorn;at is fikel and fals, fayle&thorn; whon men lest wene&thorn; &dot; and ate mest neode; hit is I-meynt wi&thorn; bitternesse &dot; and bleendynge of bales.  &para; Nis no blisse otewi&thorn; &dot; &thorn;at hit nis to deore abou&yogh;t, as hony &thorn;at me likke&thorn; &dot; on prikkynde &thorn;ornes.  &para; Nis he a sori Chapmon &dot; &thorn;at &yogh;iue&thorn; al &thorn;at he ha&thorn; &dot; for a &thorn;ing &thorn;at nou&yogh;t nis, and leue&thorn; a precious &thorn;ing &THORN;at beete may alle bales, &thorn;at me beode&thorn; him for nou&yogh;t, &amp; bi-hote&thorn; him muche meede &dot; &thorn;at he hit wole taken?  A derwor&thorn;e lord &dot; &thorn;ou beodest vs &thorn;i Ioye, &thorn;e lykyng of &thorn;i deore loue &dot; &thorn;e socour of &thorn;in helpe; and berest hit on vs stifliche &dot; al wi&thorn;-outen askyng; and &thorn;erto &thorn;ou bi-hotest vs &dot; wi&thorn; &thorn;at we wollen hit taken:  heuene-riche blisse &dot; &thorn;at is wi&thorn;-outen ende.  And we vs turne &thorn;erfro &dot; as &thorn;ei&yogh; hit nou&yogh;t ne weore; and bugge &thorn;e schadewe of &thorn;e world, a seynynge of &thorn;at is nou&yogh;t, but fikel faylynde and fals &dot; and tollyng to serwe; and &yogh;it ne haue we hit for nou&yogh;t &dot; but buggen hit wi&thorn; bisynesse, wi&thorn; angwys