im al to wreche; and I forsok &thorn;at ilke lord &dot; &thorn;at lette&thorn; my gultus, and seche&thorn; me and folwe&thorn; me, whon so euere I from him fle, and calle&thorn; me loueliche &dot; to &yogh;ift of his grace.  &para; Allas allas nou fynde I me grisloker in my gultes, &thorn;en &thorn;e grislihed of him &dot; &thorn;at helle gryse&thorn; offe.  &para; Allas &yogh;if I seo my-self &dot; I ne may soffre my-self; and &yogh;if i ne seo my-self nou&yogh;t &dot; &thorn;enne gyle I my-self . . . . &thorn;en stynkinde careyne, and muche more wlatsum &dot; bifore godes face: &thorn;en eny ful&thorn;e so foul &dot; &thorn;at eny mon may &thorn;enken; so &thorn;at me gryse&thorn; of my-self &dot; and wlate of my ful&thorn;e; &thorn;at I ne may soffre mi-self &dot; &thorn;at wrou&yogh;te haue al &thorn;is serwe.  A lord &thorn;yn ore, &thorn;at I may sike sore!  Whi ne grise&thorn; of me &dot; bo&thorn;e my mete and my drynk, my schroud and al o&thorn;er &thorn;ing &dot; &thorn;at me scholde helpe? Hou may rihtwysnesse &thorn;ole . . . . &thorn;at &thorn;er ne rise&thorn; a&yogh;eyn me &dot; alle &thorn;yne schaftes, wi&thorn; schome &amp; wi&thorn; schendschupe &dot; wi&thorn; gounyng &amp; wi&thorn; spornyng, to fihten on &thorn;is traytur &dot; &thorn;is tiraunt and &thorn;is tormentor, &thorn;at ha&thorn; al his schappere &dot; so fouliche dispiset?  &para; Whi nam I hunted wi&thorn; hem &dot; foule as a dogge?  For &thorn;ei mowe alle crie &dot; and siggen in heore kuynde:  &laquo;&THORN;ees is &thorn;e foule corselyng &dot; &thorn;at ha&thorn; vr aller makere &dot; &thorn;at maade vs to his worschupe &dot; so schomeliche offendet; &thorn;at vse&thorn; vs in his werkes &dot; to schome of vr lord.  &para; &THORN;ees is he &thorn;at more bey&yogh; &dot; in wille &amp; in werk, to &thorn;e deueles tollyng &dot; &thorn;en to godes drawyng, and more ha&thorn; rewarde &dot; to &thorn;e deueles gyle, &thorn;en to godes benfe&yogh; &dot; &thorn;at bou&yogh;t him on Rode; and hedde more likyng &dot; in &thorn;e Malice of &thorn;e deuel, &thorn;en he hedde delyt &dot; in Godes goodnesse; and ches muchel ra&thorn;ere &dot; to beo &thorn;e deueles cundle, &thorn;en wi&thorn; endeles lyf &dot; godes child of heuene.  &para; Whon god daunselede him muchel &dot; &amp; worschuped him feyre:  he ne set hit at nou&yogh;t &dot; ne dredde not his wreche; but more dredde to wra&thorn;&thorn;en &dot; a worldliche wrecche:  &thorn;en schomeliche offenden &dot; god &thorn;at him wrou&yogh;te; and more was aschomet &dot; to don in monnes siht an e&thorn;eliche


