<P>&THORN;Enk on &thorn;i Caytyf &dot; lord God almihti, and &thorn;ou his Mylde Mooder &dot; &thorn;at ben so ful of Merci; &thorn;ow Lord ffauerynde &dot; and &thorn;ou ladi be-sechinde; let me neuer faylen &dot; &thorn;at I Merci ne fynde; or elles sei me where &dot; is eny of more Merci, and more mihtful &thorn;en &yogh;e &dot; and largore of grace, &para; &thorn;at in &yogh;our defaute &dot; whon &yogh;e me forsaken, schul my neode beeten &dot; and graunten my bone.  &para; But si&thorn;en onliche in ow &dot; &amp; in non no&thorn;ur, is welle of alle Merci &dot; &thorn;at euermore flowe&thorn;:  ffor &thorn;at muchel Merci &dot; clanse my soule, and wasch hit of &thorn;at ful&thorn;e &dot; &thorn;at hit is fuyled wi&thorn;:  &para; &thorn;at I &thorn;orw or grace &dot; askape &thorn;at wreche, &thorn;at is me wor&thorn;iliche &dot; for gult of my dedes; and schild me from &thorn;at serwes &dot; nou and euer-more, &thorn;at be&thorn; to &thorn;e dampnede &dot; grey&thorn;ed in helle; &thorn;at I wi&thorn; alle &thorn;o &thorn;at ben &dot; blisful in heuene, may ow bo&thorn;e blessen &dot; ay wi&thorn;-outen ende, amen.
</P><P>Ihesu my derwor&thorn;e lord &dot; Ihesu myn oune Fader; swete Ihesu heuene kyng, mi druri my derlyng, mi deoring mi louyng, myn hony-brid my swetyng; myn hele &amp; myn hony-ter, min hony-lyf min halewy.  Swettore art &thorn;ou &thorn;en hony &dot; or Milk in Mou&thorn;e, Meode Me&thorn; or pi&yogh;ement &dot; maad wi&thorn; spices swete, or eny lykinde licour &dot; &thorn;at ou&yogh;wher may be founden.  Ho ne may loue lord &dot; &thorn;i leoue lofsum leore?  What herte is so ouer-hard &dot; &thorn;at ne may to-melte, in &thorn;e monyg of &thorn;e &dot; loueliche lord?  And ho ne may loue &thorn;e &dot; swete Ihesu?  For in-wi&thorn; &thorn;eselue aren &dot; alle &thorn;inges gedered, &thorn;at euer may maken eny mon &dot; louewor&thorn; to o&thorn;er.  &para; Feirnesse, louesum leor, flesch whit vnder schroud, make&thorn; mony mon beo bi-loued &dot; and &thorn;e more deore.  &para; Summe freodam &amp; largesse &dot; &thorn;at leuere is: menskeliche to &yogh;iuen &dot; &thorn;en quedliche to wi&thorn;-holden.  &para; Summe wit and wisdam &dot; and hap of &thorn;e world.  &para; Summe Miht and streng&thorn;e &dot; to ben kud Kene in fiht &dot; his riht to defenden.  &para; Summe nobleye &amp; hendelek &dot; and gentrise of kuynde.  &para; Summe gret Cortesye &dot; and lo&thorn;les leetes.  &para; Summe mylde and Mekenesse &dot; &amp; deboner herte, wi&thorn; swete louereden &dot; and godliche dedes.  &para; And &yogh;it ouer alle &thorn;eose &dot; kuynde mest; sibbe frendes &dot; vchon louen o&thorn;ur.  Now my derwor&thorn;e loue &dot; my swete lyf my lykyng, my louelichest leof &dot; myn herte and myn halewy, mi longyng mi mournyng &dot; mi soule swetnesse:  &thorn;ou art lufsum of leor &dot; mi swete Ihesu; &thorn;ow art also schene &dot; &thorn;at alle angeles lyf:  is to biholden &dot; &thorn;i loueliche face.  &para; For &thorn;i leor is so briht &dot; and vnimete lofsum, &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;e for-wariede &dot; &thorn;at wallen in helle, mihten hit [se] wi&thorn; e&yogh;en &dot; and loken &thorn;er-onne, al &thorn;at pyninde pich &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;ei wallen Inne, ne wolde hem &thorn;inke &dot; bote a softe ba&thorn; ba&thorn;inge; &para; ffor &yogh;if hit so mihte beo &dot; derwor&thorn;e lord, leuere hem were euer-more &dot; in wo forte dwelle, and on &thorn;i lofsum leor &dot; euer-more to loke, &thorn;en in alle blisse ben &dot; euer wi&thorn;-outen ende, and of &thorn;at bri&yogh;t blisful leor &dot; forgon &thorn;at swete sihte. &para; &THORN;ou art so schene &amp; so briht &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne weore desk, &yogh;if hit to &thorn;i blisful leor &dot; mihte ben I-euenet.  &para; &YOGH;if I wol loue eny mon &dot; for his feirnesse, forso&thorn;e derwor&thorn;e lord &dot; I wol loue &thorn;e, mi leoue blessede lord:  moder-sone feyrest, of alle &thorn;ing swettest &dot; founden in tast.  &para; A swete Ihesu gode leof &dot; let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt, and lere me for to loue &thorn;e &dot; louynde lord, &thorn;at onliche &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e &dot; be euer al my likyng, mi &yogh;eornyng mi longyng, mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t and al mi worching.  Amen.
</P><P>BOte my swete lord &dot; for &thorn;at sibbe frendes Kuyndeliche loue&thorn; hem &dot; vchon to o&thorn;er, &thorn;ou clo&thorn;edest &thorn;e wi&thorn; oure flesch &dot; mon boren of wommon; &thorn;ou toke


<PB N="2: 354">

of hire swete flesch &dot; wi&thorn;-outen hire wemmyng &dot; monkuynde follich, to &thorn;ole al &thorn;at mon mai &thorn;ole, and don al &thorn;at mon do&thorn; &dot; wi&thorn;-oute synne one, and bicom vr bro&thorn;ur &dot; of Fader and of Mooder, to maken hol [loue] vnbeden &dot; bituenen vs alle. &para; Who is &thorn;enne &thorn;at ne may &dot; &amp; ou&yogh;te to be kuynde, to louen his oune bro&thorn;ur of flesch and of blod?  &para; Nou my swete Ihesu &dot; my derwor&thorn;e bro&thorn;ur:  my sibbe kun haue I leeued &dot; for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e, and &thorn;ei&yogh; heo me forsaken &dot; ne recche&thorn; me no&thorn;ing, whiles &thorn;at I mai haue &thorn;e &dot; al one for hem alle.  &para; For &yogh;if I &thorn;e haue &dot; what scholde I more asken?  I nouh &thorn;at me neod is &dot; ne may me frendes lakken.  &THORN;ou art me more &thorn;en Fader &dot; more &thorn;en Moder; Bro&thorn;ur or Suster &dot; or eny worldliche frend, nou&yogh;t aren hem to telle &dot; a&yogh;ein &thorn;e al one.  A swete Ihesu &dot; mi derwor&thorn;e bro&thorn;er, of flesch and of blod &dot; of fader &amp; of moder:  &para; Mi swete derwor&thorn;e lord &dot; let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt, &amp; teche me forte loue &thorn;e &dot; benyngne lord, &thorn;at onliche &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e &dot; beo al my likyng.  &para; Wel artou swete &dot; and louelich ouur alle, ffor in &thorn;e one is founden &dot; &thorn;e pris of alle beute, &thorn;e pris of al richesse &dot; of loue and of largesse, of wit &amp; of wisdam &dot; of miht and of streng&thorn;e. In &thorn;e is pris of sibreden &dot; &amp; of alle frendschupe, of al loueliche &thorn;ing &dot; &thorn;at mon may wi&thorn; [in] loue ben.  But ouer al o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing &dot; &thorn;at make&thorn; &thorn;e so louelich, &amp; so louewor&thorn; to me &dot; my derwor&thorn;e lord, vnimete more:  &thorn;in ouerharde hurtes, &thorn;i schome and &thorn;i woundes &dot; &thorn;i pyne &amp; &thorn;i passiouns, &thorn;i deore de&thorn; on Roode &dot; &thorn;at was so schendful for me; heo asken al hol my loue &dot; and reuen al myn herte. A swete Ihesu leoue lyf &dot; let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt, and lere me forte loue &thorn;e &dot; louynde lord, &thorn;at onliche &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e &dot; beo euer al my likyng, mi &yogh;eornyng and my longyng, my &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; al mi worching.  amen.
</P><P>BOte moni for richesse &dot; lemmon cheose&thorn;; ffor eueriwher mai men &dot; wi&thorn; catel loue chepen.  &para; Bot is &thorn;er eny Ricchore &thorn;en &thorn;ou &dot; my leue lyf my lemmon, &thorn;at richeliche regnest &dot; in heuene &amp; in eor&thorn;e?  &THORN;ou art kud Cayser &dot; &thorn;at al &thorn;is world welde&thorn;; ffor as &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn; &dot; Dauid in his psalme:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Domini est terra &amp; plenitudo eius,</FOREIGN> &laquo;&thorn;in is &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &dot; and al &thorn;at &thorn;er-in wone&thorn;&raquo;.  &thorn;in is &thorn;e heuene &dot; and al &thorn;at &thorn;erin lyue&thorn;; &thorn;in is al &thorn;e wyde world &dot; and al &thorn;at &thorn;er is inne.  &para; Al is &thorn;in my swetyng &dot; and al &thorn;ow wolt hit &yogh;eue me, &yogh;if I wi&thorn; al myn herte &dot; al-one wol &thorn;e.  But &thorn;ou lord &thorn;i-seluen &dot; art wi&thorn;-outen ende, vnymete more wor&thorn; &dot; &thorn;en ben alle &thorn;eose.  &THORN;erfore wol I loue &thorn;e &dot; my leue lyf my deore, and al-one for &thorn;i loue &dot; alle &thorn;inges leten, &thorn;at mihte myn herte &dot; from &thorn;i loue leden, or ben encheson &thorn;erof &dot; to louen &thorn;e &thorn;e lasse.  [A swete Ihesu &amp;c.]
</P><P>BOte what is Richesse wor&thorn; &dot; or muche forto welden, &thorn;er wi&thorn;-outen largesse &dot; freodam lakke&thorn;?  &para; And ho is freore &thorn;en &thorn;ou &dot; or largore of &yogh;ifte, &thorn;at furst madest al &thorn;is world &dot; and &yogh;eue hit to my wille.  &THORN;ow &yogh;eue me such lordschupe &dot; ouer alle &thorn;i schaftes, and puttest vnder my feet &dot; al &thorn;at &thorn;ou schope.  But I hit wikkedliche fordude &dot; &thorn;oru my foule synnes.  And &thorn;ou for &thorn;i freodam &dot; &yogh;af for me &thorn;i-selue, to leese me from &thorn;raldam &dot; &thorn;at I was put inne.  &para; &YOGH;if I eny &thorn;enne wole &dot; for largesse louen, &thorn;e al one wol I louen &dot; swete Ihesu.  For o&thorn;ure &thorn;at ben large men &dot; and corteis I-kudde, &yogh;iuen of heore goodes &dot; after &thorn;at hem lyke&thorn;:  but &thorn;ou sweete Ihesu &dot; largest of alle, ne &yogh;euest not one of &thorn;i good &dot; to wouwe wi&thorn; &thorn;i lemmon, bote [&yogh;eue] &thorn;i-self for me &dot; in prys of my soule, &thorn;at


<PB N="2: 355">

&thorn;in owne herte-blood &dot; ne woldest not wi&thorn;holden.  So derwor&thorn;e dreweri &dot; ne so deore &yogh;ifte, ne &yogh;af neuer in &thorn;is world &dot; lemmon to o&thorn;ur.  And also &thorn;at &thorn;ou for me &dot; &yogh;af so &thorn;y-seluen, &thorn;ou hast me hi&yogh;ed to &thorn;e &dot; and &yogh;af me al &thorn;i-seluen, to sitten on &thorn;i riht hond &dot; coround in &thorn;i riche, wi&thorn; euer-lykynde loue &dot; to regnen in blisse.  &para; Who is &thorn;enne largore &dot; &thorn;en &thorn;ou art of &yogh;ifte, or so loue-wor&thorn;i &dot; [as &thorn;ou] swete Ihesu?  Wher may me eny loue &dot; so wor&thorn;iliche setten, whose seche&thorn; eny &thorn;ing &dot; &thorn;at eny loue aske&thorn;, as on &thorn;e my lemmon &dot; &thorn;at art loue-welle, and &yogh;eldest alle &thorn;at &thorn;e louen &dot; wellynde stremes?  A swete Ihesu &amp;c.
</P><P>But largesse is luyte wor&thorn; &dot; and luyte loue wor&thorn;i, &thorn;at riht rulynde wit &dot; and wisdam wonte&thorn;.  &YOGH;if I wol eny &thorn;enne loue &dot; for wit or for wisdam, &thorn;en wol i loue [&thorn;e] &dot; swete Ihesu; for &thorn;i wit is wonderful &dot; and wi&thorn;-outen make.  &para; &THORN;ou art wisdam i-clept &dot; and wit of &thorn;i fader; ffor he &thorn;orw &thorn;at wisdam made &dot; bo&thorn;e heuene and eor&thorn;e, and als his swete willes was &dot; al &thorn;is world wrou&yogh;te, schop &thorn;e sonne and &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute; &dot; and alle maner schaftes, and al he dihte wonderliche &dot; as hit best semede.  In-wi&thorn; &thorn;e my leue lyf &dot; is welle of alle wisdam, &thorn;at ha&thorn; so wonderliche wit &dot; sprad so wyde-where:  al &thorn;at is and euer was &dot; and euer schal betyden, al hit is before-hond &dot; to &thorn;i wit knowen.  Ne may &thorn;er-wi&thorn; no wisdam &dot; in al &thorn;is world be founden, bute hit of &thorn;at welle &dot; of &thorn;i wit streme.  &para; A swete Ihesu swete lef &dot; swettest ouer alle, &yogh;if me wit to loue &thorn;e, let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt, &thorn;at I euere serue &thorn;e, and teche me forte qweme &thorn;e &dot; louynde lord, so &thorn;at onlich &thorn;i loue be euer al my likyng.
</P><P>BOte mony mon for streng&thorn;e &dot; and mony for his hardischupe, is ofte muchel i-leten of &dot; and loued and honoured.  And is eny so hardi, so bold and so dou&yogh;ti:  as &thorn;ou art my leue lyf &dot; founden in a-say?  Nay forso&thorn;e swete lef &dot; &thorn;ou berest &thorn;e pris of alle; for &thorn;ow &thorn;i-self al one &dot; ne dreddest not &thorn;yn oune bodi, to fihten a-&yogh;eyn alle &dot; &thorn;e deuelen of helle; &thorn;e w&yogh;uche of hem alle &dot; so is lest lodlich, mi&yogh;te he him schewen &dot; [in] &thorn;e makyng &thorn;at he is, alle scholde ben agast &dot; and grysen of him one, ffor no mon mihte him i-seo &dot; and in his wit wone, but &yogh;if &thorn;i grace special &dot; baldes his herte.  &THORN;ou art &yogh;it &thorn;er-wi&thorn; &dot; so vnymete mihti, &thorn;at wi&thorn; [&thorn;i] deore hondes &dot; nayled on Roode, &thorn;ou bounde helle-dogges &dot; and raftes hem heore preye, &thorn;at &thorn;ei faste helden &dot; for Adames sunne; and as a kene kempe &dot; robbedest helle, and laddest out &thorn;i deore leef &dot; &thorn;at is monnes soule, to &thorn;i bri&yogh;te boure &dot; ful of alle blisse, to wonen in &thorn;i cluppyng &dot; euer wi&thorn;-outen ende.  &para; And &thorn;erfore &yogh;if me lyke&thorn; &dot; stalwor&thorn;e lemmon, louen &thorn;enne wol I &thorn;e &dot; louely Ihesu, &thorn;at art al mihti &dot; and strengest of alle.  Streng&thorn;e me to loue &thorn;e &dot; [swete Ihesu], &thorn;at al my feblesse mai&yogh;t &dot; streng&thorn;en at &thorn;i wille, and wi&thorn; &thorn;in hei&yogh;e hardinesse &dot; bi ni&yogh;tes and bi dayes, a&yogh;eyn my wi&thorn;erwines &dot; bolden mi soule.  A swete Ihesu mi&yogh;ti leof &dot; strengest of alle, streng&thorn;e me to loue &thorn;e, let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt &dot; derwor&thorn;e lord, &amp;c.
</P><P>Noble men and gentil &dot; and of hei&yogh; kuynde:  mony wimmen leeten &dot; menske forte loue.  A swete Ihesu Merci &dot; on what herre mon, mai I sette my loue &dot; &yogh;if &thorn;at I &thorn;e lete?  Wher is eny gentilore &dot; &thorn;en &thorn;i-self founden?  &THORN;ou art &thorn;at ilke kynges sone &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;is world welde&thorn;, and kyng wi&thorn; &thorn;i ffader &dot; kyng of alle


<PB N="2: 356">

kynges, and lord al-mi&yogh;ti &dot; lord of alle lordes.  And &yogh;it art &thorn;ow ouer &thorn;is &dot; boren of mylde Marie, of Dauides kunreden &dot; &thorn;e kyng of Abrahames blod.  Of herre cunreden &thorn;en &thorn;ou art &dot; nis non vnder sonne.  Louen wol I &thorn;enne &thorn;e &dot; swete Ihesu, as &thorn;e gentileste leof &dot; &thorn;at euer was in eor&thorn;e, &thorn;at neuer was no lac &dot; ne last wi&thorn; I-founden; and &thorn;at com &thorn;e nomeliche &dot; of kuynde of &thorn;i fader, of whom is al gentilrie &dot; and cortesye sprongen.  Let me be &thorn;i seruaunt &dot; gentil and hende, and lere me forte loue &thorn;e &dot; my derwor&thorn;e lord, so &thorn;at in &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e &dot; my lyking and my Ioye, wi&thorn;outen eny o&thorn;ur mong &dot; euer be rooted fast.
</P><P>MEkenesse and myldeschupe &dot; are swete loue-tacches, and make&thorn; ofte mony mon &dot; leof and dere.  And &thorn;ou Ihesu my leoue leof &dot; for &thorn;i muchele Mekenesse, as witnesse&thorn; holi writ &dot; to lomb were &thorn;ou euenet.  For a&yogh;eyn alle schomes &amp; serwes &dot; &thorn;at men duden &thorn;e, neuer ne opnedest &thorn;ou &thorn;i mou&thorn; &dot; to grucchen a&yogh;eyn. And &yogh;it to eken al &thorn;at &dot; al &thorn;e schome &amp; sunne, &thorn;at synful wrecches of &thorn;is world &dot; vche day recheles &dot; don a&yogh;eyn &thorn;i godhed &dot; as &thorn;ou no god ne were, &thorn;ou &thorn;olest al myldelich, and takest hit lihtlich, ne takest not sodeynlich &dot; wreche of vr gultes; but &thorn;orw &thorn;i muchele myldeschupe &dot; abydest vs longe, euer sechinde loue &dot; &amp; beodyng of grace.  And &thorn;erfore my lemmon &dot; my Ioye &amp; my blisse, euer glad mai I ben &dot; &amp; blisful to wisse, &thorn;e false mur&thorn;es of &thorn;is world &dot; to leuen &amp; misse, &amp; euer resten in &thorn;e &dot; to cluppen &amp; cusse.  A swete
</P><P>Ihesu my leoue leof &dot; my loueliche lemmon, mi derwor&thorn;e derlyng &dot; mi soule swetnesse:  &para; &thorn;reo foos fihten &dot; a&yogh;eynes me faste:  &thorn;e false world and my flesch &dot; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is &thorn;e deuel; &para; &thorn;e world to make me fals &dot; and tolle me to &thorn;ef&thorn;e; &para; mi flesch to mony ful&thorn;es &dot; of vntounes lustes; &para; &thorn;e deuel wi&thorn; wi&thorn; his sleih&thorn;es &dot; and wi&thorn; his queynte crokes, to trappe me lo&thorn;liche &dot; to drawe me to helle.  And for I was so ouer-arwh &dot; and wok of my-selue, &thorn;ei be-segede me &dot; and kene besetten:  And maden me mony a res &dot; wi&thorn; grennynde beere, fful grimme and ful grisly &dot; as wolues as hit weore; wenden in heore wyse &dot; wi&thorn; sum kunnes ginne, wi&thorn; a poynt of chekmat &dot; comen me wi&thorn;-inne; and forso&thorn;e ful neih &dot; hedde i foule fallen, bi-trapped in heore clokes &dot; and cau&yogh;t til heore preye.  And so dude I sikerly &dot; &thorn;orw my foule sunne, so fer &thorn;at I hedde &dot; be wor&thorn;i to helle, ne hedde onliche i-ben &dot; &thorn;in vnymete Merci, &thorn;at euer is so redi &dot; and &thorn;i swete grace; &thorn;at after long abode &dot; whiles I lay in sunne, and wolde not arysen &dot; for non of &thorn;i callynges, ne for &thorn;i milde wouwynges &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;enne madest, al [min] vn&thorn;onkes &dot; derwor&thorn;e lord, drouh me from myn enemy, so freoly &amp; so frendly, &thorn;at I so wrecchedly &dot; folewode so faste.  &para; &THORN;at euer beo &thorn;ou blessed &dot; in heuene and in eor&thorn;e, hei&yogh;ed and heried &dot; of al &thorn;at &thorn;ou schope! for whon &thorn;e bale was most &dot; &thorn;en was &thorn;e bote next; &thorn;e grace of &thorn;e holigost &dot; hit taylede so.  For whonne &thorn;ou se&yogh;e hit beo so &dot; &thorn;at I ne wolde arysen, ne my-self stonden &dot; a&yogh;eynes my foos, ne blenchen heore wyles, heore crokes and heore gyles, but slou&yogh; slugginde lyen &dot; slumbrinde in sunne:  &para; &THORN;enne come &thorn;ou my leof &dot; my lemmon my deore, wi&thorn; liht leytinde loue &dot; to seche me here.  &para; &THORN;ou felle for me gostly &dot; from heuene to eor&thorn;e, and ruddest me raply &dot; of al &thorn;at &thorn;er was; &yogh;if I ly&yogh;e lodly &dot; &thorn;ou reysedest me redily, and &yogh;if I fallynde was &dot; &thorn;ou breyde me a&yogh;eyn.  &para; At &thorn;e poynt of my fal &dot; whon I most dradde, &thorn;ou kuddest &thorn;e quikly &dot; to make res-


<PB N="2: 357">

cous.  And al fihte &thorn;ou &thorn;us &dot; vche day neowe, to wite me and were me &dot; in gostliche weorre.  &THORN;ou vnderfonge bodiliche &dot; for me for to fihten, here in worldliche lyf &dot; a&yogh;eynes hem alle:  &para; wi&thorn; pouert and wi&thorn; schome &dot; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e saut of &thorn;e world; wi&thorn; peyne &amp; wi&thorn; passion &dot; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e flesches lustes; wi&thorn; louhnesse and Mekenesse &dot; wi&thorn; loue and studefastnesse, a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e &thorn;ridde fo &thorn;e fend:  and al &thorn;ou ouercome.  &para; And tau&yogh;test me beo &thorn;i-self &dot; sendest me mi&yogh;te, forto weorre wi&thorn; hem &dot; in &thorn;e selue wyse, &thorn;at I ne dredde meschef:  ne recchen of worldlich wo, of seknesse bodiliche &dot; or gostlich fondynge, wrong of lu&thorn;er monnes werk &dot; or of wikked mou&thorn;es, of schome or of schendschupe &dot; wi&thorn;-oute mi gult, but euer stonde wi&thorn; &thorn;e &dot; in studefast herte, and &thorn;ole &thorn;onkyndeliche &dot; al &thorn;at &thorn;ou sendest.  For alle suche bales &dot; hose riht kennes, as witnesse&thorn; holy writ &dot; beo&thorn; toknes of blisse&mdash;&para; Iacobus:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omne gaudium existimate, fratres, cum in variis temptacionibus incideritis.</FOREIGN>  &THORN;er art &thorn;ou redilich &dot; and stondest bi-sydes: wi&thorn; alle &thorn;at be&thorn; so biset &dot; and troubled in care / or in anguisse &dot; or wandre&thorn; wawes Of &thorn;is worldly s&eacute;&eacute; &dot; seilen and faren; / &thorn;i-self steerest &thorn;e schip &dot; &amp; ledest to &thorn;e hauene Of euer-lastynde pes &dot; &thorn;er alle weoles aren, / and art in vch a such fiht &dot; in &thorn;e vanwarde, &amp; makest scheld of &thorn;i-self &dot; &thorn;i lemmon to sparen. // Now mi dere lemmon &dot; whonne hit so fare&thorn; / &thorn;at hose harde be stond &dot; haue&thorn; &thorn;e to feere, / euer wolde I fihten &dot; and seilen in care / wi&thorn; eni worldliche wo &dot; to haue &thorn;e so neere. / Euer-lastinde fiht &dot; leuer me ware, / to ben so sikerlich &dot; scheld at &thorn;i baneere, / &thorn;en after fikelynde weole &dot; for a gynge fare, / and leuen &thorn;e my lemmon &dot; my derlyng my dere.  &para; A my deore lemmon &dot; whil I &thorn;e harde cluppe, wi&thorn; loue-likynde &thorn;ou&yogh;t &dot; lastinde in herte, / al siker am I schild &dot; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;at me werren, ne &thorn;ar i dreden here res &dot; ne beo &thorn;ei neuer so smerte. / &THORN;er wol I resten &dot; and taken my truwe, &thorn;i-self stoppest my foos &dot; and makest hem to sturte, / and so me witerliche witest &dot; euer while i dwelle, of heore ferliche affrayes &dot; &thorn;at comen ouer&thorn;hwerte. // A mi swete lemmon &dot; my derlyng my deore, / hold euer my &thorn;ou&yogh;t &dot; in siht of &thorn;i chere, / &thorn;at I ne flitte &thorn;e from &dot; in fiht &thorn;at is here, / but euer schild me wi&thorn; &thorn;i-self &dot; to fiht in &thorn;i feere.  &para; Mi swetyng mi derlyng, min hony-brid mi luffyng, swettest of alle &thorn;ing:  &yogh;if me &thorn;at lastyng / of &thorn;i loue-likyng.  Do me for to serue &thorn;e, lere me forte loue &thorn;e &dot; louynde lord:  so &thorn;at onliche &thorn;i loue &dot; be al my likyng.
</P><P>A Ihesu my swete loue &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou art wondur riche, as al-weldinde lord &dot; in heuene and in eor&thorn;e:  and pore &thorn;enne &thorn;ou bi-come &dot; for me &thorn;at am so wrecched, whon &thorn;ou in &thorn;i childhod &dot; weore leyd in &thorn;e cracche; schend &thorn;ou weore and schomed &dot; of wikked mennes mou&thorn;es, fondet after wi&thorn; &thorn;e fend &dot; on fele cunne wyse, and si&thorn;en atte laste &dot; schendfuliche &amp; schomeliche, wi&thorn; strong de&thorn; &amp; pyneful &dot; hongede on &thorn;e Roode.  &para; Pore were &thorn;ou furst boren &dot; of &thorn;i leue mooder, &thorn;at mayden is and moder &dot; of &thorn;e &thorn;at art hire fader.  For in &thorn;e borwh of Bethleem &dot; ne fonde &thorn;ou no leu&thorn;e, wher in &thorn;i Bury-tyd &dot; &thorn;ou mihtest &thorn;e resten, but in a wouhles hous &dot; a-midde &thorn;e strete, &thorn;at was a symple refuit &dot; in so cold a tyme.  &THORN;er weore &thorn;ou wounden &dot; and swa&thorn;eled in Ragges, and after coldliche i-leyd &dot; in a beestes Crubbe.  So woldest &thorn;ou be conuersaunt &dot; and comuyn wi&thorn; bestes, to maken vs caytyues &dot; &thorn;at beestlich liuen


<PB N="2: 358">

heere, wi&thorn; &thorn;i-self conuersaunt &dot; in heuene-riche blisse.  &THORN;us poreliche bi-gunne &thorn;ou &dot; Ihesu my swete lemmon, for to lede &thorn;i lyf &dot; in londe for me.  // But whon &thorn;ou eldore weore &dot; &thorn;ow wox more pore.  For furst in &thorn;i childhod &dot;  &thorn;ou heddest to &thorn;i foode / &thorn;e Milk of &thorn;i mooder brest &dot; &thorn;e Maydenes pappe, and &thorn;i Moder redi &dot; euer whon &thorn;ou woldest, &amp; whon &thorn;ou sore weptest &dot; to stille &thorn;e &thorn;erwi&thorn;: &para; But whon &thorn;ou eldore was:  &thorn;ou &thorn;at alle feddest, bo&thorn;e foules in &thorn;e flyht &dot; &amp; fissches in &thorn;e flod, men &amp; alle beestes &dot; &thorn;at heere lyf leden, &thorn;oledest for defaute of mete &dot; mony hote honger, in bote of vre sunne &dot; as telle&thorn; holy writ.  &para; And &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;e heuene &dot; and al &thorn;is world wrou&yogh;test, ne heddest in al &thorn;is wyde world &dot; whon &thorn;ou scholdest dyen, wher-on &thorn;ou mi&yogh;test &dot; &thorn;in holy hed resten.  &para; But euer bi-foren heddest &thorn;ou &dot; in &yogh;ou&thorn;e and in elde, wher-wi&thorn; &thorn;ou mihtest &dot; hulen &thorn;in holy bones.  &para; But atte laste of &thorn;i lyf &dot; in &thorn;i meste neode, whon &thorn;ou for me so reu&thorn;ly &dot; heng vppon &thorn;e Roode, &thorn;er ne heddest &thorn;ou so muchel &dot; of al &thorn;is worldes wynne, wher-wi&thorn; &thorn;in holy bodi &dot; &thorn;ou mihtest inne folden.  &para; Al &thorn;us my swete lemmon &dot; pore &thorn;ou were &thorn;i-seluen, &amp; to pouert of &thorn;is world &dot; sannest &thorn;ow &thorn;e toke.  Pouert &thorn;ow louedest &dot; and pouert &thorn;ou tau&yogh;test, and treweli &thorn;ou be-hi&yogh;test &dot; &thorn;in endeles blisse / to alle &thorn;at here for &thorn;i loue &dot; pouert and pyne, Mesey[s]e and Mischeef &dot; in pacience taken.  &para; A swete lord &dot; hou scholde i ben riche / here vppon eor&thorn;e: &amp; &thorn;ou my leof so pore? . . . as &thorn;i-self weore pore &dot; for &thorn;e loue of me, for to beo riche wi&thorn; &thorn;e &dot; in &thorn;in oune blisse; ffor wi&thorn; pouert &amp; wi&thorn; wo &dot; schal me wele buggen.
</P><P>But pouert wi&thorn; menske &dot; is eth forte &thorn;olen.  (B)ut &thorn;ou lord for my loue &dot; wi&thorn; al &thorn;at ilke pouert, &thorn;ou weore schomeliche ischent &dot; reuyled and dispyset. For often men &thorn;e seiden &dot; schomeful wordes / &amp; scornful hokeres:  longe weore al to tellen.  // But [more] schome &thorn;oldest &thorn;ow &dot; &thorn;at neuer sunne wrouhtest; weore I-taken as a &thorn;eof &dot; &amp; brou&yogh;t bifore lu&thorn;er men, he&thorn;ene houndes &dot; fforte be demed of hem, &thorn;at art &thorn;i-self demere &dot; and Iuge of alle worldes.  &para; And &thorn;ou lord &thorn;at art lyf &dot; of al monkuynde, weore dempned to &thorn;e de&thorn; &dot; &amp; &thorn;at to schomeliche de&thorn;, and &thorn;e mon-quellere &dot; was to lyf i-saued; ffor alle &thorn;ei cri&yogh;ede on &thorn;e &dot; so grisliche and loude: &laquo;honge Ihesu on Roode &dot; &amp; leese out Barraban&raquo;, and was &thorn;at Baraban a &thorn;ef &dot; wor&thorn;i forte dyen, &thorn;at wi&thorn; tresun in &thorn;e Borwh &dot; hedde a mon quelled!  // But more schome &thorn;ow &thorn;oledest &dot; my sunne for to beeten, whon sunfol men so viliche &dot; in &thorn;i face spitten.  A mi swete lemmon &dot; my derlyng my deore, ho mihte more schome &thorn;olen &dot; cristen or he&thorn;en, &thorn;en &thorn;at men so lodlich &dot; in his face spitten?  and &thorn;ou in &thorn;i louesum leor &dot; &thorn;at angeles to biholden:  nare neuer folle, such schome &thorn;oledest!  &amp; al &thorn;e &thorn;hou&yogh;te menske &dot; for &thorn;e loue of me, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;test wi&thorn; &thorn;at foule spittyng &dot; wassche my soule, &amp; maken hit louelich &dot; &amp; schene in &thorn;i sihte.  For-&thorn;i &thorn;ou biddest me &dot; euer &thorn;enke &thorn;er-vppon, and seist on &thorn;is wyse:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Scito quoniam propter te mortificamur tota die; [propter te sustinui] obprobrium, operuit confusio faciem meam,</FOREIGN> &laquo;Vnderstonde, &thorn;ou seist, and &thorn;enk &dot; &thorn;at I for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e &dot; suffre schome &amp; bismare: schendful spittyng &dot; of vnwor&thorn;i men, he&thorn;ene houndes &dot; amidde my face.  And &thorn;erfore ne dred &thorn;e nou&yogh;t &dot; ffor &thorn;e loue of me, to &thorn;ole worldes schome &dot; despyt and wikked wordes Of wikked mennes mou&thorn;es &dot; wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;i gult&raquo;.  &para; And schome


<PB N="2: 359">

of alle schome &dot; soffredest &thorn;ou lord, whon &thorn;ou weore honged &dot; al mooder-naked: wi&thorn;-oute clo&thorn; or clout &dot; be-twene two &thorn;eues.  Also &thorn;ei seiden &dot; &thorn;e envyous Iewes:  &laquo;He is worse &thorn;en a &thorn;ef &dot; &amp; more schome wor&thorn;i, and &thorn;erfore hong him hei&yogh;e &dot; bi-twene hem bo&thorn;e, as he &thorn;at is heore mayster &dot; &amp; worse &thorn;en &thorn;ei&raquo;.  &para; A Ihesu my lyues loue &dot; my derwor&thorn;e lemmon, herte may to-bersten &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;eron &thorn;enke&thorn;, folliche as hit was &dot; in &thorn;i deolful de&thorn;!  &para; &THORN;ou &thorn;at art worschupet &dot; of al Monkuynde, of alle bales bote &dot; and angeles blisse:  mon for to worschupen &amp; sauen from pyne, woldest of wikked men &dot; &thorn;ole so muche schome.  &para; Men speken mony tyme &dot; of wondres &thorn;at fallen, of selcou&thorn; &thorn;inges, &thorn;at in &thorn;is world misliche &dot; ofte be-tyden:  &para; But &thorn;is was &thorn;e moste wonder &dot; &thorn;at euer bifel in eor&thorn;e, wonder ouer wondres &dot; se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;is world bigon: &thorn;at onlepi kuynde kyng &dot; coround in heuene, &thorn;at schop alle schaftes &dot; and welde&thorn; alle &thorn;ing, to worschupen his enemys &dot; wolde so mekelich, he &thorn;at is so louelich &dot; honge so schomelich, bi-twene two &thorn;eues &dot; as he were a &thorn;ef.  &para; A swete Ihesu swete leof, tech me forte loue &thorn;e &dot; so deore as &thorn;ou louedest me &dot; my deore lemmon; so &thorn;at onlich &thorn;i loue &dot; beo euer al my likyng, my mourning my longyng, wi&thorn;-outen eny endyng, amen.
</P><P>But my swete lemmon &dot; Inouh were &thorn;i pouert &dot; [&] &thorn;i muchele schome &dot; wi&thorn;-outen o&thorn;er peynes.  But &thorn;e ne &thorn;hou&yogh;te neuer Inou&yogh; &dot; for to buggen folliche &dot; my loue al enterliche &dot; whil &thorn;i lyf laste.  // A swete Ihesu Merci: what pris settest on me?  Ne was neuere vnwor&thorn;i &thorn;ing &dot; half so deore abou&yogh;t!  For al &thorn;i lyf in eor&thorn;e &dot; euer was in muche swynk &dot; for me vnwor&thorn;i wrecche, and euer &thorn;e lengor &thorn;e more; &thorn;at bifore &thorn;in endyng &dot; so harde &thorn;ou swonk, &amp; trauayledest so sore:  &thorn;at red blod &thorn;ou swatest &mdash; <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Factus est sudor eius sicut gutte sanguinis decurren[tis] in terram;</FOREIGN> ffor as seynt Luc sei&thorn; &dot; in his holy gospel: &thorn;ou weore in so strong swynk &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;i swot as blod-dropes, ron from &thorn;in holy bodi &dot; doun vppon &thorn;e ground.  &para; But what tonge may tellen &dot; what herte may &thorn;enken &dot; for serwe or for rou&thorn;e, of &thorn;at harde boffetyng, &thorn;at horlyng and defoulyng, &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;oledest schomelich: at &thorn;i furste takyng; whon &thorn;at Iudas Scariot &dot; brou&yogh;te helle-houndes, wi&thorn; treson &thorn;e to taken &dot; &amp; bringe til heore princes.  And hou heo &thorn;e bounden &dot; so egerlych &amp; so faste, &thorn;at &thorn;e blod sprong out &dot; at &thorn;e fynger nayles:  as holy halwen hit siggen &dot; &amp; writen is in boke.  And bounden &thorn;e so harde &dot; &amp; ladde &thorn;e for&thorn; ruydlich, betynde reu&thorn;lich, on Bac &amp; on scholdres: and on vch a syde.  And bi-foren &thorn;e princes, buffeteden [&thorn;e] &amp; scornden &dot; &amp; blyndfellede &thorn;yn e&yogh;en, pleieden a-Bobbe&thorn; &dot; &amp; maden &thorn;e heor fool, &amp; spitten in &thorn;i face &dot; mony tyme &amp; ofte, and maden hit so wlatsum &dot; so bleyk &amp; so blo: wi&thorn; betyng &amp; bustyng &dot; and spittyng &amp; spoutyng; wi&thorn;outen eny merci: &thorn;ei dihte &thorn;e so.  &THORN;ei grenneden vppon &thorn;e &dot; and waggeden heor heuedes &dot; and blatten out heore tonges &dot; and bonteden on &thorn;e schomeliche &dot; and maden &thorn;e &thorn;e mouwe. Si&thorn;en by-fore Pylate &dot; hou &thorn;ow weore naked &dot; bounden til a pyler &dot; and scourget so sore; so &thorn;at &thorn;ow ne mi&yogh;test &dot; none weys wrenchen: ne heore smarte lassches &dot; bi none gate blenchen.  &para; &THORN;er weore &thorn;ou for my loue &dot; wi&thorn; harde knotti scourges, swongen and beten &dot; so smart and so sore: so &thorn;at &thorn;i louely leor, &thorn;at was so briht and so cleer, was al to-fouled and I-schent, &thorn;i skin to-riuen


<PB N="2: 360">

and to-rent; &thorn;er stremed on vche syde a flood, of water and of red blod: &thorn;ow lord wi&thorn; so meke mood &dot; &thorn;oledest al heore wille.  Si&thorn;en on &thorn;in hed was set &dot; a Coroune of scharpe &thorn;ornes:  so &thorn;at after vche a &thorn;orn &dot; &thorn;e rede blod gon folwen.  &para; Si&thorn;en &yogh;it &thorn;ei beoten doun &dot; &thorn;e coroune vppon &thorn;in hed; and dresseden hit and &thorn;raste, and duden hit sitte faste, so &thorn;at &thorn;e scharpe &thorn;ornes &dot; wente in to &thorn;e brayn.  &para; Setten a reod in &thorn;in hond &dot; in stude of kynges septre, in scorn &amp; in he&thorn;ing, and maden to &thorn;e heor knelyng, and seiden &laquo;heil be &thorn;ou kyng&raquo;: and spatten in &thorn;i tee&thorn;.  And aftur al &thorn;at vileny, ne wolde &thorn;ei not be &thorn;erbi, but lu&thorn;urli &amp; falsly &dot; dempned &thorn;e to &thorn;e de&thorn;.
</P><P>A derwor&thorn;e lord &dot; what schal I nou don?  Nou mai I liue no more, for serwe and for sore: now my dere lemmon &dot; schal vnderfonge de&thorn;.  Nou mai I Murne strongly, nou mai I wepe bitterli; nou may I syke sore &dot; &amp; serwen euer-more.  // A, now me leden him for&thorn; &dot; to mount of Caluarie, to &thorn;e qualmstouwe &dot; to don him &thorn;ere o dawe.  A, my deore lemmon &dot; he bere&thorn; &thorn;e Roodetre: on his bare scholdre &dot; for &thorn;e loue of me; his bodi is so tendre &dot; his bones longe and lene: al stoupynde he go&thorn; &dot; &thorn;at del hit is to seone.  &para; A, mi swete lemmon, &thorn;e duntes &thorn;at &thorn;ei smyte &thorn;e, &thorn;e serwe &thorn;at &thorn;ei don &thorn;e!  on vche a syde &thorn;ei &thorn;reste &thorn;e &dot; for&thorn;ward vnwrestly, cri&yogh;inde hidously, to &thorn;i de&thorn; hastily; &amp; al &thorn;ou &thorn;oledest louely: for me wrecche vnwor&thorn;i.  Lord &thorn;at art almihti, &yogh;if me for &thorn;i merci &dot; muynde of &thorn;at vileny, and felyng at myn herte: &thorn;i peynes hou &thorn;ei smerte.  // A swete Ihesu leoue lyf, hou mony men nou folewe &thorn;e &dot; for to wondren on &thorn;e; &thorn;y frendes ben sori &dot; and serwhfol in herte; &thorn;i foos folwen hokerly, and lyken in heore maystri, and horlen &thorn;e lodly &dot; in al &thorn;is worldes sihte. // Allas: nou &thorn;ei han I-brou&yogh;t him &dot; &thorn;ider &thorn;er &thorn;ey wolen him slen. Now &thorn;ei casten him doun &dot; and leien him on &thorn;e cros.  Now &thorn;ei streynen out his lymes &dot; his senwes al to-bersten; his li&thorn;es breken out of Ioynt: &thorn;at non of hem may lasten.  &para; Allas my deore lemmon &dot; hou may men for reu&thorn;e, a&yogh;eyn so muchel fordede &dot; do &thorn;e al &thorn;at wo?  To &thorn;e &thorn;at art so loueli, so feir and so freoly, and &thorn;oledest so mekeli &dot; al &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolde do!  &para; A Ihesu now &thorn;e driuen &dot; &thorn;e blunte vnruide nayles: &thorn;orw &thorn;i feire hondes &dot; and &thorn;i frely feet. Nou berste&thorn; &thorn;i skin &dot; &thorn;i senwes and &thorn;i bones; min herte cleue&thorn; in my brest: for reu&thorn;e of &thorn;i mones.  &para; A Ihesu swetyng, wher is eny wepyng, wher is welle of teres, to lauen on my leores, &thorn;at I neuere bi day &dot; stunte nor be nihte, nou I seo &thorn;i feire lymes &dot; so reu&thorn;li I-dihte.  &THORN;e blood of &thorn;i woundes &dot; springes so breme, and streme&thorn; on &thorn;i white skin &dot; so reu&thorn;e to sene; &thorn;y Moder loke&thorn; &thorn;eron &dot; &thorn;at virgyne clene: hir serwe sit &thorn;e sarre &dot; &thorn;en &thorn;in as ich wene.  &para; A: now &thorn;ei setten vp &thorn;e cros &dot; &amp; setten vp &thorn;e Roode-treo, &amp; &thorn;i bodi al be-bled &dot; honge&thorn; &thorn;er-onne. &para; A: Ihesu now &thorn;ei setten &thorn;e cros &dot; in to &thorn;e morteis:  &thorn;i Ioyntes sturten out of li&thorn; &dot; &thorn;i bones al to-scateren, &thorn;i woundes ritten a-brod &dot; for-goled so wyde: lord &thorn;at &thorn;e was wo bigon &dot; in &thorn;at ilke tyde!  &para; A, my deore lemmon &dot; whon &thorn;ou heddest al bled, &thorn;ou wox al druye &dot; and gonne &thorn;hirste sore; &thorn;ei boden &thorn;e to drinken &dot; Eysel and Galle, but whon &thorn;ou tastedest &thorn;erof &dot; &thorn;ow woldest no more.  // A: my swete lemmon &dot; teken al &thorn;yn o&thorn;er wo, &thorn;ei bonteden vppon &thorn;e &dot; whon &thorn;ou heng on roode, so mylde and so meke &dot; as hit weore


<PB N="2: 361">

a lomb; lou&yogh;when &thorn;e to bisemare &dot; grennynde foule, wi&thorn; schome schakinde here hed &dot; in hoker &amp; in scorn, &para; seiden in vbbreid &dot; &laquo;lo wher he honge&thorn;, &thorn;at cou&thorn;e saue o&thorn;er men: and saue&thorn; nou&yogh;t him-seluen&raquo;.  &para; Weo: lord: vre loue is luitel wor&thorn; &dot; &thorn;at costen &thorn;e so deore, and &yogh;it vnne we hit nou&yogh;t &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou hit haue here, but folwen vr lustes &dot; in &thorn;e deueles fere, as &thorn;au&yogh; he be beter &thorn;en &thorn;ou: and more wor&thorn; were.  &para; Allas allas for reu&thorn;e &dot; &thorn;at I schal &thorn;e my lemmon, so foule seo demeynet: and myn is al &thorn;e gult; &para; al for-drawen and for-rent, bi-spit &amp; schomeliche schent, to sauen vs &thorn;er we weore: for &thorn;at was al &thorn;i cause.  &para; A Ihesu swete lemmon: hou mai I nou libben: Nou I seo &thorn;e leoue lyf &dot; &thorn;e loue of myn herte, mi derlyng my longyng, mi blesset lord my swetyng, wi&thorn; armes white and louely &dot; streyned so streytly &dot; wi&thorn;-outen eny merci &dot; naked on &thorn;e Rode: so &thorn;at men may tellen &dot; al &thorn;in holy bones.  &para; &THORN;er &thorn;ow hongedest reu&thorn;ly, so cold and so blodi; al rau and wori: is &thorn;i swete bodi.  &para; A swete Ihesu &dot; deore lemmon, nou &thorn;ou di&yogh;est for me, hongynge on Rode-tre, &amp; letest &thorn;in hed falle doun &dot; &thorn;at del hit is to se.  &thorn;e white of &thorn;in e&yogh;en &dot; is tornd upward.  &para; A Ihesu &dot; nou deske&thorn; &thorn;e sonne.  Nou &thorn;e eor&thorn;e tremble&thorn;: and &thorn;e stones bersten. Nou &thorn;e temple cleoue&thorn; &dot; for serwe of my lemmon.  Nou rysen vp &thorn;e dede, in witnesse of &thorn;i godhede: &amp; walken in Ierusalem &dot; as writen was biforen.  &para; Allas no&thorn;ing ne serwes &dot; ne no&thorn;ing ne rewes: for my deore lemmon &dot; &thorn;at pineful de&thorn; and schendful, wi&thorn;-oute sake of sunne &dot; soffred on &thorn;e cros.  &para; A mi deore lemmon, mi serwe mi blisse &dot; myn only lyues loue, &thorn;at di&yogh;edest so strong de&thorn;: for al &thorn;is worldes lyf; &thorn;e pynfolest &amp; reu&thorn;folest &dot; &thorn;at euer &thorn;olede eni bodi, or mihte dyen onne: for &thorn;e loue of me:  &para; A swete Ihesu &thorn;in ore &dot; Let me nou dyen &dot; in &thorn;i blisful armes, from al &thorn;e loue of &thorn;is world &dot; in to &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e; so &thorn;at only &thorn;i loue &dot; beo euer al my lykyng.
</P><P>But &yogh;it my derwor&thorn;e leof &dot; whon &thorn;ei hedden &thorn;e slayn &dot; al at heor wille, ne &thorn;&yogh;ou&yogh;te hem not &thorn;at Inou&yogh;, &thorn;at &thorn;ei se&yogh;e &thorn;i dede bodi &dot; so reu&thorn;li honge on Roode; ne wolde &thorn;ei not spare &thorn;e &dot; de[d] ne o-lyue, but brouhte for&thorn; Longius &dot; &thorn;at was a blynd kniht, and token him a scharp sphere &dot; to stinge &thorn;orw &thorn;in herte, so &thorn;at hit clef a-two &dot; and of &thorn;at ilke welle of lyf, &thorn;orw &thorn;at grisly wounde: runne two floodes: &para; &thorn;i Riche precious blod &dot; &thorn;at al &thorn;e world bou&yogh;te, and &thorn;at deore holy water &dot; &thorn;at al &thorn;is world wosch Of sake and of synne, &thorn;at &thorn;ei were fallen Inne: what &thorn;orw heore oune gult &dot; &amp; Adames sunne.  &para; A Ihesu swete lemmon &dot; hou kuyndeliche openest &thorn;ou me: &thorn;i derwor&thorn;e herte &dot; lyues and de&thorn;es, / fforte knowen witerli &dot; al &thorn;i loue &thorn;er-inne, and writen hit dernely &dot; in myn herte trewely, wi&thorn; trewe loue-lettres: of &thorn;in herte-blood.  &para; Wi&thorn; wronge &thorn;enne schulde I &thorn;e &dot; al myn herte wernen:  se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou hit bou&yogh;test &dot; so harde &amp; so dere:  myn herte wi&thorn; &thorn;in herte &dot; mi loue wi&thorn; &thorn;i loue, mi soule wi&thorn; al &thorn;i blisful bodi: &amp; &thorn;in holy soule!  &para; A, swete Ihesu gode leof &dot; let me be &thorn;i seruaunt, &amp; do me forte loue &thorn;e &dot; louynde lord; set as depe &thorn;i loue &dot; to brennen in myn herte: as &thorn;ou wi&thorn; &thorn;e speres ord &dot; was stongen for me; so &thorn;at onliche &thorn;i loue &dot; be euer al my lykyng, mi &yogh;erning mi longyng, swete Ihesu heuene kyng, in &thorn;ou&yogh;t and al my worching, wi&thorn;-outen eny makyng &dot; of eny o&thorn;ur mong.
</P><P>LAdi seinte Marie &dot; Moder &amp; Mayden, muche was &thorn;e serwe &dot; set at &thorn;in herte, whon &thorn;ou at &thorn;i sones de&thorn; &dot; stoode him so neih!  &THORN;ou sei&yogh; al his serwes &dot; &thorn;at


