</P><P>A swete Ihesu sweete leof &dot; my lemmon my deore lord, swettest of alle &thorn;ing &dot; my leue lyf my lyues loue: // &thorn;ou me hast defendet &dot; a&yogh;eyn myn enemys &thorn;reo, wi&thorn; al &thorn;i lyf &dot; wi&thorn; &thorn;i de&thorn;, and madest of me vnwor&thorn;i: &thorn;i lemmon and &thorn;i spous, // and brou&yogh;test me so seliliche &dot; out of &thorn;e false word, as &thorn;in owne derling &dot; to &thorn;in owne boure, &para; and as I weore &thorn;in owne brid &dot; here in to &thorn;i cage, to wone wi&thorn; &thorn;i-self &dot; in &thorn;is holy place, &thorn;at no mon of al &thorn;is word &dot; ne &thorn;ar me wi&thorn; delen: but &thorn;i-self al one &dot; &para; Ihesu my deore lemmon; where &thorn;at I may &thorn;e sen &dot; In muynde so priuely &dot; and wouwe &thorn;e so louely &dot; and cluppe &thorn;e swetely &dot; and clepe &thorn;e so redili, and as I were &thorn;i druri &dot; ay dwelle &thorn;e bi; &para; wi&thorn; a loue longyng &dot; and a stille mournyng, &thorn;at me ne schal beo lykyng &dot; in &thorn;ou&yogh;t of worldliche &thorn;ing, but in Ihesu heuene kyng, mi leue lyf mi derlyng, &thorn;at ha&thorn; me loueliche lad &dot; in to &thorn;is seli wonyng. &para; A lord blessed mote &thorn;ou be &dot; &thorn;at hast ordeynt for me &dot; bo&thorn;e mete and drinke: clo&thorn;ing and o&thorn;er &thorn;ing &dot; &amp; me ne &thorn;ar not swynke, but only tende to &thorn;e: Ihesu blessed mote &thorn;ou be.  &para; A swete Ihesu swete leof &dot; my lyues loue my swetyng, &thorn;ou hast maad me of nouht, fro &thorn;e de&thorn; &thorn;ou hast me bou&yogh;t, ffrom &thorn;e world in to &thorn;i chaumbre: leue lord &thorn;ou hast me brou&yogh;t, and more blisse &thorn;ou hast me hi&yogh;t: &thorn;en wi&thorn; herte may be &thorn;ou&yogh;t.  &para; A, swete Ihesu my deore lemmon &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;us muchel hast don for me: what may I &thorn;enke &dot; what may I speke &dot; what may I wor&thorn;ly don: for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e?  what may I &yogh;elde &thorn;e &dot; what may I &thorn;ole for &thorn;e &dot; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast &thorn;oled for me?  &para; A, mi swete spouse &dot; mi deore loue: me be-houe&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo &dot; ee&thorn; for to paye, as I wot wel &thorn;at &thorn;ou art; for a wrecche bodi and a weyk &dot; I haue heer on eor&thorn;e, &thorn;at I hedde of &thorn;i &yogh;ifte &dot; ful feir &amp; ful clene, but I haue muchel enpeyred hit &dot; and lodliche I-fuiled.  &para; But &yogh;it such as hit is, I &yogh;iue hit &thorn;e enterlyche &dot; to &thorn;i seruise: nayled and sprad faste in my roode &dot; in &thorn;is holy ordre, as &thorn;ou weore nayled for me &dot; in &thorn;in harde roode.  &para; And here wol I dwellen &dot; wi&thorn; &thorn;e my swete lemmon: and neuer-more wol I &dot; of my Roode comen, neuer whil &thorn;at I lyue: for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e;  &thorn;en wol I beo grauen &dot; heer vnder &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &dot; as &thorn;ou weore grauen for me: and on domes-day wol I rysen a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e, and wenden &thorn;enne al hom wi&thorn; &thorn;e: and wonen in &thorn;i blisse &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou grei&thorn;est nou &dot; vche day to me.  &para; A swete Ihesu leoue lyf &dot; so murie and so swete hit is &dot; forte dwellen heere, on Rode as &thorn;i fere, to &thorn;ole pyne for &thorn;i loue &dot; &thorn;at bou&yogh;test me so dere.</P><P>FOr whon I in my soule &dot; wi&thorn; al hol muynde &dot; seo &thorn;e so reu&thorn;ly &dot; hongen on Rode &dot; &thorn;i body al on blode, &thorn;i limes al to-rey&yogh;te &dot; &thorn;i Ioyntes al to-pli&yogh;te, &thorn;i woundes and &thorn;i leoue leor &dot; &thorn;at was so briht and so cleer, ben now mad so grisli &dot; and &thorn;ow lord so mekely &dot; tok hit al so louely &dot; for me &thorn;at was &thorn;in enemy: &thorn;enne fele I redili &dot; a tast wonder ferli &dot; of &thorn;i derwor&thorn;e loue &dot; &thorn;at


