h;t &dot; &thorn;enne &thorn;ou me maadest: and &thorn;at lyk &thorn;i-seluen; and for &thorn;ou madest me lord &dot; al &thorn;at I am: I am al &thorn;at I am &dot; holden to &thorn;e one.  For in &thorn;at ilke makyng: &thorn;ou madest me so clanly &dot; so feir and enterly, wi&thorn;-outen lac of eny lyme: lyk &thorn;i-self al-one, wi&thorn; al my fyue wittes &dot; resonable as angel, and &thorn;in holy angel &dot; a-signet my seruaunt, and nou&yogh;t onliche he: but also &thorn;i-seluen; and don me muchel more, &yogh;iue me wi&thorn; my cristendam &dot; al hol &thorn;i-seluen, and muchel more &thorn;en I con &dot; my-self vnderstonden.  &para; But &yogh;it &thorn;ow [&thorn;at]


<PB N="2: 365">

madest me &dot; &thorn;ou art so noble in &thorn;i-self &dot; an hondred &thorn;ousend fold &dot; and vnymete more: &thorn;en al &thorn;is world may &thorn;enken.  And also muchel as &thorn;ou art worth &dot; am I holden to &thorn;e, &thorn;at al &thorn;i-self hast &yogh;iuen to me: and madest me of nou&yogh;t. // Wherfore in &thorn;at wit &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou lord hast &yogh;iuen to me, wot I wel forso&thorn;e and seo &dot; &thorn;at I am holden &dot; fully to loue &thorn;e for me, and &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast me don &dot; muchel more monyfold &dot; &thorn;en I con seon or knowen; and &yogh;it a &thorn;ousend-fold &dot; and vnimete more &dot; am I holden for &thorn;at &thorn;ou art &dot; more &thorn;en for my-seluen.
</P><P>But swete Ihesu my lyues loue &dot; nou&yogh;t onliche madest &thorn;ou me of nou&yogh;t: But &thorn;erto, whon I was loren &thorn;orw myn oune defaute, &thorn;ou founde me and bou&yogh;test me &dot; a&yogh;eyn wi&thorn; &thorn;i blod.  But what &yogh;eue &thorn;ou for me &dot; to bugge me to blisse?  forso&thorn;e lord a deore prys: &thorn;i-self to &thorn;e de&thorn;.  &para; But swete lemmon leoue lyf &dot; of my furste makyng: am I holden to &thorn;e &dot; muchel more &thorn;en I am &dot; &amp; more &thorn;en I con &thorn;enken; and si&thorn;en of my fyndyng &dot; &amp; of my deore buggyng, &thorn;at &thorn;ou me bou&yogh;test wi&thorn; &thorn;i de&thorn; &dot; am I nou double holden.  But so muchel monyfold &dot; and vnimete more: is in &thorn;at deore buggyng &dot; &thorn;i derwor&thorn;e loue i-kud &dot; &thorn;en was in &thorn;at makyng, &thorn;at I ne wot what I may siggen &dot; ne rikene &thorn;eronne.  &para; But ouer in(!) al &thorn;is worldes wit &dot; may nempnen or &thorn;enken &dot; am I holden so fer &dot; and so muchel more: &thorn;at al &thorn;at euer may beo &thorn;ou&yogh;t &dot; al nis as riht nou&yogh;t &dot; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;at I am holden.  &para; But &yogh;it my swete derlyng &dot; my lyues loue my swetyng, not onliche madest &thorn;ou me of nou&yogh;t &dot; and after whon &thorn;at I was loren &dot; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;ou bou&yogh;test me wi&thorn; &thorn;i de&thorn; &dot; so deore vppon &thorn;e Roode: But &yogh;it ouer al &thorn;is &dot; &thorn;ou hast me trewely be-het &dot; al &thorn;i-self in blisse; &thorn;ou &thorn;at me madest so &dot; and me so deore bou&yogh;test, woldest wedde me to &thorn;e &dot; &amp; &yogh;iuen euermore &thorn;i-self &dot; al hol to be myn owne.
</P><P>A swete Ihesu my leoue lyf &dot; my lemmon my gode lord, mi swetyng my derlyng &dot; swettest ouer alle &thorn;ing: &para; what schal I nou siggen?  ffor nou am I &thorn;refold holden for to louen &thorn;e &dot; // In as muchel as I am &dot; // and &thorn;refold more &thorn;en I con &dot; // and &thorn;refold wi&thorn;-outen me&thorn; more &thorn;en in al &thorn;is world: wi&thorn; herte may beo &thorn;ou&yogh;t.  &para; On is for my makyng &dot; &para; ano&thorn;er for my buggyng, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is for my weddyng: to &thorn;e myn owne spouse.  &para; A Mi swete lemmon: what schal I nou don: &thorn;at I nam but o-fold &dot; and I-holden to &thorn;e &dot; al my-self &thorn;refold, muche more vche fold: &thorn;en herte may &thorn;enken?  &para; Nou swete Ihesu leoue lyf &dot; my derwor&thorn;e lemmon: al &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at i con &dot; onliche hit is for &thorn;e, where &thorn;at I may fynde loue: Inou&yogh; for to &yogh;eue &thorn;e. // And &thorn;au&yogh; I wuste where &dot; so muche loue to fynden: ne haue I wher to leggen hit &dot; ne wher-in to don hit.  &para; For wel I wot &thorn;e so&thorn;e &dot; &thorn;at &thorn;au&yogh; my sely herte &dot; weore widdore and largore &dot; &thorn;en is al &thorn;is wyde world: &yogh;it weore hit not suffisant &dot; half &thorn;at loue to holden, ne &thorn;e &thorn;ousend part &dot; &thorn;erof to biclosen; ffor wel I wot sikerly &dot; &thorn;at neede hit moste bersten: wi&thorn; streng&thorn;e of loue-longyng &dot; to &thorn;e my leoue lord.  &para;  Swete Ihesu my leoue lyf &dot; my lemmon so deore, ffeir swetely and freo &dot; and louely of chere, let me beo &thorn;i seruaunt &dot; and serue &thorn;e here: &thorn;at I may in &thorn;i blisse &dot; sitte &thorn;e neere.  &para; Swete Ihesu my lyues loue, &thorn;at sittest so hei&yogh;e in heuene aboue, &para; what schal I don &dot; &para; what schal I seyen &dot; &para; what schal I &thorn;enken in &thorn;i loue?  For hit is so wonder muchel &dot; wi&thorn;-outen eny bigynnynge, &thorn;at &thorn;ou me formedest


<PB N="2: 366">

furst &dot; and madest lyk &thorn;iself of nou&yogh;t; &para; and eft &yogh;it hit is so muchel in &thorn;e middel worchyng: &thorn;at wi&thorn; &thorn;i bodiliche lyf &dot; &thorn;ou hast me si&thorn;en longe I-sou&yogh;t, and wi&thorn; &thorn;i de&thorn; &thorn;at was so hard &dot; vppon &thorn;e Roode so deore bou&yogh;t; and hei&yogh;test me more monyfold: &thorn;en wi&thorn; herte may be [&thorn;]ou&yogh;t.  For al &thorn;i-self al one &dot; alweldinde lord, verrey god and so&thorn;fast mon &dot; in bodi and in soule, &thorn;ou hast me hi&yogh;t trewely &dot; forte ben myn oune, in more blisse endeles &dot; &thorn;en herte may &thorn;enken.  And tokne special &dot; bifore mony o&thorn;ure, &thorn;ow takest me of &thorn;i cortesy &dot; as &thorn;in owne druri: Drawen out of &thorn;is false world: my trichour and myn enemy, and put me her priueli &dot; to lere me louely &dot; ffor to singgen swetely &dot; in &thorn;in oune cage: so &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo al my song &dot; wi&thorn; loue-teres euer among, &thorn;at i do neuer &thorn;at wrong &dot; to maken eni o&thorn;ur mong &dot; of no worldliche &thorn;rong &dot; til tyme of myn he&thorn;en-&yogh;ong, &thorn;at I he&thorn;ene to &thorn;i-self: make my passage.</P><P>But swete Ihesu leue lyf &dot; my lyues loue mi lemmon, loue &thorn;e wol I as I con &dot; and leten for no mon.  For nou wot I what I wol don.  Si&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e &dot; is so vnymete muchel &para; &thorn;at I ne con not &thorn;enken &thorn;erof no bigynnyng &dot; for my furste makyng; &para; ne I ne con seo &thorn;erof &dot; mesure in &thorn;e middel &dot; for my middel buggyng &dot; wi&thorn; &thorn;i deore di&yogh;ing; ne I ne con &thorn;er-onne &dot; &thorn;enke non endyng &dot; for my trou&thorn;e pli&yogh;tyng &dot; &thorn;at I made at chirche-dore: whon I was a child &yogh;yng &dot; to &thorn;yn owne weddyng: &para; Swete Ihesu swete leof &dot; si&thorn;en I ne con of &thorn;i loue &dot; be-gynnyng ne endyng, forso&thorn;e swete lemmon &dot; swettest of alle &thorn;ing, a-midde &thorn;i loue I wol me don &dot; bitwene to &thorn;in armes; &para; and &thorn;ere wo I lslepen and waken, and &thorn;ere my preyers maken, mur&thorn;es in mournyng &dot; &thorn;er wol I taken, and al &thorn;is worldes lykyng &dot; for &thorn;i loue forsaken.  &para; &THORN;er wol I cluppen &amp; cussen, and swete loue-sawes ine wissen, and in a lykynde ba&thorn; &dot; ba&thorn;en of blisse, &thorn;er flowe teres of loue &dot; wi&thorn;-outen eny lisse.  &para; &THORN;er wol I souken of &thorn;i syde, &thorn;at opene&thorn; a&yogh;eyn me so wyde, wi&thorn;-outen eny fluttiyng &dot; &thorn;er wol I a-bide, as hit was opened for me &dot; so blessed be &thorn;at tyde.  &para; &THORN;er wol I lyuen and d[e]ye, bi-loken in &thorn;yn armes twey&yogh;e, and &thorn;e my lef loueliche preye, &thorn;at &thorn;ou me so wi&thorn; &thorn;i loue t[e]y&yogh;e, &thorn;at I may of &thorn;i merci wi&thorn; &thorn;i-self stei&yogh;e, to loue &thorn;i fader in siht of his ey&yogh;e.  &para; A swete Ihesu swete lef &dot; my deore herte my lyues loue, mi lyf &dot; mi de&thorn; &dot; mi blisse: ffor &thorn;ou ordeyndest me &dot; to &thorn;i deore lemmon, Bi-twene &thorn;in armes ley I me, bi-twene myn armes cluppe I &thorn;e; nou &yogh;if me felyng &dot; in &thorn;e wi&thorn;outen ending, and hold me in &thorn;i kepyng, swete Ihesu heuene kyng.  Amen. </P>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 367"><HEAD>Works wrongly attributed to R. Rolle<NOTE
ID="n11">In this category, Horstman includes miscellaneous texts assigned to Rolle by eighteenth- and nineteenth-century scholars like Thomas Tanner (<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Bibliotheca Britannico-Hibernica</FOREIGN>, 1748, p. 375), or by references in the MSS themselves.</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV2 N="MS Harley 1706" TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">The Counsels of Saint Isidore</FOREIGN><NOTE>Several versions of this text exist.  Harley 1706 records Version C, according to the Manual of the Writings in Middle English, vol. 7.</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Harl. 1706</HEAD><MILESTONE N="90a" UNIT="folio"><OPENER>These ben the gadered counsey[les] of seynte Isodre, to conferme man howe [he] schalle fle vyces and folowe vertues.
</OPENER><DIV3 TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">&para; Consyderacyon of a man hym-selfe.</HEAD><P>

O Man, knowe &thorn;i-sylfe, knowe what &thorn;ou arte, knowe &thorn;y begynnynge: whye &thorn;ou were borne, into what vse or ende &thorn;ou were goten, why &thorn;ou were maade, to what &thorn;inge in &thorn;is worlde &thorn;ou were formede.  Haue mynde of &thorn;y makynge, b[e] suche as &thorn;ou were maade, &yogh;ee suche as &thorn;i maker formede &thorn;ee, suche as &thorn;i creator ordeyned &thorn;ee.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off yuel &thorn;ou&yogh;ttys.</HEAD><P>
 Euery day ransake &thorn;in herte, euery day examyne &thorn;in herte; kepe &thorn;i soule fro synnefulle &thorn;ou&yogh;te, and lette not foule &thorn;ou&yogh;te ouer-&thorn;rowe &thorn;i mynde.  Whan a


<PB N="2: 368">

schrewed &thorn;ou&yogh;te toweche&thorn; &thorn;ee, consent not to hyt; kylle &thorn;e serpent whane he fyrste apere&thorn;, trede a-downe &thorn;e serpentys hede, &para; caste vnder foote &thorn;e bygynnynge of yuelle suggestyon or styrynge to synne, amend synne &thorn;ere w[h]ere yt is knowen.  In &thorn;e bygynnynge wi&thorn;stond a schrewde &thorn;ou&yogh;te, and &thorn;ou schalte ascape welle the remenaunte.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head"> Off chastyte.</HEAD><P>
 Be &thorn;ou not defoulyd wi&thorn; eny vnclennes, be &thorn;ou not spotted &thorn;oru&yogh;e eny luste; lete lechyrye growe no more in &thorn;e.  &para; Chastyte ioyne&thorn; a man to god, to chastyte ys byhyte &thorn;e kyngdome of heuen.  Yf &thorn;ou &yogh;ite fele the styryngges of &thorn;i flesche, yf &thorn;ou &yogh;ite be touched wi&thorn; pryckenges of &thorn;i flesshe, yf &thorn;ou &yogh;ite be styryd wi&thorn; &thorn;e suggestyon of luste, yf &thorn;e mynde of lecherye tykylle &yogh;ite &thorn;i wylle, yf &thorn;i flesshe &yogh;ite fy&yogh;te a&yogh;ens &thorn;e, yf lecherye &yogh;it tempte&thorn; &thorn;e, and yf luste &yogh;it styre&thorn; the to synne: sette byfore &thorn;ee &thorn;e mynde of dee&thorn;, putte byfore &thorn;ee &thorn;e day ofe &thorn;i dee&thorn;, sette byfore &thorn;inne y&yogh;en &thorn;e ende of &thorn;i lyf, putte byfore &thorn;ee &thorn;e streyte dome &thorn;at is to come, putte byfore &thorn;ee &thorn;e hard tormentys &thorn;at ben to come, sette byfore &thorn;ee &thorn;e euerlastynge fyer of helle, putte byfore &thorn;ee &thorn;e orryble peynes of helle.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off contynuale preyer.</HEAD><P>
 Preye wi&thorn; wepynge contynually, preye besylye, byseche god day and ny&yogh;te, morne and sorowe euer for synne.  Aryse in &thorn;e ny&yogh;te to preyer.  Lette preyer be to &thorn;e contynualle armure.  &para; &THORN;is ys &thorn;e fyrste vertu a&yogh;ens temptacyon: deuellys ben ouercome by preyer; preyer avayle&thorn; a&yogh;en alle yuellys.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off fastynge.</HEAD><P>
Chastyse &thorn;i body, by fastynge, by abstynence and by scarsnese; &thorn;ou ma[i]ste not ouercome temptacyons in her hy&yogh;e hete, but yf &thorn;ou be lerned to faste.  &THORN;oru&yogh; mete forso&thorn;e growe&thorn; luste, plente of mete styre&thorn; &thorn;e flessh to lecherye; but by fastynge luste ys restreyned, by fastynge lecherye ys ouercome.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off drynke.</HEAD><P>
Drynke forso&thorn;e ys &thorn;e instrumente of lecherye.  Fyer by castynge-to of wode encrese&thorn; more and more; &thorn;e more mater ys in &thorn;e fyer, &thorn;e more ys &thorn;e flame.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off lokynge.</HEAD><P>
Thynne y&yogh;en ben &thorn;e fyrste dartys of luste, sy&yogh;te ys desyer of woman, and woman of man; mynde ys cau&yogh;te by &thorn;e y&yogh;en.  Wi&thorn;-draw &thorn;in y&yogh;en from wantownes, set hem not in the bewte of flesshe; byholde not a woman to desyre hyr, do awey the cause of synnynge, and leue bysydes &thorn;ee &thorn;e mater of trespassynge; yf &thorn;ou wolte be sure fro lecherye, be &thorn;ou desceuered fro women, bo&thorn; in body and sy&yogh;te.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off wommen.</HEAD><P>

If &thorn;ou be departed in body from wommen, &thorn;ou schalte [falle] from &thorn;e entente of synne.  Yf &thorn;ou sytte bysydys a serpente, &thorn;ou schalte not longe be unhurte; yf &thorn;ou be longe byfore a fyre, &yogh;he alle-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou were made of yren, sume tyme &thorn;ou schuldeste melte; yf &thorn;ou abyde ry&yogh;te nye perelle, &thorn;ou schalt not longe be syker.  Ofte-tyme leyser ha&thorn; ouercome whom wylle my&yogh;te not.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off good bysynes.</HEAD><P>

Lecherye ouercome&thorn; soone a man &yogh;ouen to ydylnes, luste brenne&thorn; greuousely whom sche fynde&thorn; ydylle.  Luste &yogh;eue&thorn; place to trauele, to werke, to bysynes and to laboure.  &THORN;erfore be ware of ydylnes, lede not &thorn;i lyfe in ydylnes, spende &thorn;i body in laboure, vse sume maner of bysynes, seke vnto &thorn;e sume profytable werke where-vpon &thorn;e entent of &thorn;i soule may be sette.</P>
</DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 369"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off redynge.</HEAD><P>

&yogh;eue &thorn;e moche to redynge, take hede in medytacyon of scrypture, bysye &thorn;e in &thorn;e lawe of god; haue a customable vse in deuyne bokes.  Redynge trewely [teche]&thorn; what &thorn;ou schalt schone ..., redynge telle&thorn; whyder &thorn;ou goeste.  In redynge, wytte and vndyrstondynge encrese&thorn;.  &THORN;ou schalt moche profy&yogh;te in redynge, yf &thorn;ou do as &thorn;ou redyste.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off mekenesse.</HEAD><P>

Be &thorn;ou meke, be &thorn;ou grounded in mekenesse, [be &thorn;ou] laste and loweste of alle.  By mekenesse make &thorn;i-selfe leste, sette &thorn;i-selfe before noman, trowe &thorn;i-selfe aboue noman; a-vaunte not &thorn;i-selfe, boste not &thorn;i-selfe, enhaunce not &thorn;i-selfe wanntounly; streche not for&thorn;e &thorn;e wynges of pryde; so moche &thorn;ou schalt be &thorn;e more precyouse afore god, &thorn;at &thorn;ou setteste lytylle pryce by &thorn;i-selfe.  &para; Bere &thorn;erfore schamefastenes in chere by mynde of &thorn;i defau&yogh;ttes, for schame of &thorn;i synnes be dysmayed to loke prowedly, walke wi&thorn; a lowe chere, wi&thorn; a meke mou&thorn;e, and wi&thorn; a sad vysage.  In hy&yogh;e worschype, haue grete mekenesse; alle&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be of hy&yogh;e power, restreyne hy&yogh;nes in &thorn;i-sylfe, lete not worschype make &thorn;e prowde; &thorn;e hey&yogh;er &thorn;ou arte in dygnyte, &thorn;e lower by mekenesse &thorn;ou make &thorn;ee.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Sadnes of mynde.</HEAD><P>

Be not sory in &thorn;i dysesys, in &thorn;i sekenesse &thorn;anke &thorn;ou god.  &para; Be rather more bysy to be hoole in soule, &thorn;an in body.  If prosperytees come: be &thorn;ou not prowde; yf aduersytees falle: be &thorn;ou not heuy.  Knowe in &thorn;i-selfe &thorn;at god ha&thorn; prowued &thorn;e in sorowe for &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldeste not be prowd.  Be euen &thorn;erfor in alle &thorn;inges; for ioye ney&thorn;er for sorowe chaunge neuer &thorn;i mynde.  Vnderstonde welle &thorn;ere is no&thorn;inge but yt may falle as god wolle, and yf &thorn;ese &thorn;inges be &thorn;ou&yogh;[t]e on byfore, &thorn;ei ben &thorn;e esyer whan &thorn;ey fallen; and &thorn;erfor what-so-euer happe&thorn;, suffre yt mekely wi&thorn; fre wylle.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off paciencye.</HEAD><P>

Be more redy to suffre dysese, &thorn;en to do yt.  Be pacyent, be meke, be softe, be esy.  Kepe pacyence in alle &thorn;inges, kepe softenes, kepe mekenes.  Sette byfore a scharpe worde &thorn;e schylde of sufferaunce, and &thorn;ou&yogh; eny man sterre &thorn;e to wra&thorn;e, &thorn;ou&yogh; he whette &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou&yogh; he chyde &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou&yogh; he blame &thorn;e, &thorn;ou&yogh; he repreue &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou&yogh; he do wronge to &thorn;ee: be &thorn;ou stylle, holde &thorn;i pees, sette not &thorn;ere-by, speke not a worde &thorn;ere-a&yogh;ens; for by sylence &thorn;ou schalte &thorn;e sonner ouercome.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">(Of manhod.)</HEAD><P>

Lerne of Cryste manlynes, take hede at Cryste and be not heuy; he sufferynge wrongges lete to vs ensample.  &para; He bobbyd and buffetyd, spytte vpon and scorned, nayled honde and foote, crowened wi&thorn; &thorn;ornes, dampned to &thorn;e crose: euermore helde hys pees; ...  and so tempre &thorn;ou &thorn;i dysese by consyderacyon of ry&yogh;tewysnes&mdash;and &thorn;ou schalte suffre yt &thorn;e ly&yogh;telyer, yf &thorn;ou take hede wherefor yt come&thorn;.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off peece.</HEAD><P>

Loue peece wi&thorn;oute-for&thorn;e, loue peece wi&thorn;infor&thorn;e, kepe peece wi&thorn; alle men, wi&thorn;holde alle men in myldenesse, beclyppe charyte, proue more &thorn;i-selfe to


<PB N="2: 370">

loue &thorn;en &thorn;ou to be louyd.  Make peece &thorn;ere hate ys; haue stabylnes of mynde, haue goodnes of wylle, be redy in good desyre, speke gladly to alle men; flee chydynge, be ware of stryues, do awey &thorn;e occasyon of stryffe, dyspyse stryffe, and lyue alwey in peece; stryffe not in eny wyse.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off compassyon.</HEAD><P>

Be not glade vppon &thorn;e dee&thorn; of &thorn;in enemye, leeste perauenture vppon &thorn;e falle &thorn;e same, &yogh;he and leeste god turne hys wra&thorn;e fro hym to &thorn;ee.  Who forso &thorn;e ioye&thorn; of &thorn;e falle of hys enemye, he schalle sone falle into &thorn;e same.  &para; Be [not] glade to sorow vppon hym &thorn;at ys dy[s]esyd; in o&thorn;er mennys mysesys be not harde-hertyde, and so o&thorn;er mennys myscheefe morne as &thorn;in owne.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Folowynge of goodnesse.</HEAD><P>

In alle &thorn;i bysynes, in alle &thorn;i werkys, in alle &thorn;i lyuynge folowe good men, folowe hooly men, haue before &thorn;in y&yogh;en &thorn;e ensample of seyntys, take hede to worche welle after vertues of hooly men, lerne to lyue welle by &thorn;e techynges of ry&yogh;tewys men.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Dyspysynge of preysynge.</HEAD><P>

Dispyse &thorn;ou cheryschynge, preysynge and fauoure of peplys; stodye ra&thorn;er to be good &thorn;en to seme good; take noon hede who preyse&thorn; &thorn;ee, or who dyspyse&thorn; &thorn;ee, leste preysynge dysceyue &thorn;ee, or blamynge lete &thorn;ee.  If &thorn;ou sette not be preysynge, ly&yogh;tely &thorn;ou schalt sette bysydys &thorn;e blamynge.  &thorn;erfor suppose not &thorn;i-selfe good, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be holde goode in o&thorn;er mennys tungges; aske &thorn;in owen conscience, deme &thorn;i-selfe by &thorn;in owne dome, and not by o&thorn;er mennys speche but in &thorn;in owne mynde enscherche &thorn;i-selfe; &thorn;ere may noman knowe better what &thorn;ou arte, &thorn;en &thorn;ou &thorn;at knoweste &thorn;i-selfe; what profyte&thorn; [it] &thorn;ee, sy&thorn;en &thorn;ou arte a schrewe, to be hoolde goode?</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Honeste conuersacyon.</HEAD><P>

Flee &thorn;ou symulacyon, feyne not holynes in derke clo&thorn;inge; suche as &thorn;ou woldeste be holde in alle &thorn;i conuersacyon, suche be &thorn;ou in dede.  Schewe &thorn;y professyon in lyuynge, and not in tokenes oonly; in clo&thorn;inge and in-goynge haue wi&thorn; &thorn;e sympylnesse, in &thorn;i gate and in &thorn;i mouynge clennes, in &thorn;i berynge sadnes, in &thorn;i walkynge honeste; no&thorn;inge of vylonye, no&thorn;inge of vnclennes, no&thorn;inge of wantownes, and no&thorn;inge of wyldenes.  &para; Be ware in &thorn;i gouernaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ere apere no&thorn;inge of beestelynes.  &YOGH;eue not to o&thorn;er men cause to scorne &thorn;ee, &yogh;eue not to eny man occasyone to bacbyte &thorn;ee.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Good felowschype.</HEAD><P>

Schone yuele men, be ware of wyked men, flee schrewys, dele not wi&thorn; bro&thorn;elles; flee &thorn;e companyes of &thorn;o men ra&thorn;este whiche ben euer redy to vyces.  Ioyne &thorn;e wi&thorn; good men, desyre &thorn;e felouschyppe of dyscrete men, seke &thorn;e companyes of vertues men; for who [so] goe&thorn; wi&thorn; wyse men, he schall be wyse; and who so drawe&thorn; to folys, schalle be lyke to hem; for lyke to lyke ys woned to be ioyned.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Kepynge of &thorn;inne eres.</HEAD><P>

Schytte &thorn;in eres &thorn;at &thorn;ou here none yuele; forsake vnchaste spechys, flee vnhoneste wordys; for a vayne worde soon defoule&thorn; &thorn;e soule; and &thorn;at ys ly&yogh;tly doon [&thorn;at is] gladly herde soone.</P>
</DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 371"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Kepynge of &thorn;inne mou&thorn;e.</HEAD><P>

Lete no&thorn;inge passe &thorn;i mou&thorn;e &thorn;at my&yogh;te lette vertue.  Lete &thorn;e sowne of &thorn;i voyce breke no&thorn;inge but &thorn;at &thorn;at nedy&thorn;.  Lete &thorn;at procede of &thorn;i lyppys &thorn;at defoule&thorn; not &thorn;e erys of &thorn;e herer.  A veyne worde ys taken of a veyne conscyence; &thorn;e tunge of man schewe&thorn; hys maners, and suche as &thorn;e worde ys, suche ys &thorn;e soule, for &thorn;e mou&thorn; speky&thorn; of &thorn;e habundaunce of &thorn;e herte.  Refreyne &thorn;i tunge from veyne speche and ydyle, for an ydyle worde schalle not passe vnponysshede; who so wylle not refreyne hys tunge from ydyle wordys, he schale falle ly&yogh;tely in to synefule wordys.  Lete &thorn;i worde be wi&thorn;-owte reprefe, lete yt be profitable to the herers.  &para; Bysye &thorn;e not [to] speke &thorn;at &thorn;at lyke&thorn;, but &thorn;at &thorn;at nede&thorn;.  Take hede what &thorn;ou spekeste &amp; what &thorn;ou spekeste not, and bo&thorn;e in spekynge and not spekynge be ry&yogh;te ware.  Take good avysemente what &thorn;ou seyeste, leste &thorn;ou mayste not calle a&yogh;en &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou seydeste.  Flee &thorn;e chaunces of tunge, lete not &thorn;i tunge lese &thorn;ee.  Haue euermore scylence to &thorn;i frende; speke whan tyme ys, and be stylle whan tyme ys; speke not or &thorn;ou here, and lete askynge open &thorn;i mou&thorn;e.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Synne of bacbytynge.</HEAD><P>

Bacbyte not &thorn;e synner, but be sory for hym.  Kutte fro &thorn;i tunge the synne of bacbytynge, hurte not a no&thorn;er manys lyfe . . . .  &para; That &thorn;at &thorn;ou bacbytyste in a no&thorn;er, drede &thorn;ou &thorn;at in &thorn;i-selfe; whan &thorn;ou blameste ano&thorn;er, rep[reue] &thorn;in owen defawtys.  If &thorn;ou wolte bacbyte, &thorn;enke on &thorn;in owen synnes; byholde not o&thorn;er mennys trespasses, but inwardely by-holde &thorn;in owne; &thorn;ou schuldeste neuer bacbyte, yf &thorn;ou wolte byholde &thorn;i-selfe.  &para; Here no bacbyters, lysten not to tale-tellers; for lyche gylty ben &thorn;e bacbyters and &thorn;e herers.  Desyre not &thorn;ou to wytte &thorn;at &thorn;at perteyny&thorn; not to &thorn;ee; &thorn;o &thorn;ingges &thorn;at men speken by-twene hemselfe, bysye &thorn;e not to knowe; axe &thorn;ou neuer what eny man speke&thorn;, seye&thorn; or doe&thorn;; be not to bysye, leue suche [bysynes &thorn;at perteyne&thorn; not to &thorn;ee; by as grete] bysynes amende &thorn;in synnes, by howe myche &thorn;ou byholdyste o&thorn;er mennys.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off lyynges.</HEAD><P>

Flee bysylye alle maner of lyynge, and ney&thorn;er by hape ne be avysemente sey &thorn;ou neuer fals; ffor the mou&thorn;e &thorn;at lye&thorn;: slee&thorn; &thorn;e soule.  &THORN;erefor flee dysc[e]yte, avoyde lesynges, be ware of falsenes, speke clenly, be trewe in worde; deceyue no man in lyinge, ne brynge no man in to mys-wenynge.  &para; Speke not oo &thorn;inge &amp; doo a no&thorn;ere; sey not oo &thorn;inge and mene ano&thorn;ere.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off swerynge.</HEAD><P>
Putte from &thorn;e swerynge, doo awey &thorn;e vce of swerynge.  Vengiaunce goo&thorn; not fro &thorn;e housys of hem &thorn;at swere&thorn; myche, but schulde be fulfyllyd wi&thorn; wyckednesse.  &para; Hit ys perylouse so&thorn;ely for to swere, for ofte swerynge make&thorn; &thorn;e custome of swerynge.  Treue&thorn; nede&thorn; noon oo&thorn;e; a fey&thorn;fulle speche holde&thorn; the place of a sacramente&mdash;as who sei&thorn;: a fey&thorn;fulle worde ys as myche as alle the swerynge of &thorn;e worlde.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off a-vowe made.</HEAD><P>

Do &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste be-hote; be not ly&yogh;te in worde and harde in dede.  &THORN;ou schalte be myche gylty to god, yf &thorn;ou &yogh;eelde not &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste a-vowede; &thorn;ei dysplesen god &thorn;at fulfylen not her avowys; &thorn;ey ben a-counted amonges he&thorn;en men &thorn;at performen not her avowys.  I seye not of avowes &thorn;at ben yuelle, but good; ffor yf &thorn;ou &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;in owne folye haste made a fonned avowe, &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e doome of a dyscrete man be yt wysely turned in to good.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 372"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">To god alle &thorn;inge ys open.</HEAD>
<P>
Seye not an yuele worde in &thorn;in herte: an yuele worde may not be hydde in scilence; &thorn;at &thorn;inge &thorn;at &thorn;ou doeste or seyeste wi&thorn;-in &thorn;i-selfe, byleue &thorn;ou verely &thorn;at yt ys open be-fore god; if men ben stylle, bestes speken.  &THORN;erfor flee synne as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou my&yogh;te not kepe yt preuye, synne &thorn;ou &thorn;ere where &thorn;ou knoweste god ys not; for &thorn;ere ys no &thorn;inge hydde fro hym.  &THORN;ou schalte be funden gylty in &thorn;e iugementys of god, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be hydde to mannys iugementys; ffor he be-holde&thorn; &thorn;e herte, &thorn;at ys wi&thorn;infor&thorn;e he see&thorn;, and knowe&thorn; &thorn;at man hym-selfe knowe&thorn; not.  &para; Turne &thorn;y counceylle and &thorn;i werke euermore to god, in euery dede aske goddys helpe; arette &thorn;ou alle &thorn;inges to goddys grace and to goddys &yogh;ifte, truste not to &thorn;in owne desertys, in &thorn;in owene vertu presume &thorn;ou no&thorn;inge.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off conscience.</HEAD><P>

There may no man flee hym-selfe, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; an opene fame harme &thorn;e not, [yit] &thorn;in owne conscience dampne&thorn; &thorn;ee; ffor &thorn;ere ys no peyne gretter &thorn;en ys pryckynge of conscience.  If &thorn;ou woldeste neuer be sorye, lyue welle; a syker conscyence suffere&thorn; esylye heuynes, a good lyuer ha&thorn; euermore ioye; &thorn;e conscience of a synnefulle man ys euermore in peyne, a gylty soule ys neuermore syker; ney&thorn;er wounde nei&thorn;er dee&thorn; schalle fere &thorn;e, yf &thorn;ou lyue welle and treuely.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Hydynge of vertu.</HEAD><P>

If &thorn;ou wolte multyplye &thorn;i vertues, schewe hem not by &thorn;i wylle, [hide thi vertues] for dred of pryde and veyneglorye; flee to be seen and &thorn;an &thorn;ou deserueste mede; &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayste lese by schewynge, kepe &thorn;ou yt be hydynge.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off confession.</HEAD><P>

Schewe &thorn;e synnys of &thorn;in herte, make open &thorn;i sch[r]ewed &thorn;ou&yogh;ttes.  A synne schewed ys sone helyd; a defau&yogh;te forso&thorn;e hyde ys made more, synne doon by scylence encrese&thorn; more and more.  Truly yt behoue&thorn; more to schone yuele &thorn;en to amende yt, leste parauenture whan &thorn;ou falleste &thorn;ere-ynne, &thorn;ou mayste not avoyden yt.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Of fore-&thorn;ou&yogh;te.</HEAD><P>

By-&thorn;inke &thorn;e longe byfore &thorn;e deede, avyse [&thorn;e] longe byfore &thorn;e warke &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolte doo; encerche yt longe, proue yt longe and so do yt.  And whan &thorn;ou haste longe by-&thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;ee, do &thorn;ou &thorn;anne as &thorn;ou haste proued; in &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben certeyne of welle-doynge, tary not in puttynge -ouer tylle to &thorn;e morowe. &para; In good &thorn;inges tariynge harme&thorn;, and lette[&thorn;] &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben nedfulle.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off techynge.</HEAD><P>

Lerne &thorn;at &thorn;ou canste note, lest &thorn;ou be founden an vnprofytable techer; &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste herde, seye yt; &thorn;e good &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste lernyd, teche yt; &thorn;e more [&thorn;at it is yeuen, &thorn;e more] yt wexy&thorn;.  But [yet] lette dedys goo byfore &thorn;e worde &thorn;e whyche &thorn;ou scheweste wi&thorn; &thorn;i mou&thorn;e; ffulfylle &thorn;ou &thorn;at in warke whyche &thorn;ou techeste in wordys, in schewynge yt by ensample; ffor yf &thorn;ou teche and doo yt, &thorn;ou schalte be holden gloryous.  In &thorn;i techeynge kepe &thorn;e from mannys preysynge;


<PB N="2: 373">

so enforme o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;i-selfe, so teche &thorn;at &thorn;ou lese not &thorn;e grace of mekenesse; be ware whyle &thorn;ou reyseste o&thorn;er by techynge, &thorn;at &thorn;ou falle not &thorn;i-selfe be desyre of preysynge.  Whan &thorn;ou techeste, vse note derkenesse of wordys, sey so &thorn;at &thorn;ou mowe be vnderstonde; &thorn;e dyuersyte of personys ys to been seen; where, howe, and whom &thorn;at &thorn;ou techeste be avysed; speke comon &thorn;inges to alle men, and to fewe men schewe &thorn;at ys hyd.  Be not aschamed to speke &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou canste welle defende; &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou wanteste of kunnynge, aske of o&thorn;er men.  By kunnynge trewely schewed hyde &thorn;inges ben openned, and harde &thorn;inges ben made ly&yogh;te.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Curiosite.</HEAD><P>

Be not besy to knowe &thorn;at ys hyde, couyte note to knowe &thorn;at owe&thorn; not to be knowe.  In dysputynge do awey stryfe, do awey frowardnesse and assente sone to &thorn;e trou&thorn;e; seye not a&yogh;ens ry&yogh;tewysnesse, stryfue not to avoyde &thorn;at ys ry&yogh;te; loue more to here &thorn;an to seye, here in &thorn;e begynnynge &amp; speke &thorn;e laste of alle; &thorn;e laste speche [is] better &thorn;en &thorn;e former.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off obedience.</HEAD><P>

Worsshype euery man for &thorn;e meryte of hys holynesse, after her wor&thorn;ines &yogh;eue to eche man honoure.  Suppose not &thorn;i-selfe euyn to &thorn;i souereyn, &yogh;eue obedience to &thorn;in elders, serue to her byddyngges, bowe to her auctoryte, folowe her wylle; abeye to alle men in good byddynges; &yogh;ite so obeye &thorn;ee to man &thorn;at &thorn;ou offende note &thorn;e wylle of god.  &thorn;erfor fulfylle mekely &thorn;e charges &thorn;at &thorn;ou haste take vpon &thorn;ee, be obedyente to goddys ordynaunce, be not hardy to do a&yogh;ens hys wylle.  Dyspose alle &thorn;inges not wi&thorn; a sturdy wylle, but wi&thorn; an esye herte.  Be ware of worshippes [which &thorn;ou maist not haue withoute synne; the lightnes of worshippis] ys &thorn;e grettenes of synnes, and &thorn;e gretter &thorn;i degre ys &thorn;e gretter ys &thorn;e peyne.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head">Off souereynte.</HEAD><P>

Be besy ra&thorn;er to be loued of &thorn;i sogettys, &thorn;en to be drade; lette &thorn;i sogettys ra&thorn;er worschyppe &thorn;ee and serue &thorn;e for loue, &thorn;en for drede or nede.  Qwyte &thorn;e so to &thorn;i sogettys &thorn;at &thorn;ou be more loued &thorn;en dred.  Wi&thorn; a souereyne goodnes gouerne &thorn;i sogettys; be not feerdefulle to &thorn;i sogettys, be suche lorde to hem &thorn;at &thorn;ey may be glad to serue &thorn;e.  Bo&thorn;e in ponsshynge and in cheryschynge kepe a maner; be not to streyte, ne for&yogh;eue not to sone, but kepe maner in alle &thorn;i werke.  Hit longe&thorn; to a wyse man to mesure alle &thorn;ingges, leste of good be made yuelle.  Byholde certeynly what ys conuenyable for &thorn;e tyme, wher, whan, howe, and wherfor, &thorn;ou comaundeste eny &thorn;inge to be done; and &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldeste were doon to &thorn;ee, do &thorn;ou &thorn;at to a no&thorn;er.  Be suche to o&thorn;er men as &thorn;ou desyreste o&thorn;er men be to &thorn;ee.  &para; Hynder noman wi&thorn; &thorn;i wytnes; do noman harme, leste &thorn;ou suffre &thorn;e same.  Kepe manerlynes, kepe ry&yogh;tewysnes; defende noman a&yogh;ens trou&thorn;e; whyle &thorn;ou demeste, be he pore be he ryche, byholde &thorn;e cause and not &thorn;e persoone.  Kepe trou&thorn;e in alle &thorn;ingges; sytte &thorn;ou neuer in dome wi&thorn;oute mercy.  Be as meke in o&thorn;er mennys defau&yogh;tys as in &thorn;in owne; &para; so deme o&thorn;er men as &thorn;ou desyreste to be demed &thorn;i-selfe.  Whyle &thorn;ou arte mercyfulle in o&thorn;ere mennys gylte, &thorn;ou haste mercy on &thorn;i-selfe; the doome &thorn;at &thorn;ou putteste vpon a no&thorn;er, &thorn;ou schalte bere &thorn;i-selfe.  By what mesure &thorn;ou mesureste, yt schalle be mesured a&yogh;en to &thorn;e.  &para; Deme noman by suspecyon; fyrste prou and so deme.  In dou&yogh;tys reserue &thorn;e sentence to goddys iugemente, and at hys dome be yt demed; and &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ou welle knoweste, at &thorn;in owne dome be yt demed. </P>
</DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<PB N="2: 374"><HEAD TYPE="paragraph head"> Dyspyte of the worlde.</HEAD><P>

Ife &thorn;ou wolt be in reste, desyre no&thorn;inge of &thorn;e worlde; &thorn;ou schalt haue reste of soule yf &thorn;ou putte fro &thorn;e &thorn;e bysynes of &thorn;e worlde.  Caste fro &thorn;e alle &thorn;at may lette &thorn;e fro good purpose.  Be mesured to the worlde, and &thorn;e worlde to &thorn;e.  As &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou were dede, byholde not the glorye of &thorn;e worlde; sette not by &thorn;at, whyle &thorn;ou lyueste, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayste not haue whan &thorn;ou arte dedde.  What-so-euer &thorn;ou &yogh;eueste, &yogh;eue yt wi&thorn; good wylle; do mercy wi&thorn;oute &yogh;ifte, &yogh;eue almes wi&thorn;oute heuynes; &thorn;e good wylle is more &thorn;en &thorn;e &thorn;inge &thorn;at is &yogh;euen.  &THORN;at &thorn;at ys &yogh;euen wi&thorn; good wylle, &thorn;at god accepte&thorn;; but he &thorn;at &yogh;eue&thorn; wi&thorn; heuynes, schalle leese hys mede; &thorn;ere ys no mercy wher ys no good wylle.  Doo no&thorn;inge for preysynge, no&thorn;inge for worldly opynyon, but oonly for lyffe euerlastynge.  Amen.
</P></DIV3><TRAILER>These ben &thorn;e counselles of seynte Ysodore, whiche ben good and holsume, yf &thorn;ere be hade in &thorn;e reders and louers of hem wylfulle execucyon.</TRAILER>
</DIV2><DIV2 N="MS Harley 1706" TYPE="text">
