<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Harl. 1706</HEAD><MILESTONE N="142b" UNIT="folio"><OPENER><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Augustinus de contemptu mundi.</FOREIGN>
</OPENER><P>Iffe &thorn;ou sey to me &laquo;&thorn;is ys an harde worde whiche &thorn;ou spekeste; who may forsake &thorn;e worlde as &thorn;ou seyeste and hate hys flesshe?  I seye &thorn;e forso&thorn;e I may not so doo&raquo;: &para; To hym &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;is mocyon or &thorn;is consyderacyon, seynte Augusten answere&thorn; to hym &thorn;us and sei&thorn;: &laquo;My frende, I prey &thorn;e telle &thorn;ou me where ben nowe &thorn;e louers of &thorn;e worlde, whiche weren wi&thorn; vs here but a whyle a-goo?  &THORN;ere ys nowe nou&yogh;te lefte of hem but asshes and wormes.  Byholde bysyly in &thorn;i mynde and se a-ferre wi&thorn; &thorn;i gostely y&yogh;en, what &thorn;ey weren sumtyme, and what &thorn;ey ben nowe in tyme presente.  Forso&thorn;e men and wommen &thorn;ey weren as we be nowe; &thorn;ey eten, &thorn;ey drunken and made hem merye, and lede alle her dayes in lustys and lykyngges after &thorn;e wylle of her concupyscence, and wolde not be a&yogh;ene-seyde, but leften vtterly &thorn;e wylle of god.  &THORN;ese peplys a lytyle whyle floryschydden in her lustys, and in a poynte &thorn;ei fellen doune to helle.  A, what profytyde to hem her veyne worschyppe and a schorte gladnes, &thorn;e pryde of &thorn;e worlde, &thorn;e luste of her flesshe, and false rychesse, a grete meyne, and yuelle coueytyse?  Where ys nowe her loude lau&yogh;ynge?  where ys nowe [her] grete braggynge and al[l]e her bostynge?  Of her gladnes ys nowe made grette heuynes, after a grette luste sue&thorn; a fulle greuous ferdefulle peyne wi&thorn; alle vntellable wyckednes.  &para; And what-so-euer ha&thorn; fallen to hem, &thorn;e same may falle to &thorn;e, for &thorn;ou arte a man as &thorn;ey were, &yogh;ee a man made of cley-molde.  Of &thorn;e er&thorn;e &thorn;ou arte, and of the er&thorn;e &thorn;ou lyueste; forso&thorn;e and in to er&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt turne&raquo;.  &THORN;is sentence sei&thorn; seynte Austyne.
</P><P>Whye ys &thorn;e worlde byloued &thorn;at ys fals and veyne, sy&thorn;en &thorn;at hys wel&thorn;is been vncerteyne?</P><P>Also soone slydi&thorn; hys power away: as do&thorn;e a brokele potte &thorn;at fresshe ys and gay.</P><P>Truste &yogh;e ra&thorn;er to letters wrytten in yis: &thorn;an to &thorn;e wrecched worlde &thorn;at fulle of synne ys.</P>
<PB
N="2: 375"><P>Hyt ys fals in hys byheste and ry&yogh;te deceyueable, yt ha&thorn; bygyled manye men, yt ys so vnstable.</P><P>Hyt ys ra&thorn;er to byleue &thorn;e wagerynge of &thorn;e wynde: &thorn;en &thorn;e chaungeable worlde &thorn;at make&thorn; men so blynde.</P><P>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou slepe ei&thorn;er wake &thorn;ou schalte fynde yt fals, bo&thorn;e in hys bysynessys and in hys lustys als.</P><P>Telle me where ys Salamon, sumtyme a kynge ryche?  or Sampson in hys streng&thorn;e, to whom was no man lyche?</P><P>Or &thorn;e fayre man Absolon, meruelous of chere?  or &thorn;e duke Ionatas, a welle-beloued feere?</P><P>Where ys bycome Cesar &thorn;at lorde was of alle?  or &thorn;e ryche man clo&thorn;ed in purpur and in palle?</P><P>Telle me where Tullyus ys, in eloquence so swete?  or Arystotel &thorn;e fylosofre wi&thorn; hys wytte so grette?</P><P>Where ben &thorn;ese wor&thorn;i &thorn;at weren here-byforen, bo&thorn;e kyngges and bysshopes? her power ys alle lorn.</P><P>Alle &thorn;eys prynces wi&thorn; her power so hy&yogh;e, ben vanysched awey nowe in twynkelynge of an yee.</P><P>The ioye of thys wrecched worlde ys a schorte feeste, yt ys lykened to a schadewe &thorn;at may not longe laste:</P><P>And &yogh;it yt drawe&thorn; man from heuenes ryche blyse, and ofte-tyme make&thorn; hym to synne and doo amys.</P><P>Calle no&thorn;inge &thorn;in owne &thorn;ere-fore &thorn;at &thorn;ou mayste here leese, for &thorn;at &thorn;e worlde ha&thorn; lente &thorn;ee, efte he wolle yt cese.</P><P>Sette &thorn;in herte in heuene aboue and &thorn;enke what ioye ys &thorn;ere, and &thorn;us to dyspyse &thorn;e worlde y reede &thorn;at &thorn;ou leere.</P><P>Thou &thorn;at arte but wormes mete, powdre and duste, to enhaunce &thorn;i-selfe in pryde sette not &thorn;i luste,</P><P>For &thorn;ou woste not to-day &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalte lyue to-morowe; &thorn;erfore do &thorn;ou welle, and &thorn;an schalt &thorn;ou not sorowe.</P><P>It were fulle ioyfulle and swete, lordshipe to haue, yf so &thorn;at lordshype my&yogh;te a man from de&thorn;e saue;</P><P>But for as myche as a man muste deye at &thorn;e laste, yt ys no worschype but a charge lordschype to taste.</P>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main">IX Poyntys</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Harley 1706</HEAD> <OPENER>A man &thorn;at wylne&thorn; for to profy&yogh;te in &thorn;e wey of perfeccyon and souereynly to plese god, he muste bysylye studye to haue &thorn;e maters of &thorn;ise .IX. poyntys in hys herte &thorn;at folowe&thorn; after:</OPENER><P>Fyrste by&thorn;enke &thorn;e howe &thorn;ou my&yogh;te holde &thorn;i-selfe wrechyde, foule, and vnwor&thorn;i to eny benefyce of god, &para; Also studye howe &thorn;ou my&yogh;te dysplese &thorn;i-selfe, and desyre to plese god aloone.  &para; Also desyre &thorn;ou not to be holden good &amp; meke, holy and vertuouse, but desyre &thorn;ou to be holde suche of o&thorn;ere as &thorn;e &thorn;inke&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ou art to &thorn;i-sylfe; and of &thorn;is knowe &thorn;ou &thorn;e grette goodnes of almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;at alle-be-hyt &thorn;at man ys so vnwor&thorn;i and freyle for to synne and for to offende god, &yogh;ite he wolle vouchesafe for to [take] man to hys seruaunte, and desyere&thorn; man to be hys chylde: and &thorn;erfor holde &thorn;ou not myche &thorn;at


<PB N="2: 376">

&thorn;ou serueste god, but holde yt a souereyn goodnes of god &thorn;at he wolle brynge &thorn;e to very meekenes of herte, and &thorn;at ys &thorn;e bygynnynge of perfeccyon &amp; of goodnes of man.     The .ii. poynte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not sory ney&thorn;er mys-payed wi&thorn; no&thorn;inge &thorn;at falle&thorn;, but for synne oonly ey&thorn;er for &thorn;inge &thorn;at ledy&thorn; to synne: But of alle maner tribulacyon and wronge, dyseses and dyspytys, study for to be glaade, and hem &thorn;at dysesen &thorn;e studye for to loue specyallye, and for hem prey to god inwardely, and of alle maner tribulacyon and woes &thorn;anke god lowely and freendly&mdash;for certys &thorn;o &thorn;at god loue&thorn; he bete&thorn; hem and chastyse&thorn; by woo of &thorn;e worlde, &thorn;e which wo and dysese make&thorn; man to turne to god and hate of &thorn;e worldys condycyons.  And &thorn;is medytacyon make&thorn; a man pacyent, and wi&thorn; eese of herte to suffre anguysch and woo for goddys loue, &thorn;at suffred alle maner woo for &thorn;e loue of man.     The iiide poynte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou studye for to loue pouerte, mekenesse and symplenesse, and for to conforme &thorn;i lyuynge to Crystys lyuynge &thorn;i lorde, and of worldly goodys haue not ouer-moche bysynesse, ne couetyse but &thorn;ereto &thorn;at &thorn;e nede&thorn; to &thorn;e sustynaunce of &thorn;i body.  And by&thorn;enke &thorn;e welle and ofte &thorn;at &thorn;e more ryche and worschypfulle &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte: &thorn;e more vnlyche &thorn;ou arte to Cryste &thorn;i lord in lyuynge, and so myche more mater &thorn;ou haste of sorowe.  And &thorn;erfor yf &thorn;ou wolte lyfe withe Cryste in blys, folowe hym in lyuynge and conforme &thorn;i lyffe to hys.     The iiiithe poynte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou dyspyse no creature seme he neuer so yuele, synnefulle and vnwor&thorn;i or symple, but haue rewe, pytee and compassyon of alle as a moder wolde haue of her chylde.  &para; And &thorn;enke and holde &thorn;at &thorn;e dysese and mysese of &thorn;in euyncrysten ys &thorn;i dysese; &para; And as &thorn;ou woldeste ese &thorn;i-selfe, or ellys as &thorn;ou woldeste &thorn;at he esyd &thorn;e in &thorn;i dysese, so be aboute to esyn hym.     The .V.the poynte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou deme no man ne no womman, for &thorn;ou wooste not what &thorn;e grace of god worche&thorn; in hys soule; but whan &thorn;e seme&thorn; by eny worde or dede &thorn;at eny man or womman ys falle into synne, be more sory for hys synne &thorn;en for eny bodyly myschefe &thorn;at my&yogh;te falle to &thorn;e, and &thorn;enke inwardly &thorn;at more precyouse ys &thorn;at soule &thorn;at ys wownded wi&thorn; synne, &thorn;en be alle &thorn;e er&thorn;ely bodyes &thorn;at Cryste ha&thorn; made.  &para; And &thorn;erfor a man skylfully schulde be more sorye whan he wyste hys euencrysten falle in to a deedly synne, &thorn;an he schulde for bodyly de&thorn;e of hym-selfe or of enye frende of hys, for god ys more myspayde wi&thorn; gostly dee&thorn;e of soule, wiche make&thorn; a man to be departed from hym and from hys blysfule ende, &thorn;en for bodely dee&thorn; of eny man or womman.  The .VI.te poynte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou loue &thorn;e go[o]d and &thorn;e profyte and &thorn;e worschype and preysynge of &thorn;in euyncrysten as myche as of &thorn;i-selfe, and as &thorn;e moder ys glade of &thorn;e profyte of her chylde, so be &thorn;ou glade of &thorn;e good and profyte of &thorn;in euyncrysten, and namly of gostly goodys and profyte.  The .VII.the poynte ys &thorn;at &thorn;ou loue man ney&thorn;er womman ne eny o&thorn;er &thorn;inge but oonly for god, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou loue god for hym-selfe, and alle o&thorn;er &thorn;inge for god; for god wole haue no&thorn;inge euen loued wi&thorn; hym; for &thorn;e loue of god where euer yt be, ey&thorn;er yt ys aloone ey&thorn;er yt ys souereyne.     The .VIII. poynte ys, what-euer &thorn;ou doo &thorn;at &thorn;ou studye to haue god specyally in &thorn;i mynde, &amp; in alle &thorn;i werkys princypally desyre the worschyppe of god and &thorn;e profyt of &thorn;in euencrysten.  And in alle &thorn;ingys and werkes bysyly be aboute for to haue god present in &thorn;i mynde and in &thorn;in herte as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou sy&yogh;e hym present wi&thorn; &thorn;i bodyly y&yogh;e, and so drede hym and reuerence hym and loue hym as he were euermore in &thorn;i sy&yogh;te; for goddys seruaunte schulde neuermore &thorn;enke ne speke ne do but as he wolde do in &thorn;e presens of god.  For certeynly al &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;enkeste, spekeste or doeste, god see&thorn; yt as verely as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou were in hys presence, &thorn;ere as he sytty&thorn; in heuene.  And for goddys loue take hede, yf &thorn;ou arte a-schamed for to do a deedly synne byfore &thorn;in euyncrysten &thorn;e whiche ben freyle &amp; synfulle as &thorn;ou arte and may not greue but &thorn;i body, moche more schuldeste &thorn;ou be agaste to synne byfore &thorn;i god &thorn;at neuer trespased and schalle be &thorn;i domysman at &thorn;e day of dome.     The .IX. poynte ys &thorn;at incaas &thorn;ou


<PB N="2: 377">

my&yogh;tteste come to &thorn;e perfeccyon of t[h]ys poyntys, &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowe welle &thorn;at yt ys a grette grace of goddys goodnes &thorn;at he wolle vochesafe to &yogh;eue &thorn;e so myche grace and perfeccyon.  &para; Neuer&thorn;eles ofte by&thorn;enke &thorn;e of o&thorn;er manye benefetys of god: how he ha&thorn; worschyppyd &thorn;i soule by inpryntynge of hys owne ymage, and howe he ha&thorn; graunted to be &thorn;i foode in &thorn;is lyfe, and wolle be &thorn;i ioye and &thorn;i blysse in a no&thorn;er lyffe.  &para; And for encheson &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;te not see hym in hys godhede whylys &thorn;ou arte in &thorn;is worlde, &thorn;erfore ofte byholde hym in hys manhede, hongynge for &thorn;e vpon &thorn;e crosse, And haue sorowe and compassyon of hym as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou haddeste and sufferdyste alle hys woundys and peynes in &thorn;i body, and be inwardely sory &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;te not feele in &thorn;i body &thorn;e peynes &thorn;at he suffred for &thorn;ee, synfulle wrecche.  &para; &THORN;ese poyntys haue ofte in &thorn;i mynde, and specyally whan &thorn;ou seeste &thorn;e holy sacramente of Crystys body at &thorn;e masse or on &thorn;e auter; And &thorn;an sey in &thorn;is maner: &para; &laquo;Lorde Ihesu Cryste &thorn;at arte breede of lyffe, &thorn;at camste oute of heuene to fede me an[d] to fulfylle me wi&thorn; &thorn;ee, so graunte me &thorn;at y haue noon hunger after eny &thorn;inge but oonly after &thorn;ee, And so make me druncke wi&thorn; &thorn;i blood and of &thorn;i loue &thorn;at y be not a-&thorn;urste but after &thorn;ee; lord holde so faste my soule and my loue to &thorn;ee, &thorn;at for noon o&thorn;er loue ne for synne y neuer be departed from &thorn;e.  Amen&raquo;.
</P><P>Man byholde byfore &thorn;ee howe &thorn;i lyffe waste&thorn; . . . .  Man byholde on &thorn;i ry&yogh;te syde howe &thorn;e worlde &thorn;e bygyle&thorn;, Man byholde on &thorn;i lyf[t] syde howe &thorn;e feende &thorn;e fyle&thorn;.  Man byholde byne&thorn;e &thorn;ee &thorn;e peyne &thorn;at ende&thorn; neuer, O man byholde aboue to &thorn;at ioye &thorn;at laste&thorn; euer.
</P> </DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main"> <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Meditacio S. Augustini.</FOREIGN><NOTE
ID="n14">As Horstman notes, the text "is a free translation of a Latin piece wrongly ascribed to St. Augustine (beg. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere &amp;c., Credimus quod hanc oracionem spiritus sanctus dictavit &amp;c.</FOREIGN>)...."</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Harl. 1706</HEAD><MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio">
<OPENER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Meditacio Sancti Augustini.</FOREIGN></OPENER> <P>SEynt Austyne the holy doctour techeth thorough declaracion of holy wryte that the synfulle mane for noo synne falle in despeyre; ffor more ys the mercy of gode to mane thane any mannes synne, yef mane wolle forsake hys synne and be sory theroff and turne no more ayene; for mannes synnes may be nombred or tolde, but the mercy of gode may nomane telle, for mercy ouercometh synne be hit neuer so grete; and therfor seyde Dauyde the prophete forthynkyng hys synnes: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus secundum magnam misericordiam tuam,</FOREIGN> &para; &laquo;Haue mercy one me, almyghty gode, for thy grete mercy, and for the mekelheede off thy[n] endeles mercy do awey my wyckednes&raquo;.  Hit ys trewe that the holy gost thys prayer made, thorough whos steryng synfulle mane ys prycked with a bytter sorow of hys synne, and yeff he [be] feythfulle with a sely hoope he seketh one gode as he that knoweth hym-self gylty, and with a grete drede as a nedeffulle wrecche he falleth doune and cryeth to hys gode and beseketh [hym] for the mekelheede of hys endeles mercy haue mercy vpone hyme and for hys moche pyte foryeue hyme hys synnes.  &para; Thys ys the offyce off the holy gost to stere the synffulle thus to forthynke hys synne, and to doo the werkis that most may pay hys lorde, as he that hath nede of helpe for to haue off hyme that alle goodnes and grace lyeth in; for that noone may do thys thorow no myghte of hym-selfe but thorough grete steryng before of


<PB N="2: 378">

the holygost that oonly vysyteth whane so he wolle with bytternes and loue of hys holy grace, and maketh the synffulle to ryse fro derkenesse of syne and rewffull[y] to crye to hyme that ouer alle myghtis may and with these wordys dolfully say: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus,</FOREIGN> &para; Haue mercy one me gode.  With thys prayere Dauyde cryede one gode, that prophete was and kyng, and knew that he hade synnede and was gylty to gode in .III. heede-synnes: of spousebreche, of manslawghter, and tresone.  These the holygost let wryte in bookis, nat that the lytelle shulde be welle payde that the grete dyde amys, but that the fallyng off the grete be drede to the smale; thys ys nat wretyne in ensample to falle in to syne, but, yeff mane be fallene, with contrycione and penaunce ryse owte off hys synne, and worschyp heme that be[n] nat fallene, and lere to heme that bene fallene; with a trysty hope besechyng almyghty gode, seying or crying with this holy prophete: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus:</FOREIGN> &para; Almyghty gode, for thy endeles mercy haue mercy one me.  The synfulle mane that knoweth hyme-selfe gylty in many lothely and horryble synnes, and that he shalle come to a dredefulle dome, he knoweth the domesmane so wytty that noone may hyme begyle, so ryghtfulle that hyme behoueth to doo ryghte, so myghtfulle and stronge that nomane may hyme withstande, so pryuey that nothyng may be hydde &mdash;for alle thyng he seeth, and alle thyng to hyme ys knowene; the synffulle mane thane seeth that there ys noo helpe ne defence in noo[n] other mane but nedys hym behoueth to come before the domysmane and of hyme be demed, and with a dredeffulle and a sorowfulle herte fleeth to mercy and falleth doune, and as [he] that ys fulle of alle sorowes cryeth after helpe to hyme frome [whom] alle helpe cometh, seying these wordys that the holy [gost] wryteth [in &thorn;e] hertys of hem that shalle be sauyde: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus.</FOREIGN>  &para; A, what vertu and powere bene in these wordys that the synffulle with thus to gode prayeth with a fulle tryste that he may and wylle and [can] helpe, that of hyr grete sekenes wolde fayne be hoole for drede off the dethe that hit wolle brynge heme to, and therfor in these wordys the synfulle mane seyeth: &para; &laquo;O lorde, I knowe me synfulle and graunte me gylty to the, I knowe what I haue done and what I haue seruyde, and [that] to thy dome me behoueth bowe and come, and ther off alle my lyfe yelde a strayte accounte, and suffer ther alle that that thoue wylt to me doo.  My synnes I wolde fro the hyde, but thow heme alle knowest; I wolde withstande the yff I myghte, but ouer alle my myghtes thoue mayst; wheder so I go or what so I do, alle thou beholdest.  Forthy I se no better to doo in harde stresse but fle fro the vne-to thee, that ys, fro thy wretthe I flee that fereth me owte off wytte, and vn-to thy endeles mercy that alle helpeth fully I take me, ande thys I hope be best.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus,</FOREIGN> &para; Mercyffulle lorde, helpe me of my synnes and brynge me to thy grace: so seyne they that goode bene, and so seyne they that clene bene, and so seyne they [that thi] frendys bene, that pe[y]neth hem or besyeth heme nyghte and day how they may plese the and do thy wylle; &para; and so seyne thy chyldrene and thyne heyres, lorde gode.  I [&thorn;at] am so vnclene and so fowlede, that outtakyng ame of [alle], that forsakyne haue my fader and solde me to the fende folyly for a stynkyng lust of the flessh that sone shalle rote and passe awey; for, welawey the whyle, owtlawede I am fro my faderes reame, that lost haue alle the goodys that gode me hat[h] lent, and wasted hem so in lusty lyfe and many other synnes that noughte now with me ys lafte but forthynkyng ande ferdnes of endeles peyne: wherfor I dare nat calle hym my fader ne my lorde, ne nat elles dar I sey but: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus,</FOREIGN> Lorde gode haue mercy one me; <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Et fac me vnum ex mercenariis tuis, quia non sum dignus vocari seruus tuus,</FOREIGN> &para; and make me on of thy hyrede mene yeff hit be thy wylle, fo[r] vnworthy I am, sothely I hit knowe, to be callede thy seruaunt, or thy chylde.  And therfor, lorde fulle of mercy and of pyte, haue mercy one me yef hit be thy wylle.  &para; I knowe that thou art al myghtfulle, and what thou wolt so behoueth [it] be, for thy prophete thus wytnesseth by the there he seyth thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnia quecumque voluit dominus fecit, in celo et in terra,</FOREIGN> &para; Lord, alle thyng that thou wylt ys done, in heuene and in erthe, and yet in helle and in alle other places.  And I


<PB N="2: 379">

knowe lorde, and sothely I wote, that thou wolt [nat] the dethe of the synfulle, as thou seyst thy-sylfe thorough the prophete: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nolo mortem peccatoris, sed ut magis conuertatur et viuat,</FOREIGN> &para; I wol nat the deth of the synfulle; but thow wolt that the synfulle turne fro hys synne and lyue thorough thy grace.  &para; And lorde, sythene thou art alle trewe and may nat contrary thy[n] owne wordis that seyth thow wolt helpe me oute of syne, that I may lyue with the in ioye; and lorde, I wote welle thy mercy ys moche more then my synnes or alle the mennys synnes vpone erthe, for alle the erthe ys fulle of mercy as the prophete seyeth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Misericordia domini plena est terra</FOREIGN> &mdash;&para; and therfore Dauid the prophete of alle hys synnes that were many and grete, thorough grace hade knowyng of thy mercy that was so moche, and to the comfortyng of alle synfulle mene that wol forsake her syne he seyth the mercy of gode he shalle haue withoutene ende: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Misericordias domini in eternum cantabo;</FOREIGN> &para; and lorde, thorough a nother [prophete] thou seydest: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In quacunque [hora] peccator conuersus fuerit et gemuerit, omnia peccata eius in obliuione erunt coram deo,</FOREIGN> &para; That in what oure so a synffulle mane were turned fro hys synnes [and be full sory for his synnes], alle hys synnes shalle be forye[t]ene before gode: And therfor, lorde, feythfully I trow that thou wolt doo fully alle thyngis that thou seyst, syth thow art alle trewthe that may nat fayle by no wey; synfulle as I ame, fully to thy grete mercy I me take, forthynkyng for alle my synnes that I haue done ayenst thy wylle.  And also lorde, by olde tyme thow seydest [thow woldest come] opynly to make thy peple [safe] of hyr synnes: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Deus noster manifeste ueniet, vt saluum faciat populum suum a peccatis eorum.</FOREIGN>  &para; Lorde, [for] thy wylle was euer to haue mercy on the synffulle mane, lorde thou come in to thys worlde, as in the gospelle thy-selfe wytnessest where he thus seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non veni vocare iustos sed peccatores ad penitenciam,</FOREIGN> &para; I come nat to clepe ryghtwysemene but synfulle vnto penaunce.  &para; Therfor, lorde, for thy endeles mercy graunt me thorough thy grace suche penaunce for my synnes, to do that that most may please the and [ys] most helfulle for my synnes.  And that hath, lorde, ben euere thy werke to make ryghtwyse of hem that bene synfulle, to shap worthy of vnworthy, and to reyse Abrahame ys chyldrene of harde stones, and reyse tho that fallene bene, and helpe tho that syke bene; for they that bene hole han no nede of leche, but they that ben syke, as thou seyst thy-selfe: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non egent qui sani sunt medico, sed qui male habent.</FOREIGN>  &para; Off whyche sykenesse I may [pleyne] most of alle other, that of longe tyme haue rootyde in sykenesse of synne and as a sory wrecche peyned to the dethe.  Thys sekenesse that I me off compleyne, that many one hath pyned, made the to come fro heuyne to erthe, to brynge oute of sykenes tho that sore were pyned with yuelle; of whych nombre I ame one that most ys syke, for-thy lorde thy mercy, yeff hit be thy wylle, that to synffulle mane euer hast bene redy, as the prophete seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Misericordia autem domini ab eterno et vsque in eternum super timentes eum,</FOREIGN> &para; Sothely the mercy of gode fro the begynnyng was, and shalle be with-outene ende, vpone tho that drede hyme.  Therfore, lorde, wrecchede as I ame with a grete drede, as he that moche hath trespassede ayene the wylle of hys lorde, but for the grete goodnesse and pyte that I here telle of the that foryeuest alle, be her trespasse neuer so grete, that asketh the foryeuenesse, with a trusty hope, as I dare [I] clepe vn-to the: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei deus,</FOREIGN> &para; Haue mercy on me almyghty god, and for [the] mekylnes of thy mercy do awey my synnes, and wasshe me clene yef hit be [thy] wylle.  And, lorde, syth thou woldest thy[n] enemyes, that euer withstode the and were ayenst the, drawe hem to the with harde peynes and with thy precyous bloode hele heme of her synnes: whether thou wolt lese me, or suffre me fro the passe, that haue so moche nede, and so rufully cryed after helpe?  But sothely, lorde, I trust on thy goodnes and knowe hit so moche that hit may nat so be and I durst sey as I thynke, for grete lykyng hit ys to the to rewe on the synfulle mane and haue mercy one hyme whene he wolde leue hys syne and amende hyme; for haddest thou [nat] hade grete lykyng the synfulle to amende thorow thy mercy and thy grete pyte, thow woldest nat haue suffred


<PB N="2: 380">

so harde peynes, [betyn] with scorges that alle thy body was with noo[n] hoolle place, nayled feete and handys to the roode-[tree], alle to-drawe with roopys that the synewes [of] the body brostyne, woundyde in to the herte with a sharpe spere; and suffrede one the crosse an horryble deth; and thus woldest [thow] nat suffre, haddest thou nat hade lykyng one the synfulle mane to haue hade mercy one mankynde.  &para; Therfor, lorde, for the grete loue thow haddest to mankynde, haue mercy, haue mercy apone me; lorde, sythene thou graunted to a legyone of fendys that askede the with thy leue to entre into a drove of swyne to graunt heme here askyng, with better wylle lorde I knowe hit thou wylt graunte to thy pore creature and frende, that thou madest lyke to thy-selfe, that prayer to the of mercy [to] graunte hyme [that] with syghyngis and sorowfulle herte asketh foryeuenesse of hys synnes that he hath doone ayenst thy wylle, and resceue hyme in to thy grace to be oon of thyne.  Lorde, alle the bookis that we redyne in holy chyrche, of thy mercy vs tellyne how thou vs louest, and of thy grete pyte that so redy ys to alle the synfulle that wolde hit aske or seke: &para; Whether thow shalt nat saue me as thou other hast sauyde that her synnes forthynkene? lorde, shulde the condyte of mercy that alle resceyueth and gladeth that soore repenteth heme of her mysdedys, shal(!) become drye oonly for me?  And for the grete hope that in the ys thorough the whyche alle manere of folke bene sauyde: &para; allas why shulde hit peryssh in me? whethere thow wolt be so harde to me, that alle mene prechene so large to alle that nede hathe?  Yeff I haue noone?  Who ys syke yeff I am hoole, who hath nede of [mercy but I? who hath nede of] comforte but I?  And therfor <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">O pater misericordiarum et deus tocius consolacionis, qui consolaris nos in omni tribulacione nostra,</FOREIGN> &para; O fader of alle mercy and gode of alle comforte, that comforteth vs in alle oure trybulacion: haue mercy one me, and brynge me owte of synne, and comforte me in thys woofulle sykenes, and rewe one me though I haue longe tyme leyne in syne; for in thy grete goodnesse I truste for the wordys that by the prophete ys seyde: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In eternum seruabo illi misericordiam,</FOREIGN> &para; Withoutene ende I shalle kepe mercy to synffulle mane; and therfor, lorde, ayenst thy kynde hit were and thy trewthe, but thou one synfulle hade mercy that forethynketh hys synne and wolle aske mercy.  And I forthynkyng my synne in alle my[n] herte, pray the allemyghty gode for thy endeles mercy haue mercy one me, that thou most swete art.  My gode, my goode lorde, hertyly I be-seche the to my seke soule and synffulle thou sende some comforte and socoure off thy grace, and for thy moche mekenesse be mercyffulle to me that ame thy pore creature, off thy[n] owne makyng.  And thy mercy, lorde, ouerpasseth alle thyng that thow madest, as the prophete seyth, that thow may nat for thy goodnesse forsakene heme that askene thy mercy: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia misericordia eius super omnia opera eius,</FOREIGN> &para; For [thy] mercy ys aboue alle thy werkis; and therfor, lorde, welle I wote that thow may nat for thy goodnes and for thy endeles mercy put me fro thy mercy, yeff alle myne synnes be neuer so many ne neuer so grete; for thane thow were nat gode whos mercy and goodnesse passeth alle mennes wyckednes that wolle leue her wyckydnesse and here synne with alle here herte, as the prophete seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cor contritum et humiliatum deus non despicies,</FOREIGN> &para; The herte [that is] contryte and mekyde, God shalle nat despyse.  Wherfor fully I trust and hoole I me take to thy endeles mercy: and for mykylnesse off thy mercy haue mercy one me, Ihesu, Ihesu, Ihesu, amene.&raquo;</P>
</DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="2: 389"><HEAD>The Profits of Tribulation<NOTE ID="n15">Under this rubric Horstman prints two related works normally connected through an intervening Latin text, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nota de paciencia infirmitatis</FOREIGN>, here omitted.  The second text translates <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">De duodecim utilitatibus tribulationis</FOREIGN>, erroneously ascribed to Peter of Blois.</NOTE></HEAD>

<DIV3 N="MS Reg. 17 A xxv" TYPE="section"><PB N="2: 390">
<HEAD TYPE="main">The Six Masters</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Royal 17.A.xxv</HEAD>
 <OPENER>Here begynnyth a litil schort tretice that tellyth how &thorn;er weren sixe maisters asembliden to-gidur, and askiden eche oon of o&thorn;ere what &thorn;ey my&yogh;te best speke of that my&yogh;te moost plese god &amp; were moost profitable to &thorn;e peple, and alle &thorn;ey weren acordid to speke of tribulacioun.</OPENER><P>(T)He friste maistir seyde &thorn;at if eni &thorn;inge hadde be bettir to eny mannis lyuynge in &thorn;is world &thorn;an tribulacioun, god wolde haue &yogh;eue it to his sone; but for he say wel &thorn;er was no &thorn;inge better &thorn;an it, &thorn;erfore he &yogh;af it to him, and made him to suffre moost tribulacioun in &thorn;is wrecchid worlde, more &thorn;an dide euere eny man or euere schal.     (T)he secunde maistir seide &thorn;at if &thorn;er were eny man in &thorn;is world that my&yogh;te be with-oute spot of synne as oure lorde Ihesu Crist was, and my&yogh;te lyue here &thorn;ritti &yogh;eer and it were possible with-oute mete and drinke, and were also so deuout in preynge &thorn;at he my&yogh;te speke with aungelis in &thorn;e eir as dide Marie Maudeleyn, &yogh;it my&yogh;te he not deserue in that lijf so greet mede as a man deserue&thorn; in sufferyng of a litil tribulacioun.     (T)he &thorn;ridde maister seyde that if it so were &thorn;at the modir of god and alle &thorn;e halewis of heuene preieden alle for oo man, &yogh;it schulde &thorn;ei not gete him so myche meede ne so greet as he schulde gete hym-silf bi meeknes in suffringe of a litil tribulacioun.     (T)he four&thorn;e maistir seide: We worschipe &thorn;e cros for oure lord Ihesu Crist hyng ther-upon bodili, but I seye we schulde ra&thorn;er and by more ri&yogh;t and resoun haue in mynde &thorn;e tribulacioun &thorn;at he suffride ther-upon for oure gyltis and trespasis.     (T)he fif&thorn;e maistir seide: I hadde leuere be of my&yogh;te, of strenk&thorn;e and of power to suffre &thorn;e leste peyne of tribulacioun &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu Crist suffride here in er&thorn;e wi&thorn; meeknes in herte, &thorn;an &thorn;e meede or the reward of alle worldly goodis, for as seint Petir sei&thorn; &thorn;at noon ys wor&thorn;i to haue tribulacioun but &thorn;o that desyren [it] with clene herte and wi&thorn;-oute errour; for tribulacioun quenchi&thorn; synne, and it lerne&thorn; a man to knowe &thorn;e priuytees of god, and tribulacioun maki&thorn; a man to knowe hym-silf and his euen-cristin, and it multiplie&thorn; vertues in a man, and purgith hym and clensith hym lijk as fier doo&thorn; golde; and what man that meekli in herte suffri&thorn; tribulacioun, god is with-inne hym and berith &thorn;at heuy charge of tribulacioun wi&thorn; hym; also tribulacioun beye&thorn; a&yogh;en the tyme &thorn;at is lost, and holdi&thorn; a man in &thorn;e wey of ri&yogh;twisnes; and of alle &thorn;e &yogh;iftis &thorn;at god &yogh;eue&thorn; vnto man, tribulacioun is &thorn;e moost wor&thorn;i &yogh;ifte, also it is [a] tresour to &thorn;e which no man may make comparisoun; and tribulacioun ioyne&thorn; a mannis soule vnto god.     Now axi&thorn; &thorn;e sixte maistir whi we suffren tribulacioun with so euel wil; and it is answerid &thorn;er-to &amp; seyd &thorn;us: for &thorn;re thingis.  The firste is for we haue litil loue to oure lord Ihesu Crist.  The secunde is for &thorn;at we thenke litil of &thorn;e greete meede and profite &thorn;at come&thorn; &thorn;erof.  The &thorn;irdde is &thorn;at we &thorn;enke ful litil or nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e bittir paynes and &thorn;e greete passioun &thorn;at oure lord Ihesu Crist suffride for us in redempcioun of oure synnes, and to bringe us to his blis that neuer schal haue ende.  AMEN.&mdash; &mdash;</P> </DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section">

<PB N="2: 391"><HEAD>Twelve Profits of Tribulation</HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="prologue">
<OPENER>Here sueth a prologe vpone &thorn;e XII prophetis and auauntegis of tribulacion.
</OPENER><HEAD><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Prologus. Da nobis domine auxilium de tribulacione,</FOREIGN></HEAD><P>'LOrd god, graunte us helpe of tribulacion'.  To &thorn;e, soule, &thorn;at art distroublid and temptid, to &thorn;e is purposed &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt lerne wherof tribulacions seruen, and [not] only &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt suffre hem paciently, [but] gladlye, and comforte the inwardly of &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte discomforte outwarde.  For Seneca sei&thorn;e: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non est ita magna consolacio sicut illa que ex desolacione extrahitur,</FOREIGN> There is none so gret comforte as is &thorn;at &thorn;at is drawen oute of discomforte.  Which comforte may noman haue, but he know first the frute of tribulacion, &thorn;at is to seye, but he know how god sendith tribulacions and ordeyne&thorn;e heme to &thorn;e prophet of the soffrers, but if it so be that rebelnesse of frowardnes with-stonde &thorn;e ordinaunce of god.  Therfor &thorn;ei &thorn;at knowen her defautes one &thorn;at one partie, and &thorn;ee profetis of tribulacion on &thorn;at o&thorn;er parti, askyn to be holpyne in tribulacion, &amp; not tribulacion to be put a-weye from hem; for if &thorn;ei askyn puttynge awey &thorn;erof, &thorn;ei askene a-yence hym-selfe, as seynt Poule dyd which asked &thorn;ries &thorn;e prikynge of his flessh to be done a-weye; to whome god answeryd thus, IIo ad Corrinth. 12o: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sufficit tibi gracia mea,</FOREIGN> My grace suffiseth to the.  Many prophitis &thorn;er ben of tribulacion, but of XII I purpose to speke in speciall; the which who so will with good diligens reed or here, he schal lyghtly with goddis grace fynde gostly sauoure.  For ryght as mete euel chewed is euel to defye, ryght so techynge of hooly writt neccligently redd or herd profiteth lytell or ellis nou&yogh;te.</P></DIV4><DIV4
TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of the first prophet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum primum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The firste prophet of tribulacion is vnderstond &thorn;at it is a trew socoure of help sent frome god to delyuer the soule fro &thorn;e handis of his enemyes, whiche enemyes ben &thorn;ese: preuy suggestions of &thorn;e fende &thorn;at cruel enemy, ffalse ioyes


<PB N="2: 392">

&amp; richesse of the world &thorn;at disseiuable enemy, vnclene lustis of the fflessh &thorn;at homly enemy.  Thes enemyes sleen &thorn;e soule, and so mych &thorn;e more (perl)osly, &thorn;at &thorn;ei disseiuen it with false feyned frendshyp and so preuyly.  The which ben figured bi Ioas, IIo Regum .XX., that feyned hym frend to Amas holdynge hyme by &thorn;e chyne as he wold haue kyssed hyme, and so with his swerd in &thorn;at oder hond preuyly stiked hyme.  Vpone &thorn;is sei&thorn;e seint Gregor: Yf euery fortune is for to be drad, moch more is for to be drad prosperite &thorn;an aduersite&mdash;as schewe&thorn; opynly.  And note wel &thorn;at god ordeyneth all &thorn;ingis in tribulacion to [&thorn;e] delyueraunce of his seruauntis, as he behoti&thorn;e be &thorn;e prophet Dauid, seying &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cum ipso sum in tribulacione, eripiam eum &amp; glorificabo eum,</FOREIGN> I am with hym in tribulacion, I schal delyuer hym of tribulacion, and I schal glorifye hym for tribulacion.  For als much &thorn;an as god is with vs in tribulacion, we schal suffre it paciently and gladly, for &thorn;e more &thorn;at tribulacion groweth to &thorn;e, the more nere god nei&yogh;hith to &thorn;e, as &thorn;e prophet seith:<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Iuxta est dominus hijs qui tribulato sunt corde, &amp; humiles spiritu saluabit,</FOREIGN> Oure lord is faste-by to hem &thorn;at ben in tribulacion of herte, and he schal saue hem &thorn;at ben meke of spirite.  Therfor if the peyne of tribulacion make the heuy and greuyth the, &thorn;e my&yogh;t and the mercy of god thy sauioure &thorn;at is with the in tribulacion, schall inwardly comfort the.  But now perauenture &thorn;ou my&yogh;test answere &amp; sey thus: 'The bitter payne ofe tribulacion I fele wel, but swettnesse of his fellowshyp I fele none; ffor if he schewed to me the present swetnesse of hy[s] myrth as he doth the bitternesse of tribulacion, I schuld suffer it gladly'.  Also perauenture thow woldist seye that afore tribulacion thow felist more swetnesse in god &thorn;an &thorn;ou dedist whan &thorn;ou were in tribulacion.  Here-to may be answered, &thorn;at &thorn;e frendshipe of god in tribulacion is vnder-stond in twey maners.  First: as tribulacion encresith, so god multiplieth grace &amp; vertu for to suffre tribulacion paciently &amp; gladly.  Example: as lordis send socoure and helpe to comforte hyr seruauntis &thorn;at be in castellis besegid of her enemyes, ry&yogh;t so oure lord god sendi&thorn;e comfort of grace to soules &thorn;at ben be-segid with temptacions &amp; tribulacions.  The secund maner of the fellowschype of god in tribulacion may be vnderstonde by the comforte &thorn;at he sendith hem &thorn;at bene in tribulacion; as the apostil seithe, I Cor. IIo: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sicut habundant passiones Christi in nobis, ita habundat consolacio nostra,</FOREIGN> As the passion of Criste encresith in us, so encresith oure comforte.  Cristis passions encresyne in us when thei be sent fro hym and we to [&thorn;e] lyknesse of hym mekely &amp; paciently suffer hem as goddis seruauntis, and not as mansleers and thevis, whiche hane deseruid &thorn;at &thorn;ei sufferne.  And vnderstond well, &thorn;at comforte of grace in tribulacion is for he schulde dred god and trist in hym to be delyuerde; as we rede in the boke of holy fader seint Anton, how he after many gret spirituall temptacions was troublyd of fendis, bodyly betone and woundid all hys body, so &thorn;at whan his seruaunt cam to viset hym he found hyme lying dede &amp; so he toke hym vp and bare hym to the next towne where he watched tyll abow&yogh;t mydny&yogh;t; and &thorn;an by the will ofe god he releued and bad his seruaunt preuyly, all other sclepyng, bere hym a&yogh;en; and so he did.  And whan he was brou&yogh;t ayen thedir so feble &thorn;at he my&yogh;t not stonde, but sittynge vp he seid &thorn;us: 'Where bene ye euill spiritis, wicked feendis? lo I am here be &thorn;e my&yogh;t of god redy to withstond all youre malice'.  &amp; after &thorn;es and many [othir] wonderfull temptacions: oure lord appered to hym in wonderful ly&yogh;t &amp; comfortable.  To whom hooly Antone seid: 'A lord Ihesu, where hast &thorn;ou bene? good lord, where hast &thorn;ou be so longe fro me in tribulacion?'  And oure lord answered and seyd: 'here with the, beholdynge thi fyghtynge, redy to reward the and comforte the after thi uictory, as I am wont to do for my chosin childerne'.  For wit &thorn;ou well &thorn;at comforte oweth not to com, tyl that a place be rayed therto by tribulacion.  Also we rede of Sare, the


<PB N="2: 393">

dou&yogh;ter of Raguell, Tobie IIIo: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Hoc autem certum habet omnis qui colit te quia vita eius si in temptacione fuerit coronabitur, si autem in tribulacione fuerit liberabitur, et si in correpcione fuerit ad misericordiam tuam peruenire licebit.  Non enim delectaris in perdicionibus nostris; quia post tempestatem tranquillum facis, et post lacrimacionem et fletum exultacionem infundis:</FOREIGN> Euery man &thorn;at worschippith the, god, hath this for certeyn that yf his lyfe be here in temptacion, he schalbe crowned, and yf he be in tribulacion he schalbe delyuerd, &amp; [yf] he be in chastisyng it schalbe leffull to com to &thorn;i mercy; &thorn;ou delitest not in oure per[i]chynge, for after tempestis &thorn;ou makist tranquillite, &amp; after teers and wepyng &thorn;ou sendist gladnesse. as the prophet seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Secundum multitudinem dolorum meorum in corde meo consolaciones tue letificauerunt animam meam,</FOREIGN> After the multitude of the sorrowes in myn herte thi comfortis hane gladdid my soule.  The comforte of on oure passith &thorn;e sorrowes of tribulacion of many &yogh;eris; ffor god &thorn;at commyth for to helpe &amp; comforte, after tribulacion schal abyd with &thorn;e, gladdynge &thorn;i soule.  And perauenture yf &thorn;ou pleineste &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou tarrieste ouer-longe abydynge his comforte, as louers be wont to pleyne: here-to answeri&thorn;e a gret clerke, Cassiodorus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ipsa uelocitas dei desideranti &amp; amanti tarditas videtur,</FOREIGN> The swiftenesse of god to a desirynge &amp; a louynge soule semyth longe tariynge, [or thus: a thyng &thorn;at is moche couetyd semeth grete tariyng] to a louynge soule.  &THORN;an of &thorn;ese tofore-seid may be concluded &thorn;at a soule discomforted in tribulacion oweth not to hold hym-selfe ouercom of his enemyes, but rather delyuerde.  Si&thorn;e &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;is is sothe &thorn;at tribulacions delyueren us from oure enemyes, &thorn;ough so be &thorn;at &thorn;ei be heuy and chargeable yet neuer-the-lesse &thorn;ei schulden be suffred paciently &amp; gladly, with-out grocchynge a-&yogh;ens tribulacions; for yf we gruche a-yence hem, &thorn;an we strive a-yenst oure helpers &amp; we helpen oure enemyes.  And for we be not stronge of oure-silfe to delyuer vs from oure enemyes, pray we to god mekelye seyinge with the prophet: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Da nobis domine auxilium de tribulacione,</FOREIGN> Lord god graunte us helpe of tribulacion.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> The secund prophet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum secundum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The secund prophet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it stoppith the malice of the fend; for he is a-ferd to tempt &thorn;e soule &thorn;at is in tribulacion, for he dredith hym to be ouercome or ellis refused.  &amp; &thorn;at is figured by the frendis of Iobe, where it is seyd, Iob. IIo: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nemo loquebatur ei uerbum, videbant enim dolorem eius uehementem,</FOREIGN> Noman speke to hym a word, &thorn;ei sigh his sorrowes werne grete.  The feyned frendis of Iobe betokyn wicked feendis &thorn;at wexen or troublyn soules, which dare not com ny&yogh;e a soule &thorn;at is in tribulacion, ne tempt it beynge distroublyd.  &amp; not oonly tribulacion stoppith the malice of the fende, but also &thorn;ere-thorou&yogh; the soule deseruith comforte as of angels and of seyntis, as we rede of holy faders many oone.  Of which one commyth to mynde.  Abbot Sisoy after meke sofferrynge of tribulacions &amp; desesis, a litill to-fore the soule schuld passe from the body, he seyd: 'brethern, bene(!) glad, lo holy Anton commyth to us'; &amp; sone after he seyd: 'lo here commyth the worshypful company of prophetis'; and the thrid tyme he seid: 'now commyne the holy apostillis'; and as it semed to hem &thorn;at stodyne abou&yogh;t he spake with hem; and &thorn;en &thorn;ei prayeden [hym] &thorn;at he schuld tel hem with whom &thorn;at he spake, and he answerid and seid: 'with holy angels &thorn;at commyn to take my soule; and I prayed hem to byd[e] a while, &thorn;at I schuld suffre more pennaunce'; and &thorn;ese wordis I-seyd, &thorn;e spirit passeth with gret ly&yogh;t, all &thorn;ei felynge a wonderfull swete sauoure.  Note well &thorn;at &thorn;ere is no perell in tribulacion of temptacions so &thorn;at &thorn;ou answere not to hem by dilectacion or consentynge, as &thorn;e spech of ane opyne cursed man noyeth not but yf &thorn;ou answere to hym.  &thorn;at is figured in holy wrytt where it is seyd, Ysaie XXXVIo: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Mandauerat enim rex E&yogh;echias ne populus responderet blasfemijs Rapsacis,</FOREIGN> Kynge E&yogh;echie commaunded &thorn;at &thorn;e peple schuld not answere to the blasfemis of that tiraunt


<PB N="2: 394">

Rapsacis.  By Rapsacis is vnderstond the feend, and by his blasfemyes bene vnderstond temptacions of wicked &thorn;ou&yogh;tis, which noyeth nou&yogh;t but yf &thorn;ou wilfully assent to hem.  And if &thorn;ou fele &thorn;e feble by frelet[e] of the flessh, pray &thorn;ou god besily in tribulacion &thorn;at he stop the malicious temptacion of the fend, as the prophet seith: Lord god graunt us helpe of tribulacion.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of the thrid prophet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum tercium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The thrid prophet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it purgi&thorn;e the soule.  But it is to wit &thorn;at ther bene v. maner of materiall purgyngis.  On is purgynge of mannys body for corrupcion of humoris wicked; &amp; &thorn;at is in two maners: one ys be medicinable drynkys, a nother be crafty blood-lettynge.  The secund purgynge ys of metal, as gold be &thorn;e fire, &amp; iron be the fyle.  The thrid purgynge is of trees, as cuttynge of vynes, and voydynge of onfrutfull branches.  The fourth purgynge is of corne, as betyng or thresshyng with a flayle.  The fyfte purgynge is of grapis, &amp; that is by a pressoure.  One &thorn;us many maners god doth purge the soule by tribulacions.  For as the body is purged by medicinalle drinkis of euell humoris, ryght so is the soule made clene by tribulacions sent from the souereyne leche oure lord god of veyne affeccions and euell maners; for seynt Gregor seyth:<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Mali humores sunt mali mores,</FOREIGN> Euel humoris bene euel maners.  Drinke &thorn;is medicyne of tribulacion sent to the fro god, for he is a wise leche and knoweth all &thorn;i preuy syknesse &amp; how much &thorn;ou maist suffre and how much &thorn;ou nediste, for he sendi&thorn;e the no thynge but &thorn;at &thorn;at is profitable to the.  And he ha&thorn;e tasted and assayed and drunke afore the, not for hym-selfe but for &thorn;i purgynge, he suffred &thorn;e passione of deth; wherof he seyd to the apostellis Iohn&macr; and Iamys, Mat. xxo: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Potestis bibere calicem quem ego bibiturus sum,</FOREIGN> Mow ye drynke &thorn;e passione &thorn;at I schal drynke?  &THORN;an sith this wise lech hath dronke this medicyn for &thorn;i loue, drynke &thorn;ou therof with-oute drede, for it is holsom.  This drynke thirsted the prophet Dauid whene he seid: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Calicem salutaris accipiam et nomen domini inuocabo,</FOREIGN> I schal take the holsome passione of tribulacion.  And if &thorn;e &thorn;inke it bitter, clepe &thorn;i lord god vnto &thorn;i helpe as he seid: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Da nobis domine auxilium de tribulacione,</FOREIGN> Lord god graunt us helpe of tribulacion.  And as a purgacion schuld be receyued hastyly with-oute ouer-much tastynge or longe tarryng, so schuld tribulacion be acceptid wilfullye with-out argumentis of disputynge or rebellyone or grucchynge.  But now be wel ware: for as some-tyme &thorn;e prophet of the medicyne is letti[d] and worchith the contrary to corrupcion, not for the defaute of &thorn;e medcyne, but for &thorn;e euel disposicion of hym &thorn;at receyueth hit, so in the same wise the prophet of tribulacion is lettid of purgacion and doth the contrary, for it is begynnynge of payne, after which foloweth euerlastynge dampnacion; as we reden of kyng Pharo kynge of Egipt, for the more &thorn;at he was visettid by tribulacion, the more his rebellious herte encresyd in to his dampnacion.  The secund purgacion of mannys body for euel humoris is by crafty blood-lettynge, and that is of two maners, as by openynge [of &thorn;e veyne, or els by boxynge or ventusynge.  Openynge of the veyne] is properyd to confession, and boxynge or ventusyng, to tribulacion.  And not[e] wele, ryght as foule blode corruptith the body, so syn which is called in holy writ 'blood' defouleth the soule.  The veyne be the which blod or syne ys voidid oute, is the mouth, as it is seyd Prouerb. x: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vena vite os iusti; quia iustus in principio accusator est sui,</FOREIGN> The mouth of a ry&yogh;tful man is the veyne of lijf; for the ryghfull man in the begynnynge accuseth hym-selfe, &thorn;at is to sey, be confession.  Also note that as a man oweth by this veyne to voyde oute wicked blood for the purgynge of his body, and kepe his good blood for his norisshynge, ryght so in confession he oweth by his mouthe to shew all his synnes, and with-hold and kepe preue all his good dedis for fere of lesynge; for good [dedis] schewed in


<PB N="2: 395">

confession by veyneglory or avauntynge, turnyn fro vertu vnto vicis for defaute of wise kepyng, as we redyne of the pharase that seyd, Luc.  XVIIIo:<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Gracias ago tibi domine quia non sum sicut ceteri hominum, raptores, adulteri, uelut eciam hic publicanus; Ieiuno bis in sabbato, decimas do omnium que possideo:</FOREIGN> Lord I &thorn;anke &thorn;e for I am not lyke as other men, robbers and auoutrers, also not lyke this publycan; I fast twise in a weke, I paye tythes of all &thorn;at I haue.  Lo here &thorn;ou maist vnderstond by this pharase a false feyned and a prowd confession.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sed publicanus a longe stans noluit oculos ad celum leuare, sed percuciebat pectus [suum] dicens Deus propicius esto michi peccatori:</FOREIGN> But the publican stondynge a-ferre behynde, holdynge hym-selfe vnworthi, wold not lyfte up his &yogh;ien to heuen, but he smote his herte and seyde God haue merci on me synner; and so this publican yode thens iustified, or made ryght, by his verry meke confessione.  To this acordith the prophet Dauid where he seith thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Dixi confitebor aduersum me iniusticiam meam domino, &amp; tu remisisti impietatem peccati mei:</FOREIGN> I schall knowlege [by] meke confession ayence my-silfe to my lord myn vnry&yogh;twisnes, and &thorn;ou haste for&yogh;euen the wickidnesse of my synne.  &para; Boxynge or ventusyng, a-cordyth to tribulacion; for als many desesis as god sendith to the in tribulacion, so many remedies he ordeynith for thi purgacion.  But note wel as it is nedeful afore ventusynge, the flessh to be het and clensid, for &thorn;an the smytynge of the blood-yryne may be suffred the more esily; so it is spedful afore tribulacion &thorn;at the hert be hett with parfite loue and charite, &thorn;at temptacion of tribulacion may be suffred the more paciently and gladly.  In figure here-of the holygoste cam downe to the apostilys in lyknesse of fire, bi whome thei were so strengthid and comforted &thorn;at afterward &thorn;ei werene gladd and yedyn Ioyinge for &thorn;ei were maade worthi to suffer tribulacion, angre and repreue for the name of Ihesu, the which afore &thorn;at tyme were so dredful &thorn;at &thorn;ei fleddyn aweye fro hym and som forsokun [hym], as Petir&mdash;&thorn;at was prince of the apostilles&mdash;for fere of a woman swore &thorn;at he knew hym not, the which after [&thorn;e] commynge of the holygoste dred not the cruell turment of Nero the emperour, but paciently and gladly suffred to be crucified and dede.  The secund maner of materyall purgacion is of metallis, as gold be fyre, and irone by file.  For ryght as fire departith gold from other metallis, and purgith hym of ruste and fylth, and maki&thorn;e hire faire and clene: so tribulacion departith the soule of his aduersaries, and clensith hym of the filth of synnes, and it makith hym to god lovely and acceptable; and therfor it is seyd Sapienc.  Vo: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Tamquam aurum in fornace probauit electos dominus, et quasi holocausta hostii accepit illos, &amp; in tempore erit respectus illorum,</FOREIGN> Oure lord hath preued his chosen men by tribulacion as gold is preued in the fornaise, and he hath accepted hem as sacrifice of offrynge, &amp; in tyme of reward &thorn;at schuld be hold(!).  With this fire of tribulacion was Iob preved when he seyd, Iobe XXIIIo: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Probauit me deus sicut aurum quod per ignem transit,</FOREIGN> God preuith&mdash;by tribulacion&mdash;me as gold &thorn;at passith by fire.  And note &thorn;at amonge all metallis gold is moste preciouse, and leed is leste of price, &amp; yet neuertheles gold is not purged with-oute leed, for leed draweth with hym in the forneis the filthes of gold.  On the same maner chosine soules [the whiche be likned to gold], bene purged by dampned soules the which be likened to leed; wherof Salomon seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Stultus seruiet sapienti,</FOREIGN> The fole schal serue to the wise man&mdash;&thorn;at is to seye, euell men schal serue to purge good men by tribulacion.  &para; Also Iron is purged bi the file of ruste, and made schynyng and bry&yogh;t: so is the soule purged by tribulacion from vnclennesse &amp; comforted with gostly ly&yogh;t.  And as a knyfe &thorn;at is not vsed, abydynge in the sheth draweth ruste: so doth the soule with-oute excersise of tribulacion, desireth vnclene luste; as we redyne of Dauid, IIo Reg. IIo, [&thorn;at] whan he was with-owt tribulacion of werrynge with his enemyes, fell into auoutrye with the wife of Vry &thorn;at wor&thorn;i kny&yogh;t, &amp; after into homicide or manslau&yogh;ter.  &THORN;erfor sei&thorn;e &thorn;e prophet Ieremye: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fertilis erat Moab in diebus adolescencie sue, &amp; requieuit in [fecibus] suis:</FOREIGN>


<PB N="2: 396">

Moab, &thorn;e which is vnderstonde the son of my people, was plenteuous by grace in tyme of his tribulacion, and he hath rested in filthes of syn.  Than gruche not ayence god whan he filyth thi soule to make it faire and clene, louely and ly&yogh;t, or els may it neuer com to haue of hym that blissed sy&yogh;t whereof it is seide Mat. V<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Beati mundo corde quoniam ipsi deum videbunt,</FOREIGN> Blessed bene &thorn;ei &thorn;at bene clene of hert for &thorn;ei schull se god.  &para; The thrid maner of purgynge &thorn;at accordyth to tribulacion, is of trees, as cuttynge of vinis, or wedyng of vnfrutefull braunchis; wherof Crist seith, Iohn. XX<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Omnem palmitem in me non ferentem fructum, tollet eum, &amp; omnem qui fert fructum, purgabit eum, ut fructum plus afferat,</FOREIGN> Euery vyne-braunche &thorn;at bringeth forth no frute in me &thorn;at am a warre vyne, my fader, &thorn;at is a tilier, schal kut hym of and cast hym a-weye, and &thorn;at braunche &thorn;at beryth frute he schall purge hym, &thorn;at he may bringe forth more frute.  By this vyne may be vnderstonde mannys herte, bi tho humoris is vnderstond affeccion or loue, and by vnfrutfull braunchis bene vnderstond flesshly lustis, vnordinate loue of creaturis, carnall affeccions of kynred, and worldly richesse.  When &thorn;e humoris of a vyne or of a tree is spred aboute vnto ou&thorn;er many vnfrutefull braunchesse, hit bringeth for&thorn;e the lasse frute or ellis none; &thorn;erfor it longith to a wise tilier or to a good gardiner to cut of &thorn;es vnfruteful braunches, &thorn;at the vyne or the tree may brynge forth the better frute and the more.  Right so almy&yogh;ti god, which is a wise tilier &amp; a souereyne gardiner, cutti&thorn;e a-wey vnclene lustis of &thorn;e flessh with the knyfe of bodyly siknesse, he cutte&thorn;e a-wey vnordinate loue of creatures with the hoke of aduersite &amp; tribulacions, he cuttith a-wey carnall affeccions of kynred with &thorn;e swerd of de&thorn;e, &amp; he cutti&thorn;e a-wey worldly riches with is irone rodde, as with brennynge of fyre, drenchynge of water, robbyng of theves and such other.  On all these maners doth god chastice and purge by tribulacion, ffor he wold &thorn;at the loue of thine herte schuld abyde with hym &amp; bringe forth plenty of spiritual frute in hym, &amp; not abyde ne trust in such deseyuable frendshyp; for seynt Gregory seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Qui autem labenti adheret, necesse est ut cum labente labatur,</FOREIGN> He &thorn;at lene&thorn;e to a fallynge &thorn;inge, nedis with &thorn;at fallynge he most fall.
</P><P>The foureth maner of materiall purgynge &thorn;at acordi&thorn;e to tribulacion, is of corne, as by betynge or thresshynge with a flayle, to departe &thorn;e corne fro &thorn;e chaffe; wherof seith seint Austene: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quod flagellum grano, quod fornax auro, quod lima ferro, hoc facit tribulacio viro iusto,</FOREIGN> As the fleile seruith to corne, as the fornais seruith to gold, &amp; as the fyle serui&thorn;e to yren, so seruith tribulacion to &thorn;e ry&yogh;tful man.  As we rede &thorn;at the angel Raphael seid to Tobye, Tobie XII<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et quia acceptus eras deo, necesse fuit ut temptacio probaret te,</FOREIGN> And for &thorn;ou were acceptable to god it was nedfull &thorn;at tribulacion schuld preue the.  For as betyng of a flaile constreyneth the corne to departe fro the chaffe, so tribulacion constreyneth the herte to forsake the disseiuable loue of the world and the false frendship of synners, which ar vnderstond in chafe.  The prophet of this flayle knew &thorn;e prophet when he seid: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ecce ego in flagella paratus sum,</FOREIGN> Lo I am redy to suffer the betynge of tribulacion.  And therfor seith seynt Austin: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Noli conquerere(!) de flagello tribulacionis, si vis habere purum granum, &amp; reponi cupis in celo vbi non nisi purum granum reponetur,</FOREIGN> Pleyne &thorn;e not of &thorn;e fleyle of tribulacion, if &thorn;ou wilt haue clene corne of concience, &amp; if &thorn;ou wilt coueit to be in &thorn;e garner of &thorn;e blisse of heuen into &thorn;e which &thorn;ou maist not com till &thorn;ou be clene purgid.  Be well ware: for as corne &thorn;at is grene &amp; moiste, &amp; not ripe ne drye, is not departed from the chaffe with betynge ofe the flaile, but rather cleuith therto, so it is for to dred &thorn;at hertis which arne grene in begynnyng of conuersion and moiste in carnall affeccions, which hane not assaid &thorn;e profet of tribulacion, be not departed from &thorn;e fals frendship of hir enemyes, but rather cleuen to hem as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei wold be comforted by hem; ffor when god sendi&thorn;e us visitacions for to purge &thorn;e soule &thorn;at he louyth, be it be bodyly siknesse or by losse of godes &thorn;at ben temporall or aduersite of enemyes or eny other temptacion


<PB N="2: 397">

or heuynesse, anon &thorn;e herte rennyth all abou&yogh;te to seke comforte of his fals frendis, &amp; it hath grete dred &thorn;ere as is no nede, as &thorn;e prophet sei&thorn;e: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ibi ceciderunt timore vbi non erat timor,</FOREIGN> Thei fellyne doun for dred &thorn;ere as no dred was.  Hit may be clepid a cursed comforte &thorn;at is sett ra&thorn;er in a creature &thorn;an in god, ffor &thorn;e prophet Ieremie seith, Ieremie XIIII<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maledictus homo qui confidit in homine, &amp; ponit carnem brachium suum, &amp; a deo recedit cor eius,</FOREIGN> Cursed be &thorn;at man &thorn;at tristith in man, &amp; he &thorn;at settith any creature to be his strength, &amp; he &thorn;at departi&thorn;e his herte from god.  But it may be clepid a blessid comforte &thorn;at is sett in god, as &thorn;e same prophet seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Benedictus uir qui confidit in domino, &amp; erit dominus fiducia eius,</FOREIGN> Blessed be &thorn;at man &thorn;at tristeth in oure lord god, &amp; oure lord schalbe his trust.  And &thorn;at we schul haue ful trust oonly in god in all maner of tribulacion, &amp; dred fals comforte &amp; euel concell of oure enemyes, we hane ensample of Ochosias &thorn;e kynge &thorn;at sent messangers to Belsabub &thorn;e feend of Acharon to haue comforte &amp; councell where he schuld escape &thorn;e tribulacion of siknesse or no; &amp; god sent an angel to Hely &thorn;e prophet &amp; bad hym sey to Ochosi: 'For &thorn;ou hast sent messengers to aske councell of Belsebub &thorn;e feend of Acharon, as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;er were no god in Israel of whom &thorn;ou my&yogh;teste asken councell &amp; comforte, &thorn;erfor &thorn;ou schalt not go oute of &thorn;i bed &thorn;at &thorn;ou yedist vpon, but &thorn;ou schalt dye &thorn;erin'.  Also that we schuld not loue &thorn;e world ne truste worldlye &thorn;ingis, seint Iohn biddith, Io Ioh. II<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nolite diligere mundum neque ea que in mundo sunt,</FOREIGN> Will ye not loue &thorn;e worlde ne worldly &thorn;ingis.</P><P>The fifte maner of materiall purgacion is as of grapis, and that is by a pressoure.  For as a pressoure pressith the grapis to departe the preciouse liquore of wyne fro draffe &amp; drastis, so god purgith &thorn;e soule &thorn;at he loue&thorn;e in the pressour of tribulacion fro corrupcion &amp; wickednesse of syn, som-tyme by bodyly seknesse or preuy gostly heuynes, &amp; some-tyme be losse of temporall goodis or persecucion or slaunder of euell men and enemyes, some-tyme for lackynge of noble kynred or by the deth of feythfull frendis; and &thorn;erfor suffre paciently the prophet of &thorn;is pressoure, yf &thorn;ou wilt be brou&yogh;t into Cristis blessed seller, of which is seyd Cant. II<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Introduxit me dominus in cellam suam vinariam,</FOREIGN> The lord &thorn;e kyng hath brou&yogh;t me in to his wyne-seller.  Herto accordith seint Austen &amp; seith &thorn;at holy martires were so pressid be tribulacion in &thorn;is present lyfe, &thorn;at &thorn;e bodyly mater lefte in the pressoure of &thorn;is erth, but &thorn;e precious soules were resseyued vnto the seller of euerlastyng blesse.  Gruch not &thorn;an ayence god if he haue put &thorn;e in his pressoure of tribulacion; for he hath asayed it afore the, as Ysaie the prophet seith in the person of Crist, Ysaie lXIII<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Torcular calcaui solus &amp; de gentibus non est uir mecum,</FOREIGN> I alone haue tred &thorn;e pressoure of tribulacion &amp; no man is with me of folkis.  And &thorn;at he seith, not 'no woman', for &thorn;at blessed woman moder &amp; maide oure lady seynt Mary abode with hym in full feith when all &thorn;o apostilles fled from hym, &amp; was redy to suffre deth by compassyon of hyr son, as &thorn;e prophet Symeon seith, Luc. II<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Et tuam ipsius animam pertransibit gladius,</FOREIGN> The swerd of deth schall passe thorow thyne owen soule.  Now &thorn;an sith &thorn;is is soth &thorn;at oure lord Ihesu Crist hath seyd &thorn;is pressoure of tribulacion and that blessed lady his moder mayd Marye, what so euer &thorn;ou be &thorn;at feliste &thorn;e in &thorn;is pressoure of tribulacion, take it mekely &amp; gladly, praying with &thorn;e prophet <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Da nobis domine auxilium de tribulacione,</FOREIGN> Lord graunte us helpe of tribulacion.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of &thorn;e IIIIth prophet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum quartum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The IIIIth profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it ly&yogh;tneth &thorn;e to haue &thorn;e knowynge of god, in which is perfeccion &amp; &thorn;e profet of mannys knowynge; &thorn;e which seynte Austyn desired seing in the boke of answers to hym-selfe&mdash;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">libro soly-loquiorum</FOREIGN>&mdash; thus: 'Wold god I schuld know &thorn;e, lord, wold god I schuld know the!'  And also it is writtun in &thorn;e boke of Wisdom, Cap. XV: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nosce te iusticia est consummata,</FOREIGN>


<PB N="2: 398">

To know &thorn;e, lord god, it is fulfilled ri&yogh;twisnes endid.  To this knowynge helpith tribulacion; ffor as the rod constreyneth a child to bowe doun his heed &amp; take heed of his boke &amp; record his lesson, so tribulacion meketh &thorn;e herte &amp; makith hym to be-hold his owene freelte &amp; to know god.  Wherfor seith seint Bernard: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Deus se facit cognosci verberando, qui oblitus &amp; incognitus erat parcendo,</FOREIGN> God makith hym-selfe to be knowen in betynge with tribulacion, which was for-yete &amp; vnknowe in his mercyfull sparyng.  Daniel IIII<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>, of this we hane ensample of the kynge Nabugodonosor, which for prid was cast oute of his kyngdom &amp; leued with wild bestis &amp; ete hey as an oxe, but when he lifte up his y&yogh;e to his maker of hole herte, his witt was restored to hyme a&yogh;en &amp; he knew god &thorn;at chastised hym in tribulacion; as is the maner of children, when &thorn;ei felen scharpe strokis of the rod, &thorn;ei lifte up her yen to hym &thorn;at smytten(!) hem, for &thorn;ei wolden &thorn;at he schuld turne his face to hem by pite &amp; compassione.  Now &thorn;an, &thorn;ou lowly soule &thorn;at arte vnder &thorn;e rod of tribulacion, considre &amp; know wele &thorn;at &thorn;e maner of louers is for to send yeftis, tokens and prevy letters ecch of hem to other, for to kepe loue &amp; mynde of knowynge eche to o&thorn;er; on &thorn;e same maner oure lord Ihesu Crist, as a trew louer, sendith to his beloued children such siknesse as he toke here for hem.  For here he toke mankynde [in] which he suffred many tribulacions, detraccions, blasphemies, scornes, repreues, sclaundris, hungir, thrist, &amp; cold, &amp; many betyngis, scharpe scourgyngis, gret strokis, many thousand of depe woundis, &amp; was nayled vpon the crosse be-twene &thorn;e thevis, &amp; died &thorn;e schamfullest deth &thorn;at the Iues cowde ordeyne for hym; and after &thorn;at he was resen fro deth &amp; yed vp vnto heuen, he kept his woundis as for tokynnes, &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldest know wel &thorn;at he wold haue mynde of &thorn;e, as he seith by the prophet Ysaie, Ysaie XlIX: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Numquid obliuisci potest mulier infantem suum ut non miseriatur filio vteri [sui]?  Et si illa oblita fuerit, ego tamen non obliuiscar tui.  Ecce in manibus meis discripsi te:</FOREIGN> Whether a woman may foryete her child, &thorn;at sho haue no mercy of the sone of hir owen body?  and &thorn;ou&yogh;e sche foryete her child, I schal neuer foryete &thorn;e; lo I haue writtyn the in my handis,&mdash;&thorn;at is, in all my woundis whiche I suffred for love of the.  Sithen it is so &thorn;at he kepith &thorn;e shewynge of his woundis as for a tokyn of love to haue mynde on the, why shuldist &thorn;ou not be glad when he sendith to the such tokyns of loue as he toke here for the, for he wold &thorn;ou schuldist haue mynde on hyme &amp; know hym?  for he is thi frende &amp; wil not for-yete the.  For als many dyuerse tribulacions as he sendith the, so many sondre messengers &thorn;ou hast, clepyng &thorn;e &amp; warnynge &thorn;e to haue mynde on hym.  But now perauenture &thorn;ou wilte sey &thorn;at such tribulacions ar not most necessary to clepe &thorn;e to haue mynde of hym, but rather his gracious benefices of profet, for seynt Austyn seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Dei beneficia nil aliud sunt nisi moniciones veniendi ad eum,</FOREIGN> The beneficis of god bene no&thorn;inge ellis but warnyng or clepyng to com to hym.  To this may be answerid: All-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e gracious benefettis of god &amp; yeftis of profet, riches, bewte &amp; bounte, clepyn the to haue mynde on hym, yet neuerthelesse inordinate loue is so cleuynge to such yeftis, &thorn;at it draweth &thorn;ine herte rather to haue mynde on the yeftis &thorn;an on &thorn;e yeuer; wherfor he pleyneth to &thorn;e prophet seying: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Expandi manus meas &amp; non erat qui respiceret,</FOREIGN> I haue spred oute my handis, &thorn;at is, yeuyng benefettis, &amp; &thorn;ere was no man &thorn;at wold [behold.  He seid not that ther was no man that] wold take hem <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quia omnes diligunt munera, sequntur retribuciones,</FOREIGN> For all men loue yeftis &amp; &thorn;ei pursuen after rewardis, fro &thorn;e most to &thorn;e leste; But ther bene few or ellis none &thorn;at beholdyn, mekely knowynge the &yogh;euer of hem.  Also perauenture &thorn;ou woldist sey: all-&thorn;ou&yogh; it be accordynge to god to clepe indurat &amp; rebellyng hertis to know hym by tribulacion, neuer-the-lesse it nedith note so to god and meke hertis, the which desiren to know hyme by benefettis &amp; yeftis.  To


<PB N="2: 399">

this may be answeryd: All-&thorn;ou&yogh; good meke hertis by naturall delytynge in benefettis knowyn &thorn;e yeuer of hem, yit neuerthelesse to &thorn;e profet [of] parfite knowynge of god mow &thorn;ei not com without provynge of tribulacion.  Example here-of we redyn &thorn;at Salomon was clepyd by benefettis &amp; yeftis, Iobe was called by drawynge awey of his temporall goodis &amp; sendyng hym tribulacions &amp; aduersitees.  But &thorn;es tribulacions brou&yogh;t Iobe to &thorn;e parfite knowynge of god; Salomone be prosperite fill vnto folye, lesyng &thorn;e profet of &thorn;e parfite knowyng of god.  Yf Salomon, &thorn;at was so wise, lost &thorn;e profet of &thorn;e parfite knowynge of god: what-so-euer &thorn;ou arte trist not &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;teste longe abyd in &thorn;is knowynge [in] such prosperite.  &amp; &thorn;erfor suffer paciently tribulacions &amp; aduersitees: &amp; if &thorn;ou be discomforted &thorn;at &thorn;ei be many &amp; grete, be &thorn;ou comforted, for &thorn;e more &amp; gretter &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben &thorn;e more profet of knowynge of god &thorn;ei brynge to &thorn;e.  &amp; if &thorn;ou can not yett fele any comforte for frowardnesse or freelte of &thorn;i-silfe, pray to god &thorn;at he comforte the in tribulacion &amp; graunt &thorn;e grace to com to &thorn;e profet of parfite knowynge of hym, &amp; sey <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Da nobis domine &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> Lord graunte us helpe of tribulacion.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> The fyfte profet of tribulacione. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum quintum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The fyfte profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it reuokith or bringeth &thorn;e to &thorn;e knowynge of &thorn;i-selfe.  For &thorn;at hert &thorn;at hath not put a-wey fer from hym worldly veynglory, may not trewly fele ne know hym-selfe, for &thorn;at hert ha&thorn;e not verry knowynge of li&yogh;t; wherof &thorn;e prophet Dauid seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Lumen oculorum meorum, &amp; ipsum non est mecum,</FOREIGN> Ly&yogh;t of knowynge &thorn;ere is of myn yen, but &thorn;at ly&yogh;t is not with me.  [Wo] vnto hem &thorn;at dispendyn hyr ly&yogh;t of her knowynge in veyne ioies &amp; worldly &thorn;ingis, &amp; no&thorn;ing kepyn to knowen hem-selfe, &thorn;at ben not with hym-selfe; for &thorn;e more &thorn;at &thorn;e soule loueth &amp; desireth vayne ioyes &amp; worldly prosperitees, &thorn;e more ferther he draweth fro knowynge of hym-selfe.  &amp; &thorn;erfor seith seint Gregor: As he &thorn;at is be-seged with enemyes dar not go fer oute but he is constreined to turne a&yogh;en for dred, so tribulacions constreynen &thorn;e hert to turne into hym-selfe, &amp; &thorn;e mo aduersitees &thorn;at ben aboute hym, &thorn;e fewer he hathe of rennyngis-oute fro hym-selfe.  Than it is a blessed aduersite &thorn;at bringith &thorn;e to &thorn;i-selfe &amp; makith &thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast mysgo, to turne a-yene.  Wherof it is seid Exodi XII<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Maneat vnusquisque apud semetipsum,</FOREIGN> Dwell ech man with hym-selfe&mdash;&thorn;at is, know hym-silfe, take he kepe to hym-selfe, abyd he with hym-silfe; for as an howse in which noman dwellith, is wasted &amp; fallyth to nou&yogh;t, ry&yogh;t so &thorn;e herte &thorn;at dwelli&thorn;e or abydith not with hym-selfe.  Wo to &thorn;at herte &thorn;at renneth from hym-silfe all abow&yogh;t like as doth a iaper or a iogiller vnto o&thorn;er mennys howsis, for &thorn;e more he syngith &amp; iapith &amp; ioie&thorn;e in o&thorn;er mennys placis, &thorn;e more cause he fyndis in his owene place of sorrow &amp; of wepynge; so the more &thorn;at &thorn;e herte delyteth hym owtward in vayne &thorn;inkingis &amp; worldly ioyes, &thorn;e lasse he fyndeth in hym-selfe wherof he schuld be comforted.  Therfor tribulacion is well necessary to &thorn;e herte to make hym turne vnto hym-selfe, &amp; it constreineth hym to seye with the prophet: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Conuerte, anima mea, in requiem tuam,</FOREIGN> Torne a-yen &thorn;ou my soule vnto &thorn;i reste.  &amp; also oure lord god, hauynge pyte of &thorn;at soule &thorn;at hath for-wrappid hym-selfe with worldly &thorn;ingis, seith thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Reuertere reuertere, sunamitis, reuertere reuertere, ut intueamur te,</FOREIGN> Turne a&yogh;ene, turne a&yogh;en &thorn;ou wrecchid caitiffe soule, turne a&yogh;ene turne a&yogh;ene, &thorn;at we may be-hold &thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;ou behold &thorn;i-selfe with &thorn;e eye of concience, &amp; &thorn;at I mowe be-hold &thorn;e with &thorn;e eye of mercye.  O &thorn;ou soule &thorn;at arte distroublyd in aduersitees, suffer &thorn;e to be reuoked to knowynge of &thorn;i-selfe by tribulacion; and namly for &thorn;at tribulacion byndeth or knytteth to &thorn;e &thorn;i maker, whom wicked &amp; large


<PB N="2: 400">

fredom of &thorn;e world hathe lettun rynne longe louce fro &thorn;i-selfe.  Wherof spekith &thorn;e prophet &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In funiculis Adam traham eos &amp; in uinculis caritatis,</FOREIGN> I schal drawe hame in &thorn;e smale cordis of Adam &amp; in &thorn;e bondis of charite.  &THORN;ese smale cordis of Adam oure fore-fader, which longyn to us as by weye of heritage, ar clepid all maner of pouertees sent from god to refreyne &thorn;e hert frome veyne &amp; worldly comfortes; by which god draweth many one as it semeth by vyolence.  Wherof seith seynt Bernard: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Trahimur, quando tribulacionibus excercemur,</FOREIGN> We bene drawe, when we ben haunted with tribulacion.  &THORN;erfor &thorn;ou &thorn;at art streyned with &thorn;es cordis &amp; bondis of charite, suppose not &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte defouled or forsakyne, but ra&thorn;er maad fayre &amp; chosyn of god, all-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou haue not all &thorn;at &thorn;ou askist; ne trow not hem &thorn;at be not streyned with &thorn;ese bondis to be in verry liberte, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei han &thorn;at &thorn;ei asken; for like as &thorn;e lech whan he graunteth to &thorn;e sike all &thorn;at he desireth, it is a certeyne signe of deth, ry&yogh;t so the false fredom of this world is a certeyne signe of p[e]rechinge.  For &thorn;e more frely &thorn;ai desyre &amp; fulfillen her owen desire with-oute tribulacion, the rather &thorn;ei fall down vnto hir dampnacion.  Therfor &thorn;ou sely soule &thorn;at art troublyd, yf &thorn;ou wilte haue god to &thorn;e merciable, suffre &thorn;e to be restreyned with &thorn;es bondis of tribulacion, which come from god.  Wherof oure lord seyd to &thorn;e prophet E&yogh;echiel: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ecce dedi uincula mea super te,</FOREIGN> Lo I haue &yogh;eue my bondis vpon the.  Be &thorn;is is vnderstond &thorn;at bondys of tribulacion bene yeftis of god, &amp; &thorn;e more tribulacion is, &thorn;e strenge hyt byndeth thy soule to god.
</P><P>Also &thorn;e prophet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it spedith the wey to god; ffor als many tribulacions as &thorn;ou hast, so many messengers god hath sent to the &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuld haste to hym &amp; not lett be the weye.  Whereof seith the prophet: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Multiplicate sunt infirmitates eorum &amp; postea accelerauerunt,</FOREIGN> Hir seknesse were multiplied &amp; afterward &thorn;ei hasted hem to god.  Hereof seynt Gregor seith: Disesis &thorn;at oppressen vs, to haste to god compellene us.  Suppose &thorn;ou not &thorn;e benefette of tribulacion to be disese; for it delyueryth &thorn;e from a greuouse presone &amp; hastith &thorn;i weye to the kyngdom of heuene, as it is seid Ecc<HI
REND="sup">i</HI>. 4<HI REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="lat">De carcere cathenisque interdum quis introducitur ad regnum,</FOREIGN> From preson &amp; from yron bondis o&thorn;er-while a man is brou&yogh;t into a kyngdom.  &THORN;is preson is called all &thorn;at &thorn;e herte loueth inordinatly in &thorn;is world; &thorn;ese irone bondis arne such &thorn;ingis &thorn;at wicked affeccions bene boundyn too.  Oute of &thorn;is presone god delyueryth many oone by tribulacion, as when he putteth a-weye from hem such &thorn;ingis as &thorn;ei loue inordinatly; and &thorn;at is fygured be seint Peter &thorn;at was kept in Heroudis presone, whane oure lordis angel stode be-syde hym, on Petris syd smote, he excited hym and seyd: 'ryse vp swyth', &amp; anone the yron bondis fellen from hys hondis.  Be the syde of Petir is vnderstond &thorn;i brother, &thorn;at cam owte of &thorn;at same syde &thorn;at &thorn;ou cam of, or ellys generally all &thorn;o &thorn;at arne alyed to &thorn;e by kynred or by affynite.  For when enye of these or all which be lawe of nature ou&yogh;t to be &thorn;i frendis, is contrarious to &thorn;e, or elys is taken fro the by deth or elly[s] by ony other maner, vnderstond &thorn;ou art smytte in the syde, for &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldiste go oute of the preson of inordinate loue, &amp; sett &thorn;in herte only in god &thorn;at may not fayle &thorn;e.  But take good heed &thorn;at as Peter pleyned not vpon &thorn;e smytynge in his syde, so &thorn;ou owest not to pleyne ne to gruche of tribulacion, which delyuerth the fro the false &amp; disseyuable loue of flesshly &amp; worldly frendis; &amp; if the smytynge of tribulacion in the side be scharpe &amp; greuouse to suffer, be-hold Crist thi maker &amp; &thorn;i brother wounded in the syde for &thorn;i loue, &amp; &thorn;ou schalte suffre it &thorn;e more esily, as a trew kny&yogh;t when he seeth his lordis woundis, he felyth not his owen woundis.  Therfore refuse not &thorn;i lordis messengers &thorn;at commyne &amp; clepe &thorn;e with hym &amp; constreyne &thorn;e to haste toward hym; for he &thorn;at refuseth &thorn;e messengere, refuseth his lord.  Whan is a messengere refused?


<PB N="2: 401">

whan the herte with avisement contrarieth &amp; grucchith a-yence tribulacion.  Note well &thorn;at tribulacion turmentith in purgynge, and it purgith in turmentynge; but when the herte grucchyth a-yence tribulacion, &thorn;an he partith purgynge fro turmentynge of tribulacion, &amp; he leseth the swete &amp; profitable purgynge &thorn;orow his foly &amp; contrarious grochynge.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of the VI profet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum VI<HI
REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The sixte profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it is a &yogh;efte in payinge of &thorn;i dettis in which &thorn;ou art boundyn to god, whom &thorn;ou may not flee ne disseiue ne hyde no&thorn;inge fro hyme ofe &thorn;i dettis.  These dettis bene pennaunce which &thorn;ou owest for thy synnes; &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;e euerlastyng pennaunce be det for on dedly synne by the ry&yogh;twisnesse of god, neuerthelesse by his mercy it is chaunged in to temporall pennaunce by contricion &amp; confession, &amp; ferthermore it is for-yeuen by satisfaccion.  &amp; som-tyme it is all relesed namely by tribulacion.  Wherof vnderstond well; ffor what-so-euer thow suffreste paciently in trybulacion, afore god it is acompted to hym as a fore-paymente of thy dette.  For as a lordis auditor som-tyme in the ende of acompte leyth a cownter of brasse or coper or a nother &thorn;inge of a lytyll value to be worth or sygnifie an hundri&thorn;e pound of gold or syluer, so tribulacion of lytill tyme, with pacience receyued in &thorn;is present lyfe, delyuerth &thorn;e from euerlastynge tribulacion of &thorn;e peynes of hell, &amp; bryngeth &thorn;e into euerlastynge blisse of the rich kyngdom of heuen.  Wherof we hane ensample of the &thorn;efe &thorn;at hynge on Cristis ry&yogh;t syd, &thorn;at, when he suffred &thorn;e tormente of &thorn;e crosse &amp; was bound by du det of syn to peyne of hell, he, hauynge contricion of his wickidnesse, in &thorn;at same oure turned hym to [his lord &amp; seyde: 'Lorde, when &thorn;ou comest in to &thorn;i kyngdom,] &thorn;enke on me': &amp; anone he was vnbounde &amp; delyuerd from all &thorn;e dette of peyne &amp; herd &thorn;e swete voice of Crist seiyng to hym: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Amen dico tibi, hodie mecum eris in paradiso,</FOREIGN> Sothly I sey &thorn;ou schalt to-day be with me in paradise.  Wo to hym &thorn;at no&thorn;inge payeth of his dette in &thorn;is lyfe, but addith syn vpon syn; wo to hym: of large expencis &thorn;at he makith he schalbe constreyned to com to streyte accomptis.  So&thorn;ely such as hath leued euer with-oute acomptis, must pay for her dettis euerlastynge payne in hell with-owte any relese.  &THORN;er schullen wepe many marchauntis &thorn;at in &thorn;is lyf law&yogh;hen &amp; ioyen; wherof it is seyd in &thorn;e boke of Apocolipsis: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Mercatores terre flebunt,</FOREIGN> Marchauntis of &thorn;e er&thorn;e schullene wepe.  Marchauntis of the erth, arne &thorn;o &thorn;at sett all &thorn;er &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; her loue on er&thorn;ely &thorn;ingis; which shullen wepe bitterly, ffor god schall schew her marchaundyse to all the world.  But marchauntis of heuen, &thorn;ei schullene law&yogh;e &amp; enioye, for &thorn;ei for suffryng lyttill schort tribulacion hane gette the blysse of paradyse; where-of yt is seyd in Ecclesiastici: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Est qui multum redimit de modico precio,</FOREIGN> Some &thorn;er bene &thorn;at byen much &thorn;inge with lyttill price, &thorn;at is to seye, pacience in tribulacion of this present lyfe, &thorn;at god receyueth for &thorn;i gret dette, for it is communly seid: 'of an euyll payer men receyueth otis for whete'.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;e it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte not bounde in eny dette of dedly syne or veniall fro which tribulacion schulde delyuer the, neuerthelesse tribulacion reseruith the frome fallynge into dette, [for] as seynt Gregor seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Multa sunt innocencia que cito innocenciam perderent, nisi ea tribulaciones p[reseru]arent,</FOREIGN> Many ben innocentus the which schuld lese innocensi, but yf tribulacion preserue hem.  Therfor &thorn;ou soule &thorn;at fyndest &thorn;e bounde in dettis, or &thorn;ou &thorn;at dredist &thorn;e payment, suffer paciently tribulacions as longe as tyme indureth, hyt payeth to god for &thorn;in dettis in the which &thorn;ou arte bounden as by an oblygacion.  For &thorn;ou&yogh; all &thorn;e tribulacion[s] of &thorn;is world weryne to-gyder, &thorn;ei my&yogh;t not be lykened to &thorn;e leste payne of tribulacion of hell.  Ne all &thorn;e tribulacion[s] of erth be not in com-


<PB N="2: 402">

parisone of the leste ioye of paradyse, as seynt Poule seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non sunt condigne passiones huius temporis ad futuram gloriam que reuelabitur in nobis, Ad Romanos octauo;</FOREIGN> Ther be non worthi passions of &thorn;is tyme to &thorn;e blysse &thorn;at is to come &thorn;at schalbe shewed in vs.  Vpone &thorn;is seithe seynt Bernard: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non sunt condigne passiones ad preteritum peccatum quod nobis dimittitur, ad presentem gloriam que nobis inmittitur,</FOREIGN> Ther be no worthy passions to &thorn;e syne &thorn;at is foryeuen us, to &thorn;e present grace &thorn;at is yeue[n] us, [&] to blisse commynge &thorn;at is be-hy&yogh;t vs.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of &thorn;e seuenth prophet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum septimum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The seuenth profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it spredith a-brode or opynneth &thorn;in herte to receyue &thorn;e grace of god.  For gold with many strokis of the hammer spredith abrode, as a pece of gold or of syluer to make a vessell for to put in wyne or preciouse licoure; so all-my&yogh;ty god makith of euery creature, &amp; ordeyneth tribulacion to sprede or open the soule to put &thorn;er-in &yogh;eftis of his grace.  Wherof seith the prophet in &thorn;e salme: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In tribulacione dilatasti michi,</FOREIGN> In tribulacion thou hast spred abrode &thorn;e herte, in suffrynge paciently &amp; &thorn;e more gladly &yogh;eftis &thorn;at oure lord god putteth therin graciouslye.  &amp; considre as &thorn;e more [pre]ciouse metall is more ductible &amp; obeyinge to &thorn;e strokis of &thorn;e goldsmyth, so &thorn;e more prec[i]ouse &amp; meke herte is more pacient in tribulacion.  &amp; all-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e scharpe stroke of tribulacion greuously turmentith &thorn;e, yet comforte &thorn;e, for &thorn;e goldsmyth, almy&yogh;ti god, holdynge &thorn;e hammer of tribulacion in his honde, knoweth full well what &thorn;ou maist suffre, &amp; mesureth his smytynge after &thorn;i freel nature.  Ne will not &thorn;ou be &thorn;an as metall in a boystous gobette, with-owte spredynge of schape, as hard hertis bene with-oute techynge, in which god fynt no place in worchynge.  Ne will &thorn;ou not be as an oold fryinge-panne &thorn;at for frelte of a lytill stroke [al to-breste in mannys brekynge; right so farin frele &amp; impacient hertis in tribulacion, by a litille stroke] in temptacion of assayinge &thorn;ei fall in to many gret harmys of apayrynge.  Therfor suffre with good will tribulacion to worch his crafte in &thorn;e; for so byddith Salomon Ecc<HI
REND="sup">i</HI>. II<HI REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Sustine sustentaciones dei coniungere [te] deo, &amp; sustine ut crescat in nouissimo uita tua,</FOREIGN> Suffer &thorn;e berynge&mdash;vp of &thorn;e helpis of god to ioyne &thorn;e to god, &amp; suffre, &thorn;at &thorn;i [lyfe] increce at &thorn;i laste ende; as who seith: Suffer tribulacion in &thorn;is world for god, for whi god suffred many for the, &amp; yeld hym somwhat &thorn;e whyle of his seruyse; &amp; what tribulacion he putteth to the, take it mekely, &amp; know well &thorn;at he woll not charge &thorn;e ouer &thorn;i my&yogh;t, as seynt Poule wittenessith, ad Corinth. X<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Fidelis [est], deus, qui non pacietur vos temptari super id quod potestis,</FOREIGN> Sothly god ys full trew, &thorn;at schal not suffre you to be temptid ouer &thorn;at ye mow suffre.  Therfor suffre tribulacion in such maner, &thorn;at &thorn;i lyfe increce at &thorn;e laste ende; for &thorn;er-by &thorn;ou schalt leue after &thorn;ou hast made ende in &thorn;is world.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD>Of &thorn;e VIII profet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum VIII.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The VIII profet of tribulacion is whereby god shettith owte of the soule all worldly comfortis &thorn;at bene here-benethe, &amp; constreyneth &thorn;e to seke heuenly comfortes &thorn;at bene above.  As an erthly lord, whan he wyll sell hys wyne, forbyddith all o&thorn;er to open her tauernes, till &thorn;at he haue sold his: so oure lord god som-tyme forbyddyth erthly comfortis, &thorn;at he may brynge forth hys comforte.  &amp; &thorn;at is tokened by the prophet Ioell where it is seyd: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Bestie agri quasi arena sciciens ymbrem suspexerunt ad te: quoniam exsiccati sunt fontes aquarum,</FOREIGN> The


<PB N="2: 403">

bestis of the feeld bene as drye erth desyrynge reyne, &thorn;ey loken vp to the, for &thorn;e wellis of watris ben drye.  The bestis of the feld ben clepid affeccions &amp; flesshly desyres, the wellis of &thorn;e water he clepith worldly comfortis; &thorn;erfor whan &thorn;e erthly confortis faylen in aduersite, &thorn;an is &thorn;e herte constreyned to loke vp &amp; to seke help of heuenly comfortis; and so much more benynge is oure lord god to the soule, in asmuch as &thorn;e hert fynt gretter bitternesse in inward &thorn;ingis.  But now by these &thorn;ingis &thorn;ou maist sei: '[Of] &thorn;at I am not sory &thorn;at &thorn;e tauerne of er&thorn;ely comfortis is not opyn to me, but for &thorn;e tauerne of heuenly comfort is so longe shit fro me, for ne&thorn;er hy&yogh;er ne lower I fynd no comforte'.  To &thorn;is may be answered &thorn;us: &THORN;ou owest to haue gostly comforte, yf &thorn;ou besy the desyrynge &amp; sekynge, for &thorn;er is more myrth in the desyrynge &amp; sekynge of god &thorn;an [in] delytinge in hym; for whi &thorn;e more &thorn;ou desirest &amp; sekyst god, &thorn;e more comforte he schal brynge &thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;e more swetnesse &thorn;ou schalt fynde in hym, as mete sauereth more to an hungry man &thorn;an to an vnhungrye man; &amp; wit &thorn;ou well &thorn;at heuenly comfortis schul not longe be deferred, yf worldly comfortis be shette owt by tribulacion, yf &thorn;ou aske desyryngly &amp; seke besylye, as Salomone seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Desiderium suum iustis dabitur,</FOREIGN> To ry&yogh;twismen schalbe &yogh;euen her desyre &amp;c.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of the IX<HI REND="sup">th</HI> profet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulum nonum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The IX profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it putteth &thorn;e vnto the mynde of god, &amp; &thorn;e more &thorn;e tribulacion be, &thorn;e more he impressith &thorn;e in his mynde.  Not for &thorn;at god for&yogh;etteth &thorn;e or eny creature, &thorn;e which sei&thorn;e &amp; knoweth all &thorn;e preuyte of &thorn;e herte, but for &thorn;at scripture seith god foryettith a man &thorn;at tribulacion ys not &yogh;euene to; ffor hym &thorn;at he sendyth tribulacion he hath in mynd, &yogh;euynge goostly comforte &amp; incresynge of grace.  Therfor O &thorn;ou good soule, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou wilt be put in &thorn;e mynde of god in whoes mynd is &thorn;in helth &amp; &thorn;i saluacion&macr;, in whoes foryettynge is &thorn;in harme &amp; &thorn;i dampnacion, leren &thorn;erfor to suffre paciently aduersitees &amp; tribulacions, &amp; in &thorn;i suffring &thorn;inke mekely in god, &amp; he eftsons schall &thorn;inke mekly on the &amp; merciably; for a trew frend &thorn;inketh more frendly on his frende &thorn;at is in disese, &thorn;an yf he were withowte desese.  In figure here-of oure lord seith Ex<HI
REND="sup">o</HI> III<HI REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Vidi affliccionem populi mei qui est in Egipto, &amp; clamorem eius audiui,</FOREIGN> I haue seyen the desesis of my peple &thorn;at is in Egipt, &amp; I haue herd hyr cryinge for &thorn;e duresse of hem &thorn;at bene ouerseers of &thorn;e werkes, &amp; I know her sorrow, &amp; I haue goo downe to delyuer hem from &thorn;e hondis of &thorn;e Egipcions.  Therfor all-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e Egipcions, &thorn;at is to sey euell men or enemyes, turmentyne &amp; desesyn &thorn;e, be &thorn;ou comforted, for &thorn;e merciable beholdynge of god in &thorn;i disese much more avayleth the; as we redine of Dauid, II Regum XVI<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>, ffleyng from his sone Absolone, &thorn;at Semey, which was Dauid his enemye, cursed hym &amp; spake euel to hym &amp; seyd: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Egredere egredere, uir sanguinum &amp; uir Beliall,</FOREIGN> as who seith go &thorn;i weye go thi wey, &thorn;ou mane of synnes &amp; &thorn;ou man of Belyall; and Abisay, &thorn;at was Dauid is frend, seynge &thorn;is seyd to kyng Dauid: 'This dede hounde hath mysseyd or cursed my lord the kynge; I schal goo &amp; smyte of his heed': &amp; Dauid answerd: 'Suffer hym to mysseye or curse Dauid vp &thorn;e commaundement of god; perauenture god will be-hold my desese &amp; yeld me good for his mysseyinge &amp; cursynge &thorn;is same daye'.  Considre in &thorn;is &thorn;at Dauid wold suffer &thorn;e mysseyinge or &thorn;e cursynge of &thorn;is aduersarye, &thorn;at he my&yogh;t gett &thorn;e blissynge of god; &thorn;an loke how much &thorn;ou desire[st] &thorn;e blessynge of god, suffer so much paciently &thorn;e mysseyinge or cursynge of &thorn;e aduersarye, ffor pacience of euell mennys cursynge disserueth to haue goddis blissynge.  &amp; &thorn;at is tokened where it is seyd Daniel III<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: That the angel went doun with A&yogh;arye &amp; his felowes in to &thorn;e forneis, &amp; he made &thorn;e myddes of the forneis as a blowynge wynde of a dewe; but &thorn;e flame brent &thorn;e kyngis mynisters &thorn;at hett &thorn;e forneis, but sothly &thorn;e fyre touched not ne greued hym in any maner.  Lo here &thorn;ou mayste see &thorn;at &thorn;e fire not oonly brente


<PB N="2: 404">

hir fomen; but also it refresshed hem; be which is vnderstond &thorn;at Crist is present with hem &thorn;at be in tribulacion, &amp; yeueth hem refresshynge in desese, &amp; blessith hem &thorn;at ben mysseyde or cursed for his name.  Therfor yf &thorn;ou desyre refresshynge in tribulacion, &amp; &thorn;in enemyes to be brent, suffer paciently tribulacions, for in tribulacion god is with &thorn;e, &amp; fro tribulacion he schall delyuer the, &amp; for tribulacion gret meed he schall yeld the.  Of thes thre spekyth &thorn;e prophete where he seith &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cum ipso sum in tribulacione, eripiam eum, et glorificabo eum,</FOREIGN> I am with hym in tribulacion&mdash;lo here a graciouse fellowshyp comfortyng; I schall delyuer hym&mdash;lo here a full feith of delyuerynge; &amp; I schall gloryfye hyme&mdash;lo here a serteyne hope of rewardynge.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> The X profet of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum decimum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The X profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at it makith &thorn;i praier to be herd of god; ffor it is note &thorn;e maner of god to put awey the praier of hym &thorn;at is in tribulacione, but rather mekely to here his prevy praier.  Wherof seith Salomon: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ecce deprecacionem lesi exaudiet,</FOREIGN> Lo oure lord schall here &thorn;e praier of hym &thorn;at is hurte.  Sothly god smytyth &amp; chastiseth many men &amp; sent hem tribulacion, for to compell hem to aske or to cry mercy, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei schuldy[n] opyne hyr mouthes to god in tribulacion for to aske help, which hadden schett hyr mouthes frome hyme in prosperite.  Wherof seith seynt Austene &thorn;at god sendith tribulacion to some men to styre hem to aske &thorn;at he woll graunte.  In &thorn;e persone of such seith &thorn;e prophet: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ad dominum cum tribularer clamaui, et exaudiuit me,</FOREIGN> When I was in tribulacion, I cryed to oure lord, &amp; he herd me.  &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;e-all it hap &thorn;at in prosperite &thorn;ou prayest god, &thorn;at prosperite schull not make &thorn;e to slowe, yet neuertheles it makyth the sumetyme both insolente &amp; slowe, so &thorn;at &thorn;i prayer in prosperite is not so spedfull as it [is] in aduersite.  &amp; all-&thorn;ou&yogh;e aduersite occupye so much &thorn;in hert &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;enkest &thorn;at it hath none entente ne deuocion lyke as it had in prosperite, yet &thorn;at same aduersite makith &thorn;i prayer more precious.  And sothely all-&thorn;ou&yogh;e tribulacion oppresse the so moch &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist not open &thorn;i mouth to crye to god, certeinly thi tribulacione crieth and prayeth to god for &thorn;e, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue pacience; for as seith a gret clerke, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Magister Petrus,</FOREIGN> of La&yogh;ar, That als many woundis, so many prayers or cryers he had to god: ffor when La&yogh;ar stilled with his mouth, his woundis cryeden to god for hym.  Wherof oure lord seyd to Cayme &thorn;at had kylled his broder Abell, Genes.: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vox sanguinis fratris tui Abel clamat ad me de terra,</FOREIGN> The blood of thy broder Abell crieth to me fro the erth.  Thus &thorn;an ite schewyth &thorn;at tribulacion makith the prayer &thorn;e more preciouse &amp; &thorn;e more acceptable to god.  Tribulacions ben as it were a payment for a letter seled of delyueryng; wherof seith Iob: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quis michi det ut ueniat peticio mea, et quod expecto tribuat michi deus; qui cepit me ipse me conuertat, soluat manum suam et succidat me, &amp; [hec] michi sit consolacio ut affligens me dolorem non parcat:</FOREIGN> Who sch l geve me myn askynge, &amp; who schal graunt me &thorn;at I abyde?  god &thorn;at began me, he comforte me, louse he his hondis &amp; cut me vp, &amp; &thorn;at be to me comforte &thorn;at he turmentynge me spare not my sorrow.  Note well &thorn;at Iobe, which had lost his possessions, his sonnes &amp; his dou&yogh;ters, &amp; all his body was smyten with woundes of leper fro &thorn;e sole of the fote vnto &thorn;e ouer-parte of &thorn;e heed, &amp; was repreued of his frendis &amp; scorned of his wyfe, he desired in none other &thorn;inge comforte, but &thorn;at god schulde not spare hym.  Yf &thorn;ou aske what perteyneth [it] to his delyueraunce, hit may be answered &thorn;us: he asketh his affliccion or turmentis, for his turmentis wer paymentis of his dettus; [as] it is vsed in som place &thorn;at whan a pore man drynketh in a tauerne &amp; hath not wher-with to paye his scott, he asketh to be bettun &amp; so to be delyuerde.  Yf &thorn;ou aske where-in was [the] comforte of this Iobe when he asked to be turmentyde: Seynt Gregor answeryth &amp; seith That god


<PB N="2: 405">

spareth sum men here in &thorn;is world, to turmente hem afterward, &amp; som men he turmentith here which he afterward [wil] spare.  The comforte of Iobe was, &thorn;at he wist well be present tribulacion he schuld escape euerlastyng dampnacion&mdash; ffor, as it is seyd: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non iudicabit bis deus in idipsum,</FOREIGN> God schall not punnysh or deme twyse for o &thorn;ing.  &amp; &thorn;erfor &thorn;is same Iobe, &thorn;at askith &thorn;at god schuld not spare hyme here in &thorn;is world, asked in a nother place and [seid]: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Parce michi domine,</FOREIGN> Lord spare me in tyme commyng.  Therfor &thorn;at god spare &thorn;e in tyme commynge, suffer paciently here in &thorn;is world tribulacion; for tribulacion sauith the soule, as Iob seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ipse vulnerat &amp; medicinat,</FOREIGN> he wondyth &amp; he helyth; for he woundeth the body, &amp; helyth the soule.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of the XI profett of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum vndecimum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The XI profit of tribulacion is &thorn;at it kepi&thorn;e &amp; norissheth &thorn;e herte.  Sothly ry&yogh;t as fyre is kept in asshis, ri&yogh;t so &thorn;e hertis of &thorn;e frendis of god arne kept in tribulacion.  Therfor oure lord commaunded <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Exodi, quod tabernaculum saccis silicinis cooperi[re]tur:</FOREIGN> &thorn;at &thorn;e tabernacle of god schuld be heled with heren sackis, and goddis rich vessellys of gold &amp; siluer a-yence wyndis &amp; reynes; in tokenynge &thorn;at vertues of goddis seruauntis, &amp; namly mekenesse, ben kept in aduersite of tribulacion.  For tribulacion inforceth the herte to &thorn;enke on &thorn;e wrecchidnesse of his owen infirmitee, &amp; so it constreyneth a man to be meke, whan worldly prosperite had enhaunced hym be veyne-glorye above hym-selfe.  Also tribulacion noryssheth the herte, as a norice her chyld.  For as a moder with chyld cheweth hard mete, which the chyld may [not] chewe, &amp; drawith it in to her body where &thorn;at mete is turned into mylke to norissh the chyld, so Crist, &thorn;at in holy chirch is clepid oure moder for &thorn;e gretnesse of hys tendyr love &thorn;at he hath to vs, he chewed for vs bitter paynes, hard wordis, repreves &amp; sclaundrys, with bitternesse of his passione &thorn;at he suffred for us, to noryssh us &amp; strengh us gostly by ensample of hyme to suffer tribulacions &amp; aduersitees of &thorn;is world.  As wyne &thorn;at is clensed &thorn;orrow a bage-ful of spicis, chaungith his owen sauoure, drawynge to hym the sauour of &thorn;e spicis, so a man suffrynge tribulacion oweth to clense hyme by the blessed body of oure lord Ihesu, considerynge &thorn;e passyon &thorn;at he suffred for hym; &amp; so schul it be swete &amp; tollerable, &thorn;at to-fore semed full bitter &amp; vntollerable &amp;c.</P>
</DIV4><DIV4 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD> Of the XII profett of tribulacion. <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum duodecimum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>The XII profet of tribulacion is &thorn;at tribulacion is a certeyne tokyne of loue &thorn;at god hath to hem &thorn;at [it] is sente to.  Wherof he seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quos amo, arguo &amp; castigo,</FOREIGN> Hem &thorn;at I loue I vndernym &amp; chastiseth.  &amp; also Salomon seith Ecc<HI
REND="sup">i</HI>.: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Qui diligit filium, assiduat ei flagella,</FOREIGN> He &thorn;at loueth his sone, he scorgith it ofte-tymes.  Whereof seith seynt Ierome: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Summus &thorn;ater Ihesus Christus filios suos semper sub aliquo flagello uel uirga retinet, ut quando eripiuntur ab vno, sub alio capiuntur:</FOREIGN> Oure sauyoure fader Ihesu Criste kepith euer his children vndyr a scorge or a rodde, &amp; whene &thorn;ei bene delyuerd of oone &thorn;ei bene caw&yogh;t of a nother.  But oure god meke fader sent not all his scorgyngis all at onys togeder, but one after another, knowynge oure frelte; ffor he will &thorn;at no mane perisshe, but he will &thorn;at all men be saafe.  But euell men &amp; wicked &thorn;at leuen hym not ne louyn hym notte, &thorn;e which leuen with-owte scourge or tribulacion, whan no correccion of chastisynge may with-drawe heme fro her errowris, God schal ponyssh with all his arowes of vengeaunce.  For sothly all tormentis &thorn;at now ben departed abow&yogh;t in all &thorn;is world, than schulbe gadered to-gider &amp; abyde as in her owen place; as oure lord seith Deuteronomii XXXII<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Congregabo super eos mala, &amp; sagittas meas complebo in eis,</FOREIGN> I schal gader to-gider euell &thorn;ingis vpone euell


<PB N="2: 406">

men, &amp; I schall spende all myne arowes of vengeaunce amonge hem.  &THORN;erfor &thorn;ou good saule, yf &thorn;ou will be loued of god, will &thorn;ou not put awey tribulacions, for &thorn;ey schewen to &thorn;e wittnesse &amp; tokens of &thorn;e loue of god.  But perauenture yf &thorn;ou seiest &thorn;at goddis childerne take of hym bo&thorn;e good &thorn;ingis &amp; euell &thorn;ingis, [why is &thorn;e] takynge of euell &thorn;ingis schewynge or tok[n]ynge of &thorn;e loue of god more &thorn;an &thorn;e takynge of good &thorn;ingis?  To this may be answeryd &thorn;at god geuyth many good &thorn;ingis &amp; gret to his spiritual frendis, &amp; better &amp; gretter to hem &thorn;at he loueth more; but &thorn;e blissed fader of heuen louith with-oute comparisone more his blissed sone oure lord Ihesu Crist &thorn;an all &thorn;e world, &amp; yet he sent hym here many anguyshis, pouertees, tribulacions, aduersitees, sclaunders, repreves, scornyngis, many woundis, &amp; cruell deth, &amp; but fewe temporall goodis.  Than is &thorn;e &yogh;efte of aduersite more schewynge [or] tokyne of loue of god &thorn;an &thorn;e &yogh;efte of temporall prosperite.  Also for&thorn;ermore oure lord Ihesu Criste goddis sone, &thorn;at leued here in &thorn;is world, as a wise marchaunte vsed to ches good marchaundyse &amp; refused &thorn;e bad; for when &thorn;ei wold haue maade hym kynge of Iude, he refused it &amp; ches rather to flee in to deserte, &amp; when &thorn;ei sou&yogh;t him to turment hym &amp; to sle hym, he fled not but ches rather for to deye &amp; seid <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ego sum,</FOREIGN> I am he whome &yogh;e sech.  &THORN;an yf Crist was wisest in chesynge, &thorn;e which ches aduersitees, &thorn;ei bene moch folys &thorn;at dispisene tribulacion &amp; aduersitees, &amp; chosyn worldly prosperitees &thorn;at may not delyuer hem in tyme commynge from &thorn;e handis of her enemyes, the cruell fendis.  Suffer &thorn;an with Criste tribulacion, [&thorn;at] &thorn;ou mow take afterward &thorn;e crowne of lyfe in the blysse of heuen; for sothly [othir-wyse] mayst &thorn;ou not come to &thorn;at blysse, for the apostill seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Per multas tribulaciones oportet nos intrare in regnum celorum,</FOREIGN> Hit behoueth us by many tribulacions to entre in to &thorn;e kyngdome of heuen.  To the which kyngdome brynge he all us, That suffred deth oure lord Ihesus, amen.</P>
</DIV4>
</DIV3></DIV2><DIV2 N="MS Rawlinson C 894" TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main">Boke of Craft of Dying<NOTE>A translation of the Latin treatise normally referred to as the <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ars moriendi</FOREIGN>.</NOTE></HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Rawl. C 894</HEAD>
<OPENER> Here begynneth the boke of crafte of dyinge.</OPENER><ARGUMENT><P>FOr as much as &thorn;e passage of deth owt of the wrecchidnesse of the exile of this world for vnkunnyng of dyinge, not oonly to lewd men but also to religiouse men &amp; deuoute personys semith wonderfull harde &amp; ry&yogh;t perlouse &amp; also ry&yogh;t ferefull &amp; horrible: &thorn;erfor in this present mater &amp; tretis, &thorn;at is of the crafte of dyinge, is draw &amp; conteyned a schorte maner of exortacion for techynge &amp; confortynge of hem &thorn;at bene in poynt of deth.  This maner of exortacion ought sotely to be considryde, notid &amp; vnderstond in the syght of mannys soule, for dou&yogh;tles yt is and may be profitable generally to all cristen men &amp; women to haue &thorn;e crafte &amp; knowynge forto dye well.</P></ARGUMENT>

<PB N="2: 407">
<ARGUMENT><HEAD> This mater &amp; tretis conteyne&thorn;e VI partis:</HEAD><P>
The firste is [of] commendacion of deth, &amp; of cunnynge to dye well.  The secunde conteyneth &thorn;e temptaciouns ofe men &thorn;at dyene.  The thrid conteyneth &thorn;e interrogacion &thorn;at schuld be asked of hem &thorn;at bene in her deth-bed while &thorn;ei may speke and vnderstond.  The IIIIth conteyneth ane informacion with certeyne obsecracions to hem &thorn;at schulden dye.  The fyfte conteyneth an instruccion vnto hem &thorn;at schulden dye.  The VI conteyneth praiers that schulden be seyd vpone heme &thorn;at bene adyinge of sum man &thorn;at is abovte heme.</P></ARGUMENT>

<DIV3 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> <FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Capitulum primum.</FOREIGN> The ffirst chapter is of commendacion of deth, &amp; [of] cunnynge for to dye well.</HEAD><P>Thou&yogh;e bodyly deth be most dredfull of all ferefull &thorn;ingis as the philosopher seith in the thrid boke of Etikis, yet spirituall deth of &thorn;e soule is as much more horrible &amp; detestable as the soule ys more worthy &amp; more precious &thorn;an &thorn;e body, as the prophet Dauid seith <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Mors peccatorum pessima,</FOREIGN> The deth of a synfull man ys worst of all dethis; but as the same prophet witnessith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Preciosa est in conspectu domini mors sanctorum eius,</FOREIGN> The deth of good men is euer preciouse in the sy&yogh;t of god, what maner of bodyly deth &thorn;at euer thei dye.  &amp; &thorn;ou schalt vnderstond also &thorn;at not only the deth of holy martires is so preciouse, but also &thorn;e deth of all other ry&yogh;tfull &amp; [good] cristen men; &amp; ferthermore dou&yogh;tlesse &thorn;e deth of all synfull men, how longe, how wicked &amp; how cursed &thorn;ei hane bene all her lyfe be-fore to her laste ende, &amp; &thorn;ei dye in &thorn;e state of verry repentaunce &amp; contricion &amp; in &thorn;e verrey feith &amp; vnite &amp; charite of holy chirch, is acceptable &amp; preciouse in the sight of god; as seint Iohn&macr; seith in &thorn;e apocalipse:<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Beati mortui qui in domino moriuntur,</FOREIGN> Blessed be all ded men &thorn;at dien in god.  &amp; &thorn;erfor god seith in the fourth chapter of the boke of Sapience: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Iustus si morte preocupatus fuerit in refrigerio erit,</FOREIGN> A ry&yogh;tfull man &thorn;ou&yogh;e he be hasted or hastyly or sodenly dede, he schalbe had to a place of refresshynge.  &amp; so schal euery man &thorn;at dieth, yf it so be &thorn;at he kepe hym-selfe stably &amp; gouerne hym wisely in &thorn;e temptacion[s] &thorn;at he schall haue in the agony (or stryfe) of his deth as it schalbe declared afterward.  And &thorn;erfor of &thorn;e commendacion of [&thorn;e deth of] good men only, a wyse man seyth &thorn;us: 'Deth is no&thorn;ing els but a goynge owt of presone, &amp; endynge of exile, a dyschargynge of a heuy bordone &thorn;at is &thorn;e body, fynysshyng of all infirmytees, escapynge of all perellys, distroynge of all euell &thorn;ingis, brekynge of all bondis, payinge of dette of naturall dutee, turnyng a&yogh;en into his contree, &amp; entring into blisse &amp; ioye'.  &amp; &thorn;erfor it is seyde in &thorn;e VII chapter of Ecclesiastes: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Melior est dies mortis die natiuitatis,</FOREIGN> The [day] of mans deth is better &thorn;an &thorn;e day of his birth&mdash;&amp; &thorn;is is [to] vnderstond oonly of goodmen &amp; &thorn;e chosyne peple of god, for to euel men &amp; repreuable ne&thorn;er &thorn;e day of hir byrth ne&thorn;er &thorn;e day of her deth may be callyd gode.  &amp; &thorn;erfor euery good parfit cristen man, &amp; also euery o&thorn;er mane &thorn;ou&yogh;e he be vnparfite &amp; lat conuerted fro synne, so he be verryly contrite &amp; beleuyth in god, schuld not be sory ne troublyd ne&thorn;er dred &thorn;e deth of his body in what maner of wise &amp; for what maner of cause &thorn;at he be pute therto, but gladly &amp; wilfully, with reson of his mynde &thorn;at rulyth his sensualyte, he schuld take his deth &amp; suffer it paciently, conformynge &amp; committynge fully his wyll vnto goddis will [&amp; disposicion alone, if he will go hens and dye well] &amp; surely, witnessynge &thorn;e wise man seiynge &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Bene mori est libenter mori,</FOREIGN> To dye well is to dye gladlye &amp; wilfully.  &amp; &thorn;erefor he addith &thorn;erto &amp; seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vt satis vixerim nec anni nec dies faciunt, sed animus,</FOREIGN> Nether many dayes nether many &yogh;eres cause me to sey &amp; fele &thorn;at I haue leued longe Inow, but oonly the resonable will of myn herte &amp; of my soule.  Sith more &thorn;an &thorn;at of dute &amp; of naturall ry&yogh;te all men muste nedly dye, &amp; &thorn;at whan [&] how


<PB N="2: 408">

&amp; where &thorn;at almy&yogh;ti god will, &amp; goddis will is euermore &amp; ouyr-all good in all &thorn;ingis, good &amp; iuste &amp; ry&yogh;tfull, for as Iohn&macr; Cassian seith in his Collacions: 'Almy&yogh;ty god of his wisdome &amp; his goodnesse all &thorn;ingis &thorn;at fall, both prosperite &amp; aduersite, disposith euer finally for oure profete &amp; for &thorn;e beste for us, &amp; more prouideth &amp; is besy for &thorn;e hele &amp; saluacion of his chosyn children &thorn;an we oure-selfe may or can be'; and sith, as it is afore seyd, we may not in no wise nether flee ne escape nether chaunge the in-euitable (or [in]-eschewable) necessite &amp; passage of deth: therfore we ought to take oure deth whan god will wilfully &amp; gladly without any gruchchynge or contradiccion, &thorn;orou&yogh; &thorn;e my&yogh;t &amp; &thorn;e boldnesse of &thorn;e will of oure soule vertuousely disposed &amp; gouerned by reason &amp; verry discrecion, &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;e lewd sensualite &amp; the freelte of oure flessh naturally gruch or stryue &thorn;ere-a&yogh;ence; wherof Seneca seith thus:<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Feras, non culpes, quod immutare non potes,</FOREIGN> Soffer esely &amp; blame &thorn;ou nou&yogh;te &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist not chaunge ne voyde; &amp; &thorn;e same clerke addith &amp; seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Si uis ista cum quibus vrgeris effugere, non ut alibi sis oportet sed alius,</FOREIGN> Yf &thorn;ou wilt ascape &thorn;at at &thorn;ou art strei&yogh;tly be-trapped in, it nedith not &thorn;at &thorn;ou be in a no&thorn;er place, but &thorn;at &thorn;ou be ano&thorn;er man. For&thorn;ermore, &thorn;at a cristynman may dey well &amp; surely, hym nedi&thorn; &thorn;at he cun dey: and as a wiseman seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Scire mori est paratum habere cor suum et animam ad superna, ut quandocunque mors venit paratum eum inueniat ut absque omni retraccione eam recipiat, quasi qui socii sui dilecti aduentum desideratum expectat;</FOREIGN> To cun dey is to haue a herte &amp; a soule euer redy vp to godward, &thorn;at whan &thorn;at euer deth com he may be founden a-redy, &amp; withoute any retraccion or withdrawynge receyue hym as a man wold receyue his welbelouyd &amp; trusti frende &amp; felow &thorn;at he had long abyd and lokid after.  This cunnynge is most prophetable of all cunnynge; in &thorn;e which cunnynge religiouse men specially more &thorn;an o&thorn;er, &amp; euery day contynually schuld stody more diligently &thorn;an o&thorn;er men &thorn;at &thorn;ei my&yogh;t apprehende yt, namly for &thorn;e state of religyone aski&thorn; &amp; requireth it more in hem &thorn;en in other, not-withstondynge &thorn;at euery seculer man, bo&thorn;e clerke &amp; laye-man, where he be disposed to dye or no yet neuer&thorn;elesse he must nedis dye whan god will.  Therfor ought euery man not only religiouse but also euery good &amp; deuou&yogh;t cristen man &thorn;at desire&thorn; to dye well &amp; surely, leve in such wise &amp; so be-haue hym-silfe all-wey &thorn;at he may sauely deye euery oure when god will, &amp; so he shuld haue his lyfe in pacience, &amp; his de&thorn; in desire, as seynt Poule had whan he seyde: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cupio dissolui &amp; esse cum Christo,</FOREIGN> I desire &amp; coueit to be dede &amp; to be with Crist. / &amp; &thorn;us much suffisith at &thorn;is tyme schortly seyd of &thorn;e crafte of dyinge.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> The secund chapter is of &thorn;e temptacion[s] of men that dyene. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulum secundum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>

<P>Knowe all men dou&yogh;tles &thorn;at men &thorn;at dyen in her last siknesse &amp; ende hane grettest &amp; most greuouse temptacions, &amp; such as &thorn;ei neuer had be-for in all her lyfe; &amp; of &thorn;ese temptacions v be most principall.  The first is of &thorn;e fei&thorn;e, for as much as feyth ys fundament of all mannys soule-hele, wittnessyng the apostill &thorn;at sei&thorn;e: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fundamentum aliud nemo potest ponere,</FOREIGN> O&thorn;er fundament no man may put; &amp; &thorn;erfor seynt Austen sei&thorn;e: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fides est bonorum omnium fundamentum &amp; humane salutis inicium,</FOREIGN> Fei&thorn;e is fundament of all goodnesse, &amp; begynnynge of mannys hele; &amp; &thorn;erfor sei&thorn; seint Poule: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sine fide impossibile est deo placere,</FOREIGN> Yt is vnpossible to plese god withoute fei&thorn;e; &amp; seynt Iohn&macr; seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Qui non credit iam iudicatus est,</FOREIGN> He &thorn;at beleui&thorn; not is now demyd.  &amp; for as much [as] &thorn;ere is such &amp; so gret strengh in fei&thorn;e &thorn;at withoute it no man may be sauid, &thorn;erfor &thorn;e deuyll with all his my&yogh;te is besy to auerte fully a man fro &thorn;e fei&thorn;e in [his] last ende, or yf he may not &thorn;at, he labori&thorn;e besily to make hym dou&yogh;t &thorn;erin or sumwhat draw hym out of &thorn;e wey, or disceyue hym with som maner of super-


<PB N="2: 409">

sticiose &amp; false errouris or herisies.  But euery good cristene man is bound naturally namely habitualle &thorn;ou&yogh; he may not actually &amp; intellectually apprehende hem, to beleve &amp; full fei&thorn;e &amp; credence yeue not only to &thorn;e principall articles of &thorn;e fei&thorn;e but also to all holy wrytt in all maner of &thorn;ingis, &amp; fully to obey &thorn;e statutis of &thorn;e chirch of Roome, &amp; stabilly to abyd &amp; dey in hem; ffor also sone as he begynne&thorn;e to erre &amp; dou&yogh;t in eny of hem all, as sone he go&thorn;e out of &thorn;e weye of lyfe &amp; his soule-hele.  But witt &thorn;ou well withowte doute &thorn;at in &thorn;is temptacion, &amp; all o&thorn;er &thorn;at followene after, the deuyll may not noy &thorn;e ne prevaile ayence no mane in no wise as longe as he hath vse of his free will &amp; of reason well disposed, but yf he will wilfully consent to his temptacion; &amp; &thorn;erfor no verrey cristen man ou&yogh;t not to dred eny of his illusions or his false persuasions or his feyned feryngis or gastyngis, for Crist hym-selfe sei&thorn;e in &thorn;e gospell: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Diabolus est mendax &amp; pater eius,</FOREIGN> The deuell is a lyar &amp; fader of all lesyngis; but manly &thorn;erfor &amp; styfflye &amp; stedfastly abyde &amp; perseuyr &amp; dey in &thorn;e verrey fei&thorn;e &amp; [vnite] &amp; obedyence of oure moder holy chirch.  &amp; it is ryght prophetable &amp; good, as it is vsed in some re[li]giones whan [a] man is in his agonye (or stryfe) of dyinge, with an hy&yogh; voice oft-tymes to sey &thorn;e crede before hym, &thorn;at he &thorn;at is sike may be [fortified] in stablenes of &thorn;e fei&thorn;e, &amp; fendis &thorn;at mow not suffre to here ite mow be voyded &amp; drawen awey from hym.  Also [to] stablenesse of verry fei&thorn;e schuld strengh a sike man principally the stable fei&thorn;e of oure holy faders Abraham, Isaac &amp; Iacob, the perseuerantly abydynge fei&thorn;e of Iobe, of Raab &thorn;e womane, &amp; Achior, &amp; such o&thorn;er, [and also the fei&thorn;e of the apostils, and of] martiris, confessours &amp; virgyns vnnombirable; ffor by &thorn;e fei&thorn;e all &thorn;o &thorn;at hane [be] of old tyme befor vs, &amp; all &thorn;ei &thorn;at be nowe &amp; schalbe here-after, &thorn;ei all plesene &amp; haue &amp; schall plese [god] bi feyth; for as it is aforseyd, withoute fei&thorn;e it is imposible to plese god.  Also double profytt schuld induce euery syke man to be stable in fei&thorn;e: One ys for fei&thorn;e may do all &thorn;ingis, as oure lord hym-selfe witnessith in the gospell &amp; sei&thorn;e: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnia possibilia sunt credenti,</FOREIGN> All &thorn;ingis be possible to hym &thorn;at beleuyth stedfastly. Ano&thorn;er is, for verry fei&thorn;e getti&thorn; a man all &thorn;ingis, as oure lord sei&thorn;e: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quicquid orantes petitis, credite quia accipietis, &amp; fiet vobis,</FOREIGN> What &thorn;inge &thorn;at euer it be &thorn;at ye wollen praye &amp; [aske], beleuyth verryly &thorn;at ye schull take it &amp; [ye] shull haue it, &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;at ye wold sey to an hyll &thorn;at he schuld lyfte him-selfe vp &amp; fall in to &thorn;e see,&mdash;as &thorn;e hilles of Capsie be preier &amp; peticion of kynge Alysaunder &thorn;e gret conqueroure were closed to-gider.  The secund temptacion is disperacion, &thorn;e which is a-yenst hope &amp; confidence &thorn;at euery good man schuld haue vnto god; for when a sike man ys turmentid sore &amp; vexid with sorow &amp; siknesse of his body, &thorn;an &thorn;e deuell is most besiest to superad (or put-vpone) sorrow to sorrow, with all &thorn;e weyes &thorn;at he may obiectynge his synnes ayence hym for to induce hym into dispeire.  Forthermore, as Innocente &thorn;e pope in his &thorn;rid boke of &thorn;e wrecchidnesse of mankynd sei&thorn;e: Euery man bo&thorn;e good &amp; euell, er his soule pas out of his body, he seith Crist put in &thorn;e crosse, the good man to his consolacion, the euell man to his confusion, to make hym aschamyd &thorn;at he hath lost &thorn;e frute of his redempcion.  Also, the deuell bryngith a&yogh;en to mannys mynde that is in poynt of deth, specialli the synnes that he hath don &amp; was not schreven of, to draw hym &thorn;erbye vnto dispaire.  But &thorn;erfor ther schuld no man dispaire in no wyse; for &thorn;ough eny o man or woman had do als many theftis or manslauters or as many other synnes as be droppis of water in the see &amp; grauell-stones in the stronde, though he neuer had do pennaunce for hem afore ne neuer had bene shreven of hem afore, neither &thorn;an my&yogh;t haue no tyme for syknesse or lacke of spech or schortnesse of tyme to be shreuen of hem, yette schuld he neuer dispeire; ffor in such a cas verry contricion of herte with-in, with wyll to be schreven if tyme sufficed, is sufficient &amp; acceptable to god for to [s]aue hym with euerlastyngly; as the prophet witnessith in the psalme: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cor contritum &amp; humiliatum

<PB N="2: 410">

deus non despicies,</FOREIGN> Lord god thou wilt neuer dispice a contrite &amp; a meke hert; and E&yogh;echiel seith also: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In quacunque hora conuersus fuerit peccator et ingemuerit, saluus erit,</FOREIGN> In what oure &thorn;at euer it be &thorn;at the synful man is sory inward &amp; conuerted fro his syne, he schalbe saued.  &amp; &thorn;erfor seynt Bernard seith: The pite &amp; &thorn;e mercy of god is more &thorn;en eny wickidnesse; &amp; Austene vpon Iohn&macr; seith: We schuld neuer dispeire of [no]man als longe as he is in &thorn;is bodily lyfe, for &thorn;ere is no syn so gret but it may be helyd, outakyn dispaire alone; &amp; seynt Austen seith also: All synnes &thorn;at a man hath done afore, mow not noye ne dampne a man, but he be well a-payde in his herte &thorn;at he hath don hem.  &THORN;erfor no mane schulde dispaire, &thorn;ou&yogh;e it were so &amp; it were possible &thorn;at he alone had don all maner of synnes &thorn;at my&yogh;t be done in &thorn;e world; for be dispaire a man gettith nou&yogh;t ellys but &thorn;at god is moch more offendid &thorn;erby, &amp; all his o&thorn;er synnes bene more greuouse in goddis sy&yogh;t, &amp; euerlastyng payne is therby augmentyd infinitlye to hym &thorn;at so dispaireth.  Therfor a-yence dispeire for to induce hym &thorn;at is syke &amp; laborith in his dying to verry trust &amp; confidence &thorn;at he schuld principally haue to god at that tyme, the disposicion of Criste in the crosse schuld grettly draw hym, of the which seynt Bernard seith thus: What man is it &thorn;at schuld not be rauysshed &amp; draw to hope &amp; to haue full confidence in god, &amp; he take heed diligently of the disposicione of Cristis body in the crosse; take heed &amp; see his heed enclyned to salue the, his mouth to kysse the, his armes I-spred to be-clyp the, his hondis I-thrilled to yeue the, his syde opened to loue the, hys body alonge strau&yogh;t to yeue all hym-selfe to the.  Therfor no man schuld dispeire [of] foryevenesse, but fully haue hope &amp; confidence in god; for the vertu of hope is gretly commendable &amp; of gret merite before god, as the apostill seith &amp; exortith us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nolite amittere confidenciam vestram, que magnam habet remuneracionem,</FOREIGN> Lesith not youre hope &amp; confidence in god, &thorn;e which hath gret reward of god.  Forthermore &thorn;at no synfull man schuld in no wyse dispeire haue he synned neuer so gretly ne neuer so sore ne neuer so ofte, ne neuer so longe contynued therin, we haue [open] ensample [in] Peter &thorn;at denyed Crist, in Poule &thorn;at pursued holy chirch, in Matheu &amp; &YOGH;ache the publicanes, in Mary Maudeleyne the synful woman, in the woman &thorn;at was takyn in avoutry, in the thefe &thorn;at honge on the crosse be-sid Crist, in Mary Egipciane, &amp; vnnomberable o&thorn;er greuouce &amp; grete synners.  The thrid temptacion is in-pacience, the which is ayenst charite bi the which we be bounden to loue gode above all &thorn;ingis: for &thorn;ei &thorn;at bene in syknesse in her deth-bed suffren passyngly gret payne &amp; sorrow &amp; woo, &amp; namly they &thorn;at dyen not be nature &amp; course of age &thorn;at hapynneth ryght selde as [open] experience scheweth all daye to euery mane, but dyen oft-tymes thorow an accidentall seknesse, as a fever, a posteme &amp; such other greuous &amp; paynfull &amp; long seknes, the which many men, &amp; namly hem the which bene vndisposed to dye &amp; dyen ayenst her wyll, &amp; lackene verry charite, makyth so inpacyent &amp; grucchynge, &thorn;at other-while thorow woo &amp; inpacience &thorn;ei be-com wood &amp; witles, [as] it hath ofte be seyen in many men; &amp; so be &thorn;at it is open &amp; certeyne &thorn;at &thorn;ey &thorn;at dyen in &thorn;at wyse faylen &amp; lac verry charite, wittnessynge seynt Ierome &thorn;at seith &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Si quis cum dolore egritudinem uel mortem suscipit, signum est quod deum sufficienter non diligit,</FOREIGN> that is to seye: Who so takyth syknesse [or deth] with sorrow &amp; displesaunce of herte, it is ane open sygne &thorn;at he louyth not god sufficiently.  Therfor a man &thorn;at wyll dey well, yt is nedfull &thorn;at he gruche not in no maner of seknesse &thorn;at fallyth to hym be-fore his deth or in hys dyinge, be yt neuer so paynefull or greuouse, longe tyme or schort tyme durynge; for as seynt Gregory witnessith in his Morallys: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Iusta sunt [cuncta] que patimur, et ideo valde iniustum est si de iusta passione murmuremus:</FOREIGN> All &thorn;ingis &thorn;at we suffren we suffyr ryghtfully, &amp; &thorn;erfor we ben vnry&yogh;tfull yf we grucch of &thorn;at we suffer ry&yogh;tfully. Than euery man schuld be pacient, [for] as seynt Luke seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In paciencia vestra possidebitis animas vestras:</FOREIGN> In youre pacyence ye schull possesse youre soules; for [as]


<PB N="2: 411">

be pacience mannys soule is trewly had and kept, so be vnpacience &amp; murmuracion it is loste &amp; dampned, wittnessyng seynt Gregory in his omely &thorn;at seith &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Regnum celorum nullus murmurans accipit, nullus qui accipit murmurare potest,</FOREIGN> Ther schal no man haue &thorn;e kyngdom of heuen &thorn;at grucchit[h] &amp; is inpacient, and ther may no man gruch &thorn;at hath it.  But as &thorn;e gret clerke Albert seyth, spekyng of verry contricion: [If] a verry contrite man offerryth hym-selfe gladly to all maner affliccion of seknesse &amp; ponysshynge of his synnes, &thorn;at he may therby satisfye god worthyly for his offensis: moch more [&thorn;an] schuld euery sike man suffer paciently &amp; gladly his owen seknesse a-lone, &thorn;at is ly&yogh;ter withoute comparison &thorn;an many syknessis &thorn;at other men suffer; namlye sythen &thorn;at siknes be-fore a mannys de&thorn;e is as a purgatory to hym whan &thorn;at it is suffred as it ought, &thorn;at is to vnderstonde, yf it be suffred pacientlye &amp; gladly, with a fre [kynd] wyll of herte.  For as the same clerke Albert seyth: we hane neede to haue a free kynd wyll to god not only in such &thorn;ingis as bene to oure [consolacion, but also in such &thorn;ingis as bene to oure] affliccion.  [And] seynt Gregor seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Diuina dispensacione agitur ut prolixiori vicio prolixior egritudo adhibeatur,</FOREIGN> It is do by the dispensacion &amp; &thorn;e ry&yogh;tfull ordynacion of god &thorn;at to the lenger syn is ordeyned the lenger siknesse.  &amp; &thorn;erfor lett euery sykman &amp; namely he &thorn;at schall dye, sey as seynt Austen dyd to god: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Hic seca, hic vre, ut ineternum michi parcas,</FOREIGN> Here cutt, here brenn, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou spare me euerlastynglye.  And seynt Gregor seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Misericors deus temporalem adhibe[t] seueritatem, ne eternam inferat vlcionem,</FOREIGN> God &thorn;at is mercyfull yeveth his chosyn children temporall ponysshyngis here, lest he yeve hem euerlastyng vengeaunce ellys-where.  This temptacion of inpacience fy&yogh;tteth ayenst charite, &amp; with-oute charite may no man be saued; &amp; therfor, as seith seynt Poule: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Caritas [vera] paciens est, omnia suffert,</FOREIGN> Verry charite ys paciente &amp; suffreth all &thorn;ingis.  &amp; in &thorn;es wordis yt is notably to be marked &thorn;at he spake of suffryng of all &thorn;ingis, &amp; oute-take no&thorn;ing: &thorn;an schuld all syknesse of the body [bi reson] be suffred paciently without murmuracion or difficulte; and therfor seynt Austen seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Amanti nichil difficile uel impossible,</FOREIGN> To hym &thorn;at loueth ther is no &thorn;inge hard ne no &thorn;inge impossible.  The IIII<HI
REND="sup">th</HI> temptacion is complacens or plesaunce of a man &thorn;at he hath in hym-selfe, &thorn;at is spiritual prid, with the which &thorn;e devyll temptyth &amp; vexith most relygiouse &amp; deuoute &amp; parfite men; for when &thorn;e deuel seth &thorn;at he may not brynge a man oute of &thorn;e fei&thorn;e, ne may not induce hym vnto dispaire, ne into impaciens: &thorn;an he assaileth hym be complacens of hymselfe, puttyng such maner of temptacions in his herte: O how stable arte &thorn;ou in &thorn;e fei&thorn;e, how stronge in hope, how sad in pacience!  O how many good dedis hast &thorn;ou do! &amp; such o&thorn;er &thorn;ou&yogh;ttis.  But ayenst &thorn;ese temptacions Isodur seith thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non te arroges, non te iactes, non te [insolenter] extollas vel de te presumas, nichil boni tibi tribuas,</FOREIGN> Ne bost &thorn;e not, ne vaunte &thorn;e not proudly, ne make not moch of thi-selfe wantonly, ne&thorn;er adiecte no goodnesse to &thorn;i-selfe.  For a man may haue so much delectacion in such [maner of complacens] of hym-selfe &thorn;at a man schuld be dampnyd euerlastyngly &thorn;erfor.  And &thorn;erfor seynt Gregor seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Quis reminiscendo bona que gescit dum se apud se erigit, apud auctorem humilitatis cadit:</FOREIGN> A man &thorn;at &thorn;inke&thorn;e in good dedis &thorn;at he hath do &amp; is proud therof of hym-selfe, he fallith down anon &thorn;erfor be-for hym &thorn;at is auctor of meknes.  &amp; &thorn;erfor he &thorn;at schall dye most be ware when he felith hym temptid with pride, &thorn;at &thorn;an he low &amp; meke hym-selfe, &thorn;inkinge in his synnes &amp; &thorn;at he wit neuer whe&thorn;er he be wor&thorn;i loue or hate, &thorn;at is to sey saluacion or dampnacion.  Neuerthelesse, lest he dispayre, he mote lyfte vp his herte to god by hope, &thorn;enkynge &amp; remembrynge stably &thorn;at &thorn;e mercy of god is above all &thorn;inge &amp; all his werkis, &amp; &thorn;at god [&thorn;at] is trewe in all his wordis, &amp; &thorn;at is treu&thorn;e &amp; ry&yogh;twysnes &thorn;at nether begile&thorn;e ne&thorn;er is begiled, be-hight &amp; swor by hym-selfe &amp; seid by the prophet: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Viuo ego, dicit dominus,

<PB N="2: 412">

nolo mortem peccatoris,</FOREIGN> God all-my&yogh;ti seith: be my lyfe, I will not the deth no&thorn;er the dampnacion of no synner or of no synfull man, but &thorn;at he conuerte hym-selfe to me &amp; be saued.  Euery man schuld followe seynt Antonye to whome the deuell seyd:  'Antony, &thorn;ou hast ouercom me, ffor when I wold haue the vp by pride, &thorn;ou kepist &thorn;i-selfe a-downe by meknesse, &amp; whan I wold draw &thorn;e downe by disperacion &thorn;ou kepist &thorn;i-selfe vp by hope';&mdash;thus schuld euery man do both seke &amp; hole, &amp; &thorn;an ys the deuell ouer-com.  The V<HI
REND="sup">th</HI> temptacion &thorn;at temptith &amp; greuyth most carnall men &amp; seculer men, [is] ouer-much occupacion &amp; besynesse a-bou&yogh;t outward temporall &thorn;ingis [as her wyfes, her children, her carnall frendes, and wordely riches and other &thorn;ingis] &thorn;at &thorn;ei hane loued inordinatly before.  For he &thorn;at will dey wyll &amp; surely, most vtterly &amp; fully put oute of hys mynde all temporall &amp; outward &thorn;ingis, &amp; plenerly commytt hym-selfe all to god. &amp; &thorn;erfor the gret clerke Duns (Scotus) seith &thorn;us vpon the fourth boke of Sentence:  What man &thorn;at is seke whan he seth &thorn;at he schall dey, If he put hys wyll &thorn;erto to dey wilfully &amp; consentith fully into deth as &thorn;ou&yogh;e he had chosyn hym-selfe [&thorn;]e payne of &thorn;e deth voluntaryly, &amp; so suffreth deth paciently, he satisfyeth to god for all his veniall synnes, and forthermore he takyth aweye a parcel of satisfaccion &thorn;at he oweth to do for dedly synnes.  &amp; &thorn;erfor it is ryght profitable &amp; necessarye in such a poynte [of] nede &thorn;at a man conforme his will to goddis will in all &thorn;ingis [as] euery man ow&yogh;t both seke &amp; hole.  but seld it is seyne &thorn;at any seculer &amp; carnall man or relygiouse man [other] will dispose hym-selfe to deth, other ferthermore, &thorn;at is wors, will here ony &thorn;inge of the mater of deth &thorn;ou&yogh;e in-dede he be laborynge faste to his ende-ward, hopynge &thorn;at he schall escape &thorn;e deth&mdash;&amp; &thorn;at is [&thorn;e] most perlous &thorn;inge &amp; most inconuenient &thorn;at may be in eny cristen man, as seith the worthy clerke Cantor parisiensis.  But it is to be noted well &thorn;at the deuell in all &thorn;e temptacions above-seid may compell no man, [neither] in no maner of wyse prevayle ayenst hym to consent to hym, als long as a man hath the vse of reason with hym, but if he woll wilfully consent to hym,&mdash;&thorn;at euery good cristen man &amp; also euery synful man be he neuer so grete a synner ow&yogh;t to be were of aboue all thyngis.  For &thorn;e apostell seyth:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fidelis [est] deus qui non pacietur vos temptari supra id quod potestis, sed faciet eciam cum temptacione prouentum ut possitis sustinere,</FOREIGN> God, he seith, is trew &amp; will not suffre yow to be temptid more &thorn;an ye may bere, but he will yeue yow such supportacion in youre temptacion[s] &thorn;at ye may bere hem.  Whervpon seith the glose:  God is [trew] in his promissis, &amp; yeuyth us grace to withstond my&yogh;ttyly, manly, &amp; perseuerantly: yevyng us my&yogh;t &thorn;at we be not ouercome, [grace to gete vs meryte, stedfastnes to ouercome]; with &thorn;at he yeueth such increse of vertu &thorn;at we may suffre, and not faylle ne fall.  &amp; &thorn;at is by mekenesse, for as seynt Austen seith: Thei breken not in the forneyse &thorn;at hane not &thorn;e wynde of pride.  Therfor euerry man, ryghtfull &amp; synfull, l[ow]e hym-silfe fully vnto the my&yogh;ty honde of god, and so with his helpe he shall surely opteyne and haue the victorye in all maner of temptacion, seknesse &amp; tribulacions, euyllys &amp; sorrowes, &amp; deth therto.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>The &thorn;rid chapiter conteyne&thorn;e the interrogacions &thorn;at schulden be asked of hem &thorn;at were in her deth-bed while &thorn;ei may speke and vnderstond. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulum tercium.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>NOw followyth the interrogacions of hem &thorn;at drawen to the deth-ward while &thorn;ei hane reason with hem &amp; her spech, for &thorn;is cause &thorn;at if ony man be not fully disposed to dye, he may better be enformed, &amp; confortid therto.  And as Ancellyne &thorn;e bisshop techith, the[se] interrogacions schuld be had vnto hem &thorn;at ben in &thorn;at plyte.  Fyrst aske hym &thorn;is:  Brother, art &thorn;ou glad &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt dey in


<PB N="2: 413">

[&thorn;e] ferth of Crist?  The seke man sei&thorn;e, &yogh;e.  Knowest &thorn;ou well &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast not do so well as &thorn;ou schuldist haue do?  He answereth, &yogh;e.  Repentis &thorn;ou &thorn;e &thorn;erof? He answerith, &yogh;e.  Hast &thorn;ou will to amend, &amp; &thorn;ou haddist space and lyfe?  He answerith, &yogh;e.  Beleuist &thorn;ou fully &thorn;at oure lord Ihesu Crist goddis son dyed for the?  He answeryth, &yogh;e.  Thankyst &thorn;ou hym therof with all thy herte?  He answeryth, &yogh;e.  Beleuist &thorn;ou verily that thow maist not be sauyd but be Cristis deth and his passion?  He answerith, &yogh;e.  Than &thorn;anke hym euer therof while the soule ys in &thorn;e body, and put all thi truste [in his passion and in his dethe onely, hauyng truste] in no other &thorn;ingis; to this deth commyt the fully, with &thorn;is deth couer the fully, [in this deth wrap all thi-self fully]; and [if] it com vnto thy mynde or by thin enmye be put in to thy mynde that god will deme the, sey thus:  Lord I put the deth of oure lord Ihesu Crist be-twene me &amp; myn euell dedis, be-twene me and thi Iugement, other-wise I wyll not stryve with the; Iff he sey &thorn;at [thou hast] deserued dampnacion, sey thou a&yogh;en:  The deth of oure lord Ihesu Crist I put be-twene me and all myn euell meritis, and the merite of his worthi passione I offre for the merite that I shuld haue had and alas I haue it not; Sey also:  Lord put the deth of oure lord Ihesu Criste be-twene me and thi ry&yogh;twysnes.  &THORN;an lat hym sey &thorn;is thrise:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In manus tuas [domine] commendo spiritum meum,</FOREIGN> In to thin handis I commyt my soule; and lett the couent sey the same; and if he may not speke lett the couent, or &thorn;ei &thorn;at stont aboute, sey thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> In manus tuas commendo spiritum eius,</FOREIGN> In thin hondis lord we commend his spirit or his soule.  And thus he dyeth surely, and he schal not dye euerlastyngly.  But thou&yogh;e &thorn;ese interrogacions above-seyd be competent and sufficient to religiouse [and deuoute persones, neuertheles all crysten men bothe seculers and religiouse], after the doctour the noble clerke the chaunceller of Parise, in her laste end schuld be examyned, enquered and informed more certeynly [&amp; clerly] of the state [&] &thorn;e hele of hir soule[s]; and fyrst thus: Belevyst thowe principally an fully in the articles of the feyth, and also all holy scripture in all &thorn;ingis after &thorn;e exposicion of the holy and trew doctours of holy chirche, and forsakist all heresies, errouris and oppinions dampnid by the chirch, and art glad also &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt dey in the feyth of Criste &amp; in &thorn;e vnite &amp; obedience of holy. chirche?  The secund interrogacion shalbe this:  Knowe[lege]st &thorn;ou &thorn;at often-tymes and many-maner wises and greuously &thorn;ou hast offendid &thorn;i lord god &thorn;at made the of nou&yogh;t?  For seynt Bernard sei&thorn;e &thorn;us vpon <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cantica canticorum</FOREIGN>:  I know well &thorn;at &thorn;er maye no man be saued but yf he knowe hym-selfe, of the which knowynge wexith in a man the moder of his hel&thorn;e that is humilite, and also the dred of god, the which drede [as it is the begynnyng of wisdom, so it] is the begynnynge of helth of mannys soule.  The thryde interrogacion schalbe this: Art &thorn;ou sory in thy herte of all maner of synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast don ayenst the hy&yogh;e mageste &amp; &thorn;e loue &amp; &thorn;e goodnes of god, &amp; of all goodnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast not &amp; my&yogh;ttest haue do, &amp; of all graces &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast for-slewthed; not oonly for drede of de&thorn;e or ony other payne, but rather more for love of god &amp; ry&yogh;twisnes and for &thorn;ou hast displeased his grete goodnes &amp; kyndnes, &amp; for &thorn;e due ordre of charite by the which we be bound to loue god above all &thorn;ingis; &amp; of all &thorn;ese &thorn;ingis &thorn;ou askyst foryevenes of god?  Desirest &thorn;ou in &thorn;in herte also to haue verry knowynge of all the offensis &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast doo ayenst god and for[yete], to haue speciall repentaunce of hem all?  The IIII<HI
REND="sup">th</HI> interrogacion schalbe &thorn;is: Porposist &thorn;ou verrily and art in full wyll to amende the, and &thorn;ou myght leve lenger, and neuer to synne more dedly wittyngly and with &thorn;i will, and rather &thorn;an &thorn;ou woldist offend god dedly eny more, to leve &amp; lese wylfully all er&thorn;ely &thorn;ingis were &thorn;ei neuer so lefe to the, and also the lyf of &thorn;i body therto; and forther-more &thorn;ou prayest god to yeve the grace to contynue in this purpose?  The Vth interrogacion schalbe &thorn;is:  Foryevist &thorn;ou all maner of men &thorn;at euer ha&thorn;e don


<PB N="2: 414">

&thorn;e ony wronge or grevaunce vnto &thorn;is tyme or in word or in dede, for &thorn;e love of oure lord Ihesu Crist of whome &thorn;ou hopyst to haue foryevenes also &thorn;i-selfe; [&amp; askist also thi-selfe foryeuenes] of all hem &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast offendyd in ony maner wise?  The VI<HI
REND="sup">th</HI> interrogacion schalbe &thorn;is:  Wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;at all maner of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast in eny maner wise mysgett, be fully restored als much as &thorn;ou maist and art I-bounde, after the value of &thorn;i good, &amp; rather leve &amp; forsake all &thorn;i goodys of the world, yf &thorn;ou maist make due satisfaccion in none other wise? The seuynth interrogacion schalbe this:  Belevist &thorn;ou fully &thorn;at Crist dyed for the &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist neuer be saued but by the merite of Cristis passion, and &thorn;ankist &thorn;erof god with &thorn;in hert as much as &thorn;ou canst or maist?  Who so euer may verrily of verrye good conscience and trouth with-owte eny feynynge answere &thorn;ee to these forseyd sevyn interrogacions, he shalbe savyd verrily and hath an euydent argument I-nough of the hel&thorn;e of his soule, &thorn;at, &amp; he dye soo, he schalbe of the nombre of hem &thorn;at schalbe saued.  Who so euer is not askyd of a nother man of thes seven interrogacions when he is in such a perell of deth, for ther be ryght fewe &thorn;at have &thorn;e kunnynge of this crafte of dyinge, he most remembre hym-selfe [in his soule &amp; aske hym-selfe], &amp; sotely fele &amp; considre where he be so disposed as it is above seyde or no; for with-owte [&thorn;at] a man be disposed in such wise fynally, &thorn;ere may no man dou&yogh;tles be saved euer-lastyngly.  And what man &thorn;at is disposed as yt is above-seyd, let hym commend and commytt hym-selfe all in-fere fully to the passion of Crist, and contynually als much as he may and as hys syknesse will suffre hym lett hym remembre hym-selfe and &thorn;inke in the passyon of Crist:  for therby all the deuellys temptacions and giles be most ouercomm and voyde[d]</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> The IIII<HI REND="sup">th</HI> chapiter conteyneth ane instruccion with certeyne obsecracions to hem &thorn;at schullen dye. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulum IIII<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>FOrthermore for as much as seynt Gregor seith 'euery doynge of Crist ys oure instruccion &amp; techynge':  &thorn;erfor such &thorn;ingis as Crist dyd dyinge on the crosse, the same shuld euery man do at hys laste ende after his connyng and power.  And Crist dyd fyve &thorn;ingis in the crois: he prayed, [for he prayed] these psalmes:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Deus deus meus respice</FOREIGN> and all &thorn;e psalmes followyng next vnto &thorn;at vers <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In manus tuas,</FOREIGN> and also &thorn;at vers; and he cryed in the crosse as &thorn;e apostil witnessith; also he wept in the cross; also he commyt his soule to his fader in the cros; [also he yaf vp wilfully the gost in the crosse.  Furst he prayed in the crosse]; so a seke man &thorn;at is in poynt of deth schuld prey, namely with his herte yf he may not with his mouth, ffor seynt Isodyr seyth &thorn;at it is better to pray styll in the herte with-oute ony sounde of voyce outeward, &thorn;an to pray with wordis alo[ne] without any deuocion of herte.  The secund was he cryed; soo shuld euery man in his dying crye strongly, with &thorn;e herte, not with &thorn;e mou&thorn;e, ffor god taki&thorn;e more heed of &thorn;e desire of the herte &thorn;an of the cryinge of the voice.  The criynge of the her to god is not ellys but the gret desiringe of a man to haue foryevenesse of his synnes and euer-lastyng lyfe.  The IIId was he wept; so shulde euery man in his dyinge wepe, not with his bodyly ye&yogh; but with the terys of [his] herte, that is to sey, verrily repentynge hym of all his misdedis.  The IIII<HI
REND="sup">th</HI> was he commendyde his soule to god; so shuld euery man in his ende, seyinge &thorn;us with herte &amp; mouth if he may, and ellys in his herte:  &laquo;Lord god, into &thorn;in handis I commende my spirit; ffor truly &thorn;ou &thorn;i-selfe bou&yogh;t me dere&raquo;.  The Vth was he yafe vp wilfully his spirit; so schuld euery man in his deth, &thorn;at is to sey, he shuld dye wilfully, conformynge fully &thorn;erin his owen will to god[dis will] as he is bounde.  Therfor als longe as he &thorn;at is in poynte of deth may speke &amp; haue &thorn;e vse of reson with hym, lett hym sey the prayers followynge.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  &laquo;O thow hi&yogh;e godhed and endeles

<PB N="2: 415">

goodnes, most mercyable &amp; gloriouse trinite, &thorn;at art hy&yogh;est loue [&] charyte, haue mercy on me wrecchid sinfull man, for to the I commende fully my soule&raquo;. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  &laquo;My lord god most benyng fader, [fader] of mercy, do &thorn;i mercy to me &thorn;i pore creature, helpe now lord my nedy &amp; dissolate soule in her last nede, &thorn;at hell houndis deuoure me not.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Oracio]</FOREIGN>: Most swettest and most louely lord my lord Ihesu Criste goddis owen dere sonne, for the worship and &thorn;e vertue of &thorn;i blessid passion admytt and receyue me with-in &thorn;e nombre of &thorn;i chosen peple; my sauyoure &amp; redemptor, I yeld all my-silfe fully to &thorn;i grace and mercy, forsake me not; to &thorn;e, lord, I com: put me not aweye.  Lord Ihesu Crist, I aske &thorn;i paradise and blysse, not for the worthynes of my deseruyngis &thorn;at am but dust &amp; asshis and a synfull wrech, but &thorn;orow &thorn;e vertu &amp; effecte of &thorn;i holy passion, [bi] the which &thorn;ou vouchist-safe &amp; woldist by me synfull wrech with &thorn;i preciouse bloode &amp; brynge me into paradise&raquo;.  Let hym sey also ofte &thorn;is verse:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Dirupisti domine vincula mea, tibi sacrificabo hostiam laudis</FOREIGN>:  Lord &thorn;ou hast broke my bondis, and &thorn;erfor I shall &thorn;anke &thorn;e with &thorn;e sacrifice of the oblacion of worship; For &thorn;is verse, as Cassiodir sei&thorn;e, ys of [so] grete vertue &thorn;at a mannys synnes bene foryouen hym, and it be seyd &thorn;rise with good trewe feyth at a mannys last ende.  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>: &laquo;Lord Ihesu Crist, for &thorn;at bitternesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffrist for me in the crosse, &amp; most in &thorn;at oure whan &thorn;i most blissed soule passid out of &thorn;i body, haue mercy of my soule in hir streite passynge&raquo;.  Also afterward with all &thorn;e instaunce &amp; deuocion &thorn;at he may, with herte &amp; mouth, lett hym cry to oure blessyd lady seynt Marye &thorn;at is most spedfull and most redy mene and helpe of all synfull men to god, seying &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  &laquo;O gloriouse [lady] quene of heuen, moder of mercye, &amp; refuge of all synfull men, reconsile me to &thorn;i swete sonne my lord Ihesu, and pray for me synfull wrech to his gret mercye, that for loue of the, swete ladye, he woll foryeve me my synnes&raquo;.  &THORN;an lat hym pray to angellis &amp; sey thus:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  &laquo;Holy angels of heuen, I besech yow &thorn;at &yogh;e wold assist to me &thorn;at schall now passe out of &thorn;is world, &amp; my&yogh;tyly delyuer &amp; kepe me from all myn enemyes, and take my soule vnto youre blissed company; &amp; namly &thorn;ou good blissed aungell &thorn;at hast bene my contynuall keper ordeyned of god&raquo;.  &THORN;an lett hym pray the same wise deuoutly to all the apostillys, martires, confessoures, and virgines, &amp; specially to &thorn;o seyntis which he loued &amp; worschipped moste specially in his hele, &thorn;at &thorn;ei will helpe hym &thorn;an in his last &amp; most neede.  &THORN;an afterward lett hyme sey &thorn;ries or more &thorn;ese wordis or lyke in sentence the which ben ascryved to seynt Austene: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  &laquo;The pese of oure lord Ihesu Criste, and the vertu of his passione, and &thorn;e signe of the holy cros, &amp; &thorn;e maydenhed of oure lady blyssed, seynt Marye, &amp; &thorn;e blyssynge of all seyntis, &amp; &thorn;e kepinge of all angels, &amp; &thorn;e suffrage, of all &thorn;e chosen people of god be betwene me &amp; all myn enemyes visible &amp; invisible, in &thorn;is oure of my de&thorn;e.  Amen&raquo;.  Aftyrward let hym sey &thorn;rise &thorn;is verse:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Largire clarum vespere, quo vita nusquam decidat, sed premium mortis sacre, perhennis instet gloria,</FOREIGN> Graunt me lord a clere ende, &thorn;at my soule fall neuer downe-ward, but yeve me euerlastyng blisse, &thorn;at is &thorn;e reward of holy dying&raquo;.  And if he &thorn;at is sike can not all &thorn;is prayers, or may not sey hem for greuouse[nes] of his siknesse, lett som man &thorn;at is about hym sey hem be-fore hym as he may clerely here hym sey hem, chaungynge &thorn;e wordis &thorn;at ought to be chaunged in his seyinge; and he &thorn;at is dy[i]nge, also longe as he ha&thorn;e vse of reasone, lett hym prey deuou&yogh;tly within hym-selfe with his herte &amp; his desire as he cann &amp; may: &amp; so yeld &thorn;e gost vp to god, &amp; he shalbe saued.
</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>The fyfte chapiter conteyneth an instruccion vnto hem &thorn;at shullen dye. <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Capitulum quintum.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>But it is gretly to be notid &amp; to be take heed of, &thorn;at ri&yogh;t seld any man, [&yogh;e] amonge religiouse &amp; deuoute men, disposeth hym-selfe to de&thorn;e be tymes as he

<PB N="2: 416">

ought, ffor euery man weneth hym-selfe to leve longe, &amp; trowyth not &thorn;at he schall dye in short tyme; &amp; dou&yogh;tles &thorn;at sterynge commyth of the deuellys sottill temptacion, and ofte-tymes it is seyne opynly &thorn;at many men &thorn;orow such Idyll hope &amp; trust hath for-slewthed hem-selfe &amp; dyed or vntestate or vnavised &amp; vndisposed sodenly.  Therfor euery man &thorn;at hath loue &amp; drede of god &amp; a &yogh;eele of &thorn;e hele of mannys soule, let hym besyly induce &amp; warne euery of his euencristen &thorn;at is seke or in any perill of body or of soule, &thorn;at principally &amp; fyrst of all o&thorn;er &thorn;ingis &amp; withoute ony o&thorn;er delayes or longe tarry[i]ngis he dyligently prouid &amp; purvey for &thorn;e spirituall medycyne &amp; remedy of his soule.  For ofte-tymes, as a certeyne decretall seyth, bodyly syknes commyth of the siknes of the soule; and therfor &thorn;e pope in the same decretall chargith strei&yogh;tly euery bodyly lech &thorn;at he &yogh;eue no sekman no bodyly medicyn, vnto &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he haue warned &amp; inducid hym to sech his spirituall lech.  But &thorn;is councell ys now for-rslewthed almost of all men, &amp; is turned in to &thorn;e contrary; ffor men seken sonner &amp; besilier after medicyns for &thorn;e body, &thorn;an for &thorn;e soule.  Also o&thorn;er euellis &amp; aduersitees be ry&yogh;twise dome of god come euer-more to men for syn, as &thorn;e prophet wittnessith &thorn;at sei&thorn;e &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non est malum in ciuitate quod dominus non facit,</FOREIGN> Ther is non euell in the cite but god do it.  &THORN;ou schalt not vnderstonde &thorn;at god doeth &thorn;e euell of syn, but he yeldith ponysshinge for syn.  Wherfor euery sikman, &amp; euery other man &thorn;at is in ony perill, shuld be diligently inducid &amp; exhortid &thorn;at he make hym-selfe be-fore all o&thorn;er &thorn;ingis pes with god, resseyving spirituall medicins, &thorn;at is to seye takynge the sacramentis of holy church, ordeynynge and makynge his testament, &amp; laufully disposynge for his household &amp; other nedis if he haue any to dispose for.  &amp; &thorn;ere shuld not be yeue [first] to no man to miche hope of bodyly hele; but the contrary &thorn;erof now ys ofte-tymes do [bi] many men [into] gret perill of soules, &amp; namely of hem &thorn;at actually &amp; openly ben drawynge &amp; in poynt hastily to deye, for none of hem will here no&thorn;inge of deth; and so, as the gret clerke the chaunceler of Parise sei&thorn;e: oft-tymes bi such a veyne &amp; a false cherynge &amp; comfortyng &amp; feyned behotynge of bodyly helth, &amp; trustynge &thorn;ervponn, men ryn and fall in to certeyne dampnacion euerlastingly.  And &thorn;erfor a seke man shuld be councellyd &amp; exortid to prouide &amp; procure hym-selfe his soule-hele be verry contricion &amp; confession; &amp; if it be expedient for hym, &thorn;at schall gretly avayle to his bodyly helth, and so he schalbe mo[r]e quiete &amp; sure. And for als muche, wittnessinge seint Gregor, as a man hath seelde verry contricion, And as seint Austen sei&thorn;e also in the fourth boke of sentence the twel[f]the distinccion, and o&thorn;er doctours also, Repentaunce &thorn;at is deferryde and had in a mannis last ende, vnneth is verry repentance or pennaunce sufficient to euerlastynge hele, and specially in hem &thorn;at all her tyme be-fore nether the commaundementis of god nether her voluntarye vowes kepten not effectually ne truly, but only feynyng[ly] &amp; to &thorn;e semynge owtward: therfor euery seke man &thorn;at is in such case &amp; is com to his last ende, is to be counselled besily &thorn;at he labour with reason of his mynde after his power to haue ordynate &amp; verry repentaunce; &thorn;at is to me[n]ynge.  not-withstondynge the sorrow &amp; greuaunce of his seknes and [&thorn;e] drede &thorn;at he hath of hasty deth, &thorn;at he vse reason als moch as he maye, &amp; [in]force hym-selfe to haue full displesynge of all synnes for the due ende &amp; parfite intent, &thorn;at is for god, and withstand his euell natural in-clynynge to syn &thorn;ough he my&yogh;t leve lenger, and also &thorn;e delectacion of his synnes be-fore, and labour als much as he maye to haue a verry displesaunce of hem &thorn;ou&yogh;e it be neuer so shorte; and lest he schall fall in dispeire tell hym &amp; arme hym with such &thorn;ingis &thorn;at bene seyde above in the secund parte of the temptacion of dispeire.  Exorte hym also &thorn;at he be stronge in his soule ayenst [&thorn;e] o&thorn;er temptacions &thorn;at be put and tolde &thorn;ere also, my&yogh;tily &amp; manly withstonde [hem] all, for he may not be compellyde by the deuell to consent to none of hem all.  Also lett him


<PB N="2: 417">

be monysshed &amp; conceilede &thorn;at he dye a verry trew cristen man &amp; full beleuyd. Also it is to be considred whether he be in-volued with eny sensuris of the chirch, and if [he] be, lett hym be taught &thorn;at he summytte hym-selfe with all his my&yogh;te to the ordynaunce of holy chirch, &thorn;at he may be assoyled.  Also yf he &thorn;at schall dye haue longe tyme and space to be-&thorn;inke hym-selfe, and be not take with hasty deth: &thorn;an may be red afore hym, of hem &thorn;at be abowte hym, deuou&yogh;t histories and deuoute praiers in the which he delyted moste in whan he was in hele; or reherse be-fore hym &thorn;e commaundementis of god, &thorn;at he may be-&thorn;inke hym &thorn;e more profoundly if he may fynde in hym-selfe &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e necligently trespased a-yenst hym.  And if &thorn;e seke man haue lost his spech, [but] yit he hath hole &amp; full knowlech of the interrogacions &thorn;at be made to hym or the prayers &thorn;at bene rehersid be-fore hym, &thorn;an with som vtterly sygne or only with consent of herte lett hym answere therto.  Neuerthelesse it is gretly to be charged &amp; hasted &thorn;at &thorn;e interrogacions be made vnto hym or he lese his speche; for if his answere[s] be not lycly or shewith not in all sides to be sufficient to full hele &amp; perpetuell remedye of his soule, &thorn;an must be put &thorn;erto remedy &amp; councell in the best maner &thorn;at it may be doo: &thorn;an &thorn;ere schuld be told to hym &thorn;e perill &thorn;at he shuld [plainly] fall in, &thorn;ou&yogh;e he shuld &amp; wold gretly be a-ferde therof;&mdash;it is better and ryghtfuller &thorn;at he be compuncte and repentaunte with holsom fere and dred and so be saued, &thorn;an &thorn;at he be dampned with flaterynge and false dissimilacion; for it is to inconuenient &amp; contrary to cristen relygion and [deuellike], &thorn;at &thorn;e perill of deth &amp; of a soule for eny veyne drede of a man lest he ware ony &thorn;inge distrobilled therby shuld be hyd to ony cristen man or woman &thorn;at shuld dye.  but Isaye &thorn;e prophet did &thorn;e contrarie, ffor when kynge E&yogh;echi lay seke &amp; vpon &thorn;e poynt of de&thorn;e, he glosed hym not ne vsed no simulacion to hym, but playnly &amp; holsomly agasted hym, seyinge &thorn;at he schuld dye; &amp; yet nathelesse he dyed not at &thorn;at tyme.  And seint Gregori also holsomly agasted &thorn;e monke &thorn;at was a proprietarie, as it is red in &thorn;e [fourthe] boke of his Dialogis.  Also present to the seke &thorn;e Image of the crucifix &thorn;e whiche shuld be euermore aboute seeke men, or ellys &thorn;e Image of oure lady, or of a seynt &thorn;e whiche he loued or worshipped in his hele.  Also lett &thorn;er be holy water abowte &thorn;e seke, &amp; sprynge oft-tymes vpon hym &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at bene abou&yogh;te hym, &thorn;at fendis mowe be voyded from hem therbye.  Yf all &thorn;ingis above-seid may not be do for hastines &amp; shortnes of tyme, &thorn;an put for&thorn;e praiers, &amp; namely such as be directid specially to oure sauyoure lord Ihesu Crist.  Whan a man is in poynt of de&thorn;e &amp; hastis fast to his ende, &thorn;an schuld &thorn;ere no carnall frendis ne wife ne children ne riches ne no temporall goodis be reducid to his mynde ne&thorn;er be comoned of before him, but [in] as much [as &thorn;e] spirituall hel&thorn;e &amp; profett of &thorn;e seke man askyth &amp; requireth.  In &thorn;is mater &thorn;at is of oure last &amp; moste neede, all maner of poyntis &amp; sentencis &thorn;erof, with aduerbis also &thorn;at ben put &thorn;erto, shuld most sotely &amp; diligently be chargid &amp; considered of euery man, for alse muche as &thorn;er schal no man be rewardid for his wordis alone but for his dedis also Ioyned &amp; accordyng to his wordis, as it is seid in &thorn;e boke &thorn;at is clepid Compendy of the tru&thorn;e of diuinite, &thorn;e secund boke &thorn;e tenth chapiter.  And what man &thorn;at liste&thorn;e, &amp; will gladly dye well &amp; surely and meritorily withoute perill, he most take heede besyly and stody &amp; lerne diligently &thorn;es craft of dyinge and &thorn;e disposicions &thorn;erof above-seyd while he is in hele, &amp; not abyde vntill &thorn;at deth entre in to hym; for in truth, dere brother or sistre, I tell the soth&mdash;leve me therof&mdash;&thorn;at whan deth or gret seknesse fallith vpon the, deuocion passith owt from the, &amp; &thorn;e more nere &thorn;at [&thorn;ei taken] &thorn;e &amp; gripen &thorn;e, the ferther fleyth deuocion from the.  Therfor yf &thorn;ou wilt not be disseyued ne erre, if &thorn;ou wilt be sure, do besily what &thorn;ou maiste while &thorn;ou art here in hele &amp; hast the vse &amp; fredam of &thorn;i wittis &amp; reason well disposed, &


<PB N="2: 418">

while &thorn;ou maist be maister of &thorn;i-selfe &amp; of &thorn;i [dedis].  O lord god, how many [&yogh;e] with-oute nombre &thorn;at hane abyden soo vnto her last ende hane forslouthed &amp; deceyued hem-silfe euerlastingly.  Take heed, bro&thorn;er &amp; suster, &amp; be ware if &thorn;ou list, lest it happen &thorn;e [&thorn;e] same wise.  But lett no man wondre ne &thorn;inke &thorn;at it is inconuenient &thorn;at so grette charge &amp; diligence &amp; wise disposicion &amp; prouidence &amp; besy exortacion shuld be had &amp; mynystred to hem &thorn;at bene in poynt of de&thorn;e &amp; in her last ende as it is above seyd: for &thorn;ei be in such perill &amp; so grete nede at &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at, &amp; it were possible, all a cite schuld com to-geder with all the haste to a man &thorn;at is in dyinge; as &thorn;e maner ys in som religiouse, in which it is ordeyned &thorn;at whan a seke man ys ny&yogh;e &thorn;e deth &thorn;an euery of the bre&thorn;erne schall when &thorn;ei here &thorn;e table ysmyte, what oure &thorn;at euer it be &amp; where &thorn;at euer &thorn;ei be, all &thorn;inge I-lefte hastily to com to hym &thorn;at is dying; &amp; &thorn;erfor it is redde &thorn;at religiouse people, &amp; women, for &thorn;e honeste of hir astate schall not ren, but to a man &thorn;at is a-dyinge, [&] for fere.
</P>
</DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD> The sixte Chapiter conteyneth praiers &thorn;at shullen be seid vpon hem &thorn;at bene a-dyinge of som man &thorn;at is abowt him.<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Capitulum VI<HI REND="sup">m</HI>.</FOREIGN></HEAD>
<P>LAst of all it is to be knowe &thorn;at &thorn;e praiers &thorn;at followen mow be conueniently seyd vpon a seke man &thorn;at laborith to his ende.  &amp; if it be a religiouse person, &thorn;an whan &thorn;e couent is gadrid to-gidre with &thorn;e smytynge of the table as &thorn;e maner is, &thorn;an shall be seyd first the letanye with the psalmis &amp; orisons &thorn;at ben vsed &thorn;er-with; afterward, if he leue yet, let som man &thorn;at is aboute hym sey the orisons that followen after as the tyme &amp; oportunyte will suffre, &amp; &thorn;ei mowen be oft rehersid ayene to excite &thorn;e deuocion of the seke man if he haue reason &amp; vnderstondynge with hym; but netheles &thorn;is ought not to be do of necessite, as &thorn;ou&yogh;e he my&yogh;t not be saued but ite were do, but for &thorn;e profett &amp; deuocion of the seke &thorn;at laboreth to his endeward it may, and it is well doo &thorn;at it be so doo.  But amonge seculers &thorn;at be seke, lett &thorn;es praiers be seyd as deuocion &amp; disposicion &amp; &thorn;e profett of hem &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at ben abou&yogh;t hem askyn &amp; requiren, &amp; as the tyme woll suffre.  But alas &thorn;er ben full few not only amonge seculers but also in dyuerse religiouse, &thorn;at hane &thorn;e kunnynge of &thorn;is craft &amp; will be ny&yogh;h and assist to hem &thorn;at ben in poynt of dethe &amp; departynge out of this world, askyng hem &amp; exortyng &amp; enformynge &amp; prayinge for hem as it is above seid, namly whan &thorn;ei &thorn;at ben in dyinge wolden not or hopyn not to dye yet, &amp; [so] &thorn;e seke mennys soules stonden in gret perell.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  For &thorn;at loue &thorn;at made &thorn;e to be wounded &amp; dey for &thorn;e hele &amp; saluacion of mankynde, &thorn;at were most wor&thorn;i &amp; delicate loue of god &thorn;i blessed fader of heuen &amp; for oure sake made man, swete lord Ihesu full of mercy, foryeve &thorn;i seruaunte all &thorn;at he ha&thorn;e trespased in &thorn;ou&yogh;t, word &amp; dede, in all his affeccions, desires, mocions, strenghthis &amp; wittis of his soule &amp; of his body, &amp; in verrye remission of hem all yeve hym &thorn;at most sufficient amendement bi the which &thorn;ou wyssh awey &thorn;e synnes of all &thorn;e world, &amp; in supplecion of all his necgligencis adde &amp; put to hym &thorn;at holy conuersacion &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddist from &thorn;e oure of &thorn;i concepcion vnto &thorn;e oure of &thorn;i de&thorn;e, &amp; forthermore &thorn;e frute of all good dedis &thorn;e which han pleased &amp; shullen [please] &thorn;e in all &thorn;i chosen people fro &thorn;e begynnynge of the world vnto &thorn;e ende therof, swete lord Ihesu &thorn;at leuest &amp; regnest with &thorn;i fader &amp; &thorn;e holy gost, o verri god withowten ende amen.</P><P><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">[Oracio]</FOREIGN>:  For &thorn;e vnyon of &thorn;e most feruent loue &thorn;at stered &amp; made &thorn;e, life of all &thorn;ingis &thorn;at is levynge, to be incarnate of oure lady, &amp; with gret anguysshis of &thorn;e spirit to dey for cherite &amp; &thorn;e love of vs, we crye to &thorn;e rote of &thorn;i moste benigne herte &thorn;at &thorn;ou foryeve &thorn;e soule of &thorn;i seruaunte (me) all his (my) synnes, &amp; with &thorn;i most holy conuersacion &amp; [&thorn;e] most worthi merite of thi passion fulfill all his (my) necligence &amp; omyssions, &amp; make hym (me) to fele by experience &thorn;e

<PB N="2: 419">

most superhabundaunt gretnes of &thorn;i mercies, and us all &amp; specially &thorn;is (my) person oure bro&thorn;er &thorn;e which &thorn;ou hast disposed hastily for to be called before &thorn;i gloriouse mageste in &thorn;e most plesaunt maner to &thorn;e &amp; most profitable to hym (me) &amp; vs all make hym (me) to be presentid to you with swete pacience, verry repentaunce &amp; full remission, with ry&yogh;tfull fei&thorn;e, stable hope &amp; parfite charite, &thorn;at he may dye blissedlye in parfite state be-twene &thorn;i moste swettest [clippyng &amp; moste swettest] kyssynge, vnto &thorn;in euerlastynge worshipe &amp; preysynge, amen.
</P>
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  IN to the handis of &thorn;in endelesse &amp; vnquenchable mercy, holy fader, ryghtfull &amp; moste beloued fader, we commaunde the spirit of oure broder &thorn; seruaunt after the gretnes of loue &thorn;at &thorn;e holy soule of thi blessed sonn commendid hir-selfe to the in the crosse, prayinge interly [&thorn;at] for &thorn;ilke inestimable charite &thorn;at &thorn;i holy godhed &amp; faderhed drow fully to &thorn;i-selfe &thorn;at blissed soule of &thorn;i sonn, &thorn;at now in his last oure &thorn;ou receyue swetly &thorn;e spirit of oure bro&thorn;er &thorn;i seruaunt in &thorn;e same love.  Amen.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  SEynt Michael &thorn;e archangell of oure lord Ihesu Crist, helpe us at oure hy&yogh;e Iugement.  O &thorn;ou most wor&thorn;i gyaunte &amp; protectour &thorn;at neuer maist [be] ouercom, be ny&yogh;t to oure bro&thorn;er (me) &thorn;i seruaunt laborynge now sore in his (myn) ende, &amp; defende hym (me) my&yogh;tfully from &thorn;e dragon of hell &amp; from all maner of gile of wicked spiritis.  Forthermore we praie &thorn;e &thorn;at art so clere &amp; so wor&thorn;i a mynyster of god, &thorn;at in &thorn;is last ende or houre of &thorn;e life of oure bro&thorn;er (me) &thorn;ou will receyve &thorn;e soule of hym esyly &amp; benignly into &thorn;in holy bosom, &amp; brynge her into a place of refresshyng &amp; of pes &amp; rest.  Amen.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  Euer clene &amp; blessed mayde Marye, synguler helpe &amp; socoure in euery anguyssh &amp; necessite, helpe us swetly &amp; shew to oure bro&thorn;er (me) &thorn;i seruaunt &thorn;i graciouse visage now in his (my) last ende, and voyde all his (my) enemyes fro hym (me) thorow &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;i dere beloued son oure lord Ihesu Crist &amp; of &thorn;e holy crosse, &amp; delyuer hym (me) from all maner of desese of body &amp; soule, &thorn;at he (I) may &thorn;anke &amp; worship god without ende.  Amen.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  My moste swete redemptore, most mercyable Ihesu &amp; most benigne lord, for &thorn;at sorowfull voyce &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddist in &thorn;i manhed when &thorn;ou shuldist dye for vs &amp; were so consumed with sorowes &amp; trauellys of &thorn;i gret passyon &thorn;at &thorn;ou cridest &thorn;e for-sake of &thorn;i fader, be not fer fro oure brother (me) &thorn;i seruaunt but yeve hym (me) [&thorn;e helpe of] &thorn;i mercye in &thorn;e houre of his (my) de&thorn;e, &amp; haue mynde of [&thorn;e] greuous affliccion &amp; payne of hys (my) soule the which in his last houre of passynge for faylinge &amp; consumynge of his spiritis ha&thorn;e no my&yogh;t to call vpone &thorn;e of helpe; but by &thorn;e victory of the crosse &amp; by &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;i holy passion &amp; &thorn;in amorous de&thorn;e &thorn;inke vpone her &thorn;ou&yogh;tis of pes, &amp; not of affliccion but of mercye, &amp; comforte &amp; delyuer hyr fully from all maner of anguysshis; with &thorn;e same handis &thorn;at &thorn;ou suffrest to be nayled vpon &thorn;e crosse for hir sake with sharpe nayles, good Ihesu swete fader &amp; lord, delyuer hir fro &thorn;e turmentis ordeyned for her, &amp; bryng her into euerlastinge reste with a voyce of exultacion &amp; knowlechyng of &thorn;i mercy, amen.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  MOst merciable lord Ihesu Crist goddis sonn, for &thorn;e vnyon of &thorn;at recommendacion &thorn;at &thorn;ou commendist &thorn;ine holye soule to &thorn;in heuenly fader dyinge in the cros, we commende vnto &thorn;in vnnombrable pyte &thorn;e soule of oure bro&thorn;er (me) &thorn;i seruaunte, praiynge &thorn;i most merciable goodnesse &thorn;at for all &thorn;e worship &amp; meritis of &thorn;i most holy soule by &thorn;e which all soules be saued &amp; delyuerde from &thorn;e dett of de&thorn;e, &thorn;ou haue mercy vpon &thorn;e soule of oure dere bro&thorn;er &thorn;i seruaunte, delyuerynge hir mercyably fro all myseries &amp; peynes, and for &thorn;e loue &amp; mediacion of &thorn;i swete moder brynge her to &thorn;e contemplacion of &thorn;e ioy [of &thorn;i most] swete &amp; mery syght euerlastynge, amen.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>:  MErcifull &amp; benigne god, &thorn;at for &thorn;e michellnes of &thorn;i mercies doyst aweye &thorn;e synnes of hem &thorn;at be verry repentaunte, &amp; voydist &thorn;e blame of synnes


<PB N="2: 420">

&thorn;at ben passed &amp; done before &thorn;orow grace [of] foryevenesse, we be-sech &thorn;at &thorn;ou loke mercyably vpon oure bro&thorn;er (me) &thorn;i seruaunte, &amp; grac[i]ously here hym (me) askynge with all confession of his (my) hert remission of all his (my) synnes. Renu in hym (me), most mercyable fader, all &thorn;ingis &thorn;at is corrupt in hym be bodily freelte or defouled with &thorn;e fraude of the deuell, &amp; geder hym in to &thorn;e vnite of the body of holy chirch &amp; make hym a membre of &thorn;i redempcion; haue mercy, lord, vpon his wirkynge, haue mercye vpon his teris, &amp; admytte hym to the sacramentis of &thorn;i reconsiliacion, &thorn;at hath no truste but vpon &thorn;i mercye, by oure lord Ihesu Crist.  Amen.</P><P><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>: DEre bro&thorn;er, I commende &thorn;e to almy&yogh;ti god, &amp; commyt the to hyme whoes creature &thorn;ou art, [&thorn;at] whan &thorn;i manhed hath payd his det by the mene of deth, &thorn;at &thorn;ou turne a-yene to god &thorn;i creature &thorn;at made &thorn;e of the slyme of the erth.  When thi soule passith oute of thi body, gloriouse companyes of angellys com ayenst the, [the] victoriouse oste worthie Iuges and senatourys of holy apostilys met with &thorn;e, the fayre shynnynge company of holy confessoures, with &thorn;e victoriouse nombre of gloriouse martires com abowte the, &amp; &thorn;e worthi felowship &thorn;e Ioyfull companye of holy uirgynes receyve &thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;e wor&thorn;i felawship of holy patriarchis open to the [the] place of her ioye &amp; rest &amp; deme &thorn;e to be amonge hem &thorn;at &thorn;ei be amonge euerlastyngly.  Know &thorn;ou neuer &thorn;at is horrible in derknes, &thorn;at grynti&thorn;e &amp; flame&thorn;e fyre, &thorn;at ponysshe&thorn;e in tormentis; yeue place to &thorn;e &amp; greve &thorn;e not &thorn;at foule sathanas with all his seruauntis; in his commynge a-yence [&thorn;e], agast hym the presence of holy angels, &amp; flee [he] vnto the derkenes of euerlastynge ny&yogh;t, vnto &thorn;e grete troublous see of hell.  Oure lord aryse &amp; his enemyes be dispartlyd aboute, &amp; fle &thorn;ei [&thorn;at hatin hym fro his visage, faile &thorn;ei] as &thorn;e smoke fayleth, as &thorn;e wexe melti&thorn;e at the fyre so perissh synners fro the visage of god; &amp; lett ry&yogh;tfull men entre &amp; reioyce in &thorn;e syght of god.  All &thorn;e contrarie [legions] and mynystres of sathanas be not so hardy to lett &thorn;i iornaye.  Crist delyuer &thorn;e from turment, &thorn;at vouched-safe to deye for the; Crist goddis sonn brynge &thorn;e to Ioyes of mery paradyse, &amp; &thorn;e verry shipperd know &thorn;e amonge his shepe; he assoyle &thorn;e from all synnes &amp; put &thorn;e in his ry&yogh;t syd in &thorn;e [sorte] of his chosen children, &thorn;at &thorn;ou may see thi redemptour visage to visage &amp; presenciall[i] assistynge to him [se wi&thorn;e] &thorn;ine Ie I-blessid euerlastynge tru&thorn;e openly; &amp; amonge &thorn;e blissed companye of the children of god haue &thorn;ou &amp; reioice of &thorn;e ioye of &thorn;e contemplacion of god withoute ende, amen.
</P><P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Oracio</FOREIGN>: GO, Cristen soule, out of &thorn;is world, in &thorn;e name of &thorn;e almy&yogh;ty fader &thorn;at made &thorn;e of nou&yogh;t, in &thorn;e name of Ihesu Criste his sone &thorn;at suffred his passion for &thorn;e, [&amp; in &thorn;e name of &thorn;e] holy gost &thorn;at was infounded into &thorn;e; holy angels [&] archangels, trones &amp; dominaciones, princehodes, potestates &amp; vertuis, cherubyn &amp; seraphin met with &thorn;e; patriarches &amp; prophetis, apostiles &amp; euangelistis, martires &amp; confessoures, monkis &amp; heremytis, maydyns &amp; wedowes, childrene &amp; Innocentis helpe &thorn;e; [&thorn;e] prayer of all prestis &amp; dekens &amp; all &thorn;e degrees of holy chirch helpe &thorn;e; &thorn;at in pes be &thorn;i place, &amp; &thorn;i dwellynge in heuenly Ierusalem euerlastingly, by the mediacion of oure lord Ihesu criste &thorn;at is most hy&yogh;est mediatoure be-twixt god and man.  Amen.</P>
</DIV3></DIV2><DIV2 N="MS Harley 1706" TYPE="text">
<PB N="2: 421"> <HEAD>A Tretyse of Gostly Batayle<NOTE
ID="n17">This work draws upon the "Three Arrows of Doomsday," given below from Univ. Coll. Oxford 97, among other sources.</NOTE></HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"> Ms. Harl. 1706</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio">
<OPENER>Here . . begynneth a tretyse of gostly batayle.</OPENER><P>BRother or sustere that desyrest to come to the endeles blysse that mankynde was ordeyned to in hys fyrst creacion, whyche oure fadere Adame lost thorow brekyng off [the] commaundement off oure lorde gode, and commyttede to endeles trauayle, woo and payne, and alle mankynde in hym, that neuer shulde haue hade ende, ne hade oure lorde off hys endeles mercy becomyne mane; in the whyche manhode he suffrede gret peynes, trybulacions and sclaunders, reproues and shamefulle dethe vpone the rode-tree, the whyche was for pure lofe and conpassyone that he hade in mannes soule, and made aseeth to the fader in heuyne for the gylt off mankynde.  Also oure gracyous [lord] Cryste Ihesu, that ys bothe gode and mane, hath grauntede to alle tho that kepe hys commaundementis, louene vertew and hatyne syne, the pardone off hys mercyfulle redempcion, and there-ayens [to] alle tho that brekyne hys commaundementis and wolle nat restreyne hem fro synne and wyckydnes but enforse hem to lyfe in lustis and lykyngis and to fulfylle the apetytis off her fleysshly desyres, endeles peyne: and therfore, yeff thow wolt come to endeles blesse and avoyde frome endeles peyne, the be-houeth to haue in mynde that oure lord seyth by holy Iob: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Milicia est vita hominis super terram,</FOREIGN> Iob 8<HI REND="sup">o</HI>, that ys: Alle mannes lyfe vpone erthe ys but fygthynge and knygthode ayenst gostly enemyes.  These enemyes bene the fende, the worlde, and the flessh.  And therfore the holy gost techeth vs in [the] booke of Wysdome, seying to eche mane thus: 'Son, when thow be-gynnest to serue gode, loke thow stande styfly in rygthwysnes and drede, and make redy thy soule to with-stonde the dysceytis off the fende'.  Also seynt Powle byddeth you to clothe yow in trewe armoures of gode, that ye mowe myghtyly with-stande the temptacions of oure enemyes.  For mannes body ys [as] a clothe in the whyche the soule ys clothede.</P><P>Horse.  Also hit ys lykenede to an horse; for lyke as ane horse welle-taughte beryth hys mastere ouer many peryllys and saueth hym fro perysshyng, so the body welle-rewled bereth the soule ouer many peryllys of thys wrecched worlde. And lyke as ther longeth many thyngis to the horse thorow the whych hys mastere may sytte sadly and nat falle, and as there may noo mane fy&yogh;te ayenst hys enemy but yef hys horse be meke and mylde, ryght so the sowle may nat fyghte ayenst the deceytis off the fende but yef the body by meke and mylde; ffor yeff the body lyfe in lustis and lykyngis at hys oune wylle, hit ys lyke to peryssh the soule in the fyre off helle, for holy wrytte seyth: 'he that noryssheth hys body delycatly and lustyly, shalle fynde hym rebelle whene he leste weneth'. For assone as a mane wolle lyfe wysely after the lawes of gode and to fle the false lustes off thys worlde and to withstonde fflesshely desyres and to bowe hym vnder the yooke off goddys lawe, than begynneth hys enemyes to compasse hym with wyles and wrenches, to make hyme ouerthrowe frome the blysse that he ys ordeynede to, in to the horryble pytte off helle; wherffore hit ys behouefulle that the body be buxome and mylde to the soule in thys gostly batayle, yeff he shalle haue victory off hys enemyes.  For yeff the body and the sowle be welle accordede to-gydere and eche helpe othere in thys gostly batayle, thane shalle the enemyes soone fflee, ffor holy wryte seyeth: 'Withstande the ffende and he shalle flee fro the'.  But hit were grete ffoly for any mane to fyghte apone ane horse vnbrydelyde: ffor yeff he be wylde and off euylle condycions, he ys lyke to be hys masters confusyone and to cast hym in to the handes off hys enemyes, and therfore hit ys nedeffulle that he be brydelyde.  And yeff he be

<PB N="2: 422">

wylde and off euylle condycions, than nedeth the brydelle to be heuy and sumdele sharpe, to restrayne hyme from hys wyckyde lustys; and yef he be buxome and mylde, thane nedyth the brydelle to be softe and smothe.</P>
<P>Brydylle.  Thys brydylle ys clepede Abstinence, with the whyche the fflessh shalle be refraynede from flesshly desires and worldely affecciouns to the loue off gode and heuynly desyres: for he ys wylde and wyllfulle, and lothe to bowe to goodnes, and therfore with thys brydelle thou must refreyne hyme tylle he be meke and mylde to the sowle.  And yeff [he] be wylde in flesshly lustis |and in worldely worschyppys, thane brydelle hym with sharpe abstynence, bothe with fastyng and wakyng and with honest occupacion doyng; for yeff thow on hym wolle fyghte and late hym lyfe after hys desyre, truste sekyrly that thow shalt be ouercome. And ther[to] refreyne hyme discretely with abstynence, so that the kynde be kepte in strengthe; for ellys he xalle fayle the att nede and [make &thorn;e] lese the victory off thys gloryous batayle.
</P><P>Reynes.  The two reynes off thys brydelle shullene be two partyes off temperaunce: that ys to say, neythere to moche nere to lytelle, knytte to-gedyr by the knot off discrecione.  And holde the reynes euene to-gedyre by the knotte that none passe othere; ffor yeff any of hem be owte off mesure, hit wylle make thy horse to glyde a-syde, and so to lese the rygth waye of that gloryous blysse whyche mankynde was ordeyned to in hys furst creacion.
</P><P>That oone Reyene.  That one reyne ys to large whane thow suffrest thy flessh to haue to moche hys wylle in etyng and drynkyng, in slepyng, in spekyng, in veyne talys tellyng other in rebaudy, in lesyngis, in sweryng or any other vnprofytable talkyng.  Also hit ys to large yeff thow noryssh hit delycately in ouer-moche ease off softe lying, goyng, other syttyng, or in any othere thyng doyng that thow dost to fulfylle the [vnleful] desyres off thy flessh, and nat rewlede in mesure as reasone asketh.  For euery thoughte and euery worde and euery dede that a mane doth whyche ys nat pryncypally done in the worschyp off gode and to helpe and furtheryng off hys euy[n]crystene dewly and rygthfully as charyte asketh, hyt ys veyne, and synne, other venyalle or dedely synne, off whyche thow shalt yeue a ffulle streyte rekenyng at the dredeffulle day off dome, but yeff hit be amendyde in thys lyff here with sorow off herte and with confessyone and satisfaction makyng.
</P><P>That other Reyne.  That other ys to streyte whene thow art to sterne ayenst thyne oune fleyssh, in with-drawyng that reasone wolde that he hadde bothe in mete and drynke &amp; slepe, or [by] any other vnresonable abstynence, where-thorow hit ys so ffebylle that hit may nat serue gode durably with feruent herte, with myghty desyre and with parfyte loue, but hit ys so ffebylle that hit may neythere pray ne werke ner speke as hit oughte, but lyeth stylle as a vnresonable beste with grete fantasyes and vnclene thoughtis be cause off ydelnes off the hede or for febylnes off the body; and so yeff thow be ouersterne agayne thy fflessh, hit may lette the in [this] gostly batayle.  And therfore susteyne thy body dyscretely, so that he be neyther to wylde ne to febylle, but of euene strengthe. For yeff thow suffre hyme to haue alle hys fulle lykyngis and desyres, thane he that shulde be thy beste ffrende wolle be thy fulle enemy; and yeff thow with-drawe from hyme that he ougth for to haue in susteynyng hys kynde by reasone, than thow dystroyest hys mygth, where-throwe he may nat helpe the to haue the victorye off thyne enemyes, but [is] rather lykely to be thy confusyone.
</P><P>A Sadylle.  Also thy horse be-houeth to haue a sadylle, that thow may sytte the more sadly and semely to othere mennes sygth.  Thys sadylle ys Pacience and Mekenesse; that ys to say, thow muste be pacient in aduersyte, both in sclaunders and reproues, in sekenes, in temptacion, in tribulacions, and in alle aduersytees, and so mekely resceue heme with dewe thankyngis to gode off hys gracyous vysytacions, thynkyng that thow were moche more worthy for thy grete offensys ande trespases that thow hast doone ayenst hyme.  Also what-so-euer

<PB N="2: 423">

thow doo, thynke or speke, that hit be do with goode avysement, [&] wysely to thynke on the begynnyng and on the endyng; and that hit be doo swetely, benygnely and with mylde chere, and greue the nat in no wyse.  And [&thorn;off] thy flessh be grogyng thorow freelte off hys oune corrupcion that he hath in hys oune kynde, yet kepe mekenes in herte, and late hit nat owte with wykkede wordes, but mekely resceue heme, and thynke that they bene grete matyers off mede in the blysse off heuene, and grete peyne to heme that doone so to the, wherfore thou owest to pray for heme with pure herte to almygthy gode, that they may haue grace off foryeuenes.  And yeff thow do thus, thow shalt be gladde, for the prophete seyth that 'the meke and the mylde suffryng trybulacions in rygthwysnes for goddys loue, shullene ioye'.  Therfore meke the with ale thy mygth, bothe inwarde with herte thynkyng, and owtewarde with goode dedis werkyng, so that other mowe be conuertede by thy goode example yeuyng, and thane shalt thow haue grace, off synnes forgyfnes and to encrese in vertew, and so to come to endeles blysse that mane was ordeynede to in hys furst creacion.
</P><P>Stirop.  The styropes of hys sadylle shalle be lownes and sadnes; lownes ayenst pryde, and sadnes ayenst worldly couetyse and flesshly lustis; so that thow be nat [to] sory for no wo, ne to glad for no wele ne welfare.  Now syt sadly in thys sadylle and kepe welle thy styroppys, that for no pryde off strengthe, off byrthe, off fayrnes, off kunnyng, or ryches, or any vertew that gode hath sent the other bodyly or gostly, thow be not cast owte off thy styroppes off lownes and sadnes.  Also [for] noo wrathe nere vnpacience for sekenes, or for losse off gode, ne losse of name, ne for no vysytacion that gode sendeth the, other sufferyng the fende to vexe the by temptacions, or by vexacion off thy euene-crystene, late nat thy horse caste the owte of thy sadylle off pacience; but sytte sadly and streyne thy ffeete in thy styroppys by the vertew [of] gostely strengthe, and doo as Cryste byddeth in the gospelle where he seyeth thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">In paciencia uestra possidebitis animas uestras,</FOREIGN> that ys: Ye shullene kepe your soulys in youre pacience.  And thane lyke as the sadylle maketh the horse semely and lusty to the eye off mane, so pacience and mekenesse makis the soule louely and amyable in goddys sygth, semely and gracyous in mannys sygth, euylle and confusyously in the fendys sygth. And there-ayenst wratthe and impacience, hastynesse and hygh fulnes in herte makyne a mane vngracyous ande hatefulle in goddys sygth, sporte and gladnes to alle the deuylles in helle, and increasyn the peynes that neuer shalle haue ende. Off thys sadylle oure lorde spake to Cayne whane he was wroth with hys brothere Abelle: 'Why, seyde oure lorde, art thow wroth, and why ys thy face and thy chere so fallene?' &mdash; for he was fallene owte of the sadylle of pacience in to the foule pytt of wretthe; 'for yeff thow doo welle, thow shalt resceue off me godde mede, and yeff thou do euylle, anone thy synne cometh to the yate, to be punysshede; but the desyre off synne shalle be vnder the and thy powere, [as] the horse vnder hys master, ande thow shalt be lorde thereoff yff thou wylle, Genes. 4<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>, And so Cayn be mysgouernaunce off hys horse felle owte off the sadylle off pacience in to manslawghtere off hys brothere, be-cause he consentede to the wyckede desyres off hys flessh and wolde nat restreyne hym by the knotte off dyscrecion.  But sytte sadly Iob dyde, and sey as he seyde whane he had lost alle hys goode, and alle hys chyldrene were slayne and hym-self smytene with grete sekenes ful horryble; than he seyd: 'Yeff we hane take goode thyngis off goddis sonde, why shulle nat we suffre paynffulle thyngis off hys vysytacion?  Gode gaff and gode hath takene awey; as gode wolle so be itt doone, blessyde by oure lordis name, Iob 1<HI
REND="sup">o</HI> &amp; 2<HI REND="sup">o</HI><FOREIGN LANG="LAT"> capit.</FOREIGN></P><P>The master off kynde telleth<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> libro 4<HI REND="sup">o</HI> de qualitate elementorum,</FOREIGN> that there ys a byrde callede a barnake.  Thys byrde vexeth owte off a tree [ouer the watir, and 
<PB
N="2: 424">

als longe as it hongith one the tre] hit ys dede, but assone as hit loseth frome the tree and falleth into the water, anone hit ys quycke and swymmeth forth.  Thys byrde hath lytylle fflessch and lasse blood.  By thys tree I vnderstande mankynde that came off Adam ande Eue; by thys byrde I vnderstande euery crystene mane and womane; the whyche whane they be furst borne off here modere, be dede by orygynalle synne and nat able to the lyff off grace ne to blysse, for seynt Powle se[i]th: 'we be alle borne chyldrene off wrathe': but assone as we falle in to the fonte-stone and in watere off bapteme bene bapty&yogh;ede, anone we resceyue the lyff off grace and bene able to the blysse thate mane was ordeynede to in hys furst creacion, yeff we kepe vs fro the floode off syne.  Seynt Petyr byddeth vs in thyse wordes: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Abstinete vos a carnalibus desideriis etc.,</FOREIGN>1<HI REND="sup">o</HI> Petri 2<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: 'Absteyne yow frome flesshly desyres that fyghtene ayenst the soule'.  Sythene thane that alle mannys lyff ys but fyghtyng ayenst gostly enemyes: therfore hit [ys] nedefulle to euery crystene mane nat only to gouerne welle hys horse, but also to be suerly armede for to withstande the strokys of hys enemyes.  Ryghte so hit ys nat Inowh to rewle thy body, but also thow must arme the with gostly armure to withstande the dyntis off the dartis off the deuyllis foundyng, for seynt Powle seyth Ad Eph. 6: Alle oure fyghtynge ys ayenst wyckyde spyrytes off derkenes, that ben prynces and gouernoures off synfulle mene.  'And therfore, he byddeth, arme yow in gostly armure off gode, so that ye mowe withstande the busshementis and the sleyghtis off the fende, and to stande stedefastly and parfytely in alle thyngis off ryghtwysnes.  Stondeth, he seyth, in trowthe, and gyrde you with the gyrdelle off chastyte, and doth one the habergeone off ryghtwysnes, and keuer &yogh;oure feete in dyghtyng (or makyng redy) of the gospelle off peese; and in alle thyngis take to you the shelde of feyth, with the whyche ye may quenche alle the dartis of youre enemyes.  And taketh to you the basnet off helthe, and the swerde off the holy gost, that ys goddes worde'; for, as he seyth in a nothere place, hit ys sharpere thene any two-egede swerde, Ad Hebre. 4.  Thus Seynt Powle by lykenes off bodyly armoure techyth vs gostely armure.  He byddyth yow arme yowre body by the vertew off trouthe that ys callede the Habergeoun off Ryghtwysnes; he byddeth you do ryghte to alle and yelde to gode that longeth to hyme, to youre euyncrystene that longeth to hem, bothe to youre sufferaynes and to youre felawes and to youre subgettis, and to hem that be passede owte off thys worlde with almesdede doyng and yeldyng off dettis, and to hem that bene to come in sauyng off her ryghte inherytaunce.  Thus armeth you with the habergeone of ryghtwyssnes, bothe be-fore and be-hynde and on eyther syde. And as in the habergeone euery ryng accordeth with othere and ys knytte in othere, so shulde alle trouthe accorde and be knytte to-gedere in ryghtwysnes; for yef ye fauour othere lorde or lady spiritualle or temporalle, souereyne or subgette, kyne or frende, or any creature hygh or lowe, so moche that [it] ys hynderyng to a nothers ryghte, than youre ryngis in youre habergeone accordyne nat ne be nat welle knytte to-gedere, but there ys ane hole where-thorow the fende may sle youre sowle.     And he byddeth that ye shalle arme youre leggis with gostly pouerte, so that youre hertis, and youre affeccions and youre desyres bene drawene frome erthely thyngis, and nat to sette youre loue to moche in worldely goodes ne flesshly lustis, neyther to stryue ne to plete for no worldely goode, but the more nede compelle, seeke to lyue in pease with alle mene yef ye mowene.  And thus arme yow with gostly pouerte bothe leggis and feete, that ys to sey youre loue and youre affections, ayenst temptacions off false couetyse.  And therfore he byddyth you shoo youre feet 'in makyng redy off the gospelle of peese'; for euery crystene mane or womane oughte to haue gostly pouerte, whyche Cryste taughte in the gospelle where he seyeth thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Beati pauperes spiritu quoniam ipsorum est regnum celorum.</FOREIGN>  Also thow owest to forthere the gospelle and susteyne bothe in worde, wylle and deede vn-to thy powere; yef thow be a preste, than preche hit and teche hit dewly and trewly, reuerentely and charytabely,


<PB N="2: 425">

with meke herte and parfyte lyuyng, where-thorowgh sympelle mene that be nat letterede and hane noo power of prechyng and techyng as thow hast, may be stabelede in trewe feyth off goddis lawe to encrese in vertewe and to hate synne; and yef thow be a lay-mane, the behoueth to helpe ande susteyne heme that hane powere ande trewly techyne hit.  Also the be-houeth to here and to be-leue trewly one hit and in alle the sacrementis of holy churche, and nat [to] dyspute and ymagyne howe they myghte be so, but fully be-leve in heme, and so to conforme the in the lawes of gode and the ordynaunce off holy churche.</P>
<P>Shelde.  And taketh to yow the shelde off feythe; for as a shelde ys a tryangle and hath thre corners, in whyche tryangle yef frome the myddes be drawene thre lynes in to [the] thre corners, ther shulle be thre tryangles, whyche thre be but oone tryangle and yet noone off heme ys othere; and therfore the feyth off the holy trynyte ys lykenede to a shelde, for there be III persones ande oo gode, the ffadere the sone the holy gost, and yche of heme ys gode ande none of heme ys othere, ande yet they be alle thre but oo gode in mageste: Thys shelde of feyth of the holy trynyte ye muste take to youe in gostly fyghte, and so to sett alle youre feyghte and alle youre truste in o gode in trynyte, and prayeth to the fader almyghty that ye may haue myghte and powere, to the sone alle-wytty that ye mowe haue wytte and wysdome, ande to the holy gost that ye mowe haue grace and mercy, and so to haue myghte, wytte, and grace, to with-stonde alle gostly enemyes.  Also ye muste take to yow the basnett of helthe, that ys hope off foryeuenes off alle the trespas that ye hane done ayenst gode, and to come to the endeles blysse off heuene thorow the endeles mercy that he schewyde in hys byttere passyone; and so to haue vyctory off [your] enemyes thorow hys gloryous vysytacions.  And lyke as hitt ys clene, brygth and smothe, that shote ande strokes mowe sone glyde off: so muste youre herte be clene, brygth ande smothe ffrom wyckede thowgthys, wyckede desyres and wyckede wylles.  Ande lyke as a basnet ys hyghest off alle armoure, goyng and gaderyng vpwarde in to a lytylle coppe: so muste youre hope ande youre truste pryncypally go vp to gode, and not to sette hitt to moche in mannys mygth ne in erthely goodys that ys but rust wastyng the basnett off helthe.  And therfore the prophete seyeth: 'Acursyde be he that setteth hys truste in mane ande in fflesshly mygth, and letyth hys herte goo away fro gode; and blessyde be he that settyth hys hope ande [truste] in oure lorde gode', Ieremi. 17.     Also seynt Powle byddeth you take vambrace and rerebrace and gloves of plate, that ys goode occupacions and besynes in gostly werkes eyther bodyly whyche be in helpyng and sauyng thy soule frome synne and wyckednes. And therfore he byddeth you laboure ande wake in honest werkes ande in kepyng goddis commaund[m]ente.  For the wysemane seyth Ecclesiast. 33<HI
REND="sup">o</HI>: 'Idylnes ande slouthe ys cause off mochylle wyckydnes'.  For an Idyl mane ande lustles ys lykenede to a mane lustles ande handeles and wepynles amonge hys enemyes, or lyke a mane naked in bateylle, that for defaute off armure leseth bothe arme ande hande.  So mane beyng Idylle in sufferyng hys wyttis to wandyr aboute in wordely desyres and flesshly lustis and vnclene ymagynacions, ys lykely to lese the soule with-outene ende.
</P><P>Also ye muste gyrde you with a gyrdelle off chastyte: for lyke as a gyrdylle fast gyrte to a mane beryth vp the haberioune and saueth the body from akyng ande werynesse, so the gyrdelle off chastyte wele festenede in the loue off gode with clene thowghtis ande heuynly desyres, bereth vp the soule from the foule pytte off synne and strengtheth hyme in vertew and goodenesse.     Also ye muste haue the Iakke off fence that ys Charyte: ffor as the Iakke thorough the nesshenes and softenes that ys in hitt, feynteth ande wasteth alle the dyntes off thy enemyes that cometh ayenst hit, so charyte feynteth and wasteth alle the dyntes off thy enemyes; ande therffore Seynte Powle seyth Ad Cor. 14: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Caritas omnia suffert, omnia sustinet,</FOREIGN> that ys: 'charyte suffreth alle thynges paciently, and maketh euery trauayle soft, and beryth alle thyng esyly'.  Also the glose seyth there that

<PB N="2: 426">

charyte, pacience and benignite, with compassyone-hauyng off othere mennys myscheff, bene the pryncypalle armoure that longeth to Crystis peple.  Thys Iacke off charyte ys betokenede by the clothe off Cryste withoutene seme alle wouene aboue in to oone, [which] in tyme off hys passyone the knyghtys wolde not kytte hit but kepte hit hole and castyde lott therfore, in tokyne that euery goode knyght off gode besyly shulde arme hyme with the cloth off charyte to saue pease ande vnyte among alle mankynde to hys power.  For the ende off euery batayle shulde be peese, and to that ende ant to no other shulde euery mane fygth, as seyth seynt Powle thus: leue ffrendes, I pray yow to arme yow in gostly armoure as goddys knyghtis; for though ye be natt able to bodyly fygth, yet be ye able to gostly fygth, and in that ye be crystenede ye Crystis knyghtis beene to fygth in gostly batayle, yeff we wylle come to the blysse off heuene.
</P><P>Swerd.  Also taketh with yow the swerde off goddis worde with the whych ye shulle defende yow from youre enemyes.  For as the swerde peryssheth, kutteth and maketh separacion, so goddys worde be prechyng, redyng or heryng cutteth and maketh separacion be-twene the soule and synne, frome flesshly desyres and from wordly couetyse.  And therfor Cryst seyde he came nat to make synfulle peese, but to sende the swerde off separacion in erthe to dystroye wyckede peese that mene hane in theyr hertis with synne.  Therfore, goode frendys, as goode knyghtis haueth with youe the swerde of goddis worde bothe be heryng, redyng, and by dede werkyng.
</P><P>Spere.  And thane taketh with youe the speare of Crystis passyone.  Furst taketh hede how hys hede was crownede with a croune off thorne that went in to hys brayne, &amp; the bloode brestyng oute one euery syde, to dystroye the hygh synne off pryde.  For lyke as the hede ys hyghest and most worthy of the vtter partes off mane, so pryde ys worst off alle synnes and most vnworthy in the sygth off gode.  Take hede how hys armes were spredde abrode and drawene ffulle strayte in the tre tylle alle the synewes and veynes brestyne a-sondre, and hys hondys smytene thorowe with raggede nayles to the tre, and how grete stremes off bloode ranne owte, to dystroye the synne of wyckede werkes that mane doth with hys wykede handes.  Take hede how hys syde was openede ande hys herte clovyne a-two with a sharpe spere, and how he shadde owte both bloode and water, the whyche [shewed] that yef he had hade more bloode, more he wolde haue yeuene for mannys soule to the fader of heuene; and water, to wasshe vs frome oure synne.  Also he suffrede thys to dystroye pryde, couetyse, enuye, hate, wratthe and malyce, that renneth most in mannes herte and womans.  Take hede how hys feete were naylede to the tree streynyng oute bloode, to dystroye the synne of slouthe in goddys seruyce and in the VII dedys of mercy doyng.  Take hede how hys body was alle for-rente and alle to-tore with scharpe scourgis that frome the sole off the fote to the top off the hede there was noone hoolle place, and that was to dystroy the synne of lust and lechery that reygneth in mannes body &amp; womans.  Take hede how nakede and pore he hynge vpone the tree, to dystroye the synne of couetyse and wordely worschyppe.  Take heede how he dranke eyselle and galle, to dystroye the synne of glotonye.  And so he suffrede payne in alle partyes of hys gloryous body, to dystroye alle synne[s] in mannys [body] and womans.  Thys spere of Crystis passyone ys the best and sykerest wepyne ayenst oure enemyes.     [More]ouere ye schalle vnderstande that a wyse mane off armes wolle chese hym a goode grounde and a playne to fygth in, for itt ys perlyous to fygth in mory grounde or in stobely grounde or in pytty grounde.  And therfore seynt Powle techeth yow stonde [fast] in trowthe and equyte, that in alle youre doyng ye loke that youre grounde and youre cause be god and trewe, rygthfulle, clere and clene fro couetyse.  And a wyse knygth wylle haue with hym the hylle and the sonne and the wynde.  One the same wyse must ye in thys gostly fyght take with you the hylle of good lyuyng, that ye may sey with the apostylle:

<PB N="2: 427">

<FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Nostra conuersacio in celis est,</FOREIGN> that ys: 'oure conuersacione ys in heuyns and in heuynly thyngis', and therfor seynt Powle byddeth you stonde parfytely in these thyngys.  Also ye must haue the sonne and the lygth of goddis grace, and the wynde off holy prayere, the whyche ys a specyalle remedy to gete grace to withstande temptacions of oure enemyes.</P>
<P>Sporys.  Also ye muste haue a peyre of sporys, the whyche muste be sharpe to pryke with youre horse yef nede be, that he stynte nat in hys weye, ffor many horsys be dulle and slowe in theyre iorney but they be pryked.  These sporys shalle be loue and drede of gode, whyche among al othere vertues displesyne most the fende and sonnest bryngeth a mane or woman to heuyne-blysse.
</P><P>Rigth spore.  The rygth spore ys loue that mane oweth to god for the grete and excellent goodnesse that he [hath] shewed and sheweth at alle tymes.  Furst how he made man off noughte to hys gloryous lykenes, and made hyme lorde of alle erthely thyngys; and for that excellent loue &thorn;at he schewed to mankynde in hys mercyffulle redempcion; and for the vysytacions that he sheweth to you cotydyally bothe in sparyng yow fro endeles peynes off helle, and yeveth yow space and grace and tyme to amende yeff ye wolle, for Cryst seyth <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nolo mortem peccatoris sed ut magis conuertatur et viuat,</FOREIGN> that ys: 'I wylle nat the dethe of a synnere but rathere more that he turne therfro and lyue'.  Also he yeueth goodys plenteuosly that bene necessary and profytabely to yow, yef they be gouernede dyscretely; and so sheweth yow alle-wey grete tokenes off loue and mercy.
</P><P>Lefte spore.  The lefte spore ys dreede off paynes of helle and of purgatory that be Innumerable eyther to be thougth or seyd or tolde.  Now with thyse II sporys pryke youre horse yeff he be dulle and euylle-wylde to goodnes-warde. Furst with the ryghte spore that ys loue; and yeff he wolle nat haste hym in hys iorney, than pryke hyme with the lefte spore, that wylle make hym to sprynge yef he be in the wey off grace.  In thys manere, lyfe frendis, arme yow in thys gostly armure and myghteth yow in thys gostly batayle, and gouerne youre horse, that ys youre body, dyscretly, so that hit be nat ouer-feble by ouermeche abstynence and trauayle, ne to wylde by ouermoche ease and fulfyllyng of hys appetyte as in glotony or in lechery or in any other vngoodly desyres, for in case wykede lustes and desyres mowene be dedely synne, as thus: yeff thow luste to medle with womane or mane ayenst the lawe off gode and thow dost alle that lyeth in the to performe hitt in dede yeff thow myghtest, thane hit ys dedely synne.  Dauyd seyth that 'god knoweth and preueth mannes herte and hys leendys', that ys to sey, god knoweth mannes wylle and hys lustys, for there ys no thyng so pryuey neyther in thoughte ne in dede but that ys opyn in goddys syghte. Therfor suche as a mane ys in herte and in wylle, suche he ys by-fore gode.
</P><P>Also a wysemane, or he goo to batayle, wol knowe for what cause he shalle fyghte and whethere that hit be trewe, ande what shalle be hys rewarde; and yef hit be sygnede in two thyngis hym to chese, thane he wolle sende hys most belouede and trusty frende to see and enquere whyche ys best and most confortable.  In the same wyse muste ye in thys gostely batayle.  Ye muste fyghte to saue the soule that gode bougth so dere with hys precyous bloode vpone the rode-tree.
</P><P>Also hit ys rygthfulle, sythene god made the of noughte vn-to hys gloryous lykenesse and therto made the ffelaw with aungelys in blys that neuer shalle haue ende, that thow be fyghtyng ayenst thy gostely enemyes, and neuer to haue pease with heme&mdash;for yeff thow doo, thou art traytoure to gode and lykely to lese thy herytage the whyche thow mayst haue by grace.  Also thy rewarde ys assygnede in two thyngis, to chese the best as longe as thou trauaylyng arte in thys batayle, but be thow onys hynnes went, thow mayst not do soo, for [to] whether so thov furst comest, lyke hit the welle or euylle, there the be-houeth to dwelle for euermore; shalt thow neuer after thys dwellyng chaunge, syt itt neuer so euylle with the.  Heuene and helle ben these two thyngis whyche thow mayst chese as

<PB N="2: 428">

long as thow arte lyuyng, but [be] the soule onys departyde fro the body, than, whether thou lyke welle or euylle, nedys thou must kepe hit, and neuer after to be chaungyde; for thane, lyke as thou hast trauayled in the kepyng off goddis commaundementis and in the fulfyllyng off &thorn;e dedys of mercy, so shalle thow be rewarded, that ys for to say: yeff thow hast kepte goddys commaundementis and fulfyllyde the dedys off mercy and with-stande thy enemyes myghtfully, than shalt thou haue the blysse of heuene and be ffelaw with aungellys euerlastyng; and yeff thow breke goddys commaundementis and wylle nat withstande the temptacions off thy enemyes but consentest to theme and performest in dede, ande wylle natt amende the by sorow in herte, by confessyone of mouthe, and by satysfaccion in dede, than shalle thy rewarde be endeles payne in helle withowtene ende. Wherfor my counselle ys that thow departe thy soule frome thy body by inwarde thoughte; and to sende thy herte, whyche ys [thy] most louyde and trusty frende, before, to wete off that two thyngis whyche ys moste profytable to abyde in.  Sende thyne herte in to helle and ther shalt thou fynde [all] that that thou ha[te]st here, that ys a fawte off alle goodys, and plente off alle euylles: hote ffyre brynnyng with-outyne lyghte, with brymstone moste stynkyng; foule stormes and tempestis; gredy deuylles as wode lyones wyde yellyng; hunger ande thryst that neuer shalle be quenchede; adders, toodys ande alle venemos wormes [&thorn;at] one the synfulle shullene gnawe; wepyng, gronyng ande gryntyng off tethe; fulle off derkenes; smoke and smother, &thorn;at shalle make hem to wepe mo teerys glowyng thane ys water in the see; eueryche hatyng other as the deuylle most horryble, and euer cursyng the tyme that they were borne, and euer desyryng dethe.  And so they be euer dying but neuer ffulle dede, but shul lyue euer in payne, woo and turment.  They hatedene dethe whane they lyuedene in lustis ande lykyngis of this worlde and fulfyllede here flesshly appetytys and wolde not restreyne hym by the brydylle off abstynence, in holdyng the reynes of temperaunce by the knotte off dyscrecion.  Also the soules that shalle be there must be dyrke ande dymme, hydously stynkyng and lothsome to see; for the bodyes off heme shulle be so febylle and so chargede with synne that they ne shalle [mow] remeve the lest worme frome no party off theyre body, but must suffre alle here malyce, and yet nat only heme, but alle the paynes, woo ande tormentis that herte may nat thynke ne tonge may nat telle, for they shal haue noo mynde off no goode to theyre comforte, but euer in payne lyche newe.  Ther ys ane olde prouerbe that, ne hope were, herte wolde breste; and ther shalle be neyther herte-breste ne hope off releuyng.</P>
<P>O thow delycate creature tha[t] lyuest in wordely worschyppes and flesshly lustis in consentyng to the wykede intysyngis of thy enemyes: haue mynde how they shulle passe as the shadow, for thy body, be hit neuer so beauteuous and myghty, ande though thou kept hit neuer so welle with delycate metys and drynkes, with ryche clothes or eny other maner restorytyfys, yet hit shalle dye and turne ayene to erthe and wormes mete.  Also haue mynde off thy[s] place that ys so horryble and so paynfulle, and forsake syne whyles gode suffreth the to lyue ande hast helthe ande thy wyttes at wylle; for Salomone seyth: 'In alle thy werkes thynke one thy ende, ande thou shalt neuer doo syne'.  Thynke that thou shalt dye and thow wottest neuer where ne whene ne what dethe, ne in what state ne in what daye ne what tyme; ande therfore seyth seynt Austyn&macr; that euer shulde oure last day be in oure mynde, for whene &thorn;ou rysest thow arte nat sykere to [liue to euen, ne when thou gost to thi bed thou art nat syker to] ryse with thy lyfe.  Also haue mynde howe the sowle shalle departe frome the body with grete drede: for the fendys shulle be present and goode aungellis for to dyspute thy lyff fro the begynnyng to the ende, ande the goode aungellis shalle sey to the goode, ande the ffendys the wyckede, that noughte shalle be forgete to the leste thought that euer thou thowghtest other consentest to, ande alle the wordys that

<PB N="2: 429">

euer thow speke shullene be examynede, and alle thy dedys shewede.  And thane many synnes that thow may nat now see nor thynke, shalle than come be-fore the opynly ande perauenture more to drede ande more grysely thane thoo that thow may now see, and many thyngis [that] thow wenyst be now welle done shalle schew than fowle synne.  Moreouer haue mynde off the dredefulle day off dome: for than shalle oure lorde come and deme alle mankynde, as wytnesseth the prophete sayyng thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Egredietur dominus de loco sancto suo ut uisitet iniquitatem habitatorum terre,</FOREIGN> 'Oure lorde shalle wende oute of hys place for to vysyte the wykednes of hem that inhabytene the erthe'.  Certes, thys day oweth sore to be dredde, for as moche mercy as oure lorde sheweth nowe to mankynde, so moche shalle thane be shewede streyte vengeable ryghtwysnes; for oure lorde seyth by hys prophete Moyes: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Congregabo super eos mala et sagittas meas complebo in eis,</FOREIGN> 'I shal hepe vpone hem theyre euylles, and I shalle spende alle my arowes vpone heme'.  Thre sharpe arowes shalle be shotte off oure lorde in that day vpone hem that shullen be dampnede.  The furst arowe shalle be off clepyng to the dome, whereof Cryst seyth in the gospelle: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Venit hora ut omnes qui in monumentis sunt audient uocem filii dei, &amp; procedent hii qui bona egerunt in resurreccionem uite, qui uero mala egerunt in resurreccionem iudicii,</FOREIGN> that ys: 'the oure cometh in the whyche alle mene that bene deed in beryelles shulle here [the] voyce off goddys sone, and they that hane done goode thyngis shullene gone in to ayene-rysyng off lyff, but they that hane doo euylle thyngis in to ayene-rysyng off dome', that ys to say, to be demede.  Than the dampnable soule shalle come to the body and sey to hit: 'Aryse, thou cursyd caytyff [careyne], from thys tyme forwarde to be felaw with the horryble fendis in helle and enemy to almyghty gode.  Nowe thy ioye shalle be turnede in to woo, thy delyte in to bytternesse, and thy laughyng in to wepyng; now thy wrechyde lust shalle passe in to euerlastyng sorowe and peyne; nowe ys falle to the alle that thow hatedest, and nowe ys passyde fro the alle that thow loue[de]st.  Cursyde be thow wrecchyde careyne, for in payne for thy synnes and thy delytes and thy wykednes from the tyme that I passyde from the I haue brennede in helle; so cursyde be thow helle-bronde, ordeynede for thy synnes to the fyre off helle that neuer shalle be quenchede.  Cursede be the tyme that I was coupelede to the, for now I may nat forsake the nor thy cursyde company I may nat eschewe, for wylle I nylle I I am constreynede to be knytte ayene to the.  Goo we therfor to-gyder before the dredefulle and ryghtful iuge to here the sentence of oure dampnacion'.  Thane shullene alle wykede mene se the iust cause of theyre dampnacion wretyne with theyre owyne handes in the booke of theyre conscyence, whyche booke both lernede and lewde shullene kunne rede. Than they shalle see the domys-mane syttyng vpone the reyne-bowe with [his] voundys bledyng, and with sterne loke one hem lokyng as he were wode for wretthe.  Of thys wodnes [&amp; wretthe] spekyth the profyte Dauyd where as he prayeth to be delyueryde of bothe, seying thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Domine ne in furore tuo arguas me,</FOREIGN> that ys: 'Lorde, in thy wodenesse ouercome me nat with skyles, and chastyce me nat in thy wrathe'.  Nomane thynke that wodenes or wratthe or any suche troblede passyons of mannys kynde be in gode; but they be sette in scrypture for the werkes of gode in punysshyng and vengyng synne in hem that be worthy to take suche passyons off punysshyng as beene wrothe and wodnes in alle synners, that ys eyther they muste be chastysede by paynes that shalle haue ane ende as purgatory, that ys clepyde in scrypture the wratthe of gode, or ellys they shalle be punysshede in the payne off helle that neuer shalle haue ende, that ys callyde the wodnes of gode.  Alle thys the prophete Dauyd sawe in spyryte, and therfore in &thorn;e persone off alle suche synners he, felyng hym-selfe vnmyghty to bere euer eythere, furst asketh to be delyueryd frome helle, and [sithen from] purgatorye, seying thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei domine quoniam infirmus sum,</FOREIGN> 'Lorde haue mercy one me, for I ame vnmyghty to bere euereyther, that ys to sey, &thorn;in arguyng in thy


<PB N="2: 430">

dome, eyther thy chastyment in purgatory, but hit so be that I be vpborne or supportede by thy mercy'.  That dredeffulle day off oure lorde!  thane shalle wykede mene seene hem sytte in dome with Cryste whome they haddene [here] in despyte, and in thys syghte they shalle be troblede with ane horryble drede, saying thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Hii sunt quos habuimus aliquando in derisum et similitudinem improperii; nos insensati uitam eorum  &amp;c,</FOREIGN> that ys to say: 'Thyse beene tho the whyche [sumtyme] we haddyne in scorne and in to lykenesse [of] shenshypp.  We vnwytty wrecches heldyne ther lyffe wodenes, ande here ende with-owtene honoure: but loo now thyse beene amonge the sonnes off gode countede, and amonge the seyntis of gode ys the lote off theme.  Therfore we hane errede frome the wey off trewthe, and the lyghte off ryghtewysnes hath not shynede to vs, [and] the son of vnderstondyng is not spronge to vs]; we be made wery in the wey off wykednes and of perdycion, and we hane goone harde weyes, for the wey off gode we knewe nat.  What hat[h] pryde profyte vs? or the boste off rychesse what hath hitt brougth to vs? but [they] bene passyde as the shadowe.  And nowe we may shewe no tokyne off holynesse, for we bene wastyde in wykednesse'.  And amonge alle the multydude off seyntis they shullene fynde nat oone that shalle haue compassyone of hem, but [&thorn;ei] shullene be gladde and consent with gode in hys ryghte Iugement off here dampnacion.  Thys wytnesseth the profete Dauyd, seying thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Letabitur iustus cum uiderit &amp;c,</FOREIGN> that ys to sey: 'The ryghtwyse mane shalle be glade whene he shalle se vengeaunce'.  For the fadere that shalle be sauyde shalle ioye the dampnacion off hys sonne, the modere off the dowghter, the sone shalle ioye the dampnacion of hys modere, [the] doughter of the fadere.  For Cryst seyth they shulle seche for to entre in to creues of stonys and in to swolowes of the see, for fere off the syghte of the dredefulle face of Cryste; thane they [shul] prey mounteyns to falle opone theme, and hylles to hyde theyme.  So woo they shulle be one euery syde, for nothyng shalle res[ei]ue theyme but only helle.  And thys ys the vounde of the furst arowe.</P><P>The secunde arowe shal be sharpe reprovyng of alle false crystene mene and womene, whene oure lorde shalle seye to hem thus: 'I was hungry ande ye gaff me no mete, I was thrysty and ye gaue [me] noo drynke, I was nakede and ye gaue me noo clothes, I was herborowles and ye herborowede me nat, I was seke [&] in presone ande ye vysyte me nat ne dyd me no comforte'.  O what thys voyce shalle be dredefulle, for as ofte as they dyden nat thyse dedis off mercy to the leste off hys that had nede, so oftyne they dyde hit nat to hyme.  And noo wondere [&thorn;off] thys voyce be dredefulle in the day off dome, sythene we redyne in the gospelle that whane Cryste came in the forme of a seruaunt to be demede of false Iewes, he sayde to hem that came to take hyme: 'I am he', [&] anone they yedyne abak and fellene to the erthe.  Thene, yeff he whene he was deedly and cam to be demyde had so ferefulle a voyce that att one worde dyde throwe to grounde so many mene of Iewes, how moche [more] ferefulle thane shall be the voyce of hyme whene [he] shalle come vndedely with hys oste off aungellys and off seyntys to deme the qwykke ande the dede lyke as they hane deseruede.  Wherfore Iob seyth:<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Cum vix paruam sintillam sermonum eius audire non possunt, tonitruum magnitudinis eius quis poterit intueri,</FOREIGN> 'Sythe mane vnnethes may here a lytylle drope of hys wordes suffre eyther beholde(!), how thane shulde they beholde the thundres of hys domes whene he shalle sytte as a ryghtfulle domesmane? as who seyth, noone.  And therfore seyth seynt Bernarde: 'When the synfulle wreche shal be accusede and hys owne conscyence shal bere wytnesse ayenst hym [&amp; euery creature of god shal rise ayenst hym] in vengeaunce, thane greuous as ane arowe shalle be &thorn;e voyce off gode to suffre'.  And therfore the profete Ieremye seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sagitta vulnerans lingua eius,</FOREIGN> that ys: the tunge of hym shalle be as a arowe woundyng.  And thys ys the wounde of the secunde arowe.</P>
<PB
N="2: 431"><P>The thrydde arowe shalle be the sentence of endeles dampnacion of alle wykede mene, whene he shalle sey to heme thus: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Discedite a me maledicti in ignem eternum qui preparatus [est] diabolo et angelis eius,</FOREIGN> that ys to sey: 'Departe ye frome me, cursyde and wrecchede, in to euerlastyng fyre, the whyche ys made redy to the deuylle and hys angelys'.  Thys arowe shalle wounde heme so grevously that alle the leches ne alle &thorn;e creatures in erthe neyther in heuyne shulle mowe hele the wounde of hit.  Than shal the erthe opyne hys mowthe and swalowe hem doune in to helle, where they shalle be tormentyde with ffeendes withoutyne ende.  But allas, ther be, I drede, fulle many that wolle natt beleue thyse thyngis, tylle they felene heme; of whome seyth seynt Euseby:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ve ue quibus datum erit prius sentire quam credere,</FOREIGN> that is: 'Woo [woo] be to hem to whom hit shalle be youyn rather to fele thyse thyngis than to beleue heme'. Thys ys the wounde off the thrydde arowe.
</P><P>More-ouer sende thyne herte in to purgatory, that ys the free prysone off oure lorde gode to punyssh heme that were clene-shryvene off alle here synnes or they passyne owte off thys worlde, and hane nat perfourmede here penaunce here in thys lyff ne were nat fully clensyd as hem behouyth for to be.  In the whyche purgatory they shalle be purede with bytter peynes, and that paynes ys more harde to suffre eyther to fele than alle the paynes that euere martyres suffredene, ande more payne thane tunge cane reherse or telle.  Ther shalle thy soule be turment thorow ane hole yere for the penaunce that myght haue be done here in o day&mdash;here-fore oure lorde seyth: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Diem pro anno dedi tibi,</FOREIGN> that ys: 'I haue yeuene [the] a day for a yere'.  And trusteth for certeyne that that payne doth nat ellys but clenseth the soule frome syne; for the more ioye in heuene shalle he neuere purchase therby for that peyne sufferyng, though he were there from the begynnyng off thys worlde in to the day of dome.  But the payne that thou suffrest here with meke herte, thynkyng that thoue art worthy hit and moche more for the grete trespaces and vnkyndenes that thou euery day dost ayenst oure lorde gode, shalle bothe helpe to clense thy soule, and to encrese thy blysse in heuene.
</P><P>Also haue mynde of .VII. paynes that thy soule shalle haue.  The furst shalle be whane thy body ande thy soule shalle parte; for thane shullene the fendys appere in theyr lykenesse to rauyssh the soule in to helle with grysely chere, with chalangis ande thretenyngis as hit were theyre ryghte to haue hit, and so to brynge hit in to dyspeyre yeff they mowene.
</P><P>The seconde peyne ys thys: the grete drede that the soule shalle haue tylle the Iugement be endyde be-twene the aungelles ande the ffendis; for lyke as a mane beyng in grete tempestis on the see hath grete drede of drenchyng, so the soule heryng the grete and horryble synnes that he hath done rehersyde be the fende, stondeth in grete fere for to be dronchede in the fyre of helle; for though the soule haue ryghte be-leue ande ryghte trusty hope to be sauyde, yet oure lorde suffreth hit to haue the drede, for to clense hit frome synne.
</P><P>The III<HI REND="sup">de</HI> ys exylyng; for the soule ys exylyde oute off thys lyfe, from hys frendis, and from hys herytage&mdash;whyche ys paradyse&mdash;thorowgh syne; the whyche they shullene neuer be restorede to, vn-to the tyme that hit be purede and claryfyede as clene as hit was att the day off bapteme; for seynt Austyne seyth: 'lyke as golde ys purede and claryfyede be fyre here, ryghte so shale the soule be purede ande claryfyede by the fyre there'.  And loke, howe moch here the fyre ys hotere thane the sone-beame, so moche ys the fyre off purgatory more hote thane the fyre here; and loke, what peyne hit were to suffre any parte off the body to brynne in the fyre here, so moche peyne ande more hit ys to the soule to be in [the] fyre there; for seynt Ancelme seyth that the fyre off purgatory ys

<PB N="2: 432">

off so moche myghte and so kene, that as longe as hit ffyndeth aughte in the soule that toucheth [to] synne, hit stynteth neuer.</P>
<P>The fourthe payne ys that the soule ys boundyne with bondys off synne, that hit may nat helpe hit-selfe but nedys muste suffre, to the bondys be wasted; for lyke as a mane boundene muste suffre the malyce off hys enemyes, ryghte so the soule muste suffre the peynes tylle hit be purede.</P><P>The fyfte payne ys the sekenesse that the soule shalle be greuede with; for lyke as a mane boundene muste suffre the malyce off hys enemyes, ryghte so the soule muste suffre the peynes tylle hit be purede. The fyfte payne ys the sekenesse that the soule shalle be greuede with; for </P><P>[The sixt payne is that the soulis bene there as in dissert, where defaute is of alle gode, and plenty of alle eville.]</P><P>The seuenth payne ys the grete colde that they shullene be caste in after the feruent hete, for sodaynly oute off the brynnyng fyrre they shalle be caste in a lycoure that ys caldere thane any Ise or snowe; and oute of that colde sodaynly they [shal] be caste ayen in to feruent hete; ande so to be paynede with paynes innumerable, tylle oure lorde off hys endeles mercy wylle graunte heme grace off delyueraunce, and so to come to the endeles blysse that mane was ordeynede to in hys furst creacion.  Now whane thou hast welle examynede what peyne ys in purgatory for penaunce that ys nat done in thys lyfe, and for venyalle synnes that he was natt shryvene off neyther made [a]sythe for heme in noone other waye:  be ware thane that thou delay nat from day to day to do penaunce, neyther be recheles in doyng, ne sory to do hit, but do hit with grete mekenesse and gladnesse off herte, hauyng mynde what peyne thow were worthy to suffre for thy trespasse that thou dost custumablye ayenst thy makere, thyne ayenebeyere, and thy mercyffulle sparere, and [&thorn;at] therto foryeueth the thy peynes of purgatory for so lytelle penaunce doyng with meke herte.  More-ouer be ware off venyalle synnes: for hit ffareth therby as hit doth by a shyppe that hath a lytelle hole in the botome, in the whyche hole yeff the water entere, though hit be but lytelle and lytelle, yet by processe off tyme hit may drenche the shyppe, but hit be caste owte.  So, venyalle synnes so many there mowene be that yeff they be nat caste [oute] by sorowe of herte, by prayere ande by allemos-dede doyng, [they] may drenche the soule in to endeles paynes of helle as a dedely synne may doo. Sythyne than that almyghty gode ys dyspleasede and dyshonowrede by venyalle synnes, that be callede smale synnes, how moche more thane ys he dyshonourede and dysplesyde with dedely synnes?  and sythyne euery venyalle syne ys so grete in goddys syghte, how meche more than ys dedely synne?  Therfore haue mynde on thy trespas that thou hast done ayenst gode bothe in worde ande in thougth, in delytyng ande consentyng, in desyryng ande in dede-doyng, and euer with meke herte ande with conpunccion of teeres aske foryeuenes; and therto make satysfaccion to thyne euynecrystene off alle the trespasses that thou hast done ayenst hyme as fer forth as thy goodys wolle strecche; ande yeff thy goode wolle nat suffyse, thane behoueth the to aske foryeuenesse; and yeff thow may not come to the partyes eyther for febylnes or ellys that they be dede, thane be in wylle to aske foryeuenes, and pray for hem; so that thou mayst escape thyse peynes off helle, and the sonnere be delyueryd owte off the peynes off purgatory thorowe the endeles mercy off oure lorde gode.  For alle tho that bene quykenyde with the gracyous illuminacion of the holy gost, dredyne thyse two placys, that ys, helle ande purgatory,


<PB N="2: 433">

and so kepe[n] hem with alle theyre mygth from alle maner off synnes.  [But] for the kynde off mannys flessh ys so freelle ande so inclynyng to synne that no day passyth  withowtene synne eyther more or lesse:  therfor oure forme-ffaders that werene in grace and knewene the[r] freelnes, lyuedene in mornyng, and ofte for-thynkyng in herte with ffastyng and almes-dedys, with prayere ande grete wepyngys, sorowdene for her synnes, thorow the whych they were clensyde and caste oute off the soule.  Also som mene that hane bene before, sore defoulede with dedely synnes and with venyalle Innumerable, oftyne-tymes for drede to offende god more, and also to haue [grace &] foryeuenesse of the [synnes] before-doone, and to fle frome thyse two places that bene so paynefulle, hane forsake alle the worlde, bothe the[r] goodis and also the presence off people&mdash;for the ey off mane ys a grete occasyone to syne and thane cometh speche off mowthe, and so ofte-sythes fulfyllede in dede; wherfor they seing ther freelnes, fleddene in to deserte places, to lerne to loue oure lorde Ihesu Cryste, and there they wayledene theyre synnes before-done and therto continuelly lyfedene in prayere and in abstynence with bodyly werkes, in chastysyng the body from wykydnes; and also hauyng compassyone off theyre euene-crystene, seyng the grete torment that they were yne bothe in getyng off worldely goodes and worldely worschyppys and flesshly lustys and so lyuedene as vnresonable bestis hauyng noo mynde that they shulle dyene neythere that they shalle come ande be demede in the dredefulle day off dome, but contynuede in theyre malyce ande in wykydnes as they shulde neuer dye, or ellys wenyng that [god] ys so mercyfulle that he wylle natt punyssh synners.</P><P>
Now sende thy herte in to heuyne, to wyte how it ys there.  And ther shalt thow fynde plente off alle goodys, for there ys no maner of peyne but euer-[ich] in ioye and lykyng in helthe, and so euer fyllede with alle maner off ioye and swetnesse. For there ys al maner off melody with songe of angelles brygth, and therto sekernesse of euerlastyng blysse that neuer shalle haue ende.  Also mannys body shalle be brytere thene the sonne whene hit shyneth brygthest, and shalle haue more sw[ift]nesse then alle erthely creatures mow deuyse, and her thoughtis, her wylles and her desyres shal be fulfyllyde in the twynkelyng of ane eye.  No thyng shal be there but alle goodnes and comforte; nouther no thyng shalle withstande heme, for they shalle be so myghty that they shalle mowe passe al hylles and valeys, and so to be frome the one ende off the worlde to the othere in as breeff tyme as hit may be thoughte.  For thowgh they were so febylle here, there they shullene be so lyghte, so lusty, so beauteuouse, ande so fulfyllede with ioye, that nothyng shalle withstande theyme that ys contrary to theyre wylle.  For they shulle haue ffulle knowyng of alle thyngis that euer were doone or shalle be doone, for they shulle haue fulle knowyng of the trynyte, the myghte of the fadere, the wysedome of the sone, the goodnes of the holy gost; for in the syght of the gloryous face of oure lorde gode they shullene [se] alle that may be seene off any creature; for as seynt Austyn&macr; seyth, they shulle see hyme both gode and mane, and they shalle see hem-self in hym, and alle other thyngis more and lesse&mdash;for alle thyngis that nowe be hidde, shulle thene be opyne both in syghte ande knowyng.  Ande so they shalle be fulfyllede in theyre .v. wyttes with alle maner of ioye; for lyke as a vesselle that ys dyppyde in the water ys wete bothe with-inne &amp; with-oute, aboue ande benethe ande on euery syde, and nomore lykore may resceyue for fulnesse, ryghte so shulle they that shalle be sauyde be fulfyllede with ioye and blys with-outen ende.  Also they shullene haue endeles lyffe in the syghte of the holy trinite, and thys ioye shalle passe alle other ioyes, for they shalle be in ful sekyrnes that they shullene neuer fayle off that excellent ioye.  Also they shullene haue parfyte loue to-geder, for eche off heme shalle accorde to odyr wylle; that he that ys in the leste ioye shalbe as ioyfulle of hyme that ys in the hyghest ioye,


<PB N="2: 434">

as though he were there in the same ioye.  And so the ioyes of that gloryous blysse may noo herte thynke nor tonge reherse; ffor though alle the ioyes that alle erthely creatures couthe deuyse myghte be comprehendyde in oo ioye, yet were hit nat in comparysone to the lest ioye that ys in that gloryous blysse.  For the ioyes that bene there be so delycate, so comfortable and so fulle off swetnesse that they myghte dey for ioye, but &thorn;at god preseruyth hem fro deth as thoo that be in [the] horryble pytte off helle &amp; stynkynge paynes myghtene dyene for payne and tormentis the whyche [they] musten suffre, but that gode preserueth theym fro dethe.  For oure lorde wolle that thoo &thorn;at hane kepte hys commaundementis and hane submyttyde hem to hys lawes, to lyue in blysse with-outene ende; and there-ayens tho that wylle nat obeye to hys lawes neyther kepe hys commaundementis, that they shalle lyue in payne with-outyne ende. &mdash; Thys ys the ryghte spore that shalle haste hem to loue oure lorde in vertewe [of] goodnes, ande to hate synne for fere of peyne(!).  For yeff a creature myghte fele the lest drope off the leste ioye whyche ys in that blysse, [he] shulde fele lytylle payne or ellys noone thowgh alle the peynes that euer were in erthe or shullene be, myghte be putte to hyme; for the grete loue [&thorn;at] suche a soule shulde haue to gode, and &thorn;e grete desyre that hit shulde haue to that endeles blysse, shulde so rauyssch the soule that hit [shuld] fele noo paynes that myghte be putte therto; neyther hit shulde haue no ioye of noone erthely goodys neyther off worldely worshyppys, but rather noying thane plesyng therto.  Thys loue steryth a mane more be a thowsandefolde thane done the peynes of helle eyther of purgatory, to lyue vertously; ffor loue perysshyth and putteth oute drede, and clenseth the soule fro synne, and maketh hit to see gode thorough gostly thoughtis, thorow gostly redyngis of holy wrytte, and thorow gostly and holy prayers, and to sty to heuynly desyres.  But I drede ther be many [&thorn;at] farene as a chylde that ys borne in a depe prysone whyche ys bothe stynkyng and horryble to see.  The moder, knowyng the wellefare that she hadde owte of prysone, ys in moche sorowe and care ande heuynesse, desyryng with alle her myghte to be oute of prysone ayene in hyr welfare:  but the chylde borne in myscheff of the prysone, ande neuer hade better knowyng of welfare, yeueth lytelle tayle to that myscheff in the prysone, for as longe as he hath hys moder with hyme and hys sustenaunce thowgh hit be but ffebylle, he maketh neyther sorowe ne care, for he longeth after no better fare, for he knoweth no better; for though hys moder telle hyme off the ioye ande off the welffare that ys oute off prisone, off the sone ande off the mone eyther off the sterres, or off the fayre floures spryngyng opone the erthe, or of the byrdys syngyng, off myrthe, of melody, or of ryche aray of lordys, of ladyes, and of welthes owte of prisone the whyche she was wonte to haue, yet alle hyr tale ys but a dreme to the chylde, for he leueth hit nat and therfor he longeth nat ther-after, and wylle nat for alle that blysse and welfare that she spekyth of forsake hys moder ne hys febylle fare that he hath with hyr; and that ys for he leueth hit nat.  Ande yet hit ys as &thorn;e modere seyth.  But were the chylde onys owte off prysone, and se the myrthe, welthe ande welfare that she spake off, he wolde be fulle sory to go ayene in to prysone there to lyfe with hys modere; ffor alle hys lyf in prisone, whyche was furst lykyng Inowgh to hym, shalle thane be to hyme fulle bytter and paynfulle, and therto he shulde neuer haue ioye ne reste in herte tylle he were ageyn in that welffare whyche he sawe oute of prisone.  Ryghte so this folk of thys worlde borne and browgth forth in sorowe and care and moche trauayle in thys wrecchede worlde that ys foule and stynkyng as a prisone; for they hane so moche loue and lykyng one theyre erthely moder ande of theyre company, that ys to say one erthely thyngis, that they hane no lykyng in heuynly thyngis ne longyn nat ther-after; for though


<PB N="2: 435">

her gostly moder, holy chyrche, ande her gostely ffader gode hym-self, fader off alle, telle hem the blysse ande the wellfare whyche ys in the blysse off heuyne, hit ys to theyme but a dreme as the tale off the moder ys to the chylde in prysone, that they hane noo sade feyth theryne.  And tryste itt fully, though they beleue nat that hit ys so as oure moder holy chyrche tellyth, howe ther ys in this worlde but stynke ande horrybylyte and a foule dongeone in comparysone of that heuynly blysse, yet hit ys so as her gostly fader seyth, ande nat the lese for her mysbeleue.  Neuer-the-lese take hit for certeyne that they shalle neuer haue parte neyther ffelyng of that blysse, but they wol beleue ande trust fully that hit ys so as theyre modere holy chyrche telleth.  Wherfore withdrawe youre hertis from erthely thyngis and sette [not] youre loue to moche one youre erthely moder, ne truste her nat, for though she speke neuer so fayre and behote yow neuer so welle, she ys false ande wolle dysceyue yow at the last.  For she fareth as the nykare or meremaydene, that cast opone the water syde dyuerse thyngis whyche semene fayre and gloryous to mane, but anone as he taketh hit ande weneth to be sure theroff, anone she taketh hyme ande deuoureth hym.  Ryghte so thyne erthely moder casteth oute fayre ande gloryous thyngis to thy syghte, she casteth oute grete rychesse and worldely goodys ande worshyppes ande flesshly lustis, whyche bene fastnede to the rope off hope of longe lyff, and assone as thow towchest heme, that ys to say as sone as thow desyrest heme and laborest with alle thy myghte, with alle thyne herte and with alle thyne thoughtis to haue heme, anone she draweth the rope off longe lyfe, that ys, she seyth 'thow arte yonge and may lyue longe, ande therfor laboure to haue goodys ande gete the worschypp, that thow mayst lyue esyly in thyne age.  And thow lyue in lechery, in glotony, in pryde, in extorsyone or in any wrongfulle takynge, whene thou comest to age than shalt thow mowe doo grete almes, and so by prayers off pore men shalt thow haue foryeuenesse'; and so thorow hope off longe lyfe ande of other mennes prayers thowh thou lyue stylle in synne, [she] wylle take ande deuoure the in the fyre off helle.  And therfor trust her nat; but set thy trust, thyne hope, thyne loue in thy gostly moder that ys to beauteuouse and trust[i] to be-leue opone hyr, for she seyth nowthere behotyth but that shalle be performede, yeff thou wolt obey to here byddyngis.  For yeff thou haddest felt ore seyne the lest blysse that ys in heuyne, thene alle the ioyes and lykyngis that thow hast in thys worlde of erthely thyngis, shalle thane be to the grete bytternes, sorowe ande care.  Example haue we off seynt Petyr whom Cryst ladde opone the hylle off Thabor with Iohne ande Iames, and ther he schewede but a lytylle off [the] blysse of hys manhode, whyche was hys face shynyng as the sonne, hys clothys were whyte as snowe, ande Moyses ande Helyas apperede with hyme in grete blysse ande in grete mageste.  Than Petyr seyde vnto oure lorde Ihesu: Lorde, hit ys good to vs to be here, and make we thre tabernacles, on to the, another to Moyses, and another to Hely, and late us allewey dwelle here', and so anone in the syghte of that lytelle blys in comparysone off the blys that ys in heuyne, he forgatte alle the blysse off thys worlde, for he carede neythere for mete ne drynke ne for clothyng; hym thoughte he myghte haue lyuede there withoutyne ende by that blysfulle syghte, Luc. 9o.  Also seynt Powle was rauysshede in to heuene ande hade seene the vysyons and the pryuytees off gode; afterwarde alle hys lyfe in thys worlde was to hyme a peyne, so moche he longede agayne to that blysse:  wherfore he seyde:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Infelix ego homo sum, quis me liberabit de corpore [mortis] huius,</FOREIGN> that ys:  '[I] vnsely mane, who shalle delyuer me from the body [of this deth?  I covett to be departid the soule from the body] and to be with Cryste withoutyne ende?'  Moyes was with gode in the mount of Synay fourty dayes and fourty nyghtes meteles ande drynkles, fedde be the presence and the speche of gode; and yet sawe he but lytelle off hys blysse.  Sythene than Petyr, Powle,


<PB N="2: 436">

and Moyses werene fulfyllede and myght haue lyfede withoutene ende in the syghte off that lytelle blysse, moche more thene after the day of dome alle tho that shullene be sauyde and go to blysse bothe body and soule, shullene be fulfyllede with ioye, blysse and comforte whyche neuer shalle haue ende.</P><P>Now, brother or syster that heryst or redest thys sympylle wrytyng, take hede off thy horse, whyche ys thy body, that he be made buxome and mylde vnto the soule whyche ys hys master.  Also take hede that the soule be welle armede with gostly armour, whyche beene vertewes, and that the spere, [the] swerde, and the shelde be nat lefte be-hynde; and haue mynde off thyne rewarde whyche ys putte in thyne eleccione.  Thynke what blysse thow mayst haue, yeff thow wolt trauayle and quyte the as a trewe knyghte in thys gostly batayle; and ther-ayens what peyne, woo and tormentys thow shalt haue in fyre off helle, yeff thow be a cowarde and wylle nat fyghte ayenst thy gostly enemyes but consentest to there wykede counsellys and wylle nat obey to goddys commaundementis and to hys lawe.  Also be ware off thy erthely moder that she dysseue the nat; but trust in thy gostly moder, for she ys trew ande trusty to truste vpone and to be-leue vpone; and yeff thou doo thus, thane shalle thow come to endeles blysse whyche man was ordeynede to in hys furst creacione, amen.
</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit tractatus de bello spirituali et Armatura pertinente.</FOREIGN></TRAILER> </DIV2><DIV2
TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main">The Mirror of Sinners<NOTE>A loose and abridged translation of the <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Speculum peccatoris</FOREIGN>.</NOTE></HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Univ. Coll. Oxford 97</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="253" UNIT="page">
<OPENER>Heere bigynneth a sentence ful good and profitable to rede, which is i.-cleped 'the myrour of synneres'.</OPENER><P>For &thorn;at we been in the wey of this failyng lyf ande oure dayes passen as a schadewe, &thorn;erfore it nedeth ful ofte to recorde in oure mynde that oure freelte and oure deedly seeknesse maketh vs so ofte to for&yogh;ete.  But what thyng is &thorn;at? Certis, it is &thorn;at highe sentence of hooly writ &thorn;e whiche al-my&yogh;ty god, wilnyng oure profit &thorn;orugh his grace, hath &yogh;euen to vs by &thorn;at blessed Moyses his prophete, seienge thus:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Vtinam saperent &amp; intelligerent, ac nouissima prouiderent,</FOREIGN> that is: Wolde god &thorn;at men sauouredyn and vnderstoden, and purueieden for the laste thynges!  O &thorn;at noble and &thorn;at profitable sentence, not oones but ofte-tymes needful to be rehersed, that is:  Wolde god &thorn;at men sauouredyn and vnderstoden and purueieden for the laste thynges!  &para; My deere brother, i. prey &thorn;ee vnderstond wel what &thorn;ow redist.  For &thorn;e bisy vnderstondyng of this sentence is distruccion of pruyde, quenchyng of enuye, medicyne of malice, dryuyng awey of licherie, voidyng of boost and of vanytee, informacion of leernyng, perfeccion of hoolynesse,


<PB N="2: 437">

and reparaylyng of euerlastynge heelthe, and &thorn;erfore the prophete pleinyng oure greete blyndenesse, preieth with pitee seiynge thus:  Wolde god &thorn;at men sauouredyn and vnderstooden and purueiedyn for the laste &thorn;inges!  But allas, allas!  for al to fewe han this vertew, fful fewe &thorn;eer been &thorn;at sauouren &thorn;is heelful sentence: fful fewe there been &thorn;at setten bifore &thorn;e ei&yogh;en of here mynde &thorn;e knowynge of here owen infirmyte, here bodily corrupcion, &thorn;e mynde of here synnes, &thorn;e day of here deeth, and the horrible peynes of helle.  Be-hold now, freend, how profitable a myrour it is for synneres, the inwardly biholdyng of this highe sentence, that is:  Wolde god &thorn;at men sauouredyn and vnderstonde, and purueieden for the laste thynges!  For &yogh;ef &thorn;ow ofte biholde thi-self in this myrour, and &yogh;ef &thorn;ow bisily studye to sette thus &thorn;i-self bifore thy-self, doutelees, thow schalt be strengere &thorn;an Sampson, moore waar &thorn;an Dauyd, and wiser than Salomon.  Thise men, for &thorn;ei weren rechelees in biholdyng of hem-self in this myrour of for[e]sight, thei fellen in to here lusty desires, and to blyndenesse of here flesch.  And sitthe &thorn;ise men fellen in to so horrible synne, in the whiche theer was so greet strengthe, so heigh wisdom, and so greet waarnesse:  with how muche studye mooten we &thorn;anne awake in biholdyng on this myrour, in the whiche is soo muche freelte, so greet vnkunnyng, and so muche recheleeshede.  And for this skyle been &thorn;ise &thorn;re men i.-red and i.-spoken of in hooly churche, that &thorn;ei schulden be to vs a myrour of for[e]seynge, and not to &thorn;e ensaumple of fallynge; so &thorn;at noon of vs truste in his owene stren&yogh;the, ne presume in his owene wisdom, but euermoore to be bisy for the helthe of oure soule, and neuere to for&yogh;ete oure deedly corrupcion.  For alle &thorn;ei &thorn;at been recheles in suche maner of lokynge in this myrour, neither thei sauouren, ne thei vnderstondyn, ne &thorn;ei bysyen hem to purueye for the laste &thorn;inges.  And for &thorn;at we schulden euere be bisy aboute this studye of bifore-waarnesse, the sentence of god moeuyth vs, seiynge thus:  The men that been withouten counseil and purueaunce, wolde god &thorn;at thei sauouredyn, and vnderstoden, and purueieden hem for &thorn;e laste thynges! &para; To this heelful sentence loke &thorn;at &thorn;ow biholde, and that nou&yogh;t passyngly, but with greet studye &amp; ri&yogh;t good auysement:  ffor ri&yogh;t as encens smelleth not but &yogh;ef it be put in to the fuyr, so no sentence of hooly scripture may sauoure to the redere ne to &thorn;e herere &thorn;eerof but &yogh;ef it be i.-boyled in herte with bisy and brennyng studye of it.  And therfore, wolde god &thorn;at men sauouredyn, and vnderstoden, and purueieden for the laste thynges.  Biholde, brother, thre thynges been set bifore &thorn;e in this myrour:  Sauoury knowyng, vnderstondyng, and purueaunce.  For god wole that &thorn;ow sauoure &thorn;at &thorn;ou knowest; that &thorn;ow vnderstonde; and &thorn;at [&thorn;ow] be of good purueaunce.  &para; As for the firste, god wole &thorn;at &thorn;ow knowe &thorn;at this lyf is passyng, al bilapped in wrecchednesse, soiet to alle maner of vanytee, defouled with filthes of synne, corrupt with couetise, and &thorn;at it schal perisshe with-ynne schort tyme; so &thorn;at in as muche as this world is knowen to bee moore vil, in so muche it may the li&yogh;tloker be dispised for loue of &thorn;at lif that euer schal laste.  &para; For the secounde, god wole &thorn;at &thorn;ow vnderstonde &thorn;at &thorn;ow koome naked in to this world, and naked &thorn;ow schalt goon hennes; ffor of eerthe &thorn;ow weere i.-maad, and in to eerthe &thorn;ow schalt turne.  Wepynge &thorn;ow koome in to this wrecchednesse, with teene and traueil &thorn;ow hast endured thi dayes, and with sorwe &amp; woo &thorn;ow schalt passe hennes.  Vnderstond &thorn;erfore how wooful is &thorn;in entree, how chaungeable is thy lyuynge heere, &amp; how feerful is thy passyng awey. Ande passyng al this vnderstonde, i. prey &thorn;ee, that in this vaale of weepyng &thorn;ow art bothe seeke and an outlawe, ful poore in vertues, fful vnstable in thy lyuyng, and happily thow schalt not abide til to-morwe.  Oo brother, ful wel schal &thorn;ee bee &yogh;ef &thorn;owe sauoure &amp; vnderstonde thise thynges &thorn;at i. telle &thorn;ee, and &yogh;ef &thorn;ow wolt write hem in thyn herte as in a book; &amp; namely &yogh;ef thow bisye the to keepe in thy mynde thise two versis next folwynge:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Viue deo gratus, mundo toto tumulatus, Crimine mundatus, semper transire paratus,</FOREIGN> that is:  'Lyue thankful to thi god, buried al to the world, Maad al cleene of synne, &amp; reedy euer to goon henne'. Lo nowe, my deere brother, now hast &thorn;ow i-seye in this myrour what &thorn;ow schalt sauoure, and what thow schalt vnderstonde.  &para; But now as for the thridde, lat


<PB N="2: 438">

see what &thorn;ow schalt purueye:  preynge thus with the prophete:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Notum fac michi domine finem meum, et numerum dierum meorum quis est, ut sciam quid desit michi,</FOREIGN> that is:  'Lord, make myn eende i.-knowe to me, &amp; which is the noumbre of my dayes, that i. may knowe what me fayleth'.  O &thorn;at profitable preyer, &thorn;at heelful contemplacioun, and &thorn;at necessarie askynge of god; nou&yogh;t for to coueite to knowe bifore tymes &amp; momentis, the whiche the fader of heuene hath sette in his owen power, but &thorn;at &thorn;ow knowe and vnderstonde that &thorn;ow art but an outlawe, a gest, and a pilgrym heer in this wrecchide lyf, a freel man and a feble, and luytel while abydyng vpon &thorn;is eerthe.  For &yogh;ef &thorn;ow biholde wel to the schortnesse of this lyf, and seest how the lakketh sufficeaunt tyme to fulfille inne penaunce for thy synnes in trew keepyng of the heestis of god and in encresyng of thi perfeccion, &thorn;ow schuldest bothe sauoure and vnderstonde; and &yogh;ef &thorn;ow wolt sette the sodeynte of deeth bifore &thorn;e ei&yogh;en of &thorn;i mynde, doutelees &thorn;ow schuldest &thorn;anne withouten lette dispise al &thorn;e boost of &thorn;is lyf, &thorn;e bisynesse of worldly vanytee, &amp; alle &thorn;e lustes &thorn;at longen to the flesch, and sette wise &amp; waar kepynge of thi wittes, and bisily purueye &thorn;ee for the laste thynges.  For alle wise men awaiten as bisily to the eende of euery thyng, as to the bigynnyng, and rathere moore; &amp; verreily he is proeued for wise, that so wel &thorn;enketh of rekenyng bifore rekenyng, &thorn;at he may after in tyme of rekenyng eschewe peril of rekenyng. &para; But now perauenture &thorn;ow seist to me thus:  'Sire, i am al reedy to doo after the counseil of god, &thorn;at i. may sauoure &amp; vnderstonde &amp; purueye for the laste thynges: but whiche been my laste thynges that &thorn;ow spekest of?'  Soothly thei been thoo the whiche &thorn;e holy goost spekith of to &thorn;ee by Salomon, seiynge thus:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Fili, in omnibus memorare nouissima, et ineternum non peccabis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Sone, in alle thynges haue in mynde thy laste thynges and &thorn;ow schalt not synne with-outen eende'.  He synneth with-outen eende, that deserueth peyne withouten eende; the which synne and peyne a man may redilokest eschewe by contynuel thenkynges of his laste thynges, as it is schewed by thise verses that folwen:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Non melius poterit caro luxuriosa domari, Mortua qualis erit quam semper premeditari,</FOREIGN> that is:  'A lecherous flesch may no better be temed, than euere to thenke byfore what it schal be after &thorn;at it is deed'.  And therfore ful blessed schalt &thorn;ow be &yogh;ef &thorn;ou holde with contynuaunce this holy bithenkyng of thi laste thynges.</P>
<P>'But whiche been &thorn;ise laste thynges for the whiche men schulden purueie?' Sykerly thei been tho thynges that schullen falle to &thorn;ee in that feerful hour of thi deeth, whan &thorn;i wrecchede soule schal passe out of thi careful body dredyng and quakyng.  For trust it wel &thorn;at in &thorn;at dreedful hour &thorn;ee were leuer to haue the freendschip of god, &thorn;an alle the lordschipes of the world.  For whiche of thi freendis &thorn;ou&yogh; thei comen with swerdis &amp; armes, with oostis of poeple or with mylions of goold, mowe in &thorn;at laste grisly and dreedful hour doo &thorn;ee eny comfort or help?  Sothly, &thorn;eer schal noon mowe comforte the of alle &thorn;at &thorn;ow now loueste cleerly without a cleene conscience of thyn owene, &thorn;ough &thorn;ow loke to be holpyn of men; for refut schal &thorn;eer noon bee &thorn;anne, but at god al-one.  Thenk &thorn;erfore by the self, i. prey &thorn;ee, with what dreed he schulde be dred, with what loue he schulde be loued, and with what honour he schulde be worschiped, oure lord &amp; oure god verrey Crist Ihesu, the whiche oonly by hym-self is my&yogh;ty to do vs refut after oure deth.  And &thorn;erfore bryng it ofte to thi mynde, that dreedful day of thy passynge, and eer thi wrecched soule departe fro the prison of thi flesch, let it purueye whider it may goo.  Worche &thorn;erfore nowe suche thynges that mowen bothe helpe &amp; spede &thorn;ee in &thorn;at way, and leeue &thorn;ilke thynges &thorn;at mowen lette &thorn;ee.  &para; In this maner of thenkynge the soule conceyueth forthenkynge, fforthenkyng bryngeth forth confessioun, and confession norisscheth amendynge and ful asseth makyng, and alle thise togidere engendryn in a man verrey hope strecchyng in to god, and parfit meeknesse in a man self.  For what thyng is in eny mannes wit &thorn;at sonner meeuyth a man to mekenesse, to kepyng of hym-self fro vanytee, to voydynge of vnri&yogh;twisnesse, &amp; to perfeccioun of holynesse, than

<PB N="2: 439">

doth the consideracioun of a mannes corrupcioun and hys freelte, of his deedlynesse, and of the dreedful day of his deeth?  For whan a man bigynneth to wex seek &amp; his seeknesse groweth, &thorn;e conscience dreedith, &thorn;e herte quaketh, the heed stoupeth, the wyttes waasten, his strengthe faileth, the visage wexeth paale, the tunge engleymeth, the teeth stynkyn, the speche wexeth thynne, the breeth gooth awey, the body croketh, the flesch widerith, and alle the beaute is turned in to filthe and corrupcioun; whan the body is buried, it falleth in to powdir, &amp; is turned alle in to wormes.  Bihold now, brother, this is an horrible si&yogh;t; but it is a [ful] profitable myrour.  O ful happy is he &thorn;at bisily biholdeth hym-self in this myrour:  ffor &thorn;eer is no craft, medicyne, ne techyng, &thorn;at so soone distruyeth vice, &amp; plaunteth vertewes, as doth &thorn;e inwardly biholdyng thus of a mannes laste thynges.  And &thorn;erfore, wolde god &thorn;at men sauouredyn &amp; vnderstoden, and purueiedyn for the laste thynges!  &para; For what thyng, after &thorn;at it is deed, waxeth so vyl as a man?  For the flesch of a man is moore vyl than the skyn of a schepe.  For though a schepe dye, sum profit cometh &thorn;eerof:  the skyn is take fro the flesch, and on it men writen in both sydes; and whan a man dieth, alle dieth with hym the flesch, &thorn;e skyn &amp; &thorn;e boones.  Be a-schamed, &thorn;ow proude man, bee aschamed!  thow &thorn;at hast moore likynge to leerne &amp; to reede on the bokes of vanytees than on the bookes of holy writ!  &YOGH;it be a-schamed, &amp; heere what the prophete seith to &thorn;ee and to alle suche in his psalme: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Apprehendite disciplinam, ne quando irascatur dominus et pereatis de via iusta,</FOREIGN> that is:  'Take &yogh;e techyng of amendement of maneres, lest oure lord bee agreued and &yogh;e perissche fro the ri&yogh;te way'.</P>
<P>O how feerful a sentence is this, and howe muche to be drad!  ffor it is openly schewed be this sentence, that alle &thorn;oo schullen perisshe that taakyn not this heelful techyng of amendement.  And therfore oure lord seith &thorn;us by Moyses his prophete:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Omnis anima que non fuerit afflicta die hac, peribit de populo meo,</FOREIGN> that is:  'Euery soule schal perisshe &thorn;at chastiseth not it-self' by hertly forthynkyng and laweful amendement of his maneres, 'this day', that is to seye:  in this present lyf, whan the li&yogh;t of grace &amp; of mercy schynyth openly, take it who take wole; ffor who so wol not now taake tyme of forthynkyng, schal after hys deeth haue no place of for&yogh;euyng.  And &thorn;erfore be soore a-dred &thorn;ow wrecched chaityf synner, &thorn;ow proude flesch, thow vile careyne, bee soore a-dred!  &thorn;ow wrecche, bee a-dred!  Cast awey thi pruyde, fflee fro vanytee, and taak to the this heelful techyng of amendement, lest &thorn;ow perissche.  Be-hold in this myrour and see what &thorn;ow hast been, what &thorn;ou art, and what thow schalt bee.  &para; Thenk of how vile a mater &thorn;ow woxe vp in thy modris wombe, how vyl al thyng is whan it passeth fro thee, be it neuer so deynteuous whan thow receyuest it; and last of alle, bihold how vile wormes mete &thorn;ow schalt be lyggyng in thy graue.  Bihold now, &thorn;ow wrecche, what mateer &thorn;ow hast of sorwe moore than of ioye, what mater of meeknesse moore &thorn;an of pruyde.  And what so euer &thorn;at fooles doon, loke euer &thorn;at &thorn;ou be munnyng of thy-self:  Let the world wexe vil to &thorn;ee, eer thou be vil to hit.  And ouer al &thorn;is bihold in this myrour how &thorn;at in the laste horrible &amp; dreedful houre, whan thi wrecchide soule schalle passe fro thi body, anoon &thorn;eer schullen be reedy &amp; present a greet &amp; an horrible multitude of wykked spirites, mynistres of the foule feend of helle, ri&yogh;t as it weeren as meny lyouns rorynge for to chase thy soule as for here pray.  &para; Thanne sodeynly &thorn;eere schullen appeere ful horrible plases of peyne and of derkenesse, Places of drede and of quakynge, Places of gryndynge of teeth &amp; of wepynge.  Theer schal bee fretynge of wormes, and the hidous noyse of punysschede soules cryengge:  'Woo!  Woo! Woo be to vs, &thorn;e synful wrecchede sones of Eue'!  And whan alle thise thynges and oother moo lyk to &thorn;ise, &yogh;ee and a &thorn;owsand-foold worse thynges &thorn;en mowen be spoken, [ben] i-herd, i-seye and felt of the wrecchid soule passynge out of the caareful body:  how grysely and how muche dreed, feerdnesse &amp; tremblynge schal thanne be in it, the whiche tunge may not telle.  &para; But no[w] i. aske of thee, seyenge thus:  &para; What schal it thanne profite to &thorn;e al thy boost of kunnynge,

<PB N="2: 440">

&thorn;e pompe of the poeple, the vanytee of the world, and al the dignytee of worldly couetise?  Sothly, it schalle but encrece thi peyne &amp; thi woo, and after the quantite of thi lusty lyuyng heere, schal stoonde the quantite of thi peyne &thorn;eere. And therfore amende &thorn;ee now, whiles tyme is of mercy, so &thorn;at &thorn;ow be not dampned in the dreedful day of goddes greete vengeaunce.  And leerne wel, eer &thorn;ow go hennes, to sauoure, to vnderstonde, and wisely to purueye &thorn;ee for the laste &thorn;inges; so &thorn;at &thorn;ow bee euere-moore reedy, what tyme &thorn;at oure lord cometh to clepe thee, for to entre with hym in to the blisse &thorn;at euer schal laste.  To &thorn;e whiche blisse god brynge vs, that boughte vs with his precious blood.  AmeN.</P> </DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main">A meditacion of &thorn;e fyue woundes of Ihesu Crist</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub"> Ms. Univ. Coll. Oxford 97</HEAD><MILESTONE N="262" UNIT="page"><P>Byhold specialy in &thorn;e fyue mooste notable woundes, two in his blessed hoondys, &amp; two in his blessed feet, and &thorn;e mooste opene wounde in his ri&yogh;t syde.  In to thise woundys of Cristes blessed hoondys &amp; feet, with Thomas of Ynde put In thyne fyngres, that is to seye thyne mooste sotyle &thorn;ou&yogh;tes &amp; desires.  And in the wounde of Cristes blessed syde, sytthen it is the largeste and deppest, put in alle &thorn;in hoond, that is to seye al &thorn;i lyf and alle &thorn;ine werkes, and &thorn;eere feel Cristes herte so hoote louynge &thorn;ee; ande also &thorn;eere feel Cristis blessed herte-blood sched for thee and to raunsome thi soule, also &thorn;eere feel the watir of Cristis syde stremynge out as of a welle of lyf, for to wassche &thorn;e and alle mankynde of synne.  And &thorn;anne cleeche vp watir of euerelastynge lyf withouten ende of &thorn;ise fyue mooste opene woundis of Crist as out of fyue welle-sprynges. And vnderstond, see &amp; bihoolde &amp; leerne &thorn;at &thorn;e wounde in Cristes ri&yogh;t hoond is the welle of wysdom.  The wounde in Cristis lyft hoond is the welle of mercy. The wounde in Cristis ri&yogh;t foot is the welle of grace.  The wounde in Cristis lyft foot is the welle of goostly comfort.  The largeste and the deppeste wounde &thorn;e whiche is in Cristis ri&yogh;t syde, is the welle of euerlastyng lyf.  &para; Out of &thorn;e welle of wysdom in Cristis ri&yogh;t hoond, cleech vp &thorn;e holsum watir of trewe lerynge and techyng; leerne &thorn;eere how muche Crist god and man louede mannes soule, and how precious is mannes soule, ffor by-cause of the greete loue of mannes soule Crist Ihesu, &thorn;at is the wysdom of the fadir of heuene, schulde and wolde by &thorn;e ordynaunce of the blessede trynytee suffre his ri&yogh;twys ri&yogh;t hoond so dispitously to be nayled to &thorn;e cros.  &para; Out of &thorn;e welle of mercy in Cristis lyft hoond, cleech vp deuoutly the swete watir of remission and for&yogh;euenesse of oure synnes, and leerne bisyly heere for thy sauacion this lessun of mercy; for not-withstondyng &thorn;at the while mankynde was enemy to god, and eer that man hadde deserued it of god, &yogh;et oure blessed fadir of heuene spared not his owen sone but suffrede hym to be streyned on the harde cros, moore dispitously &amp; greuously &thorn;an euer was schepys skyn streyned on the wal or vp-on &thorn;e parchemyn-makeris harowe a&yogh;ens &thorn;e sonne to drye, ffor it is likly &thorn;at &thorn;e blessede armes of Ihesu Crist weren so soore i-strayned and sprad abrood on &thorn;e cros for oure loue, &thorn;at &thorn;e veynes to-broston.  Leerne heer &thorn;anne in this welle of mercy in Cristis lyft hoond, in whos lyft hoond hongynge and weldynge been alle richesses in heuene and in eerthe, how muche is his loue &amp; how greet is &thorn;at flood euer flowyng and also spryngynge of his mercy frely profred to man, &thorn;at suffrede so grisly and greuously his blessede armes to be sprad and nayled to &thorn;e cros, to profre his mercy and hym-self to vs his vnkynde enemyes.  Therfore sitthen euerlastynge goode god hath it of kynde, of custome &amp; of my&yogh;t to do mercy, &thorn;at neuer may ceese ne faile but &yogh;ef god loste his kynde, or loste his vertue, or loste his my&yogh;t, but sitthe this may neuer faile in goode god al my&yogh;ty, al connynge &amp; al welwillynge: &thorn;erfore tristily and stedefastly out of &thorn;is welle of the wounde of Cristys lyft

<PB N="2: 441">

hoond clecch vp &thorn;e watir of euerlastynge mercy of Ihesu Crist.  &para; Out of &thorn;e welle of grace in Cristys ri&yogh;t foot, clecch vp &thorn;e watir of goostly refresschynge, by bithenkyng &thorn;e inwardly what grace of sauacion was profred to vs alle in &thorn;at &thorn;at Crist hym-self wolde suffre his ri&yogh;t foot so grisly to bee wounded of the whiche foot holy wryt speketh &thorn;at the foorme &thorn;at it tredith vp-on is worschipful for it is holy; and so hard to be nayled to the cros &thorn;at he wolde neuere parte fro thee but &yogh;ef &thorn;ow wolt alweies forsake hym.  Heere &thorn;ou my&yogh;t li&yogh;tly cleche vp watir of greet grace profred to vs alle.  &para; Out of &thorn;e welle of gostly comfort in Cristys lyft foot, cleech vp &thorn;e Ioyeful watir of spiritual comfort &amp; gladnesse, &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of blisse louede so hertly oure soules &thorn;at for sauacion of vs he wolde suffre so soore a wounde with &thorn;at hydous nayl &thorn;orugh his lift foot &thorn;at was so tender&mdash;ffor &thorn;eer koomen to-gidere &thorn;e veynes fro Cristys herte; and &thorn;us suffrede oure blessede Ihesu for helpyng of vs.  Heer we mowen cleche vp of &thorn;is blesside welle watir of goostly comfort and ioyeful gladnesse of oure soules with-outen eende.  &para; Out of &thorn;e largeste and deppeste welle of euere-lastyng lif in &thorn;e moste opene wounde in Cristys blessed syde, cleech vp deppest and hertyliest watir of ioye and blisse withouten eende, biholdyng &thorn;eere Inwardly how Crist Ihesu god and man, to brynge &thorn;ee to euerlastynge lyf, suffrede &thorn;at harde and hydous deeth on &thorn;e cros and suffrede his syde to be opened and hym-self to be stongyn to &thorn;e herte with &thorn;at grisly spere, and so with &thorn;at deelful strook of &thorn;e spere &thorn;eere gulchide out of Cristys syde &thorn;at blysful floode of watir and blood to raunsone vs, watir of his syde to wasshe vs, and blood of his herte to bugge vs.  For loue of &thorn;ise blessede woundes creep in to &thorn;is hoot baa&thorn; of Cristys herte-blood, and &thorn;eer bathe &thorn;ee; ffor &thorn;eer was neuer synne of man ne of womman &thorn;ou&yogh;t ne wrou&yogh;t &thorn;at was laft with louely sorowe and hertly repentaunce, &thorn;at &thorn;eer ne ys in &thorn;is welle fully remyssion to buggen it, and watir of lyf fully to clensen it and wasshen it.  Therfore reste &thorn;ee heere, counforte &thorn;ee heere, lyue in Cristys herte with-outen eende AmeN.</P> </DIV2><DIV2
TYPE="text"><HEAD TYPE="main">A meditacion for oon to seie by him-self al-oone</HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub">Ms. Univ. Coll. Oxford 97</HEAD>
<MILESTONE N="305" UNIT="page"><OPENER>Heere bigynneth a ful good meditacion for oon to seie by him-self al-oone.</OPENER> <P>&YOGH;ef &thorn;ou coueite to be maad cleene in soule as it may be heere, of al &thorn;e stathel of synne the which wol alweies leeue in &thorn;ee after &thorn;i confession be &thorn;ow neuer so besy, so &thorn;at &thorn;ow mowe by &thorn;at clennesse bee maad able to receyue &thorn;e special grace of god in encresynge of &thorn;i perfection:  thanne bihoueth &thorn;e a certeyn tyme ny&yogh;t by ny&yogh;t or day by day contynuynge, as longe as &thorn;e &thorn;inketh it doth &thorn;e good, in sum pryue place [be] by &thorn;i-self, and &thorn;eere gedere to-gidere &thorn;e my&yogh;tes of &thorn;i soule, &amp; specially &thorn;i mynde, in biholdyng of &thorn;i wrecchide lyuyng, seiynge &thorn;us with herte or with mowth, or with bothe to-gedere, &yogh;ef &thorn;e bothe leste, &amp; &yogh;ef &thorn;e &thorn;enketh &thorn;at it doth &thorn;e good to do so:     'Lord Ihesu Crist', and eft-soones reherse &thorn;ise thre wordes 'lord Ihesu Crist', til &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;enke &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ow feele verreily &thorn;in herte acorde with &thorn;i mouth, and &thorn;anne passe forth &amp; not erst, &thorn;ough &thorn;ow schuldest seie it neuer so ofte til &thorn;at it so bee.  And whan &thorn;at it is so, seie &thorn;anne &thorn;us forth as i. telle &thorn;ee, with &thorn;at saame acordaunce of herte and with mowth:  'Lord Ihesu Crist, i am &thorn;at wrecche, &thorn;e mooste wykkede synnere &amp; &thorn;e mooste wlatsum of alle, &thorn;e whiche so wondirfullye haue wratthed &thorn;in highe maieste &amp; so ofte, &thorn;at my wyt may not suffice to telle it; for my synnes been as &thorn;e soond of &thorn;e see, &thorn;e whiche for multitude mowen not be noumbred'.  In &thorn;is biholdyng &amp; heere, &thorn;ow schalt sighe and sorwe as deeply and as hertly as &thorn;ow maist; ffor, &thorn;at &thorn;at smythes file dooth to &thorn;e rusty iren, &thorn;e saame goostly doth a sorweful

<PB N="2: 442">

and a deep-fet sighynge to a synful herte.     After &thorn;is biholdynge thus of &thorn;i wrecchide lyuynge in general, &thorn;ow schalt haue mynde and biholdynge of &thorn;e kyndenesse of &thorn;i lord god; and seie &thorn;us, bothe with herte &amp; with mouth as it is seid bifore:  'Lord god al-my&yogh;ty, sum tyme whan i. hadde no beynge and was nou&yogh;t, &thorn;ow brou&yogh;test me forth to &thorn;in ymage and to &thorn;i liknesse in to so noble a beeynge aboue alle oother creatures, &thorn;orugh &thorn;e whiche, hadde i. not synned, i. my&yogh;te haue had &thorn;ee by grace in &thorn;is lif, and in &thorn;at oother haue seie &thorn;ee face to face in blisse.  And i, &thorn;is wrecchide erthely worm, &thorn;e mooste vyleste synnere of alle, haue in so muche deserued &thorn;e streitnesse of &thorn;i ri&yogh;twys doom, &thorn;at but &yogh;ef &thorn;ow helpe me &yogh;euyng me &thorn;i mercy, it weere bettere to me neuere to haue been bore'.  Heere schalt &thorn;ow sighe &amp; sorwe as &thorn;ow dedist bifore.  And after haue mynde of &thorn;e kyndenesse of his incarnacion, seiynge &thorn;us, bothe with herte &amp; with mouth &yogh;ef &thorn;e bothe luste:  'Lord Ihesu Crist, art &thorn;ow not he &thorn;at highe kyng of aungelis, so lowely mekynge &thorn;ee and so wilfully for me takynge vpon &thorn;ee alle &thorn;e charges &amp; &thorn;e wrecchednesses of mankynde as hunger, &thorn;urst, and coold, with al &thorn;e remanant saue synne &amp; ignorance; and i. lord, this wrecchide erthely worm, not mekyng me but highyng me in so muche &thorn;at i haue displesyd &thorn;in highe maieste, chaungynge &thorn;ee &thorn;at art &thorn;e welle of euerlastynge goodnesse for a fewe foule stynkynge fleschly delytes of &thorn;is wrecchide lif?  A deere Ihesu, whider may i flee? huyde me may i. not, and schew me dar i. not'.  Heere schalt &thorn;ow sighe &amp; sorwe as &thorn;ow dedist bifore.  And after haue mynde of the kyndenesse of his passion, and seye &thorn;us:  'Was it not Inough to &thorn;e, my swete lord Ihesu, &thorn;us to bicome man for &thorn;e loue of man, but &yogh;ef &thorn;ow ouer &thorn;at for &thorn;e releeuynge of so menye deedly wrecches tokest vpon &thorn;ee to suffre so harde betynges, so innumerable woundes, &thorn;at fro &thorn;e sole of &thorn;i feet to &thorn;e coroune of &thorn;ine heed was no lyme ne skyn of &thorn;i blessede body &thorn;at it ne fomede ful of &thorn;i precious blode?  A, i. wikkede curside wrecche, what may i doo?  i am cause of &thorn;i deeth.  Wheer may i wone?  for by ri&yogh;twis doom of resun alle the creatures &thorn;at been bitweene heuene &amp; helle schulden fi&yogh;te a&yogh;en my oonly body.  Nowe trewely, lord, i. am wel apaied &thorn;at &thorn;ei so doo:  Let hem ryse, lord, as &thorn;in owene seruaunt&yogh; of &thorn;in owene houshold, and venge with maistrie her lord &amp; here makere of me &thorn;is straunche fremde wrecche, &thorn;at so traytourly haue been cause of my lordes turment'.  Here &thorn;ow schalt sighe &amp; sorwe as &thorn;ow dedist bifore, hauynge goostly mynde of his precious passion, wounde by wounde, to &thorn;e holugh of his herte.     But by-cause &thorn;at thise three kyndenesses bifore nempned, &thorn;at is to seye:  thy makynge, his mankynd takynge, and his precious passion, haan bee do generally to alle oothere as wel as to &thorn;ee:  &thorn;erfore schalt &thorn;ow after &thorn;is haue special mynde of sum special kyndenesse doon to &thorn;in oonly body bifore menye oothere, and seye &thorn;us:  'A goode swete lord Ihesu Crist, how menye as worthi and by a &thorn;ousand-foold moore worthy &thorn;an i, han be suffred of &thorn;ee, swete lord, for to dye, summe in here modres wombes, and summe soone after here burthe bifore eny bapteem, and so to bee dampned to eendeles derknesse; and summe to lyue in here hethenesse to here [deth]-day, and so to be dampned to eendeles peyne?  And i., sweete lord Ihesu, of &thorn;in ouerhaboundaunt goodnesse &amp; &thorn;orugh &thorn;e grace of bapteem am brou&yogh;t in to &thorn;i foold, &thorn;e whiche is holy churche, to be a scheep of &thorn;i flokke pasturynge in &thorn;i lawe, &thorn;ere be kept and saued fro &thorn;at apert dampnacion of alle mysbyleuynge'.  Here schalt &thorn;ow &thorn;anke &thorn;i lord god as hertly as &thorn;ow maist; &amp; after &thorn;ow schalt &thorn;enke &thorn;us and seye with &thorn;i mouth: 'How meny moore worthy and fer moore able to grace &thorn;anne i. am, by-cause of meny moo goode dedes doon after here bapteem &thorn;an i. haue doon after myn, been ri&yogh;tfully suffred of &thorn;ee, swete lord, summe to been honged or heded, styked or drenched or sodeynly deed in sum deedly synne, and so to be dampned to eendeles fuyr?  &yogh;e sikerly, lord, it may be &thorn;at a &thorn;owsand moore worthy &thorn;anne


<PB N="2: 443">

i. am haan bee lawefully dampned to &thorn;e boilynge put of helle, &thorn;eere for to wone as longe as &thorn;ou schalt be in heuene, for fewere synnes &thorn;an i. haue doon myn oonly body.  And &yogh;et hast &thorn;ow, my swete Ihesu, cleped me a&yogh;en to &thorn;e grace of repentaunce in &thorn;is lif, &thorn;orugh &thorn;e whiche i. may be kept &amp; saued fro al apert vengeaunce in &thorn;is lif, and after &thorn;is lif fro &thorn;at horrible dampnacion of alle fals cristene men in &thorn;e day of doom'.  Heere schalt &thorn;ow &thorn;anke &thorn;i lord as hertly as &thorn;ow maist; and afterward &thorn;enk &thorn;us &amp; seye with &thorn;i mouth:  'Lord god fadir of mercy and of comfort, what schal i. doo?  for i may not make amendis of myne innumerable synnes &thorn;at i. haue wrecchedly wrou&yogh;t a&yogh;ens &thorn;i wil, I may not &thorn;anke &thorn;ee of &thorn;e ouerhaboundant goodnesse &amp; kyndenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ow hast graciously doon to me, and &yogh;et i., &thorn;is stynkynge wrecche, vnnethes kan see &thorn;ise greet kyndenesse doon to me.  Now trewely, lord, i. weere worthy to be deed, slayn other hanged as an hound.  But for i. may not sle me my-self, &amp; also i. shulde not, &thorn;erfore i. biseche &thorn;ee, lord god al-my&yogh;ti, &thorn;at &thorn;ow wolt sle me &thorn;i-self, &thorn;at so wrecchedly haue doon to &thorn;ee.  And &yogh;ef it so bee &thorn;at &thorn;i greete pitee and &thorn;i greete goodnesse so bynde-In &thorn;i ri&yogh;twisnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ow like not to slee me thy-self, &thorn;anne i. biseche &thorn;ee &thorn;at &thorn;ow wold sende &thorn;in aungel of ri&yogh;twisnesse with his brennynge swerd, to taake vengeaunce vpon me.  And &yogh;ef &thorn;i muchel meeknesse &amp; &thorn;i grete mercy wol not suffre &thorn;ee to fulfille &thorn;e vengeaunce &thorn;at i. haue deserued, and me ou&yogh;te not by &thorn;i lawe lord for to slee my-self for &thorn;anne dampnede i. my soule, &thorn;anne wol i. do &thorn;at in me is, and alle &thorn;at i. may doo:  Heere i. &yogh;elde me to &thorn;e as &thorn;i boonde-man and &thorn;i prisoner, &amp; &thorn;i perpetuel seruaunt, and alle &thorn;e dayes of my lif neuer to departe fro &thorn;i seruyce.  And &thorn;is, lord, wol i. do as mannes freelte wol suffre &amp; specially myn, &thorn;e whiche freelte i. biseche &thorn;ee to strengthe with &thorn;i grace for &thorn;i muchel mercy AmeN'.     Heere shalt &thorn;ow falle to &thorn;e grounde &amp; &yogh;elde &thorn;ee to him as meekly and as hertly as &thorn;ow maist; and after &thorn;at sitte vp and reste &thorn;ee, &thorn;enkynge thus:  How gode &thorn;at god is in him-self, and how fair &thorn;at he is in his aungelis, and how lordly &thorn;at he gouerneth alle hise creatures; and after &thorn;at, how swete he is in his loueres; and last of alle, how mercyful he is in synneres.  And &thorn;anne seye &thorn;us bothe with herte and with mowth, withouten eny feynynge:  'My goode Ihesu, haue mercy on me.  My faire Ihesu, haue mercy on me.  My lord Ihesu, haue mercy on me.  My swete Ihesu, haue mercy on me.  My mercyful Ihesu, haue mercy on me.  And not oonly on me Ihesu &thorn;ough i. haue most neede, but in alle &thorn;e creatures quyke and deede whiche &thorn;ow hast bou&yogh;t with thy precious blood AmeN'.
</P> </DIV2><DIV2 TYPE="text">
<HEAD TYPE="main"> (St. Anselm's) Meditation I</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Univ. Coll. Oxford 97</HEAD><MILESTONE
N="310" UNIT="page"><OPENER>Heere is a good meditacion, the which seynt Anselme maade.</OPENER> <P>My lif fereth me soore, ffor whan i. bisyli enserche it is semeth to me outher synne, or withouten fruyt wel-nygh al my lif, and &yogh;ef eny tyme &thorn;eer be seyn eny fruyt &thorn;eer-Inne, &yogh;et it is &thorn;anne but as it weere feyned, or imparfit, or in sum manere corrupt, so &thorn;at outher it may not plese god as it schulde do, or ellys it fully displesith him.  Therfore now &thorn;ow synful wrecche, &thorn;i lif not welneigh al, but fulliche al, outher it is in synne &amp; dampnable, or it is vnfruytful &amp; despisable.  But wharto make i. departesun bitwene vufruytful and dampnable?... ffor it is certeyn &amp; trewe &thorn;at Treuthe seyde him-self in &thorn;e gospel: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Omnis arbor que non facit fructum bonum, excidetur et in ignem mittetur,</FOREIGN> that is to seyn:

<PB N="2: 444">

'Euery tree &thorn;at bereth not good fruyt schal be kut doun and cast in to &thorn;e fuyr'. And verreiliche, what profitable &thorn;ing &thorn;at i do, outrely i. acounte it nou&yogh;t for to answere to &thorn;e sustynaunce of body &thorn;at i. mysuse.  But who fedith eny beest &thorn;e whiche profiteth not as muche as it wasteth? and &yogh;et neuerthelees, mercyful god, &thorn;ow norisschest, fedist, and abidist &thorn;in vnprofitable worm, and stynkynge in synne.  And wel i. may seie 'stynkynge in synne': ffor withoute comparisun moore suffrable is a roten hound to men, &thorn;an is a synful soule to god; and muche moore wlatsum is such a soule to god, &thorn;an is such an hound to men. Allas allas, now may i. clepe &thorn;e no man, but schame &amp; repreue of al men, moore vile &thorn;an a beste, and worse &thorn;an a careyne.  My soule is soore anoyed of my lif; I am soore a-schamed for to lyue, and dye dar i. not.  Therfore what schalt &thorn;ou now doo, a &thorn;ow synnere?  Certes nou&yogh;t, but &thorn;at al &thorn;i lyf &thorn;ow wepe al &thorn;i lif, so &thorn;at it al weepe it al.  But &yogh;et in &thorn;is also is &thorn;i synful soule wrecchidly wondirful and wonderfully wrecchede, by-cause &thorn;at it sorweth not so muche as it knoweth &thorn;at hit schulde; but &thorn;us it slepeth siker in slouthe, ri&yogh;t as it knewe not what it were worthy to suffre.  What dost &thorn;ow, &thorn;ou bareyne soule? whi art &thorn;ou so slough, &thorn;ow synful soule?  &THORN;e day of &thorn;i doom cometh, It is ri&yogh;t nei&yogh; and swift in his comynge.  A day of wrath is &thorn;at day.  A day of trouble &amp; of anguyssch.  A day of caare and of wrecchednesse.  A day of myst and of derkenesse.  A day of cloude and of whirlewynd.  A day of trumpe &amp; of clarionynge.  A &thorn;at bitter voys of &thorn;e dreedful day of oure lord!  Whi slepist &thorn;ou, &thorn;ow synful soule and worthy to be wlated; whi slepist &thorn;ow?  For who so waketh not, &amp; who so quaketh not at so greet a &thorn;under, certes he slepeth not, but he is deed.  Thow vnfruytful tree, wheer been &thorn;i fruytes?  Thow tree &thorn;at art worthy an ax &amp; a fuyr, worthy to be kut and brent, wheere been &thorn;i fruytes? Sothly &thorn;ow hast nou&yogh;t but prikkynge &thorn;ornes and bitter synnes; &thorn;e whiche wolde god &thorn;at &thorn;ei prikkeden &thorn;ee so soore by forthenkynge &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren broke, and so schulden &thorn;ei waxe to &thorn;e so bittre &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulden vanyssche awey.  Perauenture &thorn;ow wenest &thorn;at eny synne be luytel: but wolde god &thorn;at &thorn;e streyte doomesman heelde eny synne luytel.  But allas, is it not so &thorn;at alle synne by brekynge of goddes heestes vnworschipeth god?  &yogh;us sikerly, &yogh;us.  What synne &thorn;anne dar eny synnere seie &thorn;at is luytel?  forto vnworschipe god whanne is &thorn;at luytel?  A &thorn;ow druye and vnprofitable tree worthy to euerlastyng fuyr, what schalt &thorn;ou answere in &thorn;ilke day, whan it schal been asked of &thorn;ee to &thorn;e twynclynge of an ee alle &thorn;e tyme of lyuynge &yogh;euen to &thorn;e how &thorn;ou hast dispended it?  Thanne it schal be dampned in &thorn;e what so euer may be founden of werk or of slouthe, of woord or of sylence, to &thorn;e leeste &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &yogh;e and of alle &thorn;at &thorn;ow hast i-lyued, &yogh;ef it haue not be dressed to &thorn;e wil of god.  Allas! how meny synnes schullen breste vp &thorn;eere without warnynge as it were enemyes liggynge in a wait, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ow seest not now?  Certes fer moo, &amp; happily moore grysly, &thorn;an been &thorn;ilke &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest now.  How menye &thorn;ow wenest now been not yuele, how menye &thorn;ow wenest now been gode, with open visage schullen &thorn;anne schewen hem to &thorn;e alther-derkest synnes?  Theere withouten doute &thorn;ou schalt receyue as &thorn;ow hast wrou&yogh;t heere with &thorn;i body.  Thanne, as now, schal not be tyme of mercy: Thanne, as now, schal no forthenkynge be receyued ne eny amendement suffred. Thenk &thorn;erfore heere what &thorn;ow art worthy to receyue &thorn;eere, and what &thorn;ow hast doo.  &yogh;ef &thorn;ei been meny goodes and fewe yueles, make muche ioye; &yogh;ef &thorn;ei been [meny] yueles and fewe goodes, make muche sorwe.  A thow vnprofitable synnere, whethir &thorn;ise thynges suffice not to &thorn;ee for to make in &thorn;e hidous and greet gronyng in sorwe? whether &thorn;ise &thorn;inges suffice not to &thorn;ee for to drawe out of &thorn;ee mergh and blood in wepynges?  Cursed be &thorn;at wrecchede hardnesse, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;us heuy hameres been to li&yogh;te for to breke!  A &thorn;at ouer-dulled slouthe, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;us scharpe prikkes been to blunte for to stire!  Allas for sorwe of &thorn;at deede slepe, &thorn;e which so grisly a &thorn;under is to hoos for to wakene!  A &thorn;ow


<PB N="2: 445">

vnprofitable synnere, ynou&yogh; &thorn;ise thynges schulden bee to &thorn;ee euere for to contynewe in waymentynge: thise &thorn;inges oughten to suffice &thorn;ee euermore to sobbe bisyly in wepynges.  But wharto schal i. feynyngly be stille, and stele eny &thorn;ing fro &thorn;e eyen of my soule, of &thorn;e heuynesse and &thorn;e gretnesse of my wrecchede &yogh;outhe: In pyne of &thorn;e whiche &thorn;eer schal &thorn;anne aryse withoute eny auysement so hastif sorwes &amp; so wonderful woes, &thorn;at sodeynly of hem &thorn;ere schal growe an vnsuffrable tempest?  Ceertes, &thorn;ow wykkede synnere, al &thorn;is spedeth not to &thorn;ee.  And nathelees, &thorn;ou&yogh; i. seie al &thorn;at i. may &thorn;enke, &yogh;et may it not be lykned to &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;ing is in it-self.  And &thorn;erfore let &thorn;in eyen weep by day &amp; by ny&yogh;t, and neuere to be stille.  Put-to wei&yogh;te vp-on wei&yogh;te, &amp; sorwe vpon sorwe, fferdnesse vpon feerdnesse, and woo vpon woo: ffor he schal deeme &thorn;ee to whom it falleth to punysche what &thorn;at eny trespassour or inobedient to god synneth; &thorn;e whiche hath &yogh;olde me good for euelle, and to whom i &yogh;elde yuel for good; the whiche is now &thorn;e mooste suffrynge, and &thorn;anne schal be &thorn;e mooste vengynge; now &thorn;e mooste mercyful, &thorn;anne &thorn;e mooste ri&yogh;tful.  Allas allas, to whom haue i. synned?  God i. haue vnworschiped.  The al-my&yogh;ty i. haue wratthed.  O i. wrecchede synnere, what haue i. doo? to whom haue i doo? how yuele haue i doo?  Allas &thorn;ow wratthe of &thorn;e al-my&yogh;ty, falle &thorn;ow not vpon me.  Thow wratthe of &thorn;e almy&yogh;ty, where maist &thorn;ow be taken in me?  Ceertes &thorn;eer is no &thorn;ing in al me &thorn;at may suffre &thorn;ee.  O &thorn;e anguyssches and &thorn;e annuyes &thorn;at schullen &thorn;anne bee:  For on &thorn;at oo syde schullen bee synnes accusynge, on &thorn;at oother syde streit ri&yogh;tfulnesse soore afferynge; bynethe, &thorn;e opene derkenesse of helle, aboue, &thorn;e wrathful domesman; withinne, a smertynge concience, and withoute, &thorn;e brennynge world. Vnnethes &thorn;e ri&yogh;twys shal bee saued; a synnere &thorn;us biseged, where schal he holde hym?  Thus constreyned, where schal i. huyde me? how schal i. appere?  For to huyde me it schal be impossible, and for to appere it schal bee vnsuffrable. I schal seeche where to huyde me, but nowhere fynde it; me schal agrise to appere, and euere i. schal be present.  A who is he &thorn;at schal delyuere me fro &thorn;e hoondis of wratthed god? where schal i haue helthe? where schal i. haue counseyl?  Who is he &thorn;at is cleped &thorn;e aungel of greet counseil, &thorn;e whiche is cleped sauyour, &thorn;at i may crye on his naame?  Ceertes, it is Ihesu, he him-self is &thorn;e iuge whom i. dreede so soore.  Looke vp &thorn;erfore a&yogh;en now, &thorn;ow synnere, bee of good hope and dispeire not.  Hope in him whom &thorn;ow dreddest.  Fle to him fro whom &thorn;ow fleddest.  Crie vpon him meekly for mercy, whom &thorn;ou hast soore agreued by pruyde.  Ihesu, Ihesu, for &thorn;in naame Ihesu, do to me after &thorn;i naame Ihesu.  For&yogh;et now Ihesu &thorn;is proude trespassour, and bihold with mercy &thorn;is wrecche clepyng &thorn;i naame, Thy sweete naame, Thy delitable naame, Naame of comfort to synneres and of blessede hope.  For what is Ihesu to seie but 'sauyour'?  Therfore Ihesu, for &thorn;in owene self be to me Ihesu.  Thow &thorn;at maadest me, lat me nou&yogh;t perisschen.  Thow &thorn;at bou&yogh;test me, lat me not be dampned. Thow &thorn;at maadest me &thorn;orwe &thorn;i goodnesse, lat me not perisschen &thorn;oru&yogh; my wykkednesse.   And as &thorn;ow art &thorn;e mooste mercyful, suffre not my wykkednesse to leese &thorn;at &thorn;in al-my&yogh;ty goodnesse hath maade.  Mercyful Ihesu, i. biseche &thorn;ee know &thorn;at &thorn;in is, and wipe it a-wey &thorn;at is ootheres.  Ihesu, Ihesu, haue mercy whiles tyme is of mercy, &thorn;at &thorn;ow dampne not in tyme of &thorn;i doom.  For what profit schalle be to &thorn;ee in my bloode, &yogh;ef i. schal descende in to euerlastynge corrupcion?  'For dampnede men schullen noone preise &thorn;ee, ne eny of &thorn;oo &thorn;at goon down in to helle'.  &yogh;ef &thorn;ow wolt suffre me lord entre in to &thorn;e broode bosum of &thorn;i mercy, it schal neuere bee &thorn;e streiter for me.  Receyue me &thorn;erfore, moost desirable Ihesu, Receyue me with-inne &thorn;e noumbre of &thorn;in chosyn; so &thorn;at i. bee fed in &thorn;ee with hem, and preise &thorn;ee with hem, and &thorn;at i. withouten eend ioye in &thorn;ee, with alle &thorn;oo &thorn;at louen &thorn;i name.  Amen.</P> </DIV2><DIV2
TYPE="text">

<PB N="2: 446"><HEAD>Three Arrows of Doomsday<NOTE ID="n20">This text is not to be confused with "Meditations on the Passion and Of Three Arrows on Doomsday," given in the Rolle volume under "Works of Doubtful Authenticity."</NOTE></HEAD><HEAD
TYPE="sub">Ms. Univ. Coll. 97</HEAD>
 <OPENER>Of &thorn;ree arwes &thorn;at schullen bee schot on domesday.</OPENER> <P>Who so wol haue in mynde &thorn;e dreedful day of doom so &thorn;at he mowe be moeued with dreede to flee fro synne, as &thorn;e wise man biddeth his sone&mdash;<FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Memorare nouissima et ineternum non peccabis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Haue mynde on &thorn;e laste &thorn;inges, &thorn;at is day of doom, and it schal kepe &thorn;e fro synne': heere &yogh;e mowen fynde sumwhat writen &thorn;eerof, how oure lord speketh by Ysaie &thorn;e prophete seienge &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Egredietur dominus de loco suo vt visitet iniquitatem habitatorum terre,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: 'Oure lord schal weende out of his place for to visite &thorn;e wikkednesse of hem &thorn;at enhabiten &thorn;e eerthe'.  Ceertes &thorn;is doom schulde souereynly be drad; ffor, as muche as he now doth mercy, so muche schal be &thorn;anne doo streit vengeable ri&yogh;twisnesse.  For it is of god in liknesse, as it is of &thorn;e sonne.  The sonne holdynge his cours passeth out of &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e lyoun in to &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e virgyne, and out of &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e virgyne in to &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e balaunce.  The lyoun is a strong beest and a fel, &amp; in &thorn;is signe was Crist &thorn;e sonne of ri&yogh;twisnesse bifore &thorn;e incarnacioun; ffor &thorn;at tyme he was so fel &thorn;at what man &thorn;at braake hise biddynges, anoon he schulde bee deed&mdash;ffor, as it is seid, a man was doon to deeth for he gederede stikkes on &thorn;e sabat-day.  But out of &thorn;is signe of &thorn;e lyoun he passide in to &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e virgyne, whan he took mankynde &amp; was borne of &thorn;e virgyne Marie: and &thorn;anne was he maade moore redy to doo mercy, &thorn;an euere he was to doo vengeaunce.  Thanne it bigan, &amp; &yogh;et it lasteth, &thorn;at he, &thorn;at seide whanne he was in &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e lyoun:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Anima que peccauerit cito morietur,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'The soule &thorn;at synneth, anoon it schal dye'; now, whanne he is in &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e virgyne, seith &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Nolo mortem peccatoris, sed magis ut conuertatur et viuat,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'I wol not &thorn;e deeth of a synnere, but moore &thorn;at he be turned &thorn;eer-fro and lyue'.  But, certes, out of &thorn;is signe &thorn;us of &thorn;e virgyne, he schal passe in to &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e balaunce, at &thorn;e day of doom, wheere he schal weye alle oure &thorn;ou&yogh;tes, oure woordes, and oure werkes in euene peys of his ri&yogh;twisnesse, &thorn;at he may &yogh;elde to euery man after &thorn;e trouthe of his desert.  And what he schal &thorn;anne doo? heere &thorn;ow what he seith now by &thorn;e prophete: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Congregabo super eos mala, et sagittas meas complebo in eis,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is: 'I schal heepen vpon hem here eueles, and i schal dispende alle myne arwes vpon hem'.  Three scharpe arwes schullen bee schot of oure lord in &thorn;at day vpon hem &thorn;at &thorn;eere schullen be dampned.  The firste arwe schal be of clepynge to &thorn;e doom, whan as him-self seith:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Venit hora ut omnes qui in monumentis sunt, audient vocem filii dei. et procedent qui bona egerunt in resurreccionem vite, qui vero mala, in resurreccionem iudicii,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Tyme schal come &thorn;at alle &thorn;oo &thorn;at been in graues, schullen heere &thorn;e voys of &thorn;e sone of god, and so passe forth to &thorn;e doom'.  Thanne &thorn;e wrecched dampned soule schal come to &thorn;e body, and seye to hit:  'Aryse &thorn;ow curside caityf careyne, fro &thorn;is tyme forth withouten eny eende to be felow to &thorn;e deuel, and enemy to al-my&yogh;ty god.  Now &thorn;i ioye schal be turned in to woo, &thorn;i delit in to bitternesse, and &thorn;i lau&yogh;tre in to wepynge. Now &thorn;i wrecchide schort lust schalle passe in to euerlastynge sorwe.  Now it is fulliche fallen fro the, what so &thorn;ow desiredest; now it is comen to &thorn;ee alle &thorn;at &thorn;ow dreddest.  Now it is agoo al &thorn;at &thorn;ow louedest; and now it is comen al &thorn;at &thorn;ow hatedest.  Cursid be zt;ow &thorn;ow wrecched careyne; for in pyne of &thorn;i synnes, &thorn;i delices, and &thorn;i wykkednesses, sith i. passide fro &thorn;ee i. haue besyly brend in helle.  Cursed be &thorn;ow helle-bron&macr;de, ordeyned to &thorn;e fuyr of helle &thorn;at neuere schal be quenched.  Cursed be &thorn;e tyme in &thorn;e whiche i. first was coupled

<PB N="2: 447">

to &thorn;ee, for now i. may not leeue &thorn;ee, thi cursed companye i. may not eschewe; wol i. or nyl i., I am constreyned to be knyt a&yogh;en to &thorn;ee.  Goo we &thorn;erfore togidre bifore &thorn;e dreedful domesman, &thorn;eere for to heere oure euerlastynge dampnacion'.  Thanne shullen alle &thorn;e wykkede men see &thorn;e iuste cause of here owene dampnacion writen with here owene hoondes in &thorn;e book of here consciences, boothe leerid and lewed, and reedyn it hem-self.  And &yogh;ef &thorn;ou seie &thorn;at lewede men kunne not reede, .i. seye &thorn;at &thorn;eer is noon so lewede &thorn;at he ne kan reede &thorn;e lettre of hys owene writynge.  Thanne &thorn;ei schullen see &thorn;e domesman as he weere wood, forwratthed a&yogh;ens hem.  Of &thorn;is woodnesse &amp; &thorn;is wratthe speketh &thorn;e prophete in &thorn;e firste psalme of penaunce, where he preieth to be delyuered of hem boothe, seienge &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Domine ne in furore tuo arguas me, neque in ira tua corripias me,</FOREIGN> That is:  'Lord, in &thorn;i woodnesse ouercome me not with skiles, and chastise me not in &thorn;i wratthe'.  Noman &thorn;enke &thorn;at wratthe or woodnesse or eny suche troubled mannes passion may be in god; but herfore &thorn;ei been set in scripture, for &thorn;e werkes of god in punysschynge and vengynge of synne schullen taake of suche passions as been wratthe and woodnesse in al synneres, &thorn;at outher schullen be chastised by pyne &thorn;at schal haue eende as is purgatorie, &thorn;e whiche pyne is cleped heere &thorn;e wratthe of god, or elles &thorn;at schullen be pyned by vengeaunce in &thorn;e horrible peyne of helle &thorn;at neuer schal haue eende, &thorn;e whiche is cleped heere &thorn;e woodnesse of god.  Al &thorn;is &thorn;e prophete Dauid sau&yogh; in spirit, and &thorn;erfore he in persoone of alle synneres, felyng him vnmy&yogh;ty to bere euer either, first asketh to be delyuered of helle, and sitthen of purgatorie, seienge &thorn;us <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Domine ne in furore &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> as &yogh;ef he seide &thorn;us to oure vnderstondyng:  'Lord, i. biseche &thorn;ee &thorn;at in &thorn;e dreedful day of doom, wheere &thorn;ow schalt haaue &thorn;e to synneres as a man &thorn;at weere wood, spaaryng no &thorn;ing, &thorn;at &thorn;ow ouercome me not with skiles in fynal conclusion, so &thorn;at i. be not convict for euere and be ateynt in a schameful inconuenyent of euerlastynge reproeue; &amp; herfore i. seye Argue me not, ffor arguynge, as clerkes knowen wel, is to ouercome an oothere with skiles.  But &yogh;ef me grace, goode lorde, so to argue and forto ouercome with skiles of &thorn;i lawe &thorn;e erroures of my blynde conscience heere in &thorn;is lif, whiles tyme is of mercy, &thorn;at i. may hertly forthenke hem, and cleerly confesse hem, and lawefully amende hem, by ensaumple of newe cleene lyuyng to men, feruent preier to god, and by discreet chastisement of my-self heere whiles i. lyue, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou haue no wil to chastise me in &thorn;i wratthe after &thorn;is lif in purgatorie.  And &thorn;at it be &thorn;us, <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Miserere mei domine quoniam infirmus sum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  Haue mercy on me lord; for i. am vnmy&yogh;ty to bere euereyther, that is &thorn;in arguyng in &thorn;e doom, ne &thorn;i chastysement in purgatorie, but it so be &thorn;at i. be vp born with &thorn;i mercy'.  O that dreedful day of oure lord!  &THORN;anne schullen alle wykked men see hem sitte in &thorn;e doom with Crist, whom &thorn;ei haue heere dispised; and in &thorn;is sight been troubled with an horrible dreede, seyenge &thorn;e woorde of &thorn;e wise man:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Hii sunt quos aliquando habuimus in derisum &amp;c.  Nos insensati &amp;c.,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Thise been &thorn;oo &thorn;e whiche sum tyme we hadden in scorn and despit.  We vnwitty wrecches heelden here lif woodnesse, and here eende withouten honour: but lo now how &thorn;ei been acounted amonges &thorn;e sones of god'. Thanne amonges al &thorn;at multitude &thorn;ei schullen not fynde oon &thorn;at schal haue compassion of hem, but alle schullen bee glaade &amp; consent with god in here iuste dampnacion, after &thorn;e woordes of &thorn;e psalme seienge &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Letabitur iustus cum viderit vindictam,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'The ri&yogh;twis man schal be gladed whan he schal see &thorn;e vengeaunce'.  Thanne, as Crist seith in &thorn;e gospel: thei schullen seche for to entre in to &thorn;e creuys of stones, and in to &thorn;e swelwys of &thorn;e eerthe, fro &thorn;e dreedful face of oure lord.  Thanne schullen &thorn;ei preie monteynes to falle vpon hem, and hulles to huyden hem, so woo &thorn;ei schullen be on euery syde. And &thorn;is is &thorn;e wounde of &thorn;e firste arwe.  The secounde arwe schal be an arwe of scharp repreuyng of alle fals cristene men, whan he schal seie to hem &thorn;us: 'I was an-hungred, and &yogh;e &yogh;eue me noo mete; I was a-&thorn;urst and &yogh;e &yogh;eue me no drynke; I was naked and &yogh;e &yogh;eue me noon herbere; I was seek and in prison


<PB N="2: 448">

and &yogh;e visyted me not ne dede me no comfort'.  O what &thorn;is voys schal bee dreedful whan it schal be seid to hem &thorn;at as ofte as &thorn;ei deden not &thorn;ise &thorn;inges to eny &thorn;at neede hadde in his naame, so ofte &thorn;ei deden hem not to him.  And no wonder &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;is voys schal bee dreedfulle in &thorn;e day of doom, sitthe we reden in &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at Crist, whan he koom in fourme of a seruaunt for to bee deemed of &thorn;e false Iewes, seide to hem &thorn;at sou&yogh;ten for to take hym:  'I am he':  and anoon &thorn;ei &yogh;eeden abak and fellen to &thorn;e eerthe.  &yogh;ef he &thorn;at whan he was deedly and koom to be demed, hadde so feerdful a voys, &thorn;at with his oo woord &thorn;rew&yogh; to &thorn;e grounde so meny steerne men of &thorn;e Iewys, a fer moore feerdful voys schal he haue whan he schal come vndeedly with his oost of aungelis &amp; of seyntes for to deeme &thorn;e quyke and &thorn;e deede, euery man after &thorn;at he hath deserued.  And &thorn;erfore seith Iob:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cum vix paruam stillam sermonum eius audire non possunt, tonitruum magnitudinis eius quis potest sustinere?</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Sitthe man may vnneethes heere a luytel drope of his woordes, &thorn;e greete &thorn;under of his doom who schalle mowe suffre?  As who seith noone.  And &thorn;erfore seith seynt Bernard &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Cum peccator accusatus fuerit &amp; consciencia propria contra eum testimonium perhibuerit et omnis creatura dei insurrexerit contra eum in vindictam, grauis vt sagitta erit vox domini ad sustinendum,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Whanne &thorn;e synful kaityf schal be accused, &amp; his owene conscience schal bere witnesse a&yogh;ens him, and euery creature of god schal ryse a&yogh;ens him in vengeaunce: greuous as an arwe schal &thorn;anne be &thorn;e voys of god to suffre'.  And &thorn;e prophete Ieremie seith: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Sagitta vulnerans lingua eius,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'The tunge of him schal be as an arwe woundynge'.   And &thorn;is is &thorn;e secounde arwe.  The &thorn;ridde arwe schal bee an arwe of eendelees dampnyng of alle wykkede men, whan he schal seie to hem:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ite maledicti in ignem eternum qui preparatus est diabolo &amp; angelis eius,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Goo &yogh;e cursede wi&yogh;tes in to euerlastynge fuyre, &thorn;e whiche is ordeyned to &thorn;e feend and to &thorn;e aungelis of him'.  This arwe schal wounde hem &thorn;at it falleth on so greuously, &thorn;at alle &thorn;e lechis, phisiciens &amp; surgiens, ne &yogh;et alle &thorn;e creatures in heuene &amp; in eerthe, schullen not mowe heele &thorn;e wounde of it.  Thanne schal &thorn;e opene eerthe swelwe hem down in to helle, wheere &thorn;ei schullen be turmented with feendis euermore withouten eende.  But allas! &thorn;eer been, i dreede, ful meny &thorn;at neuere wollen bileeue &thorn;ise &thorn;inges eer &thorn;ei feelen hem.  Of whom seith seynt Euseby &thorn;us:  <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Ve ve quibus est datum hoc prius sentire quam credere,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Woo, woo be to hem to whom it is &yogh;euen rather to feele &thorn;ise &thorn;inges &thorn;an to bileeue hem'. &amp; &thorn;us eendeth &thorn;e &thorn;ridde arwe.     But &thorn;anne schal Crist turne to hem &thorn;at been on his ri&yogh;t half, and seie &thorn;us: <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT"> Venite benedicti patris mei, percipite vobis regnum quod vobis paratum est a patre meo ab origine mundi,</FOREIGN> &thorn;at is:  'Cometh to me &yogh;e &thorn;at been &thorn;e blesside children of my fadir, and beeth parteneris of my ioye in &thorn;e kyngdom &thorn;at was ordeyned for &yogh;ow by my fadir fro &thorn;e bigynnyng of &thorn;is world'.  To &thorn;e whiche kyngdom and ioye he brynge vs &thorn;at bou&yogh;te vs with his precious blood.  AmeN.</P></DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="text">

<PB N="2: 449"><HEAD TYPE="main"><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">De Visitacione infirmorum</FOREIGN><NOTE>The Manual of Writings in Middle English, vol. 7, refers to the version recorded in this MS as Version E.  A related text,  based on portions of St. Anselm's <FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Admonitio morienti</FOREIGN>,  is given above from MS Rawl. C 285.</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Univ. Coll. Oxford 97</HEAD><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<OPENER>Here begynneth how men &thorn;at been in heele schulde visite seeke folke.</OPENER>
 <P>My deere sone or doughter in god, it semeth &thorn;at &thorn;ou hiest the faste in &thorn;e way fro this lyf to godward.  Ther &thorn;ou schalt see alle &thorn;i forme-fadres, apostles, martirs, confessours, virgines, and alle men and wommen &thorn;at been sauyd; and for gladnesse of suche felaschipe be &thorn;ou of good confort in god.  And &thorn;enk howe &thorn;ou most after this lyf legge a stoon in &thorn;e walle of &thorn;e citee of heuen slighliche with-owte eny noyse or stryf.  And therfore eer &thorn;ou wende out of this worlde, &thorn;ou most polissche thi stoon and make it redy, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou wolt not ther be letted.  This stoon is &thorn;i sowle, which &thorn;ou most make stronge thorugh ri&yogh;t byleue, and faire &thorn;ou most it clense &thorn;orghe hope of goddis mercy and parfit charyte, the whiche heelyn the multitude of synnes.  The noyse &thorn;at &thorn;ou most make heere in worchynge of this stoon, is ofte for-thynkynge of &thorn;i synne, whiche &thorn;ou most knowleche to god knowyng the gilty, and ther-after it is profitable

<PB N="2: 450">

to &thorn;e to haue conseil of trewe preestes the whiche owen to blesse the poeple, tellynge hem that been sorwful for here synnes that &thorn;ei schullen thorugh goddis mercy been asoylid of hem.  The strokere wherwith &thorn;ou slykest this stoon, is verrey repentaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt haue in thyn herte sorwyng of &thorn;i synne, smytynge thi-self on &thorn;e brest with greete sighyng of sorwe and stedefast wil to turne no moore a&yogh;eyne to synne.  And whan &thorn;ou hast maad redy &thorn;us thi stoon, &thorn;at is thi sowle, thanne myght &thorn;ou go the redy wey to god, and legge &thorn;i stoon sykerliche with-owten noyful noyse in &thorn;e citee of heuene.  And therfore i. conseile &thorn;e in &thorn;is lyf &thorn;at &thorn;ou schryue the cleene to god and make &thorn;e redy; ffor grisely deuelys, the whiche han tempted men to synne in this lyf, wollen in the laste hour been ful besy to begile hem, and nameliche with wanhope of goddys mercy.  And this is not oonliche to telle to syke men, but eke to hoole men, ffor euery day a man neigheth his deeth neer and neer, ffor the moore a man in this lyf wexith in dayes and &yogh;eres, the moore he vnwexith.  For, as seyntes seyn:  &thorn;e firste day in the whiche a man is born is &thorn;e firste day of his deth, ffor euery day he is diynge while he is in this lyf.  And therfore seith &thorn;e gospelle:  'Awake, for &thorn;ou wost neuere whiche hour god is to come, in thi &yogh;outhe or in thi myddel age or in thi laste dayes, or preuyliche or openliche.  And therfore [loke] &thorn;at &thorn;ou be alwey redy!  For it is semliche &thorn;at &thorn;e seruaunt abyde &thorn;e lord, and not the lord his seruaunt.  And nameliche whan greet haste is, he is worthi blame &thorn;at is vnredy.  But grettere haste no man redith of, than schalle be in &thorn;e comynge of Crist.  And therfore waketh in vertues; ffor whan the &yogh;ate is schet, it is neuere aftir openyd.  And &thorn;erfore, brother or suster in god, wete &thorn;ow &thorn;at god visiteth men for here synnes diuersliche: summe been visitid with scharp prisonynge, summe with sclaundre and bacbytyng, summe with ontrowthe of fals men, and summe with diuerse seeknesse; and &yogh;ef &thorn;at synne were clene awey, thanne seeknesse schulde slake. Here-of bereth &thorn;e gospel witnesse where Criste seide to ten myselis whanne thei weren heelyd of here lepre:  'Goth, he seith, and nyle &yogh;e synne moore, lest &yogh;e fallen wersse', als who seith: for &yogh;oure synne &yogh;e hadde this seeknesse.  And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e lawe wolde by ryght iustice &thorn;at no leche schulde &yogh;eue bodyliche medicyne to a seek man, but &yogh;ef he were in wille to take goostliche medicyne and to leue &thorn;e synne &thorn;at woundeth his sowle, schryuyng hym trewliche with good wille to don no moore euyl.  For so he resceyueth god, dwellynge in parfit charite.  And who &thorn;at is treweliche thus i-schryuen and dwellith in verrey repentaunce, I drede not that the seeknesse ne schalle slake whiche he hadde for his synne.  Or elles his peyne suffred with meekenesse, schal turne hym to muche merit in blisse after &thorn;is lyf.  &THORN;erfore &yogh;ef thi peynes slake not, comforte the in god in this manere.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD> How a man schulde comforte a nother &thorn;at he grucche not whanne he is seeke.</HEAD>
<P>Brother or suster, louest &thorn;ou god thi lorde? he or sche, &yogh;ef thei mowe speke, wol seye &yogh;e; or perauenture, &yogh;if they mowe not speke, thei wole thenke &yogh;e. Thanne thus:  &YOGH;ef thow louest god, &thorn;ow louest alle &thorn;at he doth; ande he scorgeth the for thi profit and not for his; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ou schuldest gladliche suffre hym and loue hym, ffor he wol not punyssche twyes hem &thorn;at meekeliche suffren hym.  And &thorn;at his chastisynge in this lyf is alle for loue, scheweth Salomon wher he seith:  'Sone, grucche not a-&yogh;eyns the chastisynge of thi fader': ffor it is no sone whom the fader chastiseth not'.  And this acordeth with resoun, and eke with comun manere of speche; ffor &yogh;ef a man see a nother mannys childe do euele in his faders presence, and his fader chastiseth him nought, thanne wol &thorn;at other man say that it is not his childe, or ellis that he loueth hym nou&yogh;t; ffor &yogh;ef he were his child, or ellis &thorn;at he louede hym, he wolde chastise hym. And therfore be nought euele paied of thi fadres chastisynge of heuene, ffor he

<PB N="2: 451">

seith hym-self:  'Whom i loue I chastise'.  Also seeknesse of body, meekliche suffrid, maketh helthe of sowle, and soule-helthe is not but oonliche of god. Therfore despise not goddis scorgynge, but whanne god chastiseth the, &thorn;anke hym and loue hym, &thorn;at he amendeth the, vndirnemeth &thorn;e, and blameth the; ffor alle this is token of loue ande scheweth that he wol not punyssche the in his wrathe ne in his woodnesse, but of his greet goodnesse he wole haue mercy on &thorn;e &yogh;ef &thorn;ou wolt leeue thi synne.  And &thorn;erfore &thorn;ank thi god, and specialliche that he hath largid to synful men his mercy aboue his wrathe.  Drede this lord as sone &amp; not as seruaunt: ffor he is thi iuge &thorn;at wol not dampne the but &yogh;ef &thorn;ow wolt not for lust and coueitise leeue thi synne, but he wol haue mercy on the, and therfore mercifulliche he chastiseth the, and ther &thorn;ow hast deseruyd euerelastyngliche his wrathe and to be dampned for euere, he putteth-ouer his vengeaunce and of grete mercy he suffreth vs to amende owre defautes, and punysscheth vs but a while.  And &thorn;erfore dispise not his &yogh;erde of mercy, ne grucche not thera&yogh;eyns, but suffre it gladliche, ffor alle &thorn;e domes of god been rightfulle. Now &thorn;anne, sitthe seeknesse of body is helthe of soule, and wole or nyle &thorn;ou &thorn;ow schalt haue it er &thorn;ou dye, and &yogh;ef &thorn;ou grucche a&yogh;eyns god, with &thorn;i grucchynge &thorn;ou makest thi sowle moore feble and so &thorn;ou harmest thi-selfe with thi grucchynge ffor nothyng is wers to a seeek man &thorn;an to be malencolious, and eke &thorn;ou greuest thi fadir &thorn;e whiche coueiteth to be thi leche, and &thorn;us as a fool &thorn;ou harmest thi-self in double manere: oon is &thorn;at &thorn;ou greuest thi god, another is &thorn;ou lesist thi meede &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldest haue &yogh;ef &thorn;ou suffredest alle maner diseses pacientliche to &thorn;e deth; and &thorn;ogh a man sum-tyme may not kepe pacience in sekenesse for greet accesse of diuerse passions, neuertheles he schulde, byfore thei koomen and after &thorn;e passynge of hem, purpose in his sowle to suffre alle anoyes pacientliche, and whan his hors grucchith, &thorn;at is his flesch, his spirit schulde be redy to suffre, and aske mercy for &thorn;e grucchynge of his flesch, knowynge &thorn;at alle bodiliche anoyes suffrid meekliche in this lyf maketh &thorn;e sowle fayre and stronge and rightliche to passe from purgatorie to heuene: wherfore we schulden with good wille herie god, and with glad herte take diseses.  Thenk &thorn;at &yogh;ef &thorn;ou haddest be traytour to the kynge wherfore &thorn;ou haddest deseruyd hangyng and drawynge, and he hadde for&yogh;eue the thi deth and punyssched the but a lytul while in an esy prisoun: how moche were &thorn;ou holden to hym.  Muchel moore &thorn;ou schuldest bythenke the how thow hast be traytour to god and therfore deseruyd euerlastynge peyne, and &yogh;et this merciful lord for&yogh;eueth vs heere eendeles deeth &thorn;e whiche we deseruyd, and punysscheth vs here but a lytel with bodiliche seeknesse, &yogh;ef we wollen meekly take his chastysynge.</P></DIV3><DIV3
TYPE="section">
<HEAD> &YOGH;ef deeth goo faste on a man, speke to hym thus.</HEAD>
<P>Brother or suster in god, &yogh;if &thorn;ou sawe or bithoughtest in thyn herte &thorn;e meschiefs of this wrecchid world and &thorn;e ioyes of heuene, &thorn;ou schuldest desire to be with god &thorn;ough &thorn;ou were lord of alle this world, and &yogh;ef &thorn;ou stode in grace, thow schuldest desire to forsake it to come to heuene; ffor hooly writ seith:  'Blessede be &thorn;ei &thorn;at dyen in god'.  Loke &thorn;e bigynnynge of this lif is care and sorwe; lyuynge ther-Inne, what is it but muchel trauail withowte fruyt, tene and disese, where-&thorn;orugh many men been ouer-comen with diuers temptacions and for&yogh;etyn here god, and so &thorn;ei comen to an euyl ende?  Loke nowe whethir it is better to dye wel or to lyue euele.  &yogh;ef &thorn;ou stonde in verray repentance and laste ther-Inne, stedefastlyche byleuyng in the mercy of god, thow maist dye wel.  But harde it is to lyue wel fulliche in this wrecchede worlde, ffor &thorn;e holy prophete seith &thorn;at 'eueriche man is a lyere', &thorn;at is to seye, for his firste forfeture euerich man synneth whiles he lyueth in this wrecchide lyf outher for lyinge of seruynge god after his comaundement, or ellis for &thorn;at he serueth hym not aftir his worthynesse; ffor hooly writte seith &thorn;at seuene sithes in the day falleth the ri&yogh;twyse man, and seynt Poul seith that no man lyueth in this lyf with-

<PB N="2: 452">

owte defaute.  Ther-fore we schulden prey to god with greet desir, &yogh;if it were his wille, &thorn;at we weren deede and lyueden with hym.  For &thorn;e wrecchidnesse of this world may no man telle.  For heere is hunger of goddis lawe and fewe &thorn;at desiren ther-aftir, and &thorn;ei &thorn;at thristen &thorn;er-aftir, been ofte-tymes slaked with bittere venym; and therfore &thorn;e charite of menye wexith coold thorugh &thorn;e heete of wykked couetise, ffor long trauaille and greet &thorn;at men han aftir worldliche bisynesse, and lustes maken meny men so weery &thorn;at &thorn;ei suffisen not to come to a good ende.  For this lyf is ful of envye, wrathe, glotonye, lecherye, prude, slouth, couetise, ffalshed, manslaughtre, and thefte, and of manye othere wykkednesse &thorn;at spryngen of thise, and ther nys no man &thorn;at he ne hath summe of thise, ffor no man in this lyf lyueth with-owte synne; and manye men been acombrid with alle thise, and &yogh;et thei kunne not ne wollen not dischargen hem.  Ande therfore &thorn;ise philosofres &thorn;e whiche knewen the wrecchydnesse of this lyf, maaden greet sorwe whan here children weren bore, and greet ioye whan thei dyeden and passeden from &thorn;e wo of this fals worlde; and as men fynden write, seynt Austyn whan he schulde be deed, spak to deeth in this manere:  'Welcome Deeth, end of alle wykkednesses; ffor &thorn;ou art ende of trauaille to hem &thorn;at han heere wel trauaillyd; ffor thanne and no rathere bygynneth parfitliche goode mennes eese in endeles blisse.  What man may by-thenke &thorn;e profit and &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at thow bryngest with &thorn;e?  Therfore &thorn;ou art desirful to me.  For a trewe cristene man may not euele dien, ffor aftir this lyf he schalle lyue with Criste.
</P></DIV3><DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD> Whan thowe hast tolde hym alle this, or ellys &yogh;ef &thorn;ou myght not for hast of deeth: bygynne heere eer his mynde goo from hym:</HEAD>
<P>Brother or suster, art &thorn;ou glad &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt dyen in cristene feith?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e. Knowlechist &thorn;ou to god &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast not lyued aftir his comaundement&yogh;?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e. Art &thorn;ou soory &thorn;at &thorn;ou lyuedest not as &thorn;ou schuldest?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Art &thorn;ou in good wille to amende alle trespassis doon a&yogh;ens god and thyn euencristene, &yogh;ef &thorn;ou haddest space to lyue?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Truste[st] &thorn;ou stedefastliche that god may for&yogh;eue the and alle men here synnes, though &thorn;ou ne noon othere make heere fulliche asseth for hem?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Leuyst &thorn;ou in god fadir alle-myghty, makere of heuene and of erthe and of alle &thorn;at been in hem?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Leuyst &thorn;ou &thorn;at the fadir and the sone and the holy goost been &yogh;re persones and oo god?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Leuyst thow that oure lord Ihesu Crist goddis sone of heuene was y-conceyued oonliche of the hooly goost and tooke flesshe and blood of oure lady seynte Marie, and sche mayden ande moder aftir his burthe?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Leuyst thow &thorn;at oure lorde Ihesu Crist suffrede harde peyne and deeth for oure trespassis and not for his gylt? <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Leuyst &thorn;ou &thorn;at he was aftir his deeth buryed, nad roos the thridde day in flesch, and steygh to heuene, and sente &thorn;e holy goost, ande schal come to deeme boothe wikkede and goode, &yogh;eldyng hem aftir here trauaille?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e. Thankest thow hym of al thyn herte for thise greete goodnesses &thorn;at he hath doon wilfullyche to mankynde?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  Leuyst &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne no man may be sauyd but thorugh his passioun and his mercy?  <ABBR EXPAN="Response:">R</ABBR> &yogh;e.  While thi sowle is in thi body, put hoolliche alle thi trust in his mercy, preiynge hym for his moder loue to sette his greete passioun by-twixe his doome and thi synnes, ande trust treweliche &thorn;at he wol of his goodnesse doo to the bettre &thorn;an &thorn;ou kanst desiren. And haue &thorn;ou therfore stedefastliche to thyn ende his passioun and his greete mercy in thi mynde, ffor there-thorugh oonliche been alle enemyes ouercomen. Therfore medle thi &thorn;ought with his passioun, &amp; wrappe &thorn;e as in a cloth in his mercy, and trust stedefastliche ther-Inne; nou&yogh;t thenkynge on thi wyf, ne on thyne children, ne on thi richesse, but oonliche and stedefastliche on the passioun of owre lord Ihesu Crist, hauynge the hard passioun &thorn;at oure lord Ihesu Crist suffrede on the cros lastyngliche in thi mynde.  And &yogh;ef &thorn;ou byholde any cros or ymage

<PB N="2: 453">

y-maad with mannys hondys, wite &thorn;ou wel &thorn;at it is not god, and therfore sey or thenk in thyn herte:  I woot wel &thorn;ou art nought god but ymaad aftir hym, to make men haue &thorn;e moore mynde of hym after whom &thorn;ou art ymagid. Therfore, lord fadir &thorn;at art in heuene, mercy I aske the of alle &thorn;at I haue trespassid, and &thorn;e wilful passioun of oure lord Ihesu Crist the whiche he suffrede for mankynde, mercyful fadir of thi goodnesse be it bitwyxe me and myne euele dedys, and the greete merite of oure lord Ihesu Crist queeme it to &thorn;e for al &thorn;at I schulde haue disseruyd and don&macr; and dede not; and also, mercyful lord fader of heuene, &yogh;ef it be thi wille, i byseche &thorn;e that alle &thorn;e beenfetis [&thorn;at] oure lord Ihesu Crist aftir thi biddynge dede heere in erthe for saluacioun of mankynde, stoonde bitwixe me and thi wratthe.  And blisful lady moodir of mercy seynte Marie, qwene of heuene, lady of alle this worlde, and emperise of helle, as &thorn;ou disseruedest byfore alle wommen &thorn;orugh the goodnesse of god to beren with-owten wem of thi maydenhood Ihesu Crist saueour of mankynde, soo &thorn;ou biseche thi blessed sone for me that alle myne synnes be for&yogh;euen. And lord al myghty Ihesu Crist, sitthe thyn hooly gospel witnesseth &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt nought the deeth of synful man but that he bee turnyd from synne and lyue, haue mercy of me synful wrecche, after thi woord, and as &thorn;ou blamedest Symount for he hadde indignacioun &thorn;at Marie magdeleyne for hire synnes schulde neighe the, haue mercy of me moost synful, and lord Ihesu as &thorn;ou clepedist &yogh;achee and Poul and oothere diuerse from here synnes, dispise nought me &thorn;at come to the wilfulliche wyth-owten suche clepynge; and though i haue longe leyn in my synne, thenk lord on the greete mercy &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddest and schewedest to mankynde that he schulde not schame ne despeire of thi mercy alle-though he hadde longe leyn in synne, whan &thorn;ou haddest no desdayn to reere La&yogh;ar alle-though he hadde leyn in his graue foure dayes stynkynge.  And herfore i. truste to &thorn;e, lord, for &thorn;ou art fadir al-myghty in whos mercy i. truste, to whos refuyt i. fle.  With greet desire I come to &thorn;e hyenge:  lord, dispise me not, thowgh i. be wrecched and synful, ffor i. truste fulliche to thyn help in alle my greete neede. For i. knowleche &thorn;at i. may not helpe my-self ne a&yogh;eyn-bugge me with my dedys:  but stedefastliche i. truste in thi passioun, that it suffiseth to make ful asseth to &thorn;e fadir of heuene for my synnes.  Therfore, lord, brynge me out of care and haue mercy on me; I trust not to my dedys but i. despise to trusten in hem, ffullyche trustynge to thi greete mercy, dispisynge my wikkide dedys. For &thorn;ou art my god in whom i. trowe stedefastlyche is alle myght and mercy and good wyl, wherethourgh i. hoope to be sauyd.  And therfore to the, &thorn;at art ful of mercy, i. knowleche my synne &thorn;e whiche i. haue doon thourgh myn owene defaute.  I knowleche my gilt:  haue mercy of me, ffor i. trowe treweliche &thorn;at &thorn;ou denyest thy mercy to noone &thorn;at treweliche trusten therto.  And in trust therof i. forsake wyth alle myn herte this lyf, to lyue with the.  In thyne hondis, lord alle-myghty and mercyful, I bitake my soule; For fro the bygynnynge of this worlde hath thi mercy be reedy to synful men, and so i. truste it schal be to me in myn ende.  Therfore, god my lorde ful of trewth, take my sowle, for it is thyn; doo therto as the lyketh; ffor i. woot wel of thy goodnesse it schalle fare bettere than it hath disseruyd.  Receyue it, and help it:  for in thyne mercyful hondys I putte it.  AmeN.</P></DIV3></DIV2><DIV2
TYPE="text">

<PB N="2: 454"><HEAD TYPE="main">Diliges dominum</HEAD><HEAD TYPE="sub">Ms. Univ. Coll. Oxford 97</HEAD><OPENER><FOREIGN>Diliges dominum deum tuum ex toto corde tuo, ex tota anima tua, et ex tota mente tua &amp;c., Luce decimo.</FOREIGN></OPENER><P>Thou schalt loue thi lord thi god of al thyn herte, of al thy lyf, of al thi mynde, and of al thi strengthes or myghtes; and thyn neighebor as thi-self'.  In thise two comaundement&yogh; hangeth alle the lawe and prophetis.  &para; Thanne &thorn;ou louest god of al thyn herte, that is to seye of al thyn vndirstondyng:  whanne &thorn;ou schapist alle thyn vndirstondyng pryncipalliche to knowe the endeles myght and rightwysnesse, the endeles wysdom and charite &amp; mercy of thi god:  howe god is redy &amp; wylly &amp; kunnynge to venge synne and punyssche wykkide men &thorn;at wylle not leue here synne, and how god is mercyful and kunnyng &amp; myghty to for&yogh;eue synnes to hem &thorn;at han verray repentaunce of there wykkide synnes; and for this vndirstondyng of thi god &thorn;ou most fle and destruye synne bothe in the &amp; in other men vp thi power and wit, and kepe and teche the comaundement&yogh; of god, and mayntene rightfulnesse and good lyuynge, verray pees &amp; charite; and &thorn;an &thorn;ou louest wel god of alle thyn herte, &thorn;at is of al thyne vndirstondyng.  &para; Also &thorn;ou louest god of alle thi lyf:  whanne &thorn;ou schapest alle thi lyf bothe in &yogh;outhe and in age, and in prosperite and aduersite, to [&thorn;e] worschip of god in clennesse and holynesse, herieng and thankyng thi god for al his grace and goodnesse and mercy, and for alle diseses and tribulacions &thorn;at he sendeth to &thorn;e in this lyf. &para; Also &thorn;ou louest god of alle thi mynde:  whanne thou schapest al thi mynde to thenke on &thorn;e goodnesse of god, how he maade alle thynges of nou&yogh;t, not for his owne neede ne auantage but for his owne goodnesse and [&thorn;e] profit of his trewe seruant&yogh;, as been goode angelis and goode men; and to haue mynde on Cristes wylful and peynful passioun and deth, not for his owne synne but for oure greete synnes; and to haue mynde on &thorn;e dredful day of doome, and on the endeles blisse in heuene to goode men, and on the endeles stronge peynes in helle to cursede men that wol neuere amende wel ther foule lyf.  &para; Also &thorn;ou louest god of al thi strengthes or myghtes:  whanne &thorn;ou spendist alle &thorn;i myghtes bothe of soule and body in seruise of god, and algates that thi wille be sugget to resoun, and in alle thynges y-confourmed to the wylle of god; and &thorn;at &thorn;ou waaste nou&yogh;t the strengthe of thi body in vanytees and ydelnesse and synne, but kepe it in good mesure to do goode dedis to worschip of god and help of othere cristene men, &para; and &thorn;at &thorn;ou spende wel thi fyue wyttes, as Sight, Heryng, Smellyng, Tastyng, and Touchyng, and also spekyng; also to despise synne and to do good, and mayntene trouthe of godis lawe vp al thi power and kunnynge, and greet desire of rightwisnesse; and thanne louest &thorn;ou god wel of thi strengthes. Thou louest thi neighebor as thi-self:  whan &thorn;ou willist hym good bothe in body &amp; soule as &thorn;ou schuldest by charite; as, &yogh;ef thi neighebor be in goode lyf towarde god, be &thorn;ou glad and ioyful therof, and norissche hym, conforte hym, and help hym ther-Inne, and &yogh;ef he be in synful lyf, haue greete compassion &amp; sorwe therfore, and vp al thi kunnynge &amp; my&yogh;t bryng hym out therof by deuout preyer, by holy conseillyng and techyng, and by ensample &yogh;euynge of thi good lyf, by dreede of greete peynes bothe in this world and purgatorie &amp; in helle, and by confort of the greete mercy of god, and by confort of the endeles blisse of heuene how soone he may gete that by godes mercy and verray repentaunce &amp; amendyng of his wykkide lyf.  &yogh;ef he be at welfare of body and prosperite of worldly goodis with trewe lyf kepyng godis hestis, be glad therof and help hym ther-Inne, and apeyre hym not for no maner good of this world; &yogh;ef he be at malese of body or ful nedy of worldlys catel, help hym and socour hym as &thorn;ou woldest he hulpe &thorn;e &yogh;ef &thorn;ou were in the same disese, and algates as &thorn;ou schuldist wilne to be releuyd by godis lawe of other myghty men.  &para; And not oonly loue thus thi neighebor at hoom, &thorn;at is thi frend, but a straunge man and thyn enemy, &yogh;e

<PB N="2: 455">

though he be hethen or soudon; for alle ben bretheryn in kynde of o fadir &amp; o modir, and so neighebors, &amp; we ben i-holde by charite to brynge men to good lyf vp oure kunnyng and myght.</P><TRAILER><FOREIGN
LANG="LAT">Explicit.</FOREIGN></TRAILER>
</DIV2></DIV1>

